<SLUG> BC-JDPOWER-RESEARCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERTZ, ENTERPRISE TOP J.D. POWER SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Flying into town and need to rent a car?
</P>
<P>
   You'll get the least hassle from Hertz and Enterprise, according
to a new survey by the for-profit public opinion research firm J.D.
Power and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The company's 1999 domestic rental car survey processed
questionnaires from 7,500 customers who last year picked up and
dropped off cars at agencies in and around U.S. airports. The study
found that price figured in less to overall satisfaction than how
quickly an agency could get a customer behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``After getting off a plane, you want to get your rental car and
go,'' said Steve Cohen, research manager at J.D. Power, based in
the Agoura Hills community of Los Angeles. ``The return process,
too: If you're trying to catch a flight and have to wait in a long
line (to drop off a vehicle), you might miss your plane.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Enterprise and Hertz, Avis and National also
rated well in the fourth annual survey, while Alamo, Budget, Dollar
and Thrifty came in below average.
</P>
<P>
   The J.D. Power study found the average wait time to be picked up
by a shuttle bus en route to a rental counter was nine minutes,
while returning a rental car typically took seven minutes. Rental
companies that can cut the wait time to six minutes and the return
time to four minutes will emerge as customer favorites, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond speed, customers said affordability, a good selection of
cars and a smooth reservation process were all roughly equally
important in determining satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Donahue, a spokesman for Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based Alamo,
said he had not seen the J.D. Power study but agreed that speed was
a key ingredient to success. Donahue said he didn't know why Alamo
had rated below average. ``Our objective is to make people happy,
not to get poor marks in surveys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
