<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ News analysis: When the Clinton administration
put shoring up Social Security at the top of the national agenda
early last year, White House officials said the first order of
business was to make it politically safe to have a frank debate
about the options. Fourteen months later, the two parties have an
array of choices before them. But while it has proved safe to talk
about Social Security, it remains a question whether the two
parties have enough courage and trust to move beyond the oratory
and actually do something. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
