<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BAYLOR-BLISS-HNS &LR;      03-24 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-BLISS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ Baylor officials got the big name they were hoping for when
they made New Mexico basketball coach Dave Bliss an offer he
couldn't refuse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After taking several days to mull it over, Bliss on Tuesday
agreed to take the job at Baylor and become one of the highest-paid
basketball coaches in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Bliss agreed to a five-year deal worth $3 million,
which would put him No. 3 in the Big 12 behind Texas coach Rick
Barnes ($700,000 annually) and Oklahoma's Kelvin Sampson ($610,000
a year).
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to persuade Bliss to make the move, and it proves
Baylor is serious about doing whatever it takes to be competitive
in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a banner day for Baylor basketball,'' said athletic
director Tom Stanton, a former Baylor basketball player. ``If you
had a guy on your dream list and you could make it happen, who
would it be? Dave was that individual for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this university will embrace one of the finest college
basketball coaches in this country. His record speaks for itself.
We now have a proven coach in big-time basketball, and we have a
cornerstone for Baylor athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   The salary package will make Bliss the highest-paid employee in
the Baylor athletic department, and probably at the entire
university.
</P>
<P>
   But it still is a surprise to many people that Bliss, who has
taken the Lobos to the NCAA Tournament in seven of the last nine
seasons, would be willing to leave an established program and take
the job at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people will scratch their heads,'' said Bliss,
who also has coached at Oklahoma and Southern Methodist. ``A lot of
people won't understand it. They will say you are leaving a Top 25
program and an arena that puts 17,000 people in the seats. But life
is more than that. We know what's important in our life, and Baylor
represents a lot of those things for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation here is a unique one. Baylor is about more than
just winning. It's about how you win and how you teach young
people. We are Christians, and we looked at the mission statement
of this university. The simple fact is we think the world of
Baylor. It's a new adventure in our life.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial package Bliss will receive is an indication that
officials of the Baptist-affiliated school were determined to hire
an experienced, well-respected coach who could bring instant
credibility to a struggling program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest: We were recruiting him all the way,'' Stanton
said. ``This is the person we wanted to head our basketball
program, and we did everything we could to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Turner, a former Baylor basketball player who is the chief
executive officer of Dr Pepper Bottling Co. of Dallas, was a member
of the school's advisory committee in the search for a new coach.
Sources say Turner told friends he would help the school
financially to get a well-known new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss, 55, replaces Harry Miller, who was the Baylor coach for
the last five seasons. Miller resigned March 5 after the Bears
ended the 1998-99 season with a 6-24 record, including 17
consecutive losses to close out the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we have a lot of work ahead, but Texas is a
can-do state,'' Bliss said. ``We are going to start at point zero
and add to it. I know we have some needs that must be filled in
with recruiting. It's going to be a tough and hard road, but I
really believe we have the wherewithal here to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot of the players on this team because we recruited
some of them. And I believe in Texas high school basketball. Four
of our five starting players this season (at New Mexico) were from
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss met with the Baylor players Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of disappointment with them about this year's
season,'' Bliss said. ``They had a tough year, but I told them
success isn't always measured in how much you win; it's measured in
how much you overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   During his news conference Tuesday, Bliss talked about his
coaching style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe in the 3-point shot,'' Bliss said. ``It has
allowed a lot of schools besides the Dukes of the world to be
competitive. Every year we are in the top 10 in number of 3s shot.
I just wish one year we would be in the top 10 in the number
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor guard Tevis Stukes, who was the team's leading scorer
before being suspended at the start of conference play over a
dispute with Miller, said Bliss' comments on 3-point shooting were
music to his ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as those words came out of his mouth, I started
smiling,'' Stukes said. ``That's the way I've played all my life.
Just to get coach Bliss is a big step for Baylor. He is one of the
best-known coaches in America. I think this gives us a chance to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he spoke to us, he said he wanted to make sure what
happened to us this year doesn't happen again. He told us he
believes we can turn things around next year. We're all really
excited about getting to play under him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss said he will bring his longtime assistant coach Doug Ash
with him to Baylor. Ash has been with Bliss since his head coaching
career began in 1975 at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug is in charge of keeping me from getting technicals,''
Bliss said. ``But he wasn't too damn good at it this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
