<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SPILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: 10 YEARS AFTER THE BIG SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 24:
</P>
<P>
   With the administration's backing, a bill will be introduced in
Congress today to give permanent wilderness protection to one of
America's great natural treasures, the coastal plain of the Arctic
National Wildlife Refuge. The timing could not be more apt. Today
is also the 10th anniversary of the day the Exxon Valdez ran
aground in Alaska's Prince William Sound, spreading 11 million
gallons of crude oil over 3,000 square miles and causing horrendous
damage to one of the nation's most sensitive ecosystems. Placing
1.6 million acres of Alaskan wilderness permanently beyond the
reach of the oil companies would provide a measure of expiation for
a major calamity.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Exxon Valdez incident has already left an
important mark on the long struggle to achieve a better balance
between energy and the environment. The spill forced President Bush
to abandon his drive to allow drilling in the coastal plain and, in
further repudiation of his friends in the oil business, to impose a
10-year moratorium on exploration in much of America's coastal
waters, including the California coast and the Florida Keys. The
spill also led to the 1990 Oil Pollution Act, which imposed severe
penalties on oil companies and shippers for negligence and required
safer double-hulled tankers by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the sheer scope of the disaster did much to raise
the country's environmental consciousness and taught it that a
single accident could effectively cripple an entire ecosystem. In
1981, only 25 percent of Americans believed that the risks of
offshore drilling outweighed the benefits. A year after the spill,
that figure had risen to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are still deep wounds, some of which only time and nature
can heal. Of 20 animal and bird species affected by the spill, only
2 _ the bald eagle and the river otter _ have fully recovered.
Eight others, including the economically vital herring and pink
salmon, are slowly coming back, and 10 have shown no significant
recovery. Exxon has shelled out more than $3 billion in cleanup
costs and civil and criminal fines. But it has yet to pay $5
billion in punitive damages to thousands of Indians and commercial
fishermen whose culture and livelihoods suffered severe damage. Nor
has the federal government cracked down as hard as it could on the
oil industry to upgrade its aging tankers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the companies and their congressional allies are
again hatching an assault on the coastal plain, which was left
unprotected when Congress gave the rest of the refuge wilderness
status in 1980. A narrow, breathtakingly beautiful stretch of land
flanking the Beaufort Sea, the plain is home to an extraordinary
variety of wildlife and, quite possibly, a major undiscovered
oilfield. The Contract With America Republicans tried to open it up
in the 1995 budget bill, only to be thwarted by President Clinton's
veto. This year's vehicle is an innocuous-looking measure
authorizing seismic tests that, if they showed oil, would
inevitably strengthen the case for drilling.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Rep. Bruce Vento of Minnesota has offered his bill
to put the coastal plain permanently off limits. As Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt once observed, drilling the refuge would be
an ethical calamity, the equivalent of offering Yellowstone
National Park for geothermal drilling. Furthermore, as this day
reminds us, Alaska's landscape has suffered enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
