<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF BAKER IS SONICS' GAIN _ TEMPORARILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For Sonic fans, here's the good news about Vin Baker's
injury: It's his eating hand.
</P>
<P>
   Even better news: The Sonics are looking good without him.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the wrong idea. I'm not joining the growing legions
who think the Sonics are better off without their All-Star power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Not permanently, anyway. But for the past six quarters, the
Sonics have looked as good as they have all season. Granted, that's
not saying much, but when their new, 13-11 neighborhood includes
the eighth and final Western Conference playoff spot, any
compliment is gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we can't win without Vin playing the way he
did last season,'' said teammate Dale Ellis. ``We've got a new
system, but it's a simple system. If you fight it, it just makes it
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems Baker has been fighting things, though ``fighting''
isn't an apt description of the Baker style. It's more like
``passive aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Paul Westphal's system emphasizes a faster tempo and a
more even distribution of scoring than last year, when the offense
went almost exclusively through the hands of Baker and Gary Payton.
But Baker, whether through attitude or ampleness, has been slow to
accept and adjust.
</P>
<P>
   For the second half of the Denver game Sunday and throughout the
win over Philadelphia on Monday, the Baker-less Sonics had life and
movement, two elements that appeared to have been inadvertently
waived at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the uptick had to do with the fact that Billy Owens has
finally become a solid contributor, and Detlef Schrempf has
returned to his old, albeit older, self.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that the Sonics no longer had to wait for Baker
to lumber upcourt and snuggle himself into the low post, from where
he had spent much of the season throwing the ball back from whence
it came _ not exactly evoking the image of a Karl Malone buffalo
move to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's teammates are reluctant to say much publicly, because
he's such a likable and ultimately valuable guy, but it's obvious
they have been tired of dragging his corpulent self up and down the
court with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Vin goes down, Billy getting healthy and in shape can't be
underestimated, but we seem to have hit on a way to play that suits
our players,'' was how Westphal on Tuesday summed up the past six
quarters. ``We've had the plays in before this. Now we're a little
quicker and more wide open. Before, we tended to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   For too much of the season, the Sonic offense tried to
jump-start Baker by forcing matters when he wasn't in shape to
respond. The ripple effect for a team already adjusting to six new
faces, including three rookies, was severe.
</P>
<P>
   The failed offense led to Payton's tendency to go messianic,
which was off-putting to teammates. When Payton hit the inevitable
wall, the Sonics found themselves trailing the Nuggets and Warriors
last week by more points than Holyfield trailed Lewis.
Unfortunately for the Sonics, Don King was not available to make up
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But that constipation figures to be ending, now that Baker
doesn't have to be accounted for. At the midpoint of the NBA's
Stupidest Season, the Sonics have rendered the first half of their
compressed schedule into a glorified training camp. Tuesday, they
broke camp with the long-sought veteran backup point guard, John
Crotty.
</P>
<P>
   The new starting lineup of Payton, Schrempf, Owens, Hersey
Hawkins and Olden Polynice is a little elderly _ by the playoffs,
none will be under 30 _ and a little small, but it is sufficiently
savvy and conditioned to make up for those deficiencies and then
some.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's major coaching task is to get bench production from
high energy rookies Vladimir Stepania and Rashard Lewis, each of
whom is capable of breaking a game either way. Stepania's 17-minute
contribution against the Sixers was a good example: four points,
four rebounds, four fouls, three blocks and five turnovers. For
better or worse, the man is a happening.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the past six regular seasons, the Sonics have been a
mess. But so is the league. Even without Baker, a 16-9 run over the
second half is within reason.
</P>
<P>
   The trick will be incorporating Baker upon his return to health,
be it in two weeks or six weeks. If it's the latter, Baker will be
coming back on postseason's eve, which under old coach George Karl
was the traditional time for a panicky change in the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were supposed to be getting away from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned in the NBA is that it's hard to project
six days ahead, much less six weeks,'' said Westphal, deferring any
talk about Baker's future except to say that the guy has to come
back in top shape.
</P>
<P>
   Baker would seem to have little choice. He can file for free
agency after this season, but the market would appear to be _
pardon the expression _ slim for players who make their teammates
better while reposing on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
