<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ While the Detroit Red Wings stole the
headlines on Tuesdsay, Anaheim Mighty Ducks Mighty Ducks general
manager Pierre Gauthier was content to add veteran center Peter
Zezel without disrupting his team's chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim acquired Zezel, known as one of the league's top face
off experts, from Vancouver in exchange for future considerations,
likely a low draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``(We) looked at an area we wanted more depth at and it was up
front,'' said Gauthier. ``Basically it was a chance to get a
veteran who has played in a lot of playoff games.''
</P>
<P>
   Zezel,33, gives coach Craig Hartsburg another option at center,
where the Ducks have been playing two youngsters -- rookie Johann
Davidsson and second-year man Matt Cullen -- most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Center ice is a critical position,'' said Hartsburg. ``He
(Zezel) is dependable defensively, a good penalty killer and has
provided some offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Zezel had six goals and 14 points in 41 games for the Canucks
this season. His best offensive season was 1986-87 when he scored
33 goals and 72 points for Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams may have been wheeling and dealing, but Teemu
Selanne seemed very satisfied that Gauthier chose to basically
stand pat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice confidence boost for the team that organization
trusts the players,'' he said. ``We know we can win with this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier said he didn't feel pressure to pull off a big deal,
even though his team is in a 1-3-2 slump. He's happy with the
progress the Ducks have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 12 games to go it was very important to keep growing and
not change things,'' he explained. ``You go through ups and downs.
We're a little down now, but the best way to get it back is with
the guys we have.''
</P>
<P>
   A reluctant trader, Gauthier says every deal has two sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll read teams got this and that, but don't forget to what
they gave up,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
