<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IT'S WHAT A MAYOR SAYS AND HOW HE SAYS IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The mayor could not understand why he had such a
problem with black and Latino New Yorkers. He had met with a group
of minority officials and explained how he believed in a level
playing field, not playing favorites. The officials twitched
restlessly, and left unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime city politician who had watched the meeting go down
the drain tried to explain the problem. ``I got two sons,'' he told
the mayor. ``I love them both the same. I really think I do. But
when one of them is sick, I love him more. I do.'' The people who
live in minority neighborhoods, he said, have more problems than
white New Yorkers, and because of that ``we have to love them a
little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor just looked at him quizzically. Life went on.
</P>
<P>
   That particular mayor was Edward Koch, and the politician was
Stanley Fink, the Assembly speaker. Before his death in 1997, Fink
told this story for the biography ``I, Koch.'' Rereading it, I was
reminded that we have been down this road before. New York City,
which is defined by its multiracial heritage, often produces
leaders who seem tone-deaf to the nuances of racial experience.
After Koch came David Dinkins, whose administration was so open to
input from almost everybody that the main message communicated to
the public was slightly depressive paralysis. The white and Asian
sections of New York were eager for a sign that Dinkins would take
their side when black activists behaved unfairly. But when the
chance came with the Korean grocery store boycott, Dinkins just
kept waiting and listening.
</P>
<P>
   Since Amadou Diallo was killed by police officers of the Street
Crimes Unit, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has done some good things. He
attended the funeral and made at least two attempts to meet with
Diallo's parents. He has met privately with representatives of the
African immigrant community and with black teen-agers. His police
commissioner has announced retraining for the Street Crimes Unit
and appointed a black officer to its No. 2 position.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the mood in the city and the numbers of people being
arrested in peaceful protests at Police Headquarters, none of this
has worked. That is because Giuliani has not carried on a public
conversation that makes the city's black and Latino residents feel
he understands and honors the roots of their anger.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference on Tuesday, Giuliani once again tried to
express an impartiality that he seems to feel will solve the
problem. Yes, he is concerned that police officers might be
treating some blacks and Hispanics unfairly. But he is also
concerned that people are stereotyping the Police Department as
racist and violent. If New York's police are not given credit for
the things they do well, he warned, ``it's very, very
counterproductive _ because I know cops. You're going to make
things worse.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those statements so evenhanded they are
meaningless. When people are in a rage over a clear injustice, it
does not help to point out that there are good folks and bad folks
everywhere. A good leader understands that the first step toward
healing is demonstrated empathy. The Rev. Floyd Flake, the powerful
Queens minister whom Giuliani cites as one of his allies in the
black community, says he advised the mayor to speak out more
forcefully. ``I suggested he say . . . `I'm going to stand with the
citizens to make sure the judicial process works fairly.'''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the mayor wants the judicial process to work fairly,
but Flake was looking for an expression of angry solidarity that
the mayor never delivered. ``I don't think it's in his
personality,'' he said. Giuliani needed to show, somehow, that he
had heard the stories middle-class black New Yorkers told of being
stopped by the police for no apparent reason, that he knew they
feared that their children might be killed by a frightened or
vicious police officer. Giuliani has statistics showing it is more
likely that a young black man will be killed by another young black
man than by a police officer. Flake has heard them. He believes
they are right, but for a community that has its roots in the
Southern experience of racism and abuse by the police, the
statistics are not much comfort.
</P>
<P>
   What Flake may have been waiting for is a statement that says to
the black community that although Giuliani understands and cares
about the police, for one moment he is going to understand and care
about the feelings of Flake's parishioners more, because right now
they are feeling sick and wounded. It was, perhaps, simply a matter
of tone. As a preacher, Flake says, he knows ``your delivery is
quite different depending on what you're trying to say.'' On
Wednesday Flake plans to go to the protest and get himself
arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
