<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1883 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX     03-24 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO INJURES EYE IN STARS' CLOSE WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Maybe the Stars need to hold Mike Modano out of games
played at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, who has not missed a game this season, last night
suffered an eye laceration on a first-period elbow by Phoenix
Coyotes forward Jeremy Roenick that left him with seven stitches in
the eyelid and a swollen left eye.
</P>
<P>
   The incident happened a year and 11 days after Modano suffered a
separated shoulder on the hard glass at America West Arena that
kept him out of the lineup for 17 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Stars return April 17, should Modano be allowed to
stay away from his personal ``House of Pain?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't hurt my feelings at all.'' Modano said. ``Maybe I
could get in 36 \Rholes of golf\S while the guys are out playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars looked like they were playing golf in the game's final
four minutes as they almost blew a third-period lead for the second
consecutive game. Keith Tkachuk and Rick Tocchet scored for the
Coyotes, but the Stars held on for a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Stars moved their league-best record to
44-14-12 and hit the 100-point mark for the third time in the past
three seasons. In addition, they opened their largest lead of the
season in the Pacific Division at 20 points over the second-place
Coyotes, who fell to 34-25-12.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some purple and blue around the eye, Modano said he
likely will play tomorrow against the Los Angeles Kings. Roenick
received a five-minute major penalty and a game misconduct penalty
for boarding on the play, although Modano said the injury came from
an elbow and not from his head hitting the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick could also face a possible suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Modano was behind the Coyotes' net and had tried to pick up the
puck 10 feet earlier. However, he missed the puck and was looking
backward at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I had the puck, he would have laid me out. The elbow
caught me right in the socket,'' Modano said. ``It's kind of
frustrating, he tries to catch people by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars then scored a controversial goal on the ensuing
five-minute power play that would help them on their way to a 3-0
lead. Brett Hull was credited with the goal, his 27th of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The play had to be reviewed for five minutes before the Stars
were given the goal. Hull had taken a rebound shot in a scramble in
front of the net and the puck somehow slipped behind Coyotes goalie
Nikolai Khabibulin. As Coyotes defenseman Teppo Numminen and Stars
winger Dave Reid fought to get to the loose puck that was sitting
just in front of the goal line, the puck somehow was pushed in at
the 13:18 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' next two goals were much prettier. Jere Lehtinen
bagged the second in the second period as he swooped behind the
Coyotes' net, came out to the right of Khabibulin and lifted a
perfect wrister in for a 2-0 lead. Jamie Langenbrunner then set up
Joe Nieuwendyk on a breakaway in the third period and that goal
would prove to be the game-winner. It was the sixth game-winner for
Nieuwendyk this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes refused to go quietly, though. Ed Belfour took a
shutout into the game's 57th minute for the second consecutive
game, but then watched as two pucks slipped past him. The first
came when Tkachuk was left in front of the net for an easy rebound.
The second came when Tkachuk fed Tocchet for an easy goal after
Belfour failed to play the puck cleanly behind his net.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Stars held on and held a road opponent under three
goals for the 26th consecutive road game. It's the longest such
streak in the NHL since the Detroit Red Wings held 30 consecutive
road opponents to three goals or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also pushed their road record to 20-7-8 and their
record against the Pacific Division to 14-2-2. Modano's teammates
had strong words for Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cheap, gutless; there's no room for that in the game,''
defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``It was intent to injure. As a
player, you know the puck's not there. Even if it was, he went
right for the head. \RModano's\S had concussions before, it could
have been just like \RPaul\S Kariya, he could have been done for
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes coach Jim Schoenfeld ``disagreed'' with the call and
Roenick's ejection. But Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk called it a ``a
total cheap shot.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
