<HEADLINE>
AGENT: COWBOYS ATOP ISMAIL'S LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The deal is not done, but it does appear that
the Cowboys are on the verge of finally landing speedy receiver
Raghib Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail's agent, Jack Mula, acknowledged yesterday that he was
negotiating only with the Cowboys at the moment _ though he's still
in contact with the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are negotiating with Dallas right now,'' Mula said. ``But
it's not done.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys vice president Stephen Jones: ``We are still
working on it. Nothing has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mula, who has stated at least four deadlines for a deal in the
past 10 days, said he hopes to get everything finalized by the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have offered Ismail a multiyear contract worth
roughly $3 million per season, including a $5 million signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ismail's deal is done, the Cowboys will turn their
attention toward signing free-agent center Mark Stepnoski and
free-agent linebacker Quentin Coryatt.
</P>
<P>
   Situations with several other players could also begin to
stabilize. Washington Redskins free-agent receiver Leslie Sheppard,
who is second on the Cowboys' list behind Ismail, likely will
return to the Redskins or replace Ismail with the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys unrestricted free-agent receiver Patrick Jeffers also
expects to get an offer from the Panthers, who said they would be
interested in him if they lost Ismail. The St. Louis Rams will also
make a run at Jeffers with an offer sheet in the near future.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
