A1885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NIT-NYT &LR;      03-24 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAL CRUISES IN SECOND HALF; CLEMSON WINS IN A STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For California, without a player who had played in a
post-season game before this season, the National Invitation
Tournament presented a precious opportunity, one the Golden Bears
used to reach the semifinals at Madison Square Garden on Tuesday
night. But for the opening 20 minutes of their game against Oregon,
Michael Gill mostly just watched and wondered if this moment had
passed him by.
</P>
<P>
   Gill picked up two fouls in the opening 1 minute 17 seconds of
the semifinal and then just watched. Gill, one of four seniors who
had transferred to Cal last year, arriving to find the school
serving a one-year ban for sins committed before any of the current
players or coaches had arrived in Berkeley, knew that this
tournament was the only reward, and he was missing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed in myself,'' Gill said. ``I was just
sitting, thinking about the season passing in front of me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After missing his only shot of the first half, Gill went out and
tried to get himself involved immediately in the second half. He
hit a short jumper on his first shot. He tried again on a jumper a
minute later, and it went down. He kept shooting. In the first nine
minutes of the second half, he made up for what he had missed in
the first, scoring 17 of his career-high 22 points in that span as
Cal turned a close game into an 85-69 victory over the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reaches a point where you don't know how many points you've
scored,'' said Gill, who had tied a career high with 18 points in
the quarterfinals against Colorado State. ``You're just playing
ball.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday night's championship game, Cal will face Clemson,
which defeated Xavier, 79-76, in the second semifinal. Oregon and
Xavier will settle for the consolation game.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson turned a 21-15 deficit midway through the first half
into a 40-29 halftime lead. The Tigers stretched the lead to as
much as 24 points in the second half before the Musketeers mounted
a late rally. Xavier, which had overcome a 15-point deficit against
Princeton in the third round, ran off 12 straight points to take a
76-73 lead with 1:26 left when Lenny Brown drained the Musketeers'
14th 3-pointer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Clemson responded, getting two free throws from Harold
Jamison with 1:07 left and two more by Tom Wideman, a 55 percent
free-throw shooter, with 29.3 seconds to play. Brown then missed a
3-pointer, and Andrius Jurkunas grabbed the rebound and closed the
scoring with two foul shots. Brown missed a desperation attempt
from 25 feet as time expired. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California, in earning its first shot at a post-season
championship in 40 years, avenged a pair of regular-season losses
to the Ducks and put its senior-laden squad one victory from a
storybook ending for a squad assembled of odd parts from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me if this was a rewarding win,'' Coach Ben
Braun said. ``The obvious answer is yes. Just the look of the
seniors, that makes it all worthwhile. I really feel for those
guys. They came to Cal at a tough time and I don't think anyone has
any idea how much they contributed to our program.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Gill and the Golden Bears have another game waiting, this
was already a dream ending to a rocky collegiate career for the
6-foot-6-inch Gill. He started his career at Pittsburgh, appearing
at the Garden in the Big East tournament as a freshman, then
transferred to Compton (Calif.) Community College before arriving
at Cal last year as part of a group of four transfer students that
helped rebuild the Golden Bears' program.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half of the first game, Cal's Francisco Elson,
a 7-foot center from the Netherlands by way of Kilgore (Tex.)
College, stole the ball from Oregon guard Yasir Rosemond, turned
and slammed in a dunk that shook the basket, knocking out the game
clocks at the Garden. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Play was halted while the clocks were reset, but no amount of
rolling back the clock could bring back the time when the Garden
rocked regularly during the NIT, and players like Pete Maravich and
Rick Barry drew huge crowds.
</P>
<P>
   A tournament that once drew better than 18,000 fans a game
opened on Tuesday night with a few thousand fans scattered
throughout the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They were there to see four flawed teams hoping to use the
tournament as a building block for another season when they could
qualify for the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament
or recapture a bit of pride for this season.
</P>
<P>
   No team fit that last description better than Cal, which
returned to post-season play this season after serving a one-year
tournament ban for an alleged illegal payment by the former head
coach Todd Bozeman's staff to a recruit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
