<HEADLINE>
MUNOZ SHOWING WHY HE BELONGS IN MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ Left-hander Mike Munoz's grasp on an Opening Day
roster berth could be described as a stranglehold.
</P>
<P>
   His grip grew firmer yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz pitched two scoreless innings during the Rangers' 4-3
victory against the Toronto Blue Jays at Dunedin Stadium, and one
sixth-inning pitch to Carlos Delgado demonstrated why the
33-year-old left-hander likely will begin this season in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz surrendered consecutive two-out singles to Toronto's Homer
Bush and Shawn Green, and that brought Delgado to the plate with
runners aboard first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado, a left-handed power threat who during 1998 hit .292
with 38 home runs, found himself at an early disadvantage with a
1-2 count. Munoz wasted one pitch and then induced a weak,
inning-ending ground ball to squelch the Blue Jays' scoring
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys who leaves the manager pacing in the
dugout,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``The reason he's
survived is because he's able to get guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   Relievers in search of a roster berth describe outs as a
precious commodity during March, and Munoz continues to deliver
those for the Rangers despite his deceiving 4.65 earned-run average
through seven appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Subtract his first appearance _ a horrendous March 6 outing
against the Pittsburgh Pirates _ and Munoz's ERA would be 1.04 with
opponents hitting only .257 against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did today is what he's done all of his career,'' Oates
said. ``He's a guy who's got good stuff. He's a high-walk guy, and
he throws a lot of pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz, though, did not issue a walk yesterday and required only
nine pitches for the seventh inning after throwing 19 during the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Tony Fossas, who stands as the only legitimate
challenger between Munoz and a roster berth, surrendered a
ninth-inning run on two hits yesterday. That gave Fossas a 5.14 ERA
through his six appearances this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz appears well on his way to joining Eric Gunderson as the
Rangers' specialists for late-inning situational matchups.
Left-handed batters hit .359 (23-for-64) against Munoz the previous
season, but Oates said he views the former Colorado Rockies
reliever ``more than capable'' against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado serves as one example.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten the job done the last four or five outings,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Munoz has surrendered only one run during his past six
appearances spanning 8 2/3 innings. The stranglehold grows
stronger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
