<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-BLISS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR PAYS BIG TO SECURE BLISS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Many people connected with Baylor felt it was
imperative for the university to make a competitive statement to
the Big 12 when it hired a new men's basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing now-former New Mexico coach Dave Bliss yesterday,
and signing him to what a knowledgeable source said was a
five-year, $3 million contract, was just that kind of declaration,
search committee member Jim Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss' yearly package ranks him behind only Texas' Rick Barnes
($700,000) and Oklahoma's Kelvin Sampson ($610,000) among Big 12
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could have done any better for Baylor,'' said
Turner, a former Baylor basketball letterman who is chief executive
officer of Dr Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we wanted the very best coach we could get to
win games. At the same time, we needed to make a statement that
shows Baylor has a commitment to basketball as well and I think
this does that. We want to stay in the Big 12, and it's important
for us to win both in football and basketball. Dave has been a
winner wherever he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director Tom Stanton said, ``If you had a guy on your
dream list and you could make it happen, who would it be? Dave was
that individual for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss brings a 24-year coaching record of 465-271 compiled at
Oklahoma, SMU and New Mexico and a history of 11 NCAA Tournament
appearances to a program that has been in the tournament once
(1988) in 49 years.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to bring his assistant of 24 years, Doug Ash,
with him to Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hide the fact it was a difficult decision _ not for
what we are coming to, but for what we are leaving,'' said Bliss,
55, who wrestled with the decision to accept Baylor's offer for
more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a program that regularly drew crowds of 17,000 and
played in seven NCAA Tournaments. Baylor's average attendance last
season was 2,689. He inherits a team short on major-college talent
that won only six of 30 games and was winless in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the opportunity came to apply, a lot of people scratched
their heads and said why leave \Rcrowds of\S 17,000 people, the Top
25,'' Bliss conceded. ``But when you get older, life is more than
the Top 25, more than being in the NCAA Tournament _ though that's
what we're going to be trying for here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation here is a unique one. Baylor is about more than
just winning. It's about how you win.''
</P>
<P>
   From a top program in the Western Athletic Conference, Bliss
turns to one at the bottom of the Big 12 that paid its last coach
about $150,000 yearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware of how good the Big 12 is,'' Bliss said. ``But that
allows us to recruit better; it allows us a lot of positives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone \Rin the Big 12\S is doggoned serious about
basketball now. It's going to be a tough, hard road. But I believe
we have the wherewithal, the support and energy to do it. No doubt
we have a lot of work ahead. But that's never bothered anyone in
this room.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes called Bliss a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he'll do a great job there,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss cited his previously stated fondness for the Texas
lifestyle and his past successes in recruiting the state _ four of
last season's five starters at New Mexico are Texans, as are 11 of
15 scholarship players.
</P>
<P>
   He also said new football coach Kevin Steele and the
athletic-facility expansion were testament to a new direction for
Baylor's entire athletic program. And he downplayed reports that he
wearied of constant criticism for not getting his Lobos teams to
the Sweet 16, a factor associates say influenced his decision to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the contrary,'' he said. ``I'm grateful for 11 terrific
years. We won a bunch of games and had fun doing it. But there are
other adventures in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor will be one of those.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
