r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PRO-GOLF-REPORT-T     03-24 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PRO-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL WANTS REDEMPTION IN HIS BACK YARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ David Duval, the winningest player on
the PGA Tour the past three seasons, walked off the TPC at Sawgrass
layout after a second-round 77. Convinced he had missed the cut,
Duval was steamed and silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather someone beat me in a playoff than miss a cut,''
Duval said. ``That's the one failure in golf ... I don't handle it
well mentally. Especially when it happens at home.''
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, the Florida winds increased after Duval
left the course that day in 1998. Competitors' scores soared, and
the Jacksonville native eventually survived the 36-hole cut by a
stroke and went on to finish 18th.
</P>
<P>
   But the feeling of disappointment that he had failed in front of
the home folks still gnaws at Duval, even a year later. It is
something he hopes to rectify this week at The Players
Championship, an event that Duval, 27, has attended every year
since he was a junior golfer who spent hours watching his heroes
pound practice balls on Sawgrass' driving range.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, he was invited to play as a marker with Joey
Sindelar because of an odd-numbered cut. Duval, then 18, responded
by shooting 1-under through five holes before a back injury forced
Scott Hoch to withdraw and Sindelar joined forces with Hoch's
playing partner, Greg Norman, for the final 13 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Duval still counts the experience as one of his golf highlights,
although he said it was ``terrible'' having to leave the course in
mid-round with an under-par score.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Duval shined for the first time at TPC in front of
family and friends. This week, the game's hottest player _ eight
wins in the past 17 months _ hopes to finish the job in his first
competitive appearance in three weeks at a PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably would be one of the most difficult victories for
me to achieve in my career because it's at home,'' Duval said.
``Since the people know you, they feel a little more easy about
approaching you and talking between holes. It's a bigger challenge
to block that out, but it would be more special if you could
overcome that and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting week for me. Other than the majors, this
is the most important tournament you'd want to win. Having it in my
back yard ... makes this even that much more desirable for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And even more imperative that, above all else, the PGA Tour's
winningest golfer survives the cut in front of family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ...Karrie Webb
Webb seems poised to win at Dinah Shore
</P>
<P>
   She is, without question, the hottest golfer on the planet. With
three victories in six starts, LPGA participant Karrie Webb has
more 1999 triumphs than any professional on any tour and is batting
1.000 in top-10 finishes (6-for-6).
</P>
<P>
   All signs point to Webb, winner of last week's Standard Register
Ping event, as a favorite to win the first major championship of
the season when the LPGA tour visits Mission Hills Country Club for
tomorrow's opening round of the Nabisco Dinah Shore tournament. All
signs except one, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, the 1996 rookie of the year and 1997 Vare Trophy
recipient, has yet to record a major title among her 13 career
victories. And she's getting antsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am goal-oriented. I would like to play well in the major
championships and start winning some of those tournaments,'' said
Webb, who tops the LPGA season money list with $419,063. ``It's
time for me to break through. My expectations are really high ...
and I tend to be hard on myself. But that's why I'm where I am
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb said she has refocused after a 1998 season in which she won
just two tournaments, her lowest total as an LPGA participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two great years, I kind of relaxed. I found it tough to
set goals last year,'' Webb said. ``But during the winter, I took
some time off and got the hunger back. That's made a big
difference. It's got me going again.''
SHORT PUTTS
Seeking a bag
</P>
<P>
   A familiar figure roamed the grounds yesterday at The Players
Championship in search of work. But it remains unclear if Mike
``Fluff'' Cowan, former caddie for Tiger Woods, will work this week
or even remain a regular presence at PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Cowan, dismissed last month by Woods, said reports of heightened
tensions prior to their breakup were ``way overblown'' and that he
holds no animosity toward his former employer. In fact, Cowan said
he was surprised when he received the news because the two had no
major disagreements, in his estimation.
</P>
<P>
   He declined further comment, saying changes in player-caddie
relationships are a regular part of PGA Tour life. Cowan said he is
interested in working with another player but would not be
disappointed if he does not pick up another bag on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to approach another player about it. As a
caddie, you just don't do that,'' said Cowan, a longtime caddie for
Peter Jacobsen before joining Woods in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance Cowan might work this week for Curtis Strange,
whose regular caddie will not be at TPC because of death in the
family.
Mixed results
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard Colonial officials have dispatched representatives to
TPC. Their mission: entice as many players as possible to compete
in Fort Worth at the May 20-23 event.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Colonial contingent can wave goodbye to Tiger
Woods, Ernie Els, Nick Price, Mark O'Meara and Lee Westwood. Those
five have committed to play in the Deutsche Bank-SAP Open in
Heidelberg, Germany, held the same week as Colonial. For O'Meara,
it marks a second consecutive trip to the event in pursuit of a
six-figure appearance guarantee, and O'Meara was instrumental in
enticing Woods to join him in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On the brighter side, the PGA Tour's only multiple-event winner
this season, David Duval, said yesterday that he plans to play in
both the Colonial and the GTE Byron Nelson Classic (May 13-16). In
addition, Colonial has landed early commitments from Justin
Leonard, Steve Elkington, Phil Mickelson, Ben Crenshaw, Tom Kite,
Craig Stadler and defending champ Tom Watson.
Solheim Cup changes
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a new captain for the U.S. team, there will be a
change in the format of the 2000 Solheim Cup when the biennial
matches are held in Glasgow, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bradley, a 26-year veteran of the LPGA tour and a three-time
Solheim Cup participant, has been selected captain of the U.S.
squad. But she will have two fewer matches to oversee than her
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the event, which will be played Oct. 6-8, 2000, at
Loch Lomond Golf Club, announced that the new format will include
eight foursomes matches on Friday, six four-ball matches on
Saturday and 12 singles matches on Sunday. Previous competitions
have included eight foursomes, eight four-ball and 12 singles
matches.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were made to minimize chances for matches being
suspended because of limited daylight hours in Scotland during the
fall.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
