<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIR FLEW TO OSCARS CEREMONY IN REVLON'S JET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A trip to the Academy Awards ceremony that Police
Commissioner Howard Safir and his wife took last weekend was paid
for by a cosmetics company executive, spokesmen for the company and
the Police Department said on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Safir and his wife, Carol, were guests of George Fellows, the
president and chief executive of Revlon, said Howard J. Rubenstein,
a spokesman for the company. ``They're personal friends,''
Rubenstein said, adding that Fellows, and not Revlon, paid for the
visit, which included hotel accommodations and seats on the
company's private jet. It was not clear on Tuesday night how the
Safirs obtained tickets to the awards ceremony. Details of the trip
were first reported on Tuesday night in The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   After reports of the weekend emerged on Tuesday, Safir asked
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to have the City Corporation Counsel review
the trip to see if it violated city ethics codes, said Marilyn
Mode, the Police Department's deputy commissioner for public
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revlon does not do any business with the city,'' Ms. Mode
said, ``but nevertheless, the commissioner wants to make sure that
it is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the City Charter, public officials are prohibited
from taking gifts and gratuities from companies and individuals who
do business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   After the commissioner was seen on television at the Oscars
Sunday night, questions were raised about his decision to attend
such an event during the crisis over the police shooting of Amadou
Diallo. Safir initially refused to disclose details about the trip,
although he said he did not travel at city expense.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner and his wife flew on an airplane leased by
Revlon that took off from Teterboro airport in New Jersey,
Rubenstein said. He said he did not know where the Safirs stayed or
the total value of the trip. The Safirs, however, flew back to New
York on Sunday night on a commercial airline, which they paid for
themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani knew about Safir's visit Los Angeles, although he did
not know the trip included a night at the Oscars. The mayor's press
office referred all calls to the police department.
</P>
<P>
   The City Charter bans city officials from knowingly accepting
``any gratuity'' from persons who may be affected by official
action.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision of the charter bans officials from accepting
``any valuable gift'' except those that are ``customary on family
and social occasions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
