</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS AND SABRES TIE, 1-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Every time there is a confrontation
between the Devils and the Sabres, Martin Brodeur and Dominik Hasek
are the focus of attention.
</P>
<P>
   With 48 seconds left in overtime on Tuesday night, all eyes were
on Hasek. That was not because of his customary superb play; it was
the result of a frightening collision. Hasek was on his back and
kicking his legs after the Devils' Brendan Morrison ran into him.
</P>
<P>
   He rose to the applause of the 17,089 fans and the game finished
in a 1-1 tie. The Sabres announced afterward that Hasek had twisted
his upper back.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' Scott Niedermayer managed to shoot the puck into the
net, but time had expired in the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Sergei Nemchinov, who made his debut for the Devils
after his acquisition from the Islanders a night earlier, took
center stage.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Nemchinov scored the only goal for the Devils,
who now are 1 point ahead of the Pittsburgh Penguins in the battle
for the Atlantic Division lead. The Penguins visit the Devils on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nemchinov played with intensity and intelligence as the right
wing on a line with Morrison at center and Sergei Brylin at left
wing. Brylin made the pass to Nemchinov that resulted in his ninth
goal of the season, at 2 minutes 57 seconds into the middle period,
when he beat Hasek under the stick with a shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergei made a nice pass,'' Nemchinov said of his fellow
Russian. ``All I did was shoot. I'm happy to be with one of the
best teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Nemchinov had a great chance to score on the play Hasek was
hurt, but he chose to make a pass across the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek said he was pleased with the way Nemchinov
played in his debut. ``He's a real intelligent player and he scored
a nice goal,'' Ftorek said.
</P>
<P>
   Nemchinov joined Pat Conacher as the only players to have
appeared for the Rangers, Islanders and Devils. Nemchinov played
for six years with the Rangers and nearly two seasons with the
Islanders, who signed him as a free agent from Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Scott Stevens (groin strain) and Lyle Odelein
(bruised right knee) were out and Ken Sutton played only his third
game of the season, the Devils' defense looked secure, especially
in the opening period, when Brodeur faced only four shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils (38-22-9) also played without Bobby Holik, who was
suspended for two games by the league earlier in the day for
slashing and breaking the left index finger of Toronto's Igor
Korolev last Saturday in Toronto. It was the second suspension of
the year for Holik, who served a two-game suspension in November
for slew-footing Florida's Paul Laus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no intention to injure and no carelessness,'' Holik
said in defense of his action.
</P>
<P>
   While Hasek had a busy night, facing 32, shots, including three
in the overtime, Brodeur was a spectator for much of night until
the late stages of the third period, when the Sabres tied the score
on a goal by Miroslav Satan with 3:37 left.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur faced 19 shots, none in the overtime, and improved his
record to 6-3-2 in his personal confrontations with Hasek. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0152EST &QL; 
