A1902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPTON-1STLD-WRIT     03-24 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS FALLS TO KRAJICEK IN QUARTERFINALS OF LIPTON
CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting) (sw) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ The shoulders were sunken, the head was
bowed, the racquet spewed sour notes like an out-of-tune piano.
Though Pete Sampras is again back in his accustomed perch as the
men's No. 1 player in the world, he and his game have not yet
caught up to his numeral. The bludgeoned backhand volley that
missed the court and set up his adversary's second match point on
Tuesday was visible proof of his current shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who entered the 1999 race belatedly after opting for a
Hawaiian vacation instead of the Australian Open, was gaining the
momentum to match his restored ranking here at the Lipton
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   But he was treated like a doormat on Tuesday in the
quarterfinals by his nemesis, Richard Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   A day after regaining the top spot, the second-seeded Sampras, a
two-time Lipton champion who hasn't won this title in five years,
played the shrinking violet against the seventh-seeded Krajicek and
made a 6-2, 7-6 (8-6) exit that was exceptional for its meekness.
And for its many flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Along with giving away a 4-1 lead in the tie breaker, where he
double faulted at 4-3, Sampras undermined his nine aces with eight
double faults. And he undercut his 30 winners with 32 unforced
errors, 22 more than Krajicek, now the highest remaining seeded
player here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's O.K., as long as I can live up to it,'' Krajicek said,
electing to take it as a positive omen that the last time he
defeated Sampras in a high-stakes quarterfinal, he captured his
only grand slam crown, at Wimbledon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek's latest subjugation of Sampras, whose exit leaves the
Lipton men's draw without an American semifinalist for the first
time in a decade, marked his fourth consecutive victory over him.
Just two other players, Michael Chang and Wayne Ferriera, have been
able to beat Sampras with such regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras followed last week's No. 1, Carlos Moya, and last year's
Lipton champion and No. 1, Marcelo Rios, to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   In women's play, the defending champion Venus Williams was
forced to fend off a surprisingly tenacious 6-3, 5-7, 7-6 (7-4)
twilight challenge from 27th-ranked Anke Huber.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was a mutually brutal exchange of baseline ballistics in
which Huber pinned the sixth-seeded Williams to the backcourt by
design. Searing returns from the German, whose forehand repeatedly
provoked last-gasp backhand mistakes from Williams, twice denied
Williams when she served for the match in the third set. But once
in the tie breaker, Williams charged to a 4-1 lead and nailed her
first match point when Huber soared a forehand wide.
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion's 17-year-old sister, Serena, who surfed
into the Lipton on the high note of back-to-back titles at Paris
and Indian Wells, Calif., extended her unbeaten streak to 14
matches tonight with a cursory 6-2, 6-3 demolition of third-seeded
Monica Seles. Knowing that Seles has made a meal of her opponents
by taking the ball early and on the rise, the 16th-seeded Williams
simply took the ball even earlier, screeched even louder, and
earned her a quarterfinal berth against ninth-seeded Amanda
Coetzer.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Kournikova, seeded 13th, failed to survive an erratic
outing against Austria's Barbara Schett, 6-1, 1-6, 6-1, today in
the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Martina Hingis eliminated Marlene Weingartner, 6-0,
6-2; second-seeded Lindsay Davenport ousted Yelena Likhovsetva,
6-2, 6-0, and seventh-seeded Steffi Graf trampled Natasha Zvereva,
6-2, 6-4.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
