<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1914 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BENDER-SPI &LR;      03-24 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BENDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL QUIET ON BENDER FRONT AT WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Bob Bender toured the Vanderbilt campus. He spoke with
the athletic director, again. He talked to the chancellor. He went
to spring football practice and met the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   But the University of Washington men's basketball coach did not
agree to become the Commodores' next head basketball coach. A news
conference was not held, nor is there one scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Like a ball at tipoff, the Bender situation remained up in the
air. The Tennessean newspaper in Nashville reported Tuesday that
Bender is expected to be hired by today. If so, no word of his
imminent hiring was evident Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Washington athletic director Barbara Hedges has had daily
conversations with Bender for the past week and a half. But as of
late yesterday afternoon, she had yet to hear from him again.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges remains hopeful that Bender will stay at Washington,
indicating that she believes the coach is totally happy here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct is that he's not (leaving),'' Hedges said. ``But
I'm certainly concerned about it. I don't want to lose Bob. He's
been absolutely wonderful as a coach and a person in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Bender makes a decision on Vanderbilt, Hedges plans to
talk with him in person. If that happens, it likely would be next
week after Bender returns from the Final Four in St. Petersburg,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   That would prolong matters. Vanderbilt athletic director Todd
Turner said he hoped to have a new coach in place before the Final
Four begins on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges said she does not think Bender will want an increase in
pay. Bender's salary is approximately $370,000, but with
incentives, the total package is worth $464,000, Hedges said.
Vanderbilt is believed to be offering $500,000, a negligible
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob is not going to leverage anything,'' Hedges said. ``That's
not Bob Bender. There has never been an issue of money with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges is confident that when Bender compares both universities,
he will choose to stay put. Both schools are renovating their
arenas. Washington also is building new athletic facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is not right to go anyplace,'' Hedges said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bender is on the verge of signing a deal with Vanderbilt, it
would be news to two of his assistants, Eric Hughes and Byron
Boudreaux. While Hughes was out for a run early last night, Bender
left him a message that revealed little.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was matter-of-fact,'' Hughes said. ``He's got a lot of
stuff on his mind, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender is expected to return to St. Petersburg Wednesday in time
to attend the college basketball coaches convention at the Sheraton
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hedges, there is at least one other athletic director in
the state that hopes Bender stays at Washington. Gonzaga's Mike
Roth is concerned that the UW would be an attractive opportunity
for the hottest coaching prospect around, the Bulldogs' Dan Monson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason he would leave Gonzaga is if a dream job
opened up,'' said Roth, noting that Washington qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego State and Washington State called Roth, inquiring
about Monson. New Mexico called Tuesday after Dave Bliss resigned
to take the job at Baylor. Monson pulled his name from
consideration at San Diego State and does not consider WSU to be a
dream job even though he was raised in Pasco and graduated from
Idaho, eight miles from Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're from this state, you're either a Coug or a Husky,''
Roth said. ``If WSU is not his dream job, you can read into it what
you want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a lot of fear of San Diego State or Washington
State stealing Dan Monson away from Gonzaga. I'm not so sure I can
say that about the University of Washington. Bob Bender, please
stay at Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson's Gonzaga deal was sweetened in February. Roth wanted to
be proactive and reward Monson for the job that he had done to that
point. A month later, everyone knows the name. Gonzaga nearly
advanced to the Final Four, captivating a nation in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm an A.D. anywhere in the country and I have a basketball
opening, why wouldn't I call Dan Monson,'' Roth said. ``But it will
take a tremendous opportunity for him to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
