<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WRESTLING-NYT &LR;      03-24 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WRESTLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WRESTLING FEDERATION MAY HAVE TIMES SQUARE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shunned by landlords on newly scrubbed 42nd Street,
the World Wrestling Federation may have finally found a home in the
middle of Times Square for a theme restaurant with the company's
own bizarre blend of athletics and theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant and entertainment complex, which may be called
Raw Restaurant in a reference to the cable television show ``WWF
Raw,'' would have about 650 seats and feature guest appearances by
wrestling stars like Stone Cold Steve Austin and Sable. It would
also feature live music and broadcasts, as well as occasional
wrestling matches.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives active in Times Square said the WWF might
sign a deal as soon as Thursday for more than 45,000 square feet in
the basement and ground floor at 1501 Broadway, at the northwest
corner of 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is struck as expected, the restaurant would be in
the same building where Frank Sinatra once sang to adoring fans in
the Paramount Theater, and across Broadway from where ABC-TV plans
to open studios for ``Good Morning America'' later this year.
Although theme restaurants have fallen into disfavor recently, the
WWF is betting that its phenomenal popularity and ever-changing
cast of characters will prove a winning combination.
</P>
<P>
   James Bell, senior vice president for licensing at the WWF,
confirmed Tuesday that he was ``pursuing'' a deal at 1501 Broadway.
The space there was being built for a live music restaurant by
Planet Hollywood called Sound Republic, but those plans were
shelved amid the company's financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the space, and we have an idea that can make it
work,'' Bell said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the restaurant would be about more than simply
professional wrestling, where the action is faked, or as the WWF
would prefer to describe it, choreographed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would fill that venue with a more varied entertainment
package,'' Bell said. ``We are a soap opera that just happens to
have wrestling as a backdrop. The rest of it is pure
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   A partnership headed by Robert Gries Jr., an investment banker
from Tampa, Fla., whose family once owned an interest in the
Cleveland Browns football team, and George Simon, a Cleveland
restaurateur, would operate the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   With some critics calling the entertainment vulgar and
offensive, the Wrestling Federation has not had an easy time
finding a home in Manhattan. For a variety of reasons, it failed to
make deals at the Bertelsmann Building on Broadway at 45th Street,
the New York Times Building on 43rd Street and the E-Walk
entertainment complex being built on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the Wrestling Federation offered to rent the vacant
Times Square Theater on 42nd Street, between Eighth Avenue and
Broadway. Instead, the landlord, New 42nd Street, accepted a less
lucrative offer from Livent Inc., which planned to open a live
theater. Livent has since fallen into bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater seems to think we're lowbrow entertainment,'' Bell
said at the time, ``but we're the No. 1-rated show for teen-agers
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wrestling Federation now has the top show on cable
television and often outdraws ``Monday Night Football'' among male
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales of WWF's action dolls, videos, music albums and
T-shirts skyrocketed to $500 million last year. The company also
plans to demolish the Debbie Reynolds Hotel in Las Vegas to build a
theme hotel, casino and theater.
</P>
<P>
   But the WWF is paying a high price to enter Times Square. Planet
Hollywood had spent about $13.5 million carving out a spectacular
space at 1501 Broadway before it abandoned the concept. Planet
Hollywood, which like many other theme restaurants has suffered
from declining attendance and a falling stock price, decided to
sell the space, as well as its Official All Star Cafe chain of
restaurants. Planet Hollywood still plans to move its flagship
restaurant from 57th Street to Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   According to real estate executives, the wrestling operators
have tentatively agreed to pay Planet Hollywood more than $8
million for the space and a steep rent of more than $2 million a
year. The group would probably have to spend another $4 million to
complete the restaurant and entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is hard to predict,'' said Jeff Rochlis, a real
estate consultant for theme parks and resorts at Rochlis &AMP; DeMayer
in Washington. ``There's almost a cult following. Who knows how
that translates into a restaurant experience?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
