<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1931 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAND-MACABRE-OPERA-$     03-24 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAND-MACABRE-OPERA-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPROVED LIGETI MASTERPIECE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably no opera of the last quarter-century has been seen by
more people than Gyorgy Ligeti's ``Grand Macabre.'' Since its
premiere in Stockholm in 1978, the work has had several different
stagings in Europe, though none so far in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes its second recording, taken from public performances
in Paris a year ago of the production made for the 1997 Salzburg
Festival (Sony SK2 62312; two CDs). Esa-Pekka Salonen leads the
Philharmonia Orchestra, the London Sinfonietta Voices and an
excellent cast, most of whom will be returning in December, when
the production moves into the newly reopened Royal Opera House in
London.
</P>
<P>
   The work's success is understandable. It is the biggest
achievement by one of the outstanding composers of our time, a
score with characteristic moments of aural magic, equally typical
snarls of savage comedy and more surprising touches of movingly
expressed anguish. Besides all that, it has a narrative as clear as
a comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   Nekrotzar, the ``Great Macabre'' of the title, arrives in
Breughelland to announce the end of the world. He meets various
inhabitants, including a drunken peasant (Piet), the royal
astrologer (Astradamors) and his sexually unassuageable wife
(Mescalina), two young lovers in heat (Amando and Amanda, both
high-soaring female voices) and the boy monarch (Go-Go, a
countertenor).
</P>
<P>
   Midnight strikes, and the world duly ends, but the only person
to disappear is Nekrotzar, once he discovers that his threat of
universal annihilation has not been fulfilled. The others,
meanwhile, are left floating in a new existence that seems not too
much different from the old one.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this story and a brilliant score, the opera made rapid
progress from theter to theater through the 1980s, yet all the
while, its composer was becoming dissatisfied with it. No doubt he
was growing away from its lusty vulgarity and its occasional
traffic in musical quotes. (Stravinsky's ``Sacre du Printemps'' and
Offenbach's cancan crop up in quick succession when Mescalina is
taking it out on her husband.)
</P>
<P>
   But also, as he points out in the booklet that comes with the
recording, he was troubled by practical problems: awkwardnesses in
the scoring that made the piece difficult to rehearse, and long
stretches of speech that held up the musical action. So for the
Salzburg production he spent almost a year making revisions, and
since the earlier version also exists in a recording (on Wergo),
anyone can hear what that process entailed.
</P>
<P>
   To take an example from the first scene, a whole spoken passage
in which Piet asks Nekrotzar about his part in ``this public
catastrophe'' is simply cut, and here Ligeti was surely motivated
by a desire to excise rather naive touches of self-reference as
well as to speed things up and relieve singers of the difficulties
many would find in delivering spoken lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the original version, Nekrotzar to Piet, like Christ to
Peter, turns the identity question back, and Piet guesses ``an
actor _ an opera singer or something.'' All this, happily, goes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if one compares the two recordings at this point, what is
most striking is the superiority of the later performance, in every
respect. Willard White, as Nekrotzar, is much steadier in tone,
more expressive and more ominous than his predecessor. Laura
Claycomb, the new Amanda, sings into the extreme high register that
was sketched before.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the orchestral performance is far better, whether in
the quick, snappy gestures that make a lot of the score sound like
cartoon music or in the wonderful cloud of orchestral trills that
projects, better than any spoken words, the miasma that Nekrotzar
has instead of a personality.
</P>
<P>
   Another unmissable difference is that the language has changed.
Ligeti's treatment of this issue in his booklet essay is unclear.
He says he composed the opera to a German libretto, then ``made the
appropriate rhythmic changes'' to fit the Swedish translation used
at the first performance.
</P>
<P>
   But he says nothing about the revised version, which, though so
far it has been seen only in Austria and France, has always been
sung in English.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably the original German setting was used for the
published score, and thus for the post-Stockholm performances,
including the 1987 Vienna concert performance perpetuated in the
Wergo recording. In revising this score, Ligeti appears not to have
made rhythmic changes to fit the English words: ``paradise,'' for
example, is stressed on the third syllable, as in the German
``Paradies.'' And where he was newly setting lines originally
spoken, he seems often to have been thinking in German, not
English.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, what is heard in the Sony recording sounds like a
translation. And it would do so even without the rhythmic oddities,
for ``Le Grand Macabre'' has its feet partly in a world of
Expressionist drama that is emphatically German, linguistically.
</P>
<P>
   It may turn that world upside down, mock the hysteria and the
histrionics, but it does so from a position of close acquaintance,
not from the safe distance of another language. Of the two
recordings, therefore, one provides the wrong text in the right
language, the other the right text in the wrong language.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for preferring the new version must include the musical
changes and the excellence of Salonen, his orchestra, his chorus
and his soloists. Apart from those already mentioned, Sibylle
Ehlert is wonderful in the scary-absurd coloratura arias of Gepopo,
the head of Breughelland's secret service, and in her contributions
as Venus to the brilliant star music that contrasts with robust
human behavior in the scene between Astradamors and Mescalina.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ligeti's alterations to the score, these are relatively
small but crucial. His deletions consist mostly of sequences
previously spoken without accompaniment, and the new music includes
lyrical lines to replace speech (sometimes involving choice
developments in the orchestration) and a finer ending.
</P>
<P>
   The old score finished rather heavily, with the orchestra. Now
the voices go to the end, in long farewells, while the orchestra
makes strange, wide-spanning, soft sounds, like felt bells.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than it was before, ``Le Grand Macabre'' is a wonder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
