<HEADER>
A1935 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCTIC-CIRCLE-FILM-$A     03-24 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCTIC-CIRCLE-FILM-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING LOVE IN THE ARCTIC, FINDING SUCCESS IN SPAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   Leslie Camhi's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the French director Catherine Breillat.  
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julio Medem, 40, makes sophisticated, elegantly constructed
films whose characters seem to wander blindly through a maze of
experience. The director has earned a reputation as Spain's most
promising auteur; but as an artist, he prefers not knowing where
he's going.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm working,'' he said by telephone from Madrid, ``if I
come up with something that has a very clear and concrete meaning,
I almost always put it aside.'' Instead, he proceeds intuitively,
building stories through the poetic juxtaposition of simple,
evocative images.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish audiences have had no trouble connecting with ``Lovers
of the Arctic Circle'' (``Los Amantes del Circulo Polar''), Medem's
fourth feature and a surprise hit there. The movie will be
presented in the New Directors/New Films series at the Museum of
Modern Art on April 7 and 8, and will open theatrically the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   Highly stylized, the film is a love story told alternately from
the perspective of each of the lovers, and it plays with the
tension between the lovers' fairy-tale idealism and the hazards
that govern their fate. The couple, Otto and Ana, meet and fall in
love as children. When their parents, who are both single, marry,
they become entwined in an odyssey that spans 17 years and takes
them to the fringes of Europe, from Iberia to Lapland.
</P>
<P>
   A complicated sense of identity and a feeling for far-flung
geography seem to come naturally to Medem, who is one of a number
of prominent young directors to have emerged from the Basque
provinces, the region of northern Spain whose drive for
independence has been a source of political conflict for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Medem was born in San Sebastian. His family left for Madrid when
he was 6 but spent vacations in the Basque region, and he returned
to live there when he was 22, moving back to Madrid just three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, the pressures surrounding the political situation
marked me very deeply,'' he said. ``Among bourgeois circles in
Madrid, people were largely unaware of all that Franco's
dictatorship implied. But in the Basque country, his rule was much
harsher. He prohibited the Basque language, which my mother spoke.
Some of my uncles and cousins were imprisoned. My moving back was a
very conscious ideological decision, to reconnect with that
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Medem experimented with his father's Super 8
camera. Then, while completing medical studies at the Basque
Country University, he wrote film criticism for a San Sebastian
newspaper; upon graduation, he founded a production company and
directed two short films.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 he made ``Vacas'' (``Cows''), a lyrical and visceral
first feature, set in one of the region's lush, isolated valleys.
It opens in 1875, in the trenches of a fierce civil conflict, the
Second Carlist War, and ends, some 60 years later, on the
battlefields of another, the Spanish Civil War. The same actors
play three generations of Basque peasants, locked in bitter
familial and political rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to create a claustrophobic atmosphere, to portray
that repetitive violence, that cycle of wars without exit,'' he
said. The film's fertile mysticism, epic scope, and absurdist
sensibility recall the work of magical realist and surrealist
writers like Gabriel Garcia Marquez and Jorge Luis Borges, whom
Medem read widely in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cows'' was followed by ``The Red Squirrel'' (``La Ardilla
Roja''), a 1993 feature about a musician's efforts to persuade a
pretty amnesiac that she is his girlfriend. Three years later,
Medem made ``Earth'' (``Tierra''), a metaphysical love story that
focuses on a lonely man sent to fumigate the vineyards of a
desolate patch of Spanish countryside. A sense of isolation unites
these rather disparate films, as well as a consciousness of the
fragility of individual experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovers'' draws on a similar psychological terrain, concluding
in the solitude of the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two lovers always create a space that they can share alone
together,'' Medem said. ``The Arctic Circle represents their
idealized, dream destiny. It's an impossible place, where there's
no one, where time doesn't exist. And that's the wonderful thing,
and also the dangerous thing, about running away and following a
romantic ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   With its focus on amorous themes, ``Lovers'' seems to share the
preoccupations of a new wave of Spanish directors who are turning
away from the politics of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex, death and the Civil War were the concerns of the
preceding generation,'' said Geoffrey Gilmore, the co-director of
the Sundance Film Festival. ``To some degree, young filmmakers are
trying to do anything but that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Medem's complex, allusive film language also makes him an
anomaly among his contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julio Medem is a happy throwback to an earlier era of Spanish
cinema,'' said Richard Pena, the director of the Film Society at
Lincoln Center, ``to people like Manuel Gutierrez Aragon and Carlos
Saura, who worked under the dictatorship, and created a cinema of
codes and messages, with densely metaphorical, elaborately
constructed films whose meanings had to be teased out. After
Franco's death, Pedro Almodovar and the directors who followed
turned to a very up-front, in-your-face kind of filmmaking. But
that Cabalistic strain in Spanish cinema runs very deep, and Medem
is part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His work is also informed by a highly personal sense of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was tension in my family,'' Medem said, ``because my
mother was Basque and my father, whose family was German in origin,
was supportive of Franco. There's a sequence in `Lovers' that goes
back in history, to show a Basque peasant sharing a cigar with a
German pilot whose plane was shot down during the bombing of
Guernica. For me it was a way of bringing together those two sides
of my family, in a gesture granting forgiveness, since my film is
also about finding forgiveness through love.''
</P>
<P>
   For Medem, filmmaking is a transformative experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each film is a journey that takes you very far away, with
everything you have, to a place where you always leave something
behind,'' he said. ``You create a hole in yourself. And with the
next film, you try to fill up that hole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look back,'' he continued, ``or make calculations
about where I'm heading. I want each film to be the living
expression of who I am at that moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
