<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEIR-THEATER-ART-$ADV     03-24 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIR-THEATER-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTOR WHOSE GOAL IS TO VANISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from London.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ian Rickson says he admires auteur stage directors like
Robert Wilson and Anne Bogart, who leave their emphatic imprint on
a production. But he prefers to burrow out from the inside of a
play. And if people don't notice what he has done, that may be the
highest compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Rickson's work is on display in ``The Weir,'' by the Irish
playwright Conor McPherson, 27, which opens on Thursday at the
Walter Kerr Theater. This meditative drama of barroom blarney that
gives way to a sense of loss and then of healing is the director's
first Broadway effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people talk about the play, then you've done your job,''
said Rickson, who is 35 and has spent most of his career directing
British premieres of works like ``The Lights,'' by Howard Korder,
an American; ``The Day I Stood Still,'' by Kevin Elyot, and
``Mojo,'' by Jez Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job in `The Weir,''' Rickson said, ``is to release and
realize the text, not to scribble on it. I suppose that's why
directing a new play is a specific skill; if the critics say `ably
directed' or `deftly directed,' it's the best you can hope for.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in a remote pub in rural northwest Ireland, one of the
country's poorest regions, ``The Weir'' brings together four men,
three of whom trade eerie tales of personal experience as they try
to impress a Dublin woman, Valerie (portrayed by Michelle Fairley),
who is newly arrived in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   But Valerie has her own story to tell, which alters the stakes _
particularly for the aging, solitary Jack (Jim Norton) _ and
captivates the bartender, Brendan (Brendan Coyle), whose compassion
speaks volumes, even if the character does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Weir,'' which had its premiere in London two summers ago,
was the first play by McPherson to incorporate dialogue. Both ``St.
Nicholas,'' a solo work that was well received Off Broadway at
Primary Stages last season with Brian Cox, and ``This Lime Tree
Bower,'' which opens at the same theater in May, are written as
monologues.
</P>
<P>
   McPherson is also the author of the 1998 gangster comedy ``I
Went Down,'' which has proved to be a very successful independent
Irish film.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet, reflective mood of ``The Weir'' is in almost direct
contrast to the combative tone of the Walter Kerr's previous
occupant, ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' by Martin McDonagh,
another drama set in an Irish backwater. As was true of ``Beauty
Queen,'' ``The Weir'' is arriving on Broadway in the same
production that played in London, where last month it won an
Olivier Award for best play. (Coyle won an Olivier as well, for his
bartender role.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The play is saying you must speak what is inside you,'' said
Rickson. ``It allows you to go on a human journey that is so
necessary and desired.''
</P>
<P>
   He linked the title ``The Weir'' _ which literally refers to a
dam and metaphorically to the flood of feeling released during the
storytelling _ to the lone woman, Valerie. ``The image of the weir
is important,'' the director said, ``because, if you like, water is
the unconscious, the paranormal, the feminine, and we're in a
thoroughly male world into which comes the feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A balance of masculine and feminine occurs,'' Rickson
continued. ``Jack is sort of feminized by Valerie. He's able to
tell a story about himself that he never would have at the
beginning of the play.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rickson can speak of feminine influences, similar words have
been used to describe his strengths as a director. ``Ian finds the
femininity in you,'' said Ray Winstone, the burly film actor who
has appeared in two productions for Rickson at the Royal Court,
``Some Voices'' and ``Pale Horse,'' both by Joe Penhall; Winstone
also played the brutish father in Gary Oldman's film ``Nil By
Mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of male directors who think about the macho
side of man,'' Winstone said. ``I like the other side of it, and
Ian does also _ the weaknesses that make someone a human being.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Daldry, who preceded Rickson as artistic director of the
Royal Court, said Rickson's work ``is not about showing off in a
conceptual way; Ian gets into the heart of a play and manages to
reveal that heart.'' (Daldry is currently represented on Broadway
as the director of ``Via Dolorosa,'' written by and starring David
Hare, the British playwright.)
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kent, co-artistic director of the Almeida Theater in
North London, mentioned the challenge Rickson would face in the
fall. It is then that the Royal Court returns to its venerable home
for new writing. It has been encamped in several West End theaters
while its headquarters in Chelsea were rebuilt at a cost of more
than $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about going back in,'' Kent said, ``and re-engendering
the excitement and sense of place that any theater, or at least any
building-based theater, needs. That's going to be Ian's task.''
</P>
<P>
   Rickson said he felt up to it. The director attributes at least
some of his maturity and point of view to the fact that he was just
21 when he became a father. Jack, his son, is now 13 and lives half
the time with each parent; Rickson lives in South London with Polly
Teale, a theater director and his companion of nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bringing up a child for three years on my own,'' Rickson
recalled, ``pretty much because his mum had gone back to
university. In a way, you either have empathy or you don't. When
you have a child, it's a powerful emotional experience. What it did
for me was center me as an artist. You learn to really focus on
what's important to you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
