<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1940 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOPIN-MUSIC-$ADV28-N     03-24 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOPIN-MUSIC-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEST PROPOSAL FOR CHOPIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another anniversary is upon us, yet the music business is
strangely muted. Frederic Chopin died 150 years ago, and the
relative silence has less to do with our forgetfulness than with
our despair. For what are we to give the man who has everything?
</P>
<P>
   Centennials _ bi-, tri-, sesqui- or of whatever nature _ promise
concentrated looks, resuscitations of neglected works,
re-evaluations of worth, new editions and musicological
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Bach's 300th birthday, in 1985, made us pay attention to
cantatas rarely heard outside the church these days, if even there.
The Telemann 300th in 1981, the longest of my years as a junior
critic, established the Baroque master as (alas) among the most
prolific of German composers.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart, in 1991, 200 years after his death, got Lincoln Center
into the accounting business, its various performing arms ticking
off every piece in Kochel's famous list and then some. Mozart also
gave concert presenters a ready-made way to interest listeners and
sell them tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, anniversaries have become a marketing strategy. The
Brahms year in 1997 prospered because Brahms fits modern orchestra
and concert-hall formats. Everybody played the Brahms symphonies
anyway, so why not just stick on the centennial label to add a
little tone?
</P>
<P>
   Some music schools are advertising Chopin quasi-marathons,
featuring their star pupils. This again continues what these young
people do everyday anyhow and simply gives it a name. If the FBI
kept statistics, I'm sure it would tell us that crimes against
Chopin's etudes are committed about every 30 seconds in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestras don't have to worry. Chopin's teen-age piano
concertos, near-miracles of invention, use them as backdrops, and
thin ones at that. There are songs and pieces for the composer's
beloved cello, but most everything else rests on the keyboard, and
these we know about already.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Chopin rings from every stage, every car radio and
every living-room loudspeaker; he is so beloved that we are dulled
to his qualities. The G minor Ballade has astonishing originality
and force, but its opening measures send me screaming from the
room.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful militance of the polonaises has become a cliche.
As Lincoln Center's recent film festival of historic pianists told
us over and over, Chopin remains a touchstone. I still respond to
the mazurkas: first, because of their adventure; second, because
their relative technical simplicity has been largely shunned by
virtuosos.
</P>
<P>
   So what gift can we give a man like this? Reformed performance
practices? Perhaps. Emanuel Ax has been playing Chopin on the
lighter instruments of the period; and though I don't think their
clarity compensates for their weakness, Ax plays his old Erard
beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   We tend to forget Chopin's Classical origins; he probably played
ornaments as Beethoven or even Mozart might have, not according to
the ``modern'' usage that came from editions made many years after
his death.
</P>
<P>
   But the influences seem pale next to the sui generis that was
Chopin. Even the early piano concertos are startlingly different
from anything around them. No one else explored diatonic harmony
with such vision or captured the modal flavors of Central European
folk music with such subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   By accident or on purpose, 20th-century composers (Mahler and
some American songwriters excepted) lost Chopin's endless gift for
melody. From a ground zero arrived at perhaps from outer space,
Chopin set about laying ground rules for piano writing that have
never lost their influence.
</P>
<P>
   Are we in for other marathons? Garrick Ohlsson recently gave us
Chopin complete in a brilliant series of recitals at Alice Tully
Hall extended over two seasons. Do we need more Chopin recordings?
My copy of the Schwann catalog is not quite up to date, but before
my fingers got tired of counting, I was up to 52 entries for the
preludes, 40 for the waltzes and 37 for the polonaises. Releases
drop in and out of print, but I would be surprised if the totals
weren't pretty much the same now.
</P>
<P>
   I have a modest proposal for the 150th anniversary of Chopin's
death. It is one that no one will pay the slightest attention to,
but here it is anyway. Let us remember this great man with a year
of silence. Let us ban his music from the airwaves and empty his
CDs from the bins.
</P>
<P>
   Images of Chopin will be turned to the wall. All editions of his
music _ from Paderewski to Cortot to Henle _ will be confiscated
and stored. Teachers caught teaching his sonatas will be subject to
arrest; private citizens heard whistling his wonderful tunes will
receive summonses (citizen's arrests recommended). No new
biographies, no studies, no lectures, no newspaper or magazine
articles.
</P>
<P>
   If the necessary legislation runs into trouble (it might not,
given how few Congressmen probably know or care who Chopin was),
then take this silence upon yourselves. Earplugs will be necessary;
also a hammer big enough to damage offending apparatuses.
</P>
<P>
   A great sorrow of my musical life is that that I shall never
again know the rush of delight that ought to accompany a hearing of
the Barcarolle, the D flat Nocturne, the slow movement of the
Second Piano Concerto or the great A minor Mazurka.
</P>
<P>
   I remember driving back from a Maine vacation that had been
devoid of music, turning on the radio and discovering, on the way
to the nearest country-and-western station, a Haydn quartet. What a
shock of delight it sent out. With what freshness it was received.
Silence renews, and no one needs it more than Chopin. Stop
listening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
