<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BALLET-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW INSIGHTS FOR A DISTINCTIVE MODERNIST VISION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rehash or celebration? As a work in progress, the New York City
Ballet's 50th anniversary year looks like both. The celebration is,
in effect, a retrospective: Now halfway through the 100 ballets it
plans to present through June, the company leaned toward the
familiar in its recent winter season. Yet the packaging was often
different, and new contexts made for new insights.
</P>
<P>
   The festive colors were waved early in this first of two
anniversary segments. There was a spectacular party for 50 years'
worth of company alumni, most of whom turned up two days later for
a mammoth curtain call at the New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a strange parade of guest conductors auditioning
in public for a City Ballet job, or at least offering welcome gusto
in the pit.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly the winter season was business as usual. This meant that
the dancing was glorious and that fresh talent continued to come
forward. (The young Adam Hendrickson, exciting in his tensile
energy, was this season's revelation.) Just as clearly, there was
none of the daring of the 1993 Balanchine celebration, which
attempted to revive works no longer danced at the City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the ballets were the same we have seen for
years, with a few exceptions. Jacques d'Amboise's 1964 ``Irish
Fantasy,'' which had been out of the repertory since 1982, returned
as a solid and sprightly neo-Balanchinian exercise. ``Les
Gentilhommes,'' Peter Martins' 1987 tribute to male classical
dancing, was better performed in the past. By contrast, his
``Beethoven Romance,''from 1989, preserved its romantic perfume.
</P>
<P>
   The major works presented, however, were not revivals but the
ballets by Balanchine and Jerome Robbins that are the company's
soul. As artistic director, Martins had to make the season special,
and the surprise is the success of his old-wine-in-new-bottles
approach. Theme programs, including tributes to composers,
abounded. Unexpectedly these marketing gimmicks provided fresh
esthetic insight.
</P>
<P>
   There were Russian, English, French, Austrian, German, Italian
and Polish ``tributes'' with a relevant diplomat on hand to
introduce ballets whose composers came from his country. Sometimes
the composers themselves were given a tribute, as in the all-Ravel
and all-Brahms evenings.
</P>
<P>
   One could see and hear differently and make connections when
ballets, usually spread out over seasons, were clustered together.
Martins' most brilliant packaging was in the weeklong ``Balanchine
Black and White Celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   To take in this highly concentrated dose of Balanchine's
avant-garde ``leotard'' ballets, danced mostly to 20th-century
music, was to experience the City Ballet at its essence: a
modernist company, unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one premiere, Martins' ``Walton Cello Concerto,''
whose abstracted love triangle was fervently embodied by Damian
Woetzel, Miranda Weese and Alexandra Ansanelli. The choice of
William Walton's music came out of the woodwork, but the ballet was
superbly polished, deftly chiseled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
