<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NONPROFIT-MUSICALS-AR     03-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONPROFIT-MUSICALS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY SURE WERE NONPROFIT MUSICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for NEW-MUSICALS ) 
 (af)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For musicals with big bold intentions, they certainly didn't
make much noise. The first to come and go quietly was ``Parade,''
the funereal $5.5 million Lincoln Center Theater show about the
lynching of Leo Frank. Next was ``Bright Lights Big City,'' the
$500,000 musical adaptation of the Jay McInerney novel that opened
and closed at New York Theater Workshop in what seemed like the
span of a single yawn.
</P>
<P>
   The last to depart, ``Captains Courageous,'' a $1 million
musical that opened in mid-February to the equivalent of a citywide
shrug, is to vacate the Manhattan Theater Club next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Over the course of a few punishing winter
months, the musical hopes of three of New York's most successful
nonprofit theaters were smothered in a blizzard of
mixed-to-negative reviews. And the seeming indifference of
theater-goers didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the wounds to careers and reputations _ the productions
represented highly visible New York debuts for all the composers
and lyricists involved _ was the magnitude of the setbacks: an
entire season of ambitious new musicals at institutional theaters
wiped out in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Major nonprofit theaters usually pride themselves on producing
new work intended to extend theatrical forms, not necessarily to
extend into open-ended runs on Broadway. But let's be real: an
optimal outcome would be a blending of both. No large theater today
undertakes the costly and exhausting task of creating a new musical
without the hope of a big payoff, in terms of prestige, dollars or
both. And that is why the disappearance of three shows in the space
of five weeks amounts to a fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   That the collective impact of these works has been fairly
negligible suggests a breakdown in the machinery the institutions
have in place for the hard job of developing and nurturing new
musicals. Have these theaters lost the knack of connecting with
popular musical taste?
</P>
<P>
   All of them, after all, had been successful at that in the past.
In the late 1970s, the Manhattan Theater Club broke out with
``Ain't Misbehavin' ''; a decade later, Lincoln Center Theater
triumphed with a hugely entertaining revival of ``Anything Goes''
and showed, in the success of Michael John LaChiusa's much admired
``Hello Again'' in 1994, that it could impress with new work as
well. And then, three years ago, New York Theater Workshop jolted
the theater world with Jonathan Larson's Pulitzer Prize-winning
rock opera ``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   The irregularity with which hits occur indicates how difficult
it is for any theatrical enterprise _ commercial or nonprofit _ to
make them happen. And no, as delicious as the prospect might be,
not every new musical has to rank as an unqualified delight. But
``Parade,'' ``Bright Lights Big City'' and ``Captains Courageous''
are more than routine misfires.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely because of the efforts made in each case to
develop subject matter for a constituency broader than that
represented by the theaters' subscription lists that the mistakes
loom so large. (Indeed, ``Parade'' was produced by Lincoln Center
Theater in partnership with the commercial Livent, the financially
troubled presenters of the Broadway shows ``Ragtime'' and
``Fosse.'')
</P>
<P>
   Somber, plodding and occasionally inept, the three new musicals
were peculiarly joyless experiences that left the impression that
an audience's pleasure is no longer a primary concern. This raises
the question of exactly what kind of ``serious'' musicals are being
created and whether that designation is becoming synonymous with
``inaccessible.''
</P>
<P>
   You have only to try listening to the songs that Audra McDonald
recorded recently on ``Way Back to Paradise,'' her debut album of
works by LaChiusa and other up-and-coming musical-theater composers
like Adam Guettel (``Floyd Collins'') and Jason Robert Brown
(``Parade''), to get a sense of some of the musically complex if
unmelodious directions in which these young people are taking the
form.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences desperate for someone who can write tunefully, in a
pop vernacular, must turn by default to lesser talents like Frank
Wildhorn, the composer of the current Broadway productions of
``Jekyll and Hyde,'' ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' and ``The Civil
War.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from isolated moments in the three failed new productions
_ Brent Carver's intoxicating courtroom two-step in ``Parade'';
Annmarie Milazzo's affecting solo as a cooing mom in ``Bright
Lights Big City'' _ the shows rarely gave off illuminating sparks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they stumbled over what is one of the essentials of
musical storytelling: the ability not just to represent or
recreate, but to ignite the imagination, to heighten ordinary
experience through song.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, nonprofit theaters have had critical successes
with smaller chamber musicals; Polly Pen's ``Bed and Sofa'' at the
Vineyard Theater comes to mind. And arguably, the two most
significant new musicals of the 1990s, ``Rent'' and ``Bring In da
Noise, Bring In da Funk,'' were nonprofit babies, ``Noise/Funk''
having originated at the Joseph Papp Public Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Other potentially interesting projects are on the way: Ricky Ian
Gordon and Tina Landau's ``Dream True'' opens next month at the
Vineyard, while a pair of musicals by LaChiusa, ``The Wild Party''
at the Public and ``Marie Christine'' at Lincoln Center Theater,
are scheduled for next season.
</P>
<P>
   But the three missed opportunities this season are
disheartening. Perhaps the saddest is ``Bright Lights Big City'' _
for which Paul Scott Goodman wrote the music, lyrics and book _
because under different circumstances it might have beat the odds.
It is also the clearest instance of a failure of leadership. As
staged by Michael Greif, who directed ``Rent'' to greater
satisfying effect, the show never seemed to stand much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop's apparent decision to evoke memories of ``Rent''
in ``Bright Lights Big City,'' whose shared characteristics with
Larson's musical should have been confined to the theater's street
address, robbed it of a distinct identity.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, a Scottish songwriter and rock performer, knows his way
around a pop tune. But in stitching together his first major
musical, he was left disastrously to his own devices.
</P>
<P>
   The most egregious example of the disservice done him was
Greif's decision to have him roam the stage as a grungy commentator
on the degradations heaped upon the musical's slick hero, played by
Patrick Wilson. This bizarre mishandling of the material almost
came across as an act of sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Captains Courageous'' and ``Parade'' also encountered a
variety of difficulties, but one of the most fundamental was that
of scale. With only minimal attention to some basic elements, like
choreography and comic relief that traditionally have allowed
musicals to breathe in big spaces, neither work flourished in the
lavish style in which it was staged by, respectively, Lynne Meadow
and the eminent Harold Prince, who has directed some of the most
important musicals of the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The characters and plot of ``Captains Courageous'' were
undramatic, while the relentless solemnity of ``Parade'' weighed
down the story. By the second act of the latter, when the most
absorbing relationship _ that of Leo Frank (Carver) and his wife
(Carolee Carmello) _ began to deepen, it was too late. Any concern
for them had cooled in the production's atmosphere of chilly
self-importance.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that, as seems likely with ``Bright Lights Big
City,'' the strengths that the three shows might have possessed at
an earlier point were lost in the yearslong development process?
That in raising the stakes, in packaging them as big,
Broadway-style musicals, their flaws were magnified?
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that when the scale of a show matches the scope of
its ambitions, wonderful things can happen, as evidenced by the
recent artistic success of the Music Theater Group's ``Running
Man,'' which recently ended a brief appearance at Here in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The musical-theater piece, created by the poet Cornelius Eady
and the jazz composer Diedre Murray, sparely and elegantly told a
story _ not unlike that of ``Bright Lights Big City,'' incidentally
_ of a damaged young man whose promise drowns in drug use.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, ``Running Man'' has an arresting score that
is both discordant and idiosyncratic; the audience was not likely
to leave the theater whistling a familiar tune. But with six actors
onstage for just 75 minutes, it disclosed more about the human
heart than the other three shows combined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
