<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRESTLEMANIA-ART-3TAK     03-24 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLEMANIA-ART-3TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW POP HERO: A MIRAGE OF MUSCLE AND MEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 Jeff MacGregor worked in the television industry for 20 years.  
 By JEFF MACGREGOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the presidential impeachment trial is over and its
ennobling lessons in constitutional responsibility and high-minded
judicial oratory have left an impression on our American conscience
no less indelible than a Dean Martin celebrity roast featuring
Professor Irwin Corey, many of you are no doubt wondering what will
become of your favorite media analysts.
</P>
<P>
   What will the pan-pundit class have to write about now? What
will the talking heads say? How will they eke out a living? How
feed, clothe and school the young punditae? Whither our windbag
elite now that Ms. Lewinsky has spilled the beans to Ms. Walters
and recedes hereafter into the shadows at the Fawn Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K computer-collapse panic story is no good because there
are only two possible approaches (and a like number of columns or
MSNBC appearances) in it, to wit: ``It's nothing'' or ``Hoard
ammo.'' Recent books notwithstanding, the JonBenet Ramsey case will
remain a nonstarter until they hire Batman or Angela Lansbury to
ramrod the investigation, the suggestion of which might net a few
weeks of play on ``Geraldo.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloviating about the collapse of the Asian economy just isn't
very sexy, but deconstructing Hollywood's Employee of the Month
awards, the Oscars, is far too sexy and lacks the planetary,
oracular gravitas that our Sunday morning-show quarterbacks have
come to desire for themselves. Without some imaginative thinking
then, and soon, reading the bones and entrails of popular culture
is at risk of becoming real work again.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, though, for big-name pundits, their families and Ivy
League bursars throughout the Northeast, an answer has been found.
Weirdly, it may have been stumbled upon by the Rev. Jerry Falwell
in his announcement identifying the current earthly incarnation of
Beelzebub, the gist of which (and I may have this wrong) was
something like ``And I looked and behold, a pale Teletubby and his
name was Tinky-Winky and hell followed with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus arrives 1999's red-hot growth sector for media analysis:
apocalypse theory.
</P>
<P>
   Millenarianism is the belief in a battle between good and evil
at the end of the millennium that lays waste to the earth and is
then followed by a thousand years of peace and human perfection.
(Mill(italics)i(end italics)nerianism, on the other hand, is the
belief in, um, hats.) What better way for the pop-cult eggheads and
satraps to earn their living than by pointing out for us the early
warning signs of the death of civilization?
</P>
<P>
   One such harbinger, the seemingly inexplicable resurgence of
professional wrestling, is already being written about and spoken
of by those on the critical edge of the crackpot apocalypse.
Wrestlemania, apparently, is the end of the world as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   In our Age of Incivility, it should come as only a small
surprise that professional wrestling is now the hippest ticket in
town and a regular ratings juggernaut on cable television.
Consistently landing up to 7 of the top 10 spots in the weekly
cable rankings, wrestling is lately attracting the attention of
publications as diverse as The Washington Post, Variety, USA Today,
New York magazine and The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, from Washington's Beltway to the Hollywood
geltway, the lurid billion-dollar-a-year burlesque of professional
wrestling has been startling and saddening our social critics and
business writers with the news that bad taste sells.
</P>
<P>
   Professional wrestling has been a television staple since the
late 1940s. Largely ignored by television critics since then for
being too dopey or downmarket to bother reviewing, it has always
enjoyed a small but devoted following. In decaying war memorial
arenas and on regional one-hour Saturday broadcasts, wrestling was
for decades a blandly predictable battle between good (light
trunks, waxed chest) and evil (black trunks, hairy back).
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as it was both fixed and fake in a nation where one or
the other usually suffices, it had little going for it as a sport.
As entertainment it suffered from a lack of dramatic ingenuity,
relying instead on simple declamation, e.g.:
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: How about it, Vern?
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLER: I promise to (italics)crush(end italics) the evil
Baron Von Raschke this Saturday for the North American Champion's
belt at the Prom Ballroom! Grrrrrr! 4 P.M.! Grrrrrr! All seats $5!
Grrrrrr!
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: There you have it, folks!
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLER: Free parking before 3 P.M.! Grrrrrr!
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: Wow!
</P>
<P>
   The bouts themselves were just as prosaic. Stout older men
grimly banging bellies and throwing punches until the good guy
triumphed and evil sagged to the canvas exhausted. It was like
watching a fight between two beer-truck drivers after a traffic
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Variations on this basic design (four-man tag team, six-man tag
team, women, midgets, etc.) had no effect on the moral
choreography. Good guys usually won and the bad guys glowered and
vowed revenge.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
