<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1953 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRESTLEMANIA-ART-2NDT     03-24 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLEMANIA-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: vowed revenge.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So things remained until the mid-1980s, when the first
post-modern boomlet occurred in wrestling. Most of the regional
wrestling operations were consolidated into a national tour. Local
broadcasts gave way to national syndication and several small
crossover stars were born (Hulk Hogan, Jesse Ventura, Andre the
Giant).
</P>
<P>
   No longer a mom-and-pop enterprise, it was still limited to a
tiny, almost entirely male audience. The escalation in allowable
violence in all forms of entertainment meant a proportional
increase in graphic forms of hand-to-hand mayhem in the ring, and
the matches themselves became marginally more energetic and a good
deal bloodier as a result. Singlets and nicknames became more
colorful, but the scripted outbursts remained a careful study in
black-and-white.
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: How about it, Hulk?
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLER: I promise to (italics)stomp(end italics) the evil
Sheik this Saturday for the Trans American Champion's belt at the
Marine Midland Center! Grrrrrr! 7 P.M.! Grrrrrr! All seats $16!
Grrrrrr!
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: There you have it, folks!
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLER: And you kids be sure to drink your milk! Grrrrrr!
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: Wow!
</P>
<P>
   The simple binary determinism of wrestling remained the same,
and the good guy mostly won.
</P>
<P>
   As we enter professional wrestling's late-century renaissance,
though, everything has changed. Forget good guys; as in real life,
there are none. Now there are only characters portraying various
degrees of stylish, programmatic badness along a continuum that
runs from costumed sociopath to attractively rebellious antihero.
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: How about it, Steve?
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLER: Bite me.
</P>
<P>
   ANNOUNCER: Wow!
</P>
<P>
   There are five hours of this stuff on prime-time cable on Monday
nights alone. In certain demographics (males 12 to 34, for
example), wrestling even outstripped Monday Night Football last
fall. Wrestlers routinely gab with Jay Leno or horse around with
Regis and Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   April's Playboy cover bunny is a television wrestler. As you
know, a wrestler was just elected governor of Minnesota (although
I'm not sure this is part of the same trend; Minnesota has been
working its way through some community self-esteem issues ever
since the opening of ``Fargo'').
</P>
<P>
   Most telling, perhaps, is this: By the end of 1999, professional
wrestling will have begun opening its own theme restaurants. Dire
portents all, but what do they mean? How did this happen? Who do we
blame? Or, as the pundits will ask, What does this Say About Us as
a Nation?
</P>
<P>
   By shrewdly combining elements present in the most successful
contemporary American entertainments, to wit, sex, violence and a
murderous disregard for authority, professional wrestling at the
millennium has reinvented itself as a kind of antiheroic
speed-metal cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Cruel and slap-happy as a Punch and Judy puppet show, it manages
at once to synthesize every theatrical tradition from Kabuki to
vaudeville. As predictable as a passion play (every match a
simulacrum of ``suffering'' leading to ``death,'' followed quickly
by ``resurrection''), it plays on our universal need for ritualized
catharsis; the human impulse that creates narratives as disparate
as Jerry Springer, manga Japanese comic books and ancient Norse
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing all borders of taste and tradition, like Schwarzenegger
or Van Damme, American professional wrestling is now beamed to more
than a hundred other countries.
</P>
<P>
   There are two organizations driving and benefiting from this
lucrative modernization of the old form: World Championship
Wrestling and the World Wrestling Federation. The former is a Ted
Turner property and appears variously (it seems endlessly) on the
cable networks TBS or TNT. The latter, and lately the more watched
of the two, is shown on Barry Diller's USA Network and in
syndication. Both entities also produce expensive pay-per-view
versions of themselves at least once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Although the WWF is raunchier than the WCW, accounting for its
slight edge in popularity, they appear perfectly interchangeable to
the unschooled viewer. Like touring rock acts or tent revivals,
both emanate live from different arenas every night. The opening
moments include a pyrotechnic display, close-ups of scantily clad
young women (either dancing or just standing around breathing
deeply) and a long-winded recapitulation of action you may have
missed the night before in Buffalo or last week when the show was
in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   These genially moronic synopses (``He may have sustained that
groan injury at Superbrawl, but I'm sure he'll be fighting tonight
with real reckless abandonment!'') are important to the
architecture of each show, however, because they outline the
grudges, blood feuds and byzantine subplots that now lie at the
heart of professional wrestling. Hot pants, hair extensions and
tasers aside, what makes wrestling work in a way it never has
before is (italics)story.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1954 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRESTLEMANIA-ART-3RDT     03-24 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLEMANIA-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: is (italics)story.(end italics)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Complicated as a Shakespearean comedy and as absurd as anything
by Ionesco, the drama outside the ring is what's driving the new
age in wrestling. The bouts themselves remain strangely lifeless
affairs; so much so that the commercial breaks come (italics)during
the fights(end italics) so as not to interrupt the progress of the
several twining story lines that occur every week. (Paradoxically,
the presence of close-up, hand-held cameras on the ring apron and
on the arena floor reveals wrestling's physical fakery more
completely than ever before, further evidence that it depends, like
the movies, on a viewer's willing suspension of disbelief to
succeed.)
</P>
<P>
   Power, lust and greed are the staples of these weekly steroid
serials. Locker room story lines in recent weeks have included the
betrayal of a powerful father by his own son at the instruction of
a beautiful, mysterious woman; the abduction of a beautiful woman
by an evil man hungry for her attentions; the theft of a soul by
the Lord of Darkness. This isn't wrestling; it's the Metropolitan
Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows have remarkably large casts of remarkably large
performers (like ripe olives, the smallest size of wrestler seems
to be ``jumbo''), all of whom glide in and out of various factions
and splinter groups that add further complication to the dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   The NWO, or New World Order, for example, is a clique within the
WCW made up of even badder bad guys than the normal bad guys. In
the WWF, there's the Ministry of Darkness, a cult of
Satan-worshiping heavyweights who all look like dress extras from
an underfinanced production of ``Rocky Horror Picture Show.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the performers still rely on masks or costumes or
bizarre behavior to define their characters, the two biggest
breakout stars of the last year are also the simplest in their
presentation: Goldberg of the WCW and Stone Cold Steve Austin of
the WWF. Uncannily similar in appearance (goatee, shaved head,
black trunks, neck like a draft horse), each is a natural-born
action figure. Good guys by default, they are the closest things to
heroes offered by either league.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, both leagues utilize a story line wherein the
boss is the most loathed presence in the building. Vince McMahon,
head of the WWF, is one of his own most valuable characters. He is
roundly booed whenever he appears and has actually fought against
his own wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   In real life he is regarded as the P.T. Barnum of pro wrestling.
It was he who consolidated the smaller regional leagues, turned the
heat way up on sex and bad language and then marketed the product
hard to its most gullible potential audience (television
executives). If there is someone to blame for the resurrection of
professional wrestling, it's probably McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is what the pundits and critics are looking
for. Most of the coverage of the wrestling phenomenon coos and
burbles over its financial successes but then clucks its tongue at
the very nature of the product. USA Today is so worried about your
children that it printed a handy table enumerating the 1,658
instances of ``grabbing/pointing to one's crotch'' in 50 WWF
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering whether children will emulate this behavior seems a
little disingenuous at this late date. Of course they will, just as
they did with the Power Rangers and the Teen-Age Mutant Ninja
Turtles and Davy Crockett. Expect several stories in the next year
from the playgrounds of America delineating the rash of injuries
that result from pee-wee atomic drops and flyweight suplexes
inexpertly applied.
</P>
<P>
   Professional wrestling is simply the latest incarnation of our
collective historical appetite for bad entertainment. From the low
comedy of the Greeks to commedia dell'arte to the midway sideshow,
lowest-common-denominator theater has always attracted the largest,
most impressionable audiences.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point, after all, isn't it? ``But who's to blame?''
whine the pundits, for a world full of bad taste and tight clothes,
vulgar language, violence, impure thoughts and shoddy goods? We
are.
</P>
<P>
   And What That Says About Us as a Nation? A public? A television
audience? We are an idiot. The apocalypse (italics)will(end
italics) be televised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
