<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NO-FRILLS-CINEFEST-AR     03-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-FRILLS-CINEFEST-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A HOTEL OFF I-81, CANNES IT'S NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Ill., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 Ted Loos' most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about the
filmmaker Myles Berkowitz of ``20 Dates.''  
 By TED LOOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVERPOOL, N.Y. _ The phrase ``film festival'' conjures
glamorous images: the beaches of Cannes, the slopes of Park City,
Utah, and a crush of photographers aiming at the latest starlet.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Cinefest, which prides itself on offering lots of
films and not much festival. Held at a standard-issue Holiday Inn
here off Interstate 81, just northwest of Syracuse, Cinefest has
quietly developed a reputation as the un-Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   For four days, several hundred people gather to sit on banquet
chairs in the hotel ballroom and watch movies that run from 9 a.m.
until well past midnight. The films being screened are not orphans
in search of a distributor or indies hoping to generate buzz, but
rather spirits from the past: rarely seen movies from the silent
and early talkie era.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a no-frills festival,'' said Leonard Maltin, a film
historian and journalist. ``No one comes here to be seen. This
doesn't score points with anyone. You come here because you love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19th annual Cinefest, held three weeks ago amid intermittent
blizzards, featured its usual eclectic selection of oddities and
rarities. There was a Deanna Durbin musical, ``Spring Parade''
(1940), which hadn't been seen since 1946, when it was shelved by a
legal battle over authors' rights.
</P>
<P>
   There were a series of wise-cracking, tightly structured comic
mysteries that had a large audience roaring for the first time
since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thing is the rarest of the rare,'' said Phil Serling, a
decidedly down-to-earth man, who runs Cinefest with a group of 20
friends known as the Syracuse Cinephile Society. ``The reason
people come to Syracuse is that they know they're not going to get
`Casablanca' or `The Wizard of Oz.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though several films receive brief introductions, there are no
seminars, no panel discussions, no banquets and no parties at
Cinefest. ``I've had big stars call up and say they wanted to come,
but I always say no,'' said Serling, who is too discreet to name
names. ``There are plenty of other events that would love to have
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who work in the movie business and make the festival
rounds, this event is a welcome anomaly. ``It doesn't have anything
to do with other festivals,'' said Emily Russo, the co-president of
Zeitgeist Films, an independent distributor. ``It's pure cinema
pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``If you love movies, how could you not love these
movies?'' she asked. ``It's where everything came from. You see the
seeds of everything we know about film.''
</P>
<P>
   For a $50 registration fee, participants get more than 45 films
spread over four days, and many people try to see every single one.
Free popcorn fuels the bleary-eyed, though some resort to more
extreme measures. ``The key is to bring smelling salts,'' said
Robert Woodward, a diehard from Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Cinefest started in 1980 when Serling and his friends, who had
been involved with other revival festivals, decided to show movies
their way. They rented a few rooms in a local hotel, and everyone
brought a movie from their personal collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next year I started getting calls,'' said Serling.
``People said: `What are you guys doing up there? Why wasn't I
invited?'''
</P>
<P>
   The event is still run by the same close-knit group of
volunteers. Andy Eggers mans the 16-mm projector at the Holiday Inn
for every film, as he had done since the beginning, while his wife,
Lois, runs the registration desk. Eggers, whose regular job is
projectionist at the local Imax theater, says that he has
personally shown about 52 ``onlys,'' the single surviving print of
a film.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though the festival has grown, the organizers still don't
publicize it. Word-of-mouth is enough to sell out most of the
Holiday Inn's 280 rooms to guests from all over the United States
and even a few from abroad. About 900 people bought day passes to
attend at least part of this year's festival.
</P>
<P>
   Cinefest's seriousness of purpose attracts film archivists,
writers and historians _ almost anyone with a passion for the
cinematically arcane: audience members laugh heartily at period
jokes and gently correct each other on the career paths of
long-dead character actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more accumulated knowledge about film in this room
than in the rest of the world combined,'' said Maltin, who was
attending his 17th Cinefest. ``That's really no exaggeration.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people are regulars, creating the atmosphere of a college
reunion. ``There's a Brigadoon-like quality to this event,'' said
Robert Miller, a professor of film at Northern Illinois University
in DeKalb, Ill. ``You pick up conversations from the previous year
and then continue them a year later.''
</P>
<P>
   That mythical quality is heightened when festival guests are
herded onto yellow school buses and driven to the landmark Loews
State Theater in downtown Syracuse. The 3,000-seat movie palace, an
Orientalist fantasy built in 1928, is host to Cinefest's 35-mm
program each year. This year the British Film Institute sent a
series of recently restored gems from its archive.
</P>
<P>
   Two formerly lost Lon Chaney silents, ``Alas and Alack'' (1915)
and ``Dolly's Scoop'' (1916), survive only on the prints shown
here. ``Madame Pompadour'' (1928), a silent starring Dorothy Gish
that was the most expensive British film ever made at the time,
probably had not been seen since its original release.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain these hard-to-find films, Serling relies on archives
like the George Eastman House in nearby Rochester, as well as
private collectors. One anonymous collector _ no one at the
festival has ever met him or knows his name _ lends one film each
year through a third party. This year's contribution was the only
known print of ``Young as You Feel'' (1931), starring Will Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Even professionals discover films that they didn't know existed.
``It's a busman's holiday for me,'' said Patrick Loughney, head of
the Moving Image Section at the Library of Congress, which holds
250,000 films and the same number of television shows. ``It's a
good chance to meet collectors and see what's out there. So much of
film history has been preserved by private collectors and not by
the studios.''
</P>
<P>
   While Loughney comes partly for the fun of it, he also hopes to
secure donations of films to the Library of Congress. ``We're
living in the archeological era of cinema,'' Loughney said, since
many early films were lost or destroyed. ``Much of what we'll know
about film has yet to be discovered, especially about the silent
era.''
</P>
<P>
   Serling spends all year rounding up these relics so they can
come to life once more. Each silent film at Cinefest was
accompanied by a pianist who improvises scores to movies people had
never seen before and will probably never see again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can preserve films from now until Doomsday,'' said
Serling. ``But they've got to be shown, and they've got to be
talked about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
