Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Kosovo was where the 20th century's final cycle of
Balkan wars began. Now Kosovo is where they will end; not with a
peace agreement but, surely now, with the first attack by NATO in
its 50-year history on a sovereign state _ and, if the worst comes
to the very worst, with the first major European land war since
1945.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, as Serb forces continued to sack Albanian
villages, the final realistic chance of averting allied airstrikes
against Yugoslav targets vanished as first President Slobodan
Milosevic, and then the Serbian parliament which he controls,
rejected demands for a cease-fire and the deployment of a NATO-led
international peacekeeping force in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   In dramatic further confirmation that war may be at hand,
Yevgeny Primakov, the Russian prime minister, dramatically
cancelled a visit to the U.S. which was due to start Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught, which the White House said would be ``swift and
substantial,'' could be unleashed as soon as early today
(Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   In a grim interview as he left Belgrade for Brussels to report
back to NATO, the U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke made no bones of the
failure of his last-ditch mission. The circumstances, he declared,
were ``the bleakest'' he had known in his experience of negotiating
in the Balkans..
</P>
<P>
   That experience began in 1995, when Holbrooke took the Bosnia
crisis in hand, browbeat Milosevic and the other protagonists to
the conference table in Dayton, Ohio, and secured a peace which has
turned Bosnia into a virtual NATO protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   Alas Kosovo was omitted then. Four years later it has turned
into perhaps the gravest Balkan conflict of all.
</P>
<P>
   His talks had been a ``watershed moment,'' after nearly a year
of unavailing Western efforts to broker a settlement between ethnic
Albanians and Serbs, culminating in proposals put to last month's
Rambouillet conference which Belgrade refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president didn't want even to discuss either the
cease-fire or the foreign peacekeeping force, and ``fully
understood'' the consequences of that refusal, Holbrooke added. In
other words, the time for talking has run out.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, was the unvarnished message from Western capitals. In
the House of Commons the British prime minister, Tony Blair, warned
that 65,000 more Kosovars had been driven from their homes by the
latest Serb offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The West had made a solemn promise to the ethnic Albanians, and
would not permit a new humanitarian disaster in Kosovo. Nor would
it tolerate further repression by Belgrade that would probably drag
Albania, Macedonia and Bosnia _ and perhaps Greece and Turkey too _
into ``disintegration, chaos and disorder on the doorstep of the
European Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Later the prime minister even more plainly donned the mantle of
commander-in-chief, addressing ``those British pilots who may be
called into action, their families...all those people who are part
of the armed forces... I would not ask them to undertake this if I
did not believe it was necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington the mood was equally somber as Congressional
leaders of both parties rallied behind President Bill Clinton's
call for support for military action.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the well-aired misgivings of some senior U.S.
politicians, the sense was that airstrikes were all but inevitable
_ that even the master of brinkmanship Milosevic had finally passed
the point of no return.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground as well all seemed set for war. As Yugoslav and
Serb forces continued the offensive of recent days in the Drenica
valley north of Kosovo _ a strategy which had prompted some
speculation the Yugoslav president was staking out the ground for a
partition of the province _ an ominous calm descended on the
capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   After a spate of bombings, Serb police rampages, and tit-for-tat
killings in the last few days, the city was deathly quiet. The main
market and schools were shut, and the traffic was a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   Tightening the vice, the Yugoslav authorities also closed the
southern border, thus preventing Albanians fleeing to safety in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The real question Tuesday night was when the air attacks might
start. Faced with the fresh tide of refugees and Milosevic's almost
mocking intransigence, earlier waverers in the alliance like Italy,
Germany and Greece seem to have thrown their weight, however
reluctantly, behind airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is now united and prepared to carry out its warning,''
President Clinton said. ``If President Milosevic is not willing to
make peace, we are willing to limit his ability to make war.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat has been heard a dozen times; this time however it
rang true _ perhaps explaining why the Yugoslav leader Tuesday
sacked his army's security chief.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts saw the step as continuation of a purge of senior
officers opposed to a confrontation with the West which could cost
the country much precious military hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night the main political factor staying NATO's hand
disappeared when Primakov, leader of the country which is
Belgrade's staunchest ally and categorically opposed to NATO
airstrikes, called off his visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   To have launched them at the very moment Primakov was in the
Oval Office would have been an insult which even the present
wretched state of America's relations with its former superpower
rival would hardly justify.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, however, military preparations are virtually
complete. The hope now is that one crushing blow against key
military installations _ starting probably with Cruise missile
attacks against air defense and communications sites _ will suffice
to convince President Milosevic to change his mind and accept the
international peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   If not, matters could quickly escalate, even to the point where
a NATO ground invasion _ something the allies have vowed they will
never do _ was the only option left.
</P>
<P>
   That is a nightmare scenario which no NATO leader has yet
publicly confronted, but was implicit in the warning of one NATO
defense minister visiting London Tuesday, ``Kosovo is not Bosnia.
It needs a political solution; a military solution does not
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, that solution will be up to Milosevic. In 1987,
as an ambitious younger member of the Serbian Communist party's
central committee, he went to Kosovo, the spiritual cradle of
Serbia, and made the speech that launched today's Serbian
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later he stripped Kosovo, and the 90 percent ethnic
Albanian majority of its population, of its autonomy _ the autonomy
he refuses to return today.
</P>
<P>
   By then Croatia, Slovenia and Bosnia had read the Serb writing
on the wall, and, in wars greater and smaller, left Yugoslavia. But
Kosovo, where it all started, remained a tightly controlled part of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the last Balkan war, Serbia may lose even its heart. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
