<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNY-REPORT-2TAKES-NY     03-24 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNY-REPORT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK STRUGGLES WITH LEADERSHIP ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (The following story, which was transmitted and held on 3-19, is
now released) (rk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, Gov. George Pataki gave the trustees
of the chronically troubled City University of New York a new
chairwoman, and a mandate to steer the university in a new
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Less than five months later, the trustees got a golden chance to
carry out that mandate when Chancellor W. Ann Reynolds resigned
after repeated attacks from the board.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 20 months since, the opening the trustees created has
turned into a yawning gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the board failed to find a permanent chancellor. It
is not even interviewing candidates, the search process having
broken down last summer. And other top executives at the university
have drifted away one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Five of CUNY's top jobs are now filled with temporary
appointees: there is an acting chancellor, an acting deputy
chancellor, two acting vice chancellors and an acting dean for
student services. The presidencies of 5 of its 17 undergraduate
campuses are open or about to open, and at least two more
presidents have been seeking other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The departures have come as CUNY has experienced problems on
other fronts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Student enrollment has fallen. This semester's total of
193,505 students is off about 2 percent from last year, and down 9
percent from the 1994 peak of 212,634.
</P>
<P>
   _ The university is in severe financial straits. Despite rising
costs, its budget has risen little since the early 1990s after
inflation is taken into account, and state and city support has
fallen. Both the governor and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are refusing
to pay for faculty salary increases that are in the union contract
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ CUNY has come under fire, from the governor and mayor among
others, over academic standards they say are far too lax.
</P>
<P>
   _ The trustees themselves are sharply divided, lacking both
strong leadership and the confidence of elected leaders in Albany
and New York City. Last year Giuliani went so far as to appoint his
own task force, led by the former Yale president Benno C. Schmidt,
Jr., to investigate CUNY and draw up a plan for the future,
including recommendations on privatizing some of its functions. The
report is due next month.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY, the largest urban university in the United States, was
once a beacon in public higher education, and in some ways it still
burns brightly. But in other ways it is an institution under siege,
buffeted by political forces and stretched to its budgetary limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to characterize what happened before as
higher-education nirvana,'' said Patrick M. Callan, president of
the National Center for Public Policy and Higher Education, in San
Jose, Calif. ``But CUNY is now caught in the middle of a partisan,
ideological circus.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual that the trustees are political appointees. At
CUNY, the governor appoints 10 of the 17 trustees and the mayor
five. There is one faculty trustee and one student trustee.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual is the mayor's and governor's close involvement
in shaping CUNY's policies _ and in choosing a new chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the trustees' search committee forwarded three
candidates for chancellor to the governor and the mayor last summer
that the movement to find a permanent chancellor stalled. The list
did not include Peter Salins, the provost at the State University
of New York, who was said to be the mayor's and governor's first
choice. The mayor and the governor never called in the candidates
for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually boards are meant to be a buffer from the politics,''
said Joseph Burke of the Rockefeller Institute of government in
Albany. ``Here it is more like they are a conduit for the
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the governor is happy with the trustees' progress,
his chief of staff, Bradford J. Race, said on Thursday. In
particular, ace commended the passage of a hotly debated measure in
January that will bar students from bachelor's degree programs if
they need remedial work in reading, writing or mathematics,
although they can still enroll in the community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy the remedial battle seems to be over,'' Race said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the governor's office was pleased with CUNY's
chairwoman, Anne A. Paolucci, whom Pataki had attacked after he
grew dissatisfied with the slow pace of change.
</P>
<P>
   But as the trustees themselves note, much of the board's
progress has come in close, hotly contested votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still a very contentious board,'' said Herman Badillo, a
mayoral adviser who is the board's vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paolucci denies that anyone outside the board is affecting
policy. But others on the board say the mayor has been a key force
in drawing up policies like the one on remedial education. The
mayor's press office did not respond to several requests for
comment about CUNY.
</P>
<P>
   And some board meetings have been so contentious that police
officers have been called to stand guard. At several meetings,
students, faculty members and other protesters _ including a state
assemblyman _ have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Christoph M. Kimmich, the mild-mannered historian who was
appointed interim chancellor in November 1997 and had expected to
return to his job as Brooklyn College's provost long ago, has tried
to provide a calming influence and a sense of direction amid the
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall he worked with the trustees to draw up a five-year
budget proposal for Albany, rather than the usual one-year request.
This month, he led college presidents and other top administrators
on an off-campus retreat to discuss long-term planning. The
trustees may try a similar retreat later this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of my tenure, we need to set targets and engage
people in forward planning process and make sure things do get
done,'' Kimmich said. ``It may not be the norm for someone who is
in a temporary position, but I don't think we can wait.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   He has earned the respect of both faculty members and trustees,
as well as others outside CUNY, including the governor's office,
which says he has done an excellent job. Still, there is a constant
awareness that he and many of his staff are caretakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we don't like Christoph Kimmich; he's done an
unbelievably great job under the circumstances,'' said William P.
Kelly, provost at CUNY's graduate center. ``But how can you plan
when you don't know who is going to be in charge in a year or
two?''
</P>
<P>
   Badillo said the interim appointments also color the way the
university is perceived on the outside: ``You have to have a new
chancellor for the governor and the mayor to have confidence in
CUNY,'' he said. ``An interim chancellor doesn't do it, because he
doesn't have the authority to move.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trustees set up a committee to find a new chancellor in late
1997. With the help of a search firm, the committee conducted
interviews and last summer had produced a short list of finalists:
David Adamany, the former president of Wayne State University,
Richard H. Ekman, the secretary of the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation
and Warren H. Fox, the executive director of the California
Postsecondary Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
   What was most notable about the list, however, was that it did
not include the the mayor's and governor's candidate, Salins.
Although CUNY's search committee interviewed Salins, trustees on
the committee said last summer that his presentation went poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Neither CUNY's bylaws nor state or city law calls for the
governor or mayor to approve the appointment of a chancellor.
CUNY's trustees hold that power. Although the chairwoman called the
forwarding of the three candidates' names to the mayor and the
governor last summer a courtesy, other trustees say it is one more
sign of the governor's and mayor's close involvement in CUNY
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three candidates, Adamany, has since withdrawn, and
there have been no meetings of the search committee since.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paolucci, who heads the search committee, would not comment
on the events so far, but said that the search firm is supposed to
be finding more names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good candidates,'' she said, ``but we want to build up
the list. It is a very important job.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the panel say they have heard nothing about the
search's resumption, but they and others wonder if they can even
find a plausible candidate who will want the job. Some college
presidents who were approached said the position was just too
filled with political land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you get the kind of leadership you want when the
position begins to look like a municipal appointee?'' Callan asked,
referring to Giuliani's role in prescribing policy. ``The person
has got to be accountable, but not in the same way as a municipal
employee.''
</P>
<P>
   But Race, Pataki's chief of staff, said he did not think
candidates should be scared away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, anyone who takes one of these positions takes it
knowing it is a public institution, and that public officials have
a right to express their views,'' he said. ``I don't think that
should discourage anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the turmoil at the top, the university has continued to
function, often in impressive ways: the Carnegie Foundation for the
Advancement of Teaching named a Queens College professor the
state's 1998 Teacher of the Year, the third CUNY faculty member in
four years to be so honored. Two CUNY students recently won
prestigious Marshall Scholarships for study in Britain. And City
College was designated as the new home for a biomedical research
center being created by 10 New York medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Campuses are also moving ahead on new educational initiatives.
Manhattan Community College, for example, has begun to offer a
degree in multimedia programming and design. And the trustees
recently approved a new masters degree in creative writing at
Hunter College, although they sought repeated assurances that it
would not increase costs.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY is also working to improve student preparation so more
students can pass its placement tests when they arrive. It has
expanded its ``College Now'' program to 50 high schools, so 10th,
11th and 12th graders can take CUNY's placement examinations and
receive remedial help before they graduate. The university is also
expanding its intensive immersion programs for students who fail
the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say they are encouraged that current applications are
running 2 percent ahead of last year and that applicants to the
senior colleges, which are raising their own entrance requirements,
are better prepared than a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The mood on campuses is varied. While some students and faculty
applaud the attempts to remake the university, and see the turmoil
as the cost of making sweeping changes, others say they are worn
down by the constant attacks on their university, using words like
``battle fatigue'' and ``numbness'' to describe how they feel.
</P>
<P>
   Some who follow CUNY politics predict that no serious chancellor
candidate will be put forward until summer, when Pataki has the
opportunity to make new appointments to the board, solidifying
control.
</P>
<P>
   But Race said the governor's office has no such plan, and added
that he believed that the CUNY board was pressing ahead with its
search.
</P>
<P>
   Although he expressed admiration for Salins, he said the
governor had no particular candidate. ``I know Peter well, and he's
doing a great job at SUNY,'' Race said, ``but I would have an
interest in anybody with his qualities who expressed an interest in
the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
