<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALDEZ-ANNIVERSARY-SF     03-24 2659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-ANNIVERSARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VALDEZ SPILL LEAVES BITTER RESIDUE  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORDOVA, Alaska _ It was a decade ago Wednesday that the Exxon
Valdez ran aground on Bligh Reef, hemorrhaging nearly 11 million
gallons of black, viscous crude oil into the pristine waters of
Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   That single incident devastated the sound, killing hundreds of
thousands of seabirds, thousands of marine mammals and untold
numbers of fish and shellfish. Wind and tide carried the vast slick
to the southwest, sullying more than 1,300 miles of shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, one of the richest ecosystems on the planet was
transformed into a reeking charnel house, a virtual ecological
graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the sound appears well on its way to recovery _ but no
one can agree on just what ``recovery'' means.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Corp., which owns the ill-starred ship, claims the sound
shows no long-term damage from the spill, and that fish and
wildlife are at pre-spill levels.
</P>
<P>
   Government biologists believe that most key species are
rebounding to one degree or another, but maintain that the sound's
essential ecological health remains compromised.
</P>
<P>
   And in Cordova _ the biggest settlement on the sound after the
oil port of Valdez, and the heart of the region's once-thriving
fishing industry _ ``recovery'' is just an eight-letter word for
deceit. For a sense of betrayal. For a bitterness so deep and
pervasive that it has become as much an element of daily life as
the craggy Chugach Mountains that tower over the hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, local waters are blue and pellucid and the air is as
crisp and sweet as an autumn apple. Oil? There's no visible sign of
it over the 15,000 square miles of open water, tidal flats, islands
and forested littoral that constitute the sound.
</P>
<P>
   But the great slick disgorged by the Exxon Valdez lingers in the
hearts and minds of the people of Cordova, whose economic and
spiritual connection with the sound has been irrevocably altered.
</P>
<P>
   Before the spill, everyone thought that the future would always
be like the past: Plenty of fish and shellfish to catch, multitudes
of seals and birds to hunt, a sound that was both a groaning board
of food and a source of spiritual solace.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Cordova's 2,500 residents sense that the future will
never be like the past. The town's fishing fleet is little more
than half the size it was in 1988 _ down to 400 boats from 700.
After the spill, three of the town's five canneries closed,
including the biggest. Two have since reopened under new
management, but at reduced production levels. The largest cannery
remains shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   And the malaise that affects the townspeople is deep and
abiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've learned out of all this is that
technological disasters are not like natural disasters,'' said
Brian O'Neill, an acerbic, homespun Minnesota lawyer who,
representing people who live around the sound, won a $5.3 billion
punitive damages award against Exxon in federal district court in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a natural disaster, people still feel connected to their
community and the land,'' said O'Neill. ``But a technological
disaster like this severs people from the planet. The damage is
especially severe in communities like Cordova. They had a
resource-based lifestyle _ the people depended on the land, water,
fish and wildlife for their identities as much as their food.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Prince William Sound is by no means a biological
desert.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 sea otters disport in Orca Inlet next to Cordova.
Pink salmon, bolstered by government hatcheries, are nearing
pre-spill numbers. Bald eagles are back at historic populations _
they perch nonchalantly in spruce trees along the harbor, hopefully
scanning the tidal flats for a fish carcass. And halibut, a fish of
great commercial value, are thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon uses these examples to buttress its contention that the
sound is back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has essentially recovered,'' said Frank Sprow, Exxon's vice
president for environment and safety. ``The biological communities
are in good shape. The situation there is similar to what we've
found at other large spill sites. You have acute impacts, but they
are relatively short-term. The oil degrades.''
</P>
<P>
   David Page, a professor of chemistry and biochemistry from
Bowdoin College in Brunswick, Maine, has performed post-spill
scientific analyses of Prince William Sound for Exxon. He agrees
with Sprow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the spill zone recovered in two to three years,'' Page
said. ``Candidly, it was surprising how rapidly the sound
recovered. About 99 percent of the oil was completely gone by
1994.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon spent about $300 million in direct compensation to
fishermen and other residents for economic losses, and shelled out
an additional $1 billion in a civil settlement that is being used
to purchase land around the sound. The company has also prescribed
rigorous safety rules for tanker traffic and oil transport since
the spill, and has bolstered its stockpile of oil-collection booms
and storage barges.
</P>
<P>
   But Exxon is fighting the $5.3 billion punitive damages award,
saying it is excessive. The company appealed the ruling, and it is
now before the U.S. Court of Appeals. Experts close to the case say
they expect the company to appeal it to the U.S. Supreme Court if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply not warranted,'' Sprow said. ``We took
responsibility since Day One, we apologized, we moved immediately
to compensate those damaged, and we did our best to clean up the
spill.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cordova residents say that the sound is far from healed and
that Exxon is evading its responsibilities by challenging the
punitive damages. When and if Exxon pays, the money will be divided
among the region's fishermen and natives, based on estimates of the
economic losses they have sustained.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sound's important commercial species have recovered
and others haven't. Unfortunately, the one that's doing the best _
pink salmon, which is at about 90 percent of its pre-spill levels _
is no longer esteemed in the marketplace. Prices for the fish have
crashed, a result of farmed Atlantic salmon from Chile and
Scandinavia flooding the world market. And herring _ still an
extremely valuable fishery, because the Japanese pay top prices for
the roe _ remains at very low levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the spill, my dad bought a salmon permit for
$320,000,'' said Rob Maxwell, who manages Redden Marine, a maritime
supply store and net mending facility, with his brother Mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sold it three years ago for $30,000,'' Maxwell said. ``Then
he lost his boat. Basically, he's lost his entire retirement. He's
65 now, and living on Social Security. So when we see Exxon
fighting the punitive ruling, it makes us pretty mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob and Mike both still fish, but they don't know for how long.
``We're just this far from losing everything,'' said Mike,
separating his thumb and forefinger by a quarter-inch. ``Unless
Exxon pays up, we're finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fishermen have managed to hang on to their boats, but they
are hardly in a celebratory mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going out, but we're not optimistic,'' said Virgil
Carroll, who repaired hydraulic lines last week with his son Doug
on their purse seiner, the Miss Carroll, in preparation for the
spring herring season.
</P>
<P>
   The total herring fishery has plummeted from 135,000 metric tons
before the spill to about 30,000 tons today. ``The herring biomass
is still low out there, and our quota from our fish processor is
only 30 tons,'' Carroll said. ``It isn't going to be a great
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova residents say their beef with Exxon isn't just about
money. They miss the flush times, but they mourn the loss of the
region's extraordinarily abundant wildlife even more. The sound,
they say, was once infused with magic. Now, much of that magic has
been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not the same out there,'' said Bud Janson, a Tlingit
native fisherman, as he nosed his boat, the Fish &AMP; Game, out of
Cordova harbor. ``Birds, marine mammals, a lot of fish and
shellfish species _ they're all down. There's more on our side of
the sound, which wasn't hit as hard as the west side. But it's
still not what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The spill delivered a particularly debilitating blow to natives,
because it has restricted their access to traditional foods. Given
a choice, said Janson, most natives will subsist almost entirely on
wild foods _ game, fish, shellfish, sea vegetables and berries.
Seal meat is especially important because of its high fat content
and its role in native rituals and feasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people are afraid to eat the seals now, because they
migrate and you don't know if they've been eating fish that were
contaminated from some (oily) pocket,'' he said. ``It's a terrible
thing, to be afraid of the food that has always sustained you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, said Janson, is the way the spill has undermined
native traditions. ``You can't teach your kid how to hunt and fish
for traditional foods if you can't find those foods, or if you're
afraid to eat them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If some good came out of the spill, it is in the form of the
land purchased by a trust established by the state and federal
governments with the $1 billion civil settlement. About 650,000
acres of inviolate temperate rain forest and riverine habitat along
the sound have been bought for preservation, mostly from native
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   But even this is not without controversy. Twenty years ago, the
native corporations acquired vast tracts as part of a settlement
with the federal government. The land represented a guarantee of
both continued access to subsistence hunting and fishing as well as
potential profits in the form of natural resources, such as timber.
</P>
<P>
   Now many natives are questioning the wisdom of selling their
land, even if it's for a good cause. This is especially true in
Cordova. The town's population is 20 percent native, representing
the largest settlement of indigenous people on the sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose the land, everything becomes very shaky,'' said
Patience Andersen Faulkner, a Chugash native who is the housing
coordinator for the Chugash Alaska Corp. ``Many of the native
corporations made the decision to sell because they're desperate,
they're just trying to survive. It's a terrible position to be
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon says the only place to find significant oil is at Sleepy
Bay, a northward facing inlet on LaTouche Island that has extensive
areas of beach and cobble contaminated by subsurface oily residue.
So many reporters have visited the site that locals call it ``Media
Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   The company and many of its scientific contractors say the oil
in Sleepy Bay has negligible environmental impact. ``If you took
all the individual little oil paddies and blobs at Media Beach,
you'd have an area the size of a basketball court,'' said Bowdoin
College biochemistry professor Page.
</P>
<P>
   But many independent and government biologists say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't paint a doom-and-gloom picture of the sound, because
it is definitely getting better every year as storms come in and
churn up and disperse the oil that remains,'' said Stanley ``Jeep''
Rice, a senior toxicologist with the National Marine Fisheries
Service who has headed several studies of the Exxon Valdez spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``But having said that, there is still oil out there, and it's
in several places, not just Sleepy Bay,'' Rice said. More
ominously, he noted, recent studies by his team demonstrate that
even minute traces of oil are far more toxic to aquatic life than
previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's group sprayed gravel with small quantities of oil, placed
fertilized pink salmon eggs on the gravel, then immersed the gravel
in running water. A control test was simultaneously conducted with
eggs hatched on unoiled gravel. Researchers noted how many eggs
died in both gravel plots. They then inserted tiny metal ID tags in
the noses of the fish that hatched, and released them to the sound.
When the fish returned two years later to spawn, researchers
compared the mortality and deformity ratios of the two groups.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Fewer fish from the oiled gravel returned. And those
that did showed a dramatically higher ratio of tumors, lesions and
deformities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this basically means is that oil is toxic to fish eggs
and larvae at spectacularly lower levels than we thought,'' said
Rice. ``It affects them at the parts per billion range rather than
the parts per million range that was previously assumed.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the study points to the essential reason
behind the persistent decline of several of the sound's most
important species.
</P>
<P>
   ``The link between trace levels of oil and damaged plankton,
eggs and larvae is very strong,'' said Riki Ott, a marine biologist
and former fisherwoman who lives in Cordova. ``That has
particularly severe consequences for a fish like herring, which are
on a seven- to eight-year cycle. Once they're down, it takes them a
long time to get back up. And if they're not getting annual
recruitment because their eggs and larvae are being damaged, the
stocks can be permanently depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   That has consequences for the entire sound, said Ott.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything eats herring,'' she said. ``Salmon, halibut, seals,
otters, birds _ even big herring eat little herring. They're rich
in fat, making them a tremendous calorie reservoir that keeps
everything going. Without them, it's a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Cordova's woes can be blamed on the spill, of course.
One of the few things that fishermen and Exxon agree on is that
warm water incidents like El Nino may be depressing some fishery
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some species were already in decline before the spill,
including harbor seal, shrimp, king crab and tanner crab. It is not
clear whether the spill exacerbated those trends. And global market
forces, such as the decline in salmon prices, are also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Ott thinks Cordova has to diversify to survive _ but only in
ways that are environmentally sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a heli-ski company that just came in, and we have a
successful marketing program for Copper River king and sockeye
salmon, which are recognized in the Lower 48 for their high
quality,'' she said. ``We need to add value to our other products _
specialty smoked salmon and locally processed roe for the sushi
market, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Cordovans aren't sure that's the best thing for the
town. They say oil _ properly developed and rigorously regulated _
must remain a significant part of the sound's economic mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska has always had a resource-based economy _ fish, gold,
oil, timber,'' observed Margy Johnson, a former mayor of the town
and the owner of its largest hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has always been what has sustained us,'' she said. ``We
don't want _ nor are we set up for _ industrial-strength tourism.
Generally, we have a superb environmental record in this state. If
we don't develop our oil, development will go to the (Middle East
and the republics of the former Soviet Union). And they don't have
our environmental regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 10th anniversary of the spill has Cordova's residents
grimly contemplating the past, it also has them apprehensively
surveying the future. Supertankers continue to ply the sound daily.
And despite the new safety measures, residents feel that another
disastrous accident could happen at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, we didn't know what a spill like this could
mean,'' said Janson, the native fisherman, as he guided his boat
past a pod of sea otters munching on tube worms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we do. I don't care how many tugs they use now _ what
happens if they have a bum tanker that just happens to break up? Or
say there's a quake, and the (trans-Alaska oil) pipeline ruptures _
it crosses several major tributaries of the Copper River. Every
day, you wake up worrying. What will happen next time?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
