 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 425 - March 24, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 425 -- March 24, 1999 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. BORN TO BE BLUE Drug addict, womanizer, blind man, black man
and musical visionary - all could describe Ray Charles. Nelson
George reviews Michael Lydon's 'Ray Charles - Man and Music' an
exhaustive biography of the R&AMP;B legend and his climb from the
depths of the Depression to the top. From The New York Times Book
Review. 1,000 words. 2. CAJUN SPICE There's music playing down in
the Louisiana bayous. People are dancing on their porches in the
sultry heat, or sipping mint juleps and tapping their feet in time
to familiar Cajun rythms. With its blend of traditional Cajun
music, zydeco, jazz, rock, blues and surf rhythms, the band
BeauSoleil is the sound of Louisiana. By Tamara Conniff. BPI. 800
words + photo. 3. AT HOME WITH BRIAN WILSON High in the Hollywood
hills, tucked in a private, gated neighbourhood, lives Brian
Wilson, the composer and child-like spirit behind the Beach Boys.
Widely perceived as an eccentric genius, Wilson, 56, is very open
about his emotional problems - he's been called an LSD casualty and
reportedly suffered physical abuse as a child. Interview by Steve
Morse. From The Boston Globe. 1,300 words + photo. 4. DANGEROUS
'INTENTIONS' The scandalous 18th century novel 'Les Liaisons
Dangereuses' has been filmed three times before. Now movie version
No. 4, ``Cruel Intentions,'' is sure to stir up trouble. The story
of seduction, corruption and betrayal has been updated to the
modern-day world of rich kids in New York. The film is heavy on sex
and stars teen favourites Sarah Michelle Gellar and Ryan Philippe.
By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo 5. THE 'LAW' OF
INCREASING RETURNS In the movie 'The Player,' (1992) a movie-studio
executive suggests eliminating writers from the creative process.
After all, he argues, it's easy to come up with stories - simply
pick any article out of a newspaper. It was satire then, but ``Law
&AMP; Order,'' one of the most successful shows on U.S. television, has
turned the idea of ``ripped from the headlines'' plots into a
weekly triumph. By Simon Houpt. From TV Guide Canada. 1,300 words +
photo. 6. JOSEPH FIENNES TACKLES SHAKESPEARE Joseph Fiennes played
William Shakespeare in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' voted the Best
Picture Oscar for 1998. For once, the younger Fiennes escapes his
brother's (Ralph) shadow, proving his own merit as a master of both
light comedy and passionate romance - and as a Hollywood hunk.
Interview by Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
STEVEN SPIELBERG Steven Spielberg has been so uniquely successful
that four of his films were included on the American Film
Institute's recently released honour role of the 100 best American
films ever. ``I was honoured to be on the list,'' says Spielberg,
``but I immediately called the AFI and volunteered two of my films
back in exchange for two others.'' (He told them they could have
``Jaws'' and ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' back in exchange for a
couple of his favourites - a Preston Sturges comedy and a Marx
Brothers film.) Interview by Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
TELEVISION GOES HOLLYWOOD : TURN-OF-THE-CENTURY
</P>
<P>
   TV TURNS THE CAMERA ON ITSELF Any day now, someone will announce
a television show that has no cast or setting - just two cameras
filming each other filming each other filming each other ... But
can it be healthy for the world of entertainment if its main
subject is increasingly itself? By David Kronke. TV Guide Canada.
1,300 words + photo. 9. SWEET, YOUNG AND SAVAGE : EMILY BERGL ON
'THE RAGE,'
</P>
<P>
   THE STAGE AND THE WAGES OF STARDOM On March 11, Emily Bergl, 23,
made her Broadway debut, co-starring with Laurence Fishburne and
Stockard Channing in ``The Lion in Winter'' (she plays Alais, the
French princess who is also the mistress of England's Henry II.)
The very next day she made her feature film debut in ``The Rage :
Carrie 2,'' the sequel to Brian De Palma's 1976 horror hit.
Interview by Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo. Please fax to Paris
33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81
