<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2131 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLY-WEEK-PAIN-NYTSF &LR;      03-24 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLY-WEEK-PAIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY AND PUBLIC PIETY OFFER A HOLY WEEK LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEMPHIS -- For many people, the recent Amtrak crash in Illinois
was just another sad story reported one night and forgotten the
next. For those of us in Memphis, however, the story has lasted
longer.
 &HT;    Memphis was a stop along the train's route. Several local
families had members injured or killed. The most heartrending story
was of two sisters, ages 8 and 10, who died in the sleeping-car
fire.
 &HT;    In the days preceding their funeral, the parents, members of one
of the city's prominent evangelical churches, appeared on numerous
news programs professing faith in Christ and their confidence in
their daughters' salvation.
 &HT;    Reporters repeatedly commented on their deep faith with one
saying, ``If you miss faith in this story, you miss the story.''
 &HT;    It was impossible to miss the faith story in a Bible-belt town
like Memphis. Sadly, however, the faith presented by the parents
and pastors and the pundits did not seem much more than public
piety. A chance to witness about Jesus with the cameras on.
 &HT;    It pains me to say such a thing about suffering parents -- only
God knows how much they must be suffering. But their public display
of faith shocked me -- as I suspect it shocked Katie Couric on
their ``Today'' show interview.
 &HT;    Instead of tears and anger, they calmly spoke of accepting
Jesus. The mother even said she was ``happy'' for her daughters now
in heaven.
 &HT;    No questioning God's goodness? No doubt? No turning away from
the media glare in grief? No. Keep smiling and talk about Jesus on
NBC. Watching them, I confess I felt more embarrassed than
sympathetic.
 &HT;    The girls were not the only victims of this tragedy. The parents
also have been victims -- victims of bad theology.
 &HT;    Their church promotes this bad theology. Skip over the difficult
questions. Do not worry about pain. God is in control. Everything
is God's will. Come to Jesus and get saved. Your heavenly reward is
what matters.
 &HT;    Jesus, however, neither taught nor lived this theology.
 &HT;    Certainly Holy Week should remind Christians that theology with
easy answers is not God's way.
 &HT;    Jesus taught that his way was fraught with tension. He commanded
his followers to love God and love their neighbors as themselves.
He ordered his disciples to give up family and fortune -- and even
themselves -- to follow God.
 &HT;    He dined with the most objectionable people, touched
untouchables, and embraced outcasts. He broke nearly every rule of
polite religious society. And when cornered about his upsetting
behavior, he answered his critics with riddles and parables. The
way he advocated so threatened the authorities that they executed
him for treason.
 &HT;    Holy Week reminds Christians that Jesus' way was not easy. Jesus
walked a way of sorrow, the way of the cross. His way winds through
doubt, rejection, suffering, and death. He begged, ``Take this cup
from me.'' Instead, he drank from the cup of God's absence: ``My
God, my God, why have you forsaken me?''
 &HT;    Christianity is not a cheerful religion. Holy Week is a
wrenching reminder that the Christian faith is dark and dangerous,
a faith lived for and in the world that the world despises.
 &HT;    It is not easy. It was not easy for Jesus. It is not easy for
those who follow him.
 &HT;    In his new book, ``The Ironic Christian's Companion,'' Patrick
Henry writes, ``The gospel is no neurotic refusal to face death. It
is just the opposite -- a refusal to evade it. God died ... God has
gotten through to the other side by going through despair to get
there.''
 &HT;    The surprise of all this, of course, that this dark way
eventually leads to life. Holy Week leads to Easter -- but only
after loneliness and death. Bad theology gets there too quickly,
passing through death to resurrection without skipping a beat.
 &HT;    Even Jesus was dead for three days. And he was God. Surely, we
humans must pause and listen to the lessons of darkness before we
proclaim the victories of heavenly joy.
 &HT;    If we wait and listen, allowing suffering to shape our souls,
then we will not have facile answers.
 &HT;    I, too, feel certain those little girls are safe in God.
Perhaps, however, this was not the moment to say so. Perhaps we all
need to live with the sorrow and mystery of untimely death to
better love and serve God and God's people. We should not evade
death. We must refuse to evade it.
 &HT;    Who can say what could come from such tragedy? I do not know and
pray I will never know from personal experience.
 &HT;    I do know, however, that we would all be better off if not
victimized by bad theology that bypasses human pain.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
