<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    40 years of caring by `The Sweethearts'
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Recently, we celebrate the 40th
anniversary of Las Novias Society in Palm Beach County. Young and
sassy, the 12 women who started the club in 1959 thought ``The
Sweethearts'' in Spanish translation an appropriate
self-description with sufficient panache to distinguish them from
the many other local women's groups in our community.
</P>
<P>
   Many clubs survive because they have national affiliation or
prominent status likely to enhance one's resume when applying for a
job or vying for awards. Las Novias' appeal is more personal. It
has survived four decades mostly because it maintained a core of
members who resolve that committed friendship unified in action
best serves the needs of community.
</P>
<P>
   Though membership has waxed and waned, today there are 22 active
members. Monthly meetings are formal, with a printed agenda
distributed along with financial reports and minutes that are
likely to be scrutinized carefully and corrected in minute detail.
Every protocol and anticipated need of the group, from membership
intake procedures to benevolence guidelines, has been codified in a
handbook. Las Novias has indeed come a long way from the loosely
structured group a dear friend and club founder (now deceased)
invited me to join in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   In those days we met bimonthly. The business meeting was a
free-for-all discussion of issues and projects, with the agenda
honored more in departure-from than in adherence-to. Still, we were
able to accomplish goals. We donated to community charities such as
the Shoe Fund for needy children and sponsored deserving youngsters
chosen to go on the annual school patrol trip to Washington but
unable to pay their way. Then as now, we also gave an annual
monetary scholarship award to a graduating senior.
</P>
<P>
   And we had fun: Our ``Mean Jeans'' dances at the Sunset Lounge
provided opportunities for women who came of age during the '50s to
wear jeans to an evening affair, a real breakthrough at the time.
And our annual Super Bowl party, complete with soul foods such as
chitterlings, became a coveted invitation.
</P>
<P>
   As did other members, I belonged to other organizations _ a
sorority and civic and professional clubs. Still, I needed Las
Novias' intimate social crucible to grow in understanding of other
women of different interests and temperaments. The camaraderie
provided a respite from workplace tensions. Also, I learned as much
about entertaining from the club sister who set a perfect table as
from the one who burned the bread, scraped it off and served it
with good cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the club developed formal benevolence guidelines, I
felt buoyed during family crises as members spontaneously responded
to my needs. One of my most vivid memories of such support occurred
in 1981, while I was recovering from a second cancer surgery.
Having been initially misdiagnosed by a doctor before going for
treatment, I was overwhelmed with fear. Panic-stricken and feeling
more tired and alone than I ever had, I was re-energized by three
club sisters who after a full workday visited me. Their joking and
teasing transformed my fear to confidence that I need never feel
isolated or without caring friends.
</P>
<P>
   So this morning at our annual Spring Brunch, now an established
community tradition, Las Novias will celebrate 40 years of
friendship with each other and service to our community through
births, deaths, divorce and other transitions. As we showcase the
talents of local youngsters, we take special pride in other
accomplishments such as ``Project Imagination,'' a monthly Saturday
activity day at U.B. Kinsey/Palmview School of the Arts for
students and all youngsters in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Many among our guests also have long allegiances to local
neighborhood clubs, the kind that meet a personal need while
keeping us focused on the unique needs of our community. Las Novias
prays that its survival, strong and vibrant, will help keep the
tradition alive.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
