<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Put a garage band in that new hangar
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Now, here's a sour note regarding the music
situation at the new Austin-Bergstrom International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   No amateur garage bands need apply to have their tunes played in
the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   No garage bands in the airport of the Garage Band Capital of the
World?
</P>
<P>
   That frosts my petunias. The people who are putting the airport
together have been beating their chests about the Austin flavor
they've put into the place.
</P>
<P>
   And they're excluding garage bands?
</P>
<P>
   In a town where the hat is passed more than it is worn, this is
a major blunder.
</P>
<P>
   This would be like Milwaukee excluding bratwurst, Boston
ignoring beans or Amarillo coming out against beef.
</P>
<P>
   City officials should reconsider and have a special ``Garage
Band Night'' once a week at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the new airport will feature recorded Austin music in the
Barbara Jordan Passenger Terminal. I'll admit that's a step up from
the ``Mantovani's Greatest Hits'' that you usually hear in
airports. But if your work isn't on a CD and your song isn't
published, your band won't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   That means no garage bands. That's preposterous. Garage bands
are as big a part of Austin culture as antihistamine abuse, allergy
season and driving without your directionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport asked for recognizable favorites,'' explained
Austin composer David Murray, who was hired by the city to do the
initial screening of the music played at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is requiring bands who apply to send in sheets of their
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrics? Austin bands are supposed to have lyrics?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know if we can have a hell or a damn in there,''
Murray said. ``You never know who you might offend at a public
place like the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Heck, under that kind of scrutiny, the Kingsmen couldn't have
snuck ``Louie, Louie'' past the baggage carousel.
</P>
<P>
   Just think what this city would be like if there were no garage
bands. If it weren't for Austin's garage bands, there would be no
Black Cat Lounge, no Joe's Generic Bar, and the expression ``Keep
your day job'' would never have been invented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think probably the biggest objection to garage bands at the
airport is that they're really worried about people being scared of
crashing airplanes,'' joked Ray Benson, of the Grammy Award-winning
Texas swing band Asleep at the Wheel. ``Some of those garage bands
sound like jet planes going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson is, however, pro-garage band because he used to play in
one called _ you got it _ Asleep At the Wheel. In 1974, the band
practiced in a garage on St. Elmo Road in South Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In most cities, people talk about one- or two-car garages. In
Austin, garage bands are so prevalent that we speak of having one-
or two-band garages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who do you know who uses their garage to put cars in?'' Benson
asked. ``What's a garage for? It's to store junk or rehearse.''
</P>
<P>
   So if we want the new airport to have an Austin tone, we've got
to include garage band music. May I suggest some heavy metal by the
metal detector?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
