A2146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX     03-24 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hate in the Heartland
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The way Lt. William Willcox saw it, the
protesters and the Klansmen weren't so much polar opposites as
parasites. One couldn't exist without the other. ``If those people
weren't there, this thing would be over in 10 minutes,'' said
Willcox, casting an appraising eye at the 200-plus protesters,
shouting obscenities through bullhorns. ``They're giving the Klan
just what they want _ an audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday's KKK rally at the Kettering Civic Center resembled
nothing so much as an open-air Jerry Springer Show, with
choreographed fistfights and dueling profanities (none of them
bleeped). The few residents who turned up for peaceful protest were
appalled, not only by the hateful spewings of the Knights of the
White Kamellia, but also by the crude, combative behavior of the
counter-demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters belonged to Anti-Racist Action, a
Columbus, Ohio-based group known for getting in the face of hate
groups. Some were nearly as sartorially challenged as the Klan,
wearing black Jesse James-style bandannas to avoid being recognized
by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose streets? Our streets!'' they chanted. By yelling
profanity-laden remarks over a megaphone, meanwhile, they cleared
the streets of any self-respecting citizens for miles around. While
most of the protesters were young, and many probably sincere, the
overall impression was that of a mob spoiling for a fight, ready to
rumble. They carried signs declaring, ``This is a hate-free zone,''
yet spewed venom at the Klan, an epithet for an epithet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Klan is evil and it has to be confronted, but it needs to
be confronted in love,'' said Dave Mehaffie of Dayton, who brought
three of his sons for what he hoped would be prayerful protest.
``It breaks my heart to see this, and it breaks God's heart. We
must be careful how we stand up to evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Evil it was. This was not the new Klan, trying to soft-pedal its
image. Of the three Klan rallies I've covered, this was the most
vile. The Klansmen spat out epithets like poison darts. When they
ran out of things to say, they gave a stiff-armed salute and
screamed ``White power!'' or ``Go home, race traitors!''
</P>
<P>
   The level of ``discourse'' was so low that, after the initial
shock, it bordered on the farcical, even tedious. Then one of the
Klansmen would say something to remind you that evil, however
pathetic, is very real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not condone dragging Negroes behind pickup trucks,'' one
Klansman said. ``It decreases the resale value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``James Byrd was a crackhead smoker...with an arrest record as
long as your arm, who saw fit to find himself behind a pickup
truck,'' said another. ``And they've elevated that dude to a
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   This drew applause from the 11 supporters in the fenced-in
pro-Klan spectators section.
</P>
<P>
   James Roesch, the 18-year-old former Kettering resident who
organized the rally, said that he was married Saturday. His bride
is 17-year-old April Letney of Jasper, Texas. The pair met at what
Roesch referred to as a ``cross lighting'' in Jasper after Byrd's
murder.
</P>
<P>
   How does a community respond to such hatred?
</P>
<P>
   Jenni Roer answers in two words: Stay away. The Washington Twp.
woman, executive director of the Dayton region of the National
Conference for Community and Justice (NCCJ), helped to organize the
event. National leaders for NCCJ and the Southern Poverty Law
Center unanimously recommended the same approach to Klan rallies:
Stay away. Organize an alternative event at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``ARA plays into the hands of the Klan,'' Roer said. ``They're
very misguided, very confrontational, and just provide for more
publicity for the Klan.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, 20 organizations planned a community celebration of
diversity at John F. Kennedy Elementary School. ``We worried that
not enough people were going to come, and the next thing we knew,
there weren't enough chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Roer did the math: fewer than 12 Klan supporters vs. more than
1,200 at the celebration. ``The community event by far represents
the region,'' she said. ``We have a long way to go throughout all
our communities. The good that has come from this is that Kettering
has an even stronger commitment to fight racism.''
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful moment occurred when Joyce Dumtschin, a cantor
with Temple Beth Or in Washington Twp., sang, ``Let There Be Peace
on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, spontaneously, row by row, the audience stood up,
swaying, holding hands, singing along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The example of Anti-Racist Action is not how you solve
things,'' Dumtschin said. ``You do something else, and you set an
example. You don't come down to their level.''
</P>
<P>
   In another part of Kettering, imported demonstrators chanted,
``Whose Streets? Our Streets!'' and gave the rag-tag White Knights
of the Kamellia exactly what they wanted _ an audience.
</P>
<P>
   At Kennedy Elementary School, the people of Kettering proved who
really owns these streets.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
