r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFORMATION-RACE25-CO     03-24 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFORMATION-RACE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet vs. Library: Research race proves faster isn't always
better
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At the starter's gun, it looked like a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet team blasted out of the blocks into a commanding
lead by coming up with Merrill J. Bateman, president of Brigham
Young University, in one minute, 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The library team stumbled on their first step. Not only did it
take them nearly six minutes to find the name Eric B. Shumway, it
turned out to be the wrong name. Shumway is president of BYU's
Hawaii campus, not the whole university.
</P>
<P>
   But the Battlin' Bibliophiles stood up to the Online Onslaught
by nailing Christoph Willibald Ritter von Gluck's birth date and
Jeffrey Leonard's home run total.
</P>
<P>
   After three laps, the library team was just 45 seconds and one
wrong answer down with seven more chances to make up ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle of the Century ... no, the Battle of the Millennium
was heating up.
</P>
<P>
   Since ancient times, people doing research have traveled to
libraries to tap the wisdom of the ages. These days, though, people
tend to travel no farther than to the nearest computer.
</P>
<P>
   But is the Net always the best way to do research?
</P>
<P>
   To answer that question once and for all, two teams of student
volunteers were assembled to answer the same set of 10 questions _
one team using the resources of the main branch of the Dayton and
Montgomery County Public Library and the other using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Who won? That depends on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet team was a little faster. It took them a total of
one hour, 11 minutes and 15 seconds to answer the 10 research
questions. The library team took about 10 minutes longer at an
hour, 21 minutes and 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But the library team was more accurate. After flubbing the first
question, the library team found correct answers to each of the
next nine. The Internet team answered two questions incorrectly and
failed to find an answer to a third question within the allotted
time.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson seems to be this: The Internet is a great source for
quick information on certain subjects and clearly is superior for
finding up-to-date data. But the library often is just as quick or
quicker, and its information may be more trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Wright State University English lecturer Jane Blakelock said she
encourages her students to use both the library and the Internet
for research. Her students developed and maintain a rock music Web
site, and they use all available tools to keep the site up to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a research facility here where you have an area full
of Internet computers then you walk out into a room with windows
and reference books,'' Blakelock said. ``Combining sunlight, books
and computers seems to be a very good direction to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE RACE DEMONSTRATED
</P>
<P>
   The research race was conducted on two consecutive days; the
library team was timed answering questions one at a time one day,
and the Internet team was timed answering the same questions the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   The library team was allowed to use any library resources
including reference desk personnel. Team members could use
electronic card catalogs and computers linked to other library
databases. They were not allowed to use the library's Internet
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet team used three computers with fast Internet
connections. They could use any search engine or online directory
they chose. Team members also had access to dictionaries to help
with spelling words for their searches.
</P>
<P>
   Observing the work of both teams and analyzing the results
illustrated some basic rules of research. Here are a few of those
rules:
</P>
<P>
   _ Libraries are better organized than the Internet. It's
sometimes hard to tell whether a library or the Internet has the
most information. But it's clear that libraries are better designed
to lead researchers to the information they seek. Using the
Internet often means wading through tons of irrelevant material
before zeroing in on what you need. Simple information requests on
Internet search engines often generates thousands of sites with the
one site you want placed well down the list.
</P>
<P>
   _ Internet information is more up to date. The Internet blew the
library away on pop culture questions about Buffy the Vampire
Slayer and Hootie and the Blowfish. It also gave reliable
information about the current president of Brigham Young
University. The library team found a 1999 edition of a college
information book but apparently misread the entry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not all Internet sites are created equal. The Internet team
routinely ignored Web sites that appeared to be posted by amateurs
or by companies trying to sell things. When possible they looked
for sites maintained by government agencies and universities. They
also liked sites from news organizations such as CNN. They used
sites established by fans only to get leads that helped them find
more authoritative sources. Blakelock said Internet users must
figure out who put the information on the site and what their
biases may be before accepting the information as factual.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go for primary rather than secondary sources. The Internet
team got information on the Asian population of San Antonio from a
Tejas cultural Web site. The site said the information was from the
1990 Census, but it turned out to be wrong. The library team got
its information direct from the agency responsible for gathering
the numbers; the team looked in a Census Bureau data book.
</P>
<P>
   _ The library is more than books. The library team had a hard
time finding information on ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' in printed
material. The team answered the Buffy question by using the
Electronic Library system. They used library computers to tap into
databases of recent newspaper and magazine articles. Most libraries
also have Internet terminals, but you may not be able to use them
for more than 30 minutes at a time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Become proficient with more than one Internet search tool. The
members of the Internet team tended to prefer Search.com as the
engine to find information online. On some occasions, team members
directed all three computers to the same search engine to find the
same sites and ended up in the same blind alleys. They were much
more efficient when they used Search.com, Yahoo and other search
engines all at once.
</P>
<P>
   _ Old information you know to be in a book is usually best found
at the library. Despite the speed of the Internet, you still must
find pages, wait for them to load, scan them for relevance and then
start over if you don't find what you want. You can flip the pages
of a book in a fraction of the time, and the information is likely
to be more trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet can be distracting. The Internet offers music,
video and other flashy effects along with printed material. It's
easy to get caught up with a lively interactive site and lose track
of what you're seeking. On the other hand, using the Internet to
write a report, for example, may help you find pictures and other
visual material to improve your work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just because the Internet has a lot of information, that
doesn't mean it has the exact information you want. The most
surprising result in the research race was the failure of the
Internet to supply a closing price for a particular stock on a
particular day. The Internet is treasured as a resource for
investors, and you might think such information would be easy to
find. Instead the Internet researchers found only graphs that
showed the stock's movement over time. That's great for investors
but was useless for our researchers. The library team found the
answer by leafing through old newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The research materials are only as good as the researcher.
Both teams made errors in which they found a good source for the
information but still failed to get the correct answer. The library
team got a name of a university official from the wrong campus, and
the Internet team apparently miscalculated the time difference
between Naples and Houston though they found a map that showed the
correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   THE TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   The research teams were made up of five students from the
University of Dayton and five students from Dayton's Belmont High
School for Computer Technology and Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Dayton is becoming one of the most wired
campuses in America and will require all students to have a
computer by next year. Belmont's magnet school program focuses on
computer use.
</P>
<P>
   All the students involved in the race had extensive experience
with doing research online.
</P>
<P>
   At the library:
</P>
<P>
   Joe Barger, UD, freshman: Online every day at UD.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Beer, UD, junior: Knew just where to look, Total Baseball,
for Jeffrey Leonard's home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Kilby, Belmont, junior: Noted that not everyone has access
to an Internet computer, but the library is available to all.
</P>
<P>
   Lonista Taylor, Belmont, junior: Tracked down Hootie lyrics
through the library's audio-visual department.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanica Williams, Belmont, senior: Working at the library
reminded this avid Internet user how quick library research can be.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   Renata Napier, UD, freshman: ``I'm looking for Asian population,
and they're talking about seat belts!''
</P>
<P>
   Aimee McCreary, UD, freshman: Pointed out that Internet has
excerpts while periodicals at the library have complete articles.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Palmer, Belmont, junior: Directed the action while her
brother Brandon typed at the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Palmer, Belmont, junior: Key player in translating the
Spanish sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ward, UD, freshman: Aggressively attacked the K Mart
question but was ultimately stymied
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
