<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-VIDEOPHONE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Screenphone lets your fingers do the surfing
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The future of the Internet is probably not in
traditional computers; it will be in other devices that allow
access to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   One such product will be the Alcatel Internet Screenphone. The
screenphone, due on the market this summer, will allow one-button
access to the Internet from any desktop in your home or office.
</P>
<P>
   The screenphone is about the size of a large office phone. But
in the area that would normally hold buttons for various phone
lines, the screenphone will have a small color video screen.
</P>
<P>
   The screen is touch-sensitive, so online users will be able to
navigate on the Internet simply by touching icons on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   When the screenphone is not online, the screen controls normal
telephone functions such as speed dialing and caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   The phone also has a keyboard that retracts into the body of the
phone when the Internet is not being used.
</P>
<P>
   The company also promises foolproof installation. Consumer will
be able to pull it out of its package, plug it into a phone jack
and a power receptacle and go online immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel's screenphone won an innovation award at the
International Consumer Electronics Show held in Las Vegas in
January. It also won several product awards at electronics shows
when it was introduced to retailers last year.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel, a Virginia-based telecommunications company, plans to
begin marketing the screenphone worldwide in the third quarter this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects the introductory price in the United States
to be about $300.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the phone and its public release, check
Alcatel's Web site: www.alcatel.com
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
