<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE     03-24 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Despite all the news coverage about Viagra, I've never seen a
list of ingredients. Exactly what makes up this pill?
</P>
<P>
   A: Pfizer, the manufacturer, describes Viagra as the citrate
salt of sildenafil. You're looking for exactly what goes into each
blue tablet, though, so you want the technical jargon. In addition
to the active ingredient, sildenafil citrate, each tablet contains
these inactive ingredients, according to Pfizer: microcrystalline
cellulose, anhydrous dibasic calcium phosphate, croscarmellose
sodium, magnesium stearate, hydroxypropyl methylcellulose, titanium
dioxide, lactose, triacetin, and FD &AMP; C Blue 2 aluminum lake.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the current condition of boxer Tommy Morrison, who
was diagnosed with HIV several years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: The former World Boxing Organization heavyweight champ
apparently has stopped making public appearances, and at last
report had moved to Fayetteville, Ark., after his Oklahoma home
burned down.
</P>
<P>
   A distant relative of the late actor John Wayne, Morrison was
suspended by the Nevada Athletic Commission Feb. 10, 1996, after
failing a medical examination. Two days later, his former
promoter,Tony Holden, announced that the boxer had tested positive
for HIV, and three days after that Morrison confirmed he was
HIV-positive and vowed never to fight again. Despite that, he
fought Marcus Rhodes on Nov. 4, 1996, knocking Rhodes out. That was
Morrison's last professional bout.
</P>
<P>
   Holden, who says Morrison has stopped giving interviews, said
last November that Morrison is sick but ``is doing OK.'' He added
that the ex-boxer apparently hasn't changed his views about not
taking HIV medicine, believing that the medication is what kills
HIV-infected people. Morrison has said he believes the theories of
Peter Duesber, a University of California-Berkely professor who
wrote ``Inventing the AIDS Virus,'' which promotes the
anti-medication concept. Holden refused to speculate on how much
time Morrison has left, calling it a morbid question.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard on the radio that the Supreme Court issued a decision
against the producers, directors and others involved in the movie
``Natural Born Killers'' on the same day the court denied convicted
Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh's appeal of his death
sentence. The court basically said the film was the equivalent of
yelling ``fire'' in a theater. Much was made in the media of the
decision against McVeigh's appeal, but I didn't see anything
further about the other one. Did it happen? Did I miss it?
</P>
<P>
   A: What the Supreme Court did, on March 8, was to refuse to free
filmmaker Oliver Stone from a lawsuit that says his ``Natural Born
Killers'' led a couple to shoot a woman during a robbery in
Louisiana. The court left intact a state appeals court ruling that
allowed the lawsuit to go forward. It alleges the filmmakers
intended to incite viewers to commit similar crimes shortly after
seeing the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The court's action was reported in newspapers on March 9 along
with the court's action letting stand McVeigh's conviction and
death sentence for the 1995 bombing of the federal building and
other court actions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The other night, I watched part of a congressional committee
hearing dealing with airline passenger rights legislation. One of
the committee members was Sen. Jay Rockefeller of West Virginia. Is
he related to John D. Rockefeller?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Jay, a Democrat, is John Davison Rockefeller IV. His
father, John III, was the oldest son of John Jr., who was the only
son of the wealthy American businessman to whom you refer, John D.
Rockefeller. That makes Jay the great-grandson of the industrialist
and philanthropist, who died in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently explained how the Dow Jones industrial average
is calculated. Can you provide similar information about Nasdaq?
</P>
<P>
   A: To understand the Nasdaq, it helps to relate it to the Dow.
As explained previously, the Dow Jones Industrial Average began as
a simple average of the prices of several industrial stocks. Over
the years, as its component stocks have split, it has been
necessary to adjust the divisor in order to maintain continuity. A
consequence of this adjustment process is that the highest-priced
stocks influence the average more than the lowest-priced stocks. An
average computed in this way is said to be ``price-weighted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite uses a different approach. Instead of
assigning more weight to the highest-priced stocks, it assigns more
weight to the stocks with the highest market value (also called
market capitalization).
</P>
<P>
   The market value of a stock is simply the product of its price
multiplied by the number of shares outstanding. Suppose a stock has
1 million shares outstanding and is priced at 50; its market value
is $50 million. Suppose another stock has 5 million shares
outstanding and is priced at 20; its market value is $100 million.
The second stock is worth twice as much as the first, even though
its price is less.
</P>
<P>
   In computing the Nasdaq Composite, the total market value of all
Nasdaq-listed common stocks is divided by the total market value of
all Nasdaq-listed common stocks on Feb. 5, 1971, and multiplied by
100. The result is a capitalization-weighted index, not an average.
Another example of a capitalization-weighted index is the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the 30 companies that make up the Dow Jones
industrial average?
</P>
<P>
   A: The companies change from time to time, but not very often.
These are the current components: AT&AMP;T, Alcoa, AlliedSignal,
American Express, Boeing, Caterpillar, Chevron, Citicorp,
Coca-Cola, Walt Disney, DuPont, Eastman Kodak, Exxon, General
Electric, General Motors, Goodyear, Hewlett-Packard, IBM,
International Paper, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, McDonald's, Merck,
Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing (3M), J.P. Morgan, Philip
Morris, Procter &AMP; Gamble, Sears, Union Carbide, United Technologies
and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The components are listed daily on Page 3 of the Money and
Investing section of The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does former House Speaker Jim Wright still get funds to pay
for office expenses? Will ex-Speaker Newt Gingrich also receive
funds for office expenses?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wright (D-Texas) continues to receive about $192,000 a year
for staff expenses (three secretaries and an administrative
assistant), and to cover rent, communication, utilities, supplies
and equipment, according to Pete Sepp of the National Taxpayers
Union. Tom Foley (D-Wash.), Wright's successor, receives about
$164,000 a year for running his office, Sepp said. And the same law
allowing benefits for former speakers would apply to Gingrich, Sepp
said, with the Georgia Republican eligible for about the same
amount of money as the others.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Linda Smith (R-Wash.) attempted to introduce legislation to
repeal privileges for former speakers in both the 104th and 105th
Congresses, Sepp added, but those proposals never came to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you name all the actors who have portrayed Tarzan in
films? I know Johnny Weissmuller and Buster Crabbe were among them,
and I think there may have been three others.
</P>
<P>
   A: A complete list is impossible because there have been many
unauthorized foreign Tarzan films over the years made in Russia,
India, France, China and Italy. There also have been various movies
with young actors portraying Tarzan as a child.
</P>
<P>
   The book ``The Name Is Familiar . . . Who Played Who in the
Movies?'' lists these, going back to silent movie days: Elmo
Lincoln, Dempsey Tabler, Weissmuller, Crabbe, Herman Brix, Glenn
Morris, Lex Barker, Gordon Scott, Denny Miller, Jock Mahoney, Mike
Henry, Ron Ely, Miles O'Keefe and Christopher Lambert. Other
Tarzans have been Gene Pollar, James Pierce and Frank Merrill and
Caspar Van Dien. And for future reference, Walt Disney Studios is
unveiling an animated Tarzan this year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about bad breath mentioned a mouthwash containing
chlorine dioxide that sells for about $8. What is the name of it,
and where can it be purchased?
</P>
<P>
   A: The mouthwash is one of three products _ along with a tongue
brush and a liquid gel cleanser _ designed for the prevention of
halitosis and sold by Enfresh Products of Roswell, Ga. You can get
information and the products from your dentist, or they can be
ordered by calling Enfresh at 1-877-363-7374. Online information
also is available at http://www.enfresh.com Q: Rep. Bob Barr
(R-Ga.) ran for president of the National Rifle Association last
year and lost to Charleton Heston. Is that position unsalaried and
honorary? If not, was Barr prepared to resign from Congress?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not accurate to say Barr ran for NRA president, said Jim
Manown, spokesman for the organization. What Barr ran for, and was
elected to, is the NRA board, which has 76 members. Positions on
the board, as well as the presidency itself, are unpaid and
``essentially volunteer,'' Manown added. Since Barr didn't run for
NRA president, and since it's not a paid, full-time position, the
idea of giving up his seat in Congress doesn't realistically come
into play.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the status of Mark David Chapman, who killed John
Lennon?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chapman is serving his 20-years-to-life sentence at the
Attica Correctional Facility in New York. The 43-year-old's first
parole hearing will be in October 2000 and he is eligible for
release as early as December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   An article last year in the Chicago Sun-Times reported that
Chapman, who killed Lennon in December 1980, spends his time
writing religious tracts or visiting with his wife, who comes to
see him two or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He recognizes and acknowledges the horror of what he did,''
said author Jack Jones, who spent hundreds of hours interviewing
Chapman at prison for a book on the killer. In his 6-by-8-foot
prison cell, Chapman sorts the letters he receives into piles
marked ``nut case,'' ``hate; threat,'' ``autograph seeker,'' ``hero
worshipper,'' ``sincere,'' ``semi-sincere'' or ``fake,'' the
Sun-Times reported. ``He still gets lots of mail,'' Jones said.
``Anybody who gets to know him, one thing comes across: This is
actually a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
