<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: With all the talk about the ``Star Wars'' defense system, I'm
reminded of the old DEW Line to detect missiles and aircraft coming
toward North America from Russia. I think it was erected in the
1950s in northern Canada. Does it still exist?
</P>
<P>
   A: It still exists, but in an expanded, upgraded form, and with
a new name. The Distant Early Warning (DEW) Line, code-named ``Seek
Frost,'' was created in 1958 with 31 U.S. radar stations stretching
across the Arctic Circle from Alaska to Labrador. It was upgraded
between 1987 and 1992 and subsequently renamed North Warning
System.
</P>
<P>
   The NWS consists of 15 long-range air defense radar sites and 39
short-range, unattended radar stations. Jointly funded by the
United States and Canada, the NWS is tied into the North American
Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD) military alliance, with
headquarters at Peterson Air Force Base near Colorado Springs,
Colo., and an underground command center at nearby Cheyenne
Mountain. The NWS also is linked to operation control centers at
Elmendorf Air Force Base in Alaska and North Bay, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I intend to collect the new quarters commemorating the 50
states. When will the second one, which I believe is for
Pennsylvania, come out?
</P>
<P>
   A: It already has. The Pennsylvania coin went into production on
Feb. 22, according to the U.S. Mint, with the first strike ceremony
March 8, attended by U.S. Treasurer Mary Ellen Withrow and
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge. Some 750 million of the Pennsylvania
quarters were shipped to the Federal Reserve for distribution to
financial institutions and commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   While the coin is expected to begin appearing in circulation in
late March, the Mint advises that it may not be widely available in
circulation nationwide until this summer. Delaware quarters were
the first to be produced for release in 1999; after Pennsylvania,
the remaining three this year will be New Jersey, Georgia and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   For online information, check this Internet site:
http://www.usmint.gov/ and click on New 50 States Coins.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a connection between the word Caucasian and the
Caucasus Mountains of Eastern Europe?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase
Origins explains that in 1795, German anthropologist Johann
Blumenbach divided mankind into what he termed the Caucasian,
Mongolian, Ethiopian, American and Malayan races. He chose a skull
from the Caucasus _ the region between the Black and Caspian seas
that now includes southeast Russia, Georgia, Azerbaijan and Armenia
_ as the ideal model for his racial type. He also claimed that the
Caucasus area was the home of the hypothetical race known as
``Indo-Europeans,'' to whom many languages can be traced.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenbach's theories proved unscientific and tinged with
racism, the encyclopedia notes. The word Caucasian now is defined
as ``one of the main ethnic divisions of the human race:
(including) the Mediterranean, Alpine and Nordic subdivisions, and
is loosely called the white race.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is a U.S. driver's license sufficient to drive in most
foreign countries, or is it necessary to have an international
driver's license?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department says many countries do not recognize a
U.S. license, but most accept an international driver's permit. It
advises travelers who intend to drive overseas to check with the
various embassies or consulates on their requirements. An
international driver's license can be obtained at offices of the
American Automobile Association for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I spent about a year during World War II on Samar Island in
the Philippines, but I haven't seen or heard anything about it
since. What it is like now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Samar is in the Visayas, the main island group of the
Philippines. Lying between south Luzon and Leyte, it is hilly and
steep, with the greater part of the island thickly wooded. Its
inhabitants, who call themselves Waray, grow rice, maize and sweet
potatoes, and live in three provinces. Northern Samar and the
island's west coast are frequented by travelers who like to get off
the beaten path, but central and eastern Samar are ``problem
areas'' where fighting often breaks out between government troops
and the New People's Army. The Lonely Planet guide to the
Philippines notes that Samar's potential tourist attractions
``should not be underestimated,'' but the infrastructure needs
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of Pacific World War II sites, Dent Thompson of
Midway Phoenix Corp. in Cartersville, Ga., points out that the
Midway islands also have been opened to visitors, with flights
available twice a week from Honolulu. Midway Phoenix terms the
atoll ``one of the most remote islands on Earth.'' A bachelor
officers quarters has been converted into a lodging facility, and
Midway has several restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A co-worker and I have a bet. Was the movie ``Gone With the
Wind'' filmed in Hollywood, or were some scenes done in Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   A: None of it was filmed in Georgia. Even the scene of the
burning of Atlanta actually was the torching of old ``King Kong''
sets. But even though Georgia wasn't actually used, it's easy to
see how someone could think so. The book ``The Celluloid South''
says producer David O. Selznick was committed so whole-heartedly to
accuracy in detail that the California soil where outdoor scenes
were filmed was colored to match the red Georgia terrain.
</P>
<P>
   While the architecture for the 40-acre Atlanta set was based on
period photographs, sketches and other documents, the Tara set
``owed more to imagination than research, reflecting the mythology
built up for so long by previous films and accepted seemingly
without question by the filmmaker,'' the book reports.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has any man ever served as vice president for four years, and
then been elected president?
</P>
<P>
   A: Four have been elected president directly from the vice
presidency: John Adams, elected president in 1796; Thomas
Jefferson, 1800; Martin Van Buren, 1836; and George Bush, 1988.
Richard Nixon was the first vice president elected president
several years after his vice presidential term. Between Jan. 20,
1961, and Jan. 20, 1969, he ran unsuccessfully for governor of
California, practiced law and wrote a book.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A sign in my post office says it's illegal to reuse a postage
stamp. When I inquired, the postmaster refused to provide any
information about the regulation on this. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: The theory is that a ``theft of service'' is involved if a
person doesn't affix a fresh, unused stamp to a piece of mail.
Nancy Ross of the Postal Service cited the United States Code,
Title 18, Section 1720. She said the Postal Service provides the
delivery of a piece of mail for the price of the stamp. Once that
service has been provided, that stamp is voided, whether or not it
has been canceled. Therefore, a new stamp must be purchased in
order for that customer to get another service from USPS.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Julie London, the songstress from the
'60s?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 72-year-old actress and blues singer is recovering from a
stroke in Encino, Calif. She had two careers, the first culminating
with her role in the 1947 film ``The Red House.'' After that, she
married Jack Webb, who was then an obscure radio artist. But when
Webb struck a rich lode with the ``Dragnet'' TV series in the
1950s, she retired from show business, choosing to raise their two
daughters, Stacy and Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   After divorcing Webb in 1953, London went into a period of
inactivity and what she called ``a failure of self-confidence''
before resuming her career, aided in large part by songwriter and
jazz musician Bobby Troup, whom she later married. In the mid-'50s
her career took off again, spurred by her album, ``Julie Is Her
Name,'' which included her biggest hit, ``Cry Me a River.'' She
then made a number of movies, including ``The Crime Against Joe''
(1956), ``Man of the West'' (1958), and ``Night of the Quarter
Moon'' (1959).
</P>
<P>
   London appeared on TV after her film career faded, most notably
in the medical series ``Emergency.'' London and Troup, who died
last month, had three children.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
