<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pour on the blue with these drink selections
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Go all out for a Once in a Blue Moon party with
matching drinks.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty out there.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there's Luna di Luna wine from Italy. The
chardonnay/Pinot Grigio blend sports a beautiful label and is
priced at about $11.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider Bravado, another Italian import. This Pinot Grigio
is unremarkable, but the gorgeous blue bottle comes with a stopper
that makes it reusable, maybe for olive oil. It's about $12.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of wine, think beer. Blue Moon beer is around $6 a
six-pack for Abbey Ale, Nut Brown Ale and Belgian White, or, for
more traditional tastes, Labatt Blue, a Canadian Pilsner, for a
little more than $5.
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo beer, which came in a blue bottle, seems to have
disappeared from retail shelves. But if you want to put a blue
bottle you on the table, it's as close as bottled spring water
under the Astia Ridge label, around $1.50. Or pour vodka from a
vivid blue bottle under the Skyy label, or Bombay Sapphire gin,
prettily put up in an embossed aqua bottle.
</P>
<P>
   As for drinks that are really blue, the classic used in
Hawaiian-style restaurants of yesteryear is Blue Curacao, which is
disconcertingly orange-flavored. You also can finish the meal with
Avalanche Blue Peppermint Schnapps in a visually cool bottle (a
small bottle is just $7, making it a nice visual prop).
</P>
<P>
   As for whisky, consider picking one just for the label. Johnnie
Walker Blue Label, of course, isn't blue. At roughly $180 a bottle,
it's pure gold.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
