<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BLUEMOON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Second full lunar view of month is worth celebrating with
colorful dinner party
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ N ext Wednesday is the last chance for a couple
years to do what seems to have been written in the stars: Have a
Once in a Blue Moon dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   On that day the moon will rise full for the second time in the
month, a celestial event that occurs, as they say _ for obscure
reasons _ only once in a blue moon. Actually, it's the second blue
moon of 1999, but a repeat astrological performance won't occur
again until November 2001.
</P>
<P>
   So conjure up the heavenly possibilities for a dinner menu that
focuses on blue food.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a challenge. Blue is not a popular food color. It
almost always borders on gray.
</P>
<P>
   Blue cheese is the first blue food that comes to mind. That
includes Roquefort, which is more green than blue, but then we all
were told once upon a time that the moon is made of green cheese.
Who told us that _ the man in the moon?
</P>
<P>
   Salad with blue cheese dressing is too obvious. What about steak
with blue cheese sauce, an enviable marriage of flavors? Or, for a
blue-collar get-together, blue-cheese-stuffed burgers, perfect to
pair with a Blue Moon beer.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance it seems a Blue moon dinner can be staged around
seafood. Actually, the only fish that is truly blue when it's
brought to the table is the French truite au bleu. Credit the
startling color to a cooking technique in which the live trout is
killed and immediately poached in a vinegar-spiked broth.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the blue seafood possibilities fizzle like a shooting
star. Bluefin tuna would be perfect but it's seasonally in short
supply and terribly expensive. Chesapeake blue crabs, the finest
for making moon-shaped crab cakes, are buried in the sand now,
though pasteurized crab can be used. Cape bluefish is another
possibility, though a bit gamey for all tastes. It's at its best as
smoked bluefish, served as is or as the main ingredient in a creamy
seafood chowder.
</P>
<P>
   The best seafood entree choice may be the colorful Pacific
moonfish, also sold as Opah and available fresh. Midwest Seafood in
Springboro is the place to check for it.
</P>
<P>
   But don't stop there. Consider the first and last courses of
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Because the blue moon isn't really blue but as golden as any
other full moon, I like the idea of starting dinner with a yellow
pepper soup _ served with blue corn tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, fresh blueberries in a cloud of whipped cream are a
natural choice, but if you're lucky enough to find them, $3.50 for
a half-cup seems prohibitive for anything but a garnish.
</P>
<P>
   You could resort to blueberry cheesecake made with frozen
berries. But I settled on James Beard's Moonshine Cake, a
raisin-and nut-filled item that can be made with bourbon instead of
moonshine. I substituted dried blueberries for the raisins in a
double tribute to the occasion. A few fresh blueberries scattered
on top would be as eye-catching as a comet streaking across the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Guests, I predict, would be positively moonstruck.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
