<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Injured Reds arms shadow years of what-could-have-been's
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The Atlanta Braves know when to hold them and
know when to fold them . . . which is why their rotation remains
Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine, John Smoltz and some strong-armed guys to
fill out the back of the rotation for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   That's where guys like Charlie Leibrandt, Pete Smith, Kent
Mercker, Steve Avery, Terrell Wade and Denny Neagle fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle is the latest to do his thing in Atlanta and move on . .
. to the Cincinnati Reds, who are patiently waiting to see him
pitch at full-bore against a full complement of major-league
hitters as he slowly builds arm strength from a weak shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The question that concerns the Reds should be: Is Neagle another
Leibrandt, Smith, Mercker, Avery or Wade?
</P>
<P>
   The proof:
</P>
<P>
   In three years with the Braves, Leibrandt was 39-31 with a 3.35
earned run average, then 9-10 (4.55) his next and final season.
</P>
<P>
   In two years with the Braves, Smith was 11-8 (3.28), then 17-23
(5.37) the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   In two years with the Braves, Mercker was 16-12 (3.84), then
23-28 (4.98) the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   In six years with the Braves, Avery was 69-51 (3.67), then 16-14
(5.64) the next two years and is now with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   In two years with the Braves, Wade was 7-3 (.3.87), then was 1-1
(5.06) last year.
</P>
<P>
   What all five had in common was that injuries slowed or stopped
their progress.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's Neagle, who was 38-19 (3.51) and trying to shake a
weak shoulder in time to pitch at least once or twice by April.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle pitched in a 10 a.m. 'B' game against the Minnesota Twins
Tuesday with a dozen major-league scouts and about 10 fans in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody concerned _ Neagle, general manager Jim Bowden,
pitching coach Don Gullett, manager Jack McKeon _ called his
four-inning 58-pitch fine-tuning another step toward game-readiness
after he gave up one run, three hits, walked one and struck out
two.
</P>
<P>
   The run was a home run off a misplaced change-up hit by Terry
Steinbach, one of the few Twins regulars who hauled themselves out
of bed early enough to play.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts clocked Neagle's fastball in the first inning at between
80 and 82 miles an hour, then between 83-84 the rest of the way,
with one pitch at 85.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw better today, much better,'' McKeon said, comparing
it to one simulated game appearance and one minor-league appearance
against a Baltimore Class A team. ``That's the best outing he has
thrown. He extended himself and had more velocity. We're not
concerned about that. He isn't a power pitcher . . . 86 to 88
tops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, who expressed earlier concern that Neagle wasn't cutting
loose and wasn't getting arm extension, watched from the stands
with a slight smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched better as he went on,'' Bowden said. ``He was a
little stiff at first, but got better as he loosened. He's made
great progress. He's not ready, but what I saw is encouraging, a
step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden re-iterated that Neagle most likely would begin the
season on the disabled list, backdated so that he would be eligible
Saturday April 10, if able. That would be the fifth game of the
season, putting him on the back end of the rotation for an
appearance in St. Louis against Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Gullett, though, said Neagle isn't likely to pitch in an 'A'
game, probably a simulated game Sunday, and that will determine the
next step, perhaps a minor-league game on Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time (minor-league game) was mostly to get the kinks
out,'' Neagle said. ``But I'll never know where I am unless I let a
couple go. That's the only true test and I feel good about it
because I did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm was dragging behind on some of my fastballs, but I felt
no sliding or pinching in the shoulder and that was a concern,'' he
said. ``I need more strength in the shoulder, I'm not quite there,
just a hair short and that's why my control is off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I know I can cut it loose on every pitch, then my control
will be there,'' Neagle said. In nearly empty Hammond Stadium,
Neagle shouted expletives four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it is frustrating because I feel like I'm getting
there, but when I don't I know it and drop a cuss-bomb when the
ball is still on the way to the plate, especially on my fastballs
when I let my arm drag behind sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
