<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-TABLETOPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORS: SOME ITEMS MAY NOT BE AVAILABLE IN YOUR AREA. PLEASE
CHECK.
 &HT;    High-end or budget-savvy, Easter table settings are pretty in
pastels
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Martha Stewart wannabes, the table setting is almost as
important as the food.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers, china and stemware set the mood and style of the
occasion _ transforming even the most ordinary dinner into an
unforgettable experience for guests.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to create that party perfect table for Easter, which
is April 4, turn it into a pastel fantasy. Use the pretty shades of
traditionally dyed eggs _ lemon yellow, lavender, pale green and
apricot _ to create a fashionable, tasteful look.
</P>
<P>
   Easter has always been Atlanta interior designer Bill Cook's
favorite holiday. ``It celebrates spring,'' he says. ``And you have
all the wonderful shades of the new season with which to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect to see rabbits hopping around his table.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to get too thematic with the bunny thing,'' says
Cook. ``I prefer to decorate with the egg, the ancient symbol of
new life. Jelly beans or chocolate eggs are whimsical and witty and
can be used with traditional or contemporary china.''
</P>
<P>
   As a challenge, we asked Cook to set two contemporary Easter
tables _ an inexpensive look and a pricier version. Although we
used everything new for our settings, you might want to include
nostalgic family favorites on your table.
</P>
<P>
   TARGET: ELEGANTLY INEXPENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   For this setting, Cook found sleek plastic dinnerware at Target,
which included oval plates, square platters and oversize latte
cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid of mixing colors,'' he says, as he happily
combined shades of lemon, pale green, apricot and lavender in a
place setting. Clear tumblers, accented with stripes, flowers and
dots in the same colors, carried through the theme, as did the
place mats. Other touches: colorful cloth napkins, look-alike ivory
flatware, jelly beans and a wheat grass centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Cook also chose architect Michael Graves' stainless steel napkin
holder with egg-shaped salt and pepper shakers as well as his
streamlined ice bucket, with oval handles.
</P>
<P>
   COST BREAKDOWN
</P>
<P>
   From Target stores: Soup bowl, $2.69; small bowl, $1.99; oval
salad plate, $2.49; dinner plate, $2.69; large striped or polka-dot
tumbler, $2.69; small tumbler, $2.49; latte cup, $2.49; 12-piece
casual flatware, $9.99; cotton blend napkin, $1.99; plastic place
mat, 99 cents; ice bucket, $29.99; napkin holder with salt and
pepper shakers, $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   From your local florist: Wheat grass (half a flat).
</P>
<P>
   From A&AMP;P Food Market: Russell Stover jelly beans, $2.05 for a
12-ounce bag.
</P>
<P>
   NIEMAN MARCUS: UPSCALE ELEGANCE
</P>
<P>
   To create this sophisticated, contemporary table, Cook picked
earthenware dishes from Neiman Marcus in tones of green _ from mint
to chartreuse. For contrast, he placed the plates and bowls on
silver metallic chargers (oversize base plates). To carry out this
softly hued theme, he added cream-colored linen napkins, ivory
flatware and vases in tones of green and off-white. Other accents:
elegant crystal stemware rimmed in green, rose, blue and yellow;
bamboo orchid plants in earth-tone vases; and yellow beaded
``eggs'' filled with chocolates for each guest's plate.
</P>
<P>
   Cost breakdown
</P>
<P>
   From Neiman Marcus: Fluted bowl, $51; dinner plate, $24; silver
metallic charger, $56; linen napkin, $30; five-piece sterling
silver and ivory flatware, $198; beaded egg with chocolates, $20;
moss-green vase, $25; fluted striped vase, $165.
</P>
<P>
   From 20th Century Antiques, 1044 N. Highland Ave. N.E, Atlanta:
Murano's hand-blown glasses in various shapes, $190 each.
</P>
<P>
   From Forrester's Flowers, 2070 Cheshire Bridge Road N.E,
Atlanta: bamboo orchid plants, $39.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   EYE-CATCHING EASTER IDEAS
</P>
<P>
   Interior designer Bill Cook suggests the following tips for
setting that perfect table:
</P>
<P>
   -- Touch of whimsy: Have fun and do the unexpected. For example,
throw jelly beans on your table. Remember, this isn't a state
dinner!
</P>
<P>
   -- Eclectic elegance: Be diverse in your choice of tableware and
flatware. Combine the earthy with the elegant: metal with wood;
sterling silver with rock crystal; plastic with steel; ceramic with
fine crystal.
</P>
<P>
   -- Floral focus: Flowers are always an important focus, adding
color and texture. Instead of an overblown, contrived arrangement,
go for the sleek and pared-down look. Use one or two orchid plants.
Or put a single gerber daisy in a vase at each place setting.
</P>
<P>
   -- Uncovering all bases: Don't be afraid to not use a
tablecloth. Show off stone, wood and glass tables by using place
mats, or use nothing. Let your charger (an oversize plate) act as a
base.
</P>
<P>
   -- Collected memories: Use your collections as part of the table
decoration. Limoges boxes, papier-mache or decorated Faberge eggs
are beautiful and lend your individual style to the table.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hard-boiled beauties: A basket of dyed eggs makes an easy
centerpiece for an exquisite Easter dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   _Marylin Johnson, c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
