<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MCFADDEN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For designer McFadden, all the world's an atelier
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some people you just can't see curling
up with a bowl of Froot Loops. Mary McFadden is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   McFadden is a debutante, a Sufi dervish, a former Palm Beacher,
a world traveler, a multiple divorcee, a collector of Buddhist art,
a size 2, a New York ``living landmark,'' a speaker of French and a
little Zulu, a two-hour-a-day tennis player and, incredibly, a
pitchman on the QVC shopping network.
</P>
<P>
   (She also designs clothes.)
</P>
<P>
   McFadden has visited nearly every country in the world except
Rwanda, Uganda, Senegal, Mauritania, Chile, Argentina and the
Guyanas. She took time to chat after a recent fashion show in Boca
Raton, but soon she'll be off to Russia, Venice and Yemen, which
will be the inspiration for her next collection of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   (Has she been to Yemen before? ``No,'' she says coolly, ``but I
know what I'm going to find there.'')
</P>
<P>
   McFadden travels with a bag of clothes, a bag of books, a clutch
of cameras and sometimes a male companion or two, and her recent
road trip through Mongolia for her current collection was tough
because, as anyone knows, once outside Ulan Bator the roads just
peter out.
</P>
<P>
   (Wherever she is, she can usually be reached by fax.)
</P>
<P>
   McFadden lived in Palm Beach for 13 years but left in 1983 when
her companion died, so she went back to New York and found other
companions, including a 23-year-old college student who she married
then dumped in a much-publicized divorce that included an
appearance on Donahue.
</P>
<P>
   (She is something like 60 years old but says simply, ``I've
forgotten,'' and walks off to examine wrinkles in a dress.)
</P>
<P>
   McFadden controls everything, from her plucked hairline to the
sets on her QVC show _ ``I had one that looked like a souk in
Morocco'' _ and says she spent four days just making the soundtrack
to the Boca fashion show because Mongolian music sounds ``too
Chinese,'' so she used Russian music instead.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes she's showing have been inspired by the 13th and
14th century Mongolian period in which Genghis Khan merged the
Byzantine, Iranian and Chinese cultures, and if you want to know
more just look at the two pages of notes from her recent New York
show, which read like a history lecture complete with dates.
</P>
<P>
   (She is wearing a tunic from her Central Java collection.)
</P>
<P>
   McFadden, says publicity director Laura Moffatt, is working on a
book about her travels.
</P>
<P>
   (Moffatt also says McFadden has one daughter, goes to at least
three parties a night and once, perhaps, was spotted wearing
jeans.)
</P>
<P>
   McFadden has been in business 26 years, and while her clients
sometimes beg her to design more cocktail-type styles she is quite
comfortable cooking up exotic looks from exotic lands, which is how
most of her dresses are created.
</P>
<P>
   (The rest, she says before disappearing again, ``are
fantasies.'')
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2166 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-EXPENSIVE-HOMES25     03-24 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-EXPENSIVE-HOMES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ava Van de Water
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANALAPAN, Fla. _ Frank McKinney insists he's not a gambler,
just a developer in tune with what the mega-wealthy want.
</P>
<P>
   The $12 million castle he built in Delray Beach, Fla. three
years ago was one of the country's most expensive houses built
without a buyer lined up. Now, McKinney is set to build his fourth
house so-called spec house: Priced at $39 million, it could be the
most expensive in the world.
</P>
<P>
   With a glass-domed rotunda big enough to seat 150 for dinner, a
game room as big as the average house and a 5,000-square-foot
master bedroom suite, McKinney says this is no wild dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business decision. I think God gave me a gift to
determine what these people want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A $12 million spec house is one thing _ but $39 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did the first $2 million spec house, people leaned
over and said, 'Are you crazy?' Then we did a $6 million spec, and
then a $12 million spec,'' said the 35-year-old developer, who paid
$9,000 for his first fixer-upper in 1986. But at $39 million, he
said, ``I admit I exercised my risk threshold.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, McKinney and investor Thomas Melone paid $17
million for 8.66 acres along the ocean in Manalapan, about 20
minutes south of the heart of Palm Beach. It's the highest price
ever paid for a property in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The most ever paid for a house in Manalapan is $8 million. The
Palm Beach mark is $16.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The developers have advertised the entire parcel for sale, for
$28.7 million ($35,000 an oceanfront foot), as McKinney plodded
through a cumbersome permit process with plans for his
61,318-square-foot manse on the north 4.5 acres of the property.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a chance a buyer could snap up the entire parcel _
a perimeter wall has gone up and pilings are ready to go in. But
the foundation hasn't been poured. Or someone could buy during the
24 months McKinney estimates it will take to build the 11-bedroom,
21-bath house and make changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if we got all the way through
(construction) without a buyer,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because this house, he says, fills a void in that very
narrow upper end of the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventory is king,'' McKinney said. ``There is nothing
available right now that's new, that's nice, that's on the direct
oceanfront. Most every property that is respectable as far as curb
appeal and floor plan is under contract or sold.'' Besides the lack
of inventory, McKinney says he learned from his other spec houses,
each of which was bigger than the one before. The 1,000-square-foot
game room in the $12 million La Marceaux (''The Sea Towers''), for
example, just wasn't big enough. This time, the game room will be
2,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you there will be a guy who will say, 'This could
be a little bigger,' '' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   He also learned the mega-wealthy usually have auto collections
they like to show off, which is why plans call for a 10-car
``showcase'' garage with broken brick, groin vault ceiling, stone
floor and high-tech spotlights ``that will make the chrome pop
right off the cars' bumpers,'' he said. There's also a six-car
``utilitarian'' garage.
</P>
<P>
   Bedrooms are bigger, too, thanks to comments from real estate
brokers, including Clark French, who is marketing the house. In the
children's wing, bedrooms are 18 by 18 feet, and each has its own
bath. There also are two playrooms and a nanny's day room.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the house, in the 5,000-square-foot master
bedroom suite, ``her'' closet is a humongous 17 by 26 feet.
``Finally, we might get one big enough,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the plans _ a 30-by-24-foot movie theater with popcorn
stand and ticket booth, 1,440-square-foot gym, 8- to 12-foot-wide
hallways suitable for art collections, and a 24-by-37-foot family
room opening onto a grotto swimming pool with summer kitchen, and a
two-bedroom, two-bath guest house with its own kitchen and living
room.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney and his wife, Nilsa, plan to furnish four of the rooms:
the grand rotunda, game room, theater and master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   About the only things the house doesn't have are a name and,
more important, a Palm Beach address.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in Palm Beach?'' asked luxury real estate broker
Arthur Zeckendorf, co-chairman of Brown Harris Stevens in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manalapan _ isn't that were the National Enquirerguy lives?''
asked Barbara Richey, a luxury broker at Allan M. Schneider in New
York's East Hampton. Yes, he did. And Gene Pope's widow, Lois Pope,
has her 30,000-square-foot Manalapan mansion on the market for $18
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``At $39 million, I would want to have the best address,'' said
Greenwich real estate broker David Ogilvy.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, ocean-to-lake estates in Palm Beach are rare _ even
rarer if you don't want a road between your house and the ocean. Of
the 30 or so direct oceanfront properties in Manalapan, three are
owned by multimillionaires or billionaires on the Forbes 400 list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Manalapan is the next 'best' address,'' Ogilvy said. But
for now, he said, the high price tag and out-of-Palm Beach address
is a double gamble for McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want it to be Gucci or Louis Vuitton _ not almost Gucci or
almost Louis Vuitton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by high-end brokers in luxury markets
throughout the country, all of whom said they couldn't think of a
spec house anywhere near $39 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's so far out of the norm that I can't give you any
logical thinking (on why he would build such an expensive spec)
unless he has somebody in mind for it,'' said Aspen real estate
broker Sandye Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``A $39 million spec caters to a very narrow market,'' said Palm
Beach County builder Skip Gozzo, who has a spec house in Aspen,
priced just shy of $11 million, furnished. In Telluride, a hot
Colorado ski area, an $11.995 million spec house attracted three
sales contracts at one time. ``It sold for asking price,'' Gozzo
said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a $15 million spec house in the foothills of Beverly
Hills, Calif., where a tear-down sold for $25 million last year,
said Beverly Hills real estate broker Jeff Hyland. But $39 million?
``It's mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney is prepared for such comments. After all, his property
is between the $350-and-up-a-night Ritz Carlton and shopping center
magnate Mel Simon's 40,000-square-foot estate that briefly was on
the market for $35 million. Down the road a bit farther,
billionaire William Ziff is replacing his old house with a
47,000-square-foot manse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet if you took a per capita net worth of Manalapan versus
Palm Beach, Manalapan would beat Palm Beach hands down,'' McKinney
said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Census doesn't track net worth. But according to the
1990 count, Manalapan was richer in annual income for each
resident: $115,874 for 320 people, compared to Palm Beach's $71,106
for 9,814 people.
</P>
<P>
   Manalapan is ripe for such a new house, McKinney said. Not only
is his large, ocean-to-Intracoastal property a prime spot, but the
town has a more tolerant attitude toward ''big'' than Delray Beach,
Ocean Ridge and Gulf Stream to the south. Palm Beach just doesn't
have available land, and the town doesn't take kindly to demolition
of old estates.
</P>
<P>
   So who can afford a $39 million house?
</P>
<P>
   Definitely those on the Forbes 400 list, and even the Forbes
800, if there were such a list, said Ogilvy of Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people spend $15 million on yachts, $30 million on a
Gulfstream V jet and have a net worth sufficient enough to spend
$35 million to $40 million on a house that has direct oceanfront
and (consider) the appreciation that oceanfront property has,''
it's really not much of a stretch, said French of J.C. DeNiro Real
Estate in Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, he said, is to search for land and, if it can
be found, spend three years to build. ``What's he going to say to
his wife, 'Let's save $5 million to $10 million and build it
ourselves?' It's so unique it can't be duplicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ava Van de Water writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
