<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENIUM-CRUISE25-CO     03-24 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-CRUISE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruise the world for $100 a day
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A cruise to seven continents, 27
countries, 34 ports.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Duthie of Delray Beach, Fla. is going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to do it!'' she exclaims. ``Just the idea of seeing how
large the world is!''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Tony, a retired engineer for Siemens, is going.
``When I was a schoolboy in England, I had a job at a shipping
company. The names of the boats _ oh, did they conjure up visions
in your imagination!''
</P>
<P>
   Hellen and Donald Nicol of North Palm Beach are going. Unlike
the Duthies, whose longest cruise has been one week, the Nicols
have been on six round-the-world cruises.
</P>
<P>
   And 60, and counting, other people from Palm Beach County are
going, too. They'll leave Athens, Greece, Nov. 20, 1999, on the
small Ocean Explorer I and return to Athens March 25, 2000. Along
the way, they will celebrate the millennium in Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The things they want to see are as small as the penguins in the
South Shetland Islands near Antarctica (Sheila Duthie's dream) and
as big as the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm keen on astronomy and want to see the stars in the
Southern Hemisphere,'' says Tony Duthie, who will celebrate his
65th birthday on the cruise. ``It's so strange to look up and see
stars you don't recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the ship itself. The Duthies and Nicols chose
The World Cruise Company's Ocean Explorer I because of its size
(only 820 passengers) and its destinations (exotic ports too small
for the mega-cruise liners).
</P>
<P>
   And they liked the idea of the 35 faculty members who will stay
on the ship the entire journey. A West End theater director will
give acting lessons and produce a play on board with the
passengers. Other teachers include naturalists, historians and
ornithologists. Passengers can go to art and language classes.
</P>
<P>
   Guest lecturers will include author and actor George Plimpton,
who will give a course on creative writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a Victorian approach,'' says Sam Blyth, chairman
of The World Cruise Company. ``This cruise is more enriching. There
are no dancing girls, no bingo, no daiquiries with umbrellas.''
</P>
<P>
   And by traveling by ship, he adds, there's no jet lag. ``You
arrive ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Blyth flew to West Palm Beach recently from the company's
headquarters in Toronto because of the enormous interest here in
world cruises. The company offers three world cruises a year on two
ships and many of those passengers are from Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Several local passengers, he said, have booked for a year _
three world cruises back to back.
</P>
<P>
   The fares are rock-bottom by cruise standards, starting at about
$100 a day. It would be hard to duplicate that deal on land
considering that the price includes all meals and housekeeping. And
the two ships have single cabins so there are no single
supplements, a penalty for traveling by yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the passengers have sold condominiums to take the
cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Excitement about the places they'll see is kindled by all sorts
of memories _ a picture seen in a book, a story heard long ago,
something that made a child daydream and an adult sitting behind a
desk fantasize.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Duthie, 62, wants to see Sri Lanka. ``I knew someone who
said it was absolutely beautiful. You remember these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband is eager to see Ceylon _ the old name of Sri Lanka _
too. ``When I was a youngster in World War II, we would get
quarter-pound packages of tea from Ceylon. I remember a picture of
a female tea picker on the package.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope there will be female tea pickers in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   Hellen and Donald Nicol are eager to add to their incredible
experiences on previous round-the world cruises. ``I never saw such
sunsets as those in Borneo _ flaming red,'' says Donald. ``And in
the Straits of Sumatra during a bad thunderstorm, we saw fantastic
lights, phosphorescence, on the crests of waves.''
</P>
<P>
   When they were first married, the Nicols lived in New York City
on 54th Street between Fifth and Sixth avenues. At least once a
week, they walked to the docks and watched the ships come in and
dreamed about taking those ships some day.
</P>
<P>
   When Donald retired at age 49 after working as a financial
adviser and CPA _ a job that was ``boring as hell,'' he says _ they
traveled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, they took their first round-the-world ``cruise.'' A
freighter took a few passengers _ in addition to a lot of shrimp _
to Japan, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   Hellen got seasick in the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freighter was practically standing on end,'' says her
husband. ``There were 6 inches of water in our cabin.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellen vowed never to take a cruise again. And here she is ready
to go around the world once again.
</P>
<P>
   The average age on the ship is 61, says Blyth, which means most
passengers are retirees. But there are also families, who believe a
round-the world cruise is a good education.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila worked in a library in Chicago and is excited about the
computers on board, and the huge library, which has a librarian.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her husband is looking forward to dancing the nights
away.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila doesn't know how to dance. Now she'll have plenty of
time, and the opportunity, to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
