<P>
   WALKER-COLUMN _ LONGVIEW, Tex. _ A seventh-grade homework
assignment has provided some surprising insight: For a glimpse of
your kid's future, look at his past. As I helped my son, Joaquin,
illustrate his family tree for a lesson, I enjoyed pointing to
different branches of that tree occupied by the ancestors for whom
he is named. The youngest of our children, he was blessed with
three given names, although he sometimes claims it is a burden.
(Walker, Longview News-Journal). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ For some reason I have a hard
time keeping up with who is killing whom over what in the Balkans.
(Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ After nearly 17 years of
writing a column, the one thing I've learned is that you never know
what is going to set people off. I have written pieces that I was
sure would bring in loads of nasty mail and gotten nary a word. I
have written other columns that seemed utterly innocuous, only to
discover that I have somehow pushed someone's hot button. Still,
it's good to hear from the customers even if they're not exactly
calling to bestow laurels upon you. (Borders, Lufkin Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Now, here's a sour note regarding
the music situation at the new Austin-Bergstrom International
Airport. No amateur garage bands need apply to have their tunes
played in the lobby. No garage bands in the airport of the Garage
Band Capital of the World? (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Recently, we
celebrate the 40th anniversary of Las Novias Society in Palm Beach
County. Young and sassy, the 12 women who started the club in 1959,
thought ``The Sweethearts'' in Spanish translation an appropriate
self-description with sufficient panache to distinguish them from
the many other local women's groups in our community. (Jefferson,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Last Sunday's KKK rally at the
Kettering Civic Center resembled nothing so much as an open-air
Jerry Springer Show, with choreographed fistfights and dueling
profanities (none of them bleeped). The few residents who turned up
for peaceful protest were appalled, not only by the hateful
spewings of the Knights of the White Kamellia, but also by the
crude, combative behavior of the counter-demonstrators. (McCarty,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
