 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Thursday, January
21, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAYOUT'S DONE FOR YOU: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are
available for purchase in paginated form:
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION-RACE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It's the war between the
internet and the Dewey Decimal System! Since ancient times, people
doing research have traveled to libraries to tap the wisdom of the
ages. These days, though, people tend to travel no farther than to
the nearest computer. But is the Net always the best way to do
research? To answer that question once and for all, two teams of
student volunteers were assembled to answer the same set of 10
questions. The outcome may surprise you. (Cummings, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AVIATION-HUMANFIRSTS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After all the
misfires, flops, delays, ill winds and faulty equipment, Brian
Jones and Bertrand Piccard finally made it. They're the hot-air
adventurers who floated around the world tethered to an
18,000-pound balloon. In 20 days. We offer some past ``firsts'' and
a salute to those with the pluck and luck and brains to make
headway for humanity and headlines for themselves. (Reid, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-Q&AMP;A _ A Q&AMP;A with influential jazz trumpeter Terence
Blanchard, who plays Sambuca's for two nights (3/25 and 3/26). He
talks about his road work and his studio work, which has focused on
movie scores lately. Story also wraps up other jazz happenings in
town this night. 20 inches or so. (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   STARTREK-ERRORS _ Here's a surprise: Physicists attending the
American Physical Society meeting in Atlanta say ``Star Trek'' is
chockful of scientific inaccuracies. We enumerate a few. Also: the
best of sessions on the physics of baseball, brass instruments,
magic and new applications of electromagnetic technologies. Also a
possible look ahead to the closing session: ``physics of beer.''
(Seabrook/Green, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   FOOD PAGE FROM COXNET
</P>
<P>
   COXNET_ FOOD 0323 _ ALUMINUM FOIL -- You've had one of those
``better-get-a-million-things-done-before-the-new-millennium'' kind
of days. How you'd just love to settle down to a glass of wine and
a nice home-cooked dinner. But you're not up for any heavy-duty
cooking. There is a silver lining here. And in all likelihood, it's
already in your cabinet _ right next to the wax paper and plastic
wrap. Yep, we're talking about aluminum foil. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color photo of Herbed
Vegetable Packet and a 1-column photo of Cajun Sausage and Beans.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOIL TIPS -- A list of the many advantages to cooking with
foil packets. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES -- Cajun Sausage and Beans, Herbed Vegetable
Packet and Hot Cross Buns. Additional recipes included.
</P>
