   LLAMAS-CARTING (Katy, Texas) _ Yee-haw. In the middle of horse
country and next to a rodeo arena, people are learning to drive
llama carts, an increasingly popular way to use the South American
animals. By MARTY RACINE. (Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIOUS-ARTISTS (New Skete, N.Y.) _ Working from a studio
overlooking the foothills of the Green Mountains, monastic
inconographers at the New Skete Communities paint religious icons
in the traditional way. The artists take great spiritual pride in
their work. ``The icon should be the opening through which we
receive the light of Christ,'' Sister Pat says. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCHES-MANSON (San Antonio) _ The word of God and the music of
Marilyn Manson shared twin billing in San Antonio this week as
scores of Christian activists proselytized to the shock rocker's
faithful followers _ without much success. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-TEXAS (Undated) _ If Jerry Hall were to divorce Mick
Jagger in her home state of Texas, she could ask for the world _
and probably get it. Dallas lawyer Ike Vanden Eykel, author of
``Lone Star Divorce,'' talks about the ins and outs of divorce in
Texas. By CLIFFORD PUGH
</P>
<P>
   LENNON-ARTWORK (Houston) _ Soon it will be 20 years since John
Lennon was murdered outside his home in New York City. Lennon's
artwork will be displayed in Houston in an exhibit called ``In My
Life.'' By KEN HOFFMAN.
</P>
