<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2265 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLAMAS-CARTING-ART-HN     03-24 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLAMAS-CARTING-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING HITCHED: LLAMAS AND CARTS? IT'S A MATCH MADE IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Attn: Ala.)  
 
By MARTY RACINE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATY, Texas _ Yee-haw.
</P>
<P>
   The harnessed animal crosses the parking lot at a furious clip,
but the woman holding the reins is having too much fun to be
scared. She's whooping and hollering and carrying on.
</P>
<P>
   This is horse country, and the action is taking place next to
the rodeo arena in Katy.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not horses.
</P>
<P>
   These are llamas.
</P>
<P>
   The folks gathered in this Houston-area city are learning to
drive carts, an increasingly popular way to use llamas. Carting, as
it's called, is also a major component of llama show competition.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to learn brought out about 30 llama owners
recently who paid $100 for every llama they brought to be trained.
</P>
<P>
   None of these people had ever carted. Neither had the llamas.
But that's no problem _ for the llama. This is one smart animal,
and it picks up its cues in a matter of minutes, not hours or days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't train a horse in an hour to pull a cart,'' says
Wade Thomas, a llama owner and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their curiosity makes them very easy to train,'' says Lee
Lawrence, a trainer and cart builder.
</P>
<P>
   Native to the high-altitude reaches of Chile, Bolivia and Peru,
llamas have for centuries been used as pack animals. Weighing
between 225 and 350 pounds, they can carry a third of their body
weight.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the camel family, when domesticated they are
low-maintenance, requiring little water and only hay and grains for
food. Three or four can be raised on an acre.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States _ where Texas has the fourth-largest llama
population _ they are used as guard animals for livestock. Highly
sensitive to their surroundings and stressed by change, they have
been known to chase and kick to death coyotes. They also emit a
noise that acts as a bark from a dog.
</P>
<P>
   Their wool is used in sweaters. And they've even been employed
on the golf course as caddies.
</P>
<P>
   No one can say whether llamas know the difference between a
3-wood and a 5-iron.
</P>
<P>
   But they have a way of knowing things, says Lisa Rice of Rockin'
R Llamas in Katy, who sponsored the cart-driving sessions. She says
a llama at the Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo this year
instinctively put its head in the lap of a girl in a wheelchair so
she could pet it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are old souls that are here to teach you something.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now they are learning to pull carts, first in threes, then
in pairs and finally, solo.
</P>
<P>
   The carts can be adjusted for the number of llamas. The ones
here are built specifically for llamas and designed for off-road
use by Lee Lawrence of Montgomery, Ala., a financial planner who
runs about 80 head of llamas as a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``A horse shaft (on the cart) is about 18 inches shorter,''
Lawrence points out. ``A horse runs under himself; a llama runs
with his legs out.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, Lawrence will backpack for several days in the
woods, using a llama-pulled cart. ``I put my tent and sleeping bag
under (the seat) and go just like I would on a trail ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use a lot of state parks; we use a lot of fire roads.''
</P>
<P>
   A voluntary conservationist, Lawrence is certified to use his
llamas and carts to ferry firefighting equipment into the
wilderness inaccessible by any other means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately we haven't had to do that, but we're prepared
to,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's carts, sold throughout the country, go for $1,100 and
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carting with the llamas is sort of a new enterprise,'' he
says. ``A lot of people started with the pony/cart relationship.
We're just now evolving to where we're making specific equipment
for llamas and conducting these kind of clinics.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``tack'' _ a collar, back pad, ring guides, breeching _ is
also specifically designed, though it is similar to what you would
find on a horse, Lawrence says.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the arena, two llamas are harnessed into the cart, and
the beginning drivers get their instructions. ``See, the longest
one goes on the inside, the shortest (rein) goes on the outside,''
says one. ``Did you turn the hook part out?''
</P>
<P>
   But as Ruth Jordan awaits in the seat, one of the llamas rolls
on its back and appears trapped in the rigging.
</P>
<P>
   Several people rush over and help it up; crisis averted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When two of them start jumping, it's kind of scary,'' Rice
says. ``If that was a horse, we'd have some broken things. Heaven
only knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part. Though llamas are quick learners and
respond to their owners, they are not used to having someone behind
them giving commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing here is totally different,'' says Rice.
``What we're saying is, `OK, llama I want you out in front of me,
going forward.' So they've got to figure out, where's my person?
And that it's OK out there going, responding to the commands you're
giving from behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Those commands consist of ``walk on,'' ``walk right'' or ``walk
left.'' ``Gee'' and ``haw,'' traditional mule commands, can
substitute for the latter two.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the training method used this day is with a new, accelerated
technique, Rice explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``New things stress llamas. We're putting everything on it right
now, get it over with in 10 minutes; they will have worked through
the stress and come out the other side. It's working pretty well.
They're already so much more calmer than before.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good, because a llama is capable of 40 mph over a short
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk on,'' the driver implores. ``Walk left, walk on, Stormy,
good boys. Walk right, gee, walk on, trot, Stormy, trot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
