<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX     03-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The balance achieved by this promising Atlanta combo on its
debut album is between icy-cool trip-hop rhythms and the warm,
seductive vocals of frontwoman Pam Howe. Like an old-school torch
singer on a tour of phat-ville, Howe, formerly with the jazz outfit
Cicada Sings, coos over a continuous slow-burn groove peppered with
samples and raps. Such lovely, languid tracks as ``C'est Noire''
and ``Soothing'' suggest Portishead on Prozac. Formed two years
ago, ph balance hasn't completely worked out the kinks. Howe's
relaxed delivery occasionally lapses into listlessness, and rapper
Captain Mudfish Starbolt lets a few rhymes get away from him. But
the band's inventive sound is refreshing. And it won't dry your
skin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRIP-HOP
</P>
<P>
   ``ph balance''
</P>
<P>
   ph balance. Daemon Records.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   Idahoan Doug Martsch and his bandmates take a concept as
moribund as the power trio, give it a swift kick and create
remarkably fresh-sounding music. Without resorting to
self-indulgent soloing and guitar-hero posturing, Martsch draws
striking melodic figures and wrings expressionistic riffs from his
six-string. The rhythm section of bassist Brett Nelson and drummer
Scott Plouf is capable of explosive power and delicate grace. The
songs on this major-label debut are generally shorter than on
previous independent-label releases, which only consolidates their
strength. ``Keep It Like a Secret'' is a tightly wound powerhouse
and the best chills-up-the-spine guitar record since Radiohead's
``O.K. Computer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep It Like a Secret''
</P>
<P>
   Built to Spill. Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   ``East Points Greatest Hit'' man is really the go-to guy for
hooks. That's Cool Breeze's specialty. He's the confident rapper
who came up with hip-hop's new name for this region, ``The Dirty
South.'' And though he follows guest vocal appearances by Outkast,
Goodie Mob and Witchdoctor on his recent No. 1 single, ``Watch for
the Hook,'' his chorus stands out: ``The C stands for Cool Breeze
who's known as the champ. Freddie Calhoun, the coolest cutter at
camp. My ones and my twos got your whole town shook. You better
listen to your corner and watch for the hook.'' On ``Good Good''
the hook's repeated, on ``We Get It Crunk'' it becomes a party
chant, and throughout this debut it's the hook_ and the nearly
sample-free production _ that strengthens the sometimes tiring
boasts that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``East Points Greatest Hit''
</P>
<P>
   Cool Breeze. Organized Noize/A&AMP;M. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison and Sonia Murray writes for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
