NYT-03-24-99 1215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2267 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP25-COX     03-24 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilson-Davis a beautiful match
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not an easy concept to wrangle, even for an artist thoroughly
committed to revamping genre definitions to suit her own style,
Cassandra Wilson's latest project is at once seductive and a little
frustrating. The vocalist, who seamlessly traverses folk, pop and
jazz formats because she understands how fundamentally they can
interlock, finds a kindred soul in Miles Davis: the iconographic,
iconoclastic jazz trumpeter who was among American music's great
conceptualists, and a master of soulful cool who knew the gestural
power of a single, sustained note.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson enlists an all-star cast of musicians (including
guitarist Pat Metheny, bassist Dave Holland, cornetist Olu Dara and
members of her working band) for adaptations of seven pieces
composed or associated with Davis _ often her own lyrics _ plus
several originals. The music is always beautiful, especially when
it features an organic mesh of attentively arranged string
instruments _ acoustic bass, violin, mandocello, classical guitar
and so forth _ which offers a perfect balance to Wilson's
characteristically smoky voice. When the written material rises to
the challenge the singer has set for herself _ to claim the
feminine attributes of Davis' legacy _ it's quite exciting. The
opening (and closing) ``Run the Voodoo Down'' employs Wilson's
beloved blues lore in a canny manner, with an implicit nod toward
the Muddy Waters staple ``Mannish Boy.'' And on complete originals,
such as ``Right Here, Right Now,'' Wilson continues to combine
complex adult emotions with breezy, sophisticated folk-pop: her
great strength as a crossover artist.
</P>
<P>
   What's problematic is how much of ``Traveling Miles'' succumbs
to mood-making. It's exquisite mood-making, by the way, but falls
short of the major potential that makes the concept so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling Miles''
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Wilson. Blue Note. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
