A2269 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-OSCARS25-COX     03-24 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-OSCARS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A look at some Oscar winners' earlier films
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 71st Academy Awards are history and it's all over, even the
shouting (though it's a good possibility Roberto Benigni is still
shouting somewhere).
</P>
<P>
   But maybe you'd like to know a little more about the winners and
their work. Here are a few rental suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Judi Dench (best supporting actress for ``Shakespeare in
Love'').
</P>
<P>
   You probably saw her as another legendary British monarch _
Queen Victoria _ in 1997's ``Mrs. Brown,'' for which she was also
Oscar-nominated. But you may not remember her in 1986's ``A Room
With a View'' in which she gave yet another canny cameo
performance. A sunny, impish adaptation of E.M. Forster's 1908
novel, the movie is a high comedy of manners from the James
Ivory/Ismail Merchant team.
</P>
<P>
   The cast _ many of them then fairly unknown _ is pure class.
Helen Bonham Carter plays our heroine who must choose between a
priggish Daniel Day-Lewis and a Byronesque Julian Sand. Maggie
Smith is a fluttery spinster, Denholm Elliott plays a guileless
good heart with a penchant for skinny-dipping and Dench steals
scenes as a pushy popular romance novelist.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  James Coburn (best supporting actor for ``Affliction'').
</P>
<P>
   The white-haired fat cat who accepted an Oscar on Sunday hardly
resembles the lean 'n' hungry kid who started his Hollywood career
four decades ago. But one thing remains unchanged: that
unmistakable Coburn Cheshire Cat grin.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn became wildly popular in the mid-'60s thanks to kicky
``mod''-ish spoofs like ``The President's Analyst'' and ``Our Man
Flint.'' But it's his early work with director John Sturges that
has always intrigued me.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Great Escape,'' Coburn is a lanky Australian POW (his
accent comes and goes) with a laid-back anti-authoritarian manner.
In ``The Magnificent Seven,'' he holds his own among such
up-and-comers as Steve McQueen and Charles Bronson, playing the
fastest knife in the West. That's right. Knife.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roberto Benigni (best actor for ``Life Is Beautiful'').
</P>
<P>
   You've already seen some of his best work on the various awards
shows. He does pretty much the same thing in all his movies _
wide-eyed over-the-top exuberance that makes a Lab puppy look
restrained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son of the Pink Panther,'' an attempt to revive the old Peter
Sellers series, sank like a stone in 1993. However, the more
independent-minded American movie lover has known about Benigni
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Jim Jarmusch introduced him in ``Down by Law.'' A
kind of blackened ``Stranger in Paradise'' _ the setting is New
Orleans _ the film relies on the same three-character counterpoint
and East Village deadpan that made ``Paradise'' a hit. John Lurie
and Tom Waits are two deadbeats who end up sharing a cell with
Benigni (he's like a live-action Topo Gigio). He suggests they
escape, ``just like they do in American movies.'' The picture also
features the actor's wife, Nicoletta Braschi; she's still
co-starring with him a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gwyneth Paltrow (best actress for ``Shakespeare in Love'').
</P>
<P>
   She's usually associated with another period piece _ ``Emma.''
But if you'd like to see her in something completely different,
check out ``Flesh and Bone.''
</P>
<P>
   A thoughtful, sometimes slow-paced blood-will-tell parable, the
movie's ostensible stars are Dennis Quaid as a guy who repairs
vending machines in small Texas towns; Meg Ryan as a woman fleeing
a bad marriage; and James Caan as Quaid's dad, a grifter with a
vicious streak. But the performance that stays with you is Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   She plays Caan's girlfriend, a sloe-eyed con artist in cutoffs
whose favorite scam is to pose as a mourner and steal the rings off
corpses' fingers. Not exactly the kind of thing you'd expect from
the woman who would become Shakespeare's muse, but just what you'd
expect from a multifaceted actress.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
