<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-WEEKBEST25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Pleasantville' a colorful twist on 1950s conformity
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Two '90s kids (Tobey Maguire and Reese Witherspoon) are zapped
into a '50s sitcom and slowly bring sex, color and rock 'n' roll to
the black-and-white world. (The movie's lustrous mix of monochrome
and color is a marvel of digital wizardry.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie gets preachy in its second half, as writer-director
Gary Ross stretches out an obvious metaphor about the townfolks'
fear of the ``coloreds.'' But the performances are terrific,
especially by Joan Allen as the kids' new TV mom and William H.
Macy as the Ozzie-like dad who can't even comprehend the
possibility that dinner won't be waiting for him when he gets home
from work. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
