<HEADER>
A2277 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-DISABILITIES-LAW &LR;      03-24 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-DISABILITIES-LAW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN YEARS LATER: DEBATE ON DISABILITY CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By NOELLA KERTES  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Millions of Americans today can get their wheelchairs
into voting booths, take their guide dogs into restaurants or see a
play in sign language, all thanks to a Bush administration law that
protects the disabled against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But wheelchair users and the blind and deaf probably never
figured the government would lump them and their needs with the
problems of alcoholics, people who are obese and people infected
with HIV. In the past decade, however, that is what has happened as
the disabled and the courts have tried to interpret a sweeping
piece of civil rights legislation known as the Americans With
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits have flourished as plaintiffs ranging from asthmatics
to victims of carpal tunnel syndrome have claimed relief under its
protections. In the process, the nation is undergoing a debate
about the very definition of disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always people who try to take advantage of the
law,'' said Jennifer Sheehy, a spokeswoman for the National
Organization on Disability. ``Any civil rights law is going to have
growing pains. I think that's where we're feeling some of the
growing pains, in defining disability.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the Americans With Disabilities Act, which extends
equal access to employment, government services and public
accommodations to the disabled _ will reach its 10-year
anniversary. Most say that the legislation has come a long way in
addressing discrimination against people with disabilities. At the
same time, it has sparked a debate over what the law means by a
physical or mental condition that ``substantially limits one or
more major life activities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the battle lines are being drawn,'' according to
Equal Employment Opportunity Commissioner Paul Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The government itself is assessing the law's effectiveness. The
U.S. Commission on Civil Rights, in a report issued in October,
faulted the nation's courts for often applying the law too
narrowly. ``Many federal judges appear either to misunderstand the
ADA or be hostile to it,'' the report says. And the report said
that negative publicity about the American With Disabilities Act
has overblown the law's potential for frivolous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the negative publicity focused on a handful of cases _
including that of an alcoholic executive who sued his company for
disability-related discrimination when he was fired, and a
California woman who alleged she was wrongly fired for body odor.
But regulators say those are rare examples and that more typical
cases involve employers who fire people with HIV or hotels that
refuse to make their facilities wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few cases that are frivolous,'' according to
Liz Savage, a lawyer in the civil rights division of the Justice
Department. ``The whole purpose of the ADA is to eliminate
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one of the framers of the law, former White House
counsel C. Boyden Gray, said the law has resulted in excessive
litigation. In retrospect, he believes the Bush administration
should have monitored the issue of coverage more closely from the
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been one of the most serious failings of the
act,'' said Gray, also criticizing the Clinton administration for
not taking a more active role in the monitoring of frivolous cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the law itself has been a boom for trial
lawyers,'' said Pat Cleary, vice president for human resource
policy at the National Manufacturers Association. The EEOC cited a
38 percent increase in cases it received in the first year after
the law's passage. At the Justice Department, more than 10,000
complaints were filed between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that the definitions should be tighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we proposed the first draft, we wanted it to be broad,''
said Andrew J. Imparato, a lawyer with the National Council on
Disability.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups are fighting for more specific definitions to
protect themselves from employees who claim legal benefits due to a
wide range of health conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk of someone who is not legitimately disabled pulling a
fast one over the employees increases'' because of the American
With Disabilities Act, said Mary Leon, a spokeswoman for the
National Federation of Independent Businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Eide, a lawyer with the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said
that small businesses can be particularly hurt by lawsuits, with
the cost of dismissal some $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments cause advocates for the disabled to worry that
the business community is using the confusion over definitions of
disability to gut the legislation that has cost them millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they wouldn't hire us,'' said Freida Zames, president
of Disabled in Action. ``Now they don't want to hire us because
they say they can't get rid of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many point out that litigation could be avoided if
businesses would simply accommodate a person with a disability
instead of going to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a single business has gone under because of the ADA,''
said EEOC Commissioner Miller, who was also recently appointed to
President Clinton's new National Task Force on Employment of People
With Disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for people with disabilities say the average cost of
accommodations are approximately $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately our hope is we get beyond the issue of whether or
not they have a disability,'' Imparato said. ``Any attempt to
narrow the definition will leave people out who are truly being
discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Noella Kertes is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
