<SLUG> BC-CNS-CAN-REDEMPTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLE BILL REDEEMING FOR SOME  
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By LISA SONG   
 c.1999 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shoulders sloped and feet shuffling, he pushed his
shopping cart slowly, deftly negotiating a sidewalk narrowed by
trash containers, wary pedestrians, and the bulging trove hanging
from the handle bar.
</P>
<P>
   Homeless and unemployed, this 47-year-old man, who identified
himself only as Gregory, spends most of each day sifting through
the discarded remains of other people's meals in order to buy his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Since the passage of the Recyclable Beverage Containers Act by
New York state in 1983, Gregory and hundreds like him have
discovered an alternative to a tradition of panhandling and
stealing as a means for subsistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be thankful that we are collecting cans, because
otherwise we would be robbing to survive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But far from receiving praise for work that is consistent with
the law intended to reduce street litter, professional collectors
like Gregory often endure hostility, particularly from
inconvenienced shoppers and those required to redeem his cans and
bottles. Some retailers flatly refuse to comply at all with what is
referred to as the Bottle Bill.
</P>
<P>
   When Gregory finds a store willing to redeem his cans, he often
must wait for hours ``because the girls are lazy and the stores are
full of customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent weekday morning, five men and two women, all
professionals, waited outside an Upper West Side supermarket for
two hours to be paid for their cans and bottles.
</P>
<P>
   One of those men was Jack Cooper, 37, who waited his turn while
clutching a beer bottle wrapped in a brown paper bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing shameful in collecting cans,'' Cooper said.
``I see people in suit jackets returning cans. Some people are
supporting their families with the can recycling _ one of the best
blessings they ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   While the merits of the Bottle Bill are manifest to those who
immediately benefit, others find it a tremendous burden.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Moore, the director of public affairs at the D'Agostino
supermarket chain , said that the company ``worries about customers
turning away because of the homeless people.'' The redemption
regulations, she continued, deplete the company of ``thousand of
dollars'' in labor costs from overseeing the time-consuming
container sorting and counting process. Furthermore, there is the
fee paid to the independent recycling company, Metromining, that
picks up the cans from the stores. Finally, there is the cost of
the bags and boxes that D'Agostino purchases to hold the recyclable
containers.
</P>
<P>
   At one of the company's stores in the East Village, Ms. Moore
said, she has seen men arriving in vans filled with hundreds of
cans. ``It is a little business at some stores.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stores in New York City alone _ 21 in all _
redeemed more than 2 million containers last year, Ms. Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lieblein, public affairs director for the New York
Department of Environmental Conservation, said that for the year
ending September 1997, the most recent data available, a total of
943,141,580 containers were redeemed in the city of New York for a
dollar value of $47,157,079.
</P>
<P>
   Because the law limits the number of cans retailers must redeem
for each customer each day to 240 units, Gregory visits a number of
stores daily. ``Twelve dollars for 240 cans,'' he said of the
familiar math.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not exactly lucrative, Gregory can collect this limit
perhaps four or five times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside an apartment building on the Upper West Side,
Gregory, dressed in his usual maroon sweatshirt, green jacket and
khaki pants, searched through the trash receptacles for cans and
bottles. ``Certain people have certain buildings that they do. I
have three buildings only because my godfather is the super of the
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this privilege, he has lost cans to early morning
opportunists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people out there collecting cans,'' he
said. ``We argue a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, however, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People hardly fight over cans because there are too many of
them,'' Cooper said. ``There's always gonna be aluminum cans. It's
like a respect thing _ if someone knows it's your building, they
don't go there.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his experience, Gregory has found competition stiff. He
has often had to tell intruders in his designated area ``to move,''
he said. But he shuns physical violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a waste of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Lisa Song is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
