<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-INSIDE-WEDDINGCAK     03-24 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-INSIDE-WEDDING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING YOUR CAKE, AND EXPERTS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
 CAKES   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By Naomi Starobin  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Queen Victoria's weighed 300 pounds and was topped
with an ice sculpture of Britannia surrounded by cupids. Lady Diana
and the Prince of Wales had a five-tiered hexagon with flowers on
top. The Prince's mother, Queen Elizabeth, served one that was nine
feet tall and weighed 500 pounds. And the tallest on record was 100
tiers.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the wedding cake. Few people realize that under the
beautiful frosted exterior are hidden columns, water pumps, dowels,
and even the great secret of stability, Styrofoam.
</P>
<P>
   Just as wedding rings are the key props for the ceremony, the
cake is the centerpiece of the reception. And as much science and
technology go into it as flour and sugar. Whether you choose a
theme of simple elegance or outrageous extravagance, having your
wedding cake (and eating it, too) requires expertise of all kinds:
In baking, obviously, to spin, mold and fashion sugar into an
edible wonder. In architecture, to make sure your Taj Mahal does
not become a Leaning Tower of Pisa. And maybe even in cryogenics,
to make sure that the top tier is frozen to perfection for serving
on the first anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cake symbolizes the celebration of unity; it symbolizes
the whole wedding,'' said bride-to-be Carmelia Colatorti, 36, who
was attending a recent bridal show in Stamford, Conn. She plans to
have a triple-tiered cake decorated with ornately patterned icing
and fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
   As home arts maven Martha Stewart wrote in her wedding guide:
``The bride gets to show off _ why shouldn't the cake get to do the
same?''
</P>
<P>
   Where to start? By finding the right baker, who, doubling as
psychologist, can help wedding-stressed couples figure out what
they want. ``I get to know what their fantasies and their visions
are,'' said Gail Watson of Gail Watson Custom Cakes in New York
City. She said that her clients call her a mind-reader, because she
can take their half-formed ideas and turn them into the perfect
cake.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no limit to the range of designs. New trends
include cakes in acid pop colors like chartreuse and fuchsia, or
the Alice in Wonderland cake, with layers jutting out at obtuse
angles, covered with harlequin oversized decorations in outrageous
colors. ``The more playful and dynamic, the bigger the reaction,''
said Donna Ferrari, an editor at Bride's Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a cake tells the story of the bride and groom, with a
forest or skyscraper, or depicts their hobbies _ like the one
topped with a figurine of a bride in cowboy boots. Watson has so
many ways of molding sugar that she has considered calling herself
a ``sugar manipulator'' on her tax return. She pulls, colors, blows
and spins it into just about any shape and texture imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The window of Angela Mia bakery in Norwalk, Conn., is filled
with dozens of wedding cakes, from a simple two-tiered white cake
with fresh flowers to a multipedestal, many-tiered affair with
fountains, silk flowers and plastic staircases, bearing figurines
of the wedding party.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Donna Marra has made everything from Halloween cake for
a late October wedding to a towered castle-shaped wedding cake,
complete with ivy and moat, for a Robin Hood-themed wedding. (Yes,
the bride was dressed as Guinevere.)
</P>
<P>
   And while rum cake was the only flavor available at Angela Mia
years ago, Marra said that the most popular these days is chocolate
mousse cheesecake _ with runners-up including devil's food, carrot,
spice and strawberry shortcake. Depending on the size, ingredients
and design, cakes can cost as little as $1.75 per guest, and as
much as $12.
</P>
<P>
   The most elaborate confection Marra has assembled was 14 feet
long and incorporated 20 separate cakes. It cost $7,000, and was
enough to feed 2,000 people _ even though there were only 650 at
the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   As Martha Stewart once wrote, ``anything can be built if you
have the right architect.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that any self-respecting architect would design many of the
currently popular cakes. ``It looks like a sleeping beauty castle
combined with a renaissance nightmare,'' said Phillip Zimmerman, an
architect who works in White Plains, N.Y., after seeing a photo of
a cake shaped like a Dr. Seuss fantasy castle. ``It is truly
outside the realm of architectural thinking.'' Its slender columns
could never stand up to architectural reality and the bridges
connecting the towers defy gravity, he said. ``The cake is in the
same world as honeymoon suites, heart-shaped tubs and ``Love Boat''
... an elegant statement of non-reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all brides concern themselves with architectural perfection.
At the height of wedding season (September, not June, as is
commonly assumed), Watson prepares 20 to 25 cakes for each weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``A work of art could take two to three days of decorating
alone,'' said Ferrari, so baking the cakes on Tuesday is not
uncommon. Some cakes are covered with botanically correct sugar
flowers, which must be sculpted by hand, petal by petal, then set
aside to dry before being applied to the cake.
</P>
<P>
   For a cake that is two layers or more, a wooden dowel is
inserted down through the middle to keep the layers together.
Without it, said Watson, ``the layers would start to keel over in
transport.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Slinsky of Angela Mia transfers cakes from the bakery and
sets them up at the wedding site. She loads them into a van so that
she can remove the heaviest cakes (the ones that serve as bases for
the rest) first. Then she carries them, ever so carefully, one in
each hand, from the van to the reception hall.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, it takes an hour or two to assemble an ornate cake,
building up from the base layers with columns, fountains, mirrors
and figurines. To finish off the presentation, Slinsky squirts
piping around each bottom layer and spreads flowers on the table.
</P>
<P>
   In her four years on the job, she can remember only one mishap,
a fender-bender, which caused the single cake to slide and shmush.
Fortunately, there was enough time to call the bakery and get
another one baked and decorated in time for the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Watson has seen a table holding a cake collapse; another time, a
dog attacked (and wolfed down) a cake at a reception. But perhaps
the most memorable disaster occurred when a chef dropped a
four-layer cake at the reception hall. It was too late to bake a
new one, so Watson reassembled the top three layers and replaced
the bottom with a quickly decorated Styrofoam substitute. Nobody
knew, but the bride was wisely instructed to slice into the second
tier during the cake-cutting ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   One of the secrets of a cake's stability are the columns
imbedded in each layer, like pilings under a building. Despite
appearances, the layers do not rest on each other, but on these
columns
</P>
<P>
   At the appropriate moment during a traditional wedding, the cake
is presented, the bride and groom feed each other their pieces, and
then the wait staff whisks it away to be cut and served. But wait!
What's that in the kitchen? A substitute cake? To lower costs and
avoid overbearingly large wedding cakes, many brides and grooms
have an unadorned sheet cake made _ with the same ingredients as
the small showcase cake _ to serve the guests.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of more elaborate cakes, disassembling its parts is
akin to demolishing a historic building: save the valuable pieces
for recycling. Angela Mia gladly returns deposits when columns,
fountains and mirrors, are returned to the bakery after the
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Bride-to-be Jackie Jones, 34, interviewed at a Connecticut
wedding show, is very concerned that her cake send just the right
message to her guests. Looking over choices at the show, she
decided that her cake should be decorated to match the beads and
lace on her wedding dress. It will have five tiers, and the top
will be frozen so she and her husband can eat it on their first
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Jones may want to consult yet another expert about that. After
all, many first anniversary desserts resemble something between a
dry sponge and a brick, in both texture and taste.
</P>
<P>
   Reid Wurzburg, vice president of design at Macomber Cryogenics,
says he could do better. ``The key to viability is controlling the
rate of freezing to prevent the formation of ice crystals and
bursting cell walls,'' he said. To retain the look, feel and taste
of food, a home freezer will not do. ``It's okay for a cake that
you're freezing for Tuesday, but it's different when it's for next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the design of freezing processes for various
materials _ although he's never done a cake, he deals with
everything from sperm and eggs to loaves of bread _ is based on
research by Nobel Prize winners.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, he said, bread is frozen by running it through
a chilled tunnel, then spraying it with liquid nitrogen (at a
temperature of minus 320 degrees Fahrenheit) before packaging it. A
cake would have slightly different requirements, he said, because
it has more volume and is more fragile than bread.
</P>
<P>
   Failing access to a cryogenic facility, Ferrari recommends
freezing a butter cream cake as follows: insert toothpicks around
the cake to protect the decorations, wrap it with cheesecloth, then
plastic wrap, then aluminum foil, then refrigerate it then freeze
it. This way, she says, ``the icing will look nice and the cake
will taste great.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Princes William and Harry will use these technical
experts to make certain that their wedding cakes are not only
extraordinary, but stable, tasty and well-preserved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Naomi Starobin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2282 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-ARRANGED-MARRIAGE     03-24 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ARRANGED-MARRIAGES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVORCE STILL TABOO IN INDIAN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By LULADEY B. TADESSE   
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Komal Shah turned 21, her parents decided to
find her a husband. She postponed graduate school for a year and
left New Orleans for Bombay, India, with her parents to search for
a groom. Three months later, she was married to a 22-year-old
physician.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after her wedding, she ran away from her
husband and in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   Shah phoned her parents from a friend's house and told them she
wanted to end her marriage. She was going back home to the United
States with or without them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound insane, but I got a lot of my courage back
after facing the reality,'' Shah said. ``I finally realized this
was all real and I couldn't live like this for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving a daughter away in marriage is one of the highest forms
of charity or good deed that Indian parents perform to enter
heaven. But Shah was born and raised in the United States. Like
many Indian-Americans, she grew up believing she was going to enter
into an arranged marriage but she did not realize the pressures
that such unions can bring to bear on both parties. She did not
think she would have to say yes to a man she did not like, simply
to satisfy her parents. Shah said she was not against the concept
of arranged marriages. But she feels compelled to speak out against
the stigma placed on young Indian-Americans when their marriages
fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if she is in an arranged marriage or love
marriage,'' said Prima Vora, director of Sakhi, a center assisting
South Asian battered women in New York. ``It is the value the
community places on marriage and the stigma of divorce that is one
of the factors in her feeling trapped,'' she said of her typical
client.
</P>
<P>
   But Shah, 25, said, ``This is the first generation of people
that realize we have options, we can make a choice and be
independent in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the option of divorce, only one percent of
Indian-American couples are divorced or separated according to the
1990 U.S. Census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideology is that there is no divorce, but the reality is
there are many families who live outside of the traditional
household,'' said Professor Ann Waters, a historian and
anthropologist on South Asia at Barnard College. ``You have single
women and men living apart from their family, even if it is not
officially said.'' With increased economic independence, more Asian
women might consider divorce as an option in a failing marriage,
Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   The taboo remains. ``Whether in America or India, the stigma
stays even in the upper and lower caste,'' said Maya Sharma, a
visiting scholar at Columbia University's Center for Human Rights.
Sharma has conducted extensive research on single women in India
including those who are widowed, divorced, deserted or work as
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma said divorced women are treated differently than men in
similar situations within Indian society. ``An independent identity
of a woman strikes at the heart of the marriage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Single women are seen as loose in the sense of being
available, bad ones who will steal other people's husband,'' Sharma
said. ``And when you are single you don't have the same weight as
you are married. Somehow being single is a fault. It is seen as
something pitiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Shah recalls her parents' reaction to her decision to divorce
her husband. ``My parents approached me and said that no daughter
of theirs would be getting a divorce,'' she said. They did not want
her to speak of divorce, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But in her view, her relationship with her husband and in-laws
had deteriorated to ``mental abuse'' that was ``enough to eat away
at the core of a person's soul and mental well being.'' She said,
``You will do anything to get away from the abuse, whatever form it
may be.''
</P>
<P>
   The social consequences of divorce affect men, too. Jay, who
declined to give his last name, is a 29-year-old Indian-American
who lives in Chicago. He got divorced after his wife left him and
moved back to India with their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is not getting a divorce or losing my wife,'' Jay
said. ``The biggest pressure is finding someone who likes you. You
are considered ineligible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting other Indian women to remarry has not been easy for Jay.
Like many Indian-Americans, he uses matrimonial classifieds in
Indian newspapers and online sites for arranged marriages to meet
potential mates.
</P>
<P>
   But he feels that he is at a disadvantage. ``Since I am in
America and there is a lot of choice here, why choose a divorced
man?'' Jay said. ``There are a lot of Indian single men. Based on
that alone, why bother with me?'' If he were in India, he said, he
could easily find a woman to marry. But he admitted that his wife,
being a woman with a child, would find it more difficult to find a
new husband.
</P>
<P>
   Shah recently placed an advertisement online seeking a husband.
She said she had not been aggressive about finding someone before
her divorce papers were finalized last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on her marriage, Shah said, ``I was the one that
parents always wanted their kids to be like.'' But she said she had
to make a decision: ``Either I please myself or I live a fantasy
life to please my parents.'' She chose a tough reality.
</P>
<P>
   Shah said she wanted to share her experience with other
Indian-Americans so they know they are not alone when facing
societal pressures during marriage or divorce. This past fall, Shah
addressed a group of about 100 Indian-Americans organized by Young
Jain Professionals. ``There are so many more people that can't get
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Luladey B. Tadesse is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-JAIL-MAGAZINE &LR;      03-24 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-JAIL-MAGAZINE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILHOUSE JOURNALISTS: RIKERS INMATES LEARN TO REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 DESIREE ADIB  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As their names were called out, the graduates proudly
strolled across the gummy green gymnasium floor to accept their
certificates. But this was not like any other graduation: the
students here were wearing regulation green fatigues, nine
correction officers paced along the gym's sidelines, and the poorly
ventilated air was thick, with an eerie sense of confinement. It
was commencement day at Rikers Island, the largest jail in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 12 weeks the inmates had spent hours in class
poring over back issues of the New Yorker magazine, struggled with
the rules of grammar, and learned interviewing techniques. On
graduation day they had two things to show for it: the Rikers
Review, a magazine they produced themselves and a diploma from the
Fresh Start Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time ever being in prison and because of
Fresh Start I learned a lot,'' said Pablo Rodriquez, 19, who is
serving an eight-month sentence for selling heroin. ``Now I have
respect for myself and that helps me gain respect for others.''
</P>
<P>
   These 16 graduates are among the elite at Rikers Island. After a
grueling acceptance procedure of essay writing, background checks
and lengthy interviews, they were chosen out of 200 applicants for
the Fresh Start program. Organized by a criminal justice group
called the Osborne Association, Fresh Start offers 12-week cycles
of culinary arts or journalism training for men at Rikers Island.
The goal is to teach the inmates practical skills that will help
them successfully reintegrate back into society, according to
Jennifer Wynn, the journalism instructor and editor of the Rikers
Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rikers Review is there for the inmates as a vehicle for
self-expression, for self-esteem building, to learn how to
prioritize their work loads and to learn how to cooperate with
others,'' Wynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn stressed that the computer skills are especially critical
because inmates can use them to their vocational benefit when they
are released from jail. Lenny Hughes, a former drug addict who
graduated from the program nine months ago is an example of a
someone who did just that. During the graduation ceremony, Hughes
spoke to the inmates about his achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program gave me options and hope that I can change my
lifestyle, and I am here today to show you that I did it and you
can do this also,'' said Hughes, who looked like a Wall Street
stock trader in a dark blue suit and black-rimmed glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is out of jail and employed at a marketing firm making
$17 an hour. He is also a student at the Borough of Manhattan
Community College with a 3.0 grade point average.
</P>
<P>
   After the graduation ceremonies the inmates happily munched on a
hearty meal of fried chicken and cornbread prepared by their Fresh
Start counterparts in the culinary program. The journalism students
passed out the Winter 1999 edition of the Rikers Review.
</P>
<P>
   In the magazine there were articles describing everything from
the Department of Correction's pending ban on cigarettes to the
effect of the Y2K problem on prisons and courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine not being able to obtain water from the tap ...
imagine your commissary account dropped to zero ... imagine that
your good time was erased ... that the lights went out,'' writes
Abelardo Hernandez, discussing the Y2K problem in his article.
</P>
<P>
   There is a ``Dear Doc'' column where inmates can ask Dr. Esther
Schumann questions regarding various jailhouse ailments. ``What's
the deal with hepatitis?'' asks one reader.
</P>
<P>
   There are also reviews on books such as ``The Pros and Cons of
the NFL,'' a book discussing criminals who play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authors do not just make allegations in their fascinating
and easy-to-read book _ they match crimes to players and include
mug shots, court records and police reports, as well as interviews
with victims and arresting officers,'' writes Jermaine Coit, in his
book review.
</P>
<P>
   Some inmates, like Rodriquez, contributed a personal essay that
revealed the hardship and challenges they faced in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I see this place as if it were a jungle full of
hunters stalking their prey,'' he wrote. ``Once you're here,
there's no hope of getting out without being hunted. On the Rock,
you are either the hunter or the hunted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rikers Review has been a product of the Fresh Start program for
20 years. The inmates are taught by instructors to write articles
that cater to the readership of the jail _ the inmates and the
correction officers. They are taught writing and computer skills on
Word Perfect and Windows 97 programs. The curriculum, which also
includes public speaking and self-evaluation classes, keeps the
inmates occupied and away from the trouble that tends to brew in
the overcrowded jail dorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In jail there are gangs, there are people with negative
attitudes and there are many intimidation and manipulation
factors,'' said inmate William McCray 39, who is serving eight
months for violating his parole on a prior drug conviction. ``The
program helps you get away from all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynn explained that the intentions of the journalism program and
the magazine are not to cover controversial issues at Rikers, but
rather to be a ``positively oriented magazine for inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the magazine is to inform our readers, inspire
our readers or entertain our readers,'' she said. ``This is not a
muckraking tool and we can't be a vehicle through which we are
going to be exposing jailhouse scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Fresh Start organizers and the inmates
involved, the correction officers at Rikers are supportive and
helpful with the program. During the graduation ceremonies, the
correction officers were as seemingly happy and hopeful for the
inmates as friends and family in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that I won't ever have to see any of these guys
in here anymore!'' said Capt. Susan Griffith, one correction
officer who spoke with much cheer during the ceremony. ``Instead, I
hope to one day run into them at a restaurant in Manhattan ... as
successful individuals in a free society.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all graduates are success stories. One student who was
accepted and actively involved in the journalism program was back
in Rikers on drug charges only one week after he was released.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn says that at one time, Fresh Start had psychologists on
staff who might have been able to help a student like that but
today the program is unable to meet the needs of ``troubled cases''
because of financial and administrative cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad really; programs like this should be staffed so that
we don't have to pick just the best,'' Wynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the inmates at Rikers Island are serving misdemeanor
sentences of one year or less. The average offender serves only 43
days, according to corrections officials. For the inmates at Rikers
there is no question that they will be back out on the streets; the
only question is whether they will be able to stay out. During the
ceremony, the poignant words of inmate Charlie Moore addressed this
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned one very valuable thing here at the Rock,'' Moore
said. ``It's a short bridge going there but it's a long bridge
coming back and hopefully we can rely on our hopes, dreams and the
skills we learned here to make that an easier ride back.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Desiree Adib is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
