<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia News Service provides feature stories from the New York
City area every week for your use as desired. There is no cost to
you. CNS stories are transmitted every week courtesy of The New
York Times Syndicate/NYT News Service.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are slugged  &UR; BC-CNS-keyword &LR;  and move in the ``l''
news category.
</P>
<P>
   They are edited by adjunct professors who are working
journalists at The New York Times, Newsday, the Associated Press
and The Wall Street Journal. The stories are written by degree
candidates at the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia
University. All we ask is that you send us a tearsheet.
</P>
<P>
   So please, if you can, use our stories. Most of them are news
features that can be held until you have a pesky hole to fill.
</P>
<P>
   To send us a clip:
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   GRADUATE SCHOOL OF JOURNALISM
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   2950 BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK, NY 10027
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks,
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; Professor Wayne Svoboda (212-854-3837) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Columbia News Service &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; e-mail ws52 &LR; columbia.edu &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; web site http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu/ &LR;  This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITIES LAW _ Next year, the Americans With Disabilities
Act, which extends equal access to employment, government services
and public accommodations to the disabled _ will reach its 10-year
anniversary. Most say that the legislation has come a long way in
addressing discrimination against people with disabilities. At the
same time, it has sparked a debate over what the law means by a
physical or mental condition that ``substantially limits one or
more major life activities.'' ``That's where the battle lines are
being drawn,'' according to Equal Employment Opportunity
Commissioner Paul Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ARRANGED MARRIAGES _ Giving a daughter away in marriage is one
of the highest forms of charity or good deed that Indian parents
perform to enter heaven. But when an arranged marriage does not
work out, ending it can be extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH BELLS _ The digital age has come to churches in the
form of computerized bells.
</P>
<P>
   BUS FUMES _ Minorities in northern Manhattan are not just in
danger of drugs and the gun violence found too often on inner-city
streets. They are also subjected to unsafe air, thanks to the
Metropolitan Transit Authority, activists say. The transit
authority runs more than 3,500 buses daily from 19 depots in all
five New York boroughs. Manhattan is home to eight depots; seven of
them are situated above 96th Street, where a majority of residents
are black and Latino. ``Most of these depots are across the street
from schools and large housing developments,'' one activist said.
``The fumes are seeping into the air, increasing our chances of
being diagnosed with asthma, lung cancer, emphysema, bronchitis and
heart attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE WEDDING CAKES _ Consider the wedding cake. Few people
realize that under the beautiful frosted exterior are hidden
columns, water pumps, dowels, and even the great secret of
stability, Styrofoam.
</P>
<P>
   CAN REDEMPTION _ Since the passage of the Recyclable Beverage
Containers Act by New York state in 1983, 47-year-old Gregory and
hundreds like him have discovered an alternative to a tradition of
panhandling and stealing as a means for subsistence. ``People
should be thankful that we are collecting cans, because otherwise
we would be robbing to survive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LOST AND FOUND _ The objects in the Lost and Found at Grand
Central Terminal are bits and pieces of lives waiting to be
reclaimed. Paul Noguchi, an urban anthropologist at Bucknell
University, calls them ``testaments to forgetfulness'' and
``reflections of our culture.'' ``You are what you lose, to some
extent,'' Noguchi said. ``And we find some really strange things.''
</P>
<P>
   JAIL MAGAZINE _ As their names were called out, the graduates
proudly strolled across the gummy green gymnasium floor to accept
their certificates. But this was not like any other graduation: the
students here were wearing regulation green fatigues, nine
correction officers paced along the gym's sidelines, and the poorly
ventilated air was thick, with an eerie sense of confinement. It
was commencement day at Rikers Island, the largest jail in the
nation. For the past 12 weeks the inmates had spent hours in class
poring over back issues of the New Yorker magazine, struggled with
the rules of grammar, and learned interviewing techniques. On
graduation day they had two things to show for it: the Rikers
Review, a magazine they produced themselves and a diploma from the
Fresh Start Program.
</P>
<P>
   PIGEON RACING _ Pigeons don't get much respect in New York. But
a small circle of old-timers still compete in a sport that makes
champions of perhaps the world's most despised bird. They may look
slow, but pigeons can fly at speeds of up to 70 mph. It doesn't
matter where you drop them off, they come back like a boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   SAKE BARS _ The microbrew revolution has come and gone. Martini
madness is so two years ago. But there's a new drink in town. It's
clear. It's dry. It's cool. It's ... sake.
</P>
</TEXT>
