<SLUG> BC-CNS-LOST-AND-FOUND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU ARE WHAT YOU LOSE: LOST &AMP; FOUNDS REFLECT CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By RAMONA JENKIN
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man on the other side of the Plexiglas divider
stood in front of shelves of gray plastic bins filled with this
month's gloves, cell phones, beepers, Bibles, keys and umbrellas
and politely listened to one more tale of woe.
</P>
<P>
   He opened a drawer and gently plopped down a pile of
sandwich-sized plastic bags, each one containing a piece of jewelry
waiting for its owner to come looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   After a few seconds of rummaging, a smile came across John
Judd's face as he went from loser to finder, identifying one of the
more than 14,000 objects that made their way to the Metro North
Lost and Found Parcel Room at Grand Central Terminal last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the third wedding band I lost,'' said the 34-year-old
electrician who left his ring in the men's room at Grand Central.
``I should get a box of 50 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The objects in this room are bits and pieces of lives waiting to
be reclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Noguchi, an urban anthropologist at Bucknell University,
calls them ``testaments to forgetfulness'' and ``reflections of our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are what you lose, to some extent,'' Noguchi said. ``And
we find some really strange things.''
</P>
<P>
   Noguchi has studied the lost and found at Tokyo Station for more
than 20 years. About two years ago, he said, one of his students
spurred his interest in Grand Central's.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Noguchi has visited this lost and found five times.
He has watched Fred Chidester, customer service manager and
self-described computer nerd, turn this home for lost artifacts
into an electronic wonder, reflecting the efficient and fast-paced
culture of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Chidester, 62, a former lieutenant commander with Metro North
police, studied the computerized systems of the FBI and New York
City Police Department, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We modeled our system after theirs,'' he said. ``But we came
up with a better mousetrap.''
</P>
<P>
   That modern mousetrap helped Metro North return more than 7,000
lost items last year, Chidester said.
</P>
<P>
   The fruits of Chidester's labor can be seen first-hand on the
lower level near track 100 by anyone who misplaces just about
anything on a Metro North train, at any of the outlying stations or
in Grand Central.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that comes into the lost and found is tagged, entered
on the computer and stored in a designated bin or on a shelf or
rack, Chidester said. If it has been turned in it takes only
moments to determine its location.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lost artifacts are what hurried suburban commuters
would be expected to leave on their trains _ briefcases, gym bags,
jackets, glasses, hats and wallets, Chidester said.
</P>
<P>
   Glass eyeballs, artificial limbs, juicers, golf clubs and live
mice have also been found, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tokyo and New York are major urban centers and
globalization accounts for the similarities in some of the lost
objects, like laptop computers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are lost items unique to each culture, Noguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   A surgeon riding a Metro North train on his way to perform
reconstructive surgery left a box of human body parts _ eyebrows,
ear lobes and an upper lip packed on dry ice _ on one of the
trains, Chidester said. The surgeon realized his loss after he the
train left the station.
</P>
<P>
   Chidester tracked the train down and located the package. It was
returned it to the surgeon _ unopened.
</P>
<P>
   Americans might find that event odd or weird, but there would
probably be a different response at Tokyo Station, Noguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan if something like that showed up it's a source of
anxiety, because of the concern about lost and wandering spirits,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And as Japan has become a consumption society the number of lost
furoshiki _ silk scarves traditionally used to carry goods _ has
decreased, replaced by modern shopping bags, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noguchi has also looked at other factors _ like the differences
in demographics and time anxiety about the day's agenda _ that
influence what shows up at the different lost and founds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll get more lost artifacts in the morning than in the
evening rush,'' Noguchi said of Grand Central. ``That's true in
Japan, too. There's a rhythm to lost articles.''
</P>
<P>
   More old people ride the train in Tokyo so there are more sets
of false teeth lost, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Japanese wooden shoes have been replaced by forgotten
Reeboks and Nikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have compared lost objects to museum pieces,''
Noguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike museums, lost and founds are not the intention of
anybody, he said. ``They're a voice of the people for the things
they lost.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ramona Jenkin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
