<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, BROTHER, CAN YOU SPARE AN ATM? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here are the two big, completely nonfictional
issues in San Francisco right now:
</P>
<P>
   First, Mayor Willie Brown is considering the idea of giving
automated teller machines to the homeless, so people don't have to
lug around quarters, but can just run their cards through
panhandlers' money machines.
</P>
<P>
   Let that one sink in for a minute, while you're waiting for your
bank balance to show on the beggar's machine.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the San Francisco Catholic Archdiocese has unleashed its
power and influence against the city Board of Supervisors for
voting to close a street in the gay Castro District on Easter so a
bunch of gay guys who dress up as nuns can have a block party.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us can sympathize. But you have to admit, the church has
come a long way since those centuries when it crusaded against such
worthy opponents as the Saracens and Satan.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute, the line is moving closer to the homeless guy
with the ATM. It's a long wait, but it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to stand a few feet back, according to ATM etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   That way only the homeless guy will see the personal
identification numbers being punched in.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of giving the homeless ATMs comes from a local do-good
group that wants to assure that quarters dropped in cups don't go
to the fortified wine industry. Instead, donors will be assured
that 20 percent would go to the guy holding the machine, and 80
percent to groups helping the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   How the guy collects the money, I don't know. Bank of America
and Wells Fargo aren't exactly falling all over themselves for the
homeless business. They don't even seem to want ours, to judge by
the way they treat us.
</P>
<P>
   Why anyone would run an ATM card through a beggar's machine, I
don't know either.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, when you're at a regular ATM you're always looking over
your shoulders for scruffy guys. I guess the advantage is that here
you'd be looking right at them.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's homeless policy could fit on a cardboard sign: ``Will
take any cockamamie idea as food for thought.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Brown's point man on homeless issues,
Supervisor Amos Brown, proposed taking shopping carts away from the
homeless, replacing them with small two-wheeled carts and duffel
bags.
</P>
<P>
   How homeless people are supposed to carry ATMs on those rigs is
anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   We're looking for a little consistency here, people. The cops
are running homeless people off street corners and out of parks.
Now city officials want to turn them into monetary institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Homeless people can be sources of revenue, just like illegally
parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   As the city's budget surplus slips away, perhaps the mayor will
consider extending ATM use to help solve other social problems.
</P>
<P>
   Give hookers ATMs, and use a portion of the proceeds to fund
shelters for battered women and Johns Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Give drug dealers ATMs, and some of the proceeds can go to rehab
centers. At the same time, street crime will be reduced because
there won't be cash on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Give muggers ATMs, and they won't have to drag you to one at
gunpoint to take your money. A portion of the proceeds can go to
fund the police.
</P>
<P>
   Give lobbyists ATMs, and developers won't have to create a paper
trail trying to get their highrises approved.
</P>
<P>
   Give every citizen and business an ATM, so city tax collectors
can withdraw as much money as they want and save money on stamps
and paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of running San Francisco keeps rising to support its
bright ideas. Satire doesn't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, city officials are scrambling to reach a compromise
between the Catholic Church and the guys who dress up as nuns.
</P>
<P>
   These guys, the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, made fun of the
pope when he visited San Francisco a couple of years ago, so you
can see why the church hates the idea of them getting an indulgence
from city officials on Easter.
</P>
<P>
   A church spokesman made a big mistake by saying that closing the
street for a group that mocks the Catholic Church is like closing a
street for a group of neo-Nazis on Passover.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but I can't think of the last time the Sisters of
Perpetual Indulgence kicked and beat Catholics in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, under the First Amendment, San Francisco might have to
treat neo-Nazis as if they were just any other group wanting a
street fair in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco? Press ``cancel'' when finished or choose another
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
