<SLUG> BC-CHURCHES-MANSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH GROUPS FIGHT `SATANIC' MESSAGE IN ROCKER'S MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The word of God and the music of Marilyn Manson
shared twin billing at the Alamodome earlier this week as scores of
Christian activists proselytized to the shock rocker's faithful
followers.
</P>
<P>
   Manson fans weren't easily swayed by the churchgoers outside the
dome, but most accepted the ``God bless yous'' and religious
pamphlets in jack-boot stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't want to hear the word of God,'' said Cedric D.
Williams, 31, of the New Life Christian Center in San Antonio.
``They get caught up in the music. It's a satanic subliminal
message that's coming out, and they don't want to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Bird, decked out in black lipstick and red horns, was in
no mood to be converted on her big night out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pathetic. We're not going to lose our souls,''
said the 15-year-old resident of Buda, about 60 miles north of
here.
</P>
<P>
   The witnessing campaign was choreographed by a Christian radio
station, KSLR, which warned parents about the influence of Manson,
who has torn Bibles apart at his shows.
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders across the country have rallied against
Manson's music.
</P>
<P>
   His 1996 album, Antichrist Superstar, went platinum.
</P>
<P>
   ``What good would Marilyn Manson be if no one hated Marilyn?''
the performer, whose real name is Brian Warner, said in a 1994
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Manson, who resembles an androgynous, anorexic Alice Cooper,
without snakes, likened his concerts to a freak show _ and cast
himself as the carnival barker.
</P>
<P>
   During the San Antonio performance Monday, the police kept a
close watch on the black-garbed, white-faced legions of Manson
fans, many of whom sported tattoos, pierced appendages and dyed
hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Halloween on Mars,'' Patrolman David Williams said.
``It's interesting, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson fan Ginger Oye, 19, was happily led about on a leash by
``master'' Terri Vasquez, 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has to tame me because I can't be controlled,'' Oye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the finest person that ever walked the Earth,''
she said of Manson.
</P>
<P>
   In her non-leash hand, Vasquez clutched religious pamphlets that
she said she would read later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a religious person,'' said Vasquez, who wasn't worried
about being influenced by the band. ``If you're a strong person,
you're not going to convert to Satanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the religious messages that Katie Dillon handed out
quickly became litter or were dumped in trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' said Dillon, 28. ``Garbage workers need God,
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
