<HEADLINE>
ICON ARTISTS FIND SPIRITUAL INSPIRATION IN THEIR WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on the Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, N.Y. _ When you enter the artist's studio, the air is
filled with the smell of paints and varnish, blending with aromas
of freshly baked biscotti and dog biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   The studio occupies the corner of a one-story dark-stained wood
house that could fit into any neighborhood, except this one is
nestled on a hillside near the Vermont border on the land of a
small religious community.
</P>
<P>
   Natural light floods the room streaming in from large windows
that open onto a scenic wooded area and beyond to the foothills of
the Green Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The artist's sanctuary is home to Sister Pat, who works five
hours a day, four days a week, as one of three monastic
inconographers at the New Skete Communities, in the upstate New
York community of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The painting of icons has been a part of this monastic community
also renowned for its dogs, dog biscuits, biscotti and cheesecakes
since its founding more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Pat works in her studio at Emmaus House, which is the
residence for the Companions of New Skete,
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to the parish with my husband in 1976 and began
the Companions community in this house in 1983, as one of three
couples and two widows,'' said Sister Pat, whose husband died in
1997. ``As companions, we follow a religious rule of life, as
professed monastics, like the nuns and many of the monks, which
includes daily worship and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sisters Cecelia and Rebecca work at the residence of the Nuns of
New Skete, about a mile and a half down the hill. The monastery for
the Monks of New Skete, the church and chapel are located near the
very top of the hill, a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women here are dedicated to monastic life in the
Orthodox Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Father Laurence, the abbot and founder of the community, and 11
monks (four of whom, including Father Laurence, are ordained) took
up farming in 1966 by one of the main roads in Cambridge, but the
traffic proved too busy for their monastic life and they moved to
their current location a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the hilly, rocky terrain of these 500 acres, farming
was out of the question. The community instead supports itself by
breeding German Shepherd dogs and boarding and training of all
breeds. In addition they write books, smoke meats, make dog beds,
T-shirts, gourmet cheesecakes, biscotti, dog biscuits and
liturgical works of art, from religious goods to music and painted
icons, which are found in the monks' gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   The icons are mostly commissions, from individuals and religious
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm backed up two years,'' said Sister Pat, as she
served her visitor freshly brewed coffee and homemade biscotti.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed casually in trousers and a plaid flannel shirt, instead
of her monastic habit, which is used for worship, Sister Pat sat
straight up on the edge of the seat of an armchair and told of her
career as a high school English teacher for 33 years, which is
where she met her husband, who was also a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I retired from teaching in 1987, to devote my time to painting
icons,'' she said. ``I wasn't trained as an artist. I only had 6
credit hours in college of drawing, lettering and design. But I
stopped because the work was cutting in on my other courses. But I
would draw anything. My sister, who also likes to draw, and I would
always get drawing materials from our parents at Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   When Father Laurence needed another iconographer to help meet
the demand of commissions, he asked if anyone liked to draw, and
Sister Pat showed him a large sketchbook she kept from over the
years, which happened to include a couple of pencil portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Pat studied with an iconographer in Clermont, N.H.,
learning to paint icons in the traditional way, using egg tempera
on gessoed wood, while Sisters Cecelia and Rebecca use acrylics on
the same surface. When painting with acrylics, the prepared wood
surface can be placed on an easel, as opposed to egg tempera, where
the icon has to remain flat. Egg tempera requires working with
puddles of color.
</P>
<P>
   Birch, plywood or a solid poplar, linden or any other
nonresinous (so it doesn't leech) softwood is used for an icon
painting. The wood is cut to the appropriate size, then painted
with 10 to 12 coats of gesso, with sanding between every third or
fourth coat.
</P>
<P>
   This process can take up to three days. The last is sanding with
a very fine grade of sandpaper till it becomes a smooth surface,
but still able to hold pigment. Any gold leaf work is applied last,
as it is very perishable.
</P>
<P>
   The painted surface of the icon must be sealed to protect the
pigments and gold leaf. It is customary to kiss an icon (but never
with lipstick or chapstick), showing respect of the figure
presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use a traditional olifa varnish, which is a refined linseed
oil with a bit of cobalt drier in it,'' Sister Pat said. ``It stays
tacky for a very long time, usually up to a year, and while it is
completely drying, it must be protected from dust by storing it in
an upright position in a very clean area away from traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the icons starts at $250 and goes up to $4,500 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   The artists take great spiritual pride in their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The icon should be the opening through which we receive the
light of Christ,'' Sister Pat said. ``Painting icons is a service
to the church. We hope to kindle in the viewers a renewed faith in
God's incarnation in Christ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
