<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEADING THE CASE FOR NEGOTIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan Schlictmann doesn't look at all like John Travolta. He is
slender rather than filled out, Jewish rather than Italian, and has
gray hair rather than black. But he's the real thing, the crusading
attorney of ``A Civil Action,'' the movie in which Travolta tries
to nail Beatrice Foods and W.R. Grace for polluting the drinking
water in Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency eventually required the
companies to pledge $70 million, but the pledge was to Woburn, not
to Schlictmann and his clients. He won a moral victory, but at the
cost of his partnership, his house and even his car.
</P>
<P>
   Schlictmann recovered. He wrote a book, has a car again (a
Volvo) and another polluted-water case, in Toms River, N.J. And he
has a new attitude toward the law. Instead of seeking to nail his
targets to the wall, he talks about ``establishing a relationship
of trust.'' He speaks out against his profession's presumption of
conflict, which he says ``encourages in ourselves behavior which is
pathological.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlictmann spoke to a group in SeaTac, Wash., last week
organized by attorney Dave Larson, founder of Litigation
Alternatives Inc. Larson is a practitioner of mediation and
arbitration, and a critic of his profession's take-no-prisoners
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   And so is Schlictmann. The man portrayed by Travolta as the
fighter for truth now argues that truth ``is not something to be
taken. It is something to be shared.''
</P>
<P>
   He's trying that approach in Toms River. He describes his case
as much like that of Woburn as portrayed in the movie: a town with
polluted water and 60 cases of unexplained cancer. The difference
is, he made a deal with local industry to cooperate, and each
agreed that no lawsuits would be filed for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, such a case would start with demands. But when you
start with negotiations, Schlictmann said, ``they become more
issues and concerns. You're letting go of control of that demand.''
</P>
<P>
   You're also letting go of your exclusive claim to the moral high
ground. Were you a victim? Maybe it's because you didn't stand up
for yourself. ``You disempowered yourself,'' Schlictmann said.
</P>
<P>
   To the lawyers present, he said: You're going to negotiate a
deal anyway. Why wait until you've conscripted your army and lined
up your cannons? Why not make peace now? ``Call up Jack the
insurance adjuster, whom you've known for 15 years,'' and work it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Several layers objected. You're a famous guy, they said. You
wrote the book. You were played by John Travolta. When you come
rolling into town, of course they're going to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Said Seattle personal injury attorney Scott Ericson: ``On a
single auto accident, how do we force an insurance company to the
table when they don't want to go? In essence, you are forcing them
to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right,'' Schlictmann said. Getting them to the table
``has elements of coercion. I just think what I'm talking about is
more civilized ... than piling more stones on somebody's chest
until he tells us the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   More civilized, certainly. But he never quite answered Ericson's
first question, which was, how do we do it?
</P>
<P>
   Larson, the sponsor, admits that a deal is not always possible
and the threat of court action may be required. But he says
arbitration, in which both sides agree to accept the decision of a
private judge, and mediation, in which they use a facilitator to
talk the matter out, are both better than going to court.
</P>
<P>
   One of Larson's other speakers, Justice Phil Talmadge of the
Washington Supreme Court, said it now takes three years for a
business dispute to be decided in King County court. Court
congestion is getting so bad, he said, that the high court could
order the state Legislature to hire more judges. He allowed that
this would be ``a very hard and blunt weapon, one that gets us into
a constitutional crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, Larson argues, is doing more things outside
court rather than engaging in long, expensive set-piece battles.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he says, he had a client who killed a 12-year-old
in a car accident. In our culture, our lawyers advise us never to
say, ``I'm sorry,'' or to publicly be sorry. It might be used
against us. In this case, the dead child's mother, who is
Vietnamese, didn't feel Larson's client respected her son's death.
The client had planted a ceremonial tree in honor of the dead boy,
but no one had told the mother. When the two finally met, a flood
of tears and emotions were released, and the lawsuit was quickly
settled.
</P>
<P>
   Says Larson: ``A lot of these disputes could be settled by
letting people be people, letting people be human.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
