<SLUG> BC-TAX-FOLEY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP LAWMAKERS OFFER TAX REBATE
 &HT;    310&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping for a substantial budget surplus this year,
a group of Republican lawmakers Wednesday proposed a one-time 5
percent income tax rebate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When America takes in more than it needs, it ought to give it
back, pure and simple,'' said Rep. Mark Foley of Florida, the
bill's chief sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would offer all taxpayers a minimum rebate of $100 and
a maximum of $500 on taxes owed for this year. The filing deadline
for those taxes would be April 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers earning up to about $56,000 a year would qualify for
the full 5 percent rebate on the taxes they pay. Beyond that income
level, the $500 maximum would represent a smaller percentage of
their taxes. Persons who do not pay any taxes would not qualify for
money back.
</P>
<P>
   The rebate would be available only if there is a federal budget
surplus beyond the surplus in the Social Security Trust Fund. In
order to be fully implemented, Foley's bill would require a surplus
of $22.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Congressional Budget Office is projecting a
non-Social Security surplus of less than $1 billion, but the agency
will revise its estimates this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said he expects the surplus estimate to rise, based on the
strong economy. If the surplus is less than $22.7 billion, he said,
the percentage or maximum amount of the rebate might be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Touting his approach as simple and direct without requiring a
long-term commitment to a tax reduction, Foley said he expected to
pick up wide bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Foley noted that many members of both parties are reluctant to
embrace a permanent tax cut based on projections of surpluses that
may not occur. He noted his bill would not be implemented unless
there was a surplus. Congress could decide to enact similar rebates
each year if the surplus continued.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The rebate would be different than the tax refunds may people
now receive from the government. A refund is made when someone pays
more tax than he owes, usually because too much is withheld from
his paycheck. The rebate would reduce the amount of tax owed.
</P>
<P>
   A similar rebate was given in 1975 when Democrats controlled
Congress and Gerald Ford was president. At that time the rebate was
10 percent with a $100 minimum and $200 maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., a senior member of the tax-writing
House Ways and Means Committee and a cosponsor of the bill, said
that of all the tax cut proposals floating around Congress, ``this
is the best approach because it's the most direct approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley and Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., another cosponsor of the
bill, are also members of the Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
