<P>
   Stress hormones can help us escape a leopard. But in excess,
they may do a lot of damage to the brain. For example, take an
18-year-old, stick him in a uniform, ship him off to a war and
expose him to something horrific _ say, a battle in which he's the
only soldier in his unit to survive. Chances are that some day he
may suffer from post-traumatic stress disorder. By studying
magnetic resonance images of the hippocampus of patients with PTSD,
scientists are detecting new clues about the relationship between
stress and the brain. Robert Sapolsky is a professor of
neuroscience at Stanford who studies stress-induced diseases. He is
the author of ``Why Zebras Don't Get Ulcers.''
</P>
