<P>
   ``At certain traffic densities, small causes have large
effects,'' Helbing says. ``In particular, most types of congestion
are avoidable _ they ... are caused by small disturbances that grow
and at some point cause the traffic to break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Helbing's cellular automaton model, they simulated a
realistic mix of cars and trucks on a highway, moving at different
speeds and passing one another at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   They computed the times it took the vehicles to cover six miles
of road under a wide range of traffic conditions. At one critical
traffic density_ about 35 vehicles per mile of highway _ they
observed something _ ``All of them start becoming one,'' says
Huberman. ``Suddenly the traffic is basically moving like a solid
block.''
</P>
<P>
   At the critical density, the cars and trucks adopt the same
speed, and both types of vehicle seem to maintain that speed for a
long stretch of road. That is a desirable situation, say Helbing
and Huberman: A steady speed makes for reliable travel times and
less passing, which can cause accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The solidblock state is fragile, however; increase the vehicle
density a bit and the fast-moving block dissolves into sluggish and
aggravating stop-and-go traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are ways of keeping the block intact. All you
have to do, say Helbing and Huberman, is put computer-controlled
stoplights at each on-ramp. The lights would respond to real-time
data on traffic conditions collected by wires the cars pass over.
</P>
<P>
   When the data indicate gaps in a block of traffic passing an
on-ramp, the light there turns green. When the density threatens to
shift the traffic into stop-and-go, the light turns red again.
</P>
<P>
   At rush-hour peaks, traffic would still slow to a crawl. But at
intermediate densities, Huberman says, commuters would move
smoothly and contentedly as a solid block.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people act in selfish ways, it's very hard to achieve a
common goal,'' he says. ``But here the interesting thing is you
have a rather large group of people, they're all being selfish, and
yet they all achieve a very smooth state of running through the
freeway. It's an unintended, global cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nirvana on the freeway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly. For a little while.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robert Kunzig is the European Editor at Discover magazine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHRINKING-BRAIN-AND-S     03-24 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHRINKING-BRAIN-AND-STRESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRESS AND YOUR SHRINKING BRAIN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO B&AMP;W PHOTOS AND ONE COLOR SLIDE are available FREE OF CHARGE
to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent by mail or
overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number.
Please specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT SAPOLSKY  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Every now and then, someone with a medical problem needs a CT
scan or MRI of the brain. With luck, the test rules out a
threatening disease and in the resultant relief, the doctor shows
the patient the scan.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike pictures of other organs, which inspire a bemused
response, brain scans provoke awe. Rookie med students feel the
same disquiet in anatomy class when they first hold a cadaver's
brain in their hands. The brain, after all, is the Seat of the
Soul. From this mass of tissue resembling marinated tofu emanates a
person.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a child's body stops growing, the brain has long
since settled into its adult size. Which is why it's mighty
interesting when the size of some part of the brain changes
dramatically in an adult. Lately, a certain brain region has
attracted a lot of attention because it may atrophy in response to
a certain type of serious stress.
</P>
<P>
   Take a green 18-year-old, stick him in a uniform, ship him off
to a war and expose him to something truly horrific _ say, a battle
in which he's the only soldier in his entire unit to survive. Some
rare, inexplicable supermen may come out of such an experience
unfazed or even strengthened. But the average guy may suffer from
nightmares and feel estranged from loved ones. Some survivors
remain damaged for decades.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon was called shell shock during the First World
War, battle fatigue in World War II and in modern psychiatric
parlance, is called post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just restricted to combat trauma, either. Gang rape,
childhood sexual abuse and imprisonment in Auschwitz are all
experiences that have produced the broken person labeled with the
acronym PTSD.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Psychiatric Association, patients with
PTSD suffer from flashbacks, nightmares, emotional numbness or
outbursts, loss of pleasure, an inappropriate startle reflex and
problems with memory and concentration. Those last two symptoms
have prompted recent brain-imaging studies.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, some neuroscientists have begun
generating magnetic resonance images of PTSD patients' brains and
carefully measuring the volumes of the organs' many bewildering
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, groups working independently reported that in
afflicted individuals an important region of the brain called the
hippocampus is smaller than average.
</P>
<P>
   The hippocampus is used to form long-term memories, retrieve old
ones and manage explicit, conscious memory. Surgically destroy the
hippocampus, as has been done in a zillion lab rats and some major
types of memory will be gone for good. Similar problems result when
Alzheimer's disease ravages the hippocampus.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recent PTSD imaging studies have found atrophy only
in the hippocampus; the rest of the brain is fine. The damage,
however, is not trivial. Researchers at the Manchester VA Medical
Center and Harvard Medical School who have studied combat PTSD
patients reported that one side of the hippocampus was about 25
percent smaller than expected.
</P>
<P>
   While neuroscientists agree that an atrophied hippocampus and
PTSD go together, there is a lot of debate over why. One possible
explanation involves a class of steroid hormones called
glucocorticoids.
</P>
<P>
   During stress, whether of a physical or a psychological nature,
a person's adrenal glands secrete loads of these chemicals. But too
much of the hormones _ during chronic psychological stress, for
example _ can be a trigger for all sorts of stress-related
conditions, including high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Because the hippocampus has lots of receptors for
glucocorticoids, it's the part of the brain most sensitive to the
hormones. Glucocorticoids can damage neurons in the hippocampi of
rodents and primates. Can excessive glucocorticoids damage the
human hippocampus? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Cushing's disease, in which tumors produce
astronomically high glucocorticoid levels. Researchers have found
atrophied hippocampi on MRI scans of people with this disease. The
rest of the brain is fine, but the higher the levels of
glucocorticoids in the bloodstream, the smaller the hippocampus and
the more memory problems the patient experiences.
</P>
<P>
   When the tumor is corrected and glucocorticoid levels go back to
normal, the hippocampus slowly returns to normal size, suggesting
that the shriveling was reversible and the branches grew back.
</P>
<P>
   Is this what happens in PTSD? No one really has a clue;
researchers need to study actual brain tissue to determine whether
PTSD patients really have fewer neurons in their hippocampi than
healthy individuals. Moreover, no one knows how high glucocorticoid
levels get during a rape or a bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Mount Sinai School of Medicine and the Bronx
Veteran Affairs Medical Center in N.Y. have examined PTSD patients'
glucocorticoid levels and have observed that levels are not higher
than normal, but lower. They explain the syndrome not by excessive
stress hormones during trauma but by excessive sensitivity to these
hormones after the trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the idea that trauma could cause a brain to shrink
could be completely wrong. Maybe we have the story backward. Maybe
the person with a small hippocampus who goes into a trauma is the
one vulnerable to PTSD. Some researchers are trying to figure out
whether a small hippocampus predisposes someone to PTSD.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thomas Freeman, a psychiatrist at the North Little
Rock Veterans Administration Medical Center, is taking another
approach. If the hippocampus shrinks after the trauma, the extent
of atrophy should be more dramatic in survivors of older disasters
than of recent ones. Freeman and his colleagues are comparing brain
scans of PTSD victims from the Gulf War, Vietnam and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Although the recent hippocampal research has little to say about
everyday stress and recovered memory, it does have some valuable
practical lessons for us.
</P>
<P>
   If a small hippocampus is indeed a risk factor for PTSD,
neuroanatomy should be taken into account when we decide whom to
ship off to battle. And if the atrophy is a consequence of the
trauma or the post-trauma period, scientists need to figure out how
the process works so we can learn how to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR: MEMORY, HORMONES AND EVERYDAY WORRIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of us will be spared post-traumatic stress disorder.
Instead our memory troubles will fall under the influence of
everyday stressors.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters confusing, stress also can help memory. We
remember where we were when the challenger exploded; we can recall
the details of an encounter with a mugger as if it were yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we've also experienced ways in which stress can disrupt
memory _ such as discovering that the stress of an all-nighter does
some bad things to memory retrieval during a final exam the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   We can reconcile this contradiction by appreciating the
difference between getting stressed like a normal mammal and
getting stressed like a human (over the course of, say, a 30-year
mortgage). In the former situation, the stress response is highly
adaptive, helping to save your life, while in the latter, the
unrelenting nature of the stress response sets you up for disease.
</P>
<P>
   That difference helps explain the data on stress and memory.
Stressors that last less than a few hours tend to sharpen memory,
mostly as a result of adrenaline. If the stressor persists, the
enhancement disappears, replaced by forgetfulness, mostly because
of glucocorticoids.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robert Sapolsky is a professor of neuroscience at Stanford who
studies stress-induced diseases. He is the author of ``Why Zebras
Don't Get Ulcers.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
