<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-24 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING THE CLOSET DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At the start of his career, engineer Jason Stone worked for a
large chemical company in Alabama, where any hint of homosexuality
could have sabotaged his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not come out to people other than my parents, and I was
using the job, I guess, to get my confidence and gain some
financial independence before I made any other decisions,'' recalls
Stone, 28. ``It took about two years, but I began to come out to
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, deciding how much of his private life to reveal to his
employer was especially difficult in a corporate atmosphere in
which simply being single was perceived as detrimental to career
advancement. The average age of the firm's mostly male executive
and engineering staff was 52. Most were married, settled, and set,
says Stone, and ``their beliefs were pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone eventually left the company and earned an MBA from Harvard
Business School, but he never forgot those years or how much he
might have benefited from a network of gay and lesbian
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Stone and James Robertson, an MBA candidate at the
Yale School of Management, will see the fulfillment of a long-term
goal when a two-day national professional and networking conference
in Boston, specifically geared to the needs and goals of gay and
lesbian MBA students, opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take the top 20 business schools and count the number
of gay and lesbian business students, the numbers are quite
small,'' says Robertson, 33, a native of Newcastle, England. ``We
decided to bring all these small pockets of people from top
business schools together to make a strong, professional network
for them as they enter the working world.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, titled ``From the Closet to the Boardroom,'' is
expected to attract about 150 gay and lesbian business students
from around the country. Workshops will focus on such topics as how
gays and lesbians can influence workplace policy, and keynote
speakers include Julie Palen, founder of InterNoded Inc., one of
OUT magazine's top 100 firms in 1998, and Walter Schubert, founder
of the Gay Financial Network and the first openly gay member of the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Its goal? To encourage participants to share business ideas,
make new friends, and form networks with executives from US
corporations with an interest in promoting workplace diversity. ``A
lot of good companies lose excellent employees because of issues
they don't understand or even know about it,'' notes Stone. ``And
one of those issues has to do with attitudes in the workplace
toward people who are different. I call it a war on talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed in the workplace since Robertson graduated from
Dartmouth College in 1987 with a degree in painting and Stone
landed his first professional job in the mid-90s. Back then, few
companies offered domestic partner benefits or were even remotely
interested in recruiting lesbians and gays.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many large employers are promoting themselves as being
diverse, and some actually boast of a congenial workplace
atmosphere where differences are accepted. ``There is no question
that the world has changed,'' says Kim Mills, education director of
The Human Rights Campaign in Washington, D.C., a national gay and
lesbian political organization with more than 300,000 members.
``The job market is very tight now, and companies are competing
brutally for the best and brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   One example: McKinsey &AMP; Co., an international consultancy, and
the lead sponsor of the upcoming conference at Harvard Business
School.
</P>
<P>
   While Mills points to the current labor shortage as a reason for
the demand, Jack Stephenson, a partner in McKinsey's New York
office, says diversity is important ``to the meritocracy we have at
McKinsey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very interested in getting high-quality talent, and we
are actively looking at every source of talent we can get,'' says
Stephenson. ``We have, for a number of years, sponsored gay and
lesbian recruiting dinners at the top business schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also trying to build an open, supporting environment.
Places like McKinsey often have the perception of being stuffy. We
want to make sure that that perception does not continue, and one
way to do that is to eliminate artificial roadblocks to finding and
keeping talented people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills believes the current recruiting wave has prompted more
employers to develop nondiscriminatory policies and offer domestic
partner benefits to workers. These benefits, she says, ``have
become a low-cost means of keeping and attracting top employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, 85 employers instituted domestic partner
benefits, up from 51 in 1997, reports the Human Rights Campaign. In
all, 625 companies now offer the benefits to employees in
nontraditional relationships, including Avon Products, Aetna, Shell
Oil, Turner Broadcasting, and Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM has a strong anti-discriminatory policy and so does
BankBoston,'' says Mills. ``At both companies, there is ongoing
training so that people will be treated with respect and dignity,
whoever they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, there are still messages in the wider
community that say that gay people are mentally ill and need to be
reformed. So we know that gays and lesbians are not safe in every
community. They still represent the third-highest percentage of all
hate crimes recorded by the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not a perfect world, say specialists. Yet national polls
have consistently shown that when Americans are asked whether they
believe people should be discriminated against in the workplace
because of sexual orientation, 80 to 85 percent consistently say
no.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that many more students, including those with
MBAs, are coming out on their resumes these days. By listing the
names of the gay and lesbian organizations they belong to, they are
saying, ``We want the employer to know,'' notes Mills. ``By being
open, the candidate gives the employer the option of either hiring
or not. It also opens the door so that the gay or lesbian applicant
will know exactly where he or she stands.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-PERSPECTIVE-BOS &LR;      03-24 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PERSPECTIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR DISCUSSES PLANS TO EXPAND MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The branch that the Boston Museum of Fine Arts opens in Nagoya,
Japan, next month isn't its only expansion in the works. Back home,
MFA director Malcolm Rogers is talking with architects about a plan
for a museum that is bursting at the seams, with both art and
people. Might that parking lot go underground, and a new wing on
top? Might a bridge be built over the street that separates the
museum from its affiliate school?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's possible,'' Rogers said the other day, sitting in
his antiques-filled office, at a table covered in green baize. ``As
far as the building goes, we need a master plan. We're looking at
architects to do one, and looking at what we can do within the
existing shell.''
</P>
<P>
   Having survived a year when the museum has been the subject of
controversy and criticism over owning and exhibiting art of
less-than-perfect provenance, Rogers is looking forward. Now that
the MFA has completed a $137 million capital campaign _ money that
tidied up the museum's affairs and will not be available for the
expansion _ he's focusing on a strategic plan he says the museum
will be ready to announce ``in a few months' time.'' The plan
addresses every aspect of the museum, from the urgent need for
climate control _ which more than a quarter of the museum's spaces
still lack _ to the inefficiency of having several separate
conservation departments scattered around the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the new museum,'' which is what he's calling it, ``research
and conservation will be in one place,'' Rogers says, ``whether
that's an existing or new one. We already have a major grant in
hand for that, although it's still unannounced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One'' is a word Rogers speaks often. The museum's curatorial
departments have, until now, operated as separate fiefdoms with
dramatically unequal power, money, and space. He envisions them
becoming ``a community,'' he says. ``I have no favorites in this
museum. I want every department to shine.'' Curators at the MFA _
and in other American museums _ are losing their autonomy, and many
resent having exhibition ideas foisted on them by marketing and
education departments, or by directors. How the balance of power
between the MFA's king and barons evolves will be interesting to
see. Already, though, Rogers has reined in the wild child across
the street _ the School of the Museum of Fine Arts _ by deciding
that having one of the country's top art academies on the premises
is a plus. Nowadays, if a work hanging in the MFA galleries is by
an alumnus or teacher at the school, the label says so.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is thinking globally, too. ``Having a foothold in Asia
will be a great opportunity,'' he notes. Nagoya, which will house
loan shows of both five-year and six-month durations, will bring
$50 million to the museum over the 20 years of the contract, and
will also pay for some curatorial and conservation expenses, Rogers
says, ``so it will help turn over sleeping collections.'' Nagoya
shows will be drawn from the MFA's extensive stores, ``easing the
pressure on this site,'' he adds. ``Is that a formula we can extend
to other cities? It could be part of the internationalization of
the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Global reach is a current museum trend: New York's Guggenheim
Museum, with outposts in Venice and Bilbao, Spain, is the model.
Rogers hopes that a worldwide presence could bring more money and
collections to Boston, more than Bostonians themselves could or
would provide. ``We're looking at an international council to
support the museum,'' he says. Currently, 12 percent of MFA
visitors are foreign, a number he hopes to increase: He's already
held a press event in London that has resulted in several stories
on the museum, and on Boston as a destination. And while he's at
it, he notes that visitorship in general is way up _ 1.5 million
last year _ partly due to the more than 565,000 people who saw
``Monet in the 20th Century,'' the world's most visited art
exhibition in 1998. Again thanks to ``Monet,'' museum membership
jumped from 67,000 in January 1998 to 96,000 a year later.
</P>
<P>
   MFA Enterprises _ the umbrella for the museum's retail,
restaurant, and parking empire _ has also taken quantum leaps. The
main restaurant has shed its little-old-lady air. And there's a new
restaurant for lunch, a glass-walled structure built within the
Fraser Garden Court, where you can eat under a Calder mobile.
</P>
<P>
   The store's selection of dreary reproductions has been upgraded,
and you can now find everything from Zulu baskets to one-of-a-kind,
high-end jewelry to a Dale Chihuly bowl. Rogers is particularly
proud of a new partnership with Ars Libri Ltd., the antiquarian
booksellers, which has its own section in the MFA store, sometimes
featuring books and materials related to current shows. Among other
treasures on offer here at the moment is a fragment of the
manuscript of the first edition of ``Lives of the Artists,'' by the
16th-century art historian Giorgio Vasari, and a receipt for a
painting by David.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers says the shop has also begun selling work by living
artists, both local and national. He cites this as a way to give
more presence to contemporary art, which the museum has
historically neglected. While there's precedent for this _ the
British Crafts Council has long had a sales branch in London's
Victoria &AMP; Albert Museum _ Rogers says, ``There's been a prejudice
in museums against selling real art, because you're endorsing
certain artists. But I see no problem in that.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep visitors looking longer and spending more, he also
envisions lounges within the museum where they can sit, browse
through books or interact with computers, refreshing themselves for
the next round in the galleries _ or shops.
</P>
<P>
   Is the malling of the museum healthy or hazardous? Rogers
insists the beefed-up retail is good, and in good taste, and that
commercial operations ``must reflect the excellence of the
collections.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the actual shows in the museum _ which are, after all, the
point _ the past few years have seen an emphasis on blockbusters or
slick commercial displays with little or no scholarly value. But,
after a couple of contemporary photography exhibitions that were
downright embarrassments, the MFA has come up with a winning one,
the current ``Abelardo Morell and the Camera Eye.'' And the show
schedule through the millennium looks both varied and promising. In
addition to name brands _ Sargent, van Gogh _ there are major
exhibitions on subjects including ancient Egypt, Edward Weston
photographs, the history of guitar design, and the paintings of May
Stevens, the Quincy-born artist who views life through the lens of
two other women: her mother, Alice Stevens, and the firebrand
socialist Rosa Luxemburg.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also plans to beef up collections that are already
world-class in several areas. The goal of his Millennium Project is
acquiring 100 masterworks of modern and contemporary art, ``to
address a hereditary weakness that people complain about,'' he
says. His pitch to prospective donors of these works that the
museum can't afford to buy, especially to donors from out of town,
is that gifts that would mean little to a powerhouse like the
Museum of Modern Art ``would make a real difference at the MFA.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday at lunchtime, when I met with Rogers, there were
long lines to get into the parking lot and to use the ladies' loos.
The joint was jammed. It's clear the museum needs more facilities,
but unclear where it's going to put them. The artworks need even
more breathing room than the visitors. ``European decorative arts
are not well displayed,'' Rogers acknowledges. ``Nor are American
decorative arts. And there is woefully insignificant space for
20th-century art, and for art of the ancient world.'' (What does
have an adequate piece, at least of the current pie, is Asiatic
art, with 27 galleries.)
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't yet know where the increased space will be, he
does say, ``I find it unattractive to enter the museum through the
parking lot,'' which is the only aboveground space that's a logical
candidate for a new wing. Rogers, who reopened the old Huntington
Avenue entrance in 1995, also yearns to reopen the long-closed
Fenway entrance, to reconnect with the section of the Emerald
Necklace beyond, ``which could be one of the most beautiful urban
recreation spaces in America,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautions that ``we do not know if there's money in this
community'' to pay to implement a strategic plan he calls
``transformational.'' He notes that the MFA's expansion plan
``isn't nearly as far along as Harvard's.'' Harvard University Art
Museums director James Cuno has already enlisted the aid of
internationally celebrated architect Renzo Piano for his proposed
new riverside museum; the MFA, Rogers says, is still looking around
for an architect. ``But if we can make a new museum here,'' he
says, ``we can contribute to the revitalization of Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only just begun,'' says Rogers, who can look like a
jolly round-faced imp at times, but goes suddenly solemn as he
pronounces these words. ``I really mean that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
