<HEADLINE>
ROLLING STONE HONORS THE GUITAR GODS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of throwing the usual muss-haired rock star or carefully
muss-haired actor onto its cover, Rolling Stone for April 1
features a curious drawing of Jimi Hendrix rising like Venus on the
Half Shell atop a pork chop, a third eye staring from his chest and
a third hand reaching from his sleeve. The occasion for the
enigmatic vision is a ``special issue'' celebrating Guitar Gods,
those all-time classic pickers like Hendrix, Keith Richards, Carlos
Santana, Albert Collins, and B. B. King, who have channeled their
hearts through their fingers, cut through our numbness and pain,
and scared us half to death with their brighter-than-lightning
licks. The feature is a tribute to the electric instrument that has
stimulated enough mind-altering music, sex appeal, political
friction, and drug drama to make its chronicler, Rolling Stone,
into one of the most successful publications in the country.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good moment to reestablish devotion to ``youth culture's
weapon of choice during the last fifty years,'' as managing editor
Robert Love puts it. As pop music continues to become submerged in
the studio-ized magnificence of electronica and the cleverness and
scrappiness of sampling, the Guitar Gods feature brings it all back
home. Basically, the magazine asked a few dozen players to talk
about their own guitar heroes and recall their ``Great Guitar
Moments,'' the first riffs that moved them to pick up their own
guitars. Richards says Chuck Berry's 1950s records are ``rock 'n'
roll guitar playing to the max,'' and he describes his own passion:
``Everybody else is asleep, or gone, or your old lady's left you.
Well, you've always got her. I mean, the shape alone. . . . I sleep
with the thing sometimes.'' Jeff Beck praises Django Reinhardt,
Vernon Reid praises Santana, and Santana praises John Lee Hooker:
``It's like the devil and God playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimonials are perked up by the sort of creative
phraseology that shows how challenging it can be to write and talk
about the fleeting power of music. Nancy Wilson says Jimmy Page's
chords were ``very left of center,'' Trey Anastasio from Phish
refers to the ``logical form'' of Jerry Garcia's playing, Reid
calls Santana's sound ``incredibly vocal,'' and Beck says that
Mance Lipscomb's blues ``sounds like a horse and carriage. It has
that atmosphere and that ricketiness. It's pre-jalopy.'' Nobody,
however, makes a comparison between Jimi Hendrix's electric guitar
magic and a piece of meat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The April Vanity Fair is the annual Hollywood issue, with a
triptych cover of acting's new kids. It's also, according to the
magazine, the ``biggest issue ever,'' with 414 pages of ads,
photos, ads, stories, and ads. The centerpiece is a lush portfolio
of Hollywood people, all stunning work by the usual classy snappers
_ Herb Ritts, Annie Leibovitz, Bruce Weber, David LaChapelle,
Firooz Zahedi, Helmut Newton, and Michael O'Neill. Leibovitz gives
Drew Barrymore and Gwyneth Paltrow a corpselike stillness, Ritts
turns Meryl Streep into her own best fan, and Zahedi brings us
close up to Loretta Young.
</P>
<P>
   There's a long piece by Sam Staggs in anticipation of next
year's 50th anniversary of ``All About Eve,'' the classic with
plenty of camp cachet. Staggs goes behind the scenes of the movie,
focusing on the star wars, Bette Davis's star trips, and the ``real
Eve,'' a woman called Miss X who pulled a fast one on an Austrian
star named Elisabeth Bergner.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe director Joseph L. Mankiewicz and producer
Darryl F. Zanuck first wanted Claudette Colbert or Gertrude
Lawrence to play Margo Channing. Davis, with the help of her Edith
Head outfits, left an indelible mark on the role. She also left an
indelible mark on her costars, including Gary Merrill, with whom
she fell in love on the set and married, and Celeste Holm, who
called Davis ``constantly rude.'' Apparently, Holm said, ``Good
morning'' to Davis early in the shoot, and Davis replied, ``Oh
(expletive), good manners.'' Supporting actress Marilyn Monroe also
had issues with Davis, saying, ``She didn't talk to me at all, just
sort of swept around the set, nose and cigarette in the air. She's
a mean old broad.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories _ and there are others, including George Sanders's
accusation that Davis lacked ``fundamental graciousness toward her
coplayers'' _ are juicy, recalling a time when actors could
misbehave in peace, without today's round-the-clock scrutiny by the
media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
