<HEADLINE>
WHEN SAILORS ARE IN PORT, SEAFARER'S FRIEND LIVES UP TO ITS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the early 1800s, Boston was a teeming port with merchant
sailing ships lining dock after dock. Many of the surrounding
streets were filled with seedy rooming houses, noisy bars and busy
brothels.
</P>
<P>
   Into this sometimes rough and tumble world some local ministers
thought there was a need to inject the word of God.
</P>
<P>
   So the Boston Seaman's Friend Society was born in 1827 with a
mission to provide for the spiritual and temporal needs of
seafarers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the society is now known as Seafarer's Friend and its
geographical reach extends to ships arriving in Portland, Maine,
and Portsmouth, N.H., as well as Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A ministry of the United Church of Christ, the work of
Seafarer's Friend has evolved as the needs of seafarers have
changed. Working on ships can be lonely, dangerous and backbreaking
work, said the Rev. Robert F.R. Peters, president of Searfarer's
Friend.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond tending to seafarers' souls, the organization, in visits
to more than 500 ships across New England each year, provides more
tangible aid _ warm winter clothes, phone cards so ship workers can
call home and tours of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The seafarers spend weeks confined to a ship and when they do
pull into port many times it's only for a day or even a few hours
because high-tech heavy machinery makes loading and unloading
vessels easier and quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many seafarers call their ships `a floating prison,' '' said
the Rev. Jan Willem Van der Werff, who spends four days a week
visiting the container ships, the oil tankers and automobile
carriers that arrive in Boston. ``You can go crazy. You live where
you work. The only people you have to talk to are your colleagues.
When you're in port you might be lucky to make one phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   Van der Werff, 31, who studied theology in his native Holland,
is perfectly suited to work among seafarers. His father was a
seafarer. So was his grandfather. Van der Werff himself
contemplated following the family tradition. But his father talked
him out of it, telling his son that seafaring is not as glamorous
as it might seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when my older sister was born, my father did not
see her until she was 1 1/2,'' he says, taking a break from
visiting crew members aboard a liquid natural gas tanker docked in
Boston. ``I thought when I started this job that things would have
changed. But it's still the same. Seafarers go out on 12-month
contracts and sometimes longer, never seeing their families. That
creates a lot of stress. And that's we have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, most seafarers Van der Werff works with come from Asia,
particularly the Philippines and India. Starting wages can be as
low as $200 a month _ seemingly poverty wages, but much better than
what seafarers can earn back home, Van der Werff noted. ``That is
if they even find a job,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Often, Seafarer's Friend also must play an advocacy role because
many seafarers are treated unfairly by their employers _ being made
to work longer than their contract states or having their wages
withheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly concerned with issues of equity for
seafarers,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Seafarer's Friend has been meeting with New England
Seafarer's Mission, which ministers to cruise ships, Mariner's
House, which provides rooms for seafarers in the North End and Our
Lady of Good Voyage, a Catholic church on the waterfront, to better
coordinate services to the shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world there are about 800 maritime ministries
operating in different ports, including 200 in the United States
and Canada. In many cases a minister is usually the first friendly
face a seafarer sees after being out to sea for long stretches of
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
