<HEADLINE>
FBI SEEKS SUSPECTS IN CASE OF MISSING WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 and JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONORA, Calif. _ FBI agents are questioning men with histories
of criminal violence in their quest for suspects in the
disappearance of a mother and two teen-age girls and the killings
of at least two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reviewing leads and information on possible suspects,''
said FBI Special Agent Nick Rossi, who provided little other
information on the case.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and other investigators are believed to be looking for at
three men as possible suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The intense search for the missing woman and two teen-agers
ended with discovery on March 18 of the missing trio's burned car
hidden in a ponderosa pine forest some three hours north of the
Cedar Lodge in El Portal, the town near the Yosemite National Park
where the women had been staying before they disappeared in
mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investigators found the charred bodies of Carole
Sund, 42, of Eureka and a second person, believed to be that of one
of the girls _ either Sund's daughter Julie, 15, or their friend
Silvina Pelosso, 16.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said they are seeking leads on the other
missing girl.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents and detectives from Tuolumne and Stanislaus counties
and Modesto have pored over dozens of arrest warrants of men
convicted of violent crimes to determine possible suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi said the FBI has accumulated a large volume of forensic
evidence, and much of it is being analyzed by the FBI crime lab in
Quantico, Va., but he declined to discuss the information.
</P>
<P>
   People who knew Carole Sund described her as a resourceful,
take-charge woman who would not have gone willingly with an
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that one of the bodies in that car would be Carole's,
because she would fight for those girls,'' her father, Eureka
businessman Francis Carrington, said.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington, who has praised the FBI and other law enforcement
agencies, said that even so, it's hard to sit and wait for the
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody knows the whole story, and we want it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of three men the FBI is looking at as possible suspects, one is
a 42-year-old ex-convict who lives in Modesto. His criminal record
stretches back to 1975 and includes convictions for a particularly
brutal rape of a relative while her children cowered nearby in a
car, as well as manslaughter, assault, drug possession and
attempted escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
