<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS CORRUPTION MORE WIDESPREAD OR IS IT JUST BETTER REPORTED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's hear it for the only force greater than gravity:
temptation.
</P>
<P>
   The scent of corruption overwhelms our olfactometer at a pace
unparalleled. But is humanity getting weaker? Or are there just
more of us to tumble into the pit? So sated is the news with moral
perfidy that it's hard to find a section of the paper that doesn't
reek of human failing. Is there more corruption around? Or just
more publicity about it?
</P>
<P>
   More congressional and prosecutorial lung power was spent on the
ultimately impotent impeachment business than anyone dreamed
possible. Enough said about Bill No. 1, the heartily hammered most
powerful gent in the world. Bill No. 2 (Gates), merely the richest
soul on earth, has his legal Rotweilers on the case, trying to
stave off a probe almost as long as Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot turn to the sunny playing fields of sport for relief.
The Lords of the Rings, that secretive, self-perpetuating body that
hijacked legal ownership and commercial profiteering of the
worldwide Olympic movement, are laid bare as bribe-taking
double-dealers who resist any but the most cosmetic attempts to
shovel out the dung-encrusted stable and start afresh.
</P>
<P>
   The manly art of self-defense made a cynical lunge for the
womanly share of the pay-per-view audience. Boxing's corrupt bosses
hired as title fight judge an accountant six weeks off her
bankruptcy declaration to officiate at the Holyfield-Lewis debacle.
Her judging was as bankrupt as her accountancy practice. The
ex-champ, Mike Tyson, is locked up. As boxing should be.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you looked last week, the mighty were getting humbled.
The European Commission resigned en masse; there were apparently
more rotten apples than good ones in that barrel. Russia's top
prosecutor, the unhappy star of a raunchy sex video, had to quit,
prompting Boris Yeltsin's former press secretary to say in Moscow,
``Everyone has compromising material on everyone else, and usually
it is true.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of Israel's third-largest political party, Aryeh Deri,
was convicted on corruption charges. The Rev. Allen Boesak, the
heroic black minister who stood strong against apartheid in South
Africa, fessed up to scamming on the side. Religion proved no
cleaner than the heavyweight title racket. The Rev. Henry Lyons,
head of this country's National Baptist Convention, quit after
conviction on racketeering and theft charges, nailed for handling
money and women, two temptations about which the Bible is
persistent and eloquent.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's defense minister? A drug dealer on a vast scale, some
disgruntled US investigators claimed to The New York Times after
they were ordered off the case. The Chinese government? Why, they
were spying on us! Who do they think they are? The Israelis? The
nerve of these Chinese!
</P>
<P>
   The US Congress, of course, is a great trumpeter of moral values
and proclaimer of personal political virtue. It spent most of last
year enmeshed in intimate ladies' apparel and only belatedly
realized its mistake.
</P>
<P>
   So our resensitized solons packed off last weekend to ``civility
camp'' in Pennsylvania for lectures and supervised recreation, not
unlike play group at the day-care center, with snacks, nappy time,
and constant encouragement to be nicer, kinder, gentler, and
remember to count to 10 before calling the other guy a scumbag, Mr.
Chairman. No word yet on whether the corrupt campaign finance
system will be changed. Maybe thay could hire the goofy lady boxing
judge to referee that debate. Or just-retired Major General David
Hale, fined and reprimanded for coercing sex from the wives of four
subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   A yearlong probe into presidential priapism wound down after a
half-dozen of his most rabid GOP foes found check marks on their
sexual morality rap sheets. To follow the papers, the moral outrage
meter is in danger of redlining. But, as Click and Clack, the
Tappet Brothers, would put it, maybe the trouble is in your gauge,
and not necessarily in your radiator core. Perhaps the media
machine is just more efficient at sniffing out scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The single most important task we have is bringing you ``the
news'' that has a bearing on how you and yours live day to day. But
our No. 2 chore is to ferret out corruption, look under rocks,
shine light in dark corners.
</P>
<P>
   Abuse of trust and double-dealing are all-too-human traits.
Nothing eradicates such sins like full, prompt and public
disclosure. Bad ink is like bleach; it kills germs. Making things
public has a remarkable and purgative impact on human affairs.
Things go better not with Coke but with disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The money people call it ``transparency.'' If the IOC made its
financial dealings public, as it should, it would be impossible to
manipulate site awards. If the Russian government had more
transparency and Russia's media were up to the job, then billions
of dollars in foreign aid that have disappeared into offshore Mafia
back accounts would have gone to the peasants who need it still.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy breeds coverup, period. Human nature doesn't change.
Temptation is the occasion for sin. The threat of disclosure is the
single greatest safeguard against succumbing to temptation. For a
lot of us sinners, fear of getting caught is the greatest deterrent
of them all. There's a lot to be said for shame. It's the cement
that holds the moral bricks together.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
