<HEADLINE>
HOMOSEXUAL SUES BOY SCOUTS OVER FIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A gay man fired from the Boy Scouts is suing the
organization, saying his boss hired private investigators to grill
his co-workers and friends and then fired him because of his sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Keener, 46, of Sacramento, filed the lawsuit Tuesday in
Sacramento Superior Court against the Golden Empire Council,
covering 16 counties in northeastern and central California.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit opens a new strategic front, employment, in the
struggle by the advocates of gay rights to push the Boy Scouts of
America to drop its adamant anti-gay stance. Efforts so far have
focused on the exclusion of Scout members and leaders who are
homosexual or who advocate gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Kors, a lawyer representing Keener, called the
investigation into Keener's private life an illegal and
unconstitutional witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit dismisses as a pretext the Boy Scouts' stated reason
for firing Keener in September _ his acceptance of a personal
discount from a company that was a major contributor, Kors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Keener was fired for being a gay man,'' Kors said. The
lawsuit contends that his dismissal violates the California Labor
Code, which prohibits discrimination on the basis of sexual
orientation by all public and private employers except religious
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Johnson, the council executive for the Boy Scouts in
Sacramento, defended the dismissal of Keener as an assistant
council executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Keener's discharge is based on his failure to properly
account for and resolve a situation involving personal use of some
contributed resources,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says Keener earned his Eagle Scout rank and in 1976
went to work for the Boy Scouts, first in San Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   Over 22 years he was promoted through various other posts until
reaching assistant executive in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Keener said Tuesday he always kept his personal life separate
from his professional life. The lawsuit says he was told many times
by his bosses that any employee who was known to be gay would be
fired.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, a co-worker was called in by Johnson
and told that investigators had been hired to determine if Keener
was homosexual. The lawsuit says the co-worker was subjected to
three hours of questioning, asked about her private conversations
with Keener, if she knew if he was gay and who his friends were.
</P>
<P>
   Keener's lawyer said investigators also questioned his friends.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages for Keener, who said he's
been unable to find equivalent employment and is driving a truck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1418EST &QL; 
