<HEADER>
A2438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-24 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL IS ONE OF THE LAW'S MESSIEST CORNERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In one of the many beguiling moments in Charles
Kenney's novel ``The Son of John Devlin,'' the title character
ruminates about the law, or at least the jurisprudence he inhaled
in academe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only person I know who actually enjoyed law school,''
Devlin says. ``It was so well-ordered, and what was required was so
plain and direct. It wasn't as though you had to be some sort of
analytical genius. It's not like math or the sciences, where
breakthroughs are what matter. There really isn't anything new to
learn. It's all there, collected in one place. All the rules are
there. I like the tidiness of it. The clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tidiness and clarity do not describe the legal grotesquerie
known as the Independent Counsel Act of 1994, based on the 1970s
hubris favoring nonpolitical solutions to politics and extralegal
approaches to the law. All three branches of government and the
public that hires them now recognize the folly of thinking, There
really isn't anything new to learn. The law that pandered to an
American appetite for antiseptic tidiness is now alarmingly messy.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Founding Fathers expect law to be used to pursue people
instead of crimes? In 1780, John Adams wrote into the Massachusetts
Constitution the aim of American democracy: ``A government of laws
and not of men.'' Adams risked his life to oppose King George III.
Would he readily surrender absolute power to a special prosecutor?
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee has held hearings on
the possible renewal of the law, which expires June 30. Senators
Fred Thompson, Republican of Tennessee, and Joseph I. Lieberman,
Democrat of Connecticut, have engaged in thoughtful exchanges with
witnesses, but some colleagues have been as glib as Gilda Radner on
``Saturday Night Live.'' Caught in a gross error, her character
said, ``Never mind!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Senator Richard J. Durbin, Democrat of
Illinois, said. ``Four years ago I voted to reauthorize this law.''
If he was mistaken, how about President Clinton? On June 30, 1994,
he called the law ``a foundation stone for the trust between the
government and our citizens'' and signed its reauthorization while
boasting that ``the independent counsel statute has been in the
past and is  &UR; today &LR;  a force for government integrity and public
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   As the president digests his own words, he avoids direct comment
on the law. In his press conference last week, he cited his status
as the statute's most notorious victim and most famous defendant.
Clinton, who seldom heeds Harry Truman's motto, ``The buck stops
here,'' passed this buck Friday to the American Bar Association,
which now opposes renewing the law.
</P>
<P>
   Shunning partisanship by invoking a supposedly neutral authority
is part of the Watergate hangover that created this whole
nightmare. More precisely, the special prosecutor law of 1978
ignited 20 nightmares: 20 prosecutors pursuing chosen victims,
their aggregate prosecutorial record a shallow dish of thin gruel
at a total cost of $148 million.
</P>
<P>
   If Kenneth W. Starr is the answer, what is the question? That
dilemma may trouble Congress as much as its morbid fear of being
called partisan. Even Common Cause, the Marley's ghost of the
Watergate nightmare, is having second thoughts. But instead of
letting the law die, the citizen's lobby is peddling more
nonpolitical, extralegal gizmos and gadgets, anything to prevent
elected public officials from taking responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Son of John Devlin'' deals with betrayal, corruption, sin,
and the limits of law. Congress should heed its lesson, based on
that evoked by John Milton in ``Paradise Lost,'' that ``law can
discover sin but not remove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Were Congress to resume its oversight powers, it could shame the
president and errant Cabinet members into doing their duty. A tribe
of righteous congressional investigators facing reelection is
better than an insidious, nonaccountable pack of special
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
