A2446 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-METHODISTS-HNS &LR;      03-24 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-METHODISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHODISTS SEEK TO DISCIPLINE PASTORS OVER GAY BLESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The United Methodist Church has filed charges
against 69 of its pastors in Northern California and Nevada for
going against church law and blessing a lesbian couple.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Melvin Talbert announced the charges in Sacramento on
Tuesday, along with a plea for the church to change its stance and
fully accept gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very painful day for me,'' the bishop wrote. ``I
will uphold the law, but I will not be silenced.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on Methodists on both sides of the issue to agree to
disagree and keep working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue ... working to change the position of our
church,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The charges had been expected since the Rev. Don Fado of St.
Mark's United Methodist Church in Sacramento led 94 of his fellow
clergy members in blessing the union of two members of his
congregation in a highly publicized ceremony Jan. 16. The charges
were filed against Fado and the other 68 participants from the
bishop's district.
</P>
<P>
   Fado said Tuesday, ``I think this is an opportunity for us to
show the country how we can find unity in the midst of our
diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Filing of charges triggers a investigation that could lead to a
church trial of the 69, or the charges could be dropped. At worst,
the 69 could lose their ordinations.
</P>
<P>
   The issue threatens to split the United Methodist Church and is
causing debate in every other major Christian denomination in the
United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
