<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2451 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-24 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NORTH KOREAN THREAT DOESN'T JUSTIFY DEATH STAR REDUX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I cannot believe that there are more than 10 people between
Portland, Maine, and Portland, Ore., who lie awake at night in
feverish sweats worrying about being vaporized by North Korea. Yet
in Washington, it is as if Ronald Reagan is still in charge,
pointing at futuristic drawings for those George Lucas photo ops of
the 1980s, urging us to ring the planet with death stars.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearly two decades since Reagan came to power, the United
States has spent $55 billion (almost half of what it would cost to
fix the schools) trying to build a missile defense system Darth
Vader would not laugh at. Darth is on the floor rolling. We have
not hit a missile in several practice attempts.
</P>
<P>
   That has not stopped a Washington that refuses to give the peace
dividend a chance. Though even President Bush thought a space-based
missile system was impossible and ridiculous, defense hawks in
Congress and the weapons contractors who bankroll them kept
paranoia alive on a Capitol Hill too petrified to question
thousand-dollar military toilets for fear of looking weak on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the House, in a 317-105 vote, and the Senate, in a
97-3 vote, resurrected Reagan's failed dreams. They approved
legislation to again develop missile defense. President Clinton,
ever the Republicrat chameleon, has pledged $10.5 billion over the
next six years to resume research.
</P>
<P>
   The votes came with a swiftness and lack of debate that was
incredible, given how we dissected every aspect of Monicagate. It
was abominable, given how much we have spent on nuclear weapons
programs with no oversight. It was insane, given that we already
have the power to char everyone on earth, which means that any
enemy pushing his red button has just committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   People complain about the $50 million Kenneth Starr spent over a
White House affair. The United States has spent $5.8 trillion for
nuclear weapons since 1940, a figure that is more than the combined
federal spending in the last half-century for education, job
training, agriculture, environment, social services, general
science, and space research, community development, disaster aid,
police, and energy production.
</P>
<P>
   In a groundbreaking report published last year by the Brookings
Institution, America's nuclear weapons programs have come at a cost
that, if we were talking welfare for poor folks, would make even
welfare advocates scream for cuts. We have up to 130,000
Hiroshima-sized bombs. Given that our World War II blast of that
Japanese city resulted in 200,000 deaths, we have the capacity to
kill earth's population 4 1/2 times.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, ``Atomic Audit: The Costs and
Consequences of US Nuclear Weapons since 1940,'' the evidence is
abundant of knuckleheaded nuclear ideas by paranoid politicians.
Author Stephen Schwartz said, ``When Admiral Arleigh Burke, chief
of naval operations, stated in 1957 his belief that the equivalent
of 720 warheads on invulnerable Polaris submarines would be enough
to deter the Soviet Union, the United States already had six times
as many deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When retired Army Chief of Staff General Maxwell Taylor wrote
in 1960 that `a few hundred missiles' (presumably armed with a `few
hundred' warheads) would satisfy deterrence, the United States
already had some 7,000 strategic nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara argued in 1964
that within a few years the equivalent of 400 megatons would be
enough to achieve mutual assured destruction and hence deterrence,
the US stockpile had almost 17,000 megatons, 17 billion tons of TNT
equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, there has always been a tremendous gap between what
informed military and civilian leaders thought necessary for
deterrence and what was actually deployed, a state of affairs that
has not changed with the end of the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a tremendous gap in accountability because
Congress, according to Schwartz, ``has never held a hearing,
debate, or vote on the cost, scale, pace, or implications of the
overall program, even though the potential for waste, fraud, and
abuse is at least equal to that for entitlement programs.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in the resurrection of Reagan's Death Star to
assure us of accountability, let alone sanity. Since 1957, when
Sputnik freaked out America, we have spent a total of $100 billion
on missile defense systems. Yet, as Schwartz says, ``we are not
much closer to creating a viable missile shield.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Secretary of Defense Neil McElroy stopped a foolish,
anti-Russian missile defense project for its cost and
ineffectiveness. He said, ``We should not spend hundreds of
millions on production of this weapon pending general confirmatory
indications that we know what we are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one years later, Congress and Clinton, spooked over
countries we could scorch in seconds, rush to spend billions on
weapons. They do it with no confirmatory indication they know what
they are doing. Darth Vader is on the floor in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
