A2453 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PRESSURE-BOS &LR;      03-24 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PRESSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S GOOD REASON PRESSURE COOKERS ARE MAKING A COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the first word associated with a piece of cooking equipment
is fear, you would think the machine didn't stand a chance.
Emotions run deep, especially in the kitchen. But the pressure
cooker has defied logic.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a generation, no one has used pressure cookers except
for women who were housewives in the 1950s, who tended to cook food
to death (their children claim). Now the cookers are taking off
again, rescued by very modern cooks from a variety of backgrounds,
who all share one thing in common: too little time. People will do
anything to save time _ even overcome fear. In fact, they'll
replace fear with fervor.
</P>
<P>
   Fervor for a pot? Here's what one reader wrote to Lorna Sass,
author of ``The Pressured Cook'' (Morrow, 1999): ``You have changed
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Others must agree. The US distributors for Magefesa, a sleek
spring-valve pot made in Spain, report ``huge sales.'' Amy Aldape
of North American Promotions in Palatine, Ill., which sells the
cookers by mail order (see accompanying story), says the company
has grown 1,000 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sass waited years to hear things like this. She thinks there's
more behind the pot's popularity than the need for speed. One
factor is the redesigned, streamlined pressure cookers from Europe,
which are essentially foolproof: The lid locks into place by
sliding together with the saucepan. Another is a longing for
old-fashioned food, the kind Sass describes as having ``a
soul-satisfying aspect,'' which is where the pressure cooker
excels. Then there's the growing population of vegetarians, who are
using pressure cookers for dried peas and beans; restaurateurs, who
are also buying them for legumes; and cooks on boats and in RVs,
who are short on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, pressure cookers are going to ordinary families who
don't want the nightly meal to consist entirely of pizza and
carry-out food. ``For a family on the run,'' says Stephen Black of
the Back Bay cookware shop KitchenArts, ``there's no better thing
to have around the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the pressure that builds up inside the sealed cooker,
food bubbles away at a higher temperature (250 degrees) than it
would in a regular pot (212 degrees). ``At this higher-than-normal
boiling point,'' writes Sass in her book, ``the fiber in food
breaks down and the flavors mingle in one-third or less the
standard cooking time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, you get a great flavor along with a satisfying texture.
The goal isn't to replicate your mother's overcooked pot roast but
to cook the meat quickly, just until it is very tender, and add
sophisticated garnishes _ like ginger and curry spices or roasted
peppers and fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround for the pot began slowly. For many years, the
only young cooks with pressure cookers were those who grew up with
them. ``I learned to use one when I was 19,'' says Judith Barrett,
author of ``Saved by Soup'' (Morrow, 1999). ``My mother always used
one, my brother and his wife cooked their brown rice and beans in
the pressure cooker, and I wanted to make chicken soup taste like
my mother's.'' She began with a jiggle-top pot, eventually
inherited her mother's cooker, then decided to move to the new
generation of spring-valve pots. ``I had eight. I gave some away.
Now I have five.''
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, pressure cookers were associated with terror,
because of someone's mother's split peas hitting the ceiling.
Everyone seems to have one of these family legends, revolving
around too much pressure that built up in a pot and sent food
flying out the top. ``I've heard so many versions of Aunt Tillie's
soup on the ceiling, I can't tell you,'' says Sass.
</P>
<P>
   But that can't happen with the new spring-valve pressure
cookers. Heavy, sturdily built, with a well-constructed bottom, the
``second-generation'' cookers, as Sass calls them, have built-in
safety mechanisms so the contents can't fly out. Even untrained,
tied-in-knots, technophobic cooks can operate the new pressure
cookers without worry.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently they do. Cheryl Trecoske of the television
shopping channel QVC says, ``They've been very successful over the
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``successful,'' Trecoske means about 24,000 cookers selling
in a 24-hour period, as they did last month. The same week last
year, 16,000 pots sold in a special offer. QVC airs segments for
pressure cookers about three times a month, says Trecoske.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
ITALIAN WEDDING SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Pressured Cook,'' by Lorna Sass (Morrow,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   For the meatballs:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound ground beef
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated Pecorino Romano or Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated or powdered garlic, or 1 1/2 teaspoons
minced fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the soup:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups thinly sliced leeks or coarsely chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken or beef broth, or combine them
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Italian herb blend
</P>
<P>
   3 large carrots, peeled, halved lengthwise, and cut into
1/2-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pastini or other small pasta, such as tubetti or
ditalini
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds escarole, trimmed and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly grated Pecorino Romano or Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   For the meatballs: In a large bowl, combine all the ingredients
by blending them with your hands. Shape the mixture into bite-size
balls. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the soup: Heat the oil in the cooker over medium-high heat.
Cook the leeks, stirring frequently, for 2 minutes. Blend in the
tomato paste and cook for an additional minute, stirring
constantly. Add the broth and herbs, taking care to scrape up any
browned bits. Add the carrots. Bring to a boil over high heat, then
add the pastini. Lower the heat to medium. Gently drop the
meatballs into the broth a few at a time. Set the escarole on top.
(Don't be concerned that the cooker will be filled almost to the
brim; the escarole will shrink dramatically.)
</P>
<P>
   Lock the lid in place. Over high heat, bring to high pressure.
(This may take 5 minutes since the cooker is so full.) Reduce the
heat just enough to maintain high pressure and cook for 1 minute.
Quick-release the pressure by setting the cooker under cold running
water.
</P>
<P>
   Stir gently. With a slotted spoon, remove 1 meatball. Slice it
in half and check that it is cooked through. If not, simmer the
broth, uncovered, over medium heat until the meatballs are done, 1
to 2 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Adjust the seasonings and serve in large bowls. Top each portion
with a generous sprinkling of grated cheese. Pass the remaining
cheese in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most practical size of pressure cooker is the 6-quart model
(marked 5 liters on European pots). This may seem large, but the
cooker can't be filled all the way to the top or it won't come up
to pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the European spring-valve pots cost between $100 and
$170 because of the complicated pressure mechanism in the lid.
According to a rating in Cook's Illustrated magazine a few years
ago, the Magefesa and Kuhn Rikon are the two superior cookers, with
Fagor and Monix next.
</P>
<P>
   Magefesa is not available in retail stores. You can order it by
mail (888-787-9991) or over the Internet (magefesausa.com). Kuhn
Rikon is available at KitchenArts in Back Bay (617-266-8701) and
through the Williams-Sonoma catalog (800-541-2233). Williams-Sonoma
stores sell the Fagor brand.
</P>
<P>
   For all the cookers, follow the manufacturer's instructions
carefully. Kuhn Rikon's instructions, says Stephen Black of
KitchenArts, are ``clear, succinct, confidence building, and easy
to understand,'' which is what you need the first time out.
</P>
<P>
   Once the food is cooked, you can let the pressure come down
naturally without help, or use Sass's quick-release method. To
quick-release, set the hot pan in the sink and run cold water over
the top. Tip the pan slightly so no water seeps into the vent near
the handle (if there is one) or onto the pressure rod. The pressure
will drop in minutes and you can open the cooker easily. This
system prevents food from becoming overcooked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
