<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-IT'SLIKE-BOS &LR;      03-24 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-IT'SLIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SITCOM OWES HEAVY DEBT TO SEINFELD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's like, you know, ``Seinfeld.'' And it's like, you know,
about nothing, except that it's set in Los Angeles, the capital
city of nothing, which presides over the state of vapidity, air
kissing, and locutions like ``It's like, you know.'' And it's like,
you know, much better than it has any right to be, especially
considering A) there are already too many sitcoms with 20-something
singles bantering about breasts, and B) its cutesy-colloquial
title, ``It's like, you know,'' makes you want to take refuge in a
dusty old grammar book.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, I was inclined to dislike this new ABC series, and
not just because of the title. Of the many ``Seinfeld''-influenced
sitcoms, including the successful ``Friends,'' ``It's like, you
know'' has the distinction of being the most brazen imitator.
Created by ``Seinfeld'' producer Peter Mehlman, it makes no bones
about wanting to inherit the crown, directly lifting the
Seinfeldian micro-view of life by turning the tiniest quirks into a
full-fledged comedy of manners. Nose jobs and uneven breasts all
become extended ``bits,'' with characters who are as shameless
about their shallowness as Jerry, Elaine, &AMP; Co. Two of the show's
five gabbers, Robbie and Shrug, even have inane George-and-Jerry
conversations, to the tune of: ``Don't you think the letter Q
should come a lot farther down in the alphabet?''
</P>
<P>
   Also predisposing me against ``It's like, you know'' is its
sheer soullessness. The show represents Hollywood celebrating its
own emptiness and materialism, in order to create the sort of
entertainment success that makes Hollywood such an empty and
materialistic place. The Tinseltown self-debasement is at its peak
with the casting of Jennifer Grey, who plays herself (unlike the
four other leading actors). In Wednesday's premiere, Grey, who has
undergone enough serious cosmetic surgery since ``Dirty Dancing''
to make her unrecognizable, submits to ongoing jokes about her new
face. When one character doesn't believe she's actually Jennifer
Grey, she brightly exclaims, ``Nose job!,'' and he responds, ``Just
one?'' While the quips are funny, it's a little sad to think of
Grey using her surgical mistakes as a way to re-ignite her career.
</P>
<P>
   But: the confident and ironic tone of ``It's like, you know'' is
infectious, and you may find yourself catching the buzz after an
episode or two. Against all odds, the series manages to caricature
a city that is already a living caricature of itself. The writing
is sharp, and the episode concepts are clever, including an entire
half-hour built around the observation that LA grinds to a halt
during a high-speed highway chase, to watch it on live TV. ``It's
our version of a snow day,'' one character notes. There are small
anthropological details everywhere, including an ongoing visual
joke that has the natives constantly toting bottles of water and a
forthcoming episode that finds the gang visiting an
``amnesiologist'' who can erase troublesome memories. Also, in the
manner of ``The Larry Sanders Show'' and Robert Altman's ``The
Player,'' the series features cameos by LA types like Elliott Gould
and Kato Kaelin, who show up as themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As on ``Friends,'' each of the ``It's like, you know''
characters is distinct _ a real plus in the ensemble sitcom genre.
The setup has cynical New Yorker Arthur (Chris Eigeman) coming to
LA for two months to write about the city of fallen angels. He's
staying with his old friend Robbie (Steven Eckholdt), who converted
to Left Coastism after making his fortune bringing the High
Holidays home to Jews via ``Pay Per Jew,'' and a quirky fellow
named Shrug (Evan Handler). The eggheaded Shrug is a wonderful
creation, a ``trustafarian'' who suffers debilitating guilt from
his independent wealth, and who believes, rightly, that black
people don't like him. Also hanging out at Robbie's house are Grey
and a flighty masseuse named Lauren (A. J. Langer), who sometimes
serves subpoenas to criminals once she's got them on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Eigeman, best known from his work in Whit Stillman movies
``Metropolitan'' and ``The Last Days of Disco,'' is perfect as the
grumpy New Yorker with a weakness for models. Eckholdt, who
resembles a young Colin Firth, plays the transplanted Manhattanite
to a T, marveling at the mellow freedoms of the West Coast: ``You
don't even have to be interesting in LA!'' And Handler, with his
broad frown, and the bubbly Langer _ best known from ``My So-Called
Life'' _ take the show's sensibility a giddy step further into
absurdity. Only Grey, who works well as the object of humor, is out
of place, not entirely in synch with sitcom-styled delivery and
timing. She's, like, you know, a little too real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
