<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, March 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ NATO confirmed it had begun air
strikes against Yugoslavia. U.S. officials said the attacks would
be the first stage of an extended Allied bombing campaign.
Developing. By Francis X. Clines. With graphics and photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton addresses the
nation on the airstrikes. Developing. This story may become a News
Analysis, depending on the day's events. By John M. Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Washington) _ A consideration of how
realistic are Allied goals for resolving the Kosovo crisis through
airstrikes, in the context of similar, successful Allied bombings
in Bosnia. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ NATO bombing has solidified support
for Milosevic among the young Serb intellectuals who had formerly
opposed him. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Milosevic appeared defiant on Serb
television on Wednesday; mood of resignation and disbelief on the
streets. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Undated) _ The day's developments on the ground. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ In an unusual statement, NATO
assured five of Yugoslavia's neighboring countries, including
Albania, Bulgaria and Macedonia, that it would consider any threat
to their security unacceptable. That position would represent a
significant expansion of NATO's mission. Developing. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Russian media, in a surprising move,
criticized Prime Minister Primakov for placing Russian-Serb
relations above Russian-U.S. relations in abruptly returning home
yesterday. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-BRITAIN (London) _ Pinochet must face extradition to
Spain after a court upholds his arrest, although he can't be
prosecuted for pre-1988 activities, the court said. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-CHILE (Santiago) _ Reaction from Chile to the British
court ruling on Pinochet. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-BOESAK (Cape Town) _ Alan Boesak is sentenced to six
years in prison for corruption, one day after a white farmer
received no jail time for killing a black infant. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-UNION (Berlin) _ Former Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi was named the new president of the E.U. governing body, the
European Commission, after the entire commission resigned in
disgrace last week. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMS (Moscow) _ The Russian cargo plane carrying MiGs
that was interecepted in Azaerbaijan on Tuesday was apparently
headed to a Czech company that is licensed to buy and sell them. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Two months before the 10th
anniversary of the crackdown on protesters in Tiananmen Square, a
former top Chinese official has sent an impassioned letter to
China's leaders urging them to end the ``cover up'' and renounce
the order that sent armed soldiers to disperse the demonstrators,
killing hundreds. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NKOREA (Tokyo) _ Japan on Wednesday called on North Korea
to seize and hand over two ships that had triggered a crisis
beginning Tuesday in the Sea of Japan. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-STRIKE (Jerusalem) _ Israel's 400,000 public-sector
workers (in a country with 6 million population) went on strike,
shutting post offices, phones and other essential services. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIR-SAFETY (Washington) _ The NTSP is expected to make
recommendations regarding the safety of rudders on Boeing 737s on
the final day of the hearing on the longest-running mystery in
commercial aviation. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Susan McDougal is
cross-examined as her trial continues. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Arguments are heard in a case that
challenges police who allow news crews to accompany them on
arrests; rulings in carjacking case. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HURRICANE-AID (Washington) _ The House acted on a
supplemental appropriations bill and cut Clinton spending that it
had reluctantly agreed to in order to pay for Latin American
hurricane aid. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   STARBUCKS-KILLINGS (Washington) _ Police say they have solved
the Starbucks killings.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-TRAFFIC (Atlanta) _ The state legislature created the
post of transportation czar to oversee all of issues in the state
from sprawl to traffic jams. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE (Will move in category `a') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INSTITUTE-DIRECTOR (Undated) _ The Howard Hughes Medical
Institute, the largest biomedical philanthropy organization in the
nation, named a new director: Thomas Cech, a biologist from the
University of Colorado with no administrative experience. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MANHATTAN (Undated) _ In something of a surprise, Chase
Manhattan designated William B. Harrison Jr., a vice chairman, to
succeed Walter V. Shipley and Thomas G. Labrecque as chief
executive and president on June 1. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-NETSCAPE (Mountain View, Calif.) _ America Online is
expected to announce a restructuring in the wake of its purchase of
Netscape Communications. Analysts expect the layoffs of about 700
people, which will be split between the two companies. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-MEET-ASSESS (Vienna, Austria) _ A news analysis on why the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries appears stronger and
its alliance with non-OPEC producers actually seems to be working.
By Youssef M. Ibrahim. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GATES-BOOK-TOUR (New York) _ Bill Gates swept through New York
on his book tour, meeting the press at a background-only lunch and
then appearing at a Barnes &AMP; Noble. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ECONOMY (Undated) _ What is at stake economically in
Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-IMF (Hong Kong) _ A senior official of the
International Monetary Fund, Hubert Neiss, says he is expecting the
fund to approve more financial aid to Indonesia in a board meeting
in Washington on Thursday. Indonesia's chief economic official,
Ginandjar Kartasasmita, has asked for an extra $1 billion in aid.
By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-HOLOCAUST-BANKS (Paris) _ French banks have announced a
plan for full restitution of dormant Holocaust-era accounts.
</P>
