<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCOS-DAVIS-BOS &LR;      03-24 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-DAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER SALESMAN DAVIS TAKES HIS LUMPS AS LYCOS DEAL IS CHALLENGED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ By early February, Lycos Inc. chief executive
Bob Davis had narrowed the search for a partner for his Internet
company to a few candidates, including General Electric Co.'s NBC
television network.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had a reputation as a super salesman, dating back to the
11 years he had spent hawking minicomputers for Wang Laboratories
Inc. But as the 42-year-old Dorchester native chatted with General
Electric chief Jack Welch, it became clear that this was one sale
he wasn't going to make. People familiar with the conversation say
Welch refused to trade GE's shares for Lycos stock, which he
dismissed as overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuffed, Davis instead announced a merger on Feb. 9 with major
units of USA Networks Inc., the New York media company controlled
by Barry Diller.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Davis must close the toughest sale of his career. His deal
has been thrown into jeopardy. Investors who had hoped for a merger
that included a high premium for Lycos stock drove down its share
price by a third after the announcement. To complete the merger,
Davis needs approvals from disappointed shareholders who still hope
a higher bid might emerge for Lycos, the fourth-most popular portal
site on the World Wide Web behind America Online, Microsoft, and
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the stock's decline, David Wetherell, the Internet
investor who helped found Lycos and recruited Davis to the company,
abandoned his initial support for the deal, quit the Lycos board of
directors, and vowed to use his 18.5 percent stake in Lycos to
arrange a competing bid for the company.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other institutional investor also says he would
vote against the agreement. ``They haven't made a compelling
presentation,'' said the investor of Davis and his would-be USA
Networks allies.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of smaller investors suggest Davis does not appreciate
the potential of the new medium. To some of these critics, the
stratospheric values of Internet stocks are justified. They had
expected Davis to strike a deal with terms as generous as those
received by rival Internet portals like Excite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis is one dumb donkey!'' read one recent message on an
Internet message board devoted to investing.
</P>
<P>
   Another writer commented: ``How stupid is Davis _ I can't wait
to see him watch his career go down the toilet along with the deal
that he was so proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   But Davis has a track record of striking controversial deals
that in hindsight look like winners. Shares of Lycos dropped
significantly twice last year, after it invested in two smaller
Internet companies, Tripod Inc. of Williamstown and
California-based WhoWhere Inc. But neither drop prevented Lycos
shares from closing as high as 137 in the days leading up to the
USA agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Now Davis says he's not put off by the criticism. ``This isn't a
business that I run by consensus,'' said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is busy lobbying stock analysts and fund managers to
support the deal, which he says will give Lycos the chance to boost
revenue and profits immediately through partnerships with USA
Networks units like the Home Shopping Network and the Ticketmaster
event seating service.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting to put the matter to a shareholder vote isn't likely
for several months, but Davis has won over at least one major fund
manager so far. ``Davis knows what he's talking about,'' this
person said. .
</P>
<P>
   The Lycos chief seems an unlikely Internet seer, considering
that he hadn't even used e-mail before he became the company's
first employee in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was raised in Dorchester, the son of an attorney and a
homemaker. He attended Boston College High School and Northeastern
University, where he competed on the swimming team. Both his
parents had passed away by 1979, when Davis graduated with a degree
in business administration. Later, he earned an MBA from Babson.
</P>
<P>
   While attending Northeastern, Davis also spent three months as
an intern in an IBM sales office in Waltham. He applied to become
an IBM salesman after graduation, but the company wanted to make
him a systems engineer. ``The logic behind that was I had too much
of a baby face,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he took a sales job at General Electric, then joined
Wang in 1982. In his 20s at the time, Davis was part of a group of
practical jokers who secretly moved one another's cars around the
parking lot and cleaned out desks while coworkers were away,
recalls Tom Murphy, a former supervisor who is now a sales director
at Roll Systems Inc. in Burlington. ``They'd do terrible things to
each other,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, in 1984, Davis outmaneuvered IBM to gain
Wang's first pact to sell minicomputers to the Stop &AMP; Shop
supermarket chain. Then, when skeptical Wang executives balked at
the terms, Davis went back and ``talked them into it all over
again,'' Murphy recalled. Davis ``thought he had lost, and he came
back twice as hard,'' his former boss said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, Davis had become Wang's head of US commercial sales and
marketing, but left as the company's fortunes sank. He joined
Cambex Corp., a Waltham data-storage hardware company, where he was
working in 1995 when he got a call from Dan Nova, a former Wang
salesman who had gone to work for CMGI, Wetherell's Andover-based
venture capital firm that invests in Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As Davis recalls it, Nova asked: `` `What do you know about the
Internet?' I said, `Nothing.' He said: `You're the perfect guy for
this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nova needed an executive with a fresh perspective to oversee
CMGI's $2 million investment in a new Internet company called
Lycos. The firm, named after a web-spinning spider, used a
technology licensed from Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh
to create an index of World Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; , Lycos has about 750 employees and reported revenue of
$55.3 million for the six months ended January.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1995, Davis was Lycos's sole employee, camped
in a cubicle at CMGI's offices recruiting talent and capital. The
Web was just starting to become popular, but friends wondered why
Davis had left a secure sales career for the untested medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see the vision behind this thing, but Bob knew it
was going to be big,'' said Rich Davis, a friend who's not related,
who says he passed up an offer to join the fledgling company.
</P>
<P>
   That's now cause for teasing, Rich Davis says. For example, Bob
Davis will ``point things out in magazines and ask my wife if she
likes them. If she says yes, he'll say, `That's too bad. Rich could
have bought that for you,' '' Rich Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great at taunting. But if you go up against him, you're
going to lose,'' said John Troy, a neighbor of Bob Davis in
Southborough, where the Lycos chief lives with his wife and their
three children.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lycos's most recent proxy statement, filed in
November, Davis earned $250,000 last year in salary and bonus. In
addition, he was listed as the beneficial owner of 349,475 Lycos
shares, worth $31.9 million at  &UR; yesterday &LR; 's closing price of 91
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Davis say he is annoyed by the criticism of the
USA Networks deal by his own shareholders, particularly Wetherell,
who initially voted for the agreement. (Wetherell, on vacation,
declined to be interviewed for this article.)
</P>
<P>
   Davis declines to discuss the naysayers but insists that he put
together the best deal possible, after discussions with other
potential merger partners. Other people say those companies
included Time-Warner, Bertelsmann, and CBS Corp.
</P>
<P>
   No other companies were willing to offer billions in cash or
stock, Davis says. ``Many were willing to trade on-air promotion
and their Internet sites,'' Davis said. ``But in terms of putting
in real assets, none of them were willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The USA-Lycos deal, he insists, remains the best one for
shareholders in the long run. If only he can make the sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
