A2504 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHOW WENT ON _ AND ON AND ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the 1999 Oscarcast has finally concluded _ how long did
the show run this year, three days? _ I can offer my assessment of
the festivities: ``Zzzzzzzzzzzz...''
</P>
<P>
   Being a chronic insomniac, I am highly qualified to offer
irrefutable testimony that the decision of the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences to move its awards show from Monday to
Sunday was a stroke of genius. Sunday night is usually the worst
night of the week for me, sleepwise, but that
four-hour-and-then-some Oscar show was a miracle cure. I was
sleeping like a baby by the time Whoopi Goldberg made her third
costume change.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm kidding. I watched the whole thing, including the
excruciating pre-show shows on and around the celebrity-trampled
red carpet and all the post-show shows, from the party-hopping
inanity on ``E!'' to the special edition of ABC's ``Politically
Incorrect'' that wandered onto the airwaves at 3 a.m. or so.
</P>
<P>
   I saw more Oscar coverage than the law allows, as David
Letterman might say.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, David Letterman. The critics trashed his performance as
Oscar host a few years back, but I would have happily traded
Whoopi's repertoire of one-note political jokes and tasteless
sexual innuendoes for a few minutes of a smirking Dave saying:
``Oprah _ Uma. Uma _ Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a shame that the longest awards show in the history of
the universe couldn't at least have given us the irrepressible
Billy Crystal, whose handling of the emcee duties in recent years
has occasionally approached the sky-high standards set so long ago
by best-ever Oscar host Bob Hope and his worthy successor, Johnny
Carson.
</P>
<P>
   When Crystal hosts the Oscars, he clearly understands that the
show is not about him _ it's about the movies and the movie people
who are being honored. He also understands that political humor
must cross ideological and partisan boundaries to be funny. If it
doesn't cross those boundaries, it isn't humor _ it's propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopi Goldberg's anti-Republican shtick was tedious, but it
would have been a lot easier to stomach if she could have somehow
racked her brain and conjured up a punch line or two that ridiculed
a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopi wasn't trying to amuse the millions of movie fans who may
not be Democrats, of course. She was working a room that was
overpopulated not just by Democrats but by left-wing-nitwit
Democrats. We saw the leftwits in action _ or nonaction, as it were
_ when they sat on their hands during the presentation of a
lifetime achievement award to Elia Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan happens to be one of the greatest moviemakers of all time.
He also happens to be a man who committed the politically
unforgivable sin _ for the left _ of blowing the whistle on
Stalinists in the early 1950s, when Hollywood was blacklisting
known and suspected members of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic that Kazan's enemies were describing him in recent
days as a ``Benedict Arnold'' when in fact most red-blooded
Americans in the '50s would have considered communists to be
traitors and the people who exposed them to be patriots.
</P>
<P>
   And how ironic that actor Rod Steiger, who turned up on the
post-Oscar edition of ``Politically Incorrect,'' has been so
harshly critical of Kazan in recent interviews but apparently had
no qualms about appearing in Kazan's ``On the Waterfront'' _ a Best
Picture winner that launched Steiger's career two years after Kazan
supposedly betrayed all of moviedom.
</P>
<P>
   What's that, Rod? No instruction on the meaning of hypocrisy at
the Actors Studio?
</P>
<P>
   OK. I've stalled long as long as I can. Time to face the music:
I missed five out of seven on my Oscar predictions. I can't
remember a year when I was so far off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to me and other failed amateurs, however, I feel
obligated to point out that most of the expert prognosticators were
just as awful.
</P>
<P>
   About the only pre-Oscar prediction that was absolutely
accurate, in fact, was the prediction that this year's Oscars were
impossible to predict.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
