<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDENTS-METCO-BOS &LR;      03-24 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-METCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON GROUND FOUND IN STUDENTS' OVERNIGHT VISITS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Atyia Allen and Amanda Boege are friendly, but not best
friends. They say ``hey'' in the hallways of Lincoln-Sudbury High
School, where both are seniors. But neither would normally invite
the other home for a sleepover, for example, or find enough in
common to even talk on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there they were three nights ago in the Allen family's
apartment in Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, lying side by side
under a pink and blue quilt, blond Amanda in her suburban farmer's
market T-shirt and black Atyia in her Jamaican floral headwrap,
looking every bit the cultural contrasts they are.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to an invitation by seven Metco students at
Lincoln-Sudbury to six classmates and five teachers to spend five
days and four nights in their Boston homes, the girls found that,
pajamas being a great equalizer, they share at least a little
common ground:
</P>
<P>
   Both have considered being doctors; both got early acceptance to
college; both are still trying to figure out who their prom dates
will be.
</P>
<P>
   And they both think that for Metco to really succeed in its
integration mission, kids need to spend the night at each other's
homes, tour each other's neighborhoods, eat dinner at each other's
tables, and worship at each other's churches, as they have done
over the past four days.
</P>
<P>
   The city/suburban slumber party was Metco student Monique
Worrell's idea in January, and Superintendent John Ritchie, who
joined in by spending three nights at Monique's house, was
immediately enthusiastic. Metco is a Boston-area program that
enables children from the city to attend suburban schools.
</P>
<P>
   Says Amanda, ``I signed up for this program because I felt it
would give me a better idea of what it would be like to be a Metco
student _ to be in the minority, to have to work so hard to get to
school every day, to go to a school in a place so different than
where you live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't change the color of my skin, so I'm still missing half
of it, but I'm getting a pretty good idea of how they might feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda was one of eight local students eager to take the Metco
kids up on their offer. Most of her classmates, she says, have only
seen the Boston tourists see: Copley Place, Faneuil Hall, and
Newbury Street. She considers herself more worldly: Her father
lives in Brighton and she attended Boston public schools until
third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Thursday's bus ride home with Atyia to Dorchester _ a
60-minute odyssey that begins at a Sudbury wildlife refuge and ends
at the Ruggles MBTA station _ Amanda, the only white person on
board, feels awkward. Hands jammed in her pockets on the way home
from a pizza parlor, she lets Atyia do most of the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to put yourself in the position of being the
minority,'' Amanda says later. ``I was the only white person
walking down the street, or on this bus. This is how they feel
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Atyia, an outgoing, talkative, self-confident 17-year-old,
suprises Amanda by telling her that she was so intimidated as an
elementary school Metco student in Lincoln that she didn't speak in
class for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet today she says she would never return to public school in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I wanted to go to college, I'd better come out here
than go to a Boston school. It's all in the name,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Their clothing personifies the girls' completely different
personalities: Atyia favors gold chains, short skirts, clunky high
heels, and easy laughter. Amanda wears tiny silver earrings,
corduroys, sneakers, hooded sweater, and shy smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is connection.
</P>
<P>
   Still far from turning the corner from classmates to
``girlfriends,'' Atyia says that at least now when they pass in the
hallways, ``We'll talk, we'll have something to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe next time, I can sleep at her house.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicken curry is simmering, rice is boiling, and stomachs are
growling at Monique Worrell's house on Hewins Street in Dorchester.
Monique is hosting dinner for her Lincoln-Sudbury guests: school
newspaper editor Jonathan Sclarsic, 17; Ritchie, who is both
superintendent and school principal; and teachers Caroline Han
(history) and Tom Hooper (English.)
</P>
<P>
   While her mother cooks, Monique, 17, tries to do homework on the
kitchen island. Her younger brothers start teasing that she should
go to the prom with Jonathan.
</P>
<P>
   Monique laughs gamely, but glares at her brothers when Jonathan
isn't looking.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan, an intensely earnest young man who has worked as a
page in Washington for US Representative J. Joseph Moakley
(``fighting poverty and homelessness''), says he wants to
experience what city life was really like (is there really steady
violence?), where Metco kids really live (do most live in the
projects?) and how long the bus ride really takes (do they really
have to get up at 5 a.m.?).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see another culture and what urban living is like;
something we don't get much of in Sudbury,'' he said. ``It's much
nicer than I thought it would be. Much nicer. And it's quiet and
safe. I think it's going to be an interesting experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Monique, a born politician, (her mantra: ``Where is the
justice?'') says she considers school leaders like Jonathan a key
to her cause:
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get one kid to go back to the school and say, `You
should see how nice Monique's house is,' or `Their neighborhood is
really safe,' then we'll be happy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan and the superintendent have their own rooms in
Monique's elegant, Victorian home, which was renovated by her
father, Cecil, a school bus monitor by day and carpenter by night.
The family is proud to show off his handiwork: the gourmet kitchen,
formal dining room with crystal chandelier.
</P>
<P>
   Those details are not missed by Jonathan, whose architect father
built his family's contemporary home, which sits on 11 acres in
Sudbury and is shaped like a wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house is nice, even by Sudbury standards,'' Jonathan
observes.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner is ready. Sharon Worrell, Monique's mother, changes from
her blue hospital uniform (she is a mental health worker) to a
floral dress to serve her daughter's guests. She and her husband
and sons then eat in the kitchen, insisting that Monique's friends
take the table set with white linen and fine china.
</P>
<P>
   Monique says grace, as everyone stands behind their chairs,
heads bowed, while gospel music trickles in from the den.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation is polite, if somewhat reserved, but the group
is eager enough to continue that they all end up in Monique's
bedroom to hang out and gossip _ including Ritchie, who has been
criticized by some Metco students recently for imposing a mandatory
after-school tutoring program for any Metco student with a C
average, a rule not imposed on the other students.
</P>
<P>
   On this night however, Ritchie scores points just for being
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe the superintendent is hanging out on my
bed,'' said Monique, laughing. ``What have I done?''
</P>
<P>
   It's 6:30 a.m. Friday, but it might as well be the middle of the
night as far as Howie Fugate is concerned. Like most
Lincoln-Sudbury students, he drives his own car to school _ three
minutes away _ and can sleep until 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, after spending the night in Dorchester with his
friend and football teammate Daryl Short, Howie is barely awake as
the Metco bus makes its way from Codman Square to the Mass Pike.
</P>
<P>
   Although Howie and Daryl have been friends since 9th grade,
Howie had never been to Daryl's house. So the two bonded the
previous night in a male way: They watched basketball and talked
sports.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Howie is horrified at how early (5:15) Daryl has
to wake up to get to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see now how hard it is for him to get to school, do his work
and then play football,'' said Howie. ``This whole experience has
just given me a greater appreciation for everything the Metco kids
go through to be at my school. I mean, I take the place for
granted, but they really have to work to be there. Sympathy, that's
what I feel. Sympathy and admiration.''
</P>
<P>
   At the back of the bus, Emma Miniscalco, 18, of Sudbury, is
talking about her experience with Natalie Brown, 17, of Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so isolated in my town. They were saying to me,
`Don't get shot','' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie was appalled. ``Who said that? WHO SAID THAT? I want
names!'' Emma demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why we did this program,'' Natalie told her. ``You
have to go back and tell them that is just not true. The city is a
safe place; my family is like your family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell them it's pretty courageous to be a Metco
student,'' Emma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
