<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CHANT-TEX     03-24 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHANT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC CELEBRATING MARY VISION HITS BILLBOARD CHARTS _ 400 YEARS
LATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Unless you were living in Central America
400 years ago, you've never heard anything quite like ``Guadalupe:
Virgen De Los Indios.'' Slow, soothing, gorgeous in its hymnal
softness and punctuated by percussion and wind instruments such as
rocks, log drums and clay flutes, ``Guadalupe'' is a true hybrid:
part classical, part world beat.
</P>
<P>
   This second effort by the San Antonio Vocal Arts Ensemble is
reminiscent of Gregorian chants, and for good reason: The music was
influenced by European vocals of the 1400s and 1500s. But its
percussion is as much a part of Native American traditions. And its
subject matter is older than the Pilgrims. These 18 brief songs,
dating from 1585 to 1600 and hidden away in a church attic for more
than 350 years, celebrate one of the most famous events in Mexico:
the appearance of the Virgin Mary to Juan Diego on Dec. 12, 1531.
</P>
<P>
   This merging of vocals, percussion and sacred subject matter has
made ``Guadalupe,'' on the tiny Talking Taco label, a hit with
devout Catholics and lovers of ethnic music. The CD recently landed
in the Top 15 of the Billboard Top World Music Albums chart,
alongside artists such as the Gipsy Kings and Ry Cooder's Buena
Vista Social Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it stirs a chord with people,'' says Christopher
Moroney, a graphic artist who, with his wife, Covita, marketing
director of the San Antonio Symphony, formed SAVAE in 1989. They,
along with members Lee P'Pool, Kathy Mayer, Jody Noblett, Paula
Olsen and Tanya Moczygemba, saw it as a way to celebrate early
music, especially that of colonial Latin America. ``People are
looking for a spiritual experience through music, and the story has
a mystical quality to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But that story might well have begun and ended back in the 1500s
_ if not for a chance discovery in a small Guatemalan village in
1963.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of the Virgin to Diego, a Nahua Indian, was the
catalyst for the conversion to Catholicism of millions of people in
Latin America. Symbolizing the merging of the Native American and
European cultures, the event was celebrated endlessly in song and
story.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemalan Tomas Pascual was a devotee of the Virgin. He wrote
songs with titles such as ``De la Sagrada Maria'' (''From the
Sacred Mary)'' and ``Virgen Madre de Dios'' (''Virgin Mother of
God).'' These popular songs were sung in churches and small
villages.
</P>
<P>
   And then, sometime after 1600, the manuscripts of these and
other songs were put in a small wooden box. Some were in Nahuatl,
the language of the Aztecs; others were in Guatemalan dialects,
archaic Spanish or Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Centuries passed. At some point, the box was put in the attic of
a small church in the village of Santa Eulalia. And there it might
have stayed, forgotten, if not for Father Daniel P. Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the church's roof was being repaired. Jensen, recently
assigned to the area, scrambled up to the dusty attic and
discovered the box. Curious, he opened it.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen looked through the music, much of it in what appeared to
be its original deerskin bindings, and knew he had _ well, he
didn't know what he had. He mailed a page to Robert Stevenson, a
friend and music professor in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson got on a plane the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a musicologist, he recognized this as an original
document from the 16th century, music from the century of the
Spanish conquest,'' Moroney said. ``This obviously was an exciting
historical find.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, the songs went on a long trip.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson became a professor at the University of California at
Los Angeles and published some of the music in his ``Inter-American
Music Review.'' In 1981, it was transcribed by musicologist Sheila
Raney Baird for her master's thesis at what was then North Texas
State University in Denton. From there, it went into two archives:
those of the University of Texas and the Lilly Library in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Moroneys had seen Stevenson's UCLA journal years before and
had used a couple of Pascual pieces on their first CD, 1997's
``Native Angels.'' The CD included music from colonial Latin
America from Peru, Cuba and Mexico. Then, after a concert in 1996,
Moroney was approached by a Mexican musicologist, Dr. Oscar
Garcia-Landois.
</P>
<P>
   Did they know, he asked, that there were far more Pascual pieces
available?
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Landois mailed transcriptions from the attic box to the
Moroneys, who were interested but unsure that the music would work
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already knew our second CD would be about the Virgin; you
can't overlook her importance and the event in the development of
Mexican civilization,'' he said. ``But initially I didn't think we
could use them. They were almost too simple.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Moroney had discovered ``Cantares Mexicanos,''
by drummer Don Francisco Placido. ``Cantares,'' which included drum
patterns in syllable form, had been compiled in the mid-1500s at
the behest of Aztec nobles to document their culture. The marriage
of Pascual's lyrics and Placido's percussion patterns clicked.
</P>
<P>
   Released in fall 1998, ``Guadalupe'' was immediately embraced by
the large Catholic population of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This CD is a major contribution to the whole field of
Guadalupe studies,'' said Father Virgil Elizondo, a San Antonio
resident and author of several books on the Virgin. ``It brings the
story out in music and represents the power of the event and its
consequences. It allows people to experience musically what
happened. People can remember it in a poetic way.''
</P>
<P>
   The night they heard ``Guadalupe'' had made the ``Billboard''
chart, SAVAE members were rehearsing; they celebrated with
champagne and then got on with business. They're preparing for
upcoming shows and arranging material for their next CD, expected
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to explore `Cantares'' deeper,'' Moroney said.
``The idea is to show what the Aztec civilization was and what the
Spanish civilization was through music and they fused what that
music became.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of interest, and it's great, but I don't
think we'll be giving up our day jobs anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
