<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2559 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-TEX     03-24 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SXSW HIT HIGH NOTES _ AND SOME LOW ONES, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
and MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin's South by Southwest music festival, which concluded
Sunday, is an enormous undertaking. That's why people go: to be
immersed in music, swept along by the momentum of having so many
choices in what to see and where to go.
</P>
<P>
   There's more than any one person can catch, no matter how hard
you try. Here, two music writers pick the fest's highlights _ and
its lowlights:
</P>
<P>
   DAVE FERMAN'S GOOD STUFF:
</P>
<P>
   _ Many performers coming to Austin with a lot of buzz delivered
the goods. Among them were Mercury Rev, Beth Orton and Chuck E.
Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   _ New-to-me acts, including California band Grandaddy, North
Carolina power/roots-pop quintet The Pinetops and Chicago
singer/songwriter Chris Mills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Under the Stars, a new venue behind the Under the Stars
vintage clothing store. Bands (such as Wayne ``The Train'' Hancock
and Teddy Morgan) play under the trees, illuminated only by tiki
torches, a street lamp and candles.
</P>
<P>
   _ More international and label-showcase nights than ever. It's
nice to have a number of bands from a given country (Japan, Finland
and Ireland were three this year) or on a given label, such as V2
or Jacknife, all on the same bill.
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLM MAYHEW'S GOOD STUFF:
</P>
<P>
   _ Like finding a great CD in a cut-out bin, you can stumble on
some wonderful music during SXSW simply by taking a chance on a
band you've never heard of. My great discovery was Pop Unknown, an
Austin quartet that played simple, loud, guitar-fueled pop songs.
No DJ turntables. No elements of country. No maracas. Just
straightforward rock, a real rarity these days.
</P>
<P>
   _ South by Southwest always offers free outdoor music, and this
year's bills were some of the strongest yet: On Friday, Austin
pop-rock trio Fastball performed, followed by eclectic tunesmith
Joe Ely. Saturday was equally strong, with Austin alt-country
rebels the Gourds and indie-rockers Spoon and headliners Guided by
Voices. The crowds were laid-back, the weather was nice and the
bands smoked.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free beer. They were even giving it away at a record store.
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm dangerously obsessed with the latest disc by Idaho
indie-rock group Built to Spill, ``Keep It Like a Secret,'' and I'm
relieved to say they were terrific live. The music is carved out of
sweet melodies interjected with jagged, off-kilter time changes,
but they added another layer via a lot of mesmerizing improv. The
hourlong wait outside was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sets by locals Go Metric USA, Slobberbone and the Old 97's
were wonderful in their unique ways. Sometimes I say there's
nothing going on around here, but these three bands made me happy
that, no matter how hard I've tried, I haven't left North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   DAVE FERMAN'S BAD STUFF:
</P>
<P>
   _ Not enough urban music. At all. SXSW is based around white
rock 'n' roll bands, but there has to be a way to work more hip-hop
into the mix, given the genre's huge influence on pop music in
general. And there's hardly any gospel.
</P>
<P>
   _ I heard Houndog (the new spinoff group led by Los Lobos' David
Hidalgo) and realized that neither Hidalgo nor Cesar Rosas alone is
as good as they are together.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Austin Music Awards need to be streamlined. There was far
too much dead time as bands set up. And the sound was both muddy
and too soft.
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLM MAYHEW'S BAD STUFF:
</P>
<P>
   _ For some reason, a lot of the South by Southwest clubs make
you stand outside for A VERY LONG TIME. And usually, for no good
reason. Example: We waited an hour to get in to see Lo Fidelity All
Stars Thursday at La Zona Rosa, and once we finally did get in, the
place was half-full. Think they do that stuff to paint the illusion
that you are at the hip show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bands that are hyped the most tend to disappoint the most.
Last year, the big deal was A3. Anything happen with them? Nope.
This year, the aforementioned Lo Fidelity All Stars were the big
about-to-burn-bright stars. Next year, they, too, will just be a
faded, circled name in '99's SXSW guide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Something I don't understand: Why, year after year, people
without badges throw fits when they can't get into SXSW shows. When
he couldn't get into Built to Spill's show at Babe's, some
badgeless hothead had to be chased off by the cops. SXSW is NOT for
the casual music fan; it's for the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ever heard the name Robbie Williams? If not, you probably
will, whether you like it or not. Williams is the latest heartthrob
import from the United Kingdom. In his homeland, the onetime member
of teeny-bop pop act Take That is about as popular as the Spice
Girls. He made his U.S. debut (well, as far as we know, it was his
U.S. debut) Friday at an invite-only show at Club DeVille. After
the show, this was overheard: ``Reminded me of the guy from Right
Said Fred.'' Consider yourself warned.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman and Malcolm Mayhew are pop music critics for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
