<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE25-COX     03-24 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stock your pantry with a little help from the Web
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What with Y2K hysteria and a bit of millennium madness
now seeping into the collective consciousness, even the most
level-headed folks may be getting a touch of the Chicken Little
syndrome and beginning to think about stocking up on food . . .
just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Companies dealing in survival food are reporting that business
is booming. Many people are apparently buying up huge quantities of
all sorts of Space Age and dehydrated foods to have on hand for
who-knows-what.
</P>
<P>
   However, good cooks from every millennium have always known that
a well-stocked pantry provides the security of knowing you will be
prepared for anything _ well, maybe not runaway comets heading
straight for the Earth, but unexpected guests, bad weather, a flat
tire, anything that could keep you from getting to the store.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few decades ago, a well-stocked pantry meant having a
good supply of flour, sugar, lard, some rice, beans and maybe some
canned tomatoes and other canned goods.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is an unprecedented variety of foods _ from meat,
fish and vegetable entrees to desserts and condiments _ that have a
long shelf life. There is nothing necessarily second rate about a
meal put together primarily from the pantry shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing just what you have on your pantry shelves can also take
a lot of the confusion and stress out of daily meal planning as it
eliminates ``the full refrigerator but nothing to eat syndrome.''
It also cuts down on walking down supermarket aisles in a daze
wondering what to buy. Keeping up with the basics tends to let
everything else fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   The effort needed to learn just what a well-stocked pantry
entails and keeping one inventoried is well worth the time. For
this the Internet is a gold mine of information. As with every
organizational effort, the first thing to do is make a list. On
this page are a few very good sites that list certain foods you
should consider for permanent status on your pantry shelves.
</P>
<P>
   By checking out these sites and others, you will find that
cooking from your pantry does not limit you to beef jerky and Tang;
rather, with the variety of nonperishable foods available today,
the sky is the limit.
</P>
<P>
   LISTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At Cooking Basics at http://www.ivillage.com/content
</P>
<P>
   /1,1625,378,00.html you will find an extensive list of basic
staples from almond extract to pudding mixes to Worcestershire
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.reluctantgourmet.com/pantry.htm goes well beyond
basics with items like anchovies, artichokes, bread crumbs,
mushrooms and clam juice. And there's a suggestion that if the
world ends, Marsala, Madeira and sherry are vital to life.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stocking a Low-Fat, Quick Meal Pantry at http://www.womenswire
</P>
<P>
   .com/livinglarge/grub/pantry.html lists ``everything you need to
stock a healthy, quick-meal kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See http://www.tiac.net/users/irad9/pantry.html for a
straightforward list.
</P>
<P>
   ARTICLES
</P>
<P>
   Beyond lists of what to put on pantry shelves, there are other
things you need to know about the science of keeping a stocked
pantry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.seasoned.com/issues/199802/c.ca.p1.html takes you
step by step in the process.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Your nonperishable storeroom can be the key to time saving,
money saving, and in time of emergency, even life-saving,'' begins
an informative article at
http://www.usfoodservice.com/health/storing/index.html. The site
also contains a brief list.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At
http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/012998/0129Raid
</P>
<P>
   .html you will find a very helpful and humorous article with
tips on keeping up your pantry inventory. There is also a basic
list of items and some good recipes.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   Most of the sites have recipes too, but the following are loaded
with some wonderful pantry-based recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.ibgm.com/stinson/stin-rec.htm takes the lowly
sardine and puts it to some imaginative and tasty uses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.canoe.com/CNEWSLifeArchive/jul21dollar.html does
the same for other types of canned fish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An Easter feast can be made from the recipes at
http://www.cancentral
</P>
<P>
   .com/cannedfood/pantry.cfm, which concentrates on canned food.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Find some good recipes and a good article at
http://www.sunnews.com
</P>
<P>
   /food/food1999/food012199.htm.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Peas Extraordinaire
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time:
30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1can (11 ounces) condensed cheddar cheese soup,
</P>
<P>
   undiluted
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup sherry
</P>
<P>
   1can (15 ounces) very young, small early peas, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup real bacon bits
</P>
<P>
   1can (8 ounces) sliced water chestnuts, drained and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup minced green onion
</P>
<P>
   1cup herb-seasoned stuffing mix
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons butter or margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Spray shallow 1 1/2-quart casserole or
8-inch square pan with cooking spray. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, stir soup until smooth; stir in sherry. Add
peas, bacon bits and water chestnuts. Spoon into prepared dish.
Sprinkle the green onions evenly over the top.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine stuffing and butter; mix well. Sprinkle over
green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Bake, uncovered, for 30 to 35 minutes or until thoroughly
heated.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 244 calories, 9 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 23 grams carbohydrates, 22
milligrams cholesterol, 855 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Ham With Apricot Glaze
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   5-pound, fully cooked canned ham, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   2cans (16 ounces each) apricot halves in light syrup
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   Fresh chicory or other curly greens for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Score the top of the ham into
diamonds. Drain the apricots, reserving 1/2 cup of the syrup. Stir
the mustard and ground cloves into the reserved syrup. Brush the
top of the ham with some of the syrup and stud the diamonds with
the whole cloves. Place ham in a baking pan and bake, brushing once
or twice with the glaze, for 50 to 60 minutes, until golden and
heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Serve on a bed of greens garnished with the apricots.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 273 calories, 30 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 10 grams carbohydrates, 58
milligrams cholesterol,000000 1,529 milligrams sodium, 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
