<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-EASTERTART25-COX     03-24 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EASTERTART25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pastry holds delectable ways to welcome warm weather
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine a lush banquet table set for a 10-course
Renaissance feast in the cavernous hall of a turreted Italian
castle. The centerpieces are tall-sided pies with fancy crusts
gilded with egg yolk and cradling elaborate and savory ingredients,
like pork and pigeon, cinnamon and saffron.
</P>
<P>
   Travel ahead a few centuries to the Italian countryside, where a
peasant carefully rolls out two thin crusts to encase the first
green leaves of spring, just as she will do with the last greens
before winter.
</P>
<P>
   And there, on the streets of Reggio today, are shoppers eating a
favorite street food, erbazzone, which is pastry wrapped around
spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture yourself savoring a simple mushroom pie for your
first meal on the screened porch this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Or imagine the surprising spectacle of a torta rustica _ a tall
dome of pastry with colorful layers of spinach, ham, red peppers
and cheese _ at the center of the Easter brunch table.
</P>
<P>
   Savory tarts are a supreme way to celebrate spring. And tarts _
or tortas _ are so versatile, you can tinker with most recipes to
include your favorite vegetables, cheeses and meats. Sliced thin
and small, they work well as appetizers or side dishes. Make
heartier cuts and pair with a salad for a main meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tortas began on the tables of the affluent back in the
Renaissance. Then, only the rich could afford white flour, and it
was the rich who were interested in the appearance of things,''
says Lynn Rossetto Kasper, author of an award-winning Italian
cookbook, ``The Splendid Table'' (Morrow, $35), and host of a radio
show of the same name. ``They loved to enclose all kinds of
ingredients in these fancy crusts and line their banquet tables
with these tall pies.''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Kasper writes that many of the tortas were
``designed to be show-stoppers: When their lids were lifted, flocks
of live birds flew out. ''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the peasants who often farmed the ingredients for the
landowners could keep only meager amounts of eggs and flour. So
they would use a dab of lard and roll out thin crusts to use a
minimum of flour. But they could wrap the pastry around a bounty of
greens and vegetables from their own gardens, Kasper's research
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The technique developed across the country and through the ages.
Those in the north would use more cheese, fine hams and pastas;
those in the south relied more on greens and other vegetables.
Special ingredients might be used at holidays. A torta pasqualina,
popular in Liguria, was often served at Easter. It was made with 33
sheets of paper-thin pastry _ representing the 33 years of Christ's
life _ and filled with chard, artichokes, ricotta and hard-boiled
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Inside we offer directions for building a simpler but colorful
torta rustica, a project that takes a couple of hours but will be
sure to make an impression. We also offer a simple cheese torta
using puff pastry and gorgonzola cheese that takes only a few
minutes. And there's a mushroom tart that's reminiscent of a hearty
quiche and tortas that use potatoes and polenta as a foundation,
rather than a flour crust.
</P>
<P>
   Try one for a simple family meal or as a noble addition to a
feast. Or, like the folks in Puglia, try them all and serve them in
small bites _ sort of as torta tapas. No matter how or why you
serve a torta, you're sure to find they are a lovely way to say
goodbye to the casseroles and carryout of winter and say hello to
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
