<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-EASTERTART-RECIP     03-24 2681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EASTERTART-RECIPE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seasonal ingredients fare beautifully in make-ahead pies
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I first set out to make a torta rustica, I couldn't even
envision it. It just sounded like it would taste good. But I
followed the steps in the recipe below, and wow! That's what I
heard time and time again the first time I served it up to friends.
Since then, I've made it numerous times for special occasions _
it's a favorite at bridal shower buffets.
</P>
<P>
   So I set out to try other tortas, many from a lovely little
cookbook called ``Cucina Fresca,'' written by Italian food
aficionados Viana La Place and Evan Kleiman (HarperCollins, 1987).
The whole premise of the book is food that can be served at room
temperature. That's what makes tortas so ideal for spring and
summer. You can bake many of them early in the morning and then
never have to turn the oven on again the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   From the elaborate torta rustica to simpler fare, we offer a
number of savory tarts for spring below. Pastry crusts, mashed
potatoes and polenta serve as the foundation for such ingredients
as spinach, leeks, salami and mushrooms. Once you've tried a few,
feel free to substitute your favorite seasonal ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Torta Di Polenta
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 45 minutes or longer Cooking time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Polenta is so wonderful because you can dress it up or dress it
down. Here it's combined with savory ingredients like leeks, red
onions and smoky cheese and molded in a round shape. This is ideal
for entertaining because it can be prepared hours ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup leeks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 quart vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce smoked Gouda cheese, in 1/4 inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt, if needed
</P>
<P>
   Tomato sauce (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet, heat olive oil and add garlic, leeks and
red onion, cooking until they are golden, about 7 minutes. In a
large saucepan, heat the broth with the butter. Slowly whisk in the
cornmeal and cook over medium heat, stirring constantly with a
wooden spoon, for about 15 to 20 minutes, or until it is very
thick.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the polenta from the heat and stir in the cooked onions
and the goat cheese, then the diced Gouda and grated Parmesan.
Taste and add salt only if needed. Pour the hot polenta into a
buttered deep-dish pie pan or round casserole and smooth the top.
Cover and chill for 45 minutes or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Slide a knife around the edges of
the polenta to loosen it, then invert it onto a buttered baking
sheet. Bake for 12 to 15 minutes. It should be hot through and just
barely crisping on the outside. Cut the torta into wedges and serve
with your favorite tomato sauce, if desired. _ From: ``The New
Vegetarian Epicure'' by Anna Thomas (Knopf, 1996)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 152 calories, 5 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 47), 14 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 128 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Torta Rustica (right)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 50 minutes Cooking time: 40
minutes
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of elaborate torta rustica recipes to
choose from, but I've always found this one to be a winner. Even
folks with dough phobia will find this easy. Because of the eggs,
it's more like working with a soft cookie dough. And it's fun to
layer the ingredients. You can use your imagination. If you like
the idea of adding some whole boiled eggs for Easter, simply do so.
Whatever you choose, this dome pastry will surely impress.
</P>
<P>
   6 packages (10 ounces each) frozen chopped spinach
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 large red bell peppers or a 1-pound can good-quality peeled
red peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe Soft Tart Dough
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Italian fontina, rind removed, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Black Forest ham, sliced 1/8 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Cook spinach according to package directions. Drain in a
colander and rinse under cold water to cool. Drain the spinach and,
with your hands, squeeze out excess moisture so that it is almost
dry. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the butter and oil in a small skillet. Add onion and cook
until it becomes translucent and begins to color. In a large bowl,
mix spinach, sauteed onion, 4 eggs, Parmesan, bread crumbs, salt
and pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   To roast and peel the peppers, place them over a gas burner or
under a broiler and turn with tongs until they are blackened all
over. Place in plastic bag, close the top and let them sweat 10
minutes. Remove from the bag and rinse the skins off under cold
running water. Dry on paper towels. Carefully remove the stems,
open the pepper, and discard the seeds and white ribs. Cut the
peppers to lie flat in one piece. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. To assemble the tart, roll out
two-thirds of the Soft Tart Dough on parchment, wax paper, foil or
plastic wrap into a 14-inch circle. Line a medium mixing bowl with
plastic wrap. Invert the 14-inch circle of dough into the bowl.
Peel off the paper or plastic wrap that was on the dough and pat
the dough against the sides of the bowl. Now begin to layer the
ingredients. First, place a thin layer of spinach mixture, then a
layer of red pepper, fontina and ham. Continue layering in a
pattern you like, but finish with a layer of spinach at least 1/2
inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the remaining dough into a circle large enough to cover
the filling. Invert the dough onto the tart filling and peel off
the paper or plastic wrap. Trim the edges of the circle (which will
become the bottom crust). In a small bowl, whisk remaining egg with
milk. Brush the edge of the circle with the egg wash and fold over
the extra dough from the larger circle (which will be the top of
the tart). Make sure the edges are well-sealed. Carefully invert
the tart onto a baking sheet and remove the bowl. Peel off the
plastic wrap that lined the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If you desire a sheen on the crust, brush it with egg wash
before placing it in the oven and once or twice during baking. Bake
about 40 minutes or until the crust is a deep golden brown. Serve
at room temperature, cut into pie-shaped wedges. _ From ``Cucina
Fresca'' by Viana La Place and Evan Kleiman (HarperCollins, 1987)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 407 calories, 19 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 30 grams carbohydrates, 182
milligrams cholesterol, 693 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   PASTRY
</P>
<P>
   Soft Tart Dough
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for a 14-inch tart
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Chilling time: 1 hour to 3 days
</P>
<P>
   4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 sticks (8 ounces) cold unsalted butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup milk, approximately
</P>
<P>
   To make by hand: In a large mixing bowl, combine flour and salt.
Make a well in the center and add butter, eggs and yolks. Lightly
blend butter mixture with fingertips. With a knife or pastry
blender, cut the dry ingredients into the wet ingredients until the
dough is crumbly. Gradually add milk, tossing with a fork, until
the dough comes together. The dough will be soft. Gather into a
ball. Wrap the dough in plastic wrap and refrigerate at least 1
hour or up to 2 or 3 days. When ready to roll the dough, place it
on parchment, wax paper, foil or plastic wrap to facilitate
handling.
</P>
<P>
   To make in food processor: Combine flour, salt and butter in a
food processor fitted with a metal blade. Process with short pulses
until mixture is crumbly. Add eggs and yolks with short pulses; do
not overmix. Add milk gradually with short pulses until dough
begins to clump. Remove dough and proceed as above.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 228 calories, 4 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 22 grams carbohydrates, 85
milligrams cholesterol, 161 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Cheese Tart
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is so incredibly easy and delicious, it will fast become a
regular on your party table. Look in the freezer case for the puff
pastry, which is usually sold in two large sheets equalling
slightly more than 1 pound. I like to keep a box in my freezer at
all times.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound puff pastry dough
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sweet gorgonzola cheese, trimmed of rind
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten with 1 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Divide puff pastry in half. (If
your 1-pound box of pastry already has two large sheets, eliminate
this step.) Roll out each piece on a lightly floured board into
about a 10-inch rectangle. Refrigerate until ready to use. In a
small bowl, mix the gorgonzola, goat cheese and egg yolk with a
fork. Add the pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dough from the refrigerator. Leaving an inch border
on all sides, spread the cheese mixture evenly with a rubber
spatula over one square of dough. Brush the border with the egg
wash. Place the second pastry square over the first. Crimp edges of
the tart together with a fork. Brush tart with the egg wash. Bake
on a baking sheet for about 15 minutes or until the tart is puffed
and golden brown. Serve at room temperature. _ From: ``Cucina
Fresca''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 333 calories, 12 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 61), 20 grams carbohydrates, 74
milligrams cholesterol, 628 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Gratto Di Patate (Potato Torta)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 1 hour, 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here, mashed potatoes take on a whole new life. Studded with
cheese and salami and layered with tomatoes, this unusual
presentation is a filling main course.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned Italian tomatoes with juice, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 large all-purpose potatoes, boiled and peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped salami
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup diced smoked provolone or scamorza, skin removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Saute the onion in 3 tablespoons
olive oil in a skillet over low heat until golden, about 3 to 4
minutes. Add the tomatoes, salt and pepper. Cook over medium heat
until the tomato sauce is thick and dry. Put potatoes through a
ricer or mash in a bowl with a fork until smooth. Combine the
potatoes with the eggs, salami, mozzarella, smoked provolone,
Parmesan and parsley. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter a 9-by-2 1/2-inch springform pan. Coat heavily
with bread crumbs, reserving some for the top. Spread 1/3 of the
potato mixture evenly in the bottom of the pan. Spread half the
tomato sauce over the potatoes. Spread another third of the potato
mixture evenly over the tomato sauce. Repeat with the remaining
tomato sauce and the potato mixture. Smooth the top. Sprinkle with
the remaining bread crumbs. Drizzle with the remaining 3
tablespoons olive oil. Place on a baking sheet. Bake for 1 to 1 1/4
hours or until the top is crusty and brown. Let cool completely at
room temperature. Refrigerate for several hours or overnight to
make slicing easier. _ From ``Cucina Fresca''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 474 calories, 17 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 41 grams carbohydrates, 124
milligrams cholesterol, 675 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mushroom Tart
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 1 hour Cooking time: 45
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Any type of mushroom will work with this recipe, and if you have
access to fresh wild ones, by all means substitute 1/2 pound for
the 1 ounce dried. This makes a quichelike tart that's hard to
refuse.
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried porcini or shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 unbaked 10-inch Pasta Frolla tart shell (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh white or brown mushrooms, stemmed and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh thyme or 1/2 teaspoon dried thyme leaves,
crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound dandelion greens or arugula, washed, dried and
coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Madeira or port
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces prosciutto, julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Gruyere cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   Place the dried mushrooms in a bowl and cover with very warm
water. Set aside for at least 30 minutes or until the mushrooms
soften. Line a 10-by-2-inch removable-bottom round tart pan with
the pastry and chill for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Heat 2 tablespoons of the butter
and 2 tablespoons of the oil together in a medium skillet. Add the
sliced fresh mushrooms, salt and pepper. Saute over moderate heat
just until the mushrooms begin to wilt; do not overcook. Remove
from the heat and turn into a strainer to drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon each of the butter and olive oil in a small
skillet. Add the minced garlic and thyme. Stir over low heat until
you smell the herb. Add the dandelion greens or arugula. Saute over
moderate heat just until the greens wilt. Turn into a clean
strainer to drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the dried mushrooms. Check the mushrooms to be sure they
are free of sand. Dry them. Heat 1 tablespoon each of the butter
and oil in a small skillet. Add the dried mushrooms and saute
gently. Add the Madeira or port and cook until the wine evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the tart, scatter the bread crumbs over the bottom
of the pastry shell. Add the greens, both types of mushrooms, the
prosciutto and the Gruyere. Lightly beat together the eggs with
half-and-half in a bowl. Pour over the other ingredients in the
shell. Bake the tart in the middle of the oven for about 45
minutes, or until a knife inserted in the center comes out clean.
The tart will puff slightly. Cool at least 10 minutes before
removing from tart pan. Serve at room temperature, cut into
pie-shaped wedges. _ From ``Cucina Fresca''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 517 calories, 13 grams protein, 39 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 68), 31 grams carbohydrates, 213
milligrams cholesterol, 256 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   PASTRY
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Frolla (Tart Shell Dough)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 sticks cold, unsalted butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons ice water
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour and salt in a medium mixing bowl. Add the
butter pieces. Rapidly cut the butter into the flour with your
fingertips or two knives, until the mixture resembles coarse meal.
Gradually add the water and mix the dough with a fork until it
gathers together. Shape the dough into a ball, wrap in plastic wrap
and refrigerate at least one hour before using.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to make a tart, remove the dough from the
refrigerator, unwrap it and place on a lightly floured board. Hit
the dough a few times with a rolling pin to soften it, and then
roll out into a circle to a thickness of 1/8 to 1/4 inch. Gently
lift the dough up on the rolling pin and ease into the tart pan.
You may want to allow the dough to rest in the pan for 30 minutes
before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 267 calories, 3 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 63), 22 grams carbohydrates, 49
milligrams cholesterol, 62 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
