<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kahlua cake request sends fans to files
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the recipes continue to pour in, Holly Matheson
of Smyrna (Ga.) was among the first to e-mail a Kahlua Chocolate
Cake recipe in response to Penny Wahl's plea for ``the best cake
you ever had.'' Matheson says it is one of several published in a
booklet from Kahlua years ago and she agrees, ``It really is
fabulous.'' A quick look at the ingredients tells you it has to be.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Kahlua Chocolate Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup strong cold coffee
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Kahlua
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 pound confectioners' sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Kahlua
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons hot coffee
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour two 9-inch cake pans. Preheat oven to 350
degrees. Beat egg whites until frothy, then beat in granulated
sugar until stiff peaks form; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, cream butter and brown sugar until fluffy. Beat
in egg yolks one at a time. In small bowl, sift flour, cocoa and
baking soda together. Add to creamed mixture alternately with
coffee and Kahlua; blend well. Fold egg-white mixture into batter.
Pour into prepared pans and bake 30 to 35 minutes, or until done.
Cool 20 minutes, invert onto wire racks and cool completely before
frosting.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: Cream butter and confectioners' sugar. Add
cocoa powder, Kahlua and coffee. Beat until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 621 calories, 7 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 28), 108 grams carbohydrates, 139
milligrams cholesterol, 325 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Susan W. Vaughn of Conyers (Ga.) is looking for a recipe for
Hot Water Corn Bread. After reading about it in a cookbook that
extolled the bread's unique texture, caused by the hot water, she
was disappointed to find that the book didn't contain the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
