</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN DEMOCRATS PRODUCE A SECOND JFK AT THEIR L.A. CONVENTION? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 28) , (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   WASHINGTON _ Now that the Democrats have
decided to hold their presidential nominating convention in Los
Angeles for the first time since 1960, it is inevitable that
comparisons will be drawn between the nominee of that year, John F.
Kennedy, and the party's prospective nominee of 2000, Al Gore.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the presidential search-and-dissect season takes off, the
question is whether Gore can rekindle the fire that burned so
brightly so long ago when the Cold War was the great threat to
America and the civil rights movement was just gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the fact that both men can be categorized as
Democrats wanting to be president, there are few similarities
between Kennedy and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The issues and atmosphere in America have changed greatly in the
four decades since Kennedy officially launched the ``New Frontier''
from the City of the Angels. But in that time, the assassinated
president has achieved a special place in the hearts of Americans
and a special meaning in terms of electoral politics.
</P>
<P>
   A recent public opinion poll listed Kennedy along with
Washington, Lincoln, and Franklin D. Roosevelt as one of the
republic's greatest presidents. So much for the public's historical
perspicacity.
</P>
<P>
   In his short time in the White House, Kennedy did not score many
memorable achievements, although he did launch the successful
effort to place a man on the moon and he did stand up to the Soviet
Union in the Cuban missile crisis of 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's most memorable achievement may have been that he, the
first American president born in the 20th century, inspired a
generation of young Americans, including Bill Clinton, to seek to
careers in public service. He and his wife, Jacqueline, also made
the White House a showcase for elegance and appreciation of the
arts, letters and the contributions of America's Nobel laureates.
</P>
<P>
   What often matters in politics is the aura achieved by a public
figure, and Kennedy's aura continues to glisten despite the recent
revelations about his promiscuous private life.
</P>
<P>
   It should not be surprising, therefore, that when Democrats go
back to Los Angeles, many will be hoping to anoint a nominee who
can emulate Kennedy's victory at the polls and create enthusiasm
for public service among young people. As things now stand, that
nominee probably will be Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was but 15 when Kennedy was assassinated, there are
some small links between the two men. Kennedy and Gore's father,
Albert Gore Sr., served together in the House in the 1940s and
early 1950s and were elected to the Senate on the same November day
in 1952 that Dwight Eisenhower won the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kennedy and the senior Gore, Al Gore also served in House
and Senate before being tapped by Clinton in 1992 for the vice
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's 1960 campaign centered around what he called the need
to ``get America moving again'' after eight years of the Eisenhower
administration, a slowdown in the national economy and his claim,
which later proved false, that America had fallen behind the Soviet
Union in missile development.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy, whose Catholicism was both a political asset and
liability, was no shoo-in. He won the Democratic nomination only by
defeating all prospective opponents in the primaries. Then he beat
Richard Nixon in the closest presidential election in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is nominated, instead of promising to get America moving
again, he will be forced to defend, rather than criticize, the
administration because he has been an integral part of it. No
previous vice president has enjoyed as close a relationship with
his president.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy continues to flourish and if criticism of
Clinton's policies in Kosovo, China and other foreign lands does
not become an explosive political issue, Gore may fare well. But if
the economy winds down and if Republicans can make voters believe
that Clinton has been the architect of a weak and misguided foreign
policy, he will have a tough time.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were able to capitalize on allegations that the
Democrats had mishandled overseas matters at the end of the Harry
Truman administration in the early 1950s and again in 1968 and 1972
during the tragedy of Vietnam. A further problem for Gore will be
his closeness to a president whose moral and ethical standards are
in disrepute.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the Republican nominee, Gore may
focus on the economic doldrums that persisted during his father's
presidency, while Bush may hit hard at the moral turpitude of the
Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who lacks Kennedy's charisma, has said some foolish things
of late, including his claim to have helped create the Internet.
But his basic intelligence, his grasp of modern technology, his
protection of the environment, his understanding of economic
matters and his experience in the highest reaches of government
should serve him well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
