<HEADER>
A2617 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     03-24 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU JUST THINK YOU KNOW BEANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All cooks think they can make a pot of beans. Like Poggie Ames
of Granbury, Texas, says, ``You just dump them in a pot and boil
them until they don't rattle anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy enough for Ames to say; he has three first-place awards and
two seconds to his name at the annual General Granbury's Birthday
Celebration and Bean, Rib and Chili Cook-Off.
</P>
<P>
   The event is this weekend on the town square from 9 a.m. to 5
p.m. Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of cooks will fire up their stoves for ribs and beans
Saturday. Sunday is for the chili cook-off, a new event this year.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of judges will choose the official winners, but this
festival also allows the public to judge. Visitors pay a dollar for
a small cup, a spoon and a ballot. They get to pick their favorites
for the ``people's choice awards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one we go for,'' Ames said. ``We want our beans
cooked for the people; we really don't care much about the other
judges.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes a difference, because the judges are looking for the
best beans only. They don't want to see any meat in the beans; they
just want beans and seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   But Ames said that's not the way he was taught to cook beans.
That's not the way his mother fixed them, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was the only woman I ever knew who could cook just
enough for the five of us, have 10 others show up, and there ended
up being plenty for everyone with a little left over,'' he said.
``I've never been able to figure out how she did that. I sure
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen Ames would always watch her boys _ Poggie, Dan and Fred _
when they cooked at the bean cook-off. She made sure they didn't
overseason the beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put too much in,'' Ames said of the seasonings. ``And
you can't take it back. Once you season them, that's the way it's
going to be. Once you get 40 pounds of beans boiling, you can't
just call it off.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the seasoning that determines how good the beans are.
There is no other really deep, dark secret, Ames said. You just add
seasoning at different times. He said he uses crushed tomatoes,
cilantro, sauteed onions, salt and a little bit of brisket. The
salt goes in last, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also has soaked the beans overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of meat you use depends on what you're serving with
the beans,'' Ames said. ``If you are going to serve them with
chicken, then you put chicken in the beans. I always serve mine
with brisket, so I put brisket in the beans.''
</P>
<P>
   When cooking 40 pounds of beans, he added, he'll toss in about a
dozen jalapenos.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people will turn up the fire and boil their beans
until they're done,'' Ames said. ``I really don't do that. I'll
bring them up to a good rolling boil and then I'll turn the fire
off. I'll let them sit there until I can put my hand on the side of
the pot without burning it. The pot will still be hot, maybe 120 or
130 degrees, but the beans won't be boiling. Then, I'll add the
sauteed onions and diced tomatoes and bring the beans back to a
boil for about 10 or 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ames said he cooks the onions ahead of time in ``just enough
grease to make them slide around.'' He cooks them until they are
translucent.
</P>
<P>
   After the beans have returned to a boil, he again turns off the
fire and begins to stir in the diced brisket. It's back to a boil
again, then off again.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he adds the chopped cilantro. ``I kind of let it set
there on top,'' Ames said. ``The oil comes out of the cilantro and
gives it a flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds salt, stirs the pot, and pronounces them ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cook the beans like I like them,'' he said. ``We go for the
people's choice awards and showmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Ames and his two brothers will join Hood County Sheriff Allen
Harden this year in fixing what they call ``Chain Gang Beans.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff and his chief deputy, and an investigator, will be
dressed in their western lawmen outfits, with the Ameses dressed in
prison uniforms and shackled to a ball and chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a good time,'' Ames said. ``We've lived in Granbury
all our lives, and we wouldn't miss this event. That little square
will be jam-packed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
