<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENNON-ARTWORK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT SKETCHES LENNON'S ARTISTIC SELF-PORTRAIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEN HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Soon it will be 20 years since John Lennon was
murdered outside his home in New York City. Yoko Ono, who was with
him the night five shots rang out, says, ``I don't often cry about
it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ono, 66, is a wealthy businesswoman. She still records and
performs occasionally. She is an artist. Her son, Sean, is putting
out his own records now. Ono has moved on.
</P>
<P>
   But every so often, something casts her back to life with
Lennon. Such as one little drawing he did in 1969, just a scribble
that took only a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of those days _ it's kind of a bittersweet
feeling,'' Ono says in a telephone interview. ``It's John and I
holding each other, almost like a yin-and-yang drawing. It's a
beautiful thing that he did. This was in England, and we were so
much in love. It just chokes me up in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Beatles and ``She Loves You,'' long hair, peace and
love and worldwide fame as a rock 'n' roller, John Lennon was a
young man with a sketch pad. He drew just as fast and furiously as
he played his guitar, with the same passion and humor, and often
with the same raunchiness.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, he was talented enough to win admission to the
Liverpool College of Art. Success with the Beatles ended his school
days, but he never stopped drawing. Even after the birth of his son
Sean, when he put down his guitar for five years of stay-at-home
fatherhood, he continued doodling his life on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The largest collection of Lennon's artwork ever exhibited will
be on display this weekend at the Renaissance Houston Hotel. ``In
My Life: The Artwork of John Lennon'' will feature more than 100
drawings, including the never-before-shown pieces used as cover art
on the ``John Lennon Anthology''recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings are a self-portrait, 1969-1980. He depicts the
major events in his life, from his courtship of Ono and their
wedding through his immigration battle to live in the United States
to domestic bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Limited-edition reprints of the drawings, signed by Ono, will be
for sale during the exhibit. While most will sell for about $1,000,
they'll range in price from $140 to $24,000 (for an original
lithograph).
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, reprints of handwritten lyrics will be for
sale; prices will range from $125 to $1,000. The songs include
Beatles classics such as ``Lucy in the Sky With Diamonds,''
``Revolution,'' ``Nowhere Man and Day Tripper,'' plus solo hits
such as ``Woman,'' ``Beautiful Boy'' and ``Watching the Wheels Go
Round.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was cranking them out all the time,'' Ono says. ``He would
send postcards or letters, and there'd be a little drawing on them.
He'd finish a drawing and just say to people, `You want this?' He
was very generous. He could be generous because he was so talented.
He was just a talented guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of Lennon's life after the Beatles, there were two
constants at his side: Ono and a sketch pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at these drawings, and I remember when he did them. I
was usually around when he was drawing. Usually I was around all
the time. We were together a lot. It reminds me of those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd draw wherever we were. Sadly, he'd just throw a lot of it
away. The drawing of John and I holding each other, he initially
thought, `Oh, it's not good enough.' He was going to throw it away,
but I saved it. A couple of days later he said, `It's not bad.' Now
we use that drawing for our logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art was not a formal thing with John. He wasn't that kind of
artist. He was an inspired artist. He'd draw anywhere _ on a plane,
in a conference with lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ono remembers one emotionally agonizing encounter with lawyers
that she and Lennon endured in 1971 at the Family Law Center in
Houston. They were trying to gain custody of Kyoko, Ono's daughter
from a previous marriage. They had heard that Kyoko was living in
Houston with Ono's ex-husband, filmmaker Anthony Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for Kyoko. We knew she was in Houston. But
when we got there, they just left town,'' Ono says. Mother and
daughter weren't reunited until 1997, when Kyoko called Ono.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very nice feeling about Houston except that it wasn't
a very nice occasion,'' Ono says. ``Despite that, I thought, `Hmm,
hip town.'''
</P>
<P>
   To announce the arrival of the Lennon art exhibit, two
tractor-trailers will pull up at the Houston Food Bank and unload
60,000 pounds of food, a gift from Ono.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that whenever we do a show of John's work, we
make sure to do something for a local charity . That's what it's
about,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
