<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER DRAFTS DIVORCE BOOK FOR TEXANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Texas native Jerry Hall were able to divorce Mick Jagger in
her home state instead of Great Britain, her claim for $50 million
might not seem that exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, any divorce settlement would be dictated by
what the couple accumulated during their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   So if the famous couple amassed $100 million during their
relationship, her request would be a ``little low'' under Texas
standards, Dallas divorce attorney Ike Vanden Eykel says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down here, if we're representing a wife and all we get is 50
percent, we consider that a loss,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain: A high-profile divorce in the Lone Star
State is likely to have a ``Gunfight at the O.K. Corral'' quality
to it, says Vanden Eykel, author of the new ``Successful Lone Star
Divorce: How to Cope With a Family Breakup in Texas'' (PSG Books,
$16.95).
</P>
<P>
   Divorce is different in Texas than it would be almost anywhere
else on Earth, for a number of reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas is one of only nine states that recognize community
property. Under state law, a non-wage-earning spouse has just as
much right as a wage-earning spouse to property accumulated during
the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   _ For all practical purposes, alimony is nonexistent, Vanden
Eykel says. The Texas Legislature passed a limited law in 1995 that
allows maximum payments of $2,500 a month for three years to an
ex-spouse who was married at least 10 years and has no means of
support.
</P>
<P>
   _ Either party can ask for a jury trial. In a divorce case, a
jury can determine community property and custody issues and even
decide the value of a disputed business. Texas is the only state
where a jury can determine custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got 12 people (deciding important divorce issues), and
that makes it somewhat of a gunfighter's type of justice still in
this state,'' says Vanden Eykel, whose clients have included Texas
Rangers baseball player Juan Gonzalez and the ex-wives of
evangelist Robert Tilton and millionaire Rex Cauble.
</P>
<P>
   Things often get nasty if there's a fight over custody or if one
party feels harmed by a spouse's extramarital affair and embarks on
a personal vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things so easily get out of hand. You have to realize
the system rewards `nuclear war.' It's like going into an oil
refinery with a blowtorch. If you set it off, there is going to be
a fire,'' Vanden Eykel says.
</P>
<P>
   He offers these suggestions for helping to maintain civility
during a divorce case:
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider your options.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously ask yourself: Is the marriage salvageable? If there's
a chance, try counseling, therapy or a trial separation to work out
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have ended it, there's nothing left to save. If you
try to save it, you might just succeed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do your homework.
</P>
<P>
   Educate yourself on the legal system and what a divorce will
cost you emotionally and financially. Know both your financial
situation and your spouse's, including the value of retirement
funds and the amount of outstanding or potential debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in without knowing that, and they end up learning
about the system halfway into it, and by then they can't get out of
it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Interview several lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Ask friends who have been in similar situations for referrals.
Interview at least two lawyers before deciding to hire someone.
Compare what each says, and gauge how comfortable you feel that
your interests will be protected.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the same questions of each lawyer, and don't tell one what
the other said. Ask about the types of cases they have handled,
their thoughts about mediation, which mediators they use (if they
can't name one, they probably don't use mediation often), and
specific questions on how they would handle your situation.
</P>
<P>
   Vanden Eykel, who charges $450 an hour, agrees that not everyone
needs a high-priced divorce attorney. He recommends hiring ``the
most lawyer you can afford'' for your situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can destroy an anthill with a missile, but a shovel will
do just fine,'' he says. ``Not every case needs to be attached to a
team. You may not require someone at the top of the fee range.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay involved.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've hired a lawyer, be a part of the process. Don't
abdicate the case to your attorney. Let him or her know what you
are thinking; otherwise, you may be left with unanswered questions
after the divorce is finalized.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shut up.
</P>
<P>
   People going through a divorce often feel a need to tell
everyone how lousy the ex-spouse is and other details of the
breakup. Such negative talk can come back to haunt you,
particularly during delicate negotiations. You may also
inadvertently give away your strategy with such loose talk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay focused on your objective.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let thoughts of vengeance or vendettas blur your focus.
Try to fashion a resolution that gets you all or much of what you
need without putting your spouse through a ``human meat grinder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep the emotions out, because it is an emotional
situation, but you can try to keep them under control and not let
them be damaging to you,'' Vanden Eykel says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite news accounts that often highlight the most acrimonious
divorces, more than 85 percent of divorce cases in the state are
resolved in mediation without going to trial, Vanden Eykel says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magic of mediation is, quite frankly, amazing,'' says the
attorney, who calls mediation the most significant development in
his 25 years of practice (followed by the invention of the
photocopier and the fax machine).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mediation has allowed for an avenue to resolve differences
without this `nuclear war.' It forces (couples) to sit down with a
trained mediator and try and settle the case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
