<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADERS-OUTFITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO CHEERLEADING OUTFITS FORCE GIRLS TO WORRY TOO MUCH ABOUT THEIR
BODIES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Marcia Ritter informed cheerleading
hopefuls and their parents that tryouts would be done in a set of
double sports bras last month instead of the traditional white
T-shirt, they didn't even blink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of questions about other things, but not one
comment about the sports bras,'' Ritter said. ``Nobody raised their
hands about it. There was not a word.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Colleyville Heritage High School varsity cheerleading
coach would learn later, there was plenty of concern among parents
that the policy would put an unhealthy emphasis on body weight, and
perhaps on girls' bustlines.
</P>
<P>
   When Ritter got wind of parents' concerns, she immediately
abandoned the idea. But the controversy is an example of what
experts see as continuing societal pressure on young women _
cheerleaders or not _ to look and act a certain way.
</P>
<P>
   This perception was further confirmed in a recent study, which
found that despite all of the publicity about eating disorders,
teens are still struggling with self-esteem and body image. A major
culprit: photos and articles in magazines such as ``Seventeen'' and
``Glamour,'' which help convince many teen girls that they are fat
and should diet.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released this month by Alison Field of Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston, interviewed 548 girls in grades five
through 10 and reported that seven in 10 girls said magazine
pictures influence their ideas of the perfect body shape. Nearly
half said they want to lose weight because of those pictures,
although only 29 percent were overweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we do a very good job of raising boys to be or do
whatever they want,'' said James T. McElroy, author of ``We've Got
Spirit: The Life and Times of America's Greatest Cheerleading
Team.'' ``But we seem to impose on girls a lot of `shoulds' ... as
opposed to allowing them to do what they feel happy and comfortable
doing.'' For instance, he said, if a girl feels comfortable wearing
a sports bra, then let her. If she doesn't, then she shouldn't be
forced to.
</P>
<P>
   One parent, Sharon O'Dell, said she doesn't have a problem with
girls wearing the sports bras, because the girls often wear more
than one. ``These are like 6 inches in diameter,'' said O'Dell,
whose 16-year-old daughter is a cheerleader at Heritage High.
``They look like halter tops. They're just form-fitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Routen, varsity cheerleading sponsor at Arlington Heights
High School in Fort Worth, has tried to steer girls away from tight
and revealing clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took over the cheerleading, I took out the category in
tryouts for appearance,'' said Routen, who requires her squad to
try out in T-shirts and walking shorts. ``I tell them it is not
their place to look sexy at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this 11 years, and I don't think there has
ever been a year when I didn't have at least one and sometimes as
many as three (cheerleaders) who were anorexic. I've seen cases so
severe, they had to do treatment or leave school.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her efforts to de-emphasize looks, Routen said that
girls still want to wear tight and revealing clothing and often
ignore her suggestions, such as lengthening their cheerleading
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   But Ritter said the switch from T-shirts to a sports bra was
simply a practical one, to avoid T-shirts flopping in the girls'
faces. She said T-shirts become untucked and can wind up leaving
the girls' bras exposed anyway. It was never her intention to make
anyone feel pressured about the switch, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tryouts are scary enough for these young girls,'' said Ritter,
who was following the sports-bra trend at the college level. ``It
was not my goal to make it any more uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Graham of Champion Cheer in Colleyville, Texas, agrees
that sports bras have their pragmatic points. She said that even at
the middle and high school levels, most girls wear them under
T-shirts, whether they are required to or not. Graham owns one of a
growing number of businesses that train girls on school
cheerleading teams and private teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are being used to determine a girl's size and
prettiness, I have a problem with that,'' said Graham, a former
Martin High School cheerleader from Arlington. ``If they're being
used for practical reasons such as preventing the T-shirt from
flying up into their faces while tumbling, that's a different
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham also said she feels that the pressure on girls to look a
certain way is usually self-imposed. Many cheerleaders strive to be
``a flyer or top person'' in stunts. Those girls are generally more
petite than those on the bottom, who must lift the smaller girls
over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smaller you are, the easier it is, so there's definitely
pressure to stay fit,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheerleaders at Arlington Heights High School agree, saying that
even though Routen always emphasizes a clean, wholesome look, some
girls concentrate on keeping their weight down.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth James, who has been a cheerleader for 11 years, most
recently at Arlington Heights, said that she has never experienced
pressure to be thin, but ``can still see it happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``We've Got Spirit,'' McElroy, an award-winning journalist
and husband of a cheerleading coach, follows a Kentucky high school
team's quest for its ninth national cheering title. Like the recent
study, he blames the body-image problem squarely on advertisements,
TV shows, clothing stores and models: ``Cheerleading is \Rmore\S
concerned with issues of grace, athleticism, and
self-esteem-building confidence in girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said that if coaches are telling girls to make judges
like them, the question of how becomes paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come across as perky, smiley and attractive,'' McElroy
said. ``And depending on how you interpret that, it may involve
supertight tops or short skirts. The sexuality issue is a tough
one, because on the one hand you don't want to make girls feel
pressured to look or act a certain way, but on the other hand you
run the risk of making girls feel bad about their sexuality, and I
think that would be too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy sees the trend for more-revealing uniforms filtering
down from the professional cheerleaders, who tend to wear nothing
but Lycra body-hugging outfits. For instance, instead of the short
pleated skirts, more teams are wearing skirts that look like strips
of fabric over a pair of shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they move, the strips open and are more revealing,'' said
McElroy. ``They might as well just be wearing underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   This trend seems to be limited, at least locally, to All-Star
teams, privately-owned teams formed strictly for competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of teams who wear the crop-top uniforms and the
fly-away skirts with the slits,'' said James, also on an All-Star
team. ``It's crazy. Most All-Star teams have those because they
look good when you twist.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is concern that sexier outfits are making their way
to the high-school level.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Claire Bloxom, another cheerleader at Arlington
Heights, said uniforms are becoming ``more and more risque'' every
year, pointing to one local cheerleading group that wears tops with
spaghetti straps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're trying to put out a sex magazine,'' she said,
``instead of lead cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
