   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ American-led NATO forces strike
Serbian military positions in the first attack on a sovereign
nation in the military alliance's 50-year history. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO (Washington) _ President Clinton, in an address to the
nation, seeks support from the American public for U.S.-led air
strikes against Yugoslav forces. Earlier, he cast the struggle with
President Slobodan Milosevic as an effort to quell ``destructive
racial, ethnic, religious and cultural'' aggression in Kosovo. Some
Republican leaders voice reservations about the air strikes. By
STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TARGETS (Washington) _ Likely targets of the NATO strike
against Yugoslavia will extend far beyond its air defense network
to navy docks and ships along the Adriatic coast as well as bases,
ammunition dumps and military supply centers across the country,
experts say. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLITICS (Washington) _ The domestic debate on NATO's
military action against Serbian forces in Kosovo highlights the
Republican split on Washington's role in international conflicts.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-PROBE (Washington) _ A House panel begins a probe into
whether the U.S. military's mandatory anthrax vaccinations are safe
and effective. Pentagon officials testify that they are, but many
service members still refuse to take them. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-MEDIA (Washington) _ Several Supreme Court justices
express doubts that police officers can lawfully take TV
photographers and other news media into homes during an arrest or
search. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Austin, Texas) _ A proposal to allow thousands
of Texas students in six urban counties to get taxpayer-funded
vouchers for private school tuition is headed for action before the
state Senate Education Committee, whose chairman is the bill's
author. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
