 (PLEASE NOTE: This budget has been transmitted three times _ into
the ``v'' advisory, ``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news
files.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., March 29 and
anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEAD MAN BECOMES FATHER &LR;  _ Last week, for the first time, sperm
taken from a dead man resulted in a human birth. Gaby Vernoff, who
gave birth in a Los Angeles hospital, did not have written consent
to take her husband's sperm after his death. This case may inspire
a law to that effect to be passed in New York state, amid concerns
that sperm may be ``stolen'' from men who had no intention of
reproducing. By Philip Cohen and Michael Day. 600 words. (slugged:
BC-REPRODUCTIVE-TECHNOLOGY-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOULD HIV PATIENTS TAKE BREAKS FROM THEIR DRUGS? &LR;  _
HIV-infected people may benefit if they take repeated ``holidays''
from their drug treatments, say some AIDS researchers who believe
that these breaks from therapy could boost a vital component of the
immune response. By Michael Day. 600 words. (slugged:
BC-HIV-TREATMENTS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERFECT SCANS EVERY TIME ... EVEN WITH SHAKY HANDS &LR;  _ A new
compact hand-held scanner produces perfect, clear images from even
the wobbliest of hands. California-based Hewlett-Packard's new
device can move across a page recording a succession of images,
which can then be sent straight to a printer without the need for a
computer to process the image. By Duncan Graham-Rowe. 600 words.
(slugged: BC-HAND-HELD-SCANNERS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLD BURN TAKES STING OUT OF BIOWEAPONS &LR;  _ Bleaches or
chemicals used to clean sensitive electronics contaminated with
biowarfare agents, often damage the equipment. Now researchers in
New Mexico have come up with a less damaging technique that burns
off surface contaminants with atomic oxygen. They hope the
technique may eventually be used to decontaminate people's skin. By
Jeff Hecht. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-BIOWEAPONS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
