</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Making good on months of threats, NATO
launched airstrikes on Yugoslavia Wednesday to punish its hard-line
leader for refusing to make peace in the southern Serbian province.
Detonations went off in Pristina, lighting the hills over the
darkened Kosovo capital. In Belgrade, witnesses reported eight
explosions, some near a military airport and at least one near a
power plant. (Early summary by wires.) By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Washington) _ Why does the United States
think bombing will make Milosevic give in? Bombs alone did not work
with Hitler, Ho Chi Minh or Saddam Hussein. Only atomic bombs at
Hiroshima and Nagasaki worked without ground troops. This issue is
behind the fear of ground troop involvement. By R. W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-PINOCHET (London) _ The Law Lords, who constitute
England's highest court, ruled on Wednesday that Gen. Augusto
Pinochet must remain in England and face possible extradition to
Spain, but they significantly narrowed the charges on which the
case will turn. By Warren Hoge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-SAFETY (Washington) _ The National Transportation Safety
Board blamed the crash of two Boeing 737's on a phenomenon that it
said it could deduce but not explain, two simultaneous failures in
a hydraulic valve in the rudder. It made what could be one of its
most far-reaching recommendations on Wednesday, that the rudder
systems on more than 3,000 such planes in service should be made
``reliably redundant.'' By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-SAMESEX-MARRIAGE (Chicago) _ For the second time in a
year, a United Methodist Church minister will face an
ecclesiastical trial, on a charge that he violated a church law
against ministers officiating at same-sex unions. In its largest
sense, the coming trial illustrates a national controversy, in both
religious and secular spheres, around the issue of same-sex unions.
Even while gay men and lesbians have filed lawsuits in states like
Hawaii and Vermont seeking legal recognition of their unions, the
federal government and a majority of states have passed laws
against recognizing the legal validity of such bonds. By Gustav
Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
