<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEMENT-BOYS-NYT &LR;      03-24 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEMENT-BOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GUYS ONLY IN THE BASEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Michael Segell is the author of ``Standup Guy: Masculinity
That Works,'' to be published in May by Villard.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL SEGELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ambiance might charitably be described as early 20th-century
American dungeon: The cobwebbed walls are made of thick slabs of
Manhattan schist set in brown mortar, which over the last century
has shed enough sand and lime to form an inch-high berm at their
base. A network of rusty pipes _ steam, gas, drain, sprinkler and
water _ crisscrosses the floor and ceiling. The air is moist and
pungent, redolent of No. 2 heating oil and steam-boiler exhaust and
shimmers in rude blue fluorescent light. This is a basement, my
basement, and I love it.
</P>
<P>
   In our five-story, five-bedroom house, this is the one place I
can truly call my own. Each of my children has his or her own
bedroom. My wife, who works at home, has her own study. Even the
washer and dryer get their own four walls with a door that closes.
By default, I get everything beneath the house's habitable spaces.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about a louche rec room with a wet bar and a
60-inch television. I'm not even talking about the kind of slightly
mildewed chamber that is hospitable enough to house a laundry or a
sewing nook. I'm referring to a nether world of sewer drains, leaky
pipes, tool-strewn work benches and smoky power plant that only a
man could covet. I'm talking about the kind of creepy, irredeemable
vault that, much as I may wish for it, could not even be converted
into a teen-ager's bedroom. Banished to this subterranean briar
patch by the local matriarchy, I secretly howl with joy.
</P>
<P>
   In a culture that has been working overtime to break down gender
barriers and eliminate old-boy clubs, the basement continues to
resist integration. And that's not likely to change anytime soon,
says Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi, the author of ``Finding Flow: The
Psychology of Engagement With Everyday Life'' (Basic Books, 1998),
the best-selling analysis of peak experience.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his research into flow, that absorbing psychological
state that athletes, musicians and surgeons refer to as ``the
zone,'' the University of Chicago psychologist outfitted 200
working men and women with electronic pagers, beeped them randomly
during the day and asked them to write down where they were and how
happy and creative they felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that the basement is the part of the home in which
men have the greatest number of positive moods, and the environment
in which women have the fewest,'' Csikszentmihalyi said.
</P>
<P>
   Where are women happiest? ``In the bathroom,'' he said. ``It's
one of the few places they don't feel hassled by children or
husbands _ a place where they don't feel obligated to do anything
but focus on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be impolitic to say it, but the affinity for what
Csikszentmihalyi calls the micro-ecology of the basement almost
certainly originates in the Y chromosome. My 16-year-old daughter
was surprised recently to learn we had one. Her younger sister has
explored the region a couple of times with her twin brother but now
refuses to venture beyond the top of the stairs, from which outpost
she often rouses me from a board-drilling fugue to request dinner
or announce a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Social constructionists would undoubtedly argue that my girls
are simply taking their cues from their mom, who refuses to honor
this sanctuary, the very foundation of our cozy Upper West Side
Manhattan familial corporation, with even an occasional visit. They
would also have a generous explanation for her apparent snub: she's
cutting me some slack,  &UR; honoring my space &LR; . Perhaps. But she also
shudders just thinking about the moist ecology of our basement and
shakes her head, mystified, when I eagerly head off down below. I
don't expect her to understand my urge to drain the boiler, arrange
my drill bits, practice my slap shot and disassemble things that
work just fine any more than I can figure out why, when the world
is too much with her, she finds peace in an hour or so of furtive
folding and sorting.
</P>
<P>
   My 9-year-old son, by contrast, follows me into the sanctum
sanctorum every chance he can get, to learn, among other things,
the fabulously destructive potential of the Sawzall. He and his
pals can often be found there after school, furiously flailing away
with hammers and saws, industriously building nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Are we just an old-fashioned family, immune to the new gender
politics that has done away with His and Hers? I don't think so.
For one thing, our corporation requires two very modern paychecks
to stay afloat. I submit, however, that my basement puttering
satisfies a vital, even if seemingly outdated and redundant,
psychological need, long important to the male ego. With my
protective hands on the pulse of the domestic compound, I can
literally take and adjust its temperature, insure its proper
hydration and hygiene and feel as if I have guaranteed the good
health of the family gene pool for another day.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not so benighted as to expect credit for my efforts, though.
In the ongoing national and local debate on who does more domestic
scut work, basement chores rarely figure into the tally. For years,
researchers have churned out studies showing that, while working
dads are performing more household chores than their fathers did,
women still do the maid's share of them _ and often after racing
home from the office themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures from the Families and Work Institute, a
Manhattan research group, show that men now put in 75 percent as
much time as women taking care of grunt work in the parlor, kitchen
and nursery _ up from 30 percent in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   But what would happen to that ratio if the obligations of the
basement were added to the usual cleaning, shopping and diapering?
I would trade having to plunge my arm shoulder-deep into a
backed-up sewer drain in search of a Furby someone has flushed down
a toilet for a hundred diaper changes any day.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe I would not. The basement is my world, and I'm
not ready to give it up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1633EST &QL; 
