<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2682 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SOUND-GAMES-NYT &LR;      03-24 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SOUND-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC OF THE SPHERES, SQUIGGLES AND SNIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember Silly Putty? An amorphous blob of industrial goo
marketed to children, its chief virtue was flexibility, and its
many uses were encyclopedically demonstrated in Saturday morning
television commercials: You can stretch Silly Putty into any shape!
It can be rolled into a ball and bounced!
</P>
<P>
   And if you flatten it over a comic book, the image transfers,
turning the featureless, gray-beige lump into a temporary storage
medium for colorful drawings. Would wonders never cease?
</P>
<P>
   So you bought the Silly Putty and did all the things you saw in
the commercial, then promptly lost interest because at the end of
the day, Silly Putty doesn't have much to say for itself. It's all
style and no substance.
</P>
<P>
   Audiorom's Shift Control does for sound what Silly Putty did for
industrial goo. The product of a London-based design collective,
Shift Control showcases a dozen ways to stretch, bounce and
manipulate sound in an environment studded with references to
computer games, techno music and club culture.
</P>
<P>
   It's insanely stylish. The program begins with an explosion of
circular schematic diagrams _ perhaps cross sections of a
cylindrical skyscraper, or tiny gears or cells _ drifting across
the screen like boulders in a classic game of Asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   Each contains a sound sample, triggered when the cells
intersect. Nudge the cursor inside one of these membranes and it
will float along inside a bubble of sound as the audio snippet
loops indefinitely. Click twice, and each diagram opens a cleverly
crafted audio interface.
</P>
<P>
   There's a mixing board where you can stretch audio samples like
melted mozzarella and stack them in layers. A paint program assigns
each color a different sound effect, so you can sweep the cursor
across the screen to ``play'' the image as a soundscape.
</P>
<P>
   Another interface positions sounds in space: dragging an icon up
or down changes the volume; dragging it left or right pans between
speakers. Like Silly Putty, these features allow you to stretch
stuff and make it stick to walls.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the rolling-into-a-ball-and-bouncing category,
there is another group of Shift Control interfaces that makes
sounds into virtual objects subject to virtual physics. If you
throw miniature schematic diagrams around, they'll trigger sound
samples whenever they bounce off the walls (a sly, winking
reference to Atari Breakout, a console game old enough to buy
alcohol).
</P>
<P>
   Another interface, shamelessly derived from the work of Toshio
Iwai, a Japanese sound artist, uses movable barriers to trigger and
redirect audio samples. Place two barriers across from each other,
set the ball bouncing between them, and voila, a simple sound loop.
</P>
<P>
   With more objects in motion and more barriers in place, the
sound scheme becomes denser and more complex. But it's still, at
heart, a game of follow the bouncing ball.
</P>
<P>
   A third cluster of sound toys bridges the gap between music and
text, converting the text keyboard into a sound keyboard, with each
row of keys corresponding to a bass line, melodic groove or ambient
wobble. It seems arbitrary at first, but most translations of music
into text are arbitrary _ the lines and dots we use to represent
music on a page, or the fact that 440 vibrations per second
translates into the letter A.
</P>
<P>
   Before typewriters, musical keyboards were the only kind. Shift
Control restores the keyboard interface to its source, with a
twist.
</P>
<P>
   Riffing on the translation of text into sound, another sound
tool spins alphabet letters into saxophone phrases that flow
smoothly into one another. Frequent letter combinations like ``re''
or ``ion'' become leitmotifs. Business memos and Read Me files
metamorphose into reasonably interesting music. Snippy e-mail from
erstwhile sweethearts also sounds snazzy (must be all the
exclamation marks).
</P>
<P>
   This is the only feature of Shift Control that stands up to
continuous play. The rest, like Silly Putty, loses its appeal when
the novelty wears off. It's visually beautiful, but an extremely
superficial experience. It's great the way a movie trailer or a
book jacket or album liner notes can be great. You're impressed,
but only once or twice, and then you want to know what's
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't anything beneath the surface here because Shift
Control isn't about content. It's about different ways to package
content. As a packaging showcase, Shift Control is a spectacular
success.
</P>
<P>
   It does everything great packaging is supposed to do: It makes
whatever is wrapped inside (in this case, unremarkable techno
music) seem hipper and more exciting that it actually is. And it
garners kudos in the design community, which awarded Shift Control
a handsome plaque at the Milia 99 Festival in Cannes. So this disk
is circulating in art departments up and down Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In six months, these packaging ideas will be used to sell blue
jeans, soft drinks and prepaid long-distance calling cards. It's a
short hop from the London Institute of Contemporary Art to the
advertising world. Follow the bouncing ball.
</P>
<P>
   (Shift Control, by Audiorom, sells for 16.99 pounds _ about $28.
It can be ordered online at www.audiorom.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
