<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GOLF-DESIGN-NYT &LR;      03-24 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOLF-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS DISSECT THE INSTANT WHEN CLUB MEETS BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (af)  
 By BRIGID BUCKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer-aided design software, a tool usually thought of in
connection with architecture and interior design, has played a
significant role in the evolution of golf equipment in the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rugge, the director of research and development for the
Taylor Made Golf Co &UR; . &LR; , based in Carlsbad, Calif., said computer
capabilities had altered the development process by allowing the
company's engineers to assess club designs through animated motion
and readouts that the computer programs provide.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Joe Hoffman, a design engineer at Taylor Made, can
fine-tune an animated club head that appears on his computer screen
by experimenting with properties the software makes visible, such
as the center of gravity, a pivotal element to a strong club
design.
 &UR;  &LR; The center of gravity is designated on screen with a small X on
the club that can be moved according to design needs. Thus,
engineers can redesign the club with different materials or in a
different shape in order to shift the center of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-aided design tool also makes it easier to
experiment with some materials, like titanium, by allowing the
engineers to see how specific metals will react to collisions.
 &UR;  &LR; Designers can then determine what alterations are necessary to
maximize performance on the computer screen before the club is
physically brought to life in the modeling room through a data
transfer process that is similar to sending a word processing
document to a printer.
</P>
<P>
   In Taylor Made's modeling shop, prototypes in both wax and
machine resin are developed from the computer data. The clay-like
machine resin prototype is painted according to the graphic design
sketches and evaluated aesthetically. If the resin prototype is
given the go-ahead, it is then cast in the appropriate metals.
 &UR;  &LR;  This completed prototype is then brought to Taylor Made's swing
dynamics lab, a mid-sized room brimming over with computers and
electronic gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   David Anderson, a Taylor Made mechanical engineer with an
impressive handicap of 7, strategically places light meters on the
club and his own body, then stands in front of five light sensor
cameras and swings the prototype club at a ball, launching it into
the wall in front of him with a sharp bang.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras record the movement of the club and Anderson's
swing, feeding the motion and velocity data into customized
analytical software. This software analyzes how the ball and club
react upon collision, and how the club interacts with the golfer's
body. It also allows the engineers to watch the swing and collision
in a stick-figure representation complete with a complex data
readout.
</P>
<P>
   It is this process that helps the design team assess whether or
not the club is performing as predicted. If not, they can analyze
the problems. If the club performs to the satisfaction of the
development team, it then moves on to a test of player reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that can take the place of testing them by
putting them in the hands of golfers and letting them hit balls,''
said Rugge.
</P>
<P>
   If the club fails to win the support of the players in the test
group, as well as Taylor Made's tour staff, an assortment of pro
golfers including Mark O'Meara, it goes back to the computer
screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
