u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GOLF-EQUIP-NYT &LR;      03-24 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOLF-EQUIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUPED-UP TOYS FOR GOLFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of golf balls and drivers made possible by
new technology, with the manufacturers' recommended retail prices:
</P>
<P>
   ORLIMAR TRIMETAL DRIVER ($400): A driver with a stainless steel
shell, a face that blends a variety of metals and copper-tungsten
weighting.
</P>
<P>
   TAYLOR MADE FIRESOLE DRIVER ($399): This oversized titanium club
head is 12 percent smaller than Taylor Made's last driver, the
Tibubble2. Tungsten is added to the bottom of the club to weight
it, which the company says will give more power to a ball struck on
the sweet spot.
</P>
<P>
   CALLAWAY'S GREAT BIG BERTHA HAWK EYE TITANIUM DRIVER ($500): The
latest in the Big Bertha line has a tungsten screw in the sole of
the oversized titanium clubhead. The company says the lower center
of gravity results in a more powerful drive.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON'S STAFF TITANIUM STRAIGHT DISTANCE BALLS ($35 per dozen):
This ball has a dimple pattern that the company says is designed
for extra distance. Wilson call this its longest-flying ball to
date.
</P>
<P>
   TOP-FLITE'S BI-METAL BALLS ($37 per dozen): This ball uses
titanium in the cover and tungsten in the core.
</P>
<P>
   TITLEIST PROFESSIONAL BALLS ($54 per dozen): A cover made from a
rubbery plastic creates a softer feel for this ball, which is meant
for better players who can get better control over a soft-cover
ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
