<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BUTTERFLIES-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO A DANGER TO MONARCH BUTTERFLY MIGRATION
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: Austin American-Statesman preparing graphic showing
migratory route. It will be on CoxNet in science-medical folder
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL ROSARIO, Mexico _ In a scene out of science fiction, millions
of monarch butterflies cling to the branches of fir trees in
shivering clumps, swaying gently like giant prehistoric flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the sun bursts through the forest and the monarchs
explode into flight, creating a blizzard of orange and black wings
as translucent as stained glass, as delicate as the strains of a
harpsichord.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please watch your step!'' urges guide Sergio Antonio Moreno,
as tennis shoes kick up dust and narrowly miss butterflies in their
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, ma'am,'' Moreno answers a woman carrying a plastic bag,
``you can't take the butterflies with you, not even the dead
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in this remote forest 120 miles west of Mexico City, a
country is struggling to balance one of the world's most
extraordinary natural wonders against the needs of very poor
farmers and the demands of well-meaning tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is the 2,000-mile monarch butterfly migration,
from summer breeding grounds on the U.S.-Canadian border down
through the Gulf states and into winter enclaves in Mexico's Sierra
Madre mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Flying about 100 miles a day, the butterflies' trek is as old as
modern humans.
</P>
<P>
   But the migration is so endangered by logging, land erosion and
poorly managed tourism that it could be wiped out within our
lifetime, according to some experts. That danger exists despite a
decade of attempts to protect the monarchs' habitat in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is now the Achilles' heel of the monarch migration,''
said biologist Lincoln Brower of Sweet Briar College in Virginia.
``Losing it would be like losing Yellowstone National Park.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the number of butterflies that have
gathered in Mexico have declined 70 to 80 percent (CQ), according
to Brower. The reasons remain a mystery, but Brower is convinced
that El Nino's drought conditions, logging and the draining of
water from streams for cottage industries are the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Homero Aridjis, a Mexican writer and environmentalist who grew
up among the butterflies, said logging -- clandestine and legal --
continues to destroy the fir trees known as ``oyamel'' that are the
butterflies' protective blanket while they winter in Michoacan and
Mexico states between November and late March. Most of the monarchs
that migrate from east of the Rocky Mountains winter in this area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine the scandal if you were to destroy the Sistine
Chapel,'' said Aridjis, calling the butterflies' gathering in
Mexico ``a masterpiece of nature'' comparable to ``listening to
Mozart.''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to protect the butterflies' habitat, Brower, the
World Wildlife Foundation and others are working with the Mexican
government on a scientific review of monarch sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, researchers confirmed that monarchs resting in
Mexico during the winter came from the Great Lakes region and the
American Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, five out of a dozen mountain ranges in the Sierra Madre
identified as monarch habitat were declared sanctuaries, areas
where logging would be either prohibited or strictly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say it is urgent that areas not yet protected
be declared sanctuaries also, or those forests will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do it drive through that area and see all the
logging trucks, most illegal,'' said Chip Taylor, a University of
Kansas entomologist and director of Monarch Watch, a group that
monitors the migration.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty has led to a plundering of the forest as farmers raze
trees to make way for crops or cut down trees to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're just as poor as they were before,'' Aridjis said.
</P>
<P>
   If it is going to declare more land as sanctuaries, Mexico also
needs a long-term plan for showing people who own that land now
that they can earn money from a ``living forest'' through managed
tourism and other activities, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctuaries like El Rosario -- where farmers now serve as guides
-- are a beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Each family that owns a piece of the land here must send a
member to work at the sanctuary, either as a guide or maintenance
worker. In exchange, they receive a cut of the proceeds from
tickets, which are about $1.50 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all poor here, but most of us are in agreement with
this now,'' said guide Antonio Moreno, 20.
</P>
<P>
   But Moreno and other guides now well versed in the monarchs'
needs said even tourism is taking a toll on the sanctuary. On
weekends, as many as 8,000 people pour through the reserve, raising
thick clouds of dust and making so much noise that the butterflies
flee higher into the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Outside El Rosario, shacks selling souvenirs stand on bare land
where groves of trees hosted monarchs a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really very worried,'' said Javier de la Maza, director
of Mexico's protected areas. ``I'm the first one to say that things
have gotten out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Mexico may consider proposals to allow environmental
groups to work with farmers to manage the tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The monarchs' breeding ground in Canada and the United States is
vast, encompassing about 1.3 million square miles and stretching
from the Great Lakes down into Texas and other Gulf Coast states.
</P>
<P>
   But in Mexico the insects funnel into an area that measures only
about 30 by 60 miles. And only a fraction of that -- 60 square
miles -- is currently protected.
</P>
<P>
   Within those 60 square miles, logging is prohibited in less than
18 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific review of the monarchs' habitat could increase
the number of sanctuaries, said de la Maza. But nothing is certain.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico also has launched reforestation projects it hopes will
restore some of the forest that's been lost inside sanctuaries, de
la Maza added.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm clock that starts the monarchs on their journey to
Mexico is the autumnal equinox in late September. That when they
return to the winter grounds from where their great-grandparents
flew the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Like a orange snowstorm, they flutter into the Sierra Madre in
late October, just in time for Mexico's Day of the Dead celebration
on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say they return to pay their respects to their
ancestors,'' said Moreno. He said he and his neighbors used to call
the butterflies ``doves'' and had no idea where they came from each
year.
</P>
<P>
   On a quiet weekday, the sanctuary's trees are covered with
butterflies. By mid-morning, they drop from the trees and fill the
air, lighting in meadows to drink from dew and streams and to feed
on wildflowers. Sometimes hundreds tumble from branches in one fell
swoop, like a waterfall or carpet unfurling. Their wings beat a
soft hum that competes with the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The monarchs mate, some die and around the vernal equinox in
late March they leave in droves, flying north again where three
more generations are born before the cycle is repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a unique world phenomenon,'' Brower said.
``There are certain areas in world that transcend nationalism. The
monarch reserves are one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
