<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2740 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GOLF-TECHNOLOGY-A     03-24 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOLF-TECHNOLOGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE GOLF BAG: GEAR TO ERASE ALL SINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Calif., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By BRIGID BUCKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As golfers count the days until they can launch balls down lush
green fairways, they start to look doubtfully at their equipment:
Will that dinged-up putter really do this year? Has some new club
come along to prompt the golfer to put last year's flashy titanium
driver out to pasture? Is the next guy's ball giving him a huge
advantage over everybody else?
</P>
<P>
   But those questions are entwined with some troubling issues for
the sport. Golf, seemingly one of the lowest-tech pastimes, is
trembling from traditionalists' charges that technological advances
have sullied the game.
</P>
<P>
   The digital revolution has helped bring equipment design to the
point where oversized, even cartoon-like, drivers are now the norm,
and golf balls composed of seemingly sci-fi materials are common.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the governor of the sport in this country, the
U.S. Golf Association, strives to keep talent, not technology, the
deciding factor in matches _ and to keep the world's hallowed golf
courses from becoming obsolete beneath the boom of high-tech clubs
and balls.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA tests each innovation carefully. ``We are using
technology to fight technology,'' said Frank Thomas, the
association's technical director.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, equipment manufacturers support the changes in
clubs and balls. ``The average player is getting a big benefit from
technology,'' said Frank Garrett, director of golf research and
development at the Wilson Sporting Goods Co., based in Chicago.
Wilson was the nation's top seller of golf club sets in 1997,
according to the National Sporting Goods Association.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, golf is a game in which club hits ball for all of
450 millionths of a second. The variables at play in those instants
are the skills of the 26.4 million golfers who play nationwide and
the capabilities of their balls and clubs. About $3.4 billion was
spent on such equipment in 1997, the sporting goods association
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said golf clubs had become more forgiving, giving even a
poorly hit ball a better chance of being a decent shot. He also
pointed to improvements in balls. ``Golf balls are much more
consistent than they were 25 years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gutta-percha, a tough rubbery gum used by modern dentists as a
filling substance, was the primary or sole ingredient in golf balls
until around the turn of the century, when a ball with a solid core
covered in tightly wound rubber with a gutta-percha cover took
over. By 1907, these balls were prompting calls from some members
of the USGA for standards to keep such improvements from ruining
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Today's players choose between two basic types of balls: low
spin and high spin. Low-spin balls, with a harder cover, are
designed to help the amateur. They offer added distance and
straighter shots.
</P>
<P>
   Carol King, a secretary from Canoga Park, Calif., who has been a
golfer for 40 years, said the low-spin balls gave her longer,
straighter shots. She sticks with her favorite low-spin brand
because, she said, the difference from ball to ball can be
pronounced. ``There are some balls that feel like rocks, and some
that jump right off of the club,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   High-spin balls are designed for the skilled player who already
has distance and accuracy under control and needs a ball with a
softer cover to get finer control. Such balls can be expensive,
however, with some listing for more than $50 per dozen.
</P>
<P>
   The Titleist Professional balls (manufacturer's suggested retail
price $54 a dozen) use new rubbery plastic materials to enhance
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Balls that costly, however, are enough to steer away golfers
like Darren Pavesi of Woodcliff Lake, N.J. ``Personally, I wouldn't
even look at them,'' he said. ``What is that _ gold in there?''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, the golf association tested all balls at
the hands of Iron Byron, a robot golfer that looks somewhat like a
metal oval mounted onto a miniature Eiffel Tower at the test range
at the group's headquarters, in Far Hills, N.J. Until last
November, Iron Byron was relied upon for tests enforcing the USGA's
overall distance standard, which allows a ball to travel a maximum
of approximately 280 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Iron Byron was replaced by an indoor test range;
the range's launcher shoots golf balls through a tunnel lined with
light meters, which send data to customized analytical software.
The system tests the ball's characteristics in flight.
</P>
<P>
   The software can take into account the launching angle, spinning
rate and velocity of the ball as well as the temperature, relative
humidity, barometric pressure and wind speed of the
microchip-created fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Also tested for each ball model are spherical symmetry, maximum
weight, minimum size and initial velocity, which cannot exceed 250
feet per second with a 2 percent tolerance. The USGA tested 642
models of balls, submitted by more than 40 manufacturers from 14
countries, to find out if they should be included on this spring's
list of approved balls. Only eight types failed; they were either
overweight, undersized or did not pass the initial velocity test.
</P>
<P>
   The golf association also has a biomechanics laboratory to
assess things like the interaction between a club and a golfer's
swing. In the laboratory, reflective markers are attached to the
golfer's clothing as well as to the club being assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Five video cameras record the movement of the golfer's swing by
reading the reflective markers and send these data to a computer
program that can generate a software model of a golfer; such models
make it easier to analyze things like the effect of a particular
club on a golfer's joints.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs are also tested to see if they conform to association
standards. The most technologically advanced clubs are the
long-hitting drivers; putters and irons are peripheral to the
technology debate. Since 1979, drivers that are hollow and made
primarily of metal (now called metal woods) have pushed classic
wood woods out of most golfers' bags.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until 1995 that titanium, a silvery white,
lightweight metal known for its tensile strength, became a
golf-club star with the introduction of the Great Big Bertha
Titanium Driver, made by the Callaway Golf Co., based in Carlsbad,
Calif. A relative of Callaway's 1991 sensation, the Big Bertha, the
Great Big Bertha used titanium to make a lighter club with a bigger
head.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most metal wood manufacturers quickly followed suit, with
similar lightweight club designs with big heads. Some designs now
involve other metals beyond titanium.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the popularity of oversized heads, Dick Rugge, the
director of research and development for the Taylor Made Golf Co.,
based in Carlsbad, Calif., said, ``You get better results with a
bad swing, and that's where most golfers live.''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, the USGA began testing certain types of
metal-wood drivers, especially the titaniums, for an undue
springlike or trampoline effect on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In the test, an air cannon shoots a golf ball at the club face.
The ball is monitored by ballistic light meters that feed data into
a computer. The computer calculates the initial velocity of the
rebounding ball and any trampoline-like behavior by the club.
</P>
<P>
   Ely Callaway, the founder and chairman of the Callaway Golf Co.,
opposes efforts to restrict technological improvements in
equipment. The added distance from improved drivers ``is good for
the game and good for the 40 million golfers around the world,'' he
said, adding, ``We're not saying there should be some artificial
power allowed, like gunpowder.''
</P>
<P>
   The USGA's main concern with metal-wood drivers is that they may
make cherished older golf courses obsolete by adding distance to
drives. The association wants to avoid a repeat of the assault on
the Augusta National Golf Club in Augusta, Ga., during the 1997
Masters tournament, when Tiger Woods won with a record-breaking
270, 18 under par.
</P>
<P>
   The technologically advanced equipment used by Woods and other
competitors helped them make such inroads that after the
competition, the club had to upgrade four holes to make them
harder.
</P>
<P>
   Many metal wood manufacturers see the USGA's standard as a block
to club development. Callaway has threatened to sue the USGA if any
of its drivers are rejected. As of the first round of testing,
which ended in January, no American-made clubs had failed the
``springlike'' test.
</P>
<P>
   The new clubs have been popular among golfers. Clocking ball
after ball onto the driving range at the Griffith Park Harding and
Wilson Golf Course in Los Angeles, Robert Heinz of Malibu, Calif.,
was using a new oversized titanium driving club with tungsten
plugged into the bottom of the club for extra weight. ``It just
hits a lot straighter,'' he said. His drives aren't longer, he
said, but are more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary Kahn, 27, a production assistant living in Los Angeles
who started playing golf when he was 11, said that he and his
fellow golfers were susceptible to marketing hype. ``The mentality
is, If it's new, it's better and I'd better buy that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn uses an oversized driver, but he said he would rather use a
driver made of persimmon wood, the kind used by greats like Sam
Snead and Babe Didrikson Zaharias, if he could find one. ``I like
the way a persimmon looks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is not clear that the equipment makes the golfer.
Byron Nelson, for whom Iron Byron was named, had what many consider
the single best year for any golfer when he shot an average of
68.33 strokes per round. The year was 1945.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Morgan Brown, 28, a golfer from Dana Point, Calif., who competed
professionally for four years, recently switched to an oversized
titanium driving club, which has yet to win him over. ``I'm not
sold on the whole bigger-is-better deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Barber, a golf professional at the Griffith Park Harding
and Wilson Golf Club who has been playing for 35 years, said he did
not know what options the manufacturers had left for new drivers.
``They've basically exhausted all of the metals,'' he said. ``It'll
go back to smaller. You can see the pendulum swing back and
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King, too, has doubts about the technology. She recently
tried a couple of oversized titaniums but has settled for a smaller
graphite metal wood that she said gave her distance and consistent
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think we should have any more technology _
we're already outdoing the golf courses,'' she said. ``Well, I'm
not, but other people are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1709EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2744 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FILM-RESTORATION-     03-24 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FILM-RESTORATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING OLD MOVIES: TO THE RESCUE IN THE FINAL SCENE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By ERIC A. TAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While we were waiting for a man to land on the moon in the
1960s, the U.S. space program rewarded us with useful byproducts
like Teflon and Tang. Today, while many Americans wait for the
price of high-definition televisions to drop from the completely
absurd to the merely ridiculous, they have already reaped largely
unseen benefits from this new broadcast standard. Thanks to the
technology involved in HDTV, many classic motion pictures that have
been damaged over time may soon be restored to a nearly pristine
state.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to do this kind of restoration has long been sought
by filmmakers and film preservationists. Many films have simply
been lost, while the surviving copies of others have become deeply
damaged through repeated screenings and improper storage. Prints
for more than 50 percent of all movies no longer exist, said John
Galt, vice president for high-definition technology development at
Sony Pictures Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike visual arts of the past, such as prehistoric cave
drawings, motion pictures simply won't last for even 500 years,''
Galt said in an interview. The company's High Definition Center,
based in Los Angeles, has become a nexus for the development of new
techniques in film restoration. The methods all focus on
transforming a film into digital images, then using computers to
manipulate those images.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, it was nearly impossible to fix motion
picture film that had been scratched or stepped on or chewed up by
machinery. Fixing a sequence required physically touching up tens
of thousands of individual frames, a virtually impossible task. At
best, some scratches could be removed through the wetgate process,
in which a damaged film is immersed in fluid before light is passed
through it. The fluid helps fill in the gashes, which then do not
print through to the new copy.
</P>
<P>
   The development of high-definition videotape, which can
reproduce an image that is virtually as sharp as that possible with
motion picture film, gave film archivists the tools they needed to
do more than just get rid of scratches.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology allows them to virtually recreate missing
frames. Because high-definition videotape is digital, a motion
picture can be transferred onto it, and then those digital images
can be manipulated in the same way that home computer users can
alter their scanned photographs by placing a dog's head on a
brother-in-law's body. It just takes a lot longer when you are
trying to work on a 20-minute reel of a movie instead of one single
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Pictures first tried this technique on Frank Capra's silent
classic ``The Matinee Idol.'' All copies of this 1928 Columbia
release were presumed lost, but in 1992, a film historian found a
copy in a canister in France, complete with French title cards and
missing and rearranged scenes. Grover Crisp, the vice president for
asset management and film restoration at Sony Pictures, heard about
the find and, thanks to a joint effort between Sony and the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, was able to get a copy sent to
Los Angeles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After the picture was transferred to high-definition video,
restoration artists eliminated scratches by ``painting'' damaged
areas with computer styluses. Crisp had new English-language title
cards created on high-definition videotape, and damaged frames were
restored by copying similar elements in surrounding frames on the
computer and pasting them into the areas that needed repair. The
process is similar to the way photomanipulation software like Adobe
Photoshop adds and subtracts picture elements by ``borrowing''
colors and textures from surrounding parts of an image.
</P>
<P>
   Using similar techniques, Crisp has just completed restoring
85,000 frames of a 1960s classic, ``Easy Rider,'' removing vertical
scratches that appeared throughout the entire 19{-minute running
time of two of the film's 10 reels. The reels were transferred to
high-definition videotape, and the vertical scratches were filled
in one at a time by a computer. A computer program analyzed each
frame for dirt marks; when the computer sensed that an area was
considerably darker or lighter than its surroundings, it assumed
that dirt was the reason and modified the density of the area so it
matched.
</P>
<P>
   But this automated process of dirt removal has some significant
flaws. For example, if the computer sees rain, it thinks ``dirt''
and removes it. So images that contain intentional light or dark
areas still need to be cleaned up by a person checking each frame
on the computer. And since color dyes fade at differing rates, it
is up to the individual restorer to bring tones back into balance.
</P>
<P>
   The goal in film restoration is not to create a new copy that
looks as if it had been shot last week, but to restore a print so
it looks as it did when it was first screened, complete with all
the washed-out or overly saturated colors that we might find
unusual today. It is like restoring an old painting; the esthetic
of the time when the work was created reigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be very careful,'' said Galt, of Sony Pictures.
``Restoring films is like peeling an onion _ you correct one gross
problem and you then find smaller ones. But the restorer's goal is
`to do no harm.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
