<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2778 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-JAIL-PENPALS-2TAK     03-24 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-JAIL-PENPALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-MAIL PEN PAL SITES GIVE PRISONERS A LINK TO THE WORLD OUTSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Ohio, Ark., Mo., Calif., N.Y., Wash.)   (af)  
 By GEORGE ROBINSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using e-mail is not the easiest way to start a relationship.
Just ask Diane A., a psychotherapist from Colorado. In 1995, she
began exchanging letters with a man whom she met through a notice
posted on a Web site. Through their correspondence, the pair fell
in love and plan to marry next year. That is the earliest her
fiance is expected to be released from prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine meeting someone new and the first thing they want to
know about you is the worst thing you've ever done in your life,''
Diane said, recalling their first exchange of letters. Her fiance,
now in his late 30s, robbed a convenience store when he was 19 and
received a sentence of 15 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, he was involved in a knife fight that resulted in the
death of another prisoner. He spent six years on death row before
the Supreme Court overturned his conviction on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Diane, who asked that her last name not be used (``My parents
don't know that I've fallen in love with someone in prison,'' she
said), met her fiance through Penn-Pals (pennpals.org), one of a
half-dozen Web sites that connect inmates of state and federal
prisons with pen pals outside the gates.
</P>
<P>
   Because no prison system in the United States _ federal, state
or municipal _ allows inmates to receive e-mail directly, these Web
sites typically collect e-mail messages for prisoners, print them
out and mail them to the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   For the creators of prison pen-pal sites and their advocates,
the sites are a tool for breaking down the invisible walls of
loneliness that inevitably accompany incarceration. But critics
contend that these sites represent all the common fears of the
Internet writ large: that predatory criminals use these sites to
establish relationships and win the confidence of naive _ and some
not-so-naive _ online correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Penn-Pals, the site where Diane A. met her fiance, was started
in 1995 by Charles Sparks, at the time a manager at a Cleveland
robotics firm. A friend of Sparks who was in prison was looking for
a traditional pen pal. ``He requested I assist him in placing an ad
in a local supermarket tabloid,'' Sparks said. ``I realized the Net
would be far superior for his purpose in affording access to people
from around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   What began as a simple favor became a Web site in March 1996.
Sparks creates a personalized Web page for each inmate, using
information they provide by filling out a questionnaire, and a
photo where possible. Each prisoner is then given an e-mail address
for receiving messages, which Sparks collects and distributes.
</P>
<P>
   Most prisoners become aware of his service by word-of-mouth.
Sparks estimates that since he began the site, he has helped 1,350
inmates find pen pals.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks said that he had never been in prison himself but that
while he was growing up, his father was imprisoned for six years.
``That left an impression on me,'' Sparks said. ``I try not to make
a big connection between that and the Web site, but it's something
that has never left me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks now works on Penn-Pals full time. ``I tried to price it
so that inmates could afford it, with a little sacrifice,'' he
said. ``It's $20 for the setup, the Web page and everything you get
with it, $5 more for a photo, for scanning it in. That's for the
first 30 days, then it's $5 a month thereafter. So $35 for 90 days
with a photograph.'' He fulfills about a quarter of the requests at
no charge. ``If you're in solitary, you're not working, you have no
income,'' Sparks said. ``Of course they're the ones who need human
contact the most.''
</P>
<P>
   The site provides a richly layered venue for prisoners and their
families to express their hopes, fears, anguish and regrets. Art
created by prisoners, much of it striking and passionate, adorns
the Web pages, and there are special areas for prisoners on death
row, parents of prisoners and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of the inmates are looking for more than a
letter. ``Someone told me we ought to start a chapel here,'' Sparks
said with a laugh. ``We've been responsible for quite a few
marriages. Most recently, I got a letter from Steve Risinger _ he's
in prison in Arkansas, met a nice lady and they just got married.
He sent me a wedding picture.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace-Inmates, which is run out of rural Missouri, averages
more than 2,000 hits a week. Another site, Prison Pen Pals, logs
between 3,000 and 5,000 hits a week. Sparks' site registers 820
user sessions per day, with 3,550 total pages being viewed each
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most remarkable thing I've ever done in my life or
ever will,'' Sparks said. ``I can't imagine going back to a regular
job. I worked in robotics for seven years and didn't add anything
to society at large. This makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shares his enthusiasm. The sites' creators receive
some criticism directly. ``I have had death threats via e-mail,
been told that I should be raped or have a child murdered,'' said
Priscilla Pletcher, who runs the Prison Pen Pals site. ``Sometimes
you wonder if the right people are in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Ida Ballasiotes, a Republican member of the Washington State
House of Representatives and co-chairwoman of its Criminal Justice
and Corrections Committee, recently called a committee hearing to
discuss the Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I don't want to see going on,'' Ballasiotes
said in an interview. ``I know some of the individuals who are on
these sites. I saw a guy who murdered his fourth wife and is being
investigated in the death of his second wife, and talks about
taking long walks in the moonlight. These are really manipulative
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cardoza, a Democratic state assemblyman from California,
has been also pushing for a review of the sites. ``A constituent of
mine was on the Net and he came across his daughter's killer on one
of these Web sites,'' Cardoza said. ``You can imagine the trauma
that caused him.''
</P>
<P>
   The only state that does not allow inmates to receive mail
generated through Sparks' site or any other third-party service is
New York. James B. Flateau, spokesman for the New York State
Department of Correctional Services, said that the state's right
has been upheld in numerous court cases. ``We do not allow mail
kiting, the sending of mail through third parties,'' he said. ``For
security reasons, we want to know who inmates are writing to and
getting mail from.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks said that taking precautions at the start of the pen pal
process is the way to make these sites safe. He warns inmates not
to look for anything more than a pen pal through the site and he
screens the questionnaires the inmates fill out. ``And there have
been some I have refused. One guy was a pimp. Some people just have
their priorities screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Corcoran, vice president of the California Correction
Peace Officers Association, said that the sites should not be
regulated but that users should exercise caution. ``Pen pals can be
a valuable support for a prisoner,'' Corcoran said. ``I have found
that what works the best are religious outreach programs for
inmates. With an Internet site you have no idea what you're signing
up for. You have no knowledge of the individual, and you're
divulging personal information to them about yourself and your
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Diane, who writes to three other pen pals besides her
fiance, said that she was ambivalent about some of the inmates who
use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I write to tell me that 40 to 50 percent of the
people in prison, I should be glad they won't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Her own fiance, whom she met face to face for the first time
last summer, is scheduled to walk out of prison within the next 24
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was released from death row 14 months ago,'' Diane said.
``The most intense period in my entire life was the two months in
which we waited to see what the Supreme Court would say. After he
was released from death row, he said to me, `I'm really struggling
to cope with the idea that I have a life again. What am I going to
do with it?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
