<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WINDCHILL-MEASURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL WEATHER STATIONS CAN PROVIDE INFORMATION WHEN YOU VENTURE
OUTDOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, N.Y., Pa. ,  Mass.)  (rk) 
 By   IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last July when a vicious storm descended on the unnamed mountain
peak that Michael Coyne was climbing in Alaska, he pulled out a
palm-size gadget with a tiny fan protruding from the top.
</P>
<P>
   As the air currents starting spinning the fan, a liquid crystal
display told him that the winds were gusting up to 72 mph. The
device then calculated that the wind chill was a numbing minus 21.1
degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely helped me make some decisions,'' said Coyne, a
mountain climber and adventurer from Boston who decided that day to
fasten down his tents and wait out the storm. ``Sometimes the wind
is misleading. Without measurements, you don't realize that the
gusts of wind are as high as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The device Coyne carried, a Kestrel 2000, which sells for $119,
is one of a series of small, relatively inexpensive electronic
devices that are rapidly evolving into handheld personal weather
stations.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Kestrel's manufacturer, Nielsen-Kellerman of
Chester, Pa., will introduce a $159 model that, in addition to
measuring temperature and winds, as the current model does, will
also be able to measure relative humidity. That will enable it to
calculate the dew point as well as the heat index, warm weather's
version of the wind chill factor.
</P>
<P>
   And a competitor _ the Brunton Co., distributor of the Wind
Watch, made by its parent company, Silva _ is expanding its
electronic handheld wind measurer and thermometer to include a
barometer and an altimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Naughton, the Kestrel product manager at
Nielsen-Kellerman, said his company hoped the expanded features
would make the tiny weather stations attractive to the general
public. ``They are becoming a general consumer product for anybody
who's going to spend anytime outdoors,'' Naughton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kestrel wind meter technology developed, somewhat
improbably, from Nielsen-Kellerman's main line of business:
producing electronic devices for rowers. Among its offerings for
that market is a highly sensitive speedometer.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid forcing users to drill holes through their racing
shells to install the speedometer, the device uses a tiny fan with
a magnet at its center that spins on jeweled bearings like a
mechanical watch movement. That unit is fixed onto the outside of
the boat under the water line. On the inside, a separate sensor
detects the magnet's revolutions to calculate speed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of Kestrel's customers have been sailors and
``anybody connected to anything that involves flying or falling
through the sky,'' Naughton said. The company is trying to sell
parents on the idea that they need to check the wind chill or heat
index levels before sending their children outside.
</P>
<P>
   That information, of course, can already be obtained by flicking
on the Weather Channel. But Naughton argued that you would not get
accurate information there or on the Web unless you lived very
close to an airport, the usual place for monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least one group of concerned urbanites has turned to
the weather device. Last year, the organizers of the Macy's
Thanksgiving Day parade used it to track wind speed ahead of the
inflatable floats. ll
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
