<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2795 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     03-24 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADGETS OF THE GEEK ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Wash., Calif., N.Y., Texas, Pa. ,  Del., Va.)  (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ The 800 people who are attending the PC
Forum 99 conference here, an annual gathering of some of the
world's technological elite, are the people who envision, finance
and make the products and services used by the ``early adopters,''
people who buy new technologies for technology's sake.
</P>
<P>
   For many of these executives, time is as precious as water is to
the creatures in the vast desert that surrounds this resort area,
so they have no patience for technologies that do not work
properly.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, are their favorite gizmos and gadgets?
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are ubiquitous. During conference breaks, dozens of
people dash to the courtyards and stand in the sun, like so many
cacti in designer sunglasses, with upraised arms holding tiny
wireless phones to their ears.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Pilot screens glint in the light, and inside, clusters of
people huddle around laptop computers that are connected to the
Internet over wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Quinlan, vice chairman of the MacManus Group, the New
York advertising concern, said she carries two cell phones ``in
case one goes down.'' Mitchell Kertzman, president of Network
Computer of Redwood Shores, Calif., carries a pager, a Palm Pilot
personal digital assistant, and a miniature Motorola digital phone,
all of which he stuffs into his pockets and hopes are
inconspicuous. He adds that he expects to go catatonic if ever they
all start vibrating and buzzing simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   David Nagle, chief technology officer for AT&AMP;T and a former
Apple Computer executive, also has a cell phone (AT&AMP;T, of course)
in his pocket. ``I just bought a Palm V,'' he said, referring to a
slim, shirt-pocket computer made by the 3Com Corp.'s Palm Computing
division.
</P>
<P>
   Nagle said he is annoyed that he has to regularly synchronize
the information in his Palm V with the information in his desktop
computer, over a direct connection, instead of simply synchronizing
all his information with all of his devices over a network.
</P>
<P>
   Will we ever see a pocket-size, network-centric, wireless,
AT&AMP;T-branded gizmo like that? ``Well, no announcements, but I think
it's a good idea,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Lonier, chairman of Working Solo, a consulting company for
free-lancers and other self-employed people in New Paltz, N.Y.,
lovingly displayed her sea-foam green Nokia 6160 cell phone, a
nearly constant companion. ``To me, one of the interesting things
about this conference is that a year ago everyone was on Motorola
Star-tacs, and this year almost everybody is on Nokias,'' she said.
``It's the shift from analogue to digital, and the introduction of
AT&AMP;T's One Rate plan.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sculley, former chief executive of Apple Computer and now a
private investor in New York City, corroborated Ms. Lonier's phone
observation by whipping out his Nokia 6120. ``I notice everyone has
switched over to this model,'' said Sculley, who recently became
chairman of a start-up company called Zapa Digital Arts. He
explained that the multi-modal Nokia can move seamlessly from
analogue to digital and from the United States to Europe, something
most cell phones cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley, the father of the Apple Newton, conceded that he now
carries a Palm Pilot. ``And then I carry a notebook computer. I
have several of them, but the one I usually carry around is a Sharp
Actius, because it's only 2.8 pounds. It's got almost a full
keyboard, high-resolution display, and its got everything I need
for e-mail and web access built in.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Griffiths is president of the software developer
Perspectives Unlimited, a virtual corporation with offices in
Delaware, California, Virginia and New York. ``One thing that I
definitely can't give up is my videocam,'' she said, referring to a
videoconferencing system her company assembled using Dell and IBM
computers, Intel digital cameras and Microsoft's Netmeeting
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for me to be able to take an idea and run with
it independent of geography or time zones or boundaries created by
walls. I can basically plug into any telephone line so that we have
real-time video conferencing, even if I'm sitting in an airport or
a hotel room.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Bezos, chief executive of Amazon.com in Seattle, reached
for a wallet-sized device on his belt. ``My newest gadget is the
Motorola Pagewriter 2000,'' he said, referring to a wireless device
known as a smart pager. ``It's nicely designed so that you can flip
it open and read your e-mail messages without taking it off your
belt. They've really thought it through well. You can send e-mail
and receive e-mail, and it is not as interruptive as a cell
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect, some technology executives are most
enamored with devices that are still on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban, chairman and president of Broadcast.com of Dallas,
and some friends rigged his home PC to receive HDTV broadcasts. It
is his favorite technical toy right now. ``But what I want,'' he
said, ``is mobile wireless access to my PC in my car. That's like
my nirvana right now. You always become untethered somewhere along
the line and I hate that, hate it, hate it, hate it. To be able to
sit by the pool, or jump in my car and stay tethered, that's the
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   How long does he think it will be before he reaches nirvana?
``Two years, three years max,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How about stuff available right now? ``My Sony Vaio 505,'; Cuban
said, referring to his thin, light laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Raymond, president of Open Source Initiative of Malvern,
Pa., does not carry any devices. ``I am certainly not resistant to
technology,'' he said. ``I've been a happy Internet user since the
1970s. But at the moment I find that I don't have a Palm Pilot, I
don't have a cell phone. Each of these devices has a little too
much cost and complexity associated with it, relative to its
function for me. I don't want to carry 20 different devices that
each do one thing; I want to carry one device that does it all, and
we're not there yet. Maybe it's my unwillingness to look like a
character from a William Gibson novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Has that been a hindrance in the high-tech circles in which he
travels? ``No, but then, I have a good memory,'' he said, tapping
his head. ``I have the equivalent of a Palm Pilot installed
neurally.''
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson, whose company Edventure Holdings is host for the
annual technology conference here, does not have a telephone in her
New York apartment. ``Look,'' she said, patting her pockets. ``I've
got nothing on me, no buzzer, no cell phone, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   People who spend all their time thinking about technology have
the power to choose whether or not to use it, she noted. To Ms.
Dyson, the ideas that flow to her via the technology, whether they
come as electronic mail or an exciting new software application,
are far more interesting than the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``I carry my Sony Vaio with me wherever I go,
pretty much,'' Ms. Dyson said. ``I don't like the gizmos, but I
love my PC.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
