<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TARGETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-AIRCRAFT DEFENSES TOP NATO'S TARGET LIST IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The likely targets of NATO war planes and missiles
attacking Yugoslavia include naval docks and ships along the
Adriatic coast as well as military bases, ammunition dumps and
supply centers across the country, military experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO forces first must destroy Yugoslavia's air defense
network, a protective shield of surface-to-air missiles, early
warning radars and electronics that pose a danger to allied pilots.
The first phase of the military operation that began Wednesday was
focused mainly on this task.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pentagon, the Yugoslavs operate some 100
surface to-air-missile batteries, including mobile SA-6 missiles,
and less mobile SA-3s; about 2,000 mobile air defense guns along
with shoulder-fired missiles similar to the Stinger missiles in the
U.S. arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Navy Adm. Leighton Smith, who directed NATO attacks
against Bosnian Serb forces in 1995, said that once the air
defenses are eliminated, all Yugoslavian military facilities would
be fair game, not just those in the embattled province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were calling the shots, I'd go after military
capabilities in Serbia (the dominant Yugoslavian province) and I'd
take out the biggest targets and then work down from there,'' said
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   He indicated that high on his target list would be airport
runways and command and communications centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect NATO to go after military facilities, motor
pools, and supply bases,'' Smith said, adding, ``I would take out
all of their ammunition and transportation capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, declining to discuss specific
targets, said Wednesday that the target list is ``extensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO attacks began after Yugoslav military forces failed to
call off their crackdown on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, where Yugoslavian forces are battling the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA), there are about 40,000 Yugoslavian troops
operating 400 tanks, several hundred armored personnel carriers and
several hundred artillery pieces, said Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   While these are also likely targets, Smith said that attacking
them would pose a challenge to NATO pilots because of the
difficulty of distinguishing between troop concentrations and
facilities under control of the Yugoslav government and those
controlled by the KLA forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant problem,'' Smith said. ``If you go after
forces in Kosovo, you have some difficulty in identifying what is
the right thing to hit because there is nobody on the ground to
identify who is friend and who is foe.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he encountered a similar predicament in 1995 when
NATO attacked Bosnian Serb targets in order to pressure the warring
parties to sign a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Naval Institute, much of Yugoslavia's
military capability is spread across some 15 major military bases,
most of which are not in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Janes Information Group, a leading British publisher on foreign
militaries, said that among the top targets of NATO pilots are
Yugoslavia's main early warning and coastal missile defense center
at Mount Rumija in the province of Montenegro on the Adriatic
coast; the main air surveillance site at Kopanik in southwestern
Serbia, and the Podgorica airbase near Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's also identifies as likely targets the naval base at Tivet
on the Adriatic, a tank base at Krusevac in central Serbia, and air
bases at Ladjevci in central Serbia, Ponikve in western Serbia, and
Slatina near the Kosovan capital of Pristina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
