<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ABE-LINCOLN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SERIOUS LINCOLN SCHOLARS, CHANCES FOR NEW DISCOVERIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill. , Utah, Neb., Conn.)  (Eds: Herbert Mitgang is the author of ``Abraham Lincoln: A Press
Portrait'' and the play ``Mister Lincoln.'') 
 (nk) 
 By HERBERT MITGANG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is reassuring to know, 190 years after Lincoln's birth in
1809, that in 2000 and beyond, new studies will continue to seek
clues to the 16th president's life and language _ electronically.
Even though the shelves hold more books about Lincoln than about
any other president, modern technology will soon enable historians
to scour his ideas and actions even more closely than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers University Press brought out the Abraham Lincoln
Association's eight volumes of ``The Collected Works of Abraham
Lincoln'' nearly a half-century ago. Though somewhat outdated, they
have been the standard reference tool in the nonstop field of
Lincolniana.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Web site is being developed that will offer the complete
multivolume ``Works'' _ all 2,048,683 printed words. Lincoln
scholars hope to unearth nuggets that will help to interpret his
rise from near obscurity to the White House, his brilliance as a
wordsmith and his momentous decisions during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site will be a building block to create an electronic
archive, said Thomas F. Schwartz, Illinois' state historian. ``It's
the beginning of what will become a virtual Lincoln library _ the
first of its kind for any American president.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Schwartz's editorial guidance, the searchable database for
Works was produced by a search-engine company called Word Cruncher
Internet Technologies, in Alpine, Utah. The database, which is near
completion, will be available at the association's Web site
(www.alincolnassoc.com).
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Schwartz forwarded a test copy of the Lincoln
database on a disk and suggested that I give it a try. (Just in
case of a nervous breakdown _ the computer's or mine _ I kept a
well-worn printed edition of the eight volumes close at hand.)
After installing the program, just for fun, I called up two words
that have been big in the contemporary vocabulary _ impeachment and
censure _ to see if Lincoln ever used them.
</P>
<P>
   In a wink, the answer appeared on the screen. The word
``impeach'' came up only twice, while the word ``censure'' was
found 14 times. Was there a subliminal message here? It was amusing
to think so, but of course, the Lincoln database referred neither
to a presidential impeachment nor to a censure, in the recent
senses of the words.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on July 14, 1863, 10 days after Gen. Robert E.
Lee's defeated army at Gettysburg turned tail and escaped
southward, an unhappy Lincoln had to calm down Gen. George Meade,
who failed to pursue the Confederate Army, by damning him with
faint praise in a letter that began: ``I have just seen your
despatch to Gen. Henry Halleck, asking to be relieved of your
command, because of a supposed censure of mine. I am sorry now to
be the author of the slightest pain to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Lincoln scholars have already found the database to be
useful.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to cross-reference words and phrases more handily
without having to depend on the incomplete index to the printed
volumes. Take the words ``union'' and ``nation.'' Professor James
Rawley of the University of Nebraska found that Lincoln tended to
drop the word union during his presidency and increasingly began to
call the United States a nation.
</P>
<P>
   There are already a few surprises that will demand fresh
interpretation by scholars. In 1858, the year he debated Stephen A.
Douglas, Lincoln frequently referred to the Declaration of
Independence, but in the final years of his life in the White
House, he avoided mentioning the document, which declared that
``all men are created equal.''
</P>
<P>
   An effort is also being made to trace Lincoln's stylistic
fingerprints. Which words did he write himself and which were first
drafted by one of his secretaries? In the famous letter of sympathy
to Mrs. Bixby on the death of her sons in battle (quoted in the
film ``Saving Private Ryan''), the word ``beguile'' appears.
Professor Michael Burlingame of Connecticut College said that
beguile had not been part of Lincoln's vocabulary and attributed it
to John Hay, a Lincoln secretary who often used the word in his own
writing. In the same letter the words ``our heavenly father'' turn
up _ again, not a phrase in the Lincoln lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   Will the new electronic research really change our knowledge
about the character and achievements of Lincoln or any other
president? It is too early to tell. With the printed word, the
slower process of turning the pages can sometimes lead a researcher
to lucky discoveries. My guess is that the books and the database
are destined to supplement rather than replace each other. After
fact-finding, educated analysis will still be necessary. A database
is a research tool, not a thinking cap.
</P>
<P>
   But Lincoln, a sometime inventor and a lecturer on the power of
books and the print media, might well have cheered the idea of
reaching a wider audience with his words _ in any form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
