<HEADLINE>
BLUE SCREEN: NOT `DEATH,' BUT ANNOYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is a ``blue screen of death'' error?
</P>
<P>
   A. This error with the ominous nickname, when the computer just
stops and reverts to a blue screen, can happen in Windows 95, 98
and NT. It is usually called a fatal exception error in Windows 95
and 98, according to the error message displayed at the time of the
crash, but the higher-end Windows NT systems call it a Stop error.
</P>
<P>
   Many things can cause the error, like older device drivers on
your machine that are conflicting with the rest of the system.
Conflicts between two pieces of hardware and problems like bad RAM
chips on your motherboard can also cause fatal exception errors.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get the blue screen and the error message, you cannot
really do much other than restart or shut down the computer.
Utility programs like Norton Crash Guard offer to help you prevent
and recover from blue-screen crashes.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, you might go to Microsoft's Support Online
area and read article Q136337
(support.microsoft.com/support/kb/articles/q136/3/37.asp). It gives
several tips for dealing with start-up errors and driver problems.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
