u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LUDDITE-LOST-NYT &LR;      03-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LUDDITE-LOST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTES FROM THE LAND OF THE E-LESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ My dear aunt Mildred, a 98-year-old Roman Catholic nun
who lives in a convent, stopped me at a recent family gathering to
broach the topic of the newfangled ways of modern society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you use the Internet?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Aunt Mildred,'' I confessed, ``I'm not quite up to speed
with that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she replied, thrusting a card into my palm, ``when you
get up to speed, here's my e-mail address.''
</P>
<P>
   It is getting to be embarrassing to be off line.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen times a day, people ask for my e-mail address. And
I have to tell them: I don't know how to e-mail. After more than a
decade of paying off college loans, I now discover at the age of 40
that I am illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, half of American households still do not have
computers. Not everyone is sitting around surfing the Net, visiting
Web sites and zipping off clever notes to their e-mail pals.
</P>
<P>
   It just seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when it was perfectly acceptable, even a bit
stylish or edgy, to be a Luddite. People thought you were an
Individual, or at least eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're just a dud, the technological equivalent of a
cigarette smoker or a mink wearer.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how society is losing patience with
techno-laggards, observe the nastiness that is creeping into the
computerized voices on telephone menus.
</P>
<P>
   The old message: ``If you are not calling from a touch-tone
telephone, please stay on the line, and an operator will be with
you shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   The new message: ``If you are not calling from a touch-tone
telephone, hang up and call back from a touch-tone telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Get with the program, Buster.
</P>
<P>
   Inter-nots, as we might be called, have become social misfits.
With e-mail, even far-flung co-workers can essentially shout across
the room to one another, sharing office gossip and trading work
tips.
</P>
<P>
   People who are out of the loop, like me, are just out of luck. I
know they're talking to one another. Worse yet, maybe they're
talking about me.
</P>
<P>
   There is a whiff of superiority about all of this, a
country-clubby we're-in-and-you're-not superiority.
</P>
<P>
   The smugness is well founded. Is there a realm of life that is
not made quicker or easier for those with a computer? Heaven help
the poor suitor who is unable to conduct a courtship without being
able to tap out sweet, unpunctuated E-nothings all day.
</P>
<P>
   For the E-less, there is no refuge. Scarcely a television
commercial flits by anymore without a Web address flashing across
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   And when people make small talk, the Internet seems to rank
somewhere on the interest scale between sex and money. (Listening
idly to all of this chit-chat must be what life is like for people
who do not follow sports.) Macho talk these days turns to souped-up
computers and high-powered components. It all gets so torqued it
sounds like gear-heads at the drag strip.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, of course, stocks with any remote connection to the
Internet are making zillionaires of people in the cyberknow. And
who bought these stocks at a pittance and sold them for bundles?
Not guys like me.
</P>
<P>
   So not only are computer people smarter, but now they're also
richer.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen? Weren't the computer guys supposed to be
the nerds, the geeks?
</P>
<P>
   I have always been in the bottom half of the technology class.
That is partly how I ended up in journalism. I was told there would
be no math.
</P>
<P>
   When I started working in this business in 1979, I used a manual
typewriter. Grudgingly, I moved to an electric typewriter, and then
to a word processor, when employment required it.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, I have used a portable Zenith 286. In the
broadest sense, this is defined as a computer. In my hands,
however, it is just a glorified typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   My machine is slightly smaller than a window air conditioner.
They no longer make computer cases large enough to fit it. I carry
it around in a big nylon gym bag with socks and underwear for
cushioning.
</P>
<P>
   People titter at my machine and brag about how small their
computers are. I don't understand this. What's wrong with a little
heft? Working with itsy-bitsy things makes me want to pick up a
brick and hurl it through a window. I like a machine that has taken
a few hard knocks, like its owner.
</P>
<P>
   My computer went on the blink recently. It was frightening. I
feared I might lose my old, old friend.
</P>
<P>
   I took it to a computer store and laid it on a table. The
computer technician touched it gently, as if it were a museum
piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fix it, then?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing?'' he responded incredulously. ``I wouldn't have a
clue.''
</P>
<P>
   He told me about an old Israeli fellow in the next town, Abe,
who ran a satellite dish store and was said to be able to tinker
with all sorts of oddball devices.
</P>
<P>
   I took it to Abe and he fixed it.
</P>
<P>
   So my trusted old jalopy of a writing machine is still in
business. Change is not good. That has always been my motto.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust of fads has generally served me well. It saved me from
leisure suits and raw fish and microbrews, not to mention the
macarena.
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, trying to live life on the cutting edge can
get dull. Chase trends long enough and you run out of gas, like the
aging yuppies. Or you take up cigars. Now that's hip.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I figured this information superhighway, as they
used to call it, was going to be. Just a flash in the pan. So I
stepped aside and waited for it to pass me by.
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, I admit, I have been thinking about learning to use one
of the new computers. My aging 286 can't be expected to last
forever. And neither can Abe.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows. I might even learn about the Internet and start
sending messages on this newfangled e-mail thing.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to keep up with Aunt Mildred. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
