<HEADLINE>
THE PHONE THAT BOSSES AROUND APPLIANCES 
THE $299 COMPUTER 
PREPARE FOR THE BONBON CHAT ROOM 
COUPON CLIPPERS ONLINE 
PAGERS FOR KIDS 
E-KNOCKING 
HOME, GARDEN, INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an advance that will allow people to program their VCRs while
also speeding down the freeway _ not that this is necessarily a
good thing _ a German company has come up with a way to turn
telephones into remote controls for household appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Siemens, calls the technology Residential Gateway.
It allows mobile or stationary phones to program a VCR, control the
home thermostat and turn on the power for coffee makers and other
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The Gateway consists of the remote, called the Euroset 845
(which doubles as a telephone), and a receiver box that sits in the
home. Users enter commands into the Euroset, which sends radio
signals to the black box, which directs the signals to various
appliances. In the case of a coffee maker that you want turned on
or an iron you forgot to unplug, the device sends the appropriate
signal to the appropriate wall socket.
</P>
<P>
   With the mobile phone, users dial into the Euroset from just
about anywhere, punch in the commands and then have them sent to
the VCR or home alarm system.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether this will solve one of the world's
great challenges: people's ability to program the clock on the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   New Computer for $299? Well, Most of One
</P>
<P>
   Will computers join the likes of gum, batteries and magazines as
impulse buys in the checkout aisle? That's not implausible, given
the phenomenon loosely known as the Incredibly Falling Price of
PCs. The latest sign of that trend is a $299 computer from a
Seattle company called Microworkz Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the word's been getting out, the company's Web site and
phone line have been bursting at the seams with traffic, said Rick
Latman, the company's chief executive. Not one lacking in
confidence, he projects that Microworkz will produce 200,000
computers a month starting in April. ``How is Michael Dell going to
compete with us?'' Latman said. ``He'd better concentrate on
servers. We're going to take the low end.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts are not that ready to crown Microworkz. The
$299 computer comes with a Cyrix 300-megahertz processor, a
3.2-gigabyte hard drive, 16 megabytes of memory and a year of
Internet access. But calling it even a bare-bones machine is a
stretch, as it is missing a few big bones: a monitor, floppy drive
and a CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really just an Internet appliance,'' said David Stremba,
an analyst at Dataquest, a market research firm in San Jose, Calif.
``To create a full-fledged system, it'll push it into $500.''
</P>
<P>
   Online Delivery Service Wants to Be a `Food Portal'
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cybermeals.com, the site that lets users order food
for delivery from thousands of restaurants across the country, was
reborn as Food.com. Robert Frank, the entrepreneur behind the
original site, hopes that food lovers will have even less reason to
leave the house.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for the original site came from seeing Sandra
Bullock order a slice of pizza over the Internet in the movie ``The
Net.'' Among Frank's ambitions is to turn Food.com into a ``Food
portal'' (forgive him, it had to happen). He plans a potpourri of
culinary-related content, like stories about ``superchefs'' and
more recipes than you can shake a mouse (or is that mousse?) at.
Can the bonbon chat room be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   The site has already created a hunger among one group:
investors. Food.com said it had just secured $25 million in
capital, which means that some private investors are banking very
heavily that the modem is the maitre d' of the future. There's
already been one beneficiary: the man in Northern California who
sold the company its new domain name. That earned him enough, Frank
said, to ``put his daughter through college.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Coupons
</P>
<P>
   The use of coupons delivered via the Web is starting to take
off, according to a study by the NPD Group, a marketing research
company based in Port Washington, N.Y. The survey, which was based
on a questionnaire answered by 2,673 individuals who are online,
found that nearly a third of them get Web coupons for shopping in
an average month.
</P>
<P>
   While that is still a mere 3 percent of the total coupon use by
those households, NPD found that more people were planning to use
online coupons more often and in increased quantity. Of the 49
percent of respondents who were aware of online coupons, 87 percent
said they planned to use some or more online coupons in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Online coupons are often quite similar to the standard ones
found in newspapers and fliers. Shoppers go to the Web, print them
out and present them at the checkout register just as they would
with traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Smith, vice president of NPD Online, said people used Web
coupons in the ``same general pattern'' as regular coupons, mostly
for groceries. Online coupon users tend to be between the ages of
25 and 44, and a third of the online coupon redeemers have
household incomes over $75,000. The most popular coupon sites found
by the survey were Coolsavings.com and Valuepage.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ LESLIE KAUFMANN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail Device Scaled Down for Children
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that pagers and cellular phones ring during the
opera. Now they might go off during nap time. Playmates Toys has
just released a just-for-children pager that is called Friend.link.
The $20 keychain toy can send e-mail-style messages via radio waves
to other Friends.links within 25 feet. The messages are entered
with a small data wheel and can be up to 48 characters long.
Children can also enter personal information like their sex, age
and hobbies. When that device comes within range of another unit
programmed with similar interests, the pagers will ring, alerting
the owners, much like last year's Japanese toy matchmaker, the Love
Getty.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting feature of the Friend.link allows the recipient
list to be customized. Users can choose to send a message to a
single friend, to all the Friend.links in the vicinity, or to only
boys or girls. The last choice could be an example of retrograde
sexual stereotyping or enlightened difference feminism, depending
on your point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that at the target age, 8 through 13, people tend to
polarize into groups based on gender,'' said Tom McClure, director
of marketing for Playmates Toys. ``The girls talk about the boys,
and the boys talk about the girls.'' Now the playground battle of
the sexes can be waged electronically.
</P>
<P>
   _ BRUCE HEADLAM
</P>
<P>
   Always In Touch
</P>
<P>
   A new program for the ICQ instant message system means users can
run, but they cannot hide. The Signaler, from the Israeli company
NECS, works by sending something like an electronic knock on the
door to a designated computer's modem. Even if the recipient is not
online, a window will open on the screen, signaling that someone is
trying to get in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Only users who download the Signaler software, available at
www.signaler.com, can send and receive the signals. Users can
choose a do-not-disturb mode when they would rather not be
bothered. NECS is offering the service free for a 21-day trial.
After that, users must pay $9.95 per month. The company is
developing the software for use with other programs, like Yahoo
Pager and AOL Instant Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Plugged-in Gardeners
</P>
<P>
   Which of the following doesn't belong: a mouse, a modem and a
gardening hoe? It's a trick question: According to a new survey of
Internet users, they all belong.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings of the survey, compiled by Nielsen Media
Research, is that there is an unusually large overlap between the
people who use the Internet and the people who watch Home and
Garden TV. The survey found that men who use the Internet named
these as their top five commonly watched networks: Comedy Central,
Home and Garden, Fox News, MSNBC and MTV. Women in the same
category watched MTV, Home and Garden, CNN Headline News, the Movie
Channel and Comedy Central.
</P>
