<SLUG> BC-COURT-MEDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT QUESTIONS MEDIA INVOLVEMENT IN POLICE RAIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court questioned Wednesday whether
reporters and photographers who accompany police officers on
searches of homes trample on privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the help (to law enforcement) provided here? It is not
merely for entertainment?'' Justice David H. Souter asked during a
lively session on a pair of cases from Maryland and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The debate raised not only questions about whether journalists
can accompany the police on raids and searches, but also how far
live-action television shows, such as the Fox network's ``Cops,''
can go in bringing to the public images of officers arresting and
searching suspected criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why you have to take the news media people into
someone's home ... it sounds like fluff,'' Souter said later.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Cordray, a Grove City, Ohio-lawyer representing
federal agents who allowed a newspaper reporter and photographer to
accompany them during a search of a private residence, argued that
the news media ``ride-alongs'' have been common for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a law forbidding police from taking
reporters with them,'' he told the court.
</P>
<P>
   His argument drew a quick retort from Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor, who asked, ``Ride right into the house?''
</P>
<P>
   In the two cases, the high court must decide whether police
officers who take along reporters, photographers and camera people
to observe and film the execution of a warrant in a private
residence violate the Fourth Amendment guarantee against
unreasonable searches and whether those officers can be sued by the
private citizens involved.
</P>
<P>
   If the court rules media ride-alongs are unconstitutional,
reporters and camera people will be limited to filming and
observing only those arrests and searches that occur in public
places.
</P>
<P>
   In his arguments before the court, Cordray told the justices
that media coverage was essential to ensuring accurate reporting
and raising public knowledge of police procedures.
</P>
<P>
   He also said reporters protect the rights of the individual who
is being arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any mistake made by the police will be caught on camera for
the world to see,'' Cordray said.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington lawyer Richard Willard, who represented a
Maryland couple photographed by the Washington Post in their night
clothes as sheriff's deputies and deputy U.S. marshals
unsuccessfully searched for their fugitive son, said the media
coverage was an ``obvious'' invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only authority police have is to enter the home, (not)
bring along the media on a news-gathering expedition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Willard's arguments were echoed by Los Angeles lawyer Henry
Rossbacher, representing a Montana couple whose ranch was raided by
federal agents accompanied by a Cable News Network camera crew. He
urged the court to penalize the law enforcement officers ``who came
to search for poison (and) brought along the press to search for TV
footage.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the extended session, most of the justices appeared
to side with Willard and Rossbacher. Along with Souter and
O'Connor, Justices Anthony M. Kennedy, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and
Stephen G. Breyer and Antonin Scalia critically questioned the
policy of reporters accompanying the police on searches and
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia asked Cordray, ``Why don't you just ask the person,
`Would you mind if we bring in some cameras?'''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four news organizations have sided with law enforcement
officers in both cases to defend the media's watchdog role.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maryland case, Montgomery County sheriff's deputies and
deputy U.S. Marshals were accompanied by a Washington Post
photographer and reporter when they entered the Rockville home of
Charles and Geraldine Wilson the morning of April 14, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs taken were never published, and the search did
not turn up the couple's grown son, Dominic. At his parents'
request, he surrendered later that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilsons sued the police, claiming their Fourth Amendment
rights had been violated, but lower courts rejected their case.
</P>
<P>
   In the Montana case, about 20 federal agents accompanied by a
CNN camera crew arrived at Paul Berger's sheep and cattle ranch on
March 24, 1993, to search for evidence of eagle poisoning. At a
subsequent trial, Berger was acquitted of all charges except
improper use of a pesticide, a minor offense.
</P>
<P>
   CNN eventually used footage of the raid as part of its coverage
of government efforts to protect endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco ruled
that Berger and his wife could sue the federal authorities who
organized the raid and allowed the television crew to come along.
``The record ... suggests that the government officers planned and
executed the search in a manner designed to enhance its
entertainment, rather than its law-enforcement, value,'' the
appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule on the cases in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
