<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX-PROBE-HNS &LR;      03-24 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY ANTHRAX VACCINATION PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before a skeptical House panel, the Pentagon on
Wednesday defended its program of mandatory anthrax vaccinations
for all troops, saying the shots are safe and effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud of the anthrax vaccination program,'' said Dr.
Sue Bailey, assistant secretary of defense for health affairs. ``It
would be irresponsible if we were not using this vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the Defense Department ``is confident, as is the
Food and Drug Administration, that the FDA-licensed anthrax vaccine
is safe and efficacious (in) immunizing the total force against
anthrax.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, testifying before the House Government Reform
Subcommittee on Human Resources, said exposure to deadly anthrax
bacteria is a major threat to U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 countries, including Iraq, have or are suspected of
having anthrax spores, she said. The disease begins with flu-like
symptoms and within one to six days can result in total organ
failure. Without the vaccine, the mortality rate after exposure is
99 percent, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Surgeon General Charles Roadman told the panel that
although U.S. troops haven't yet been exposed to anthrax, it's
``not a question of whether but when we are exposed to this.''
</P>
<P>
   But the subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., said many servicemen and women are afraid of the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The missing element of the mandatory anthrax vaccine program
is trust,'' he said. Shays added that the use of Agent Orange
during the Vietnam War and illnesses suffered by troops after the
Persian Gulf War have ``made military men and women understandably
distrustful of the Pentagon on medical matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said Wednesday's hearing was the first of many
that he plans to hold on the controversial vaccination program.
</P>
<P>
   Current service members, however, told the panel that many
troops are afraid the vaccine will cause unknown long-term health
effects and some have refused to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Pfc. Stephen Lundbom, stationed at the Marine base at Twentynine
Palms, Calif., said 27 members of his unit initially refused the
vaccinations. All but five ultimately took them after being
threatened with loss of pay, extra duty, demotion and discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Lundbom said that when he first heard of the vaccination
program, he turned to the Internet for information. He said he
found a Web site that said no research had been conducted into
whether the shots cause birth defects, cancer or sterility.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, saying that much of the Internet information is
incorrect, has countered with its own Internet site that discusses
what it calls the ``myths and facts'' about the anthrax vaccine. It
plans to vaccinate 2.4 million active-duty and reserve military
members by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials have reported that about 200 service members
have refused to take the vaccinations. Some have been discharged,
and disciplinary action against the others is pending. Earlier this
week Robert Garner Jr., who served in the Army at Fort Sam Houston
in San Antonio, was demoted from sergeant to private and averted a
court martial by accepting a discharge under ``other than
honorable'' conditions for refusing to take the anthrax vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said the number of defiant service members is small
compared with the 223,000 troops who have received anthrax shots to
date.
</P>
<P>
   Mark S. Zaid, a Washington attorney who has represented service
members facing disciplinary action for refusing to take the shots,
said the numbers don't tell the full story. He said they do not
include people who initially refuse the shots but then change their
minds because they cannot risk losing their military careers or
having their pay and rank cut.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to quell fears among the military about the program,
which went into effect last year, Defense Secretary William Cohen
was recently photographed receiving an anthrax shot.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey and Army Surgeon General Ronald R. Blanck said they are
in the midst of receiving their series of vaccines, which consists
of six shots over an 18-month period and annual booster shots
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pentagon admits that no long-term human tests have
been conducted on the vaccine, Bailey said the department is
unaware of any long-term health effects among people who have been
receiving shots over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved the vaccine in 1970,
and it has been used by livestock workers, veterinarians and
military lab technicians since the mid-1970s. About 150,000 troops
were given the vaccine during the Gulf War in 1990-1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
