<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      03-24 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS AIR STRIKES BUT POLLS SHOW A DIVIDED U.S. PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (EDS: President is scheduled to address nation at 8 p.m. EST)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton appealed Wednesday for public
support for his decision to order air strikes against Yugoslav
forces in the Balkans, warning that a humanitarian ``catastrophe''
loomed without NATO intervention to stem murderous attacks on
civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, ordering the fourth U.S. military attack on a sovereign
nation in seven months, said the rampage of Yugoslav forces across
the Maryland-sized province of Kosovo has spawned 60,000 refugees
on the run in the last five weeks alone to join 200,000 other
predominantly ethnic Albanians who have fled mass executions, arson
and artillery salvos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo's crisis now is full-blown,'' the president declared in
brief remarks at the White House as cruise missiles began raining
down on Yugoslav targets in and near the embattled province.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not act, clearly it will get even worse. Only
firmness now can prevent greater catastrophe later,'' Clinton
added.
</P>
<P>
   British and American forces operating as part of the 19-nation,
U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) led the initial
attacks that included aircraft from a total of 11 nations.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was the first attack staged against a sovereign
nation by the NATO alliance since the Cold War-era alliance was
formed in 1949 to combat threatened Soviet-bloc aggression against
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Six 1950s-era B-52 bombers based in Britain launched more than
three dozen precision-guided cruise missiles against targets in and
near Kosovo. Two U.S. B-2 stealth bombers based at Whiteman Air
Force Base in Missouri dropped laser-guided 2,000 pound bunker
buster bombs in the first combat use of the billion dollar
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Warplanes based at Aviano, in northern Italy, swept across the
Adriatic Sea to strike targets in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warships also fired cruise missiles against targets in
Yugoslavia as well.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said allies resorted to armed force after Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic rejected diplomatic persuasion to end
his year-old military crackdown to crush an independence movement
in the predominantly ethnic Albanian province of two million
people.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants Milosovic to permit an allied
peacekeeping force of 28,000 troops _ including 4,000 American
troops _ to enter the Yugoslav province of Kosovo to enforce a
yet-to-be negotiated cease-fire and political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who drew parallels on Tuesday between the Yugoslov
attacks and Nazi exterminations of civilians in World War II, said
``tens of thousands'' of ethnic Albanian civilians could be driven
from their homes in Kosovo into neighboring Albania and Macedonia,
unless the Yugoslav offensive is halted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the allied onslaught a ``stand against ethnic
violence and atrocity,'' adding: ``It will clearly be much more
costly and dangerous to stop it later than this effort to prevent
it from going further now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the operation was designed to demonstrate the
``seriousness'' of allied opposition to Yugoslav aggression;
dissuade attacks on civilians; and damage Yugoslavia's capacity to
wage war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since last August, Clinton has ordered U.S. forces to attack
Iraq, Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, speaking in London, said the
allies ``must now act'' to quell a year-old civil war that has
claimed the lives of more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, speaking at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, said the allies ``must stop the violence
and bring an end to the humanitarian catastrophe now taking place
in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton canceled a planned three-day trip to Ohio, Nevada and
California that included political fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are deeply divided on the use of military force in
Kosovo, according to a Cable News Network/USA Today survey released
before the raids.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,018 adults questioned in a survey that concluded
Sunday, 46 percent said they favored U.S. participation in a
military operation, if necessary; 43 percent said they opposed U.S.
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were equally divided on whether U.S. national
interests are at stake. Only 42 percent said the United States
``needs to be involved in Kosovo in order to protect its own
interests,'' compared to 50 percent who said the United States need
not be involved.
</P>
<P>
   With the military operation underway, Clinton garnered reluctant
rally-round-the-flag support from some wary Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who had a long-planned
lunch with Clinton at the White House, issued a statement
afterwards that expressed support for troops involved in ``a
complex and delicate situation that involves European stability and
our own nation's security.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert added that he has questions about the long-term strategy
of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who has questioned
Clinton's penchant for launching military operations overseas,
offered support for troops in the operation _ if not for Clinton's
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever our reservations about the president's actions in the
Balkans, let no one doubt that the Congress and the American people
stand united behind our men and women who are bravely heeding the
call of duty there,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a likely GOP presidential candidate,
said he supported the air strikes but said ``everyone wants to know
what Plan B is.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson said ``the time for debate is
over,'' adding: ``The time for prayer has begun.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials denied that Clinton cancelled his
political trip to the West Coast in response to Nicholson's demand
that the president forego a $1 million fund raising trip and remain
at the White House during the operation.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential hopeful John Kasich, a Republican congressman
from Ohio, said he would support the president's decision for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look _ the planes are flying,'' Kasich told reporters, adding
that he hoped the White House was mapping ``what the next step
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said the United States ``diminishes itself'' by becoming
entangled in ``civil wars and ethnic conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said a ``great power has to not only know when to go, but
when not to go'' to war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to brace the American people for the possibility
that U.S. pilots could be shot down _ and killed or captured _
during the second phase of the operation when piloted aircraft are
expected to be used to attack tanks, artillery, anti-aircraft
batteries and concentrations of Yugoslav troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action is not risk free,'' Clinton warned. ``It carries
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said he had ordered additional
search and rescue teams into the region to retrieve any downed
pilots. A Marine Corps team rescued Air Force Capt. Scott O'Grady
in June 1995 after O'Grady evaded capture for six days after his
F-16 fighter was shot down by Bosnian Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-led operation threatened to chill U.S.-Russia
relations. Clinton spoke by telephone with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin about five hours before the attack began but failed to
persuade the Kremlin leader to support the allied air strikes
against a traditional Russian ally in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov abandoned
a planned visit to Washington and turned his U.S.-bound aircraft
around over the North Atlantic to return to Moscow after receiving
a telephone call from Vice President Al Gore that the allies were
preparing to attack targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DECORATING-RELATIONSH     03-24 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECORATING-RELATIONSHIPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUMPY MARRIAGE OF DESIGNER AND CLIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LUCIE YOUNG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty-two months ago, Mark Weinstein bought a
one-bedroom co-op in Manhattan's Chelsea section and asked Lloyd
Schwan to turn it into a colorful repository of playful storage
units and curvaceous 1970s-inspired design. The renovation is still
not complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``When am I going to get my stool?'' Weinstein asked Schwan at a
photo shoot that brought the sparring partners together. ``You are
just trying to humiliate me in front of all these people,'' Schwan
shot back.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein, 40, produces and promotes music videos for clients
like Janet Jackson and Busta Rhymes. Schwan, 43, is renowned for
curling, elastic, often cartoony pieces of furniture that artfully
blend multiple colors _ sometimes, 117 of them. The resulting
pieces can cost $3,000 to $15,000, and clients for his interiors
are usually creative types like Jenette Kahn, president of DC
Comics and Mad magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Like a marriage, the relationship between Schwan and Weinstein
went through phases. There was the honeymoon period, when promises
were made. (Schwan's intricate design for Weinstein's
600-square-foot apartment would be as tightly functional as a
ship's cabin, he said, and done in just three months.) The outlook
seemed rosy.
</P>
<P>
   This was followed by a period of intense disillusionment, when
nothing seemed to be turning out right. ``It's like scenes from the
movie `The Money Pit,''' Weinstein said. Battles ensued. ``You
can't be afraid to insult each other and get down and
mud-wrestle,'' he added. Eventually, they settled into a routine
that alternated between bickering and mutual admiration. Think Tom
and Jerry. Or Fred and Ethel. Or Felix and Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the project, designer and client worked in harmony.
Schwan's first drawings for the apartment mirrored Weinstein's
fantasy of having a space with a '70s vibe (the period when he was
coming of age, he said), a seating arrangement that fitted together
like a puzzle and lots and lots of storage for his 1,000 CDs and
pop videos and for his clothes. Weinstein didn't want to pay more
than $75,000, although Schwan said the budget ultimately escalated
to around $100,000. The difference included a desk fashioned out of
five types of fake wood.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation was extensive. When Weinstein bought the space,
it was painted baby blue and full of doors, Schwan said. The
designer stripped the interior down to the floorboards and then
rebuilt it. He punched out rounded doorways and a giant porthole
window to connect the living room and kitchen. In the bedroom, he
built in a wall of seemingly invisible closets and invisible
drawers for Weinstein's exuberant collection of hip-hop clothes. He
turned dreary kitchen cabinets into an arty assemblage of
mint-colored boxes of different sizes and depths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to feel like the hippest junior suite on the
planet,'' Schwan said.
</P>
<P>
   The delicate window treatments, linen squares hung off simple
drape hooks, are a surprise. Schwan developed that notion during
three months when he lived in the apartment to pick up its aura.
Weinstein was concerned that Schwan would stay on, especially when
the apartment came together. ``I had to phone and say, `Are you out
yet?'''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein holds informal business meetings in the apartment. ``I
think the people in my business appreciate something that is a
little fun and different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As in many other embattled relationships, Schwan and Weinstein
have a history. Eleven years ago, Weinstein, on a friend's advice,
commissioned Schwan and his former partner, Lyn Godley, to design
an elaborate media cabinet for Weinstein's previous apartment. The
result was not a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all standing there shaking as we put it together,''
Schwan said. ``None of the stereo stuff fitted in the shelves.''
But because the concept was so exciting (even if the stereo didn't
fit), the designers were asked to do other work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece looked so great and spectacular, I decided the rest
of the apartment was wrong and had to be redone,'' Weinstein said.
He gave Schwan and Ms. Godley the commission of a lifetime: 15 new
pieces of furniture for the apartment and a wood-tile floor that
Weinstein described as ``like a crazy game of Twister.''
</P>
<P>
   When Weinstein moved on, he sold almost everything. It was time
for a change, he said, but he wanted Schwan to work with him again.
</P>
<P>
   One conflict in the new apartment arose over the art, which
Schwan installed uninvited. Weinstein rolled his eyes at the
memory. What Schwan calls paintings are strips of plastic laminate
colored in dull '70s shades of blue, green, yellow and orange or
made to look like pieces of wood grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should someone mind if you put art on their walls?''
Schwan said, running a bony hand through his blond hair. He termed
the abstract pieces ``family portraits,'' a description that made
Weinstein snort in derision.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a way of getting revenge, Weinstein keeps his
grandmother's Oriental gilt, orange and blue tea set on a shelf in
the totem-pole-style living room cabinets that Schwan designed. ``I
know it annoys him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few more hiccups in the new apartment. A love
seat looked all wrong. (Schwan paid for that, Weinstein said,
because it ended up nothing like the drawing.) Wood floors had to
be refinished twice. (They both shared that cost, Weinstein said.)
Despite such problems, they can both laugh over the time Schwan
accidentally wired the television to a dimmer switch and blew it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Schwan said that snags are inevitable when clients have to deal
with original designs. Schwan, by the way, has developed a line of
furniture for Box Design in Sweden based on Weinstein's supposedly
unique bedroom floating shelves and living room media cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   But Weinstein remains devoted to working with a designer on an
apartment. ``You focus your money toward a maximum impact,'' he
said. He believes that Schwan's work has increased the value of his
apartment. ``I think I can realize a profit of $50,000 over and
above the cost of the apartment and of the structural renovation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he has come around to the idea that the design process
is never ending. ``Now things are needing to be adjusted and
redone,'' he complained, but with a note of relish in his voice.
The two began conspiratorially discussing improvements to
Weinstein's nearby 1,200-square-foot offices, which Schwan began
working on last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is he wanted me to do it in two weeks and on no
budget,'' Schwan announced. Weinstein sighed.
</P>
<P>
   The client in this case has come to realize that originality
comes at a price. ``Sometimes it's a comedy, but you live through
it because it doesn't matter if it's Lloyd or some other designer _
you are always going to have problems,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end justifies the bumpy route.'' he added, ``And the
occasional wrestling bouts. I hired Lloyd for his vision and his
ability to excite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
