<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A late season storm will lash southern California on Thursday as
a potent jet stream disturbance moves ashore from the Pacific
Ocean. Intermittent showers will douse the coast and interior
foothills while isolated thunderstorms erupt in the afternoon as a
pocket of unusually cold air arrives aloft at altitudes near 10,000
feet. As the moist air impinges the interior mountains, it will
further moisten and cool, setting the stage for accumulating snow
in the upper reaches of the San Gabriel, San Bernadino and southern
Sierra mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and isolated thunderstorms will also surround
a slow-moving front stretched from eastern Texas to the South
Carolina coast. Farther south, warm and generally sunny conditions
will cover Florida. It will also be more humid than recent days
across the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   An expansive ridge of high pressure will spread over the upper
Middle West and Northeast Thursday. Sinking currents of air
associated with the high will promote abundant sunshine over the
region. A weak jet disturbance, however, will bring a few clouds to
the northern and eastern Great Lakes as well as interior New
England. Meanwhile, the clockwise circulation around the high
pressure will draw increasingly warm air north into the high Plains
and Front Range of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to mostly cloudy skies will cover the Pacific Northwest
with spotty showers expected west of the Cascade Mountains.
Steadier rain will arrive tonight in western Washington as a cold
sweeps through the region. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Weather Spotters Network &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many National Weather Service offices are currently sponsoring
severe weather awareness weeks to prepare for arrival of
thunderstorm season. While modern technology has increased the
ability of meteorologists to observe and predict severe
thunderstorms and tornadoes, the weather service maintains a
network of citizens to watch for developing severe storms. These
so-called ``weather spotters'' spend hours learning the important
characteristics that distinguish developing severe storms from
otherwise harmless cloud formations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
