<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning four pages of coverage
on KOSOVO for the paper of Thursday, March 25. These stories are
scheduled to move tonight in The New York Times News Service
report, in the ``i'' news file. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ NATO launches airstrikes on Yugoslavia
to punish its leader for refusing to make peace in the southern
Serbian province. Detonations go off in Pristina, lighting the
hills over the darkened Kosovo capital; in Belgrade, witnesses
report eight explosions, some near a military airport and at least
one near a power plant. Developing. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Washington) _ News analysis: A
consideration of how realistic are Allied goals for resolving the
Kosovo crisis through airstrikes, in the context of similar,
successful Allied bombings in Bosnia. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ A tally of both Yugoslav military
installations, arms and troops, and U.S. and NATO arms and troops.
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton is expected to
address the nation at 8 p.m. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Once again, Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic is gaining short-term political
capital from a policy that, while it may seem self-immolating to
outsiders, plugs into profound feelings of victimization and
historical injustice among Serbs, feelings that animate both rural
farmers and Belgrade sophisticates. The threat of NATO bombing has
solidified support for Milosevic among the young Serb intellectuals
who had formerly opposed him. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ German forces participate in a bombing
on European soil for the first time since World War II. By Roger
Cohen
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Russian media, in a surprising move,
criticized Prime Minister Primakov for placing Russian-Serb
relations above Russian-U.S. relations in abruptly returning home
Tuesday. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ As NATO's bombs and
cruise missiles bring the Balkan wars he initiated to his doorstep,
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic calls on his people to defend
their country ``by all possible means.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Two enormous flashes fill the
sky. Seconds later came the explosions. The first NATO missiles hit
a point south of the city, possibly the airport or one of the
military bases, shortly after 8 p.m. Minutes later the electricity
is cut, pitching the city into blackness. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO gives unusual written
assurances to five countries neighboring Serbia that the alliance
will consider any military strikes against them by Belgrade
``unacceptable.'' Officials say the letters went before Yugoslavia
warned Romania, Albania, Hungary, Bulgaria and Macedonia on Tuesday
night not to support NATO bombing raids or the ethnic Albanian
rebels in Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ At the time when the Clinton
administration has been searching for ways to squeeze the Yugoslav
president, it has relinquished an economic weapon, allowing him to
do business with Saddam Hussein, according to U.N. documents. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS (New York) _ Reaction to the day's events
from Albanians on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS (Undated) _ Reaction to the day's events from
Serbs in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TV (Undated) _ A reporter's notebook assessing media
coverage of the day's events. By Caryn James.
</P>
