<SLUG> BC-BORDER-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES SAY TRADE IS BEING HAMPERED ALONG U.S.-MEXICO BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Business leaders from border cities in the
Southwest complained Wednesday that traffic congestion and
stepped-up efforts to halt drug smuggling and illegal immigration
are hampering trade between Mexico and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has become the United States' second largest trading
partner behind Canada since the passage of the North American Free
Trade Agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement efforts to crack down on drug trafficking
and the lack of adequate infrastructure impede business between the
two countries, the business leaders contend.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Garcia, a San Ysidro, Calif., businessman and president
of the International Chamber of Commerce, complained that U.S. law
enforcement agents routinely hassle legal border crossers from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And Garcia said agents with the Customs Service and Immigration
and Naturalization Service confront thousands of Mexican citizens
who cross legally to spend $3.5 billion each year with U.S.
businesses along the border from California to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Ambassador Jesus Reyes Heroles said NAFTA had changed
``the border concept'' from small towns marking the 2,000-mile
international boundary to an industrial region that encompasses the
cities of Monterrey, Mexico, and San Antonio, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to base our actions on good neighbor principles,''
Reyes Heroles told about 100 business leaders attending the 3rd
annual U.S.-Mexico Border Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work hand-in-hand to find common solutions to the
various challenges that we face,'' Reyes Heroles said.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen attending the conference, sponsored by the
U.S.-Mexico Chamber of Commerce and the El Paso (Texas) Hispanic
Chamber of Commerce, complained that neither country has provided
infrastructure to keep up with increased trade.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Iovino of the Ford Motor Co. said delays on the
U.S.-Mexico border have disrupted shipping and cost U.S. automakers
more than $3 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.S. business executives also complained that Mexican
border officials were charging a duty on more than $50 in goods
purchased in the United States by Mexican citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on the border are having a tough time,'' said Rep. Ciro
D. Rodriguez, D-Texas. ``There is a need for us to look at NAFTA
and individual purchasing power, not just freight of products.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas, said the business conference was
designed to alert members of Congress from outside the border
region to problems facing the Southwest border states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get better and more informed decisions here and in
Mexico City, that will provide us with better support,'' Reyes
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
