<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AFTER THE PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Farmer told me a few years ago that the civil
rights leaders of the 1950s and 1960s made a grave error when they
failed to develop plans to build upon their stunning successes.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer, a co-founder of the Congress of Racial Equality, was one
of the big four civil rights leaders who led a midcentury movement
that changed this nation and influenced much of the world. The
others were Martin Luther King Jr., Roy Wilkins and Whitney Young.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in 1995, Farmer said: ``We did not do any
long-range planning. So we were stuck without a program after the
success of our efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar problem could face the men and women who, by their
protests, have thrown such a brilliant spotlight on the problem of
police misconduct in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the long effort to get someone to address the
pervasive evil of unwarranted police violence and the systematic
violation of civil rights and civil liberties has been successful.
The Police Department is being investigated by the U.S. attorney's
office in Brooklyn, the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan, the
New York state attorney general's office and the U.S. Commission on
Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx district attorney's office is investigating the
shooting of Amadou Diallo, and the case against the officers
accused of attacking Abner Louima is expected to come to trial
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even the normally unyielding Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has been
forced to acknowledge that there is a ``reality'' that underlies
the concerns of the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   But after the investigations are completed and the findings and
recommendations are in, what then? Reforms are coming, no doubt.
But even if they are effective and police misconduct is
substantially reduced, the problem of fighting crime will remain.
And that will require the good faith and mutual cooperation of the
Police Department and the community. It is hard to overstate how
difficult that will be in an atmosphere that is so charged with
mistrust and hostility. The initiative for such an effort will
probably have to come from the very people who are currently
marching, waving placards and offering their wrists up for plastic
handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Protesting is often the easy part. Now is a good time for
protest leaders to heed the lesson of James Farmer and start
planning ways to work with a better-behaved Police Department in a
continued crackdown on crime.
</P>
<P>
   There are people anxious to do this. A few weeks after Diallo
was killed, Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer met in his
office with more than 100 members of the clergy. They came from all
over the borough and represented a wide variety of denominations
and ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Roswell, the spokesman for Ferrer, said: ``The one thing
everybody at the meeting said was: `We could be a resource. But
they're not using us. The police don't even know us. They don't
come and talk to us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Roswell said the clergy members wanted to work with the police
not just in the aftermath of the Diallo shooting, but in general.
</P>
<P>
   There are men and women across the city who feel similarly. One
of the unfortunate responses to the protests has been the repeated
suggestion by Giuliani and others that the people angry over police
misconduct have been critical of the entire department. Just the
opposite is true. Nearly everyone has offered words of praise to
the cops who routinely give the city an honest and brave day's
work. And most would like to help those cops.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer, who was arrested with 140 others outside Police
Headquarters Monday, is no more anti-cop than Giuliani. Rep.
Charles Rangel, when he was arrested last week, said, ``Insulting
the men and women who put their lives on the line daily to protect
our lives serves no positive purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters have already made a valuable contribution in the
fight against police brutality and other forms of misconduct. Their
tougher mission is to help craft a long-term fight against crime
while establishing the basis for permanently improved relations
with the police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
