<HEADER>
A2847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     03-24 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: FOR WINTER AND SUMMER, TIPS ON ADEQUATE ATTIC
VENTILATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good attic ventilation is important because it helps to
dissipate excess heat in the summer, making it easier to cool the
house and lowering energy costs. In the winter, a well-ventilated
attic expels water vapor that would otherwise condense in the
insulation. Proper ventilation also maintains a cold roof in the
winter and prevents the formation of troublesome ice dams.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the value of good attic ventilation has been
recognized only within the last few years, so most homes, even
relatively new ones, may not have good ventilation. Most homeowners
assume that a few vents through the roof will be enough to keep the
attic air circulating, but these may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   To tell if your attic is ventilated properly, first look for
these signs: In the summer, hot air and high temperatures in the
attic are indications that the air is stagnating and the space
needs to be vented. Hold your hand near the vents. You may actually
be able to feel a slight breeze -- an indication that the vents are
pulling air outside.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter, look carefully to see if moisture is condensing
on the framing members or on the insulation. This will happen when
the attic temperature is low and there is little air circulation.
As warm, moist air leaks into the attic from below, the moisture in
the air will condense on the cold framing unless vents draw it to
the outside.
</P>
<P>
   You can also tell if your attic is too warm by looking at the
roof after a snowstorm. A cold roof will have an even coating of
snow from the ridge to the eaves. If the roof is relatively clear
near the ridge but has snow accumulations near the eaves _
conditions that contribute to the formation of ice dams _ the attic
is holding too much heat and needs to be vented.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to evaluate the efficiency of the attic ventilation
system is by calculating the attic area and comparing it to the
vent area. Start by measuring the attic floor then estimate its
area. Next, measure the openings of the vent holes, including
soffit and roof vents. Determine the area of each then add up the
total.
</P>
<P>
   Most building codes require that there should be a minimum of
one square foot of vent opening for every 300 square feet of attic
floor space. This ratio is generally adequate if you have soffit
vents with other vents positioned in the roof at least three feet
above the attic floor. If your attic does not have vapor barriers,
you may need more vents so the ratio is closer to 1 to 150.
</P>
<P>
   Before adding vents to the attic, consider how attic ventilation
actually works. A good ventilation system requires vents near the
roof peak and also vents closer to the eaves. The warm air in the
rooms below the attic rises through the ceiling and mixes with
attic air that has been heated by the sun- baked roof. This hot air
will eventually escape through the top vents to the outside. Cooler
replacement air flows in through the lower vents to help push the
hot air out.
</P>
<P>
   This recycling air flow is generated by the temperature
differences between the peak and eave areas, but other forces help
the process. Wind currents passing over the roof cause a pressure
drop directly above the roof. This draws the hot attic air up
through the vents and it is replaced by cooler air coming in from
the vents below.
</P>
<P>
   There are different types of vents; rarely will one house have
all types. Soffit vents are positioned in the panels on the
underside of the eaves. Roof vents are positioned directly on the
roof. They have a flange that projects through a hole in the roof
into the attic. Turbine vents are another style of roof vent. They
have a rotating turret that harnesses wind action to draw air from
the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge vents are positioned on the roof peak and extend the
length of the roof. They draw air from the attic through slots cut
into the roof sheathing. Gable vents are positioned in the end
walls of a house, near the roof. They offer a good way to increase
cross ventilation in an attic without altering the roof line.
Cupola vents are small louvered structures on the roof peak. In
addition to increasing ventilation, they can add an architectural
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Next week this column will focus on the procedures for
installing the different types of vents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
