<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DISSENT25-COX     03-24 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DISSENT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BROAD DOUBTS SURROUND DECISION TO BOMB SERBS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Domestic opposition to the NATO bombing campaign in
the former Yugoslavia was high as the operation began Wednesday,
with opponents raising a wide range of objections.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Americans rally behind the president when he
sends troops into combat, and criticism was muted as the raids
began and Clinton began making his case for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gallup and ABC News polls released this week before the
bombs began falling, nearly half of Americans opposed using force
to help defend the province of Kosovo against Serbian aggression,
while about the same percentage were in favor.
</P>
<P>
   That lukewarm support would be severely tested by American
casualties. The ABC poll of 534 adults found only 37 percent saying
peace in Kosovo would be worth U.S. lives, and 59 percent saying it
would not.
</P>
<P>
   The dissent raises questions about whether the administration
has abandoned the unwritten rule of the post-Vietnam era: that
troops should go to battle only with clear and obtainable
objectives and the overwhelming backing of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The deep doubts about American intervention were reflected in
comments by leading officials and former officials as the Senate
was debating a resolution authorizing U.S. participation in the
strikes. The measure was approved Tuesday night, 58-41.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major objections:
</P>
<P>
   _ The country has no major stake in the conflict. ``My question
is, where is the vital U.S. national interest?'' said Sen. James M.
Inhofe, R-Okla. Pointing to civil strife and massacres in countries
such as Sudan, Algeria and Angola, he asked, ``Why is there no
outcry for these millions of people who are being brutally murdered
in other places in the world, but we are all concerned about the
humanitarian problems in Kosovo?''
</P>
<P>
   _ The military action will be ineffective. The United States is
in a ``no-win situation'' against President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia, said retired Army Gen. Brent Scowcroft, who served as
national security adviser during the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can take out his air defense net, no question about that,''
Scowcroft said on CNN. ``We can destroy his air fields. We can
destroy a lot of his military installations.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Scowcroft said, ``we cannot keep him from launching small
unit attacks in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   _ There is no exit strategy. ``Bombing is no real solution
because there is no long-term strategy in place,'' said Sen. Jeff
Bingaman, R-N.M., a member of the Armed Services Committee. ``No
one knows what the next step will be.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The country could be drawn into a long involvement. ``We all
remember the promises made by the administration about Bosnia,''
said Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., who added that the president had sent
peacekeeping troops to that Balkan state in 1995 with a promise
that they would be home in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it has been more than three years, more than $14
billion, and there is no end in sight,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The United States could damage key relationships. Former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger has warned that the bombing will
relations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians have been the historic protectors of Serbia,''
Kissinger told CNN's Crossfire. ``I do not believe that Russia has
the capacity to interpose itself militarily. ... But for this I
think we will pay a political price in relations with Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   _ There is a threat of major escalation. Sen. Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, offered the darkest warnings, telling his Senate
colleagues, ``We're coming close to starting World War III.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
