<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMMATH-MANSIONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE IN PARADISE: THE CHANGING OF THE GUARD IN PALM BEACH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As the Florida sun beats relentlessly on the
perfect palms and spotless thoroughfares, the residents of this
Mediterranean-style mecca are losing their cool over big houses.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, a Palm Beach neighbor of the oil billionaire
David Koch and his wife, Julia, who are gutting a landmark mansion
here (while still renovating the former Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis
apartment on Fifth Avenue) filed suit to block them from enclosing
their upstairs porch. The neighbor charged that the second-story
alteration would block his ocean view.
</P>
<P>
   To many Palm Beach inhabitants, the lawsuit is symbolic of the
bad feelings whipping through the banyan trees, as hundreds of
newcomers from the north, younger than ever before, put down roots
in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this is the town that used to be known as a place rich
people came to to die,'' said David G. Ober, the chairman of
Sotheby's Southeast, who, with his wife, Polly, is rearing two
teen-agers here. ``But if it was true, it's certainly not true
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, they're coming here to build.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report commissioned by the town, architectural
consultants hired to assess the Big House Problem found that zoning
issues in Palm Beach have become ``increasingly fractious and
divisive, causing citizens to turn against one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The town is faced with a paradoxical demand from citizens,''
they wrote. `` `Don't let them build any more big monster houses,
and don't get in my way when I want to add rooms to my own
house.'''
</P>
<P>
   On a trip from tiny Via Vizcaya up winding Lake Trail, the roar
of giant construction projects punctuates every block: rafters are
rising, and concrete mixers are grinding. Piles of sand and
cast-iron pipes dot yards awaiting new turf; pickup trucks and
painters' vans are parked helter-skelter.
</P>
<P>
   In one yard, workers are hoisting two dozen cast-stone columns
topped with Corinthian capitals with sea horses and shells. They
were trucked in, just as columns were shipped in from Italy during
this town's last heyday _ the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   In a town nine miles long and four blocks at its widest, there
are at least 20 houses of more than 10,000 square feet under
construction _ more than at any time since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``This island is sinking from the weight of the concrete,'' said
Judith Green, the author of ``Sometimes Paradise,'' a 1987 novel
based in Palm Beach, who has been coming here since she was 19.
``There are people here playing Monopoly _ building the most
conspicuous house just because they can.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also criticized longtime residents who allowed their
mansions to go to seed and to be replaced by new houses built with
new money. Some people, she said, ``run around screaming: `What's
happened to our island?' '' She added, ``Well, they couldn't keep
the place up, could they?''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest houses, rising on ``estate size'' lots (at least one
and a half acres), are almost indistinguishable from the vintage
villas, and that is the point. They are being built by this
decade's heirs and high-tech millionaires, who want that Palm Beach
look: the carved stone curlicues, the Gothic windows, the atriums
and the archways _ but without the tiny bedrooms, and with walk-in
closets and central air-conditioning. One house being constructed,
under a security guard's watchful eye, has windshield wipers on its
ocean-front windows, to wash off the salt spray every day.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Kochs are spending millions to remodel their
ocean-front mansion (the neighbor's suit was dismissed) and to
restore the ballroom by Maurice Fatio, one of the big four
architects of Palm Beach's heyday (along with Addison Mizner,
Marion Syms Wyeth and John Volk), whose work is the rage among the
new cognoscenti.
</P>
<P>
   A few streets away, Agi Rosos and Jacques Hava _ she runs her
family's chemical company in Chicago from here; he works for the
company _ have moved into what she calls a ``cozy little home'' of
8,000 square feet. She said her husband particularly likes the view
through a series of rooms, to their Picasso on the study wall.
Recently, ensconced in his media room, Hava jacked up the Dolby
digital sound on the latest James Bond movie for a visitor, sending
his wife scurrying. ``Other people have bigger home theaters,'' he
said, ``but I have the best one.'' The house is built of coquina
stone, locally quarried rock that looks as if it had been nibbled
away by sea creatures for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Along Lake Worth, which separates the island from the mainland
city of West Palm Beach, Damon Mezzacappa, a vice chairman of
Lazard Freres &AMP; Co, and his wife, Liz, are building a
12,000-square-foot Venetian-style mansion. Estee Lauder's son
Ronald S. Lauder is building behind her ocean-front house.
</P>
<P>
   In January, James H. Clark, the chairman of the Netscape
Communications Corp., paid $11 million for Il Palmetto, a
magnificent (but decrepit) Fatio-designed mansion. Extensive
renovations are de rigueur. Sydell Miller, the retired chairwoman
of Matrix Essentials, the beauty products company, is building a
37,000-square-foot house of stone, repeatedly cited by townsfolk as
too big, too bold and too austere.
</P>
<P>
   Showing off one house under construction, complete with Gothic
arches and minarets, Jeffrey W. Smith, 44, the Palm Beach architect
who has designed many of the new houses, including the Miller
mansion, stopped in his tracks and surveyed his handiwork. ``This
is fantasy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disneyland tries to do it, but they're doing it out of
plastic,'' he said. ``We're doing it in cast stone and stuccoed
clay tiles.''
</P>
<P>
   lorin thinks we still need &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New homeowners, like Mary and Antony Underwood, are arriving
younger and staying longer. The Underwoods, who emigrated from
England with their two daughters, live here eight months of the
year and run their private tour company from Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 census, the most recent, reports that Palm Beach County
was the second-fastest-growing county in the state. For the first
time in years, the number of births was twice the number of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   To see the changes, take a drive down Royal Palm Way, the main
road from West Palm Beach. The newly built investment banking
headquarters are staffed increasingly by younger men and women who
were recruited by bank executives. At least four private
kindergartens have sprouted in the last five years in Palm Beach,
where there had been only one. On the block-long Via Mizner, there
are three clothing stores, one each for infants, children and
preteens.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Kenneth and Barbara Horowitz typify the new Palm
Beach family. Horowitz, a founder of Cellular One, commutes to New
York two days a week. The couple say they measure the season not in
the old way, by weeks, but in the new way, by the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm Beach is a small town, especially when the snowbirds
leave,'' Mrs. Horowitz said. ``The town employees are exceptionally
considerate, from the garbage collector to the policeman, who ride
their bikes and know our kids by name.'' She paused. ``We spend
most of our time with the other parents, watching our kids play
soccer. I guess you could say we're homebodies.''
</P>
<P>
   They moved from a two-bedroom cottage in Ithaca, N.Y., after
their second child was born. ``I couldn't bear to put on one more
snow suit,'' Mrs. Horowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
