<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Thursday, March 25, and thereafter. The stories will carry the
``f'' financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For
questions about stories, contact David Brady at the Daily News,
(818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   HALLMARK (Rivero) w/art _ The last store at the Sherman Oaks
Galleria is having a hard time saying goodbye. Not that the owners
of Nicole's Hallmark don't want to close. In fact, they say they've
been trying to leave the mall for a year. But now that the
world-famous mall is a week from closing, the card shop owners say
they've been treated poorly by the mall's managers and are sitting
on thousands of dollars worth of merchandise that they can't sell
because there are no customers at the mall anymore.
</P>
<P>
   LASER (Takenouchi) w/art _ A leading international laser-cutting
systems manufacturer opened its newest facility in Valencia
Wednesday, showcasing the kind of cutting-edge technology that has
helped it capture about 20 percent of the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY (Adamson) _ Countrywide Credit Industries is expected to
report today higher earnings for the fourth quarter and year-end
than last year, thanks to 1998's record real estate market. While
expectations are optimistic, it's anyone's guess what the stock
will do after the earnings report comes out.
</P>
