<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMMOTH-MANSIONS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PALM BEACH, Fla.: Mrs. Horowitz said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The couple looked at almost 60 properties before buying a 1931
bungalow covered with bougainvillea on a huge lake-front lot. The
house had structural problems, so they tore it down and hired James
Carmo, a young local architect, to design an 18,000-square-foot
Spanish-style hacienda, with stenciled beams, a winding central
staircase _ and a lawn big enough for soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other kids' parents are renovating a big property _ bigger
than this,'' Mrs. Horowitz said. ``We're all trying to be very low
key.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horowitzes live in the north end of town, overlooking what
is still called Lake Worth, although it has long been opened up to
become part of the Intercoastal Waterway. While they have an
estate-size lot, there are hundreds of other, much smaller
100-by-120-foot lots in the neighborhood that worry town officials
and preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Now, preservationists are trying to change the way new houses
sit on these lots _ not only to make them smaller, but also to make
them more interesting, with the courtyards, well-proportioned
details and lush landscaping found in houses by the town's master
architects. In February, the town council voted to change the
zoning on smaller lots. But the changes, up for final passage on
April 5, are minor _ subtracting a foot and a half from some new
downtown houses and slightly reducing cubic footage for new houses
in the north end.
</P>
<P>
   Still worried about the town's architectural future, officials
and the Preservation Foundation of Palm Beach, a private group,
have met with Urban Design Associates of Pittsburgh, who helped
plan Celebration, the new Disney town in central Florida. The
consultants have proposed a pattern book _ similar to ones of a
century ago, but with examples of what not to build: blocky
mansions with oversize windows and entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Land prices have doubled here in the last five years, creating
what Polly Anne Earl, the executive director of the foundation,
calls ``a divisiveness between neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One wants to introduce a mansion, another wants to sell to a
developer, another may want to keep the old scale of his house,''
she said. Compliance with a pattern book would be voluntary, but
bonuses _ like the chance to build a wider house _ could be granted
to those who follow the recommendations. The town council has
ordered a detailed study, due in two months.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach, most of the great houses have landmark status,
but that does not prevent the gutting of a historic interior. Only
houses more than 50 years old can be landmarks, but there is some
pressure to lower the age requirement to include 30- or 40-year-old
homes, like those by John Volk, who was still designing in the
1950s and 60s. Many people here also believe that large chunks of
the north end and parts of the town center should be protected
historic districts. But currently, Palm Beach does not have
district designations.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the town didn't need them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even five years ago, the architects controlled what was
built,'' said Robert L. Moore, the town's outspoken director of
planning, zoning and building. ``We depended on them to design what
was in context. But now, their clients won't let them. They just
want the biggest house imaginable. And the architects have to go
along with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
