<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING Q&AMP;A: GOOSEBERRIES, BULBS, IVY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing Gooseberries
</P>
<P>
   Q. Several years ago, I bought a gooseberry bush. It has grown
and is now a monster with thorns but no gooseberries. I planted it
on a former compost pile (it was originally sickly), so maybe it is
getting too much nitrogen. What should I do to start it going in
the right direction?
</P>
<P>
   A. You may be right that excess nitrogen in the compost pile may
be promoting vegetative growth at the expense of flowers and fruit.
But there is another possible reason: age. Your gooseberry may
still be a juvenile, not yet ready to flower. If so, time will
provide the cure.
</P>
<P>
   Since your gooseberry is now well, this spring, before it begins
to grow, will be a good time to trim it back and move it from the
compost pile emergency room to a more worthy permanent site with
good air circulation and soil rich in organic material. Full sun is
preferred, but gooseberries, unlike other fruits and berries, will
do fine in partial shade. To keep it a reasonable size and at its
most productive, prune out canes more than three years old.
</P>
<P>
   Gooseberries, a member of the same family as currants (Ribes),
are much more popular in Europe than they are here. Many
gooseberries are highly susceptible to the powdery mildew that is
common in the United States. Breeding for disease resistance seems
to be at odds with great flavor, but there are resistant cultivars
(remember, resistant does not mean immune), like Hinnomakis Yellow,
Hinnomakis Red, Oregon Champion and Achilles, that produce great
fruit, sweet and juicy, not puckery and tough.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans don't realize just how tasty, or how beautiful,
gooseberries can be: light green, red, reddish-purple or golden
yellow. But even the best gooseberries are a risk. They flower so
early that in some years there may not be any bees around, or the
flowers may be killed by a late frost, reducing the harvest,
sometimes to nothing. Still, it's a reasonable price to pay for the
pleasure of fresh gooseberries and of pies, jams and gooseberry
fool.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, the federal government banned gooseberries
and currants because they are the hosts to white pine blister rust,
a devastating disease. The federal ban on gooseberries was lifted
in 1966, but they are still forbidden berries in some states and
counties. Check with your local cooperative extension office to see
if that gooseberry is an outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   A wide variety of gooseberries are available from Oregon Exotics
Rare Fruit Nursery, 1065 Messinger Road, Grants Pass, Ore. 97527,
(541) 846- 7578, catalog $4, and from Southmeadow Fruit Gardens, PO
Box 211, Baroda, Mich. 49101, (616) 422-2411, free price list.
</P>
<P>
   Send in the Bulbs
</P>
<P>
   Q. I must have planted at least 100 bulbs last fall, but, alas,
only a handful are sending up shoots. I was extremely careful to
plant the bulbs at the recommended depth. Is there anything I can
do to make sure I have blooms next season? I'm so disappointed to
miss out on my own daffodils, crocuses and tulips.
</P>
<P>
   A. You are simply a little too anxious for spring's peak. If
you've planted Dutch hybrid crocus (Crocus vernus), the
large-flowered ones like Flower Record, Pickwick and Jeanne d'Arc
commonly found in garden centers in the fall, they will continue to
tease you for a while because they are the last crocuses to bloom.
Earlier-blooming species, like C. chrysanthus (Blue Pearl, Cream
Beauty, Ladykiller, Prins Claus and Zwanenburg Bronze) bloom about
three weeks earlier, and C. tommasinianus (Ruby Giant, Whitewell
Purple and others) can be weeks earlier yet.
</P>
<P>
   Your daffodils and tulips will follow the crocuses, but exactly
when depends on whether they are early-, middle- or late-season
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding your anxiety is the fact that newly planted bulbs of
all types generally bloom two to three weeks later the first year
than they will in years to come. You can use this to your advantage
by planting bulbs every fall to extend the following spring's
blooming period.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy Problem
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have had a hanging ivy plant indoors, in a window that gets
quite a bit of light, for a couple of years. It hasn't really
thrived, but it hasn't died either. This plant produces a sticky
substance that creates a crust on the leaves and also falls onto
everything beneath it, especially when it's hot, but to a certain
degree year-round. My guess is that this is some sort of protective
mechanism, but needless to say, the sticky mess it creates is very
annoying. Is there anything I can do?
</P>
<P>
   A. That sticky mess, called honeydew, is not a protective
mechanism, and it's not even coming from the plant. It is _ how to
be delicate here? _ sap from the ivy that has not been entirely
digested. The culprits are soft brown scale insects, common on many
houseplants. They are quite small, and as adults they form a
flattish, yellow-brown oval, scalelike covering. Look for them on
the undersides of the leaves, along the midrib and on the stems.
They are good at hiding, very nondescript, mostly just sitting
there quietly, so look carefully, using a small magnifying lens.
</P>
<P>
   Juveniles, or crawlers, are even smaller than adults. They move
about, looking for a place to settle down, and are more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? If the ivy is that encrusted, I'd throw it out, buy
another plant, and check it now and then for pests. If you prefer,
crawlers and adults can be killed with insecticidal soap. Apply it
every two to three days, according to the label, until the insects
are gone. Or you can remove them one at a time, on an otherwise
boring evening, with a cotton swab dipped in rubbing alcohol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
