<HEADLINE>
AS BOMBS FALL, MILOSEVIC GETS SUPPORT FROM UNEXPECTED QUARTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS, KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV) 
(wg) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Because he hates what Slobodan Milosevic
has done to Yugoslavia, Milanko Zablacanski, a prominent actor
here, quit his well-paid job with state-controlled television three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Because he wants a democratic way out of his nation's decade-old
cycle of ethnic conflict, gangster economics and deepening poverty,
Zablacanski joined the tens of thousands of Serbs who protested in
the streets of this capital for more than three months in late 1996
and 1997, demanding that Milosevic resign. He was with the noisy
crowds who compared the Serb leader to Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Just before NATO bombed Yugoslavia on Wednesday, however, the
actor said that he was honor bound to support a leader he loathes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to support Milosevic now. All the protests are now
absolutely unimportant because the West is soon to bomb my country.
This will make Milosevic stronger,'' Zablacanski said, echoing the
views of many well-educated and accomplished Serbs who have
struggled for years in an effort to try to end Milosevic's control
of what remains of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it seems, Milosevic is gaining short-term political
capital from a policy that, while it may seem self-immolating to
outsiders, plugs into profound feelings of victimization and
historical injustice among Serbs, feelings that animate both rural
farmers and Belgrade sophisticates.
</P>
<P>
   This nationalist wagon-circling _ a phenomenon that has been
provoked and amplified by shrewd manipulation of state radio and
television _ occurred to a limited degree in the first half of this
decade during wars in the former Yugoslav republics of Croatia and
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a dominant theme throughout most of the last year,
as violence erupted in Kosovo, a province in Yugoslavia that many
Serbs regard as their Jerusalem but where 9 of 10 people are ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   And with Western powers beginning what has been advertised by
the West as a major bombing campaign against military targets
across Serbia, it is happening again, even among Serbs who say they
know that Milosevic has behaved in a way deserving of being bombed.
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind this wagon-circling on behalf of a largely
unloved leader derives from a toxic admixture of prideful Serbian
history and relentlessly misleading propaganda by the
state-controlled electronic press.
</P>
<P>
   As a piece of real estate, Kosovo is fundamentally different in
the minds of many Serbs from both Croatia and Bosnia. Quite unlike
both of those former members of the Yugoslav federation, Kosovo is
a treasured part of Serbian tradition. Obsessive popular attention
is paid in Milosevic's Serbia to a glorious and failed medieval
battle by Serbs in Kosovo against the Ottoman Turks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West has no idea what Kosovo means to the Serbian
people,'' said Zablacanski.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
