<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-2NDTA     03-24 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BELGRADE, Yugoslavia: said Zablacanski. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zablacanski said the presence of NATO troops in Kosovo, even as
peacekeepers, is an unwarranted and unjustified instance of
foreigners interfering in business they do not understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Scottish people wanted to separate from the United
Kingdom, would the West bomb to help Scotland become independent?
Of course not,'' the actor said.
</P>
<P>
   State-controlled television and radio, the only mass media that
most Serbs see or hear on a regular basis, fuel these sentiments
several times a day. Most people here, even many members of the
intelligentsia, do not see the television pictures of Serbian
police and Yugoslav Army forces burning villages in Kosovo that are
routine evening news fare in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The propaganda machine functioned in the same way during the
Bosnian war. Between 1993 and 1995, foreign correspondents who
witnessed the shelling of civilians in Sarajevo by Serbian
artillery would often draw incredulous stares from well-meaning and
well-educated Serbs if they spoke of the bloodshed they witnessed
in the Bosnian capital. People here said then that there must be
some mistake. They said they simply could not believe such
anti-Serb lies.
</P>
<P>
   The violence in Kosovo has been sold in Milosevic's media as a
strong, but measured response to Albanian separatist terrorism. The
NATO bombing, in the same way, has been sold as foreign
intervention by a hugely powerful and arrogant Western powers
against outnumbered but courageous Serbs. Many people in Belgrade,
even those with the highest levels of education, seem to be buying
much of this argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, Milosevic can say after the bombing that he tried,
that he put up a fight,'' said Ivan Vujacic, a former member of the
federal parliament and an outspoken opposition figure. ``The
opposition cannot win in wars or chaos. We have nothing to do. No
where in world has an opposition party, even in a democratic
country, won anything during time of war. There is no way.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's political survival has depended on a seemingly
endless succession of losing fights. While losing wars, he has won
elections that outside observers said were more or less fair. His
political stability, although severely tested by failure in Croatia
and Bosnia, did not begin to weaken him substantially until after
those conflicts ended and international sanctions were eased.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here say it was then, in late 1996, that Serbs had
their first chance to question why state pensions were being paid
late, why the economy was in a free fall, why gangsters were taking
over Belgrade businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a real crisis, it pushes Serbia into an
existential debate,'' said Ivan Vejvoda, executive director of the
Fund for an Open Society, a pro-democracy group backed by the
financier George Soros that supports independent news media.
``People will then ignore the crumbling city and the lack of money.
Milosevic knows that. He is scared of normal economics. That is why
he is a crisis-monger.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trouble triggered by a sustained bombing of the Yugoslav
military machine, however, is likely to be substantially more
destabilizing for Milosevic than wars in distant republics,
according to some opposition figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the very short-term, the bombing will make him stronger,
but after a couple of weeks I believe that there will some kind of
anarchy and military forces in Serbia could split,'' said Zoram
Osdojic, a political analyst and former director of an opposition
television station in Belgrade that has been taken over by the
Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   During daylight hours on Wednesday this city seemed numb in
anticipation of NATO bombing. Serbs who said the only honorable
choice was to support Milosevic sounded miserable in their
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I have to do now?'' said Zablacanski, the actor.
He was scouring Belgrade on a shopping mission in anticipation of
the bombing. ``I have to go somewhere and buy some condensed milk
for my two sons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
