<HEADER>
A2862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-SECRETS-ART-2TA     03-24 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-SECRETS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAMES ARE WORTH AT LEAST 500 WORDS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A picture frame, usually the final fillip, the last deft
gesture, is many things to many people.
</P>
<P>
   Degas called the frame the reward for the artist. Picasso and
Matisse shopped flea markets for frames, paid the equivalent of $5
for 17th- and 18th-century gilded frames, then made paintings to
 &UR; fit &LR;  the frames. Monet, too, liked to see his paintings in
18th-century French frames. ``It meant that people could afford the
frames,'' said Laurence Kanter, curator of the Robert Lehman
Collection at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 20th century, Marsden Hartley and John Marin, who
had little money, bought simple wood frames and painted them to
match their paintings, said Eli Wilner, a custom framer in New
York. In the mid 1950s, some Abstract Expressionists chose a
no-frame look, and in the '70s, thin frames, either metal or wood,
were popular.
</P>
<P>
   Framing a picture can be daunting. There is the wealth of
materials _ the rosy warmth of gilt, the gleam of silver, the charm
of carved wood. Colors are infinite, too, as are prices. But
choosing a frame for an Old Master, a vintage family photo, a quilt
or a snapshot taken yesterday, is really an exercise in visual
thinking. And although framers and curators insist that there are
no rules, the experts can suggest ways to think about framing an
object.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of a frame,'' wrote Nicholas Penny, Clore curator
of Renaissance painting at the National Gallery in London and
author of ``Frames'' (National Gallery Publications, 1997), is to
make a proper impression even when the picture is not looked at
``but simply `taken in' with the silk of a lampshade, the rosewood
of a piano and the porcelain of a teacup.'' A frame has its own
presence _ opulent or unadorned, showy or subtle. Think of it as
the bridge between the art and the interior of the home.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when a frame was not a subject for discussion:
it was part and parcel of a painting. Until the 15th century,
artists painted on plaster, stone or wood, where the frame was
integral to the work. When an artist painted on a wood panel, the
frame was attached to the panel, and the entire panel was given to
the artist. In the 15th century, artists began to paint on canvas,
and the frame became detached.
</P>
<P>
   Because frames are so often a matter of fashion, it is a fallacy
to assume that a painting should be matched to a frame of the same
era. Listen to Kanter describe an imagined journey of a Titian
across three centuries: ``If King Philip IV of Spain had it, he put
it in a Spanish frame. If 50 years later, it went to England, it
went into an English frame, and if the Englishman had to sell it to
pay off his debts and sold it to an American millionaire, he'd put
it into a 18th-century French frame.'' Matching a painting with a
period frame is strictly a modern idea, he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes an artist offers framing clues. ``If an artist wants a
particular look _ a steel frame or a width of mat _ you go with
it,'' said Peter Perez, the conservation framer at the Museum of
Modern Art in New York. For a 1997 show at the Staley-Wise Gallery
in New York, David LaChapelle exhibited color photographs of models
in intricately designed, fantastical sets. The narrow wood frames,
painted brilliant shades of pink, red and green, were equally high
voltage. For a show at the gallery in November, his sets will be
simpler, and he has chosen understated chrome frames.
</P>
<P>
   When the artist's intent is unknown or impossible (or too
expensive) to realize, the art, by itself, will begin to speak to
the framer. Consider posters, for example. Perez often uses
aluminum frames, cool and minimal, for new posters, and wood frames
for 19th-century ones. For older posters, welded aluminum is too
shiny, too stark a contrast to paper that has darkened over a
century. For architectural renderings, he would use aluminum for
the drawings of Mies van der Rohe, matching modernism to modernism,
but for Frank Lloyd Wright, whose houses were designed to merge
with nature, he would choose wood.
</P>
<P>
   At J. Pocker &AMP; Son, a New York frame shop whose clients include
interior designers like Keith Irvine and Thomas Fleming, the issue
isn't necessarily the art. ``We talk furniture, furniture,
furniture,'' said firm president Robyn Pocker. ``Empire, Colonial,
Biedermeier.''
</P>
<P>
   If asked to frame a botanical print of a hydrangea for a room
filled with Biedermeier furniture, Ms. Pocker might use bird's-eye
maple veneer with black trim. If the house was Colonial, she might
suggest a blond wood frame.
</P>
<P>
   Once a frame is chosen, there is the question of selecting a
mat, the spacer that separates the art from the frame and from the
glass. ``If moisture gets in under the glass,'' Perez explained,
``art will stick to the glazing, and if the glazing breaks, the
photo is gone.'' A spacer can be nearly invisible, like
1/8-of-an-inch-thick strip of plastic, or it can be prominent, like
a thick, 6-inch-wide paper border. Framers recommend mats of 100
percent rag board made from natural fibers. Acids in chemically
treated paper can leach into artwork and leave brown spots, Ms.
Pocker said.
</P>
<P>
   A mat also gives the art breathing space. Art that goes to the
edge of the frame can look tight and cramped. When a 6-by-6-inch
photograph is surrounded by a 6-inch-wide mat, the photograph
appears to ``float in its own space,'' Ms. Pocker said. If the same
photo was framed with a narrower mat, it might get lost on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But not every picture needs a mat _ and sometimes barely a
frame. At the Museum of Modern Art, Perez stood in front of Roy
Lichtenstein's 10-by-14-foot painting ``Interior With Mobile.'' A
1/2-inch-wide, 3-inch deep, maple L-frame unobtrusively surrounds
it and protects the edges. ``This painting is so big that a strong
frame is superfluous,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   And what about art without the capital A? The gently faded
photograph of grandma and grandpa at their wedding in 1928, the
background sepia toned, the picture frayed at the edges. A baby's
first birthday, the dimpled face smeared with vanilla ice cream and
crumbs of chocolate cake. A three-dimensional object like great
grandma's rosary. A small hand-hooked rug of a horse cavorting in a
meadow.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Malce and Jolie Kelter, antiques dealers who work out of
their house in New York's Greenwich Village, know when an object
needs framing and whether or not to do it professionally (spend
some money) or whimsically (spend a little bit of money). They are
reluctant framers of textiles like rugs and quilts. ``I like quilts
on beds, and I like rugs on floors,'' Malce said. Only when they
are ``very tender,'' as he says _ when it is a matter of wear and
tear _ does he suggest putting textiles on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   If a textile is fragile, it should be given to a professional
framer, who also does restoration. The framer will stitch it onto a
piece of fabric, stretch it on a wood frame, and sometimes insert
it in an acrylic vitrine or box designed to filter ultra-violet
rays and protect the textile from dust. A box gives a
three-dimensional object more presence than if it's just hung
against the wall, Ms. Kelter said.
</P>
<P>
   When a collection is family photographs, scattered across
decades and ranging from sepia-toned pictures to Polaroids, Ms.
Kelter likes to connect them by texture. On her mantelpiece, she
has family photos in antique velvet frames, souvenirs of flea
markets. The velvet is slightly worn, purples fading to lavender,
burgundies to dark pink, but they unify the collection. Sometimes,
she uses large frames whose sheer size or extravagance says, ``Look
at me.'' She framed a portrait of herself by Dan Basen, a New York
artist who died in 1970, in an intricately carved tramp-art
rectangle, all dark and pointy. A collage of a photograph of Rocco
Malce, Malce's son, that incorporates Victorian decoupage is set in
an oval mahogany frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``An elaborate frame gives it good attention,'' Ms. Kelter said.
It is also whimsical. It can give import to a snapshot of Fred, the
family cocker spaniel.
</P>
<P>
   Perez offered a final thought: When you look at a painting, what
is it that you remember?
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be the frame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
