A2866 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEAPONS-HESTON-KAN &LR;      03-24 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEAPONS-HESTON-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Charlton Heston promotes Missouri's concealed-carry proposal  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Actor Charlton Heston flew into Missouri's
two largest cities Tuesday for a whirlwind promotion urging
Missourians to vote yes for a concealed-weapons law, Proposition B,
on April 6.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, president of the National Rifle Association, spoke in
favor of the measure, saying it would support the constitutional
right people have to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at Downtown Airport in front of a sign that read,
``Honest Citizens Deserve the Right,'' Heston began his speech by
quoting Missouri's state motto, which translates from Latin into
``Let the welfare of the people be the supreme law.''
</P>
<P>
   About 450 people waited his arrival, crowding behind a velvet
rope. Like the parting of the Red Sea, the rope split the crowd
down the middle to allow photographers and news crews clear shots
of the man who once played Moses.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd sported Proposition B signs and buttons and
wielded flash and video cameras. At least one woman held a
handwritten sign that read: ``Moses for President.''
</P>
<P>
   Heston's visit was sponsored by the NRA and the Missourians
Against Crime. He made a morning visit to St. Louis before speaking
at Kansas City's Downtown Airport. Also speaking were Wayne
Lapierre, executive vice president of the NRA, and Jim Baker, the
group's legislative affairs executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, in his 70s, walked with measured steps and a slight
stoop. He flashed his movie-star grin and thanked the audience for
being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to deter crime is to allow lawful citizens to
carry handguns,'' he said. ``Right-to-carry creates a climate of
uncertainty. In a world where the wolves can't tell the lions from
the sheep, the entire flock is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The hour-long event brought a show of solidarity from law
officers from nearby Missouri counties who support the bill. After
his speech, Heston stepped down and shook the hands of the two
dozen law officers to his right.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the airport terminal was at least one protester, Col.
Fred Mills, retired superintendent from the Missouri Highway
Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sadly disappointed in this NRA road show, especially when
they're trying to make this into a Second Amendment right,'' he
said. ``Heston is a fine actor, but as a person, I'm disappointed
in his real life role: participating in a multi-million dollar
campaign where he's going around Missouri trying to deceive
Missourians on what this issue is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a narrowly focused issue against carrying guns
into our public places....If Proposition B doesn't pass, it won't
change the United States Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Fitzgerald, spokeswoman for the Safe Schools and Workplaces
Committee, agreed that Heston's arguments exaggerate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA is trying very hard to paint this debate into one
about rights in the Second Amendment,'' she said. ``This is not
about the right to have a gun. No one will lose their gun over
Proposition B. It's about whether we want every Tom, Dick and Harry
to carry weapons into our community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
