<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCORDION-COMPETITOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT SEEKS TITLE OF HOTTEST ACCORDIONIST IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Take a look at Jason Stephen. The hoop
piercing the 21-year-old's upper ear. The dark, rock 'n' roll
sideburns. The spiked, gelled hair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, take a look at his musical instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Piano keys on one side, constellation of white dots on the
other, pleated bellows in between. That's right, an accordion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the University of Missouri-Kansas City history major
hardly looks like a traditional accordionist, Stephen's hipster
image is a big reason he's a finalist for Hottest Accordionist in
America. The contest begins at noon Thursday in Branson, at the
Lawrence Welk Champagne Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much a contest for the past generation of players,
such as The Lawrence Welk Show's own Myron Floren (who will be one
of the judges) as for the next generation. Organizers hope people
like Stephen will appeal to younger music fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showmanship is the key to this contest,'' Stephen explained.
``It won't matter how good you are. It's going to be how you sell
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Stephen can play. Last summer, at the American
Accordionists Association's national competition in Louisiana, he
took first place in three categories.
</P>
<P>
   But his play, as much as his appearance, defies the stereotype
of the player who wanders between tables at an Italian restaurant
or whips up a dandy polka at weddings. For instance, in winning the
contest last summer he played a French jazz piece, variations on
``Dark Eyes'' and a tango.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all `Lady of Spain','' he said. ``I really believe
that Bach sounds better on an accordion than on any other
instrument, but I also like to play hip-hop, swing, rock 'n'
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   He started playing in first grade back in New Hampshire, when
his teacher passed out coupons for free accordion lessons at a
local music studio. At the end of the free month, he convinced his
parents he wanted to continue. By eighth grade, he had started
winning contests. And in high school he earned pizza money by
playing at retirement homes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he takes six hours of accordion classes a semester
at UMKC, which has a national reputation for teaching the
instrument.
</P>
<P>
   And his play has made an impression. Dan Lennon, organizer of
the hottest accordionist contest, says Stephen is the most
classically trained of the finalists. Lennon, brother of the famed
Lennon Sisters, explained: ``There are hundreds of excellent,
talented accordionists in America. Always have been, probably
always will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what we're looking for here is an entertainer. Sure, he
has to be able to play. But he also has to be able to get a crowd
on its feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner will walk away with a trophy topped by a gold
accordion, the chance to play and record at the theater this summer
and a title that Jay Leno has already been making jokes about.
(Jay's line: ``The Lawrence Welk Theatre is searching for the
hottest accordionist on Earth. I hear their main concern is that
the search may never end.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Lennon noted that simply being chosen as one of the five
finalists was an honor. More than 150 players sent videotapes of
their work. Those not chosen ranged from a Northern Alaskan who
used the accordion to accompany his recitation on the meaning of
life to a man who was accompanying the Mexico City symphony
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists include a New York chanteuse, rock 'n'
rollers from New Jersey and California and a Cajun-style player
from Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen, when he's not squeezing sounds out of his black box,
spends his days reading up on ancient Greek siege weapons.
Alexander the Great, he explains, conquered what was then the known
world partly because others weren't ready for his new approaches to
warfare. Stephen has translated that history lesson to his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opening is a secret,'' he said, smiling. ``But you know, if
this goes like I hope _ and I've spent a lot of time thinking about
this _ when I walk onto that stage, people's mouths are going to
drop open, because I'm going to be doing stuff they've never seen,
or dreamed they could see, on an accordion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
