<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COVERT-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     03-24 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREMLINOPHILIA TO KREMLINOPHOBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just who exactly was Jay Lovestone anyway? As Ted Morgan reports
in his fascinating new biography, he was asked that question often
while writing ``A Covert Life: Jay Lovestone, Communist,
Anti-Communist and Spymaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of those few who remembered him,'' Morgan writes, ``fewer
still knew why he was worth remembering: `Boss of the American
Communist Party, wasn't he?' `Expelled by Stalin, as I recall.'
`Started his own party, what were they called, the Lovestoneites?'
`Handled foreign affairs for George Meany in the AF of L.'
`Something to do with the CIA, under the cover of the labor
movement.'''
</P>
<P>
   As Morgan goes on to point out, Lovestone was ``a Zelig-like
figure'' who kept showing up in the most unlikely places. For
instance, that was Lovestone, a teen-ager still named Jacob
Liebstein, who boxed for prize money on Bronx tenement roofs around
1910. That was Lovestone interviewing Stalin for an hour in the
Kremlin in May 1927.
</P>
<P>
   That was Lovestone learning to tie trout flies in the 1950s from
James Jesus Angleton, head of the Central Intelligence Agency's
counterintelligence division, and also making love to Louise Page
Morris, a former Powers model who became the American Mata Hari.
</P>
<P>
   That was Lovestone who gave President John F. Kennedy the line
``I am a Berliner'' in Berlin in June 1963. (Actually, writes
Morgan, he told Kennedy to say ``I too am a Berliner,'' which by
referring to other people would have avoided the double-entendre in
German, ``I am a jelly doughnut,'' but Kennedy couldn't pronounce
the German word for ``too.'') That was Lovestone having lunch with
Daniel Patrick Moynihan at the Century Club in 1976, urging the U.
S. representative at the United Nations to seek the nomination for
senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   If Lovestone resembled Zelig, it was not from a desire to efface
himself but rather because he liked to work behind the scenes. As
Victor Reuther, one of his rivals in the labor movement, said of
him: ``If Jay was invited somewhere, he would come in through the
transom even if the front door was open. He loved to be
conspiratorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, he was contentious, strong-willed and
ideological. ``I may be wrong but I'm never in doubt,'' he liked to
say. That lack of doubt imbued him early in his life with the
Socialist ideas that so many immigrant Russian Jews brought from
their struggle with czarist injustice. Intense study led him to
Communism, whose American party he headed by age 29.
</P>
<P>
   But in challenging Stalin's view that American capitalism was on
the brink of collapse in 1929, he failed to see that whatever
Stalin dictated through the Comintern had little to do with reality
but instead depended on the twists and turns of the battle to
succeed Lenin. Once Lovestone caught on he found himself purged
from the party and out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Stalin's subsequent execution of his rivals and his elimination
during the Spanish Civil War of local groups that stood in the way
of a regime controlled by Moscow completed Lovestone's
disillusionment. He became as devout an anti-Communist as he had
once been a worshiper.
</P>
<P>
   Linking himself to the trade union movement, he got himself
picked by George Meany, the head of the American Federation of
Labor, to run his foreign affairs division. This led to undercover
work for the CIA, where he reported secretly to Angleton. For the
rest of his long career he devoted himself single-mindedly to
fighting Communism's advances throughout the world. In November
1954, Pageant magazine pronounced Lovestone, along with the likes
of J. Edgar Hoover and Monsignor Fulton J. Sheen, one of the top
anti-Communists in America.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, whose previous six books include biographies of W.
Somerset Maugham, Winston Churchill, Franklin D. Roosevelt and
William S. Burroughs, is by turns admiring of and delighted with
his subject. He writes stirringly of Lovestone's career as a
Communist, making especially vivid the complex factional battles he
fought in the 1920s and '30s. He credits Lovestone's campaign for
free trade unions in postwar Germany, France and Italy with having
saved Western Europe from falling under Soviet influence.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter two-thirds of his book, he pauses frequently to
portray some of the more exotic people Lovestone conspired with,
made love to, railed against or outraged. All the while, Hoover's
minions kept investigating him. It took them seven years to grasp
that he was spying against the Communists, not for them.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often Morgan strikes a wrong note. He titles his first
chapter ``The Blond Beast,'' because Lovestone happened to be
flaxen-haired and blue-eyed and was billed when he boxed as ``The
Blond Bum'' or ``The Blond Jew,'' none of which would seem to
justify evoking the figure of the notorious Nazi Reinhard (Blond
Beast) Heydrich.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the death of a CIA figure known as ``the
Grasshopper,'' because he was ``always hopping around the globe,''
Morgan writes a shade callously: ``In 1972, on a British Airways
flight from London to Brussels, he hopped his last. His plane
crashed on takeoff at Heathrow.'' You would never know from reading
``A Covert Life'' that the Bert Wolfe who was Love-stone's early
comrade and later rival is the same Bertram D. Wolfe who wrote the
distinguished account of Lenin, Trotsky and Stalin, ``Three Who
Made a Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``A Covert Life'' remains an enlightening and lively
book. It offers a fresh perspective on the 1930s, making you
realize the degree to which the American Communist movement was a
tool of Stalinism, which, if it hadn't been resisted so vigorously,
might have done some of the murderous damage it succeeded in
working in postwar Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On a lighter note, Morgan makes you realize that if you've ever
had trouble grasping precisely what a Lovestoneite was, there's a
good reason. To judge from this biography, a Lovestoneite was
anything from a revolutionary dedicated to the violent overthrow of
capitalism to a believer in free enterprise as the only true
vehicle for the extension of democracy. But to get a true
understanding of what a Lovestoneite is, you must read ``A Covert
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   `A COVERT LIFE: Jay Lovestone, Communist, Anti-Communist and
Spymaster'
</P>
<P>
   By Ted Morgan
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 402 pages. Random House. $29.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
