<HEADLINE>
READERS BARE THEIR GRIPES OVER NAKED COLUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Who would have thought that a column about seeing a
naked lady at the gym would cause such a stir?
</P>
<P>
   Not me for one, but plenty of people wrote me letters. Many of
them were nice (nearly all written by women), but the rest were
real NASTY (nearly all written by men). While I'm sure most nudity
enthusiasts are nice people, the ones I heard from were a roguish
lot, mean critters with poison tongues and boiling blood. For folks
who don't think twice about unveiling themselves in the wide open,
they sure are uptight when someone else has an opinion about
nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they didn't know it, each scribe with a poison pen
became a contestant in The Cranky Naked Letter Writer Contest,
including Steve and Nancy, who actually wrote me a letter while
nude, and Don, who pathetically attempted to insult me by
insinuating that I was a latent lesbian and THEN quoted
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The letters were examined and scrutinized with several standards
including: General Idiocy; Complete Disregard for the First
Amendment; Level of Creepiness; Demonstration of Raw Aggression;
Number of Times the Panel of Judges _ me, my friends Godfrey and
Jamie, and my mom _ Burst Out Laughing While Reading It; and,
finally, Creativity.
</P>
<P>
   All contestants received the VOODOO Tweety Bird E-Mail Chain
Letter as a gift, which requires that they pass on the VOODOO
Tweety Bird E-Mail Chain Letter to 100 of their closest friends or
ultimately let karma dictate their cranky fate. Now let's move on
to the contest! &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Cranky Naked Letter Writer Contest
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second Runner-Up &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Entry title: ``Please Tell Me That Was Satire.''
</P>
<P>
   Contestant: Capt. William W. Dials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never written to anyone in the news media in my life, but
your piece just got to me. Are you that hung up on nudity? Filthy?
WOW! You need to see some serious professional help if that is how
you feel. Did you happen to note what year in time you are in?
God's creation, the biggest miracle in the world, is beautiful. Man
invented clothes. And you're ashamed of YOUR OWN SEX no less? WOW!
Filthy? You have some clear hang-ups and they run pretty deep. I
caution you to stay away from beaches because the bikini has
evolved to nearly nothing, in case you hadn't noticed, and it may
cause you to have a complete nervous breakdown. Sheesh. This is
1999 for crying out loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Judges' comments: As you know, Captain Bill, as Judge Godfrey
pointed out, after God made us naked, he also made it necessary for
us to crap, and none of the judges wanted to see you do that,
either. As for your proclamation that it is 1999, you are CORRECT!
And, in light of that, the judges sadly bowed their heads when we
realized that in 1999, some people still have to hear the words
``Knock! Knock!'' before they understand something is a joke. WOW!
Wait, wait _ one of the judges just saw another judge's naked calf
and she's having a nervous breakdown, Captain Bill, just like you
said! Are you psychic? Just kidding! OOPS, sorry, we mean, ``Knock!
Knock!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
First Runner-Up
</P>
<P>
   Entry title: ``I Pity Your Husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Contestant: Jack Lundeen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read your article in the Rep this morning and could not help
feeling sorry for you. You have not only lived a very sheltered
life but also one that has led you to endure some horrific
inhibitions. Your Catholic upbringing and slanted ideas from your
mother's point of view are real cause for concern. When you were
going to school, did you never take a shower after gym class or
extracurricular activities? Did you never have youth sleepovers
with your girlfriends in high school?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only pity your husband for what he must have to endure
when it comes to intimacy with you and your ideas about sex. You
should really talk to someone about your feelings before you
embarrass yourself by writing articles like the one I read today.
Maybe you should start writing for the Pope or doing radio work for
the Christian Coalition!
</P>
<P>
   ``Not surprisingly, your e-mail address seems incompatible with
AOL/CompuServe, so I am mailing my comments instead. You need
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Judges' comments: Jack, your paranoia concerning e-mail really
scored points with us, especially in the General Idiocy category.
We wouldn't pick on Laurie's mom if we were you, since she has
nearly 34 years of hand-to-hand, mother-to-child combat experience
under her waistband. Believe us, she'll shut that fresh little
mouth of yours in five seconds flat, and can do it while she's
driving a station wagon (begin ital) and (end ital) wearing
flip-flops. In fact, Laurie's mom mentioned that maybe the letter
writer ``played around too much at his childhood sleepovers. Men do
that. You know, `Mine's bigger than yours,' things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges also wanted to advise you that you asked some very
pointed, personal questions in that letter, questions that you'd be
arrested for if Laurie were under 18. Considering that, you were
the landslide winner in the Creepiness category. Do you know what a
herd of angry Catholics looks like? We have a feeling you're about
to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Grand Prize winner
</P>
<P>
   Entry title: ``Oink! Oink! Pigger!''
</P>
<P>
   Contestant: R. Macejak.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are SICK! It is people like you in the world that make it
a perverted, degenerated place to live! God made our bodies and we
should be PROUD of them. It is man who societally changed people
like you into disgusting pigs. MAN made the human body a sick
vehicle of morbid attraction and abuse and shamefulness, and you
suckered right into that!''
</P>
<P>
   Judges' comments: Are you all right, Mr. Macejak? Take a deep
breath. There was only one comment that seemed appropriate enough
for this entry and that was: ``Lithium.'' Judge Jamie needed
clarification that if Laurie (begin ital) did (end ital) want to
take her clothes off in front of strangers and/or see them naked,
she (begin ital) wouldn't (end ital) be a ``disgusting pig''?
</P>
<P>
   So what if Laurie doesn't want to get naked in front of
strangers? How does that really affect you? Judge Godfrey suggested
that perhaps you once had a relationship with a pig that left you
scarred, hurt and vulnerable. Maybe you can hook up with the two
other naked ``winners'' at a bar, slug back a case of Coors Light
and commit a hate crime on a sweater. You can take turns, pull it
apart, row by row.
</P>
<P>
   All of the judges agreed that you should win the grand prize
because you took time out of your busy workday at IBM (as your
e-mail address indicates) to carefully and creatively compose your
thoughts, and because your letter made one of the judges laugh so
hard she tinkled in her pants.
</P>
<P>
   P.S: Do yourself a favor: Get checked out for an extra Y
chromosome, OK? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by e-mail to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
