<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAPIRO-DANCE-REVIEW-     03-24 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAPIRO-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAPIRO AND SMITH DANCE: WITH WORDS AND SPIRIT, CONJURING UP THE
DEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ You never know what you will get with Shapiro and
Smith Dance, the modern dance troupe headed by the husband-and-wife
team of Danial Shapiro and Joanie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, you know what you will not get. At the opening of the
company's run at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday night it was obvious
again that pure movement and form for its own sake are never its
concern. ``Shtick,'' a new solo for Shapiro, takes on the angst
behind a comedian's grinning exterior, while ``Notes From a
Seance,'' a mock Gothic romance, zeroes in on fake spiritualists.
</P>
<P>
   Both works are quirky and sharp-witted, and for all their
emotional messages, these messages come through best in Shapiro and
Smith's way with movement.
</P>
<P>
   Each piece, even Shapiro's solo, is jointly credited; and when
they get going, they are very good choreographers. The proof comes
easily in a superb quartet danced to Beethoven's ``Moonlight''
Sonata, in the middle of ``Notes.''
</P>
<P>
   With Tadeusz Majewski as a committed pianist, Mathew Janczewski,
Kelly Drummond Cawthon, Wilson Mendieta and Midori Satoh plunged
deeper and deeper into a series of changing relationships that move
in and out of different dimensions as the movement itself changes.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography unwound itself like a huge unfurling rug with
two couples drawn into a group embrace and then pulled apart with
centrifugal power. The idiom is full of light and springy jumps and
rolls to the floor with never a break.
</P>
<P>
   This fluidity comes in part from the choreographers' training
with Alwin Nikolais and Murray Louis. (Both danced in the Louis
company until 1985.) But there is also an eclectic range that
includes the natural rounded look of Isadora Duncan's dances,
exemplified by Ms. Satoh's brilliant performance, and the high
flying leaps and athleticism of the company as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many who came out of formalist training, Ms. Smith and
Shapiro have no trouble telling a story. Whether in these new works
they tell us something we do not know is another matter. But they
have a great gift for making movement shift before our eyes from
one emotional range to another. It is fascinating to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shtick,'' inspired by Borscht Belt comedians, Shapiro is a
cross between Marcel Marceau and a dangling marionette. The solo is
a variation on a familiar theme: the fear behind the public facade
of the star entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   Like Marceau, Shapiro has a mobile face and curly hair, but his
mimetic gestures become incorporated into a twitchy rocking dance,
a collage of movement that matches the word fragments on Scott
Killian's sound score. Happiness is the sound of laughter, and the
solo grows punchier as Henny Youngman's one-liners are delivered on
tape. In all, a penetrating study in agility and fragility.
</P>
<P>
   The theosophist Madame Blavatsky inspired ``Notes From a
Seance,'' which has some of the seriocomic features of Paul
Taylor's ``Night Shade.'' The satire is not always pointed, but in
this tale of gullible seekers of the unknown lies a wider moral
about hypocrisy and human nature.
 &UR;  &LR; The ruling conceit is a fictional letter written by the heroine
portrayed by Susie Bracken to a friend about her life in a
spiritualist commune. Paul Selig, who wrote the text, and Gayton
Scott, the live narrator, have all seen the right movies. Ms. Scott
puts on a hilarious deadpan British accent, and the letter has all
the references to gazebos one could desire.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Scott reads, the words are not illustrated so much as
expanded upon: when she refers to a waltz, men leap in to waltz
music and swing a leg wide behind them. The cast is mainly in
Victorian dressing gowns, and the jokes often work.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith as Madame B. walks on water by standing on a divan
that is pushed along. Madame frowns on sex, but her accomplice, the
Professor, portrayed by Shapiro, has a complex duet with Ms.
Cawthon that leaves them suspiciously entangled. Ms. Bracken is
also attached to him, dangling upside down in a clever duet in
which she remains limp.
</P>
<P>
   John Beasant is the victim of a card-reading scam, and his body
becomes amazingly convex as he registers shock and amazement.
Janczewski's nuanced dancing turns a quivering solo into a suicide
image. When Madame B. ``dematerializes,'' as the text says, the
heroine takes over the new Elysium. The other composers heard live
or on tape were Chopin, Killian, Mischa Levitsky and Villa-Lobos.
Sean Murphy did the lighting. ``Notes'' is scattershot, but it
draws you in as a genuine creative effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
