<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: TOMORROW IS ANOTHER DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To recap the battle over the sequel to the sequel of ``Gone With
the Wind'': when last visited in November, negotiations involving
best-selling novelist Pat Conroy, his agents, two book publishers
and the executors who control the rights to the saga were
concluding after nearly two and a half years of complexity and
fury, the literary equivalent of Sherman's siege of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers, like armies, can get bogged down in the marsh of
detail on the way to great victories. In this quaggy struggle,
Conroy apparently had been the winner, and he certainly emerged as
the only one who displayed any wit and audacity: In the book he
proposed, written from the viewpoint of Rhett Butler, there was
even the terrible possibility that he would kill off Scarlett
O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sadly, Conroy is gone with the wind, so to speak, from this
project, having dropped out after nearly three years of numbing
haggling. ``I went through more negotiations with this `Gone With
the Wind' than the Germans did in World War I with all the clauses
at Versailles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, getting back to the right metaphorical war, it seemed easier
maneuvering Lee to Appomattox Court House than realizing closure on
this deal. Conroy walked from the project, he said, because
Margaret Mitchell's literary executors, who are lawyers, wanted him
to pay a good part of their legal fees. ``They wouldn't tell me
what they were or how much, but it could have been $500,000. They
didn't seem to be serious people,'' he said. ``I wanted to do the
book badly, but they didn't want it badly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing his royalty agreement with the executors, Conroy
said, ``I thought that of every dollar I was going to make on the
book, I was giving 60 cents to a dead woman,'' Mitchell, ``and I
thought that was enough to show my good faith in the project.''
Conroy's advance was to come from the $4.5 million that the estate
would receive from St. Martin's Press for the privilege of
publishing another ``GWTW'' spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Anderson Sr., a lawyer and executor, said ``we agreed on
what was to be charged against receipts from the book before the
royalties were divided.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have thought we wanted him to pay all the attorney's
fees,'' he continued. ``We wanted certain attorney fees off the top
before the royalties were divided.'' A misunderstanding difficult
to conceive.
</P>
<P>
   With Conroy in, St. Martin's was gearing up for a great coup.
With Conroy out, St. Martin's is stuck with one of the trickiest
chores a publisher can face: finding the right author for a likely
blockbuster best seller. Moreover, while no one will confirm it,
several people involved in the negotiations indicated that St.
Martin's had but one more chance to find an acceptable author
before the executors are free to look for a new publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Richardson, president and publisher of St. Martin's trade
division, didn't agree or disagree on any of this. She quite
understandably declined to comment at all, as did the agent for the
executors, Owen Laster of the William Morris Agency.
</P>
<P>
   So this is a crazily unpredictable moment for everybody involved
with Scarlett O'Hara, except Conroy, and the stakes are high. The
first sequel to Mitchell's epic, ``Scarlett'' (Warner Books, 1991)
by Alexandra Ripley, was a huge commercial success. When St.
Martin's acquired the rights for a second sequel from Mitchell's
literary estate, the house planned to have Emma Tennant, its author
of two Jane Austen sequels, write the sequel to Ms. Ripley's book.
</P>
<P>
   But then Conroy said he wanted to do a ``GWTW'' book, and
everyone except his regular publisher, Nan A. Talese/Doubleday,
said ``Wow!'' or the equivalent. That is, until the executors heard
Conroy's ebullient ideas. Now that he has pulled out, St. Martin's
has to find an equally dazzling writer who can produce a good book
and satisfy the estate.
</P>
<P>
   In the end ``this was not a good deal for Pat,'' said Carolyn
Krupp, Conroy's agent. ``The executors were all over him, and he
doesn't respond well to being told what he can write and what not
to write. The executors said that they would be hands-off, but
still they had to read everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Over at Doubleday, where Nan Talese has her own imprint, it was
a jubilee day when Conroy walked. ``Nobody was happier than Nan,''
said one executive. Ms. Talese vehemently did not want her author
doing a highly visible novel for a competitor, particularly a book
that would take several years to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Now Conroy can get back to working on his next book for Ms.
Talese, nonfiction this time, to be titled ``My Losing Season.'' It
will be a chronicle of the 1966-67 basketball season at the
Citadel, where Conroy played point guard on the team. ``I thought
we had a good team, but we had a bad team,'' the author said.
Whatever, he has found and interviewed the coach and his teammates
and will weave all this into a passage-through-life journey.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, while St. Martin's is trying to keep this
project alive as a high-concept literary work, those with a craving
for the subject can satisfy themselves by buying all sorts of
executor-approved ``GWTW'' odds and ends _ books, Scarlett dolls,
``Frankly, My Dear'' baseball caps, T-shirts, a Mammy fan, musical
and nonmusical wristwatches, etc. _ on the Internet through
www.gwtwmemories.com.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the final word can be left to Conroy's agent, Ms. Krupp:
``If the executors want Scarlett to live forever, they should get
Anne Rice to write it. She'd be a perfect choice. Scarlett could be
a vampire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
