<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 Georgians among top philanthropists
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A trio of Georgians are among the 100 most generous
Americans, Worth (April) reports in its third annual listing of
philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   They are media mogul Ted Turner, who ranks 23rd on the list with
total lifetime giving of more than $172 million; Atlanta
conglomerate builder J.B. Fuqua, 46th at more than $85 million; and
Bernard Marcus, chairman of Home Depot, 54th with donations of $72
million.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine doesn't mention Turner's 1997 pledge to donate $1
billion to United Nations causes over a 10-year period. Last year,
Turner's foundation announced it had so far donated $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Billionaire investor George Soros heads the list with charitable
giving of more than $2 billion, Worth says.
</P>
<P>
   As for Microsoft chief Bill Gates and investor Warren Buffett,
who often vie with each other as the richest men in the United
States, Gates ranks 15th with lifetime charity of $196 million,
with Buffett near the end at 90th place with giving of $40
million-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Good ol' boys go North
</P>
<P>
   Stock car racing is no longer the domain of Southern good ol'
boys, but a $2 billion industry quickly finding a national stage,
Fortune (April 12) reports in its cover story.
</P>
<P>
   The Nascar racing organization also may be the hottest marketing
vehicle in sports, with gross sales of more than $1 billion
expected this year for Nascar-sanctioned clothing, die-cast cars
and other race-related products.
</P>
<P>
   Primary sponsors pay from $5 million to $9 million to put their
logos across a car's hood, on the trunk or on the front of the
driver's shirt.
</P>
<P>
   State-of-the-art Nascar racetracks have opened outside the South
in places such as Las Vegas and Los Angeles, with more on the
horizon for Chicago and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Even Donald Trump is scouting the New York City area for a
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   A floor under the market
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (March 29) agrees the Dow Jones industrial average
will close above 10,000, and then some. But the magazine says the
Dow isn't likely to rise as far as fast in the future as it has in
the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is interest rates, which have fallen from as high as
14 percent in the 1980s to current levels just above 5 percent.
That lengthy drop in rates is largely responsible for the bull
market, Business Week says _ but rates can't fall another 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rethinking a merger
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, once synonymous with Wall Street, is now
``looking weary and confused, eclipsed in the marketplace by its
rivals,'' says Forbes (April 5).
</P>
<P>
   The magazine says that's why the New York securities firm is
reconsidering a merger offer from Chase Manhattan Bank _ as a way
to ``regain its glory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
