<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AIRSTRIKES IMMINENT, SERB FORCES PRESS ON AGAINST GUERRILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV) 
(wg) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Two enormous flashes filled the sky
shortly after 8 p.m. on Wednesday. Seconds later came the
explosions as the first NATO missiles struck somewhere south of the
city, possibly the airport, or one of the military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later the electricity went off, pitching the city into
blackness.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bright moon, tracer fire from an antiaircraft gun tore
upward into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   A few lone cars roared through the streets, mostly deserted long
before darkness fell. An hour later, ripples of powerful explosions
resounded far off in the distance. Otherwise, Pristina, the Kosovo
capital, lay dark and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The air raid sirens first sounded over the city just after 1
p.m., as a test apparently, but tensions were raised as people
piled into buses to escape the province. Many of those who stayed
behind prepared for a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers cleaned out the stores of basic supplies of sugar,
flour and candles. Long lines of cars formed at gas stations. Buses
pulled out of town, packed with passengers and belongings, heading
for neighboring Macedonia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Still other people were out walking the streets, soaking up the
warm sunny weather.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bombing began Wednesday, the war being fought
here _ in villages, from the hills, and along the roads _ was
continuing in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   With airstrikes imminent, army and police units seemed to still
be pressing their offensive against the guerrillas in all parts of
Kosovo and stepped up police activity in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy explosions sounded across the northern part of Kosovo as
Serbian forces continued to shell guerrilla positions on either
side of the Cicavica mountain range.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Kosovo, near the main border crossing, the military
was out in force and the village of Gajre, taken by Serbian forces
almost two weeks ago, was on fire, reporters said.
</P>
<P>
   Here, police officers and army soldiers outside a police station
on the road north out of the city suddenly came under fire in the
mid-morning. The police threw themselves to the ground, rolling
behind a fence for cover as soldiers leapt out of their trucks to
take up firing positions.
</P>
<P>
   An officer in a black mask, worn as much to intimidate as to
obscure his identity, pulled his pistol from his belt and ordered
traffic to move away, fast.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of fire fight between the rebels and the Serb forces
has been occurring almost daily, frequently blocking the main road,
as the guerrillas, positioned on the hills, have kept the police
pinned down with bursts of automatic gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents said they expect the airstrikes to precipitate
still more violence. On Wednesday, armed paramilitaries, a new
sight in this city, drove through the streets in a green jeep.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians say they fear police raids, or a wave of
revenge attacks, while Serbs expect the guerrillas to take
advantage of the bombing, to strike in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``By increasing tension in the towns, the KLA would draw away
police and army from the region of Podujevo and Drenica,'' said
Milivoje Mihajlovic, editor-in-chief of Radio Pristina and of the
Serbian Media Center.
</P>
<P>
   The region of Podujevo and Drenica, where some of the heaviest
shelling and fighting has taken place in the recent offensive, hold
some of the heaviest concentrations of Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   The police were probably taking extra measures in the cities to
forestall any attack, Mihajlovic said. He was also sure that the
military would continue its offensive, as intensively as possible
despite the bombing, to keep pressure on the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas were bound to want to strike at the security
forces while those forces were preoccupied and weakened by the
bombing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the army does not reduce the danger of the KLA, the
continuation of the bombing will increase the danger of the KLA,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we somehow have a war between NATO and Yugoslavia, but we
have forgotten that the major issue is the situation with the
KLA,'' Mihajlovic said. ``Are they going to invade the towns? Are
they going to use NATO as an air force?''
</P>
<P>
   Serb fears may be real but whether the guerrillas are ready to
attack the cities in any sort of coordinated action is arguable.
</P>
<P>
   Although some groups appear to be conducting ambushes on police
units in the city, senior commanders say they cannot take the war
to the cities.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The New York Times this week, the general
commander of the KLA, Suleyman Selimi, said the guerrillas'
intentions were purely defensive, and he said they did not want to
target civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA has never killed a child or a civilian, and we are
fighting only their regime,'' he said of the ethnic Serbs in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He, like other commanders, said he wanted NATO troops on the
ground in Kosovo to bring order out of the chaos that most people
in Kosovo think will be the immediate result of the bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDBERG-MUSIC-REVIEW     03-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDBERG-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: ZESTFUL VARIATIONS ON BACH'S `GOLDBERG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ It was some party. You half expected old Bach
himself to show up. After all, Christopher Beach, the director of
the Performing Arts Center at the State University of New York
here, was summoning ghosts: that of Roger Norrington's
``Experience'' weekends on the campus a decade ago and the hoarier
one of the Pepsico Summerfares directed here by his mentor,
Christopher Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The weekendlong ``Exploration of the `Goldberg' Variations,''
attached for whatever reason to Bach's 314th birthday Sunday, had a
refreshing air of spontaneity. In part it had to, because of the
late cancellation of its keynote performer, Rosalyn Tureck, the
noted Bach pianist and harpsichordist, for medical reasons. But it
may also have represented a last gasp of innocence and local color
before the Bach Year to End All Bach Years (probably not),
commemorating the 250th anniversary of the composer's death in
2000, when the Bach industry takes over.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was well set in a preconcert lecture Friday evening by
Bach scholar Christoph Wolff, who located the ``kernel of truth''
in the famous tale of the variations. In Wolff's reading, Bach did
not write the work for the harpsichordist Johann Gottlieb Goldberg,
who was a mere 14 when it was published, to play for the diversion
of his insomniac patron, Count Hermann Carl von Keyserlingk.
Instead, Bach probably presented a copy of the printed score to
Keyserlingk, with whom he stayed when he visited Dresden, and
Goldberg caught up with it after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ms. Tureck, who recently re-recorded the work on piano for
Deutsche Grammophon, was to have played it on harpsichord. John
Gibbons, the fine Boston harpsichordist, took over on little more
than a day's notice. Despite it all, he refused to play safe with
tempos except, perhaps, in the madly trilling 28th Variation, and
not surprisingly, his performance was a little scattered. But it
was also shapely and insightful.
</P>
<P>
   The variations were performed again, on organ by Anthony Newman
and on piano by Garrick Ohlsson, on Sunday evening. Newman's
performance started late, and he was asked to cut it short, so in
addition to skipping a number of sectional repeats, he indulged his
propensity for haste. The resultant blurring, especially in the
29th Variation, gave the performance a soft-edged feel, contrary to
the clean lines one might expect from the organ. The instrument
also gave the folklike strains running throughout the work and
culminating in the ``Quodlibet'' the unfortunate character of a
militant chorale.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlsson, who performed the work just two months ago in New York,
seems already to have cast it in a more personal light. There was
less sheer virtuosity here, but plenty of that in Beethoven's
``Diabelli'' Variations, which he tossed off to open his program.
Instead he seemed inclined to linger and savor, all with delicious
results.
</P>
<P>
   This listener missed a performance of the variations by string
orchestra on Sunday but caught the New York City Ballet performance
of Jerome Robbins' illuminating mix of musical analysis and
interpretation on Saturday. Here, Cameron Grant had the ungrateful
task of playing the work almost complete on piano at tempos often
seemingly not his own, whether uncomfortably fast or slow. He
performed honorably under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Related events on Saturday included Peter Schickele's delightful
presentation of P.D.Q. Bach's ``Goldbrick'' Variations and
discussion of musical humor; a generally fascinating program of
contemporary variations on the ``Goldberg'' theme by Kenneth
Frazelle, Christopher Rouse, Peter Lieberson, John Corigliano,
Richard Danielpour and Schickele, effectively performed by Marcy
Rosen, a cellist, and Diane Walsh, a pianist, and an evening of
typically compelling jazz stylizations of Bach by the elegant
French pianist Jacques Loussier and his superb trio, including
their first rendition of the ``Goldberg'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   But buried in the middle of it all, on Saturday afternoon, was a
little gem of a recital by Bradley Brookshire, a harpsichordist who
more and more appears to be the rising star on the New York
early-music scene. Brookshire played a fascinating series of
variation works leading up to Bach's masterpiece, as well as a few
items from Bach's own ``Art of Fugue.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the familiar _ Rameau's Gavotte and Variations, and
Handel's ``Harmonious Blacksmith'' _ came rare delights by Dietrich
Buxtehude (``La Capricciosa,'' a model for the ``Goldberg''
Variations, it turns out) and Bernardo Storace. Brookshire played
it all with remarkable technical ease and security. New York needs
to hear more of him, soon and often.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping, too, that Beach will expand his explorations into
other areas. But to judge from the way events ran late and pushed
others even later here, his board of directors should present him
with a stopwatch and a calculator as fond mementos of this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-BIBLE-NYT &LR;      03-24 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BIBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HANDWRITTEN BIBLE WITH A NEW PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early eighth century, the Benedictine monks of Wearmouth
and Jarrow in Northumberland, England, copied a monumental Bible,
which they presented to the pope in 716. In 1168, the Benedictines
of San Vito in Pisa created another, paid for by 60 laborers whose
meager donations were dutifully recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at the New York Public Library, an order of
Benedictine monks from Collegeville, Minn., unveiled the first page
of what they call the only handwritten and illuminated Bible to be
commissioned since the advent of the printing press more than 500
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's Abbey, a Benedictine monastery, and its associate,
St. John's University, both in Collegeville, have retained one of
the world's foremost calligraphers, Donald Jackson, to carry out
the project. Jackson, who holds the position of scribe to Her
Majesty Queen Elizabeth's Crown Office at the House of Lords, will
work with a team of artists and theologians to produce 1,150 pages
in seven volumes. The St. John's Bible is expected to be completed
in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Its creators say it will be the first handwritten Bible to
interpret and illustrate Scripture from a contemporary perspective,
reflecting a multicultural world and recent strides in science and
technology. The Bible also will incorporate imagery from Eastern
and Western religious traditions as well as some Native American
cultures in the Minnesota area.
</P>
<P>
   The translation used in the Bible is the New Revised Standard
Version, which employs language inclusive of both sexes. For
example, said Brother Dietrich Reinhart, president of St. John's
University, it prefers ``humanity'' to ``man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bible will be written at Jackson's scriptorium in Monmouth,
Wales, and at his artist-in-residence studio at St. John's. He has
developed a unique lettering for the Bible that will involve using
goose quills and handmade ink on vellum. His concession to modern
technology is his use of a computer to estimate the number of
letters on a page and other layout details.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible's estimated cost is $3 million, to cover the work of
Jackson and his scribes and craftsmen; materials like vellum,
pigments and gold leaf, and the administrative staff. So far,
$900,000 has been raised, Reinhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from specifications for where the illuminations should
lie, Jackson has been given artistic freedom. ``We don't know a
thing other than what the first page looks like,'' Reinhart said,
referring to the frontispiece, which features a menorah depicting
the genealogy of Jesus as portrayed in the Gospel according to
Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   A collector's edition and eventually a shortened facsimile are
planned, Reinhart said. The university also hopes to create a Web
site where pages will be presented as they are completed. The first
volume, ``The Gospels and the Acts of the Apostles,'' is expected
to appear on Christmas Day in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the calligrapher's Sistine Chapel,'' Jackson said in a
telephone interview from Minnesota. ``I realize now this is the
thing I have been preparing for all of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
