<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2892 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTISTS-MUSEUMS-ART-3     03-24 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISTS-MUSEUMS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INDIVIDUAL ARTISTS, MUSEUMS ALL THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 (Eds: Deborah Solomon is the author most recently of ``Utopia
Parkway: The Life and Work of Joseph Cornell.'') 
By DEBORAH SOLOMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I don't know what it says about America that we have
a Yogi Berra Museum &UR;  &LR; but not an Alexander Calder Museum. Maybe
Calder didn't play on the right team. Or maybe the art world needs
better managers.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, plans for a Calder Museum are under way, and they
sound inspired. A cross between an artist's studio and a
presidential library, the museum would bring together some 3,000
artworks and almost as many cardboard boxes packed with personal
papers and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   By now we're so familiar with Calder's light-as-air mobiles that
we tend to take him for granted, but Calder is one of the deities
of American sculpture, and few would deny that his work deserves to
be seen in depth.
</P>
<P>
   Will the museum happen? Alexander S.C. Rower, the artist's
35-year-old grandson and the director of the Calder Foundation, is
having trouble finding a building. He recently made an offer on 2
Columbus Circle, that eccentric porthole-filled edifice owned by
the City of New York, but then so did Donald J. Trump, who wants to
construct a hotel on the site and can offer more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like twisting arms trying to get the city to understand
the benefits of culture,'' Rower said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rower has been flying to Paris to discuss the
museum with French officials, who, he says, keep using adjectives
like ``fantastique'' and suggesting that he relocate to France.
That kind of enthusiasm would help explain why Europe has more than
400 single-artist museums; in this country, there are fewer than
40.
</P>
<P>
   A single-artist museum, as the clunky phrase implies, is a
public institution devoted to the work of one lone artist, and the
tradition has given rise to such universally beloved haunts as the
Musee Picasso in Paris, the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam, the Miro
Foundation in Barcelona and the Edvard Munch Museum in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   And in this country? Government indifference to the arts is an
old story, yet despite the obvious obstacles, artists' museums are
finally gaining some momentum. New York may not want them, but
other cities do.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Norman Rockwell Museum opened in Stockbridge,
Mass., and the building itself, by Robert Stern, bespeaks its
serious ambitions. Since 1994, the Andy Warhol Museum has been
spreading the gospel of pop in the artist's hometown, Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Cy Twombly Gallery brought a note of haute elegance
to Houston. And in 1997, the Georgia O'Keeffe Museum opened amid
fanfare in Santa Fe, N.M., a shrine to America's favorite desert
prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Only a Pollyanna (or a publicist) could claim that all of these
museums have top-rate collections or impressive buildings. They
range widely in quality, with the Warhol Museum standing apart as
the most ambitious of the lot. But together they reflect a mounting
desire to honor American artists, and surely they're not unrelated
to the rise in art-market prices that has turned so many former
Bohemians into favored bank customers.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a lot of money to start your own museum _ and every
artist seems to harbor the fantasy. While writers can gather their
prose in books and composers can rely on CDs, artists have only one
way to bring their work together. As the painter Brice Marden says,
``If you have your own museum, when you end up dead, you're still
in control.'' Will we ever see a Brice Marden Museum? ``Maybe. If I
live to a ripe old age.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, few artists' museums are founded by artists.
Children, grandchildren and fierce widows are gaining expertise in
setting up tax-free foundations and appointing trustees to run
them. Every known _ and less known _ artist qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Chaim Gross Studio Museum in Greenwich Village,
which opened in 1995, or the just-being-built Abraham Rattner
Museum at St. Petersburg Junior College in Florida. Abraham who?
Like so many New York artists of his generation, Rattner
(1893-1978) headed to Paris in the 1920s, breathed the Cubist air
and was converted overnight into a ... not-so-great modernist.
Seeking more information, I looked him up in the famously
definitive 34-volume ``Dictionary of Art,'' only to find no
listing.
</P>
<P>
   Does America need a Rattner museum? On the surface, artists'
museums might sound like monuments of self-advertisement. Big
museums have not been sympathetic to the creation of specialized
ones, which threaten to splinter our culture into a jumble of
vanity fiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge gamble to put your prize possessions in your own
museum,'' says Robert Storr, a curator at the Museum of Modern Art.
``There are certain works that ought to be part of a dialogue, and
it's a pity to have them in a context where they're only another
piece in an artist's biography.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, why should artists allow curators at the
Metropolitan Museum or the Getty or the Art Institute of Chicago to
determine their place in Western art? Curators, traditionally, have
followed taste rather than created it.
</P>
<P>
   Artists' museums are a welcome antidote to the sameness and
smoothness of big museums, which typically link one or two works by
each of hundreds of artists into a suspiciously tidy story, one
that might open in ancient Greece, shift abruptly to Renaissance
Italy and take a detour to Impressionist France before closing (on
a triumphant note) in New York, the current art capital.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet art, to its makers, is not a story. It's a slow, solitary,
often messy process that takes place every day of the week in a
studio where the telephone is probably buried beneath mounds of
paint rags _ as artists' museums remind us. Instead of showing us
one painting in a gold-leaf frame, or one sculpture on a pedestal,
they show us one life. They allow us to see an artist whole; they
reinvest art with the romance and pathos of its creation.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, such institutions are integral to the cultural scene.
To be sure, when Americans go to Paris, they tend to head to the
Louvre and spend half a day wandering its labyrinthine halls. But
there is also the sweetly intimate experience of visiting the
dozens of art shrines one seems to find on every other block.
</P>
<P>
   They include the Musee Rodin, the Musee Delacroix, the Musee
Gustave Moreau and the Brancusi Studio, which reopened in 1997, a
stylish replica of the sculptor's atelier complete with piped-in
strains of his favorite jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Art pilgrims, of course, pride themselves on their sojourns to
museums in the south of France as well. They're out of the way, but
that's the point; by requiring you to travel long distances, they
give you the chance to prove your art devotion anew. Who would deny
that Nice would be far less nice without the presence of museums
devoted to Matisse, Chagall and Dufy, or that Cezanne put
Aix-en-Provence on the map?
</P>
<P>
   In America, by contrast, artist worship remains an alien ritual.
Sure, Americans love art; it's just artists they can't stand. Even
our most celebrated painters and sculptors tend to be viewed by the
public more as weirdos than as shining heroes, perhaps because
their life stories do not include exultant tales of last-second
touchdowns or sold-out concerts at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   It is athletes and rock stars who galvanize the deepest strains
of adulation, which makes one wonder how single-artist museums will
ever find enough support to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Their attendance tends to be on the low side, at least to judge
by last year's turnouts at the Warhol Museum (which drew 63,000
visitors), the Isamu Noguchi Garden Museum (some 25,000 viewers
made the trek across New York's East River to Long Island City), or
the Chinati Foundation in Marfa, Texas, the Minimalist wonderland
founded by the sculptor Donald Judd in the middle of
cattle-ranching country (10,000 visitors).
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Marfa is not easy to reach, but neither is
Memphis, which didn't prevent some 700,000 people from descending
on Graceland last year to commune with the ghost of Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   At least one artist's museum has proved a commercial hit _ and
do I have to add that it's not devoted to an American artist? The
Salvador Dali Museum, in St. Petersburg, Fla., drew some 225,000
visitors last year. It was founded by the Cleveland industrialist
A. Reynolds Morse and his wife, Eleanor, who spent half their lives
amassing Dali's work and the other half trying to give away their
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Museums everywhere turned them down. After reading about the
Morses' plight in a newspaper, officials in St. Petersburg quickly
volunteered a building; the museum opened in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   I visited the place in December and it seemed, well, surreal,
though not in the way Dali used the word. All in all, it feels less
like a museum than a sprawling store _ with five modest galleries
attached. It occupies a former warehouse perched on the edge of a
scenic harbor, and you enter through the gift shop. The day after
Christmas, the aisles were mobbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks just like Macy's!'' Marshall Rousseau, the museum's
director, gleefully exclaimed as he surveyed the jostling crowds. A
two-beat pause. ``Oops. I mean, it looks like the Metropolitan gift
shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in our age of overdeveloped museum stores, the Dali Museum
has no rivals for consumerist chutzpah. Prices start at 50 cents
for little matchboxes bearing reproductions of Dali's work, an odd
choice considering that he was nearly killed when a fire erupted in
his castle in 1984. Pencils, mugs and T-shirts carry a quotation
from Dali in one of four languages: ``The only difference between
myself and a madman is that ... I am not mad!''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he wasn't. One wishes for more madness, more imaginative
wildness, in the art on view here. The collection, which the museum
bills as the largest of Dali's work, contains about 1,700 paintings
and works on paper, including a few gems from the 1930s, when Dali
was still a young Spaniard with a dazzling talent for fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   But mainly we see the bombastic later pictures, the oversize
epics from the 50s like ``The Discovery of America by Columbus,'' a
theme that Dali believed perfectly paralleled his own arrival in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the Dali Museum is not the Prado, but it does represent a
valuable addition to the Florida cultural scene; it's the only
attraction on the west coast of Florida to merit three stars in the
Michelin guide. Besides, the museum was one of the first of its
kind in this country, so it deserves points for being a pioneer. On
the other hand, as I left the museum, I wondered a bit
disconsolately why I had come. I had traveled to Dali country in
search of an authentic art experience. Foolish notion. Instead I
had found just another Florida theme park.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And yet art pilgrims continue to wander, willing to go anywhere
to renew their faith. Information about artists' museums is
exceedingly limited, but there is at least one book on the subject,
``World Directory of Artists' Museums,'' which was compiled by
Selby Whittingham and published in London.
</P>
<P>
   The author claims that Europe remains the capital of artists'
museums, but that the situation here improved dramatically with the
opening in 1994 of the Warhol Museum in Pittsburgh, ``the first
major example of the genre in America.''
</P>
<P>
   I visited the museum when it first opened, and it did seem
impressive. It occupies a designer-name building by Richard
Gluckman and brings together about 5,000 artworks, most of them
Warhol's Warhols, owned by the artist at the time of his death.
Granted, the collection has some gaping holes; it skimps on work
from the early 60s, the pioneering years when Warhol went Pop.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have a first-class ``Marilyn'' painting and can
probably never afford one; nor is there a ``Dick Tracy.''
Nonetheless, the B-plus collection is compensated for by the A-plus
profusion of archival material. In the library, you can pore over
the endless ephemera that Warhol collected, including the ``Time
Capsules,'' 605 cardboard boxes stocked with fan letters and movie
ticket stubs and even a pair of brown shoes once worn by Clark
Gable. And let's not forget the important experience of having an
up-close glimpse at Warhol's fiber wigs.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there's something antiseptic about the museum.
Truth be told, I think of it as the University of Warhol, a
research center filled with young people earnestly taking notes. Of
course, any museum runs the risk of squeezing the vitality out of
art.
</P>
<P>
   Museums, by definition, classify and catalogue objects, and
their taxonomic thrust might seem to go against the manic
inventiveness of art. Yet institutions don't have to feel
institutional. The best artists' museums don't just honor the dead;
they coax a vanished world back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed one shining winter afternoon when I paid a visit
to Renee Gross, a stout, red-cheeked woman of 88, and the widow of
the sculptor Chaim Gross. ``Would you like a snack of crackers and
cream cheese?'' she asked in a thick Russian accent, while leading
me on a spirited tour of the Chaim Gross Studio Museum, which bills
itself as the only single-artist museum in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1995, four years after the artist's death, the museum
occupies a turn-of-the-century, cast-iron building on LaGuardia
Place in Greenwich Village. It's a picturesque place, a sculptor's
atelier preserved down to the last dusty detail _ complete with his
mallets and chisels, his boxes of steel wool and bottles of
benzine.
</P>
<P>
   There are some 300 sculptures in all, the massive heads and
undulating dancers that secured Gross' reputation as a wood carver.
Asked why she started the museum, Mrs. Gross replied without
hesitation, ''It would have pleased Chaim very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, few people know the name Chaim Gross, although framed
photographs hanging in the entranceway attest to a charmed life.
There he is, shaking hands with New York City Mayor Ed Koch or
Golda Meir. There he is, palling around with fellow artists like
Larry Rivers or Louise Nevelson.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph from 1937, taken at an early Gross exhibition,
shows Helen Keller in a floral straw hat, fingering the planes of
one of his sculptures with obvious pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the museum is free, although not many people come
by. ``Some days we get four visitors,'' Mrs. Gross said, ``and some
days we get 40 visitors. Some people ask good questions and some
ask dumb ones. The other day, someone asked me if Chaim had any
mistresses. I said he may have, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Chaim Gross Studio Museum stands as a reminder
that memorable museums don't have to be devoted to the likes of a
Dali or a Warhol. Seeing a minor artist in a personal setting can
be more rewarding than seeing a major artist in an impersonal one.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Chaim Gross Museum attracted only 4,000
visitors last year, to my mind it ranks as a success: it puts you
on intimate terms with art. It strips away the textbook ``isms''
and gives you a renewed respect for one man and the creative
struggle that took place day after day, year after year, inside his
studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chaim's not popular now,'' his widow said. ``I don't
advertise, and unless you advertise you're forgotten. But Chaim
will be back. Anyone who takes the time to look can see he was an
original.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
