<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-WOMNOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke coming out of shadow
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ After pulling off one of the biggest upsets _
if not the biggest _ in women's NCAA Tournament history, Duke got
an unprecedented amount of media coverage Monday for its victory
against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But the questions weren't necessarily related to spoiling the
Lady Volunteers' bid for four consecutive titles. Instead, they
were queried about the reaction from Duke men's players Trajan
Langdon, Shane Battier and Chris Carrawell, who were in Greensboro,
N.C., for the East Region finals and were shown repeatedly during
ESPN's telecast of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reporters asked us, `So what did they say?' `` Duke center
Michele VanGorp said. ``It was disappointing. This is our time,
this is our moment, and that's what they want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp said the players on both teams get along well and are
supportive of each other, as are coaches Gail Goestenkors and Mike
Krzyzewski. But as the first school to send both men's and women's
teams to the Final Four in the same year since Georgia in 1983,
it's probably going to be hard for the media to treat them
separately. Especially with the top-ranked men an overwhelming
favorite to win the NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get overshadowed by them because they have a tradition,''
VanGorp said. ``We're trying to establish one, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once, I would like for it to be about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another game
</P>
<P>
   While the women's basketball world continues to reel from
Tennessee's upset to Duke, Goestenkors doesn't see what all the
fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was 5-4 after losing to Tennessee by 14 points in December,
then embarked on a 16-game winning streak. The team believes that
game gave it the confidence to reverse the score the second time
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's as big as everyone else thinks that it is
across the nation, because we did believe that we could win,'' she
said. ``Our goal was not to beat Tennessee. Our goal was not to get
to the Final Four. Our goal is to win a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a prospect that looked far from reality when Goestenkors
was hired in 1992 after being a longtime assistant at Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils had missed the NCAA Tournament the five years
before her arrival. But by recruiting academically oriented players
_ much as Stanford did to win to national titles in the early 1990s
_ Duke has been in the NCAA Tournament for the past five years and
has been ACC regular-season champion the past two.
</P>
<P>
   No time to enjoy
</P>
<P>
   Despite Krzyzewki's encouragement to take some time and enjoy
her first Final Four trip, Goestenkors was in her Cameron Indoor
Stadium office at 8 a.m. Tuesday breaking down Georgia game film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Take at least this morning and this afternoon to
enjoy this; you really need to appreciate this,''' she said. ``But
this is such a busy day because we leave so early (Wednesday for
San Jose). It's just been a pretty hectic day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
