<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-VELODROME25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kennesaw State eyeing on-campus velodrome
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kennesaw State University officials are investigating
the possibility of building a $3 million velodrome on the Cobb
County campus.
</P>
<P>
   The decision whether to proceed could come within the next two
months, Kennesaw State President Betty Siegel said Wednesday at a
working session attended by 25 people. The bicycle-racing facility
would be financed through private donations, and no university
money would be used. Kennesaw State would donate on-campus land,
valued at $1 million. Construction would cost $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under consideration for the past two years, the project has
obtained a $250,000 matching grant from Jim Kennedy, chairman and
CEO of Cox Enterprises, which owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reached the point where I felt we needed an extra push,''
said Kennedy, a competitive cyclist who has held national and
international age-group records.
</P>
<P>
   The project was conceived by David Weller, a three-time Jamaican
Olympic cyclist who won a bronze medal at the 1980 Games. Weller
founded the Cox Atlanta Velo team, which just finished competing in
California and will race this week in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rich tradition of being involved in cycling at the
grass-roots level,'' Weller said, pointing out that the racing
track also could be used by the public, as well as by cycling
teams.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by Weller, the velodrome would be a multi-sport
complex that also would house a team handball facility on the
infield and a rollerskating track and picnic areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about opportunities that are not so
far-fetched,'' Weller said.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said she supports the project because it also would serve
an educational function.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ash, chairman of the university's Department of Health,
Physical Education and Sports Science, said a physiology lab
already on campus could work with athletes, and sports management
students could serve internships at the velodrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting as an academic endeavor that has
credibility,'' Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
