<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILL-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURYN HILL: WITH A SONG IN HER HEART, A WOMAN OF THE PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lauryn Hill staked out her high-minded aspirations as
she began her set on Tuesday night at the Theater at Madison Square
Garden. From a darkened stage came Bob Marley's ``Redemption
Song,'' about music's promise of freedom and consolation; then she
sang ``His Eye Is on the Sparrow,'' about the certainty of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Reggae and gospel are touchstones for Ms. Hill, who's determined
to pass on positive messages along with a groove. But she doesn't
stop there. She also wants to update the sensuality and
confessional intimacy of smooth 1970s soul and to harness the
street-wise bluntness of hip-hop. For long stretches of her show at
the Theater she managed to do it all.
</P>
<P>
   Her first solo album, ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill''
(Ruffhouse/Columbia), has sold five million copies and won the
Grammy Award for album of the year, making it clear that Ms. Hill
no longer needs the Fugees, the hip-hop group with whom she made
two albums.
</P>
<P>
   As both singer and rapper, she has forged a multilevel pop
persona: smart and vulnerable, affectionate and strong, fervent but
capable of admitting mistakes. She falls for untrustworthy men,
demands more of them and decides to rely on herself. And she
insists, to herself and to performers who would pander to mass
tastes, that ``music is supposed to inspire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill has placed herself in the lineage of visionaries like
Stevie Wonder, Marvin Gaye, Donny Hathaway, Curtis Mayfield,
Maurice White and Prince, musicians whose omnivorous tastes reflect
their unwillingness to accept any arbitrary barriers.
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of gospel preaching, she offers her own
experiences as cautionary tales and hopeful parables while trying
not to set herself above her listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how many awards I get or how many albums I sell,''
she announced on Tuesday night, ``I'm still the same person.'' She
added that she was ``no different'' from her listeners. ``I just
got opportunity, thank God,'' she said, and an organ chord swelled
behind her as if she were in a church pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   Performers obsessed with their own responsibility can turn into
bores, but Ms. Hill knows better. Onstage, she put the music ahead
of the words: vocal phrases melted into cascading melismas while
the band's lush, rolling vamps evolved from quiet-storm romantic
soul to crisply syncopated reggae.
</P>
<P>
   Where Wyclef Jean of the Fugees uses his concerts as an
exhibition of his versatility, trotting out styles one by one, Ms.
Hill treats her music as a pool of kindred African-American (and
Caribbean) ideas from which any strain can float to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Girl talk, American and Jamaican-style raps, sultry crooning,
soulful exhortation and even a hint of jazz scat-singing poured out
of Ms. Hill, while her band followed every fluctuation. She had a
horn section to underscore her reggae leanings, a pair of disk
jockeys and a male backup MC for hip-hop effects and three female
backup singers to deliver gospel-soul responses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill could sound tender or aggressive, husky or airy; she
turned notes into spiraling long melismas or glided coolly through
her melodies. She is a student of pop-soul improvisation, borrowing
vocal lines from Bill Withers, Mavis Staples, Etta James and Aretha
Franklin. But while she openly relies on her musical ancestors, the
character she creates is her own.
</P>
<P>
   For the first third of her show, she was remarkable: confident,
improvisatory, utterly persuasive. Then she stopped trusting her
own material. She disappeared backstage for a 10-minute costume
change while her band dispensed drum and percussion solos (adding
Latin music to the show's palette).
</P>
<P>
   Then she returned with a lengthy, misguided ploy: a battle
between the disk jockeys playing records and the band backing her
in other people's hits, from the Jackson Five's ``I Want You Back''
to Jay-Z's ``Hard Knock Life'' to Bob Marley's ``War.'' But her own
songs had already demonstrated her range, better than the borrowed
songs, and eventually she returned to them.
</P>
<P>
   With the motherly love of ``Zion,'' the admonitions of
``Doo-Wop'' _ warning girls that some men are only after ``that
thing'' _ and the steadfast optimism of ``Everything Is
Everything,'' Ms. Hill sent the grooves from New York to Jamaica
and from the 1950s to the 1990s. As as the music pumped and surged,
she gently insisted that intelligence and fortitude are the best
foundations for a good time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
