<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOESAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-APARTHEID CLERIC SENTENCED TO 6 YEARS FOR EMBEZZLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ A judge on Wednesday sentenced former
anti-apartheid activist Allan Boesak to six years in prison for
stealing hundreds of thousands of dollars donated to help needy
children and educate black voters.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak, 53, was convicted last week on one count of fraud and
three counts of theft. He was found guilty of using money from
foreign donors, including singer Paul Simon, to buy two luxury
homes, a recording studio and other things.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, John Foxcroft, referring to a letter sent by
Archbishop Desmond Tutu in defense of Boesak, acknowledged that the
former cleric had played an important role in ridding South Africa
of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, when it came to a serious crime like theft, ``all
must be treated alike.'' If anything, he added, Boesak's position
made his crimes more egregious.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom here was packed with Boesak's supporters, and
after the sentencing, many questioned whether South Africa's
justice system, heavy with apartheid-era judicial appointments, was
still working with a dual standard.
</P>
<P>
   Boesak's sentencing comes a day after a judge in Pretoria gave a
suspended sentence to a white farmer who shot and killed a
6-month-old black girl about a year ago. The baby was strapped to
the back of an older cousin who was walking across the farmer's
property. The children were relatives of workers who lived on the
farm.
</P>
<P>
   The justice minister has asked for a report on the case.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the sentencing, Boesak appeared to be
fighting back tears, but after being released pending an appeal, he
was defiant. Boesak, who once headed the World Alliance of Reformed
Churches, has consistently denied all the charges, saying they were
the result of a witch hunt by the former apartheid regime. ``My
innocence is not touched in one way or the other by a conviction of
this court,'' he told reporters outside the courtroom. ``The last
word is not spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the farmer's sentence, Boesak said: ``I have not
fought for the murderer of a black child to walk free and for
something like this to happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Boesak's case has gripped this nation, in part because of the
details of his lavish spending and in part because because of the
support he has gotten from President Nelson Mandela, who raised
money for his defense and attacked the prosecution's case. Mandela
eventually apologized. Wednesday, Mandela said he would have no
further comment on the case until the appeals process ended.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, Foxcroft denied an application for an
appeal. But Boesak's lawyer, Mike Maritz, said he would fight the
decision before the appellate court. He has a 21-day window to make
the motion, during which time Boesak can remain free.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing for a suspended sentence, Maritz had said that Boesak
had been punished enough already, noting that he was bankrupt, and
that his career had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But the state prosecutor, G.C. Gerber, asked the court to give
Boesak a sentence at least as tough as the one given to his former
bookkeeper, Freddie Steenkamp, who was convicted of embezzlement
last year and given a six-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Foxcroft agreed that Boesak had already suffered and said that
he took ``no pleasure'' in sentencing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not likely that he will be able to slip into
obscurity,'' the judge said, ``and the stigma will probably follow
him to the end of his days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
