</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL ENDURES GENERAL STRIKE BY PUBLIC EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel shrugged off a general strike Wednesday as
400,000 unionized workers walked off state jobs but failed to halt
most essential public services or to force the government to accept
their wage proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Mail deliveries stopped, passport offices closed, and garbage
trucks remained in garages as the workers conducted a shutdown of
state agencies and a slowdown in government-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But a court order kept skeleton crews running state utilities
and bus and train lines, minimizing economic disruption.
</P>
<P>
   With negotiations with the Finance Ministry indefinitely
postponed after a bitter bargaining session Tuesday, union leaders
have pledged to increase pressure Thursday with further work
stoppages at airports, seaports and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu lashed out at strikers,
accusing them of trying to blackmail the government. Netanyahu
pledged to resist the proposal for an immediate 14 percent salary
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggest that workers go to work,'' said Finance Minister
Meir Sheetrit. ``Anyone who strikes and does not work will not be
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has proposed a 3.85 percent raise, about equal to
the projected inflation rate. The government contends that routine
wage adjustments pushed up median state salaries 4 percent last
year. The workers counter that their last wage increase, in 1997,
was undercut by a higher than expected inflation rate of 8.6
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The strike occurs in a bitter campaign leading up to Election
Day on May 17. Netanyahu said the unions had timed the stoppage for
maximum political effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unthinkable that in a democracy, on the eve of
elections, they should point a gun at the public's head and on
false grounds try to extort money from the public treasury,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The effects on the campaign, however, seem muted. None of the
major candidates for prime minister endorse the stoppage or the
wage proposal. Netanyahu's comments notwithstanding, few
politicians appear to see a tactical advantage in vociferous
strike-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the strike inadvertently underscored the weakness
of an organized labor movement that remains rooted in the
government jobs while high-tech business provides most new
employment and the government is selling state industries.
</P>
<P>
   Bezeq, the national phone company, which is selling controlling
interests to private investors, was hit by wildcat maintenance
walkouts last week to protest planned staff reductions. Wednesday,
Bezeq announced that it would cut its work force further, to 6,500
or less this year, down from 8,300 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As its economic power has declined, the Histadrut labor
federation has become politically marginal. The federation was once
the organizational and ideological backbone of Labor and its
predecessor parties, which for decades ran Israel. But its leader,
Amir Peretz, broke ranks with the party this year and is heading
the parliamentary slate for his own small new Workers' Party.
</P>
<P>
   Labor, meanwhile, is so distanced from its historic union roots
that its campaign posters do not even mention the party's name. The
party leader, Ehud Barak, who has chosen to be identified instead
as the candidate of broader One Israel movement, conspicuously
declined Wednesday to back the unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the strike,'' Barak said, ``it doesn't matter who is right.
What matters is who is suffering, and the public is suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   With schools already closed for the Passover holiday next week,
when other public services are also routinely suspended or
curtailed, the strike seemed more like an early start to a
government vacation than the paralysis that the unions had
advertised. Businesses remained open, and flights resumed on
delayed schedules after a three-hour morning shutdown of Ben-Gurion
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Israelis are inured to national and municipal work
stoppages, which almost monthly disrupt telephone service or school
schedules or welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, strikes have shut airports, universities,
the state water company, the weather service, Social Security
offices and, even, the Labor Ministry. Histadrut itself was the
target of a strike by disgruntled employees, who at one point
blocked Peretz and other officials from entering the federation
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1916EST &QL; 
