<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-NKOREA-NYT &LR;      03-24 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NKOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRUDERS TURN TAIL, AND JAPAN THRILLS TO ECHOES OF ITS OWN ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan called on North Korea on Wednesday to seize and
hand over two ships that set off a crisis Tuesday in the Sea of
Japan, and the government here seemed to exult in its relatively
firm response to the ships' infiltration.
</P>
<P>
   Japan let the two ships escape, apparently into North Korean
waters, Wednesday morning for fear that continued pursuit could
lead to a naval clash with North Korea. But for the first time
since World War II, Japan dispatched destroyers and had them fire
warning shots at intruding vessels, and coast guard patrol boats
fired warning shots for the first time since 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis, which dominated news in Japan, began when routine
monitoring detected unusual radio communications by a ship
approaching the Japanese coast. Coast guard planes and boats sent
to investigate found two ships that bore false markings of Japanese
fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the gunfire and a dozen warning bombs dropped by
Japanese planes, the ships fled to the open sea, and Wednesday
morning Japan gave up the chase when it could no longer protect its
destroyers with air cover. Japanese officials were particularly
concerned when radar detected North Korean aircraft approaching.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has not commented, but Japanese officials seem
convinced that the ships were North Korean naval vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Three theories are making the rounds of Japanese intelligence
analysts: that the ships were doing routine intelligence gathering,
that they were dropping off or picking up agents in Japan, or that
they were smuggling drugs or other contraband into Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has no diplomatic relations with North Korea, but it has
contacted the North Korean mission to the United Nations and the
North Korean Embassy in Beijing to ask for the ships to be
returned. So far, North Korea has not responded.
</P>
<P>
   Sadaaki Numata, the chief Foreign Ministry spokesman, said
Wednesday that the Japanese destroyers could not have gone beyond
warning shots. Japan restricts the use of force to self-defense,
and Numata said that this restriction would permit firing on the
fleeing ships only if they were firing at Japanese ships.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese constitution drafted by Gen. Douglas MacArthur
after World War II states that Japan must ``forever renounce war as
a sovereign right of a nation and the threat or use of force as a
means of settling international disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials seem to be hoping to use the incident to
bolster their case for new military guidelines that would make it
easier to use force or to support U.S. troops in a crisis in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and other officials seemed delighted
with their show of force. The use of destroyers and warning shots
signaled a seriousness that has rarely been seen before.''We
consider that this kind of action is important to demonstrate our
determination to insure our national security,'' Obuchi told
Cabinet ministers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although North Korea has not commented on the two ships, it has
reiterated its view that the real threat to peace in the region
comes from the United States, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. and South Korean warhawks are these days busy with
frequent war exercises under different names aimed at making an
outbreak of war against the North a fait accompli, bringing war
exercises closer to a real war,'' the official North Korean news
agency said Wednesday. It referred to ``the ulterior intention to
expand the U.S. colonial domination and ferocious fascist
repressive rule to the North.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
