<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-PINOCHET-NYT &LR;      03-24 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET ARREST UPHELD, BUT MOST CHARGES ARE DISCARDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also PINOCHET-CHILE; this story was budgeted earlier as
PINOCHET-BRITAIN) 
(bl) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ England's highest court ruled Wednesday that Gen.
Augusto Pinochet must remain in England and face possible
extradition to Spain, but they significantly narrowed the charges
on which the case will turn.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-1 decision, the Law Lords said that the former Chilean
dictator could not be extradited on allegations of crimes committed
before 1988, the year in which torture committed overseas became a
crime punishable in Britain. Almost all of the crimes against
humanity with which the 83-year-old general is charged date from an
earlier period of his 1973 to 1990 rule of Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The Lords also directed British Home Secretary Jack Straw to
reconsider whether he wanted to go forward with the extradition
proceedings now that Pinochet had been found no longer answerable
to the major counts against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of this decision,'' Lord Browne-Wilkinson, the
senior law lord, said, ``is to eliminate the majority of the
charges leveled against Senator Pinochet by the government of Spain
and relied upon as the basis for extraditing him.'' The general had
himself declared a senator for life as a way of immunizing himself
from any prosecution in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition request from Spain that Straw approved in an
``authority to proceed'' decision in December had been predicated
on charges of murder, conspiracy to murder, hostage-taking, torture
and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday night, Straw promised to heed the
court's direction to review his finding ``as swiftly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict's unexpected emphasis on the extradition issue
served to overshadow a significant finding on the principle of law
on which the five-month old Pinochet case first reached the Lords:
the claim of sovereign immunity. All but one of the seven judges
turned down the general's claim that as a former head of state he
was immune from arrest, an almost complete reversal of the original
High Court verdict on the question last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is loud and clear _ head of state immunity does
not grant freedom to commit crimes against humanity and acts of
torture,'' said a spokesman for Amnesty International, a
participant in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But while the general lost that critical legal argument in
Wednesday's verdict, he gained ground in his personal struggle to
leave England and return to Chile. His lawyers Wednesday afternoon
obtained a hearing before the High Court on Monday to seek his
early liberation by emphasizing the point that the lesser charges
do not constitute a substantial enough case to hold him any longer.
</P>
<P>
   In an undramatic and crisply delivered address to the peers
seated along the red leather benches in the ornate Lords' chamber,
Lord Browne-Wilkinson explained the reasoning behind the panel's
decision as the principle of double criminality: ``Nobody can be
extradited to a foreign country unless the conduct alleged against
him constitutes a crime under both the law of the foreign country
and the law of the United Kingdom.'' That changed, he said, when a
new Criminal Justice Act came into force on Sept. 29, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the charges postdating 1988 and therefore still
confronting Pinochet were an isolated charge of torture and certain
other charges covering conspiracy to torture and conspiracy to
commit murder in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Foes and allies of Pinochet who have been angrily facing down
one another since the general's arrest each found validation of
their points of view in Wednesday's decision, and there were
celebrations among both the backers and opponents gathered outside
the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision dispels any doubts,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy
director of Human Rights Watch. ``Not even a self-proclaimed
president like Pinochet can claim immunity after torture or give
himself amnesty for his crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilean Foreign Minister Miguel Alex Schweitzer, who is one of
the general's lawyers, said, ``Compared to what we had before, this
is good.'' Fernando Barros of the Chilean Reconciliation Movement
said, ``It has been confirmed that the Spanish case now has no
substantial basis on which to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters had been hoping for a Lords decision that would have
permitted Pinochet to leave England immediately, but they spoke
confidently of their expectation that he might achieve his goal now
in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now five months old, the Pinochet case is one that has shaken
international law, galvanized human rights and exile groups and
stirred bitter and passionate old antagonisms in Chile and other
countries with recent experiences of dictatorial regimes. It has
brought a host of diplomatic problems for Britain even though the
government has been at pains to say that the detention of Pinochet
has been from the start a police and judicial matter rather than a
political one.
</P>
<P>
   The general has been protesting his arrest in London on Oct. 16,
saying that as a former head of state he has sovereign immunity.
That view was upheld in a unanimous verdict by a three-judge panel
of the High Court on Oct. 28 but reversed in a 3-2 decision of five
Law Lords on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The British police had arrested the general in response to an
application from a Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon, seeking his
extradition to Madrid to stand trial on charges of genocide,
torture and kidnapping in connection with the death or
disappearance of more than 3,000 people in the years after he
seized power in a coup in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon is conducting an investigation into the atrocities
committed during the so-called dirty wars in Latin America in the
1970s, and he exploited Pinochet's presence in London to take his
surprise action based on the mass of evidence he had been
assembling. At the time of his arrest, the general was in a London
clinic recuperating from back surgery and planning his return to
Chile a week later.
</P>
<P>
   After the Law Lords' original decision, Straw validated the
Spanish claim, and the general was obliged to appear in person for
the first time since the highly charged episode began. He sternly
told a bail hearing Dec. 11 that he did not ``recognize any other
court, except in my country, to try me against all the lies of
Spain.'' The magistrate nevertheless continued his house arrest,
prompting predictions that he would be unable to leave England for
at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a development that deeply embarrassed the British
judiciary and led to the 12 days of hearings ending Feb. 4 that
produced Wednesday's new finding, the Lords set aside its earlier
decision because one of the judges who ruled against the general,
Lord Hoffmann, had not disclosed his association with Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in Britain's history that the Lords had
ever reviewed one of their rulings, and the naming of seven Law
Lords instead of the customary five was seen as a measure of the
gravity of the case for Britain and its court system.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet and his wife, Lucia, have been living in a rented
mansion in an exclusive suburb in Surrey south of London since his
hospital release Dec. 1. A Chilean military plane landed at Brize
Norton Royal Air Force on Wednesday morning prepared to ferry him
home. It was the third time since October that a Chilean aircraft
has been idling at the Oxfordshire field on the same mission. Once
again Wednesday, it moved to a side runway and took up a parking
space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
