<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-370&AMP;AD     03-24 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ITALIAN PREMIER CHOSEN TO HEAD EUROPEAN COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Leaders of the European Union on Wednesday appointed
former Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi to take over as
president of the European Union Commission, the powerful
Brussels-based executive body whose top officials resigned in a
corruption scandal last week.
</P>
<P>
   The quick decision, at the start of a summit meeting, was
supposed to signal European cohesion and a determination to give
new impetus to the continent's integration in the city that long
symbolized Europe's division into rival blocs.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Santer of Luxembourg, the 61-year-old president of the
European Commission, and his 19 fellow commissioners quit after a
report by an independent panel of experts found the Union's $100
billion annual budget was mismanaged and said it was ``becoming
difficult to find anyone who has even the slightest sense of
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Commission runs important areas of European policy,
including trade and antitrust matters, and the resignations had
threatened to bring paralysis at a time when the Union is
attempting an ambitious reform of its budget that would open the
way for new members from the former East bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Prodi, a center-left politician who lost the
Italian premiership last summer, should help avert such paralysis.
The European Parliament, which must act on the leaders' decision,
indicated Wednesday that it would back him.
</P>
<P>
   Although Prodi would take office for a five-year term only at
the end of the year, his appointment is expected to clear the air,
allowing the departing Commission to work in a caretaker capacity
until then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nomination is a great demonstration of trust for Italy,''
Prodi said. ``I am delighted for Italy. We must make the machinery
of the Commission work again.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which holds the rotating presidency of the European
Union, has been particularly concerned that the crisis at the
Commission not hold up reforms that would cut its big contribution
to the European budget and open the way for Poland, the Czech
Republic and Hungary to join the Union. Such enlargement is seen by
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder as an important symbol of a
continent-wide integration.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Europe's most virulent divisions _ those that have plagued
the Balkans for much of the last decade _ quickly overshadowed
Prodi's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 15 leaders spent much of the day discussing the
conflict over Kosovo. Although the presence of four neutral nations
prevented explicit backing for NATO air strikes, the European Union
spelled out the reasons for military action.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued before the NATO attacks began said:
``Aggression must not be rewarded. An aggressor must know that he
will have to pay a high price. That is the lesson to be learnt from
the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Making clear that European patience with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic has finally run out, the heads of state said
their action was ``directed against the irresponsible policy of the
Yugoslav leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But neutral Austria, a European Union member, said in a
statement that it would close its airspace to NATO planes striking
Yugoslavia because there was no clear United Nations mandate for
military action.
</P>
<P>
   Several European nations, including Germany and France, have
expressed concern in recent months over what they saw as a need for
a specific mandate from the U.N. Security Council to attack
Yugoslavia. But after long efforts to negotiate a settlement at
peace talks in France, those concerns have been replaced by
indignation at Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO will act for as long as it take for Milosevic to regain
his humanity,'' Schroeder said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a shaky start at the head of a previously untried
coalition of Social Democrats and environmentalist Greens, the
German leader is looking desperately for a success at the two-day
summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He wants an agreement to hold down agricultural spending, which
accounts for close to half of the European budget and chiefly
benefits southern countries including Spain, Italy and France.
Without such an agreement, farm spending would soar when any new
members with large farm sectors, like Poland, join.
</P>
<P>
   Although an outline agreement to hold farm spending to about $44
billion a year was reached this month by agriculture ministers,
France has since expressed reservations. It is far from clear that
an accord will be reached in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said the image of the European Union had suffered from
the corruption at the Commission and would have to be restored by
Prodi. One commissioner, Edith Cresson of France, was shown to have
hired a friend to do spurious scientific work for the Commission at
a cost to European taxpayers of close to $200,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
