a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     03-24 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: FUMING OVER SMOKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, March 26)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being a former smoker, I am, of course, one of the most
militant, obnoxious, uncompromising, jerk-wad, anti-smoking zealots
on the face of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   I have no sympathy whatsoever for the five or six remaining
nicotine addicts who must trudge outside (preferably in a cold
rain) to indulge their habit. If I happen to pass within 30 yards
of their little cell of stink, I make a big production of fanning
the air with my hand and screwing up my face in a look of disgust.
</P>
<P>
   At baseball stadiums, where smoking is prohibited except in
certain areas shared by lepers, Republicans and other social
pariahs, if I see someone's hand so much as brush his or her pack
of Marlboro Lights, I start hollering for the usher, making a sound
much like Donald Sutherland made in ``The Invasion of the Body
Snatchers.''
</P>
<P>
   I laughed when California passed a law outlawing smoking in
bars. Drive 'em into the sea, boys. Make 'em smoke under water.
</P>
<P>
   New York recently passed a law where they can confiscate the
cars of drunken drivers. This seems a little extreme to me.
</P>
<P>
   However, I would have no problem if they passed a law where they
can confiscate the car of someone caught smoking. Maybe follow it
up with a brisk flogging, then make 'em sit in a bar for eight
hours without smoking.
</P>
<P>
   I'm against flag burning, but not for patriotic reasons. It's
the smoke that bothers me.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers whine that they are being singled out for persecution.
This is absolutely true, of course, and totally justified. The
amazing thing is that smokers actually figured out that they are
being persecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Because, let's face it, smokers _ and remember, I used to be one
of them _ are not exactly the sharpest knives in the drawer. Thirty
years of medical research have pretty much proved that you're
better off, health-wise, giving yourself a plutonium enema than
sucking on a Winston 100.
</P>
<P>
   As I recall, there's even some sort of government warning on
every pack of cigarettes, something subtle like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Warning! These things are poisonous! They will kill you! Just
handling the pack could lead to a horrible, agonizing death! We've
had lab rats die of cancer simply by chewing on magazine ads! If
you want to kill yourself, there are better ways. Like a gun or
jumping off a high bridge. And let me tell you another thing, pal.
You still listening? Hello? Anybody home?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to smoke these cigarettes no matter what I tell
you, aren't you? I could tell you these Salems are filled with
gunpowder and the top of your head will blow off the instant you
light up and it wouldn't make a bit of difference, would it? Well,
fine. Go kill yourself; see if I care. I'm warning you, pal. You
light one of these babies around me, I'm calling the cops.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that cigarette smoking causes cancer is probably the
single, most widely known fact in America today. Little kids learn
that smoking is bad for you before they learn their colors or how
to eat with a spoon. And yet many of these kids will grow up and
start smoking. Why?
</P>
<P>
   In America, which as we all know is a great country, some adult
cigarette smokers _ grown-up people who presumably know their
colors, how to eat with a spoon and maybe a few other things _ are
suing the tobacco companies because they heard a rumor that
cigarette smoking may have some harmful side effects, such as
death. They blame their health problems on the tobacco companies
because the tobacco companies, for some strange reason, neglected
to mention these harmful side effects in their advertising.
``Welcome to Marlboro Country! It's a cancer ward! Pretty cool,
huh?''
</P>
<P>
   This is very imaginative on the part of smokers, I must say, but
not nearly as imaginative as the Pennsylvania man who sued God for
failing to intervene when his (the man's, not God's) employer, U.S.
Steel, fired him in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Donald Drusky accused God of taking no
corrective action and, by means of damages, asked God to return his
youth and grant him the guitar-playing skills of famous guitarists,
as well as resurrecting his mother and pet pigeon.
</P>
<P>
   Also named in the lawsuit, which a judge cruelly threw out on
the grounds that it was frivolous, were former Presidents Reagan
and Bush, the television networks, all 50 states, every single
American, all federal judges and the 100th through 105th
Congresses.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette smokers may cash in by claiming their addiction is the
fault of the tobacco companies, but if they're looking for the
really big bucks, they should definitely think about suing God.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
