u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEED-TRAPS-NYTR &LR;      03-24 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEED-TRAPS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT OFFICER, THIS SPEED TRAP WASN'T ON THE WEBSITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EMILIO SAHURIE The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ Despite appearances, the police cruiser
frequently parked next to Clemmons Trucking Inc. off U.S. 82 in
Gordo is not part of a speed trap, says Gordo Police Chief Todd
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that a police officer parks his patrol car there when
he goes to work at a second job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It acts as a deterrent,'' said Hall. ``That's a secret we
would like to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   But the daily sight of the police car has given that location a
reputation on the Internet as a speed trap. The Gordo location and
hundreds of others around the country are listed in the Speedtrap
Registry at www.speedtrap.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site might sound useful to motorists, but some police
officers question its accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can send in information to these sites without any
basis on fact,'' said Tuscaloosa Police Capt. David Hartin.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he thought the Web site was more entertaining than
useful.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was concerned that speeders would think the site
would help them avoid a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure people know we are doing our job to keep
them safe,'' Hall said. ``Speeding is not worth risking your lives
or the lives of others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Speedtrap Registry lists places where users say tickets have
been issued. Anyone can submit a location with details such as time
of day, speed limits and costs of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site lists several locations where motorists have been
ticketed in Tuscaloosa, but Hartin said these areas were not speed
traps.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that many police departments, including the one in
Tuscaloosa, announce the locations where they will be running
police checks through news outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Speedtrap Registry creator Andrew Warner readily admits that
some of the information posted by his readers may not be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to be 100 percent correct,'' said Warner, who
is 24 and who works for a computer company in Atlanta. ``But this
is a great start.''
</P>
<P>
   The site, which Warner launched four years ago when he was a
college student, averages about 100,000 visitors a week who browse
it for potential enforcement areas.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who received his only speeding ticket while driving
through Kansas in 1995, said he often used the site when he went on
vacation. The 24-year-old said the site was useful to alert
motorists of areas where officers might be lurking or where
authorities recommended that drivers slow down for dangerous roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you are speeding or not,'' Warner said, ``it's human
nature to be on the lookout for the people who are on the lookout
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Tuscaloosa News in Tuscaloosa, Ala., is part of The New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
