<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2925 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIANTS-REVIEW-LADN     03-24 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIANTS' CLIMBS TO NEW HEIGHTS, BUT THAT'S ABOUT IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use  Friday, March 26 by  NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 1 1/2 STARS 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Among Giants'' may be the first movie ever made
about a bunch of working-class blokes who paint high-wire
electrical towers. And, who knows, it may not be the last. There's
certainly plenty of emotional ground yet to be explored because the
makers of this movie have decided to concentrate on pretty aerial
views, hazy metaphors and half-baked characters. The originality
has been confined strictly to the setting.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad because with fine actors like Pete
Postlethwaite (``In the Name of the Father'') and Rachel Griffiths
(``Hilary and Jackie''), this could have been a much more absorbing
movie. But as it stands now, you'll leave the theater wondering
more about electrical towers (when was the last time you saw a
fresh coat of paint on one of those?) than you will about what you
saw on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among Giants'' was written by Simon Beaufoy, the English
screenwriter who gave us ``The Full Monty.'' Beaufoy has a knack
for creating warm, believable blue-collar characters, but, here, he
shows his limitations when forced to fashion a story that requires
more than a one-note gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   Postlethwaite plays Ray, a 50ish hard-hearted English loner
separated from his wife and kids. Ray takes risky, high-paying jobs
so he can have the freedom to get his thrills climbing cliffs in
his spare time. His latest gig involves painting miles and miles of
electrical pylon towers along the Yorkshire moors.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently he's been recruited for this job on the sly, although
the movie never quite makes that clear. The one certainty: Ray and
his scruffy band of painters must finish painting before the power
is turned back on (how the people served by these towers get their
power in the meantime is a mystery); otherwise, someone is going to
be in for the shock of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ray soon faces a different challenge, though, and one he's not
emotionally prepared to handle. A footloose backpacker, a woman, no
less, (``This is not right!'') wanders into the boys' party and,
after demonstrating some climbing prowess, lands a job on the crew.
Gerry (Griffiths) and Ray eventually begin a fervent romance, which
leads soon enough to a naked romp through an abandoned water tower
that has both actors' full monty on extended display.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the climbing, you know there will be a close call or
two with gravity. And given that the work is being done on
electrical towers, someone is bound to get an unwanted charge out
of the situation. Toss in some strained metaphors about knowing
when to hang on and when to let go and you've got a clunker of a
movie that never manages to get off the ground. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAK     03-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS ARE ASKED TO DEFEND THEIR COUNTRY `BY ALL POSSIBLE MEANS'
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS, KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV) 
(wg) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ As NATO's bombs and cruise missiles took
the Balkan wars he initiated to his doorstep on Wednesday night,
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic called on his people to
defend their country ``by all possible means.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, about 8 p.m., four hours after the Serb president had
addressed the nation on television, the first cruise missiles hit
in Kosovo. Air raid sirens sounded in Belgrade. Flashes of
anti-aircraft fire dotted the night sky and over the next few
hours, three large orange fireballs could be seen on the city's
outskirts, one to the northwest in the direction of a large air
force base, and another to the south, near Zarkovo, where there is
an aircraft plant.
</P>
<P>
   State television interrupted its programming to announce the
airstrikes, urging the population to remain calm. ``The criminals
of NATO can inflict a lot of damage,'' one of the anchormen said.
``But they can never win and they can never defeat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Local editors said that the Serb Information Minister Alexandr
Vucic had called them in and given them a list of regulations,
which included the requirement to call NATO ``criminal,'' and
injunctions not to demoralize the population with detailed
descriptions of targets.
</P>
<P>
   Serb authorities also moved to cut off the transmission of
television pictures from Western networks, in particular those from
NATO-member countries.
</P>
<P>
   On state television, there was much martial music and canned
film of brave Yugoslav soldiers handling sophisticated weaponry,
and the first two state television channels showed an old movie
called ``Battle on Kozara,'' about the victory of Yugoslav
partisans over the Nazis. Keeping to the theme, the foreign
ministry issued a statement saying: ``From this moment, neo-Nazi
America suspends international law.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the military chief of staff said that 20
installations had been targeted by NATO forces, including the
civilian and military air field near Pristina, the Kosovo capital,
and the air base northwest of here at Batajnica. A Serb who spoke
to his mother there by telephone said that a large explosion had
blown out the windows of houses, including hers, about a mile from
the airbase.
</P>
<P>
   The sky over a blacked-out Pristina was full of explosions and
light, and there were reports of explosions in other Yugoslav
cities, including Krusumlija, Pancevo, Novi Sad, Golubovac,
Danilovgrad and the air base near Podgorica, the capital of
Montenegro, the other republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no way to tell how accurate the strikes were, and
no specific reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In his television appearance, a defiant Milosevic said the
decision not to allow foreign troops into the southern Serb
province of Kosovo was the right one to protect Yugoslavia's
sovereignty. He hinted darkly that NATO wanted to occupy all of
Yugoslavia, and said: ``What is at stake here is the freedom of the
entire country, and Kosovo was only the door intended to allow
foreign troops to come in and steal away our freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said that he still wanted to solve the Kosovo problem
peacefully, with equal guarantees for all the people of the
province. But he vowed: ``We will defend the country if it is
attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, at Batajnica, where the air base is,
Milosevic's citizens were scarcely gung-ho. They were depressed,
anxious, slightly hostile and still disbelieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe they'll bomb us; something will happen,'' Sadi
Dragan, staring up at the sunny sky outside his auto-parts shop.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has moved in the last few days to try to insure that
people have access only to the approved state media. Early this
morning, police shut down the independent radio station, B92, which
has been an important dissident voice to official propaganda, and
detained its editor, Veran Matic.
</P>
<P>
   Matic was released 8 hours later, around 11 a.m. on Wednesday,
but the radio's transmitters were sealed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, in Belgrade, the police shut down a
satellite transmitter of the European Broadcasting Union used by
Western television networks, which were forced to transmit from
government facilities. Later tonight, those broadcasts were
themselves restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Obradovic, a former general in the Yugoslav army who now
leads an opposition party called Social Democracy, also criticized
NATO's decision to use military force in an interview on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that Milosevic is most guilty in bringing
the country to war,'' Obradovic said. ``But NATO will also be
losers, and the ones who will lose the most are ordinary civilians,
in Serbia and especially in Kosovo. As a general, I tell you, even
in the most modern war, civilians are the main casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   Obradovic, 51, who spent his whole career in the military before
quitting in 1992 out of disgust with Milosevic's Balkan ambitions,
said that the Yugoslav army ``will defend Kosovo, and they do not
joke when they say they will defend it in every possible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the army would prefer a different policy, Obradovic
said. ``Milosevic not only brings us into a war with the whole
world, but he pushes us into a war with one another. That is the
whole organizing principle of his politics, if he has one.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said that the West miscalculated the difficulty of any
Serb accepting foreign troops and a loss of control over Kosovo.
``It may sound like only a phrase, but it is really true that
Kosovo is something special to the Serbs. And it is also true that
the person who signs a document giving up Kosovo will have the
stamp of a traitor on himself and his children forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic would rather lose Kosovo, said an official considered
close to him, than to be accused of surrendering it. ``If it is
lost, we keep the right to reconquer it, even 100 years from no,''
he said. ``If we give it away, it is lost forever.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo itself, having driven thousands of ethnic Albanians
out of their homes as it pursues the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
Yugoslav military and police units began to disperse their heavy
equipment in preparation for NATO attacks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces were making it very difficult for Western
journalists to move freely outside Pristina, the capital, where the
testing of air raid sirens caused panic among the population.
</P>
<P>
   In Batajnica, near a monument to the town's World War II
dead,by, one man spoke about the difficulty of life here, about
Yugoslavia's decline under Milosevic and the need to work two jobs
to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   He has two sons, ages 6 and 4, he said, and thinks only of them
and their future. ``If I thought that my sons' lives will be better
in 20 years, I would go lie on the tarmac of the Batajnica air base
and wait for the bombs, throwing a party for my friends,'' the man
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think this attack will make their lives or this
country any better,'' he said. ``Quite the contrary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
