<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PRIMEMINISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB PLANS TO RUN FOR PRIME MINISTER OF ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the ever-shifting chess game of the Israeli
election campaign, Azmi Bishara has put a new piece on the board.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli Arab member of Parliament and political philosopher,
Bishara said he will join the race for prime minister, becoming the
first Arab to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He said the move is a calculated power play, intended to thrust
the problems of Israel's 1 million Arab citizens onto the agenda of
a campaign that has tended to ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   Bishara hasn't the slightest chance of winning the May 17
election, 17, and he has already drawn fire from Arab critics. But
he hopes to make the difference in a close race by throwing his
support behind the candidate who is committed to solving the
problems of Israel's Arabs, long disadvantaged in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is empowerment of a minority,'' Bishara said in an
interview. ``There has never been such an effective tool, and now
that the electoral system has moved the center of gravity to the
race for prime minister, we have to be there. This is power that
should be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of a new breed of Israeli Arab politicians, Bishara, 42, a
Christian from Nazareth, asserts that the Arabs in Israel, one out
of six Israelis, should be recognized as a national minority in a
``state of all its citizens'' that would grant genuine equality to
Jews and non-Jews alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of the Arabs in Israel is missing from the debate
between the candidates,'' Bishara said. ``If we aren't in the race,
the issue won't exist and we'll be nothing more than a stock of
votes. I want to put the Arab issue on the agenda of the election
for prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Bishara is well on the way to collecting the
required 50,000 signatures to submit his candidacy, and he is
planning to throw his hat in the ring at a news conference
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by surveys showing that many Israeli Arabs would vote
for an Arab candidate for prime minister, Bishara optimistically
predicts that he will win at least half of the Arab turnout, or
more than 150,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Arab critics dismiss those figures as an illusion and argue that
Bishara's candidacy will waste votes needed to unseat Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, whose policies most Israeli Arabs
oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Arab voters have traditionally favored the dovish Labor Party
over Netanyahu's conservative Likud. But if enough of them vote for
Bishara, they could drain support from Labor Party leader Ehud
Barak in a three-way race with Netanyahu and his other main
competitor, Yitzhak Mordechai of the new Center Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bishara countered by citing opinion polls that have consistently
shown that even without his candidacy, none of the three main
candidates would get more than 50 percent of the vote, forcing a
runoff between the two leading vote-getters.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks ahead, Bishara plans to use his electoral leverage
to bargain with Barak or Mordechai for his support. The price of
his endorsement and withdrawal from the campaign, he says, will be
an ironclad, signed commitment to address the problems of Israeli
Arabs. An alliance with the hawkish Netanyahu is out of the
question, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a 50-50 race the Arabs can tip the scales,'' Bishara said.
``Why should I be in anyone's pocket without trying to have an
impact? We're ready to negotiate with the candidate who is prepared
to solve the problems of the Arab population. We'll all mobilize
and work for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishara ticked off the most urgent demands: a halt to
expropriation of Arab lands; approval of master plans for the
expansion of Arab communities; increased budgets for Arab schools;
Arab participation in state planning and building councils;
appointment of Arabs to the boards of major state corporations;
supply of public services to dozens of Arab hamlets that lack
sewers, water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   For all the novelty of Bishara's move, it has not won the
support of other Arab political leaders, who fear that it will hurt
chances of defeating Netanyahu. Many Arab rivals accuse Bishara of
trying to salvage a political career threatened by the possible
failure of his party, the National Democratic Alliance, to get
enough votes to enter Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no more than a media gimmick that neutralizes the Arab
vote and harms the prospect that the Arab population will throw its
full weight to topple Netanyahu,'' said Muhammad Barakeh, leader of
a competing party, the Democratic Front for Peace and Equality.
</P>
<P>
   Bishara asserted that if his conditions are met, he will deliver
his votes to one of Netanyahu's opponents and in the process drive
an important point home to the Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will understand what I mean when I say a state of all
its citizens,'' he said. ``This is an important civics lesson for
both Jews and Arabs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
