<HEADLINE>
IF IT GLOWS, BITE IT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   B &UR; ryce Bryan &LR;  of Pittsburgh, Pa., has received a patent for
extracting a substance from jellyfish, glowworms or fireflies and
mixing it with edible material to create food that glows.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan told the New York Times that his company, Prolume Ltd., is
working on cake frosting that will glow bright blue for 30 minutes.
After that product is perfected, he plans to turn his attention to
luminescent yogurt, ice cream and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration hasn't approved this stuff for
human consumption, but an official Prolume announcement said the
company believes ``that these additives are safe since they are
present in the ocean's food chain.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Disney chief  &UR; Michael Eisner &LR; , who was with his family in
Manhattan last week, got around in a chic four-wheel-drive vehicle
with chauffeur, said New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Kate Moss &LR;  is naked in a photo spread that goes along with a
British Vogue story about how she's recovered from alcohol and drug
abuse and is a regular at AA meetings; nearby, in the same
magazine, Moss, on behalf of L'Oreal, declares war on split ends.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Salman Rushdie &LR; , suffering from a condition that weakened his
eyelids and made it difficult to keep his eyes open, has had
surgery on his eyelids. ``This was done entirely for medical
reasons,'' he told the Sunday Times. ``I am long past beautifying
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; President Clinton &LR; , just back from Central America, brought
back a gift for Senator  &UR; Trent Lott &LR; , R-Miss., perhaps in the
interests of healing after the impeachment proceedings. The gift,
which came with an engraved card reading ``Compliments of President
Clinton,'' was a very large cigar, reports the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   _ A conversation with  &UR; Danielle Steel &LR;  about the death of her
son,  &UR; Nick Traina &LR; , at 19, is featured in the newsletter of the
National Alliance for the Mentally Ill. Steel cites her son's manic
depression as a cause of his death, presumably having caused the
heroin overdose not mentioned in the interview. A note informs
readers of the availability of Steel's book about her son, ``His
Bright Light'' (Delacorte; $25).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TALES TRICKLING IN FROM TINSELTOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``Democratic source'' told the New York Post that Governor
 &UR; Gray Davis &LR;  was so worried about attending the same post-Oscar
party as Monica Lewinsky, &LR;  that he called Vanity Fair contributing
editor  &UR; Dee Dee Myers &LR;  to discuss it. In the end, he didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the traditional insiders' party thrown by  &UR; Dani Janssen &LR; ,
the Post said  &UR; Tom Hanks &LR; ,  &UR; Harrison Ford &LR; ,  &UR; Jack Nicholson &LR; ,
 &UR; Clint &LR; 
 &UR; Eastwood &LR; ,  &UR; Steven Spielberg &LR; ,  &UR; Shirley MacLaine &LR; ,  &UR; Sally Field &LR; 
and  &UR; Garry Shandling &LR;  got into such a hot discussion about  &UR; Elia &LR; 
 &UR; Kazan &LR; 's award that Shandling ``finally moved to another room.''
 &UR; Norman Jewison &LR; , who won the Irving Thalberg award, said he agreed
with the protesters. ``To betray his friends for your career when
he already had a lot of money. ... It wasn't like he had to feed
his kids.''
</P>
<P>
   _ After a New York newspaper revealed that New York City Police
Commissioner  &UR; Howard Safir &LR;  had flown to the Academy Awards
ceremony in a private jet owned by Revlon, the commissioner said
he'd have a city official review the trip to see if it violated
ethics codes. A police press representative noted that the city
does not do business with Revlon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING DRESSED FOR THE LAW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a story datelined San Francisco, the Wall Street Journal
notes that California lawyers _ particularly the ones who represent
high-tech firms run by young people _ are wearing casual clothes
rather than suits seven days a week. ``Show up at a high-tech
company in a tie,'' says  &UR; Keith Wetmore &LR; , managing partner of
Morrison &AMP; Foerster, ``and everyone assumes you don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers in East Coast firms still wear suits for work, a
problem arises when they visit their informal colleagues in West
Coast branches of those firms. ``It's fascinating to watch East
Coast lawyers come through here,'' said a lawyer at a big Internet
company. ``You've got your British-explorer types in suits,
insisting on dressing up for dinner in the heart of Africa. Then
you've got the guys who take it all off and try to go native.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Toothpaste is the new wrinkle cream.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Now don't go smearing it all over your face, tootsie. What
metaphor-slingers at Elle magazine means &LR;  is that would-be beauties
with yellow teeth are trying to remedy that condition with
whitening toothpaste.
</P>
