<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      03-24 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a fearsome barrage of air and missile power,
President Clinton and a largely American force Wednesday answered
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic's refusal to end his
military offensive against Kosovo Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
   But that answer in that small part of the world only raised
larger questions about US foreign policy all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   With US troops engaging in hostile action over Iraq, providing
security for embassies around the globe, responding to terrorist
attacks, assisting humanitarian operations after natural disasters,
and attempting to disrupt the production and movement of illegal
drugs, Washington is presiding over a military for all seasons, but
is motivated by no one great reason.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's response to the year-old crisis in Kosovo
demonstrated, as the US response to Saddam Hussein and to the
terrorists who bombed US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania did last
year, that Clinton's mobility in foreign affairs has not been
substantially curtailed. Despite his impeachment and the bitter
trial in the Senate, the president's ability and willingness to
project US force abroad has not been diminished.
</P>
<P>
   But the president still has not articulated a vision for the
role of America in world affairs, producing a vacuum not only in
this country, but also in diplomatic circles. In an age when there
is no Cold War antagonist, and when the threat from China is more
prospective than real, there remain no guidelines for the
application of US force, no walls between police action and
military action, no sturdy principles of US engagement.
</P>
<P>
   The president underlined the difficulty five weeks ago in his
radio address delivered the day after the Senate impeachment trial
ended. In his remarks proposing to send as many as 4,000 US troops
to Kosovo if a peace agreement were reached, Clinton said,
``America cannot be everywhere or do everything overseas. But we
must act where important interests are at stake and we can make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the principals in the Washington political wars has been
able to articulate when Americans should be involved, what US
interests are at stake, and how US forces can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   This discomfort was palpable in the capital this week, as the
Senate debated a measure that would have barred funding for
airstrikes and other military activities without explicit prior
congressional approval. As the likelihood of airstrikes grew, the
Senate put the measure aside in a gesture of solidarity when
American lives were on the line, but the discomfort remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo's crisis is now full-blown,'' the president said
Wednesday. ``And if we do not act, clearly it will get even worse.
Only firmness now can prevent greater catastrophe later.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the president set out three objectives _ to curtail
aggression, deter attacks on civilians, and damage Serbia's
capacity to continue its offensives against Kosovo _ there exists
no more fundamental expression of US objectives in foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to fashion a coherent world view for the new
millennium is not confined to Clinton or to the Democrats.
Republicans, too, have been reluctant, if not unable, to establish
principles and guidelines for a world without superpower rivalry.
Though the Berlin Wall, and the world communist threat itself, fell
a decade ago, political leaders of both parties have struggled to
define the extent or, perhaps more important, the limits of US
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The split is evident even in the nascent GOP presidential
campaign. Among the contenders, three Republicans, Senator John
McCain of Arizona, publisher Steve Forbes, and former Governor
Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, expressed support for airstrikes in
Yugoslavia before the operation began. The other candidates opposed
US involvement, with the exception of Elizabeth H. Dole, who had
not taken a position on the issue. Wednesday, however, she issued a
statement asserting that ``this action can be instrumental in
forging a peaceful solution to a dangerous, escalating military
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   This issue divides Republican candidates more than perhaps any
other as the 2000 campaign approaches. But presidential nomination
struggles rarely touch on foreign affairs _ the great exception in
recent years is 1968, when tensions over Vietnam boiled over in the
Democratic primaries _ and there is little indication the
candidates will clash over broad foreign policy objectives in the
next several months.
</P>
<P>
   The great expectation is that the Kosovo involvement would be
surgical and relatively brief, removing the overriding issue from
public attention _ but leaving the big questions unanswered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 1937EST &QL; 
