<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-SKIING-LADN     03-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-SKIING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AVALANCHE IS STILL DEADLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART BENTLEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The party of German skiers traveled from Berlin to
hit the slopes of Lech, Austria, for their Christmas vacation.
Their instructor had warned them snow conditions could not be more
dangerous, but they went anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The instructor refused to take out the skiers when they arrived.
They called him a coward and said they would ski without a guide.
The instructor finally relented, insisting on leading them to the
least threatening descent he could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``He crossed it himself and then they followed and the whole
hillside came down in a rush, rising over them as a tidal wave
rises. Thirteen were dug out and nine of them were dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer was not a contemporary news reporter describing last
month's ``white death'' in the Alps, but Ernest Hemingway. A skier
himself, he was chronicling the events of the winter of 1925-26 in
Austria, ``the year that so many people were killed in
avalanches.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced last month in Europe _ and by a recent fatal event
in Alaska _ avalanches remain as potentially deadly to skiers and
other winter recreationists today as in Hemingway's day. In Austria
alone, February's slides killed 38 people and stranded 15,000; at
least four people were killed Sunday when an avalanche buried
snowmobilers at Turnagain Pass, about 62 miles south of Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   But avalanche forecasting and preventive measures _ though far
from failsafe _ have advanced significantly since the mid-1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Europeans were a little shocked,'' observed
Richard Armstrong, a senior research scientist and avalanche expert
affiliated with the National Snow and Ice Data Center at the
University of Colorado. ``They thought the barriers they'd built in
the mountains above the towns were more effective. They thought
they had better control.''
</P>
<P>
   Man is wresting better control over avalanches, at least on this
continent, according to Armstrong. Avalanche fatalities are
exceedingly rare for skiers schussing in-bounds and obeying posted
warning signs at North American ski resorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what a ski area wants you to believe,'' Armstrong said.
``There's risk in every recreational activity, but that's a minimal
one. Anything that happens is usually out-of-bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this sense of security is the improvement in
forecasting techniques for comparatively small areas, such as ski
resorts. A typical forecast might span only a half-dozen avalanche
paths. These routes are not surveyed by a ski patroller digging
holes to determine the snow's stability but by one of many
``automatic weather stations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the sophistication of these automatic weather
stations, you can get a much better idea any time of day what the
weather is doing to increase avalanche hazards,'' Armstrong
explained. ``So instead of having only one (manned) station, they
have an array of automatic stations scattered around at critical
points of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Augmenting the weather stations is another method of forecasting
known as ``nearest-neighbor models.'' In this approach, a
forecaster enters data on weather and snowpack at a given location
in his computer, which searches for similar conditions at adjacent
sites to determine whether they've led to avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   The information these techniques try to uncover is how likely
the snowpack is able to support its own weight, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   For backcountry skiers who might visit a resort only to ride
lifts that provide access to out-of-bounds terrain, the outlook is
entirely different. (Skiing in unpatrolled areas outside a resort's
boundary is permitted, as long as there are no signs indicating
they are closed to the public.)
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for large wilderness areas are little more than
educated guesses, based on assessments of snow characteristics by
observers. In Colorado, for example, some 30 to 40 observers might
telephone their assessments to the state's avalanche center, which
uses the data to provide general information on avalanche hazards
for several regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put instruments on every slope or every
mountaintop,'' Armstrong said. ``So the focus is on education. We
try to educate people so they can get basic information on how a
snowpack has developed. Once they're out there, we hope they can
make the right decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
