<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-NYT &LR;      03-24 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES QUESTION PRESENCE OF NEWS CREWS IN POLICE SEARCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supreme Court justices across the ideological
spectrum were sharply critical Wednesday of police and other law
enforcement officers who allow reporters and photographers to
accompany them as they search homes for evidence and suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you have to take photographers into someone's house?''
Justice David H. Souter demanded of a lawyer for two groups of
federal agents who brought journalists with them as they executed
search and arrest warrants on a Montana ranch and in a Maryland
home. ``You can have a news conference when it's over,'' the
justice said.
</P>
<P>
   The question before the court was whether media ``ride-alongs''
of this sort violate the constitutional rights of people whose
encounters with law enforcement authorities turn into unwelcomed
photo opportunities. Two cases, combined Wednesday in a single
argument, demonstrated both the variety of police-press
collaboration and the range of judicial responses to it.
</P>
<P>
   One federal appeals court, ruling in a Montana case in which a
Cable News Network crew accompanied federal wildlife agents onto a
ranch to search for evidence that eagles were being illegally
killed there, held that the network's presence turned a lawful
search into one that was unreasonable under the Fourth Amendment.
The court, the 9th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in San Francisco,
reinstated a suit the ranch owners had brought against the agents
and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, almost simultaneously, another federal
appeals court refused to allow a Maryland couple to pursue their
suit against county and Federal agents who brought a Washington
Post reporter and photographer into their house in an unsuccessful
effort to arrest their son, a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   That court, the 4th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in Richmond,
Va., held that no matter what the constitutional merits of the
couple's lawsuit _ a question it did not decide _ the law at the
time of the search in 1992 was sufficiently unclear as to make the
officers immune from personal liability.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning one of the agents' lawyers Wednesday, Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor described the Maryland incident as ``an amazing
invasion'' of the couple's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Souter dismissed as ``fluff'' the proposition by a lawyer for
the federal agents that the presence of the news media at searches
and arrests serves a broader public interest by documenting police
behavior and preventing abuses.
</P>
<P>
   From the justices' responses Wednesday, a two-part decision
would not be surprising. The court could rule both that the police
practices violate the Fourth Amendment, which prohibits
unreasonable searches, while at the same time concluding that these
particular officers, operating in the early 1990s under official
manuals that encouraged ride-alongs as good public relations, could
not reasonably have been expected to know that.
</P>
<P>
   The liability of the media itself is not directly at issue in
the cases before the court, Wilson vs. Layne, No. 98-83, and Hanlon
vs. Berger, No. 97-1927. The Maryland couple, Charles and Geraldine
Wilson of Rockville, did not sue the Washington Post. The Montana
ranchers, Paul and Erma Berger, did sue CNN along with the federal
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Constitution applies only to government behavior, a
private entity such as a television network would ordinarily not be
liable for a constitutional violation, but the 9th Circuit held
that CNN's close cooperation with the government agents had made
the network a ``state actor.'' The justices have taken no action on
CNN's appeal, which remains pending on the Supreme Court's docket.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cordray, the lawyer representing the federal agents in
both cases, told the court that whether media involvement turns a
particular search from a lawful into an unconstitutional one should
depend on a ``reasonableness test'' that would ``balance the nature
of the intrusion and the objective served'' by the media's
participation. The purpose of the Fourth Amendment was ``not only
to preserve privacy but to prevent abuses of government power,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not every day that lawyers for law enforcement agencies
sing the Fourth Amendment's praises before the Supreme Court, and
Justice Antonin Scalia could not resist teasing Cordray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not say to the person, we're going to do you a favor'' by
bringing a news crew along to show that a search was ``absolutely
fair,'' Scalia said, adding: ``Why don't you ask the homeowner if
he wants that protection? Why force it on him?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Willard, the lawyer representing the Maryland couple,
said the court should apply ``not a balancing test, but a
bright-line rule drawn at the door of the home.'' He said that when
the police execute a warrant, ``they have one purpose, to
effectuate an arrest, not to bring along the media on a
news-gathering expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices indicated by their questions that they saw
important differences between reporters and photographers covering
searches and arrests in a home, on the one hand, and in less
private places, on the other. They asked questions about the
daylong search of the Bergers' 75,000-acre ranch that were not
resolved during the course of the argument.
</P>
<P>
   The search took place on the grounds and in outbuildings. The
agents briefly entered the ranch house but did not search it. One
wore a hidden microphone that broadcast conversations taking place
in the house for CNN's benefit. A CNN camera was mounted on the
front of one of the government cars. The network withheld its
broadcast until after Berger's criminal trial in 1994 on charges of
poisoning eagles; he was acquitted of that charge, but convicted of
a misdemeanor, misusing a pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing in the press was absolutely designed to maximize the
intrusion,'' Henry Rossbacher, the Bergers' lawyer, told the court,
adding: ``There can be no greater affront to privacy than a
worldwide broadcast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
