<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-0325-COX     03-24 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM AVIANO: LAUNCHING THE POINTY END OF NATO DIPLOMACY
 &HT;    With US-KOSOVO-0325.
 &HT;    EDs: A Photo Mug of Holmes is available.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy _ As the sun sank, American and NATO
warplanes rose into a misty Italian sky to deliver the
long-promised punishment to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 6 p.m. local time on Wednesday, two U.S. Air Force
F-16s, their wings bristling with missiles and bombs, led the wave
from the long and wide runway at this air base Italy shares with
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The planes were followed by almost seamless stream of aircraft
-- futuristic F-117A Nighthawk stealth fighter-bombers, F-18s
fighters piloted by the Canadians and the Spanish, A-10
tank-killing Warthogs, EA-6B Prowler radar-jamming aircraft, and
modified C-130 cargo planes which serve as airborne command centers
to direct the air assault.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missiles are the U.S. military's weapon of choice in this
high-tech version of gunboat diplomacy, as practiced this decade in
Iraq and the Balkans. They are accurately guided by satellites,
fired from a distance and place no U.S. personal at risk. Scores
were launched by U.S. Navy ships on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are greater and more perilous at Aviano.
</P>
<P>
   In 100 minutes Wednesday at dusk, some 70 planes thundered into
the air from a single runway nestled in this bucolic valley in
Northern Italy. The waxen smell of jet fuel hung in the air, as did
an unspoken anxiety about the mission American pilots were leading.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials stress that pilots from five NATO nations are
involved in operations from Aviano. But American flyers comprise
the bulk of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 U.S. pilots and servicemen live and work at this
air base and the hamlet of Aviano nearby. An olive-drab tent city
near the aircraft hangers accommodates many of those without
families.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials and the families of the pilots are naturally
fearful that some of the planes will not come back, a fact made
clear in Aviano not by what they said, but by what they refused to
say.
</P>
<P>
   In the town center, American dependents did not want to discuss
the night's mission. At the base, the U.S. commander, Air Force
Brig. Gen. Daniel Leaf, considered holding a news conference, but
in the end decided to remain quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists were told the pilots would not be available for
interviews now or in the future during the operation against
Serbia. Media exposure would identify them to the Serbs and thus
jeopardize them should they have to bail out over hostile
territory, said Maj. Scott Vadnais, an air force spokesman at
Aviano.
</P>
<P>
   Watching warplanes rip into the night sky, punctuated by the hot
glow of their afterburners, is not unlike watching a violent
thunderstorm -- simultaneously beautiful and frightening. The
multi-billion dollar arsenal of warplanes at Aviano is profoundly
graceful and terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic will wonder what hit him,'' a camouflage-clad U.S.
airman said to himself while standing on the tarmac watching the
planes soar to the east, across the Adriatic Sea and on to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no open discussion here of the failed diplomacy
over Kosovo and the ultimate effect of this night's formidable rain
of pain on Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The focus was starting and completing the first night of combat
for which pilots have trained for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pointy-end-of-the-spear kind of experience,'' said
Vadnais.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
