<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-TRAFFIC-584&AMP;A     03-24 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-TRAFFIC-584&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA LEGISLATURE APPROVES PLAN FOR TRANSPORTATION SUPERAGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In January, it seemed a radical proposal for a
conservative state: a transportation superagency with broad powers
to impose transit systems and highways on local governments,
restrict development, and even put pressure on cities and counties
to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Many supporters predicted that Gov. Roy E. Barnes would have a
hard time getting his plan through a skeptical state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a measure of the seriousness of Atlanta's struggles
with traffic and sprawl that both houses of the Legislature passed
the proposal on Tuesday with only a few mutterings of dissent, and
only one change of any significance.
</P>
<P>
   When Barnes signs the bill early next month, Georgia will assume
a leading role in the growing national effort to limit the urban
sprawl that is choking so many cities in air pollution and traffic
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do something fairly drastic to reverse a 30-year
trend of developments that allowed Atlanta to sprawl,'' said John
A. Williams, chairman of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce,
which put the full force of the local business community behind the
bill. ``We're going to have to work very hard to quickly reverse
this trend, while still allowing the region to grow and prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   So many people are moving to Atlanta that ever-widening rings of
rural counties around the city are finding their roads clogged with
commuters. The region, which has doubled its population in the last
three decades, to 3.1 million people, is ineligible for federal
money for new road projects because its ozone level is one of the
worst in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes acknowledged Wednesday that the problems will take years
to correct. But the bill is intended to overcome years of inaction
and squabbling among local governments in the 13-county Atlanta
area, many of which have competed for new development while
remaining unable to agree on a regional plan for growth and mass
transit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, if a county decides to build a shopping mall in
an overly congested area, or an area without adequate
transportation, a newly created Georgia Regional Transportation
Authority could in essence veto the mall by refusing to issue
permits necessary to tie it into the road system. The authority can
plan and build new rail or bus systems or car-pool lanes, and if a
county balks at paying required taxes, the authority can withhold
vital state money until the county complies.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, whose election campaign last year was based on a promise
to reduce congestion, staked much of his political capital on the
bill, and is likely to have the loudest voice in how it is
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wednesday he would like to see more buses and some light
rail lines built in the region, and because he appoints the 15
members of the authority, his proposals are being taken very
seriously. Many people involved in shaping the bill said
legislators seemed relieved that a prominent political figure was
willing to stake his reputation on such an intractable issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the previous reluctance of this region to come together
around regional solutions, I thought it would be very tough to get
this passed,'' said Jim Chapman, executive director of Georgians
for Transportation Alternatives, a citizens group that supported
the bill. ``But what happened was that almost everyone now accepts
there is problem. When Barnes said give me the magic wand and don't
complain, no one else had a better idea.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Early on, the biggest stumbling block appeared to be rural
legislators, concerned that the authority would spend the state's
transportation dollars exclusively on Atlanta. Barnes had to
compromise on a formula that guaranteed counties outside the
Atlanta region a steady stream of road money.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawmakers also seemed impressed by a Georgia State
University study that showed the effect on the rest of the state if
Atlanta began to be perceived as a dirty, congested city and its
growth began to decline: a loss of 530,000 jobs outside the
metropolitan area by 2050, along with cutbacks of up to $1.7
billion a year in state money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they realized that if we didn't do something in the
metro area, there was going to be a great big sucking sound when
those federal dollars are withdrawn,'' said Charlie Smith Jr., a
state representative who helped manage the bill through the House.
``And we couldn't abandon the metropolitan Atlanta area, so when
all that federal money was gone, some state money would have to go
in and where was it coming from? From the rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The final votes _ 41-12 in the Senate, and 158-14 in the House _
were considered a triumph for Barnes, who also won most of the rest
of his legislative package. But in a news conference Wednesday, he
took pains to reassure the state that his Transportation Authority
would not shut down the engine of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole process in regard to regional transportation has
been to make sure we continue to grow and not to stop it,'' Barnes
said. ``But it has to be growth in a planned sort of way; it has to
be growth that is served by infrastructure. These are tough
decisions that have to be made, but we have the framework in place
now to make those tough decisions and to begin the solution to the
problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
