<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jazz trumpeter captures film roots on new album
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jazz trumpeter Terence Blanchard has been living a
double life. His career divides neatly between tours and recordings
with his band and his work as a composer for movie soundtracks _
most frequently with Spike Lee, an association that began with
``School Daze'' (1987).
</P>
<P>
   But with his latest album, ``Jazz in Film'' (Sony Classical),
the 37-year-old New Orleans native combines the best of both
worlds. Among the movie themes Blanchard arranges are those for
``Chinatown,'' ``The Subterraneans,'' ``Taxi Driver'' and his own
``Clockers.'' It also includes two selections from Duke Ellington,
whose themes for ``Anatomy of a Murder'' and ``Degas' Racing
World'' make the most sensible segue into the combo format.
</P>
<P>
   We recently spoke with Blanchard, who brings his sextet to
Sambuca's Jazz Cafe for shows tonight and Friday. Audiences can
expect to hear some snappy new approaches to vintage cinematic
sounds. And, guaranteed, it'll be Celine Dion-free.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You had the great tenor saxophonist Joe Henderson on the
album. He must have been a treat to work with?
</P>
<P>
   A: Like a dream come true. There were huge lessons to learn
there. We took a lunch break and we all were out in the lobby
trying to figure out what we were going to eat. I realized that Joe
wasn't there, so I went to find out if there was anything he
wanted. There's Joe Henderson at the piano with the (sheet) music
playing through all the chord changes. That a person on that level
sits down and does that and has so much respect for the music
taught me a lesson. My hunger went away _ quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You did the score for Spike Lee's upcoming film, ``Summer of
Sam.'' Doesn't that seem to be a departure for him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Everybody says that. The interesting thing about it is it
seems to be a departure. Spike is very much like Woody Allen. Those
guys do New York stories. They have a certain style. The Son of Sam
is definitely a New York thing and that fits up Spike's alley. I
remember when I moved away from Brooklyn. Man, I thought he was
going to hang me!
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Son of Sam?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, Spike! He's such a New York guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Blanchard Sextet
</P>
<P>
   8:30 and 10:30 tonight-Friday. $10. Sambuca Jazz Cafe, 3102
Piedmont Road N.W., Atlanta, Ga. 404-237-5299.
</P>
<P>
   Other jazz tonight
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tempest Little Big Band: Organized by saxophonist James Rozzi,
this weekly big band session features a revolving cast of Atlanta
musicians and a repertoire that includes pieces by such jazz
immortals as Duke Ellington and John Coltrane. It also includes
arrangements and originals from band members. The setting, a
neighborhood bar and restaurant in a Sandy Springs strip mall, can
be noisy and distracting, but the players are game. This is the
real stuff, rather heroically presented in a city that, for the
most part, doesn't support traditional jazz.Three sets beginning at
8:30 tonight. $5. Cafe 290, 290 Hildebrand Drive N.E., Sandy
Springs, Ga. 404-256-3942.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Puttin' on the Ritz'' _ WCLK-FM 25th Anniversary Party: The
noncommercial Atlanta jazz radio station, which has operated for 25
years from the campus of Clark Atlanta University, celebrates its
silver anniversary. Guests include vocalists Ernestine Anderson and
Loston Harris. Critic, op-ed columnist and sometime pugilist
Stanley Crouch, a guiding force behind Jazz at Lincoln Center and
mentor to Wynton Marsalis, will be master of ceremonies. 8 tonight.
$50. JW Marriott at Lenox, 3300 Lenox Road N.W, Atlanta, Ga.
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Blanchard Sextet
</P>
<P>
   8:30 and 10:30 tonight-Friday. $10. Sambuca Jazz Cafe, 3102
Piedmont Road N.W. 404-237-5299.
</P>
