<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-DEREG25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gas companies' competition for business accounts heats up
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Almost six months after Georgia's natural gas industry
was deregulated, marketers are going after business customers
tooth-and-nail.
</P>
<P>
   They have gone to great lengths to snag residential customers,
with expensive ad campaigns, free gas credits and other giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta Gas Light Co.'s 100,000 business customers _
accounting for only 7 percent of the total _ are perhaps the most
highly prized because they offer ``more bang for the buck.'' More
gas is sold for every dollar spent on marketing, billing and
customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dogfight,'' said Timothy Sheehan, marketing manager for
Shell Energy Services. He noted one business can easily buy the
equivalent amount of gas as 400 homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very competitive, more than residential,'' added Deb
Stone, commercial marketing director at Columbia Energy. ``Larger
accounts can be easier to serve and support.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Darby, senior vice president at SCANA Energy, said the
South Carolina-based supplier decided early on to focus on
residential customers rather than face the ``huge amount of
competition'' in the commercial market. SCANA claims a 45 percent
market share, with businesses accounting for only 2 percent of its
total customers.
</P>
<P>
   A. Clifton Payne, vice president for marketing at Georgia
Natural Gas Services, said some competitors have engaged in
``irrational pricing'' to build their commercial customer rolls.
``I don't see how some of the marketers can sustain the pricing
they have for some of the customers right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many larger companies, empowered by the sheer volume of gas
they purchase, have been able to negotiate special rates. Some have
hired high-powered consultants to negotiate contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Clarkson, senior vice president of Service Resources, said
his Atlanta-based energy consulting company has represented
companies such as Home Depot, Target, Wachovia, Emory University,
Haverty's and Upton's. He said many of his clients are saving ``at
least 30 percent'' on their gas bills.
</P>
<P>
   Most marketers quote standard rates for smaller businesses that
are lower by a few cents per therm than residential rates. But as
establishments and their consumption gets larger, marketers become
more willing to cut special deals.
</P>
<P>
   Larger business customers are even taking bids. In many cases,
employees who also sign up are offered reduced rates for their
homes. Special rates also have been negotiated with trade
associations that give marketers the inside track with member
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most highly-sought accounts are those with multiple
locations. Restaurants and fast-food chains are at a premium
because they use high volumes of gas year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Roswell-based Peachtree Natural Gas even put a Korean-American
dry cleaner on commission to market to the hundreds of cleaners
operated by Koreans in the metro area. John Kim, who operates a
cleaner in Buckhead, first approached Peachtree in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knocked on the door, introduced himself and said he had
definite marketing plans in mind,'' said Donna Peeples, vice
president of Peachtree. Kim secured the endorsement for Peachtree
of the 300-member Korean Cleaners Association of Atlanta and has
signed up about 120 dry cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Dry cleaners are a ``good, steady load,'' Peeples said. ``It's
one thing to have heavy usage in the winter, when everybody else is
using gas, but it's another to have a steady baseload year-round.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim said monthly gas bills can run anywhere between $600 and
$1,200 and that Peachtree's rates are between 25 percent and 30
percent cheaper than Atlanta Gas Light Co.'s.
</P>
<P>
   Some Korean cleaners may not be totally fluent in English and
have language problems negotiating with marketers. But, Kim said,
``Money talks. Everybody understands.''
</P>
<P>
   Yun Kim, who operates a dry cleaner in Roswell and is president
of the cleaners' association, cited savings as his reason for
signing up with Peachtree.
</P>
<P>
   Shell has signed agreements with the Building Owners and
Managers of Atlanta and Georgia Textile Manufactuers Association,
both huge gas consumers, to make special rates available to members
and their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Shell is also supplying Georgia restaurants of McDonald's,
Popeyes and Church's fried chicken. The Houston-based company hopes
to develop national accounts with such companies as deregulation
expands into gas and electric utilities in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Among other deals:
</P>
<P>
   _ United Gas Management has signed up Harry's Farmers Market and
United Parcel Service's corporate headquarters in Sandy Springs,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ GasKey is serving DeKalb County Schools, Zoo Atlanta and 200
U.S. post offices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reliant, formerly known as Noram Energy Management, has scored
with Home Depot. Jim Laird, manager of energy programs at Home
Depot, said the company is saving about 20 percent on annual gas
bills for its 25 Georgia superstores, totaling about $300,000 last
year. He attributed most of the savings to lower gas commodity
costs and said deregulation has allowed the home imporovement
retailer to take maximum advantage of commodity price swings. Home
Depot's contract with Reliant pegs rates to prices on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Natural Gas Services has a contract to provide gas
service to 19 Georgia Applebee's and Rio Bravo restaurants. William
R. Kampbell, energy buyer for Kansas-based Applebee's
International, said a contract will reduce annual gas bills from
$145,623 last year to $11,959 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
