<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-POLICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKEPTICAL JUSTICES QUESTION POLICE ALLOWING MEDIA TO JOIN THEM ON
ARRESTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday considered whether
police violate the Constitution when they allow reporters to
accompany them on arrests or searches of a suspect's property.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, hearing cases from Montana and Maryland, also
weighed whether police who invite the media along can be held
liable for violating the suspect's Fourth Amendment right against
unreasonable searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices, citing the privacy rights of individuals,
appeared disturbed by the decision of U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service officers to bring television reporters and cameras along as
they searched Paul and Erma Berger's 75,000-acre Montana ranch on
March 24, 1993. Justices also seemed perturbed, based on the same
privacy concerns, with the decision of the U.S. Marshals Service
and local police to allow two newspaper reporters, one with a still
camera, to join the officers as they tried to execute an arrest
warrant at the Rockville, Md., home of fugitive Dominic Wilson's
parents at 6:45 a.m. April 14, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The cases the high court heard depart from the usual Fourth
Amendment litigation in which a defendant urges the justices to
rule a search unconstitutional in order to prevent incriminating
evidence from being used in court.
</P>
<P>
   In the Montana and Maryland cases, the people searched are suing
the police, saying the officers violated their constitutional right
against unreasonable searches and seizures by bringing the media
along.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the police argued that the officers acted
constitutionally when they invited the reporters. But even if the
police did violate the Constitution, they cannot be sued because
they acted under a reasonable belief that their actions were
legitimate, the attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   But attorneys for the people searched countered that the
officers exceeded their constitutional authority. The attorneys
also argued that the police could not have reasonably believed that
bringing reporters and cameras to watch them execute search and
arrest warrants was allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Richard Cordray, representing the police in the Montana
and Maryland cases, told the high court that officers have a
legitimate interest in having reporters join them as they execute
warrants. He said media coverage of the police in action could
boost public confidence in crime fighters and deter people from
violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices David H. Souter and Antonin Scalia expressed
concern that police, in their desire for good public relations,
might trample on the privacy rights of people. Souter said the
police can avoid the privacy issue by holding press conferences
after executing a search warrant and extolling how successful their
action was.
</P>
<P>
   A sarcastic Scalia wondered aloud if the police have enough
authority to let family members attend an arrest or search.
Imagining himself the subject of a police search, Scalia told
Cordray that ``personally, I'd rather have your sister-in-law
along'' than the media.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from the justices, Cordray, of Grove City,
Ohio, conceded that police bringing reporters into a person's home
would raise serious constitutional concerns. But Cordray, referring
to the Maryland case, said it is reasonable for the media to be
present when officers execute an arrest warrant, one of the most
important elements of police work.
</P>
<P>
   Assisting Cordray, attorney Lawrence Fletcher-Hill argued that
the police cannot be held liable even if the high court decides
that the Constitution barred them from inviting the media to the
searches. No court had ruled on the validity of the controversial
searches when they were conducted in the early 1990s and,
therefore, it was ``reasonable'' for the police to believe their
invitations were proper, argued Fletcher-Hill, an assistant
attorney general of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the people searched, Henry Rossbacher, said that
the police may invite to arrests and searches only those people
needed to help in executing the warrant, which generally does not
include reporters. For example, police searching someone's house
for stolen goods can certainly bring along the person whose items
were stolen to identify the property, said Rossbacher of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Assisting Rossbacher, attorney Richard Willard objected to the
contention that the police acted reasonably in bringing reporters
along, saying the media's attendance violated the privacy rights of
those searched. Willard, of Washington, urged the justices to adopt
``a bright line rule drawn at the front door of the home,'' which
the police cannot allow the media to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Media outlets joined in a legal brief urging the justices to
rule for the police. ``A rule that it is unreasonable per se to
permit the press to observe the execution of a search warrant will
unnecessarily deprive the public of valuable information about the
functioning of its government,'' the media companies wrote in their
brief.
</P>
<P>
   Souter said officers could reasonably believe that media
presence during an arrest or at a search is a valid method for
building public support for law enforcement. ``We live in a
political world,'' said Souter, adding that good press could result
in increased funding for the police.
</P>
<P>
   Willard, however, rejected the public-relations argument, saying
``the framers of the Fourth Amendment would roll over in their
graves'' if police were free to bring reporters into the private
residences of people being arrested or searched.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the cases,
Hanlon vs. Berger and Wilson vs. Layne, by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the controversial search of the Bergers' Montana ranch,
officers found the poison Furadan, which Paul Berger put on sheep
carcasses in an attempt to kill eagles and other predators on his
ranch. Paul was convicted of the federal crime of using a
registered pesticide in a manner inconsistent with its labeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergers sued the officers who invited the media. The 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco, reversing a lower
court decision against the Bergers, said it was unreasonable for an
officer to believe he could invite reporters on a search.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maryland case, police, with reporters in tow, entered the
home of Charles and Geraldine Wilson, whose son was wanted on a
charge of violating probation. The officers found Charles Wilson in
his underwear and Geraldine Wilson in a sheer nightgown. One
reporter took notes and the other took pictures. Charles and
Geraldine Wilson sued the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va.,
reversing a lower court decision for the Wilsons, said the officers
reasonably believed their invitation to the media was permissible.
The appeals court did not address whether the police violated the
Fourth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
