<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-PHYSICS-SOCIETY25 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unknown physical force may be pushing Pioneer 10
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Strange things are happening to Pioneer 10, the little
spacecraft launched in 1972 and now winging its way through deep
space outside our solar system, researchers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists described the problem as a slight, unexplained
acceleration of the spacecraft. A similar problem is affecting its
sister craft, Pioneer 11. Nothing that the physicists have in their
repertoire of possible causes can explain the situation -
suggesting an unknown physical force may be acting to speed the
spacecraft along.
</P>
<P>
   If no explanation is forthcoming, ``then we must consider the
small probability that nature is saying something new,'' says
Martin Nieto, a physicist with the Los Alamos National Laboratoryo.
</P>
<P>
   Nieto presented the findings at the 100th annual meeting of the
American Physical Society in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He said several explanations have been offered for the slight
acceleration, but none of them are conclusion. For instance,
scientists thought it might be due to heat from the instrument
compartment being vented from the rear of the craft, computer
errors or gas leaks from the altitude-control thrusters. But none
of those pan out.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have suggested that a fifth unknown force - the
other four are gravity; electromagnetism and the strong and weak
forces in atoms - may be present in the universe, but none was
willing to discuss such a possibility on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nieto said the effect is not observed in planetary or asteroid
orbits. What is needed is a force that affects the 570-pound
Pioneer spacecraft, but does not affect planets or asteroids. That
would be a ``tall order,'' Nieto said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pioneers are the first man-made objects to break free of our
solar system. The spacecraft are expected to travel for thousands
of years, eventually within hailing distance of other stars.
</P>
<P>
   In other reports Wednesday at the APS meeting:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Researchers with NASA say that almost everywhere they look in
the universe, they are finding an abundance of big organic
molecules. These molecules may be the precursors for life, and
their ubiquitous presence adds more evidence to theories that life
may be common in the universe. ``We probably are only at the
beginning for finding even more complex organic molecules,'' said
Lou Allamandola of NASA's Ames Research Center in California.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  John Simpson, a noted University of Chicago scientist who also
worked on the Manhattan Project that produced the world's first
atomic bomb, urged the development of safe nuclear reactors that
could meet a growing energy demand while reducing the risk of
nuclear fuel proliferation for bombs. ``The world isn't going to
wait around for the United States to phase out of nuclear energy,''
said Simpson. ``The developing nations represent 90 percent of the
world's population and they're going to go nuclear. We have to face
that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
