<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-STARTREK-ERRORS25     03-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-STARTREK-ERRORS25 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The American Physical Society's 100th annual meeting: Aliens'
visits unlikely, expert says
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Extraterrestrials would be bound by the same laws of physics we
are, says physics professor.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ET might call us. But he won't visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extraterrestrial aliens haven't visited here and won't be
coming here,'' says Lawrence Krauss, chairman of the physics
department at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It's a message he's been touting this week at the 100th
anniversary meeting of the American Physical Society. Krauss, who
has been called the successor to Carl Sagan for popularizing
science among the masses, ridicules the idea of an alien invasion _
and other sci-fi concepts masquerading as science on popular TV
shows and movies.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that there are no extraterrestrials out there. Krauss
believes millions of planets around other stars in the universe
harbor life, although far fewer probably have intelligent life. But
he believes even if advanced civilizations exist elsewhere in the
universe, they are bound by the same laws of physics we are. Those
laws would make it pretty tough for them to get to Earth or
anywhere else in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the nearest star to Earth is about four light
years away. Others are hundreds, thousands and even millions of
light years away. A light year is the distance light, which travels
at 186,000 miles per hour, travels in an entire year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can travel faster than the speed of light in empty
space, so you don't just zip from star to star,'' says Krauss. Even
if an advanced civilization could build a spaceship that could
travel at near the speed of light, the energy requirement would be
stupendous, equivalent to the energy produced by many stars.
</P>
<P>
   Krauss is especially critical of TV shows and movies that
purport to explore reports of alien visitation, from mind-altering
implants to abductions, and treat it as ``news.'' One such program
was broadcast in February by NBC: ``Confirmation: The Hard Evidence
of Aliens Among Us?''
</P>
<P>
   It is little more than ``yellow journalism,'' says Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   Krauss, however, is a fan of ``Star Trek,'' the TV and movie
series about the starship Enterprise's travels through the
universe. In flitting about the galaxy, the ship bends all kinds of
physics laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's compelling science fiction,'' he says, adding that he is
fascinated with the explanations the crew offers for overcoming the
limits of physics.
</P>
<P>
   In his lectures and in his 1996 book ``The Physics of Star
Trek,'' Krauss reveals what the series got wrong _ and what it got
right _ about science.
</P>
<P>
   An example of a ``physics blooper'': One episode shows an
explosion in space, obviously hundreds of miles away, as viewed
from the bridge of the Enterprise. It is seen and heard at exactly
the same moment, even though sound does not travel in empty space.
(And even if it did, light and sound travel at different speeds.)
</P>
<P>
   Krauss also pokes holes in the idea of a transporter, the ``Star
Trek'' gizmo that gave rise to the phrase, ``Beam me up, Scotty.''
One of the many problems he finds with such a machine is having to
encode all the information in a human body _ including all of the
atoms whose number amounts to 10 followed by 28 zeros _ to zap it
from one place to another. ``That's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he puts down most of ``Star Trek's'' gadgets and gizmos,
he ends up on the side of human imagination. While its writers may
not have gotten everything right, the power of the imagination
could one day make travel to the stars possible. ``But it will
never be a round trip.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: Our site offers a full schedule of events at the
physicists' meeting, plus daily coverage by the
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
