<HEADLINE>
KINGS HOPING TO FINISH 9-3 TO MAKE PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even for one of the top teams in the NHL, the task
would be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   And the Los Angeles Kings are not one of the top teams in the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   As they looked Wednesday at the schedule for the final
three-plus weeks of the regular season, beginning with a home game
tonight against the league-leading Dallas Stars, several Kings made
a prediction: The team probably needs to post a 9-3 record in its
final 12 games to have a realistic shot at making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the hunt,'' defenseman Doug Bodger said
following practice at Iceoplex. ``We're going to do our best to put
a streak together.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings finish 9-3, it will be a major accomplishment,
considering the remaining schedule includes two games against
Dallas, two at Colorado and one at Detroit, the three teams most
likely to skate with the Stanley Cup at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a visit to Boston, where the Kings have won twice
since the 1980-81 season, two games at Nashville (the Kings are 0-2
against the first-year Predators), a home game against the Mighty
Ducks (against whom they are 0-5 this season) and a home game
against the St. Louis Blues (who the Kings haven't beaten in two
years).
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to go after this first game,'' Coach Larry
Robinson said when asked if there was a more palatable way for the
Kings to view their task. ``It's all you can worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the first game is against the Stars, against whom
the Kings have suffered four one-goal losses this season. The Kings
haven't beaten Dallas since Barry Melrose was coach, posting an
0-10-6 record since then. ``I'm sure it's definitely a mental
thing,'' Robinson said. ``You question if you're ever going to beat
them. I think if there ever was a time where we wanted to beat
them, this would be the time.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE PUCKS: Defenseman Dave Babych, acquired Tuesday in the
trade that sent Steve Duchesne to Philadelphia, is expected to
participate in the morning skate today, but probably will not play
tonight, Robinson said. ``I think he brings a hell of a lot of
experience,'' Robinson said. ``He maybe will give us some
stability. He's not the answer to the future. But he's still a good
player.'' Babych, 37, was the second player chosen in the 1980
draft, right after the late Doug Wickenheiser was selected by
Montreal and eight picks before the Kings chose Jim Fox, now the
color commentator on their telecasts. ... Of the Duchesne trade,
Robinson said, ``I'll be the first one to say he's not totally the
reason we are where we are. At the same time, he's part of the
reason. We had higher expectations of him running the power play
and it didn't work out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
