<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHASE-MANHATTAN-ART-N     03-24 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-MANHATTAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 CHASE NAMES A CEO WHO CAN HANDLE DIVERSE PERSONALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an unexpected move that is likely to dampen merger
speculation surrounding the nation's third-largest bank, the Chase
Manhattan Corp. said Wednesday that William B. Harrison would
succeed Walter V. Shipley as chief executive on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Chase also said that Thomas G. Labrecque, 60, the bank's
president and chief operating officer, would retire on June 1.
Harrison, 55, currently a vice chairman who supervises Chase's
lucrative corporate banking and trading businesses, will assume
Labrecque's duties at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley, 63, who will remain the bank's chairman, has repeatedly
said that he plans to retire at the latest by November 2000, after
his 65th birthday. Analysts and other observers had expected a new
chief executive to be named closer to that date. Within the bank,
it was widely believed that Shipley might try to recruit a new
chief executive through a merger with another major financial
services firm.
</P>
<P>
   But the promotion of Harrison, who is slated to add the
chairman's title to his portfolio when Shipley retires, resolves
the timing of the succession issue at Chase _ if not fully putting
to rest the possibility of a merger sometime within the next year
or two. Chase has courted a number of brokerage firms recently but
is not desperate to consummate a merger, largely because of the
stellar financial results the bank has been posting.
</P>
<P>
   While Shipley's imminent retirement undoubtedly made the bank
more attractive to certain merger partners, Shipley scoffed at the
notion that he was holding his job out to affect a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press reports that sort of portray me wandering around
offering the CEO position, that's not how things work,'' he said
Wednesday. ``We feel very comfortable with how the company is today
and looking forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase executives and bank advisers have said privately that
Chase, which wants to enhance its ability to underwrite and sell
stock, is likely to try to snap up Lehman and Paine Webber in quick
succession or merge with J.P. Morgan rather than pursue a deal with
larger firms like Merrill Lynch or Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
Merrill's chief executive, David H. Komansky, told analysts last
Friday that his company, while not ruling out a merger in the
future, was in no hurry to do a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Harrison's ascension indicates that Chase
will eventually set its sights on a smaller partner. ``I think the
perception in some quarters that they were managing the company for
a merger may have caused some unrest within the senior ranks,''
said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``But I
think the announcement will probably deflate takeover speculation
involving major brokerage firms and may lead to a deal with a
second-tier firm like Lehman Brothers, Paine Webber, or J.P.
Morgan.''
</P>
<P>
   Merger issues aside, Harrison, who joined Chase in 1967 after
earning a bachelor's degree in economics from the University of
North Carolina, was not considered a shoe-in for the top job. An
executive reshuffling in late 1997 appeared to weaken Harrison's
position at the bank, leading many analysts to believe that Marc
Shapiro, Chase's head of finance and risk management, would succeed
Shipley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Harrison is a very reasonable choice but I think the view
on the Street was that Marc was going to get the job,'' said David
Berry, an analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc. ``Having said
that, this is a real vote for continuity because Harrison's done a
very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, although not regarded as a particularly charismatic
leader, has a strong command of Chase's operations and has
effectively corralled some of the more abrasive egos within Chase's
executive suite, most notably that of James B. Lee, the volatile
head of Chase's large corporate lending business.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley, a modest and well-regarded executive who has quietly
managed two of the largest mergers in the banking industry,
Wednesday made note of Harrison's talent for managing diverse
personalities. Shipley said that was one of the leading factors in
Harrison's favor when he began asking Chase's board to anoint his
successor about six months ago, a decision which he said had
nothing to do with merger considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the board's judgment that he was the right guy,''
Shipley said in a telephone interview. ``Bill is the architect of
what now represents about two-thirds of the bank's earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said he planned to make few drastic changes. ``The
value story that Walter and Tom have created here is something I
feel great about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added he would continue to oversee Chase's corporate
businesses and did not intend to appoint a chief operating officer,
president or any other executive to be second-in-command. He said
all of the bank's senior executives in the consumer and corporate
businesses would retain their current titles and positions.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was speculation Wednesday about Shapiro's
commitment to Chase after having been passed over for the chief
executive's spot, Shapiro said in an interview that he was
``excited about the company'' and firmly intended to stay. He noted
that he and Harrison had been close friends for two decades and
that he ``admires what Bill has done'' at Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Although Labrecque shared senior duties with Shipley, he was
never considered a serious contender for the chief executive spot.
Labrecque was the chief executive of Chase Manhattan when it merged
with Shipley's Chemical Banking Corp. in 1996. The new bank kept
the Chase name, but was otherwise dominated by Chemical executives.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts expected Labrecque to leave after that
merger was completed, he remained longer largely because of his own
determination and Shipley's willingness to accept him as an equal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
