<SLUG> BC-CAR-SPEEDWAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY NIGHT OFFERS SMALL TASTE OF INDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Some have called Irwindale Speedway a mini
version of nearby California Speedway in Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 25, it will seem more like Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   That's the night when the twin-ring oval is the site of the 59th
Turkey Night Grand Prix, the Indy 500 of open-wheel midget cars.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of several marquee races on Irwindale's 68-event
inaugural season schedule. Others include two NASCAR Featherlite
Southwest series races on July 31 and Oct. 2 and a USAC Coors
Silver Crown series event on Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   None should be be bigger then the Turkey Night Grand Prix, which
in recent years has been held at Mesa Marin Speedway in Bakersfield
and Perris Auto Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   A list of past Turkey Night competitors reads like a who's who
of open-wheel racing, including four-time Indianapolis 500 champion
A.J. Foyt and Indy Racing League standout Bill Boat. Boat won the
event for three consecutive years from 1995-97 before graduating
full-time to the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you combine the history of the event with this facility,
there's certainly the possibility for it to be as big as (the
Indianapolis 500),'' said Tommy Hunt, USAC's vice president for
Western States Operations. ``(Turkey Night) is such a huge event
for USAC with a lot of history. And this is such an incredible
place. It's a great combination.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Turkey Night Grand Prix tops the list of showcase
events, it's not the only reason to head out to Irwindale Speedway
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The USAC Coors Silver Crown series event on Oct. 16 will
showcase some of the drivers who will compete at the November race,
including 1998 champion Jay Drake and 1999 USAC points leader Jason
Lefler.
</P>
<P>
   The two NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Tour events feature
slightly smaller versions of the ones raced on the NASCAR Winston
Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 series champion, Steve Portenga of Reno, Nev., will
lead the charge around the Irwindale half-mile oval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
