A2997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR25-COX     03-24 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio gov. pledges to uphold `the union tradition'
 &HT;    By William Hershey and Wes Hills
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. Bob Taft, whose grandfather remains a
villain to the American labor movement nearly 50 years after his
death, drew a standing ovation Wednesday from the Ohio AFL-CIO when
he promised to withhold support from any effort to dismantle ``the
union tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor's show of support highlighted a day in
which Ohio union leaders flexed their muscles against a backdrop of
shrinking membership and a statehouse legislative agenda full of
anti-union proposals.
</P>
<P>
   It also marked another movement by the governor away from his
own party's conservative wing and toward the political center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a welcome comment by him to try to find middle
ground between labor and a Republican governor so we can work
together toward some common goals,'' said Tom Ritchie, Dayton-based
regional director of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees' Ohio Council 8.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie was among about 300 participants at Ohio AFL-CIO's
Legislative Conference who marched a block and half through the
center of downtown Columbus from the Adams Mark Hotel to the
statehouse where they fanned out for individual meetings with
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders interpreted Taft's remarks to mean that he would
not support a so-called right-to-work bill now before the
legislature. It would remove any requirement that workers join
unions or pay dues as a condition of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Taft, in a hurried exchange with reporters, declined to comment
on specific legislation. But Scott Milburn, his spokesman, said the
governor was referring to the right-to-work bill, cosponsored by
Dayton-area Rep. Jeff Jacobson, a Phillipsburg Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news,'' said Wes Wells, executive director of the
Miami Valley Regional Labor Council
</P>
<P>
   Taft's grandfather, the late Sen. Robert A. Taft, who died in
1953, was the author of the 1947 Taft-Hartley labor law which
weakened unions by calling for cooling-off periods before strikes
and requiring union officers to sign affidavits disavowing
Communist Party connections.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction of the the governor, Ohio AFL-CIO President
William Burga recalled labor's opposition to Taft's grandfather but
urged the audience to give the governor a polite welcome. Burga
said Taft was the first Republican governor who has agreed to
address a legislative meeting of the state labor group. Burga, in
an interview, called Taft-Hartley, the ``worst labor act ever
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor warmed up to Burga and the crowd right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also want you to know that I respect who you are and what
you are all about,'' Taft said. ``Everyone who works in Ohio today
owes the union movement, the labor movement, a great debt of
gratitude for improving wages, working conditions, benefits and
workplace safety.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that as governor he recognized the ``role that unions
have played and will continue to play in making Ohio one of the
most productive places in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   While he and union members may not agree on everything, Taft
said that he wants them to have a ``relationship based on open
access and easy communication.''
</P>
<P>
   He also thanked them for supporting his health care reform
proposal, the Patient Protection Act, which would give consumers
the right to sue their health plan for medical malpractice. Taft
has had trouble finding Republican support for this plan.
</P>
<P>
   Burga, the state AFL-CIO president, was pleased with Taft's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it about time? Whether they're Democrats or Republicans,
they're supposed to be on the side of the people. We represent the
working people, not just union members.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
