</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF OFFICIAL EXPECTS MORE AID FOR INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ A senior official of the International Monetary Fund
said here Wednesday that he expected the fund to approve more
financial aid to Indonesia in a board meeting in Washington on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Neiss, the fund's Asia Pacific director, said, ``the IMF
will propose that the existing commitments be increased.'' He said
such an increase requires the board's approval, but added, ``I
would expect that the board will agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's chief economics official, Ginandjar Kartasasmita,
had asked for an extra $1 billion in aid in a meeting last month
with the fund's managing director, Michel Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss would not say how large the increase would be. But last
year, the fund approved an additional $1 billion in aid to
Indonesia, raising its total commitment to $11.2 billion. All told,
Jakarta is receiving a $43 billion rescue package from the fund and
other international aid groups .
</P>
<P>
   The fund has already disbursed $8.8 billion, and analysts said
the Indonesian government was worried that unless the IMF agreed to
pledge more, the country might have trouble soliciting aid from
other sources.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's move to release more aid is both an acknowledgment of
the steps Indonesia has taken to overhaul its shattered economy and
a sign of how far it still must go to join the ranks of the
recovering in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss said Indonesia needed the extra help because, unlike South
Korea or Thailand, it was not yet attracting private capital.
Analysts said foreign investors were generally steering clear of
Indonesia as it made a trouble-prone transition from the Suharto
era to a more democratic system.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neiss praised Indonesia for taking steps to clean up its
ruined banking system. On March 13, the government of President
B.J. Habibie closed 38 banks, took over seven and indicated it
would bail out nine others.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after a sudden two-week postponement that had
provoked new cries of cronyism from government critics. Critics
said that politically connected bankers had pressured Habibie to
order the delay so that they could raise capital and save their
banks from closure.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss said that while he regretted the delay, ``I prefer
postponement to things going wrong.'' He added: ``No bank owner in
any country would like to have his bank closed. They will fight
tooth and nail to keep it open.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiss made his remarks to reporters at an investment conference
in Hong Kong sponsored by Credit Suisse First Boston. Earlier in
the day, he sparred with a leading critic of the fund: Jeffrey D.
Sachs, a Harvard economist, who has accused the fund of aggravating
the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs renewed those criticisms Wednesday, saying that the fund's
insistence on high interest rates and stable currencies had
deepened investor panic and capital flight in Thailand and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss replied that the fund's policies calmed South Korea when
it was hit by a wave of capital outflows in late 1997. He also said
the fund should not be blamed for the region's collapse. Rather, he
said, the governments did not respond quickly enough to the
unfolding crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In general, though, Neiss struck a mostly optimistic note. He
predicted that most Asian economies would return to growth in the
second half of 1999. ``When we say the worst is over, we are simply
stating the facts,'' he said. ``The larger task of getting the
recovery off the ground is still before us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
