A2999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSTITUTE-DIRECTOR-NY     03-24 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTITUTE-DIRECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO PROFESSOR TO HEAD RESPECTED BIOMEDICAL INSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Del., Md.) (rk) 
 By   NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Howard Hughes Medical Institute has chosen as its next
president Thomas R. Cech, an expert on the chemistry of biological
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment will make Cech a significant patron of
biomedical research, giving him the power to dispense more than
$500 million a year in research funds and to shape research
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The institute had a colorful beginning as an instrument created
by Howard Hughes, the eccentric aviator and industrialist, to
minimize interference by the federal government in his industrial
empire.
</P>
<P>
   It has grown over the last 15 years to become a prominent player
in the world of biomedicine. Its awards are highly coveted because
they are more generous than those given by the National Institutes
of Health, the major source of federal funds for biomedical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The 318 scientists now supported by the institute include many
of the nation's most prominent biologists.
</P>
<P>
   Cech, who won the Nobel Prize in chemistry in 1989, is in some
ways a surprising choice because at 51 he is comparatively young
and still actively engaged in research. He is a professor at the
University of Colorado and has a reputation for the rigor of his
experiments as well as for his enjoyment of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna Gray, president emeritus of the University of Chicago and
chairwoman of the institute's board, said Cech (pronounced check)
was chosen because of his scientific credentials and his interest
in education, the institute's two principal activities. ``He is a
first-rate scientist with excellent taste in science, someone who
is widely respected and admired within the scientific community,''
Dr. Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, over which Cech will assume control next January,
has an endowment of $11.4 billion. Its offices are in a sumptuous
new building in Chevy Chase, Md., near the National Institutes of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   The institute was founded by Hughes in 1953 and vested with
ownership of the Hughes Aircraft Co. at a time when the Air Force
seemed intent on taking control of the company because of Hughes'
chaotic management. But the institute did close to nothing until
Hughes, its sole trustee, died without a will in 1976, leaving no
instructions as to his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Its modern era began in 1984, when a Delaware court vested
control of the institute in a board of nine trustees. The new board
sold its single asset, Hughes Aircraft, to the General Motors Corp.
for $5.2 billion and made peace with the Internal Revenue Service,
which had long been on its heels.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Purnell W. Choppin, its president since
1987, and W. Maxwell Cowan, its chief scientific officer, the
institute has come to finance the best of the nation's academic
biologists, replacing the National Institutes of Health as their
major patron.
</P>
<P>
   Cech said he had ``many ideas but no agenda'' until he took
office. He also said he would continue to spend one week a month in
his Colorado laboratory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
