A3000 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CACTUS-LADN     03-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINING DIAMONDS IN THE DESERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ ``If you build it, they will come'' became the
catch phrase in ``Field of Dreams,'' the movie that starred Kevin
Costner.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Cactus League has made it work in the real world,
only there are no corn fields to be found here in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   The Cactus League is booming now, attracting major league teams
to the Valley of the Sun faster than you can say Dodgertown. Ten of
the major leagues' 30 teams conduct spring training here, with more
expected to come, possibly even the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of Cactus League teams are playing at facilities that have
been built within the past six years. The oldest -- the Angels'
6-year-old Tempe Diablo Stadium -- still sparkles in the desert
sun.
</P>
<P>
   The trend now is to put two teams in one extra-large complex.
That's the case in Peoria, where the Mariners and Padres share the
Peoria Sports Complex, and in Tucson, where the Diamondbacks and
White Sox share Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs (Mesa) and Brewers (Maryvale) train in new facilities,
and the Giants play in a rebuilt Scottsdale Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the growth of the Cactus League can be traced to the
departure of the Cleveland Indians, who left Tucson for Florida in
1991. That prompted the Arizona state legislature to form stadium
districts to provide funds to improve existing facilities and to
build new ones. A rental-car tax in Maricopa County helped raise
most of the approximately $100 million that revitalized the Cactus
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland was the only team in Tucson and they shocked
everybody by moving to Florida,'' said Jerry Geiger, president of
the Cactus League since 1996. ``It was a wake-up call. Other teams
were worried about other teams leaving. If there were only four
teams here, there would not be enough competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the turnaround was the `T' word (tax) nobody wants
to hear about,'' Michael Scully, executive director of the Maricopa
County Sports Commission, told the Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Based on surveys, out-of-state and out-of-area fans pump $100
million a year into the Arizona economy.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is up throughout the Cactus League this season, after
a slight drop in attendance last year blamed on El Nio-related bad
weather in early March.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who train at Mesa's HoHoKam Park, are traditionally
the biggest draw, and are even more attractive this year with Sammy
Sosa the talk of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we were heading into a better season. Thank you,
Sammy,'' Robert Brinton, head of the Mesa Visitors and Convention
Bureau, told the Arizona Republic. ``It's more festive all
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are considering joining the party in Arizona after
spending 50 years in Vero Beach, Fla. They are negotiating to move
to the Fort McDowell Yavapai-Apache Indian Reservation, located
northeast of downtown Phoenix. The complex would cost $20 million
to $30 million and hold 12,500 fans. The Dodgers would likely share
the facility with another club, possibly the Royals, Blue Jays,
Astros, Rangers or Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have not ruled out staying in Vero Beach, which
relies on the $30 million generated by the team for its economy
every spring. Vero Beach and Indian River County have proposed
buying Holman Stadium, the practice fields and the conference
center from the Dodgers, then leasing them back to the team for a
minimal amount.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that the Dodgers could train in Arizona, a 1
1/2-hour flight from Los Angeles, and that Southern California fans
and sponsors would be more likely to visit might be too good for
the Dodgers to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough decision for them to make,'' Geiger
said. ``The economics of the decision favor Arizona. But we also
understand and appreciate the 50-year tradition they have there,
going back to the old Brooklyn Dodger days in Florida. It's going
to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have always been a part of the Cactus League, but
until 1993, split spring training between facilities in Mesa,
Ariz., and Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the benefits of a new ballpark, clubhouse and front
office facilities, the Angels have enjoyed the convenience that has
resulted since moving to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regard to the coaching staff and the front office,
performance didn't improve, but the ease with which it took to
prepare improved,'' Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, once the Angels' director of minor league operations,
said the biggest impact the move had on the organization was at the
minor league level.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' minor league camp is at Gene Autry Park in Mesa, but
with no central spring training headquarters in place, the club had
to rent trailers to serve as their spring training offices every
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the games there were like road games for us, because the
players would have to dress at a hotel nearby,'' Bavasi said.
</P>
<P>
   That's one prickly situation that was solved by moving to Tempe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
