<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK CAR FRENZY TOUCHES DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Stock car racing is one of the country's
fastest growing spectator sports. NASCAR events annually draw more
than six million fans and have worked their way into mainstream
America.
</P>
<P>
   Irwindale Speedway, which is scheduled to open its gates
Saturday, hopes to take advantage of that frenzy twice this season
when it plays host to a pair of NASCAR Winston West 250-lap events,
in June and August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely will be the marquee event there,'' said Glendora
businessman Joe Nava, Winston West team owner for the No.77 Ford
Taurus driven by Joe Bean. ``That's going to be good for Irwindale
and be good for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cars are identical to what you will see in Winston Cup.
We have good equipment with good drivers. You're going to see a lot
of side-by-side racing. It should be very exciting. We're just
hoping we can be the inaugural winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Winston West series, which has launched the careers
of Winston Cup regulars Derrike Cope and Chad Little, is nearly as
old as NASCAR itself.
</P>
<P>
   It started in 1954 when it was known as Grand National West. It
has experienced nearly the same amount of growth as Winston Cup.
This year, series sponsor Winston has increased its contribution in
the points fund from $50,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for us to get two Winston West races is pretty
prestigious,'' said Doug Stokes, Irwindale Speedway's director of
communications. ``A lot of tracks have just one race, and we have
two. If you're a NASCAR fan, it's a really big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston West cars are virtually the same as those raced in
Winston Cup events. Both feature wheel bases of 110 inches and
maintain a minimum weight of 3,400 pounds. The cars are powered by
a 358-cubic inch V-8 engines. The difference lies in the
compression ratio; Winston West cars are limited to a 9.5-to-1
ratio.
</P>
<P>
   The series visits tracks ranging in size from Irwindale's
half-mile oval to Roger Penske's two-mile D-shaped California
Speedway in nearby Fontana. The tour also competes at Las Vegas
Speedway and on two road courses, including Sears Point Raceway in
Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   The events held at California Speedway, Las Vegas and Sonoma
serve as support races for Winston Cup events, so most of the 30
drivers who compete regularly on the starter series are excited to
come to Irwindale's new half-mile superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Las Vegas (and some of the other big tracks), other races
are the headliners,'' said Dan Bixler, marketing director for
Winston West rookie Rick Ware. ``At Irwindale, we will be the big
cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   While neither Jeff Gordon nor Dale Earnhardt will drive at
Irwindale, some of the future stars of Winston Cup will be
competing, including 1997 series champion Butch Gilliland of Chino
Hills and Sean Woodside of Saugus.
</P>
<P>
   El Monte's Kenny Smith, winner of the California Lotto in 1994,
is also slated to compete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
