<HEADLINE>
AID WORKER ESCAPES KOSOVO HOURS BEFORE BOMBS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The head of operations for a Northwest-based aid agency was one
of the last Americans to flee Kosovo Wednesday, passing massed
Serbian troops, tanks and artillery to reach safety in Macedonia
just hours before the start of NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Heselius, a 66-year-old great-grandfather who has worked
in the strife-torn province for Mercy Corps International since
since 1993, said in a telephone interview that he led a convoy of
six vehicles from the Kosovo capital of Pristina to the Macedonian
border Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it might be a bit touchy getting out because it was
very tense _ quiet but tense _ in Pristina this morning,'' Heselius
said after arriving at the Skopje, Macedonia, office of Mercy
Corps. ``We passed a lot of heavy artillery, tanks and military
personnel about six or eight kilometers from the border, then heard
some heavy artillery firing behind us after we had passed that
area. We crossed the border about 8:35 a.m. Everybody was glad to
be out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Heselius could have fled to safety on Tuesday after leading two
evacuation convoys on the one-hour journey from Pristina to the
Macedonian border. But on both trips, some Albanian members of
Mercy Corps and other aid agencies were denied permission to cross
the border because they didn't have the proper documents.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to abandon his local staff at the frontier, Heselius
and another American, Scott Charlesworth, returned to Pristina with
the group late Tuesday and spent a very tense night. Wednesday
morning, just hours before NATO began bombing, they made a final,
successful dash for the border.
</P>
<P>
   Heselius said his ethnic Albanian colleagues _ four adults and
seven children _ drove their own vehicle and had arrived safely in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Among Heselius' passengers were two CNN correspondents whose
vehicle tires had been slashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were probably the last Americans to leave Pristina,'' said
Heselius, a former businessman who lived in Kirkland from 1991
until early 1993, when he joined Portland-based Mercy Corps as head
of the agency's Kosovo operations. ``The CNN crew had no
transportation. The civilian (Serb) population in Kosovo was
getting dangerous. Many of them are armed and this kind of
situation gives them a reason to do anything they want to do. You
can see the animosity and there's not much you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heselius, a devout Christian, said he prayed Wednesday before
making the final journey to the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I felt pretty good about it,'' said Heselius. He
plans to stay in Macedonia in hopes he will soon be able to return
to Kosovo and resume the aid program he established six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will soon come to some sort of solution,'' he
said. ``If so, I've got to go back in to help people. There are a
lot of people in there who need help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
