</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SEEK TO CAPITALIZE ON IMPEACHMENT PROCEEDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as congressional Republicans work publicly to
shed their image as the party of impeachment, party officials
behind the scenes are using the trial of President Clinton as a
fund-raising tool with conservatives to help Republicans keep
control of the House of Representatives next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee on Tuesday began testing a
direct-mail appeal for a ``Republican Impeachment Supporters
Election Fund.'' The letter, signed by Jim Nicholson, the party
chairman, says, ``The Republicans who impeached President Clinton
are now being targeted for defeat by one of the most vicious
liberal Democrat, Big Labor Boss, special interest group campaigns
in American history.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The appeal notes that a $20 contribution would amount to 10
cents ``per Republican congressman who voted for impeachment and is
under attack,'' and asked for contributions as high as $60. ``The
defeat of our Republicans by those vowing revenge will be President
Clinton's final victory and it will undercut our chances of
recapturing the White House in 2000,'' the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee, which raises
money for House races, is considering a telephone appeal that would
feature one or more of the 13 House managers who prosecuted the
president. Some House Republicans are also in the process of
creating a ``Defend Our Managers'' Web site, which they hope will
draw at least 10,000 hits, raising an average of $10 each. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And several House Republicans are using political action
committees to raise money for the the House impeachment managers or
else benefit from their appeal in conservative circles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republican drive is the flip side of Democratic efforts to
capitalize on impeachment. Determined to win back the House,
Clinton himself has raised more than $9 million for Democrats since
mid-January, and party officials attribute the surge in donations
to a backlash against Republican efforts to remove the president.
People for the American Way, a civil liberties group, has begun a
$5 million ``Recall the Right'' drive to help Democrats regain
control of the House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they are responding to reports that Clinton is
seeking to defeat them because of their drive against him. ``You
feel very uncomfortable trying to make money off of impeachment,''
said Rep. Thomas M. Davis III of Virginia, the chairman of the
House Republican re-election effort. ``You almost cheapen it. But
the president has done it. The Democratic leaders are doing it. You
can't sit idly by and be a punching bag. We are testing the market
on an appropriate way to respond.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are not yet certain how successful the appeals will
prove. Some of the party's big business donors were uncomfortable
with the impeachment drive, but officials say that the House
managers have become conservative cult heroes who are spawning
spontaneous fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for example, Jane Chastain, a conservative radio
talk show host and commentator for Crawford Broadcasting, asked
listeners last month to ``adopt'' a House impeachment manager and
held an adoption ceremony on her show. ``The phones were just
jammed,'' she said in an interview on Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said she told listeners to help in any way they could,
including providing campaign funds. ``If you're a good adoptive
parent you support your kids in every way they need to be
supported,'' she said. ``They need your prayers. They need your
encouragement. In some cases they need your dollars.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham of South Carolina, one of the managers, said
he is now in high demand as a party speaker. ``It's been an
unbelievable experience for me,'' Graham said. ``I sit in an
airport for five minutes reading a paper and half a dozen people
come up and just kind of shake my hand and say we're really proud
of what you tried to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist experimenting with fund raising
through the ``Defend Our Managers'' Web site said the appeal of the
Internet is that unlike direct mail, it is an inexpensive way to
prospect for donations. ``On line has low overhead, low
maintenance,'' he said. ``If it is out there it will come. If it's
not it will cost you $90 bucks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that that many of the managers will actually
need huge infusions of money. Only two are from districts that are
considered competitive between the two parties _ Reps. Steve Chabot
of Ohio and James Rogan of California. Rogan is weighing whether to
give up his seat and challenge Sen. Dianne Feinstein next year.
Another of the House managers, Rep/ Charles Canady of Florida, will
not be running for re-election because he made a term-limit pledge,
and says he intends to abide by it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals go on. Rep. Christopher Cannon of Utah, one of
the House managers, was reported on Wednesday in The Hill newspaper
to be creating a House Managers political action committee to
handle checks that have been coming in spontaneously to the 13 men
who prosecuted the president. Jeff Hartley, a political aide to
Cannon, said the congressman had received about $3,000 in such
small donations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, who is not running again in 2000
because of a term-limits pledge, created a PAC in February that she
named ``Helen's List'' to support candidates who share her
conservative views. In a fund-raising advertisement in the national
edition of The Washington Times this month she said ``the Clinton
pit bulls are already working at raising money they will need to
elicit revenge on the House managers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. David McIntosh, R-Ind., who has long had his own PAC,
has supplemented it with a House Managers Defense Fund. In a recent
fund-raising letter, he asserted that Clinton ``wants the scalps of
all 13 House managers and any other Republican who dared to blemish
his all-important place in history.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
