<HEADER>
A3012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANMEN-NYT     03-24 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICIAL URGES BEIJING TO END TIANANMEN `COVER-UP' 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Two months before the 10th anniversary of the
crackdown on student protesters in Tiananmen Square, a former top
Chinese official has sent an impassioned letter to China's leaders
urging them to end a decade-long ``cover-up'' and to renounce the
order that sent soldiers to disperse the demonstrators, killing
hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have only one thing to say and that is to urge you to
reverse the assessment of the 1989 student demonstrations without
delay,'' wrote Bao Tong, a former Central Committee member jailed
from 1989 to 1996 for sympathizing with the protesters. ``The
events of June 4, 1989, are shameful to humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders have repeatedly defended their decision to
forcefully move out the protesters, who they said were involved in
a ``counterrevolutionary rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao's letter, dated Thursday, is an opening public salvo in what
is likely to be a tense prelude to the anniversary. Despite
constant surveillance, Bao has remained the most prominent Chinese
critic of the government's actions in 1989, expressing the
misgivings that many citizens feel but dare not utter.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the politician, he argued in the letter that the decision
to fire on students must be re-evaluated because it was morally
wrong and because it undercuts public support for China's ruling
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Letting the wrongful assessment of the events to remain
without reversal means the continuation of severe pain for the
Chinese people,'' Bao wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders have taken pains to insure that June 4 will pass
uneventfully, hoping to focus attention instead on the communist
regime's lavish 50th anniversary celebration, planned for Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have recently become more aggressive in closing down
political discussion groups and publications that were tolerated
just a year ago. And several former student protesters say they
have been visited by local public security officers and warned
``not to make trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the biggest deterrent is that Tiananmen Square _ the
only open space in this packed city of 14 million _ is currently
boarded up with high walls, closed for renovation in preparation
for the Oct. 1 celebrations. The project was originally scheduled
for completion this spring but local officials recently announced
that the reopening had been postponed until July.
</P>
<P>
   Most ordinary Chinese still regard June 4 as far ``too
sensitive'' to discuss in public. But privately, many remain deeply
chagrined about the decision to use force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people in Beijing and hundreds of thousands of
bystanders from other parts of the country watched the events
unfold,'' Bao wrote, adding: ``The history of bloodshed remains in
people's hearts; they will not forget.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Bao said he wrote the letter out of
the conviction that ``when each of us begin to speak out and make
our own views known, it will become increasingly necessary for the
leaders to reconsider the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bao has been warned about his ``unapproved'' contact
with foreign reporters and the police screen visitors to his home,
he is cryptically optimistic about his current situation: ``My life
seems free, it should be free and I hope it stays free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter is addressed to President Jiang Zemin, Prime Minister
Zhu Rongji and the members of the Politburo Standing Committee. In
the late 1980s, Bao was chief of staff for Zhao Ziyang, then the
Communist Party chief.
</P>
<P>
   But in May 1989, both Zhao and Bao opposed the used of force to
disperse the demonstrators. Both lost their jobs in the days before
the June 4 crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao has been in under house arrest ever since. On May 28, 1989,
a government driver picked Bao up at his home in Beijing for a
supposed meeting _ and drove him to prison. He spent the next seven
years in solitary confinement, followed by a year of house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   He was freed just before President Clinton's visit last summer
and immediately started speaking out on issues like free speech and
the rule of law. Expressing a common view on the streets in
Beijing, Bao says the student leaders were naive and certainly
``made mistakes,'' but adds that their protests were ``orderly''
and nonviolent. ``Whatever they did or said should be dealt with
according to democratic principles and the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bao, a political insider in the spring of 1989, places
responsibility for the crackdown on Deng Xiaoping, China's top
leader at the time, who died in 1997. He takes issue with the
conventional wisdom that China's current leadership could never
criticize the crackdown because many were already in power at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the tragedy happened, most of you were not in the highest
level decision-making positions in handling the event (except for
one who bore a lesser responsibility) and had no involvement in the
case,'' he wrote. ``It is unnecessary for you to bear such a burden
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``one who bore a lesser responsibility'' is a reference to
Li Peng, the current head of the National People's Congress, who
was China's prime minister in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Bao's letter also contains a Cassandra-like warning: That if the
Party does not reverse the verdict, 1.2 billion Chinese will rise
up and do it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to initiate the reversal of the judgment of the
1989 students demonstrations, the benefits to China would be great
and the cost would be minimal,'' he wrote. ``Such a course of
action would be beneficial to the people and to all of you, and
especially in strengthening the reputation of the Party. Therefore,
I believe it best for me to urge you, rather than others, to take
such action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
