<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-BOS &LR;      03-24 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SERBS HAVE LITTLE BUT PRIDE TO HOLD ONTO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ As low-flying missiles streaked over this capital,
signaling the start of NATO's bombing campaign, many Serbs went
about their business Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night with remarkable indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Lights stayed on in homes and businesses throughout the city,
and people could be seen waiting for city buses even after the
first explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Beaten down from the wars that broke up Yugoslavia, and the
severe economic downturn that followed it, many Serbs have nothing
to cling to except their national pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are small,'' said construction worker Tomislav Krstic, 53,
``and NATO will break their teeth on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing with him was Momo Kalkan, a Serb from the Bosnian
capital of Sarajevo, who with his wife has been run out of two
homes in this decade's Balkan conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our third war. Why not smile? It's the only weapon we
have,'' said Kalkan, who runs a grocery store here. ``We came to
Belgrade emptyhanded. Our life is the Serb story.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government line, that the West has unfairly singled
out Serbia as the whipping boy of Europe, plays well with many
here. The Serbs had few other stories to hear Wednesday, after Serb
officials cracked down on independent news outlets and
international broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an atmosphere where everything is presented as a kind of
defense of the motherland, the distinction between the regime and
the country becomes less and less,'' said Vojin Dimitrijevic, a
human rights activist and former head of the international law
department at Belgrade University.
</P>
<P>
   Air-raid sirens went off in Belgrade at about 8:05 p.m. local
time. Soon afterward, reporters on the roof of a downtown hotel saw
two bright flashes near Abala mountain, to the southeast of the
capital. Two orange flashes to the northwest of Belgrade followed,
and a dull thumping could be heard in central Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hit appeared to be to the southeast, where a bomb
led to a bright orange blaze. Repeated flashes and sparks from the
blaze suggested the missile may have hit a munitions supply.
</P>
<P>
   City and federal officials here had dug in for a fight even
before the bombings. The government, operating under an ``imminent
state of war,'' prepared bomb shelters for citizens. Local,
state-controlled television gave citizens directions on what to do
during a bombing, followed by patriotic scenes of happy Serbian
family life and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn, Serb police walked into the downtown offices of
B-92 Radio and arrested the independent station's editor in chief,
Veran Matic. They demanded that reporters move away from their
computers and set down their telephones, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   The police, accusing the station of having exceeded the allowed
power limit for radio transmissions, delivered a Telecommunications
Ministry order banning the station from transmitting, said Matic,
who was released after spending eight hours in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The order removed Belgrade's last source of independent
broadcast news. The police also removed a critical piece of
satellite equipment required to transmit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so-called virtual repression,'' Matic said.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite equipment also was seized Wednesday from some foreign
TV outlets, including CNN. Reporters were told they could transmit
only through state-run studios.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic indicated to the West that it was willing to continue
talks on Kosovo. Serbia faces airstrikes because Milosevic has
refused to sign a Western-brokered peace agreement that gives broad
political autonomy to Kosovo, a southern province of Serbia
overwhelmingly populated by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an 11th-hour appeal from US special envoy Richard
Holbrooke, Milosevic was steadfast in rejecting a Western demand
that he allow 28,000 NATO-led troops into Kosovo to police the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In a taped appearance on state-run Serbian TV, Milosevic said he
wanted ``to continue to look for a peaceful solution to the problem
of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Serb leader said, ``The only acceptable decision,
the only right decision, was to refuse the presence of foreign
troops on our territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said he wanted to ``continue the political process''
but also ``to defend our country in the manner in which it is
attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's brother, Borislav, the Yugoslav ambassador to
Russia, also appealed for further talks.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke was in Budapest Wednesday, and Milan Bozic, a Yugoslav
government minister, said in an interview that he was confident
Holbrooke would return to Belgrade to continue talks. Holbrooke's
final public words before he left Belgrade after failed
negotiations Tuesday night were a reminder that Milosevic had his
telephone number, in case the Yugoslav leader changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   But a US diplomatic source said Holbrooke's visit to the
Hungarian capital _ a six-hour drive from Belgrade _ may be only
personal. Holbrooke's wife, Kati Marton, has Hungarian roots and is
involved with a national cultural event in Budapest this week.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombing, downtown Belgrade was quieter than usual,
but not deserted. For the first time in weeks, the weather was
springlike, drawing out pensioners to sun themselves on city
benches even as it gave NATO planes clearer skies for more accurate
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Some people began stocking up on supplies, and there were long
lines at gasoline stations. But shop shelves were not empty, and a
sense of panic was absent among the populace.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and banks were open, and mail was delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else are we to do when our country is under threat?''
said Bozic, the government minister. ``It's the choice between
flood and fire. Either choose to have solidarity and integrity, or
choose to be bombed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the aftermath of the bombs, both physical and
political, leaves many here worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic for the first time will understand the reality _
that Serbia is a very unstable country,'' said Zoran Djindjic,
president of the anti-Milosevic Democratic Party. ``Bombing is
opening up a Pandora's box. A lot of things could come in this
chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess the power structure would be seriously
threatened, once faced with a military defeat,'' said Milan Protic,
senior fellow at the Institute for Balkan Studies. ``The options
are so tragic _ between occupation and bombardment. We might get
both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
