<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-LANGDON-HNS &LR;      03-24 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-LANGDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Team That Can't Lose was in a little bit
of trouble _ not too much, mind you, but enough to create an uneasy
moment or two.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Krzyzewski sensed it. Further down the bench, the mood was
growing more somber by the moment. Things hadn't quite reached the
crisis stage, but something needed to be done, and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Without a word, Trajan Langdon defused a potentially touchy
situation.
</P>
<P>
   A runner. A 3-point bomb, then another and another. In all, 11
points in less than three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble? What trouble?
</P>
<P>
   ``They were daring Trajan to shoot,'' Duke teammate Chris
Carrawell said a little later. ``I might dare me, but I wouldn't
dare him to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple dared and regretted it. In the seeming blink of an eye,
the fifth-year Blue Devils senior turned a four-point deficit into
a five-point lead. If John Chaney's team wasn't quite finished, it
was well on its way.
</P>
<P>
   The Alaskan Assassin had struck again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Trajan's hitting, it changes the whole game,'' Carrawell
said. ``He hits three or four in a row, you've got to guard him
now. That opens up Elton (Brand) inside.''
</P>
<P>
   It did this time, too, as Brand rallied from a ragged start to
finish with 21 points. Langdon's 23 were even bigger, though, a
fact hardly lost on the losing coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is as pure a shooter as I have seen in the game of
basketball,'' Chaney said.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of it all, from Krzyzewski's point of view, was that
Langdon had turned the game around so calmly, without so much as a
hint of the panic that could unnerve a young team feeling pressure
in the Tournament for the first time. And typically, he had done it
without raising so much as an eyebrow, much less a voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trajan _ because he's so quiet and humble _ you don't look at
him and say he's a great leader, but he's been a great leader for
us,'' the coach said Wednesday. ``Our kids really respect Trajan.
Behind the scenes, he does amazing things with this club, not only
by example _ because he's our hardest worker _ but by things he'll
say in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll close the door. He won't necessarily have one of those
fire-and-brimstone talks, but he'll say, `OK, this is what coach
meant.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like my interpreter. He does a really good job.''
</P>
<P>
   For Langdon, taking command may have been in the genes.
Certainly, it was suggested by his birth certificate. When Steve
Langdon _ a professor of anthropology at the University of
Alaska-Anchorage _ and his wife, Gladys, brought their son into the
world, they gave him a name that virtually precluded him from being
anywhere but out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trajan'' is for a Roman emperor who put an end to the
persecution of Christians. ``Shaka,'' his middle name, is taken
from a Zulu leader who organized his tribe into a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would that be the end of the influence Dad has had on his
son's athletic career. Leaving little to chance, Steve Langdon
carefully structured the process, taking the boy to Florida for a
baseball camp one year.
</P>
<P>
   At age 14, Trajan spent time at Loyola College in Baltimore,
where he played pickup basketball games with older players and
honed his pitching skills with a catcher whom his father had
arranged to work with him.
</P>
<P>
   In time, he developed enough skill in both sports to earn a
basketball scholarship from Duke while also playing three years in
the San Diego Padres' minor-league system. Eventually, basketball
won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of Alaska know basketball,'' he says. ``In the villages
and outlying areas, basketball is the main sport. It's the one kids
relate to and try to play. Basketball is what they grew up on.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, folks back home know Trajan Langdon. When he returned
as Duke played in the Great Alaska Shootout in 1995, he couldn't
play because of knee problems but still was followed by autograph
seekers wherever he went. Schools and groups around the state court
him to visit and give motivational speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, he was back again when the Blue Devils returned
to the Shootout. This time, he made the all-tournament team even
though Duke suffered its only loss of the season, dropping a
two-point game to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Now, March offers a chance to clear up some other unfinished
business.
</P>
<P>
   While younger teammates have known little but success in Durham,
N.C., Langdon was around for the dark days _ Krzyzewski's back
problems, a losing season (13-18) in 1995 and the rebuilding that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out the next year with the knee problem, Langdon
experienced a different sort of disappointment the past two
seasons, including last year's South Regional final when Duke blew
a 17-point lead and lost to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Falling short of the Final Four _ a virtual birthright at Duke
when Langdon first arrived _ was bad enough, but adding to those
unhappy memories was the knowledge that he hadn't been much help.
In the Blue Devils' past two trips into the bracket, Langdon made
just 19 of 68 shots, including 11 of 38 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got worn down because he carried us _ further probably than
we should have advanced a couple of times,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   Those teams weren't as talented or versatile as the one Langdon
leads into Tropicana Field to face Michigan State on Saturday
night. William Avery, Shane Battier and Elton Brand were freshmen a
year ago, and Brand was injured and barely a factor against
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Langdon can lead without having to do it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different mindset,'' he said. ``I put too much pressure
on myself in the postseason the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have such a talented team, they don't really need my shot,
or if I don't shoot well, we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does shoot well, winning is a whole lot easier. Against
Temple, Langdon made six of seven shots (five of six from 3-point
range), loosening up the middle and helping Brand find room to
operate. In three NCAA games (he sat out the opener against Florida
A&AMP;M with a foot injury), Langdon has hit 19 of 30 3-point tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches and my teammates have ultimate confidence in me,''
he said, ``and I have ultimate confidence in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That bond could be tested again Saturday. When the teams met in
the Great Eight in December, Duke came away with a 73-67 win
despite being outrebounded 41-25 by the Spartans, a game in which
Brand grabbed just three boards.
</P>
<P>
   The difference? Langdon's 23 points on 7-of-12 shooting, 4-of-7
from outside the arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more balanced now,'' Krzyzewski said. ``But everything
we do starts with Trajan.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, a player his coach calls ``the bridge'' between Duke eras
old and new tries to finish what these Blue Devils have started.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special kid,'' Krzyzewski said. ``I'm happy for
everybody, but I'm especially happy for Trajan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
