<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISTANBUL EX-MAYOR'S JAILING FUELS TURKEY'S TENSIONS ON RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ When former Istanbul Mayor Recep Tayyip
Erdogan enters jail Friday to begin serving a sentence for
subversion, he will be the most visible victim to date of an
intensifying campaign against what military commanders and their
civilian allies say is Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   Erdogan resigned at the end of 1998 after he was sentenced for
reading a poem that said: ``The mosques are our barracks, the domes
are our helmets, the minarets are our spears and the faithful are
our warriors.'' That was judged an incitement to religious
rebellion, and Erdogan, until then thought of as a rising star of
the Islamic political movement, was given a 10-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict between the secular establishment and
religious-oriented political parties, which has dominated Turkish
politics in recent years, is intensifying again. Prosecutors are
threatening pro-Islamic politicians with political bans, jail
sentences and even execution.
</P>
<P>
   The most aggressive prosecutor, Vural Savas, was given a public
seal of approval Wednesday when senior generals paid him a visit.
Afterward he advised against repeal of a law that permits
prosecutions of public figures on the ground that they are
fomenting religious or ethnic hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament was about to consider a repeal last week when the
military chief of staff, Gen. Huseyin Kivirkoglu, said he opposed
it. His warning effectively ended the debate.
</P>
<P>
   A national election is due in April, and polls suggest that the
Islamic-oriented party is likely to do well, perhaps even finish
first, as it did in the last election, in 1995. That prospect
deeply upsets secular leaders, who accuse the party of harboring a
secret agenda aimed at wiping away the secular state.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 election produced a government led by the
Islamic-oriented Welfare party, but it collapsed after a year under
intense military pressure. Last year the party was outlawed and its
leader, former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan, was banned from
politics for five years. But the party has re-emerged under a new
name, Virtue, and Erbakan appears to be directing it from behind
the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   That has outraged prosecutors, and in recent days they have
mounted a concerted attack on Virtue, seeking to outlaw it and to
prosecute its leaders for sedition. Erbakan may also be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Most startlingly, one prosecutor has indicted four former
members of the banned Welfare party and demanded that they be
executed. He charged the four _ one who was the party's deputy
chairman and three others who were members of Parliament _ with
``seeking to undermine the current constitutional state and replace
it with a state based on religious principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital punishment has not been administered for more than a
decade, and few expect that the indicted men will suffer it. The
mere mention of the possibility, however, is evidently intended to
show pro-Islamic politicians how seriously the government
disapproves of their activities.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Virtue party insist that they support the secular
state and merely want Turks to embrace their religious roots and
incorporate religious ethics into public life.
</P>
<P>
   Those political and legal clashes are not the only ones
convulsing Turkey in the pre-election period. A spate of terrorist
attacks has followed the arrest of Kurdish guerrilla leader
Abdullah Ocalan in February. In response, the police have launched
a fierce crackdown. Sunday they arrested more than 2,000 people who
celebrated a traditional spring festival that has become a focus of
Kurdish protests.
</P>
<P>
   Television footage showed police in a mostly Kurdish
neighborhood of Istanbul charging into crowds of demonstrators and
beating men and women. Shots were fired on both sides, and some
protesters shouted slogans supporting Ocalan and his rebel
movement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
