<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-SAMESEX-MARRIA     03-24 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-SAMESEX-MARRIAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHODIST MINISTER ACCUSED OF BLESSING SAME-SEX UNION GOES ON
TRIAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ill.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; CHICAGO _ For the second time in a year, a United Methodist
Church minister will face an ecclesiastical trial on a charge that
he violated a church law against ministers' officiating at same-sex
unions.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, the Rev. Greg Dell, 53, has been formally charged
with disobedience to Methodism's ``order and discipline'' for
having blessed the union of two men in his church, Broadway United
Methodist Church, here in Chicago last September.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will begin on Thursday, with 13 ministers acting as a
jury and a retired bishop as judge, in a church sanctuary in
suburban Downers Grove. A verdict could come on Saturday.
Conviction could lead to loss of his ministerial credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In its largest sense, the trial illustrates a national
controversy, in both religious and secular spheres, over same-sex
unions. Even while gay men and lesbians have filed lawsuits in
states like Hawaii and Vermont seeking legal recognition of their
unions, the federal government and a majority of states have passed
laws against recognizing the legality of such bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Many religious groups have been wrestling with questions of how
to relate to the gay men and lesbians in their midst. But while
much of the controversy in Protestant denominations has turned on
whether to ordain noncelibate homosexuals as clergy members,
controversy over same-sex unions has become acute lately among the
country's 8.5 million United Methodists, who constitute the
nation's second-largest Protestant denomination, after the Southern
Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this is because the church, whose members include
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former Sen.
Bob Dole, is theologically diverse, including liberal and
conservative wings, as well as a broad center. It also lacks a
single, central authority, like the pope, but at the same time does
not permit its congregations the sort of autonomy found within
Jewish synagogue organizations and some other Protestant
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the church's top policy-making body, the General
Conference, voted to place the following sentence in the church's
rule book: ``Ceremonies that celebrate homosexual unions shall not
be conducted by our ministers and shall not be conducted in our
churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the sentence was not inserted among the book's specific
regulations, but in a section detailing advisory stands on issues
like the use of tobacco and alcohol, some questioned whether it was
binding.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, the Rev. Jimmy Creech, who had blessed the union
of two women at his church in Omaha, was narrowly acquitted in a
church trial after his lawyers argued that the sentence was
advisory. (Creech's bishop did not reappoint him to his pulpit,
however.) In August, the denomination's highest court, the Judicial
Council, ruled that the sentence had the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, Dell blessed the union of Karl Reinhardt, 33, a
high school English teacher, and Keith Eccarius, 41, a computer
systems analyst, at a service attended by about 150 people at
Broadway Church. Eccarius had been a member there for eight years.
He and Reinhardt, who met at a Christmas party in 1996, had asked
Dell to officiate at their union a year before the ceremony was
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Within Dell's case some would discern an additional ethical
question. Can a clergy member violate a denominational law if he or
she believes the pastoral care of an individual requires it? Or
does such law-breaking, especially in a highly contentious issue
like this one, threaten the integrity of the institution to which
that clergy member belongs?
</P>
<P>
   Dell, who is married with an adult son, says about 30 percent of
the people in his urban, 181-member congregation are gay men and
lesbians, and it would be discriminatory not to offer them the
ministerial services he provides to heterosexual members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense will be, the only way I can obey the order and
discipline of the denomination is to violate this rule in this
context,'' Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Stephen C. Williams, who has agreed to prosecute
the case for the church's Northern Illinois Conference, said the
issue was one of a minister's being accountable to the vows he took
to uphold church rules. ``He's free to try to change church law,''
Williams said of Dell. ``He's not free to break it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell, who attended Duke University Divinity School with Creech
in the 1960s and remains a friend of his, said he had officiated at
33 same-sex unions since 1981. He does not call them weddings,
because such ceremonies lack legal sanction. Among other clergy
members here, Dell has a reputation as a supporter of liberal
social causes, an inclination he traces to the influence of his
childhood pastor, a Methodist minister in suburban Chicago who
spoke out against racism in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   After the Judicial Council ruled that the pronouncement on
homosexual union had the force of church law, Reinhardt and
Eccarius asked Dell if he still felt he could officiate. Reinhardt
said they would have ``fully understood'' had Dell decided they
needed to find another minister. ``I did it as an act of pastoral
ministry,'' Dell said in the interview. ``I didn't do it to raise
attention to this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, Bishop C. Joseph Sprague, head of the Northern
Illinois Conference, filed a complaint against Dell, saying he was
bound as bishop to uphold church law, but also saying he personally
disagreed with the stand against same-sex unions. Sprague has said
he will make no further comment until after the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said he saw the trial as a test of ``the nature of
ministry,'' the latitude a clergy member is allowed in working with
a particular congregation.
</P>
<P>
   One of Dell's critics offered a somewhat similar appraisal of
what is involved in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about issues of conscience, both on Greg's side
and the side of others,'' said that critic, the Rev. Scott Field, a
Methodist minister in nearby Naperville, Ill., who also serves on
the board of Good News, an evangelical caucus within the United
Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Field said he saw a ``collision between moral visions'' in the
case. For Methodists on both sides of the issue, he asked, ``can we
still walk together?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3025 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TV-BOS &LR;      03-24 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE FOR CONTROL OF TELEVISION ACCOMPANIES BOMBING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hours before the first NATO missiles struck Yugoslavia
Wednesday, a new type of warfare flared in Belgrade: a battle for
the control of televised images.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that dramatically reshaped broadcast coverage of the
first day of military hostilities, Serbian police officers raided a
Belgrade hotel and confiscated equipment necessary to transmit live
and taped television footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally cannot feed our own pictures,'' said a frustrated
M.L. Flynn, senior foreign producer of NBC News. ``We've been
shooting all day in Belgrade, and now we can't get any of the
pictures we enterprised into our story.'' Added Marcy McGinnis,
vice president for news coverage at CBS: ``It turns TV into
radio.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, the situation had grown more dire for
journalists, as Serbian authorities arrested and detained about two
dozen reporters and producers.
</P>
<P>
   From a visual standpoint, television faced an unusual battle
Wednesday. Instead of the dramatic, on-the-ground footage that is
meat and potatoes to networks when war breaks out, viewers were
mostly fed thin gruel _ locator maps alongside still photos of
network correspondents delivering reports by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The preemptive strike against television by Serbian authorities
illustrated both the medium's power and its vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   From Vietnam to the Gulf War, images beamed out by television
have arguably been the key variable in molding public opinion. But
increasingly, that fact means that television _ and the free flow
of information _ has been the first casualty of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the propaganda war is as big as the military war,''
said Janet Kolodzy, a former senior producer at CNN who is now a
writer-in-residence at Emerson College. ``The Serbs want to control
the images, want the images told the way they think they should be
told. They want to control the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Kalb, a former network reporter who is now at Harvard's
Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy,
said the Serbians view ``a news story as part of a propaganda war.
The war will be fought in two arenas: the arena where the bombings
take place, and the other arena will be the image of the bombings
that is presented to the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Wednesday, virtually the only images available to
networks came from Serbian TV. To some network officials, it was
puzzling that Yugoslavia chose to choke off independent televised
images of damage and casualties that could engender some sympathy
for its cause. But others saw the crackdown as a symptom of the
deep anger Serbian authorities harbor toward the international
media for what they consider biased coverage of the Kosovo
conflict. It is an anger that has some networks worried about the
safety of their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very dangerous,'' said CBS's McGinnis. ``We're even
hearing from the veteran correspondents, who've been in every war
known to man, that tensions are very high, even higher than the
Baghdad tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   There was danger for journalists in Kosovo even before
Wednesday's airstrikes. ABC reporters James Wooten and Mike Lee
were ordered out of Kosovo _ and relocated to Belgrade and
Macedonia, respectively _ after they were threatened, according to
an ABC spokeswoman. Safety concerns also prompted NBC to order
reporter Ron Allen to move from Kosovo to Belgrade, according to an
NBC spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a CNN spokesperson confirmed that CNN reporter
Christopher Burns left Yugoslavia after authorities told his
network that the reporter's life might be in danger. Officials have
denounced CNN on Yugoslavian television as ``a factory of lies,''
and also have broadcast Burns's picture.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Brent Sadler was also threatened by gun-wielding men when
he and several colleagues transmitted a report from Pristina prior
to the attack. One of the men held two bullets in his hand, pointed
at CNN employees and said, ``these bullets are for you.'' After
Sadler finished his report, he discovered that the tires on his
vehicle had been slashed.
</P>
<P>
   The move Wednesday against the television networks by Serbian
authorities occurred in two stages.
</P>
<P>
   First came the shutdown of the satellite transmission equipment.
Initially, authorities allowed the networks to broadcast reports
from a state-controlled TV station. That raised fears of
censorship, since the authorities could pull the plug at any
moment.
</P>
<P>
   CNN correspondent Christiane Amanpour, forced to resort to a
telephone hookup, spelled out the consequences for viewers before
she was detained by Serbian police: ``We can no longer broadcast
independently. We have to broadcast either by telephone or through
facilities provided by state-controlled media.''
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, however, once the military attack on
Yugoslavia began, Serbian authorities eliminated even that option.
``The Americans have been kicked out'' of the studio, said NBC's
Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   Network officials said the Yugoslav government offered no
explanation for the crackdown. It forced the networks to scramble
for ways to get the story out. Correspondents delivered their
reports over satellite telephones, sometimes accompanied by
previously taped images that had been fed earlier to bureaus in
London or elsewhere. Producers made plans to transport taped
reports to other transmitting stations, perhaps beyond Yugoslavia's
borders.
</P>
<P>
   The quandary confronting TV news organizations was exacerbated
because viewers have grown accustomed to continuing live coverage,
with pictures, during times of crisis. ``It doesn't stop us from
reporting the story, but it stops us from showing the visuals you
wish to have,'' said CBS's McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time TV networks have had to confront
government hostility. During the 1991 Gulf War, the Iraqi
government censored reports and the US military tightly controlled
media access to information. Chinese authorities tried to halt TV
transmissions during the Tiananmen Square uprising of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Network producers Wednesday vowed not to be deterred by the
Serbian authorities. ``It's not the perfect situation, but I think
we'll be fine here,'' said NBC's Flynn. ``We'll always figure out a
way to tell a straight story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
