<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSTOMS-PROFILING25-C     03-24 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-PROFILING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia lawmaker: Customs detains blacks more often at airport
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) called Wednesday for a
formal investigation into allegations that blacks are being
targeted for customs inspections at Hartsfield International
Airport based on nothing more than the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints come from a half-dozen customs inspectors who say
the unwritten rule at Hartsfield is to ``go after blacks.'' Lewis'
action also was prompted by a recent report on Fox Television's
WAGA-TV that alleged that customs inspectors at Hartsfield are more
likely to detain blacks than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis sent a letter to Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who
oversees the Customs Service, saying that he has been told that 90
percent of the individuals sent to Atlanta-area hospitals to be
X-rayed for drugs were black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced, based on what I've heard, that there is a
systematic pattern on the part of the custom agents in Atlanta to
select black males,'' Lewis said. ``There's something that's not
fair about this, something that is not right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee, which is conducting a
comprehensive review of the Customs Service's enforcement and
commercial operations, also will review how the agency conducts its
inspections. Senate Finance Chairman William Roth (R-Del.) plans to
hold hearings on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Roth said that he was aware of the allegations
of racial discrimination during the customs process nationwide. He
said he has expressed concern to the upper ranks of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that we can work together to successfully
identify and address any weaknesses in customs' overall
management,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Murphy, a Customs Service spokesperson, said the
department would thoroughly investigate the allegations about
inspections at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take this very seriously,'' Murphy said. ``We will take
immediate action and do what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Murphy noted, the agency's own statistics tell a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, officials searched three times more whites than
blacks during customs inspections last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2 million passengers passing through Atlanta last year,
about two dozen were X-rayed to detect drugs. About 16 of those
people were black, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the agency's policy is clear: Smugglers can be of
any shape, size or color, and there is no room for discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smugglers come in all races,'' Murphy said. ``Babies have been
used to smuggle drugs as have 70-year-old grandparents. I do not
believe we are being discriminatory. In fact, our policy is just
the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that inspectors go through 12 weeks of training and
are given additional training on cultural sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Cathy Harris, a customs inspector for the
last 13 years in Atlanta and Miami. It is a matter of routine, she
said, for the agency to single out blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're Nigerian, forget it, your name is in the computer,''
said Harris, a senior inspector who has filed several complaints
over the last four years alleging discrimination in customs
inspections. She also has filed complaints alleging that she has
been subjected to discrimination and sexual harassment at the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a hostile work environment,'' said Harris, who
said she has been singled out for coming forward with her
complaints. ``They have done everything to me except handcuff me
and throw me against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy would not comment on Harris' complaints because they are
pending in court.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
