<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BOBBY-LABONTE-HNS     03-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BOBBY-LABONTE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
FORT WORTH _ Bobby Labonte has a difficult decision to make this
week at Texas Motor Speedway. The Corpus Christi native has to
decide whether racing in pain is worth the gain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labonte loves to compete on the track in his home state. He
finished in the top 10 in each of the first two Winston Cup races
at the 1.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   But Labonte comes to Texas with a fractured right shoulder
blade, the result of a practice-session crash last week at
Darlington. He also ranks third in the Cup points race, only 26
points behind leader Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Busch Grand National points leader Matt Kenseth helped Labonte
stay close in the points chase by replacing Labonte early in the
race and driving the Interstate Batteries Pontiac to a 10th-place
finish last weekend at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   Now Labonte has to decide what's best for him and his team:
Should he try to go the distance in Sunday's Primestar 500 and
fight the pain in his shoulder or hope Kenseth can provide another
quality performance?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take it one day at a time,'' Labonte said. ``We
went to work Monday in rehab and have been treating the shoulder
all week. On Friday, we'll evaluate it and see where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has decided he will not compete in Saturday's Coca-Cola
300 BGN race. Former BGN champion Steve Grissom will drive the MBNA
Pontiac for the Joe Gibbs team.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on the Cup race isn't as easy. At age 34, Labonte
is considered one of the rising stars on the Cup circuit and one of
the few who has any chance at unseating Jeff Gordon for the Winston
Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte must carefully consider what is best for the team this
weekend at TMS. Is he likely to garner more points by driving the
entire race with one good arm on the steering wheel, or is Kenseth
more likely to drive the No. 18 Grand Prix to a competitive finish?
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be there if Bobby needs me,'' Kenseth said. ``I hope he
doesn't, but I will do whatever Bobby wants me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has to start the race to earn the points, which he did
at Darlington. He was supposed to turn the driving over to Kenseth
on the first caution, which came on the fourth lap.
</P>
<P>
   But Labonte was so far back in the field that the leaders would
have lapped his car had he tried to make the switch then. He
toughed it out for another 39 laps before rain brought out a red
flag.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth took over when the race resumed and did better than
anyone on the Gibbs team could have hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt did a real good job for us,'' said Jimmy Makar, Labonte's
crew chief. ``He had to come from last all the way to 10th. I think
Matt had a good time in the car, and we had a good time with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, who will become a full-time Cup driver next year,
thought he could have moved up still more had the race not ended
early because of the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran as hard as I could and passed as many cars as I could,''
Kenseth said. ``I really didn't know where we were until the race
was over. When they told me we were 10th, I said, `Wow. That's
pretty good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bobby did a tremendous job of staying out there as long as
he did. I know he was in pain, but he sucked it up and stayed with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte admits he probably would not have been able to drive the
car to a top-10 finish as Kenseth did, but his 43-lap effort showed
Labonte what he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't feel all that bad, better than I thought it would
be,'' Labonte said. ``That definitely relieved a lot of pressure
off my mind. Just knowing I could get back in there made me feel a
lot better about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing while hurting is nothing new for the Labonte family. Big
brother Terry is known as NASCAR's ``Ironman`` because of his
record 607 consecutive starts. A few of those starts were made when
most people would have been in a hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby has been through this situation before, when he fractured
his left shoulder blade in 1995. That injury also came in a crash
at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte drove 110 laps the next weekend at Bristol before
getting out of the car and letting David Green take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labontes are tough,'' Makar said. ``But you can only be so
tough. When you've got something broken and it hurts you, it's
going to be hard to do your best. Since we've been through this
thing with Bobby before, we know what to expect with his
limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte could hold off driving until Sunday by letting Kenseth
qualify the car for him Friday. But Labonte wants to get track time
on the rebuilt surface at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Makar and Gibbs say they will not allow Labonte to drive if they
feel he is endangering himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first concern is Bobby's health, even before points and
everything else,'' Makar said. ``It would take a little bit of wind
out of our sails, but Bobby and his family is what matters most to
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
