<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW FAILS TO JOIN IN AS NASDAQ RISES FROM TUESDAY LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks caught fire in the last 90 minutes
of trading Wednesday, lifting the Nasdaq composite index to a 1.83
percent gain, a recovery of more than half of what it lost in the
broad market selloff Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The late rally did little, however, for blue-chip stocks as the
Dow Jones industrial average, dragged down by American Express and
oil issues, slipped 4.99 points, to 9,666.84, receding further from
the 10,000 mark it flirted with last week.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq rose 42.44 points, to 2,365.28. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 6.45 points, or five-tenths of a percent, to
1,268.59.
</P>
<P>
   The session began ominously, with markets in Tokyo and Hong Kong
skidding about 3 percent overnight and tension building from NATO's
decision to begin bombing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of turning to renewed selling, the market steadied.
One contributor, analysts said, was Abby Joseph Cohen, the
influential Goldman, Sachs strategist, who predicted the Dow would
rise to 10,300 by the end of the year, up from her previous
prediction of 9,850.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect 1999 and 2000 to be years of ongoing profit
expansion, with better aggregate gains than 1998, which was
disappointing,'' she said in a report to clients.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor may have been bullish words from Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co. about IBM, which also announced a $3 billion order for computer
parts from EMC. IBM, the Dow's biggest gainer, rose 4 1/8, to 169
1/2. EMC jumped 5, to 118 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   A government report of the biggest decline in more than seven
years for big-ticket manufactured goods also seemed to help settle
the stock market because a slowing economy implies lower interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The market mostly marked time until President Clinton announced
the beginning of the bombing in Yugoslavia, apparently dispelling
some of the uncertainty that Wall Street detests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a surge of buying in high-tech stocks,'' said Anthony
O'Bryan, a market analyst at AG Edwards in St. Louis. ``Perhaps
that's signaling that the worst of the correction is over.''
Sometimes the most auspicious market turns, he added, are those
touched off by no particular news, but only a sense that the
pendulum has swung too far.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Herrmann, chief investment officer at Waddell &AMP; Reed in
Overland Park, Kan., said a sound high-technology sector was
essential if the market is to resume its advance. ``It's tough for
the stock market to make a lot of progress with tech bumping
along,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Technology issues, along with blue chips, paced the market's
long rise into record territory but have succumbed of late to
evidence of slackened growth and fears of overvaluation, especially
compared with lesser stocks, which have mostly lagged.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small companies, for example, has
fallen 8.9 percent this year, compared with a 7.87 percent gain for
the Nasdaq and a 5.29 percent gain for the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Internet deal found no shortage of buyers.
Miningco.com Inc., which supplies human guides for people trying to
search the Web, saw its initial public stock offering, priced at
25, soar as high as 62 1/4 before closing at 47 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Among the high-technology gainers were Microsoft, up 4 11/16, to
171 1/4; Intel, up 4 11/16, to 119 1/4; Dell, up 2 13/16, to 38
1/2, and Cisco, up 4 1/8, to 104 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
