<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRSTRIKES REVEAL SPLIT WITHIN REPUBLICAN PARTY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-RATIONALE and
KOSOVO-CONGRESS, which will move shortly.) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's decision to bomb Kosovo on
Wednesday sparked Republican reactions that revealed divisions
within the GOP on how to conduct foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The differing opinions have been evident as lawmakers in
Congress wrestled with whether to support the president.
</P>
<P>
   But they have also surfaced among likely presidential candidates
who want to stake out a firm position without interfering with
current policy-making.
</P>
<P>
   On one end of the spectrum, Elizabeth Hanford Dole, echoing the
assessment of her husband, former Senate Republican leader Bob
Dole, endorsed the mission based on humanitarian and strategic
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., argued ``American
lives are being put in jeopardy because of a civil war in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz, grudgingly supported the
president's decision while slamming the administration for its
handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   McCain voted to support the airstrikes, but said, ``Congress and
the American people have good reason to fear that we are heading
toward another permanent garrison of Americans in a Balkan country
where our mission is confused and our exit strategy a complete
mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, McCain, who was a prisoner of war in Vietnam,
added, ``Our adversaries around the globe will take heart from our
inability to act in concert to defend our interests and values.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, whose father led the nation
in the 1991 Persian Gulf War with Iraq, has been notably reticent
about the military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes that it is a decision for the commander- in-chief
who has the military and intelligence information,'' said Bush
spokeswoman Linda Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush believes if we are going to commit American
troops we must be sure there is clear mission and an achievable
goal and an exit strategy,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Among other contenders, conservative television commentator Pat
Buchanan, Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, and conservative activist Gary
Bauer opposed the attack; former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander
supported airstrikes but opposed ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The range of reactions mirror the ongoing debate within the
Republican Party over what the U.S. role should be on the
international scene.
</P>
<P>
   Their divisions also reflect the lack of consensus among the
American public, whom polls show are almost equally divided on the
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say candidates walk a fine line as they
attempt to highlight their differences with the administration
while at the same time not appearing to undercut American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have got to be very careful. We are involved in an act of
war and you have to be supportive of the nation and its
commander-in-chief,'' said Greg Mueller, an adviser to candidate
Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is supporting the airstrikes but opposes placing U.S.
ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Mueller said the impeachment damaged the president's
credibility, giving candidates more latitude to criticize Clinton
and be openly skeptical of his promises.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle cited the impeachment in his
critique of the president's Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said the Balkan situation has spiralled out of control
because Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic sensed ``a weakened
American president.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bush administration, in which Quayle served, warned
Serbs in 1992 to stay out of Kosovo, Quayle now, as a presidential
candidate, is questioning the extent of U.S. involvement in the
Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States can take the lead when it comes to
intelligence, logistics, medical help and things like that,''
Quayle said. ``But when it comes to ground troops and ground
support, I say that you really need to have the Europeans there.
It's a European problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole argued that Kosovo is more than that.
</P>
<P>
   She called the region of ``important consequence to America's
national interest.'' She cited humanitarian concerns, particularly
the allegations of ethnic cleansing by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The fissure within the Republican Party between those who
advocate international involvement and those that have opposed
interference abroad have been around for years. Some Republicans
actively opposed U.S entry into both world wars.
</P>
<P>
   But one expert said some of the Republican response reflects not
just philosophical or political differences with the Clinton
administration but the failure of the White House to adequately
explain its Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case has not been made as what our strategy is and what
our interests are to justify the commitment,'' said Ed Djerejian,
director of the Baker Institute for Public Policy at Rice
University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   George Edwards, professor at Texas A&AMP;M University, argued that
Clinton has the advantage because Milosevic, who has been blamed
for massacres of ethnic minorities in his country, is easy to cast
as the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is such a monster. It is very helpful to the extent
you can demonize,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only Republican candidates who face risks in staking
out positions on Kosovo. Vice President Al Gore, leading in polls
on the Democratic presidential contest, is inextricably tied to the
administration policy and could face criticism if lives are lost.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's adversary in the Democratic primaries, former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, was quick to criticize the administration's
strategy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are escalating our commitment without establishing a clear
exit strategy. As with Bosnia, we run the risk of becoming bogged
down in a quagmire whose end we cannot predict,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
