<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3043 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ECONOMY-NYT &LR;      03-24 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ECONOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING UNLIKELY TO HURT YUGOSLAVIA'S ALREADY DEVASTATED ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV, moving in `i'
category.) 
(bl) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Yugoslav economy already battered and trade limited
since international economic sanctions were first imposed in 1992,
air strikes by the United States and its NATO allies against
Yugoslavia are unlikely to cause great economic harm.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the economic impact, Andrew Kenningham, an East
European economist at Merrill Lynch in London, said, ``It's
completely irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's total exports in 1998 rose to $3 billion, from $2.4
billion in 1997, and of that total, only $12.6 million went to the
United States. The country imported $73.9 million worth of U.S.
goods last year, according to the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Both numbers were up from 1997, when $10.4 million of Yugoslav
goods _ about 0.4 percent _ were shipped to the United States, and
Yugoslav imports from the United States totaled about $54 million.
Yugoslav exports consisted primarily of manufactured goods,
machinery and commodities.
</P>
<P>
   NATO began air strikes against Serbian military targets in the
former Yugoslavia on Wednesday because Belgrade refused to sign a
peace deal on Kosovo and halt Serbian violence against ethnic
Albanians there.
</P>
<P>
   Although the direct economic impact of the military actions will
be limited, there could be a negative impact on relations between
the United States and Russia or on Wall Street if the military
action rattles investors, said Morris Goldstein, a senior fellow at
the Institute for International Economics in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Italy was Yugoslavia's largest trading partner in 1997; taking
about 12 percent of its exports. Macedonia and Germany accounted
for about 9 percent of exports, and Russia, a traditional Serbian
ally, accounted for 7 percent. Yugoslavia's primary exports are
food, such as fruits and vegetables, chemicals, iron, steel and
textiles. Before economic sanctions were imposed, the United States
sent aircraft, computers and other products there.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's thinly-traded currency, the dinar, fell slightly to
10.66 dinar to the dollar Wednesday, down from 10.7 on Tuesday.
That means that one dinar is worth a little more than 9 cents. It
has lost more than half its value in the year since the Kosovo
conflict began, moving from 4.85 to the dollar, or about 21 cents,
to its current level. As a result of a possible devaluation, the
dinar had traded as high as about 11.15 during the past 12 months,
said Jamie Coleman, managing foreign exchange analyst at Thomson
Global Markets in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions prevent trading of the dinar in the United States.
Elsewhere, Yugoslavia's lack of hard currency means that the dinar
can be purchased as an investment, but it cannot be sold, and must
therefore be bartered for other products.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's economy is among the victims of the civil war that
broke out in 1991, and it is now characterized by black market
dealings, bartering and hyperinflation. The breakup, which left
Yugoslavia with only two republics, Serbia and Montenegro,
destroyed the country's industrial sector, cutting off Serbia's
large manufacturing sectors from suppliers and outlets _ a
situation that was worsened by international sanctions, imposed in
June 1992 and lifted in January 1996. The United States imposed
sanctions again in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Before the civil war, a Yugo plant in Kragujevac, for example,
that rolled out 200,000 vehicles a year, had been a centerpiece of
the economy. The cars, priced at $4,000 apiece, were exported to
other East European countries and to the United States in 1986. But
the small, boxy cars quickly became known for their shoddy
construction and were withdrawn from the U.S. market in 1992. By
1996 production at the Kragujevac factory, about 90 miles south of
Belgrade, fell below 10,000 cars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Few U.S. companies have a presence in Yugoslavia. ICN
Pharmaceuticals Inc., a U.S. drug maker that had some operations in
Yugoslavia, merged those operations with a Yugoslav drug maker in
1991, and its assets there were seized by Serbian police and
paramilitary forces in February. Nike Inc. has manufactured a small
amount of footwear-related equipment there, a spokesman said,
adding that he would have to check on the present situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
