<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLITICS-540&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONAIRE PROPOSES OVERHAUL OF CALIFORNIA'S CAMPAIGN FINANCE
LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ron K. Unz, the Silicon Valley millionaire who
sponsored the ballot proposition that effectively ended bilingual
education in California last year, is proposing a sweeping new
measure that would overhaul the state's campaign finance and
disclosure laws and take reapportionment out of the hands of the
Legislature and turn it over to an independent commission.
</P>
<P>
   The complex proposal, dubbed the California Voters Bill of
Rights, would require all contributions of $1,000 or more to be
disclosed electronically over the Internet within 24 hours of their
receipt by a campaign committee, bar candidates for statewide
office from raising money except in the 12 months before their
primary election, impose a contribution limit of $5,000 per
election to candidates for statewide office and ban corporate
contributions outright.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also impose voluntary spending limits for
gubernatorial candidates of $6 million in a primary and $10 million
in a general election for candidates who agreed to accept partial
matching public funds, which could only be used to finance
television, radio or other electronic advertising.
</P>
<P>
   California is one of a relative handful of states with no
contribution or spending limits, and campaigns here consistently
break national spending records, with the two major candidates for
governor last year having spent a total of more than $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Unz, a Republican, said in an interview Wednesday that he was
confident he could gather the 670,000 signatures needed to put the
measure on the ballot in the state's primary election next March,
and that it would win easily. But the proposal drew quick criticism
from a bipartisan range of political consultants and campaign
finance experts who described it as an unwieldy mix of worthy
ideas, administrative complexities and tepid changes certain to
prompt a welter of legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of reform, the most important one we can
make is full and instant disclosure,'' said Leslie Goodman, a
Republican political consultant in Sacramento. ``But this just
sounds like the Rubik's Cube of campaign finance reform all wrapped
up in one initiative. On the one hand, it has the seedlings of some
important reforms, but also some complex and untenable elements in
the context of a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Miller, executive director of Public Campaign, a
Washington group that advocates public financing of campaigns,
dismissed the core of Unz's proposals as ``very '70s style
reforms,'' that address only ``a tiny percentage of the playing
field'' of the richest contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like there are new '90's bells and whistles in terms
of disclosure,'' Ms. Miller said, adding, ``I'm not ridiculing it
and saying it's not useful relative to the wide-open nature of
California law right now. But will it address the fundamental
issues of money in politics? No, it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Unz noted that a 1996 ballot measure that set contribution
limits of $500 for statewide candidates has been blocked by federal
courts as unconstitutionally restrictive. That measure's principal
backer, Tony Miller, a Democrat and former acting state secretary
of state, has signed on as co-sponsor of Unz's current proposal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
