<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-POLITICS-540&AMP;AD     03-24 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLITICS-540&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: current proposal. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new measure is Unz's latest foray into the politics of the
nation's most populous state, since the overwhelming victory last
June of his Proposition 227, which essentially ended bilingual
education programs in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Unz ran an unsuccessful primary challenge to then-Gov. Pete
Wilson in 1994, but has now chosen to become a major player in the
state's ballot proposition wars, which in recent years have
increasingly decided important policy issues in the face of
legislative stalemate or inaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Mr. Mischief now,'' said Bill Carrick, a leading
Democratic political consultant who has been active in major
campaigns here. ``He's decided that he doesn't want to pursue his
own personal political ambitions but wants to play initiative
politics instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Unz contended that, ``Many of the people who obviously would be
opposing this are people vested in the current system, and many of
those people have done very well.'' He added, ``But if we're
talking about many of these being worthy proposals, then why hasn't
the state Legislature implemented them for all these years?''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the measures Unz proposes would be novel and
relatively noncontroversial, like immediate Internet disclosure of
campaign contributions, which has yet to be required by any state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one who does that on a 24-hour turnaround,'' said
Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, a nonprofit group in Washington that studies campaign
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures, like a proposal to require a statewide
referendum on pay increases for state officials that exceed the
Consumer Price Index, will doubtless be popular with voters in an
era of wide distaste for politics and politicians. So might a
requirement that candidates liquidate their campaign funds after
each election, giving half of whatever is left over to their party
and half to the state's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   But other elements, like turning legislative redistricting over
to a commission of retired judges appointed by legislative leaders
from both parties, are certain to draw intense opposition,
especially from Democrats, who control both houses of the
Legislature and the governor's office for the first time in nearly
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``An initiative is only as strong as its weakest proposals,''
said Dan Schnur, a former aide to Wilson who is now a political
consultant. ``The problem with a sweeping initiative is it's easy
to run against.''
</P>
<P>
   Unz declined to say how much he was willing to spend of his own
money, or raise from others, in support of his plan, but one of the
state's most prominent Republican strategists, Ken Khachigian, said
the money would be better spent in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party's got to realize that if we try to raise $8 million
or $10 million for one of these things in an effort to change
redistricting, it would be better spent by putting it into Assembly
and Senate campaigns and winning back the Legislature,'' Khachigian
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
