<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE PLANS TO LAY OFF UP TO 1,000
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By   MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ In an effort to pare redundant
operations resulting from its acquisition of the Netscape
Communications Corp., America Online &UR;  &LR; Inc. Wednesday announced
plans to lay off between 700 and 1,000 employees at the newly
combined company.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the layoffs will come at the Dulles, Va.,
headquarters of America Online, which has 9,500 employees, and half
in Netscape's offices here.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Pittman, America Online's president, said the
dismissals would be across all divisions but that the impact would
be more heavily felt in corporate positions like accounting, human
resources and public relations than in engineering or product
development.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman said he sought to send the message to Netscape employees
that ``they are not some bolt on AOL, and this is not some
assimilation game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are putting two public companies together and really
integrating them, there are jobs that fall out of that,'' he said,
adding that America Online would seek to carry out the layoffs
within two weeks. ``We're trying to be fair with folks, very
straightforward and very quick so there's not any lingering
anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-and-a-half hour meeting at Netscape's headquarters was
the first face-to-face gathering of executives from America Online
and employees of Netscape since the acquisition was announced in
November. Since then, the value of the deal has soared to $10
billion from $4.2 billion as a result of a precipitous rise of
America Online's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting followed days of nervous speculation by Netscape's
2,300 employees, some of whom had already begun exploring other job
opportunities. But several Netscape employees who attended the
meeting said that the reception for America Online was not
unfriendly and that they were relieved to have some sense of the
company's direction.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, one Netscape employee said, the only overt
hint of cynicism about America Online came from an employee who
asked whether the giant online service would put its logo on the
Netscape building. When the answer was ``No,'' employees cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts viewed the layoffs as a positive step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there are cuts from both sides shows me that
they are looking to truly integrate Netscape,'' said Paul Noglows,
a senior analyst for Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, a San Francisco investment
bank. ``There is a high level of commitment here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the mood has not been all that gloomy at Netscape since
the merger was announced, in great part because the acquisition
entails swapping Netscape stock for America Online's stock at a
fixed ratio, meaning that Netscape employees who own stock have
seen their net worth rise rapidly in recent months with the run-up
in America Online's shares. The stock closed Wednesday at $117.375,
down $3.625.
</P>
<P>
   And Netscape employees who do face layoffs are expected to be in
high demand at other Silicon Valley companies. Several employees
said they had already been contacted by headhunters.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Chroman, a principal in the Chroman Group, a recruiting
and consulting firm in Silicon Valley, said the Internet market was
``booming,'' adding that she did not think displaced employees
``would have any difficulty finding jobs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, some Netscape employees did not wait around to find out
what would happen. One former engineer who left Netscape for
another Silicon Valley firm said he did not want to risk the
uncertainty of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have a family, I would have stuck it out,'' said
the engineer, who requested anonymity. But, he added, he remains
concerned that America Online will impose a more conservative
culture on the laid-back style of Netscape, where dogs roam freely,
employees wear shorts to work and cubicles are decorated with
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman said the company had no intention of altering Netscape's
culture. ``We fully expect Netscape to behave differently,'' he
said. ``All we care about is what comes out in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to announcing layoffs, America Online said it would
slightly reorganize its corporate structure, adding a new
management division to oversee Netscape's enterprise software
business.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will have four product groups: Netscape
Enterprise; Interactive Services, which will oversee America
Online, Compuserve, the Netscape browser, Netcenter and AOL TV; the
International Group, which will focus on expanding the company
overseas; and Interactive Properties, which will manage the ICQ
chat business and the Digital Cities local guides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
