<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-HNS &LR;      03-24 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR LIMITS NUMBER OF TEXAS STUDENTS WHO MIGHT QUALIFY FOR
VOUCHER PROGRAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The number of children who might be eligible to
participate in a school voucher program was drastically cut,
perhaps in half, Wednesday by a key state senator proposing the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Teel Bivins, chairman of the Senate Education Committee,
amended his voucher proposal _ actually called a ``public education
scholarship program'' in Senate Bill 10 _ to limit participation to
5 percent of eligible schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The change means that if the Legislature approves the plan,
perhaps only 71,500 schoolchildren will be eligible to attend
private schools with public tax dollars, rather than the previous
estimate of 143,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' original proposal would have made vouchers available to
all low-income students who failed the most recent state-mandated
testing program in the six largest metropolitan areas: Harris,
Bexar, Dallas, El Paso, Tarrant and Travis counties. But his
amendment now would limit participation to 5 percent of those
schoolchildren. Students also would have to be enrolled in the
current and previous school years in public schools to get a
voucher.
</P>
<P>
   It remains uncertain whether a voucher bill will pass the
Legislature this year; efforts in the past two sessions have
failed, but Gov. George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry are behind
a voucher plan.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Perry told a meeting of newspaper executives
that he thinks the Senate will pass a limited voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   Debate was still raging in committee Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins, an Amarillo Republican, said he put the cap on
eligibility to try to make a voucher experiment more acceptable to
those who believe it would be too much a financial drain on public
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   The cap ``will assure we don't have a mass exodus'' from public
schools, Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   But testimony from many people who jammed the Education
Committee hearing Wednesday indicated the change did not lessen any
of the opponents' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ill-prepared for the level of emotion that surrounds
this issue,'' Bivins said as he greeted a hearing room so packed
with people who wanted to testify that many were sitting on the
floor and standing in hallways hoping to get into the room.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that proponents and opponents are equally
passionate in their beliefs. Opponents say it will create a
financial drain on schools, that there is no solid research to
support claims that students will do better scholastically and that
private schools cannot provide services for physically, emotionally
and mentally disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that parents should have the right to send
their children to whatever schools best suit their needs, and that
the nation's first experiment in vouchers in Milwaukee has been
successful. They also contend that school choice is already
available _ but only to those families wealthy enough to afford
tuition at private schools or to move to neighborhoods with
top-rated public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who is right,'' Bivins said. He added that his
only purpose in suggesting Texas adopt a voucher plan is to
``create a laboratory in which we can test these theories.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also amended the bill to require private schools
to provide transportation to voucher students if those students
would have been provided school bus transportation by their public
schools. The change was offered by Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant and chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been concerned for some time that the Achilles heel in
any broad-based voucher program is that if you do not provide
transportation ... only those who can afford transportation are
afforded choice,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, private schools would receive 80 percent _
about $4,000 _ of state and local funding that is allotted for each
child; the remainder would remain in the child's home school
district.
</P>
<P>
   Among other stipulations, private schools would have to agree to
take all applicants or use a public lottery to select voucher
students if they had more applicants than room. They would be
prohibited from charging voucher students' parents more tuition
than what the voucher pays. And they would have to administer the
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills tests to all voucher students
in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Bivins plan, the voucher experiment would
automatically end after five years unless private schools can
demonstrate that voucher students post TAAS test scores 10 percent
higher than their counterparts in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
