<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0325-     03-24 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE CONFIDENCE, U.S. MILITARY WARY OF RISKS IN KOSOVO
CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    EDs: With US-KOSOVO-0325.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the allied warships and bombers at the
vanguard of strikes against Yugoslavia returned safely to their
bases Wednesday, U.S. officials tried to prepare the American
public for a conflict much bloodier than the high-tech wizardry of
past bombing missions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as a risk-free military operation,''
Army Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
during a briefing for reporters at the Pentagon after the first
wave of American and allied forces -- including the batwinged B-2
stealth bomber, had pounded military targets throughout Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   While the first bombing raids had targeted Yugoslavia's air
defense system, Shelton emphasized that the system is still ``very
capable'' and ``poses a considerable threat'' to the NATO aircraft
launched against Serb forces being used to attack civilians and
villages in the embattled, independent-minded Yugoslavian province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the relatively primitive air defenses of Iraq's Saddam
Hussein, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has a sophisticated
Soviet-built anti-aircraft system. In addition, anti-aircraft
equipment is easily hidden in the forested terrain of Kosovo. And
the province is frequently covered by clouds or fog, both a
hinderance to laser-guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate, the capability of the air defenses all make this
a very tough environment in which to operate militarily,'' Defense
Secretary William Cohen said at the Pentagon briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making every reasonable effort to protect our forces
while eliminating carefully defined military targets,'' Cohen
added. Even so, ``all military action involves risk,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, too, emphasized the risk to allied forces.
But ``the dangers of acting now are clearly outweighed by the risks
of failing to act: the risks that many more innocent people will
die or be driven from their homes by the tens of thousands; the
risks that the conflict will involve and destabilize neighboring
nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cohen and Shelton provided few details of the military
action against Milosevic, they emphasized that the bombing would
continue until the Serb leader halts his aggression against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo. To bring a halt to the NATO bombing, Milosevic
has to ``stop his slaughter of innocent people,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Yugoslavian military targets from Belgrade to
Pristina in Kosovo began with air- and sea-launched cruise missiles
fired by American B-52 bombers and NATO ships based in the
Mediterranean and Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said there had been some ``engagement'' between Yugoslav
and NATO planes, but gave no details. When asked about unconfirmed
reports of a NATO plane being downed, Cohen reported that ``our
aircraft have returned safely'' after the first wave.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air force also included Air Force F-117A stealth
fighter bombers and two radar-avoiding B-2 bombers, the first
combat role for the $2.1billion aircraft. Cohen said the B-2
aircraft ``performed according to its capabilities.'' He would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said the initial bombing raid sought to degrade
Milosevic's air defense system ``in order to reduce the risk and
the threat to our pilots and air crews in subsequent missions.'' He
indicated, however, that there has not been adequate time to assess
the initial damage caused by the NATO strike.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
