<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVLON-MARKETPLACE-AR     03-24 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVLON-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE RUMORS PUSH REVLON STOCK UP 54% IN 2 DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, The Netherlands)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DANA CANEDY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Revlon Inc. rose sharply for the second
straight day Wednesday on speculation that a buyer may soon step in
and rescue the cosmetics giant from its huge debt and weak
performance lately in the powder and perfume business.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon surged $5.1875, or 30.4 percent, to $22.25 on the New
York Stock Exchange. Its stock has risen 54 percent over the last
two days on heavy volume. Wednesday, 4.5 million shares changed
hands compared with average daily volume of 145,600.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are reacting to growing speculation that Revlon and
the billionaire Ronald O. Perelman, who controls 83 percent of its
shares, may be near a deal to sell the struggling company, which
makes Revlon, Colorstay and Almay cosmetics, to a larger
consumer-products concern.
</P>
<P>
   The two names mentioned most often by bankers and analysts as
potential buyers are Unilever NV of the Netherlands and the Procter
&AMP; Gamble Co. in Cincinnati. Both companies declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   While investors have signaled their ebullience about a possible
deal, Perelman is unlikely to sell his stake without a significant
premium to the $24 a share at which the stock traded when he took
Revlon public three years ago. He bought the company in a leveraged
buyout in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon, which is based in New York, declined to comment
Wednesday on the market activity and takeover rumors. Perelman also
declined to comment through a spokesman for his holding company,
MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   If a potential buyer is courting the company, ``it's a wide open
question what this thing is worth,'' said Tim Drake, an analyst at
the Bank One Corp., which is Revlon's fifth-largest shareholder
with about 330,000 shares. ``But even with the debt, the purchase
price they would have to pay is not out of line with other
acquisitions of that sort.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that Revlon would sell for ``in the range of $30 to
$50'' a share.
</P>
<P>
   By way of comparison, Drake said, the French cosmetic giant
L'Oreal SA bought Maybelline Inc. in 1996 for $44 a share. Sales of
cosmetics companies typically command between one and half to two
times sales.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear whether P&AMP;G or Unilever wants to snap up
Revlon at all. Bankers and analysts said P&AMP;G, which makes Cover
Girl and Max Factor cosmetics, was an unlikely buyer because it
would likely run into antitrust problems. A sale to Unilever, they
said, would be a better fit because, while that company owns the
Elizabeth Arden cosmetics line, it has only a small presence in the
mass retail market.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Unilever's vast international operation, coupled with
Revlon's powerful global brand name, would give the company a
substantial competitive edge in the marketplace. ``My read on this
is that Unilever would be interested in Revlon's foreign markets,
particularly the European markets, of which I think the company has
had a spotty performance,'' said Terrence Dwyer, a analyst at KDP
Investment Advisors in Montpelier, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon suffered last year from a loss of consumer purchasing
power in Asia, Russia and Latin America as well as from a slowdown
in the domestic cosmetics market as drug stores consolidated and
pared inventories. In the most recent fourth quarter, for instance,
the company reported an 82 percent drop in earnings on flat
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Revlon, whose stock had declined by 60 percent over
the last year before the run-up of the last two days, said it would
dismiss about 7 percent of its worldwide work force, or about 1,200
people, to cut costs. The company has about $1.7 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said companies the size of P&AMP;G and Unilever could take
on the debt load, but the amount could also make reaching an
agreement on a selling price a point of contention. ``The debt
level is really a function of how much you are willing to pay,''
said William Steele, an independent analyst in San Francisco who
follows consumer companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said the Revlon name alone would be worth a
premium. Perelman may be more receptive these days to selling some
of his holdings after several notable stumbles in recent years. He
sold the debt-ridden Coleman Co., the maker of outdoor camping
equipment, to the Sunbeam Corp. last year but then watched his
investment in that company tumble after the household appliance
maker reported huge losses that sent the stock tumbling from a high
of $52 to about $5. Perelman did not do much better with
Consolidated Cigar Holdings, which he controlled until selling it
last year at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Revlon struggling, Perelman may be more likely to
unload it at the right price.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a marketing standpoint they have not come out with
anything since the Colorstay, age-defying kind of things they
introduced three years ago,'' said Allan G. Mottus, publisher of
The Informationalist, a cosmetics industry trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Mottus said the company has also faced stiffer competition from
L'Oreal's Maybelline brand in the United States and P.&AMP; G.'s Oil of
Olay cosmetics lines in Europe. At the same time, Revlon stuck
retailers with too many promotional items and has failed to develop
aggressively more competitive fragrance, hair color and skin-care
lines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has been stubbing its toe for a while now,'' Mottus
said. The Revlon board seems to have noticed. After the company's
dismal performance last year, the board cut the salary of George
Fellows, Revlon's president and chief executive, by 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question really is, `Can this group sustain the company?'
'' Mottus said of Revlon's management. ``From Ron Perelman's point
of view, that has to be a major issue.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
