</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIAL SAYS POLITICS DIDN'T HALT MEXICO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.. Calif.)   (bl)  
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A senior U.S. Customs official said Wednesday that
a major inquiry into money laundering by Mexican banks was stopped
only after undercover agents had been unable to proceed in talks
with corrupt bankers to move more than $1 billion that was said to
belong to the Mexican defense minister and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter that included his first public comments on the case,
the Customs official, John Hensley, head of the Los Angeles office,
wrote, ``Numerous attempts by the undercover agents to push for a
meeting with this alleged general/minister were unsuccessful.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley also said that when a defendant in the case linked the
money to Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, he did so only ``in a
hypothetical manner,'' speculating that because the amount was so
large ``maybe it belongs to the president or his Cabinet.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, as well as one by Customs Commissioner Raymond
Kelly, strongly denied political motives for closing the operation.
The letters, to the head of a House subcommittee, Rep. John Mica,
R-Fla., were made public as the former senior agent in charge of
the case, William Gately, testified to the panel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The letters referred to statements that they said were made in
an article March 16 in The New York Times. The article quoted
government officials and Gately as having said senior Clinton
administration officials had declined to extend the undercover
operation past its scheduled end in May to investigate the planned
transaction, which Kelly described as ``a significant allegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Hensley strongly denied statements they attributed to
the article but that it did not make.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the charge that the case was brought down ``so that
U.S. officials could keep a high-ranking Mexican government
official from being investigated as part of the case is grossly
untrue and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But the article merely quoted Gately as complaining that no
strong effort had been made to pursue or follow up the traffickers'
proposal and speculating that foreign-policy concerns, along with
other reasons, might have been involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2057EST &QL; 
