</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SMOLTZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Triumph over pain Smoltz's breakthrough
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Don't let the numbers fool you.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz's 17-3 record last season looked great on paper. But
it came at a hefty price _ constant pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the outside, I was effective,'' said Smoltz, who twice went
on the disabled list while recovering from his second elbow surgery
in three years. ``On the inside, I was miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   But at 31, he has learned to deal with pitching and pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back over the year, and I really was the most proud
I've ever been,'' Smoltz said. ``It was the greatest year I've ever
had, under some very difficult circumstances. I didn't enjoy it.
But when it was over, I said `Man, it's amazing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz had surgery to remove bone spurs from his right elbow in
December 1997. It was the same surgery he had had in 1994, only
this time he didn't have six months to recover. So he began 1998 on
the disabled list, made his comeback after a rehab tour through the
minor leagues and then had to go back on the disabled list in late
May after the elbow flared up again.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he was stellar.
</P>
<P>
   When Smoltz came off the DL in June, he went 13-2 in 18 starts.
He won 12 of his last 13 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   His strong performances have carried into the spring. Smoltz
didn't look as sharp on Tuesday against the Mets as he has most of
the spring, but it was still a good outing. He gave up two runs in
five innings, which increased his ERA to 1.93.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm ready for the start of the season,'' Smoltz said.
``Every year the goal in spring training is to throw pain-free, and
you try and get hitters out and you try to get ready for the
season, and ... I've accomplished all three.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that success came when he started using a change-up he
developed. It was a pitch born of necessity and perfected through
conversations with Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone, Greg Maddux
and Tom Glavine. He has stopped throwing his split-finger, to ease
the pressure on his elbow, and he hasn't missed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's developed a lot of pitches,'' manager Bobby Cox said.
``He's still got the crackling curve and the zippy fastball....
He's tough to hit now, because he does have variety and almost the
same velocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz said, ``I've become a much better pitcher because I've
had to find a different way to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz got away from baseball this offseason. Instead of
starting rehabilitation a few weeks into the offseason as he has
the last several years, he had some bone chips removed in October
and followed that with rest. He didn't start working out much until
several weeks before coming to Florida. As a result, both his elbow
and his mind are fresher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could deal with last year, I could deal with any year,''
Smoltz said. ``I was as good as I'll ever be. I still can't believe
I was 17-3. On the flip side, I know how much better I can be if I
could just somehow be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
