<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMBAT DEBUT OF $2 BILLION B-2 `STEALTH' BOMBER
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV,
KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(wg) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The B-2 ``Stealth'' bomber, the most expensive and
intricate aircraft ever built, made its combat debut on Wednesday
in a world far different from the one for which it was conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials said two Stealths from Whiteman Air Force
Base in Missouri took part in the Nato attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Each B-2 dropped about 16 2,000-pound satellite-guided bombs,
said Brig. Gen. Leroy Barnidge Jr., the base commander. He provided
no details on the targets or damage inflicted, but Defense
Department officials said they included command bunkers and
air-defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at Whiteman, Tech. Sgt. Dee Ann Poole, said she
did not know if either plane came under fire. She said both planes
completed their missions unscathed and that no one aboard either
aircraft was injured. Each B-2 carries a pilot and a weapons
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The safety of plane and crew were surely of high concern to the
Pentagon. Each B-2 costs well over $2 billion (total development
costs have been easily 10 times that), and its critics have
suggested that it is not only the most expensive plane ever but one
of the costliest white elephants as well.
</P>
<P>
   The radar-dodging aircraft was conceived to carry nuclear
weapons into the territory of the Soviet Union, an adversary that
no longer exists. With the break-up of the Soviet empire, the B-2s
backers suggested that its 6,000-mile range would make it ideal for
delivering non-nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   One critic scoffed at that notion. ``It's the equivalent of
saying we're going to send a Rolls-Royce down into a combat zone to
pick up groceries,'' Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But now as defense secretary, Cohen said the B-2 had ``performed
according to its capabilities.'' He described it as ``a stealthy
aircraft that can fly in all weather'' and carry a hefty bomb load.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics have expressed doubt about the B-2's stealthiness,
wondering whether it can really make itself invisible to radar.
There was even doubt for a time about the plane's ability to fly in
heavy weather, given its supposedly ultra-sensitive radar-evading
skin.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts about weather prompted an Air Force demonstration in
1997. Hoses sprayed water on a B-2, with no apparent ill effect.
``We fly in the rain all the time,'' one pilot said. ``Do people
think the skin is made of sugar?''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force would not say when the two B-2s would return home
to Whiteman. They are among nine on ready at the base, Poole said.
The other 10 in the Air Force's possession are at Northrup
Grumman's plant in Palmdale, Calif., having their computer systems
upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in civilian life, computers can become obsolete almost
overnight, even those on a $2 billion aircraft, Poole said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOST-OBRIEN25-C     03-24 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-OBRIEN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Brien both a wonderful father and coach
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ March will forever be a painful time of
year for Jim O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   It was eight years ago this month that his wife, Chris, died
from a heart ailment. She was 41.
</P>
<P>
   Her death left him alone to raise two teen-age daughters, Amy
and Erin, now 22 and 24. Both, not surprisingly, are basketball
coaches like their father.
</P>
<P>
   The two were in Knoxville, Tenn., last week to share in their
dad's _ and really, the family's _ biggest professional triumph: A
regional final victory that earned Ohio State a berth in the Final
Four. It is O'Brien's first trip to the national semifinals in 22
years of coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying, I was happy, I was sad,'' said Erin, a former
Division II player who is an assistant women's basketball coach at
Vanderbilt University. ``I was just so happy that my sister and I
were there. It was great to just get on the court and give him a
big hug and tell him how proud we were of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy, who works for an insurance company in Boston and coaches a
freshman girls' team at a local high school, said her father was
almost speechless after the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just saying, `Can you believe this? Can you believe
this?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens Saturday when Ohio State (27-8) faces
Connecticut (32-2), this improbable run by a Buckeye team that
finished 8-22 last season will remain one of O'Brien's fondest
memories. But while the success has been extremely gratifying, he
and his daughters know it is not the most important thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned through the death of my mother that life is more
important than a game,'' Erin said. ``That the love you have and
the closeness you share is the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her father rarely, if ever, asks specifically about
basketball during their weekly phone conversations and occasional
visits. ``It's, 'How's life?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Life hasn't been easy for the O'Briens since Chris died in 1991.
But through adjustments, some small, some not so small, the three
have grown stronger and closer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien immediately altered his work schedule to spend as much
time as possible with his daughters. Sometimes, he took the girls
on trips with him and the three visited France, Italy and
Yugoslavia together. At dinner time, prom time or game time _ both
Erin and Amy played basketball in high school _ he was there. And
when his daughters needed a companion for a visit to the doctor or
the dress shop, O'Brien went along.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was involved in our lives through my mother almost,'' Erin
said. ``She was initially the one we would turn to. Then he became
the sole confident, where we were turning to him and he had to deal
with everyday issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was all we had so no subject was taboo. And now we feel
comfortable going to him about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Amy: ``He's had to learn a lot of things about girls that I
don't think he wanted to know. But it's worked out and our
relationship has definitely grown.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien acknowledged there are many facets of his daughters'
lives that he's involved with ``that at one time I wasn't.'' He
spoke about his experience as a single father only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that a lot of parents have to go through,'' he
said. ``I don't think it's all that unique. I was very fortunate
that they were two well-rounded kids. I think I was more dependent
on them than they were on me.'' Their father offered as much moral
and emotional support as he could. He tried to become the big
booster their mother was of their Westwood High School sports teams
in suburban Boston. (In addition to basketball, Erin and Amy played
softball and soccer.) In fact, O'Brien insisted his daughters, both
guards like their dad, participate in their basketball team's state
semifinal game three days after their mother's death. He was in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Amy and Erin will be in the stands cheering him.
They hope to again watch their father celebrate with a victory
dance as he did in Knoxville. And maybe this time, he'll be more in
step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they win their next game, we have to give him some
dance lessons,'' Erin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
