<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MICHST-FLINTSTONE     03-24 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHST-FLINTSTONES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Flint, Mich., was built for production. It's the city that put
America on wheels.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the city whose skyline abounds with smokestacks has taken
some major hits, and production is down.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1980s and '90s, Flint gained more notoriety for
producing gang violence than automobiles. It built a reputation as
being a place you don't even want to visit, much less live.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, Flint is again being talked about as a place of
production, though the talk is still not about cars. It's about
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those players are at Michigan State, which plays Duke in
the semifinals of the NCAA Tournament on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Flintstones: Mateen Cleaves, Antonio Smith, Morris
Peterson and Charlie Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth be told, it's not good to have that many guys from the
same city, because usually they are hated rivals,'' Michigan State
coach Tom Izzo joked. ``Actually, it has been a great thing for our
team. And it's not like they just keep to themselves, but they have
included everyone else into their group and made us much closer as
a team.''
</P>
<P>
   And much better as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Flint foursome are the Spartans' top two scorers and
rebounders and, more important, their team leaders. All told, the
Flintstones account for 55 percent of the team's point production,
54 percent of its rebounding and 68 percent of its assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the floor with my boys from Flint, it seems like
we're playing at home,'' Cleaves said. ``We know we've come a long
way, but we're not about to forget where we came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely a day goes by that the group does not mention being proud
of its hometown and looking forward to going home to talk to the
next generation about how hard work can pay off, regardless of
where you are from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing for more than just Michigan State, our families
and ourselves,'' Cleaves said. ``We're playing for Flint. That is
something to be proud of. We know the city is behind us, and we
hope we're giving it some good publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flintstones are walking advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Flint has produced the likes of Glen Rice,
Trent Tucker, Roy Marble and Andre Rison, but none has had the
impact on the city's image the Flintstones seem to have.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helps that Cleaves and Smith won a state title
together at Northern High School in 1995, Bell was Mr. Basketball
in Michigan his senior season (1997) and Peterson led the city in
scoring as a junior and senior.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cleaves is a two-time All-American, Smith is projected as
an NBA draft prospect, Bell is one of the Big Ten's best defenders
and Peterson might be the best sixth man in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Several national news outlets have chronicled their stories, and
many more will this week leading up to the Final Four. They are
easy to spot, thanks to a prominent tattoo of ``Flint'' in Old
English lettering on the upper right arm of all but Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know where we're from so they can form a
better opinion of Flint,'' Smith said. ``All you hear about it is
the negative, but we wouldn't be here doing as well as we are,
going to school and playing basketball, if it couldn't be done.
Kids need to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday in St. Petersburg, Fla., the stands at Tropicana
Field will be packed. Millions more will be watching on television
when Michigan State tries to beat a team that is billed as one of
the best in college basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   For the Flintstones, though, No. 1-ranked Duke is simply a team
trying to keep them from realizing their next goal _ playing in the
next game. Just like it is at the Berston.
</P>
<P>
   If you are familiar with urban ballplayers, you know they play
with a unique intensity. One of the most significant reasons for
that is what's at stake _ the right to play the next game.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves' eyes light up when you ask him about Berston
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball players may be born in hospitals, but in Flint, the
Berston is where they grow up, where true hoopsters build their
reps.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the spot,'' Cleaves said. ``If you can play there, you
can play anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A physical 6-2 junior, Cleaves overpowers most point guards. And
though his statistics appear normal, he knows how to win games.
Those two attributes were necessary to be successful at his old
stomping grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really call a foul, because you're gonna be doing
some hacking yourself,'' Cleaves. ``Plus if you do call one, you
have to argue like crazy to get it, so it's not even worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with the NCAA Tournament, you win or you're out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be so many people there waiting to play that if
you lost, you might as well go home 'cause you weren't getting
another up,'' Cleaves said. ``People everywhere, just waiting to
play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Even many who would seem more suited to playing other sports
found their way to Berston. Coaches know that is where you go to
find talent. That's where Izzo found Smith, his first recruit and
his first Flintstone.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a 6-8, 250-pound strongman, says he would probably be a
better football player than basketball player, but he couldn't
resist the lure of the game in Flint.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have some guys that will stick to football, like Andre
Rison or my brother (Fernando, a five-year NFL veteran who played
with the Jacksonville Jaguars last season), but that is very few,''
Smith said. ``There is nothing else to do there but play
basketball, and if you can play basketball, you know you can be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flintstones are proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all taught the value of hard work,'' Peterson said.
``We're from a blue-collar town, and that is part of our makeup.
It's a part of our makeup that we are very proud of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
