<HEADER>
A3070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      03-24 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 STARR AIDE CHALLENGES McDOUGAL TESTIMONY  
 (bl)   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ A prosecutor for Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr sought Wednesday to undermine Susan McDougal's testimony
about President Clinton's knowledge of decades-old financial
dealings in Arkansas, portraying her as someone who has never
accepted the reality of her own criminal conviction and who tailors
her accounts to fit the drama of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal, testifying in her own defense on the second day
of her trial here for obstruction of justice and criminal contempt
for refusing to answer questions before a grand jury, had testified
Tuesday that she had no knowledge of any wrongdoing by Clinton, the
governor then, in connection with the Whitewater real estate
venture. She and her husband, James McDougal, were partners in the
company with Clinton and his wife, Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. McDougal had refused to answer the same questions
from the grand jury, choosing instead to serve 18 months in jail,
she declared Tuesday that she was confident that Clinton had
testified truthfully in 1996 at her criminal trial for bank fraud,
in which she was convicted of four felony charges. The president
said then that he had no knowledge of an improper $300,000 loan
made to Mrs. McDougal, although the man who made the loan testified
that he had been pressed to do so by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal told the jury on Tuesday that if Clinton had not
told the truth in 1996, she would have registered her objection.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Barrett, an associate counsel in Starr's office,
Wednesday showed a videotape of Mrs. McDougal being interviewed in
prison in May 1998, in which she said she had no idea if the
president had testified truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal is heard on the tape telling Tim Russert, the host
of the NBC News program ``Meet the Press,'' that she could not
confirm her lawyer's statement that Clinton had testified
truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to check the transcript,'' she said. ``I would
have to have his testimony before me and go through it line by
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett also sought to remind the jury Wednesday that Mrs.
McDougal is a convicted felon by asking her to confirm that she had
been found guilty of bank fraud in the very same courtroom. Mrs.
McDougal tried to turn the question into an opportunity to inveigh
against Starr, saying that she was the victim of ``a ruthless
prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett and Mrs. McDougal then reached a verbal standoff until
Judge George Howard ordered Mrs. McDougal to respond that she had
indeed been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mrs. McDougal portrayed her decision not to
testify about the Clintons before a grand jury as an almost
religious experience, an act of personal redemption, because she
was defying a prosecutor she believed was pursuing the Clintons
with what she described as Nazi-like determination.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning earlier in the day by her lawyer, Mrs.
McDougal told the jury that she had often made ethical mistakes in
her life and was given to ``cutting corners.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, she had decided that she could not abide living
with herself if she accommodated prosecutors whom she said wanted
her to lie about the Clintons and even hoped she would testify that
she had had a sexual affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old Mrs. McDougal labored to justify her decision
not to talk to the grand jury even though she made clear Tuesday
that she believed she had no information of value to impart. To
make her case, she tried to depict Starr's prosecutors as predators
who offered to relieve her of unrelated criminal charges in
California if she provided damaging information about the Clintons.
She said that one prosecutor, Ray Jahn, told her that if she did
not cooperate she would be subjected to an income tax
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal said that her late former husband, James, had
urged her to cooperate with Starr's prosecutors even if it meant
lying. She said that McDougal had also told her that one of the
prosecutors, W. Hickman Ewing, would be satisfied if she testified
that she had had an affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this fellow, Hickman Ewing, in the Office of
Independent Counsel. He believes he can get Clinton on a sex charge
before the election,'' she quoted McDougal as having told her in
1996 when she was considering making a deal with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who has been in charge of the Arkansas phase of the
Whitewater investigation and who was sitting in the gallery as Mrs.
McDougal gave her testimony, later denounced her comments as
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal on Wednesday also answered the final question
prosecutors had put to her before the grand jury: What is the
explanation for the notation ``Payoff Clinton'' in her handwriting
that appeared on a 1983 check for $5,081 from the Arkansas savings
and loan she owned wth her husband.
</P>
<P>
   She said the notation referred to a land deal in Clinton, Ark.,
and not to Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
