<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRITE     03-24 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LIKENS KOSOVO INTERVENTION TO EFFORTS TO HALT HITLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates with Clinton remarks, edits to tighten.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton invoked the specter of Adolf
Hitler's massacres across Europe Wednesday night to dramatize his
plea for public support for the U.S.-led air campaign against
Yugoslav forces to stem murderous attacks on civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered his 13-minute appeal from the Oval Office just
six hours after ordering the fourth U.S. military attack on a
sovereign nation in seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States and 18 allies in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization had to halt the rampage of Yugoslav
forces across the Maryland-sized province of Kosovo before the
conflict and its refugees spilled into neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ingredients for a major war are there _ ancient
grievances, struggling democracies and in the center of it all, a
dictator in Serbia who has done nothing since the Cold WAr ended
but start new wars and pour gasoline on the flames of ethnic and
religious division,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav crackdown on ethnic Albanians' quest for autonomy in
Kosovo has spawned 60,000 refugees in the last five weeks to join
200,000 others. Kosovo is a province of Serbia, one of two states
that make up the Balkan nation of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,000 Yugoslav troops and police officers have ``started
moving from village to village, shelling civilians and torching
their houses,'' Clinton explained. ``We've seen innocent people
taken from their homes, forced to kneel in the dirt and sprayed
with bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   After making elliptical references to Nazi atrocities in World
War II, Clinton declared: ``Just imagine if leaders back then had
acted wisely and early enough, how many lives could have been
saved. How many Americans would not have had to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used two maps and likened distances in the region to the
mileage between Washington and New York in a bid to drive home the
scale of the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending this tragedy is a moral imperative,'' Clinton declared,
adding: ``Inaction invites more brutality _ but firmness can save
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was taking military action now ``in the interest
of avoiding an even crueler and costlier war'' later ``so that
future generations of Americans do not have to cross the Atlantic
to fight another war.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's address followed earlier remarks as the allied
offensive began to fall across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   British and American forces led the initial attacks that
included aircraft from 11 nations.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was the first attack staged against a sovereign
nation by NATO forces since the Cold War-era alliance was formed in
1949 to combat threatened Soviet-bloc aggression against Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Six 1950s-era B-52 bombers based in Britain launched more than
three dozen precision-guided cruise missiles against targets in and
near Kosovo. Two U.S. B-2 stealth bombers based at Whiteman Air
Force Base in Missouri dropped laser-guided 2,000 pound
bunker-buster bombs in the first combat use of the billion dollar
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Warplanes based at Aviano, in northern Italy, swept across the
Adriatic Sea to strike targets in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warships also fired cruise missiles against targets in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said allies resorted to armed force after Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic rejected diplomatic persuasion to end
his year-old military crackdown against an independence movement in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants Milosevic to permit an allied
peacekeeping force of 28,000 troops _ including 4,000 Americans _
to enter Kosovo to enforce a yet-to-be negotiated cease-fire and
political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who drew parallels on Tuesday between the Yugoslav
attacks and Nazi exterminations of civilians in World War II, said
``tens of thousands'' of ethnic Albanian civilians could be driven
from their homes in Kosovo into neighboring Albania and Macedonia,
unless the Yugoslav offensive is halted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the allied onslaught a ``stand against ethnic
violence and atrocity,'' adding: ``It will clearly be much more
costly and dangerous to stop it later than this effort to prevent
it from going further now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the operation was designed to demonstrate the
``seriousness'' of allied opposition to Yugoslav aggression;
dissuade attacks on civilians; and damage Yugoslavia's capacity to
wage war.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, Clinton has ordered U.S. forces to attack Iraq,
Sudan, Afghanistan and now Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton canceled a planned three-day trip to Ohio, Nevada and
California that included political fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   With the military operation underway, Clinton garnered reluctant
rally-round-the-flag support from some wary Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who had a long-planned
lunch with Clinton at the White House, issued a statement
afterwards that expressed support for troops involved in ``a
complex and delicate situation that involves European stability and
our own nation's security.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert added that he has questions about the long-term strategy
of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who has questioned
Clinton's penchant for launching military operations overseas,
offered support for troops in the operation _ if not for Clinton's
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever our reservations about the president's actions in the
Balkans, let no one doubt that the Congress and the American people
stand united behind our men and women who are bravely heeding the
call of duty there,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a likely GOP presidential candidate,
said he supported the air strikes but said ``everyone wants to know
what Plan B is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, said he would support the president's
decision for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look _ the planes are flying,'' Kasich told reporters, adding
that he hoped the White House was mapping ``what the next step
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said the United States ``diminishes itself'' by becoming
entangled in ``civil wars and ethnic conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said a ``great power has to not only know when to go, but
when not to go'' to war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to brace Americans for the possibility that U.S.
pilots could be shot down and killed or captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action is not risk-free,'' the president said. ``It
carries risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said he had ordered additional
search and rescue teams into the region to retrieve any downed
pilots. A Marine Corps team rescued Air Force Capt. Scott O'Grady
in June 1995 after O'Grady evaded capture for six days after his
F-16 fighter was shot down by Bosnian Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-led operation threatened to chill U.S.-Russia
relations. Clinton spoke by telephone with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin about five hours before the attack began but failed to
persuade the Kremlin leader to support the aerial attacks against a
traditional Russian ally in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov abandoned
a planned visit to Washington and turned his U.S.-bound aircraft
around over the North Atlantic to return to Moscow after receiving
a telephone call from Vice President Al Gore that NATO was
preparing to attack targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
