</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GET-RICH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They're in the money: Georgians worth $100,000-plus on the rise
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia has about 40,000 more households with incomes
greater than $100,000 a year than at the beginning of the 1990s,
according to a study by a company that analyzes such information.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Georgia households with six-figure incomes or
beyond has ballooned by 52 percent since the start of the decade,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   About 114,145 of the 2.1 million households in Georgia have
passed the $100,000 threshold, and most of them _ 82,450 _ are in
metro Atlanta, according to John Karevoll of Acxiom Corp., which
specializes in database analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Growth of the six-figure set is a sign of the state's rapid
economic expansion, as well as the influx of outsiders moving here
for professional jobs, he said. ``This has been a top-down
recovery. Those who had higher income were the first to benefit
from the growth of the economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study relied on figures compiled through the fall of 1998
from federal and private sector sources.
</P>
<P>
   In one ZIP code _ 30327 in Buckhead _ 44 percent of households
had more than $100,000 in income. The average annual household
income in the United States is still shy of $40,000, according to
the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Economists warn against seeing the numbers as proof that Georgia
has surged into affluence.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation alone since 1990 has amounted to 25 percent, said Jeff
Humphreys, director of economic forecasting at the University of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Jared Bernstein, economist at the Economic Policy Institute in
Washington, D.C., questioned the study's conclusion. ``That is a
very big change, and I am suspicious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Wayne Gantt, economist and president of the Ansley Group, a
consulting firm in Atlanta, said the $100,000 benchmark itself is
misleading. ``I'd say $100,000 isn't what it used to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
