<HEADER>
A3074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-SAFETY-NYT &LR;      03-24 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR SAFETY BOARD URGES RUDDER CHANGES IN BOEING 737 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Va. _ The National Transportation Safety Board said
Wednesday that changes should be made in thousands of Boeing 737s
to assure that no more crashes occur because of a single mechanical
failure in the plane's rudder control mechanism. The recommendation
for the world's most popular airliner, which is based on
investigation of two crashes and several smaller mishaps, could be
among the most far-reaching the NTSB has ever made.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing Co. responded that it knew of no problems that would
not be solved by changes already under way, and the Federal
Aviation Administration said it did not understand what the NTSB
meant when it recommended making the system the pilots use for
moving the rudder ``reliably redundant.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said it was up to the FAA to determine how that should
be accomplished. In aviation, redundancy means having a second
piece of equipment to perform a crucial job if the first one fails.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation came as part of a finding issued Wednesday in
the case of USAir 427, a 737 that crashed on approach to Pittsburgh
in September 1994, killing all 132 people on board. The finding was
unusual because its conclusion _ that the crash was caused by a
hydraulic jam that swung the rudder opposite the direction the
pilot wanted _ was not based on any physical evidence. This was a
crash solved by computer simulation, with the NTSB's staff saying
that such a rudder malfunction was the only way the plane could
have fallen the way it did.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB declined to specify what would modifications should be
made in the control system, although Boeing and the FAA said they
might involve adding a second hydraulic valve, or installing a
rudder split horizontally, the upper half and lower half being
controlled by separate systems.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Boeing executives responded by saying that the rudder was
already being made fully redundant because fixes have been ordered
and are now being made to to hundreds of planes a month as a result
of the Pittsburgh crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything in the hearings that leads me to
believe anyone has data about a problem that needs to be fixed,''
said the chief of aircraft safety at the FAA, Thomas McSweeny. He
did, however, acknowledge that there is at least one recent
incident of a rudder malfunction that experts cannot explain. In
that mishap, in which there were no deaths or injuries, the 737s
rudder had already been modified.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB is an independent agency and has advisory powers only,
although the FAA follows the great majority of its recommendations.
NTSB members complained bitterly Wednesday that if the FAA had
acted promptly on their recommendations for better flight data
recorders, two recent non-fatal rudder malfunctions in 737s might
have been recorded in greater detail, reducing the mystery behind
Flight 427.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA and Boeing said they agreed with another NTSB
recommendation, for intensive additional study of the rudder
mechanism, which the NTSB also blamed for the crash of United
flight 585 as it attempted a landing at Colorado Springs, Colo., in
March, 1991. In that sense the investigation of the Pittsburgh
crash, the longest in the NTSB's history, will continue.
</P>
<P>
   In voting to approve a finding that rudder malfunction be cited
as the probable cause of both crashes, the board's four members
held no public debate. Their conclusion, after extensive private
discussion, was unanimous but not without misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there's much evidence in these investigations, the vast
majority of it is not things you can lay your hands on,'' said
George Black, one of the four members. He and others expressed
frustration about the failure to find scars, cracks or other
evidence of a jam on the hydraulic valve or other parts of the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also stressed the lack of evidence, maintaining that
either mechanical failure or pilot error was possible in the
Pittsburgh crash, but it said it would not argue the point with the
NTSB.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB, Boeing and the FAA on Wednesday all praised the 737, a
plane that has accumulated 91 million flight hours of service,
moving more passengers than there are people on earth.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would gladly participate in a joint study, with
safety board engineers and others, to find other ways that the
rudder could fail.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 of the planes are in service worldwide, although
the NTSB's recommendation covers only those registered in this
country, about 1,300.
</P>
<P>
   Various changes, some requiring substantial effort, have been
made voluntarily by some airlines and have now been made mandatory
by the FAA. These include changing a valve to prevent the kind of
jam that the NTSB said occurred in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   When rudder controls malfunction, pilots can fly using controls
on the wings called ailerons and spoilers, but at low speeds the
rudder overpowers these other flight controls.
</P>
<P>
   In investigating the Pittsburgh crash, engineers determined that
the 737 is unusual in that it is often flown at speeds slow enough
for the rudder, if it malfunctioned, to be more powerful than the
other controls. One of the NTSB's recommendations Wednesday was
that pilots be taught that if a rudder malfunctions, they should
push the nose of the plane down into a dive, and pick up enough
speed to let them overcome the rudder.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB also said that 737s should routinely fly faster on
approach to airports, to keep the speed above the level where a bad
rudder could overpower other controls. A spokesman for the Air Line
Pilots Association, John Cox, who is a captain with USAir, said
that his airline responded to the problem by lowering the wing
flaps earlier; that, too, increases a pilot's control of the plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
