<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBAL-ONE-ART-NYT     03-24 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-ONE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOMMUNICATION CONSORTIUM IS SAID TO BE NEAR COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Global One telecommunications consortium of Sprint, France
Telecom and Germany's Deutsche Telekom is close to collapse, and an
agreement to dissolve the venture could come within as few as six
weeks, executives close to Global One said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dissolution would set the stage for Sprint to be acquired by
another communications giant and for Deutsche Telekom to seek
international acquisitions of its own.
</P>
<P>
   William T. Esrey, Sprint's chairman, sent a letter three weeks
ago to Ron Sommer and Michel Bon, the chairmen of Deutsche Telekom
and France Telecom, respectively, saying essentially that Global
One was failing in its current form and that the companies should
move decisively to resolve the partnership, said the executives
close to the venture.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies founded Global One in 1996 mainly to offer
large multinational corporations complete, integrated
telecommunications services worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey appeared to refrain from calling for the venture's
termination outright, the executives said, because the agreement
among the three companies specifies large financial penalties for
any one company that initiates a break-up of Global One, the
executives said. They added, however, that the German and French
companies, which together own 20 percent of Sprint, interpreted the
letter as a sign that Sprint would like to end its role in the
partnership, which has been troubled from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Since the letter was sent, representatives of the three
companies have been locked in negotiations that appear destined to
lead to the venture's end, the executives said. They added,
however, that there was still a small chance that Global One could
be salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and Sprint declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Global One has become a problem for Sprint in two main ways,
executives close to the venture said.
</P>
<P>
   First, the consortium never ran smoothly. From the beginning,
Sprint was frustrated by the German and French companies' shuffling
of executives in and out of the venture, and the companies never
quite agreed on which companies should assume which
responsibilities in operating the venture. Also, the companies
never fully integrated their networks, the executives said,
increasing the difficulty of offering seamless services around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has said that Global One's performance has picked up
since Gary Forsee, formerly head of Sprint's long-distance
division, took over as Global One's chief executive. But the member
companies still have remained far apart on how best to position the
venture and on details of its budget.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important as Global One's operational problems, however,
has been the realization at Sprint that Deutsche Telekom and France
Telecom are not likely to acquire the 80 percent of Sprint they do
not already own, according to executives close to Global One.
</P>
<P>
   It has been clear for some time that Sprint believes that its
long-term survival will depend on combining with at least one other
major telecommunications carrier.The pace of consolidation in the
phone industry has become so brisk that otherwise Sprint risks
becoming relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   From Sprint's perspective, France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom
would be ideal partners, but the European companies have all but
decided not to acquire Sprint, executives close to Global One said.
The first hurdle is the sheer amount of capital required; Sprint's
common stock (which is separate from the stock the European
companies own) has a market value of $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom wants to focus its international investments in
Europe, so there is no appeal in spending that kind of money for a
U. S. company. Deutsche Telekom has additional concerns, ranging
from questions about the technical details of Sprint's network to
doubts about its own ability to retain valuable Sprint executives
after an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   So, according to executives close to Global One, the thinking at
Sprint seems to be: What is the point of remaining locked in with
France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom in this so-so partnership if
they are never going to step up and marry us for real? Why not
clear the decks so we can pursue a merger with someone else (like
the BellSouth Corp., perhaps, though a deal like that might founder
before regulators)?
</P>
<P>
   The main complication is that even if Global One is dissolved,
France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom still would together own 20
percent of Sprint, a stake they agreed to buy in 1994 for more than
$3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Global One, there would be little reason for
the French and German companies to hold on to their Sprint stock.
But getting rid of it would not be simple. They could sell it to
the public, but it is unlikely that Sprint would agree to a
secondary offering that would depress its stock price. In all
likelihood, France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom would end up
keeping their Sprint stakes with the understanding that they would
sell them to a company that made a friendly deal to acquire the
rest of Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   As for Deutsche Telekom, it has been considering a host of
options for expanding its presence outside Germany and around the
world, either alone or in continued partnership with France
Telecom, the executives said. Among the companies that would seem
to make sense for Deutsche Telekom to acquire are Qwest
Communications International Inc.; the recent combination of Global
Telesystems Group Inc. and Esprit Telecom Group of Britain; RSL
Communications of Bermuda; Global Crossing of Bermuda, and the
communications unit of the Williams Companies Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
