<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHN-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Good chemistry and an excellent coach' reminiscent of '68
Buckeye team
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They are still close friends, 31 years later.
Except for family and war, no bonds are stronger than those forged
in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hosket and Denny Meadors were two kids who came out of
Dayton in the '60s and helped restore Ohio State basketball. They
went to the Final Four together in 1968 and now the memories rush
back as they see the similarities between their situation and the
one the present Buckeyes face.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams shocked the state after several mediocre seasons. The
'68 bunch followed Buckeye teams that went 12-12, 11-13 and 13-11.
This year's team followed five straight losers.
</P>
<P>
   Both went to the Final Four as ``That Other Team.'' In '68, the
three anointed teams were Houston, UCLA and North Carolina, ranked
1-2-3. This year, the three are Duke, Michigan State and UConn,
ranked 1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Hosket, who is close to this team as an analyst on Buckeye TV
games, noted another, deeper similarity. ``I see exactly what we
had,'' he said, ``good chemistry and an excellent coach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And no egos,'' said Meadors. ``These kids really like each
other. Just like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosket went to Columbus first after playing on Belmont's state
championship team of 1964. Meadors followed a year later after a
terrific career at Stebbins.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1967-68 season, sick of losing, they were ready for, as
Hosket said, ``a magical season.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, only the league champions went to the NCAA
Tournament, and on the final day of the season, the Buckeyes were
one game behind Iowa, needing a miracle _ last-place Michigan had
to beat Iowa to get OSU into a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Rudy Tomjanovich?'' Meadors said of the present
Houston Rockets coach. ``He was on that Michigan team. He's the
reason they beat Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   So you're a Rockets fan now?
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet I am,'' Meadors said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks beat Iowa 85-81 in the playoff, took down East
Tennessee State in the first round of the Midwest Regional, but
then had to play No. 4 Kentucky in Lexington, where the Wildcats
hadn't lost all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their pep band kept playing, California, Here We Come,''
Meadors said. ``But we hung with them.''
</P>
<P>
   With three seconds left, Hosket in-bounded to Dave Sorenson and
Sorenson banked one in to beat the 'Cats, 82-81.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is from Kentucky,'' Meadors said. ``And they were
all there. They wanted me to do well, but they wanted Kentucky to
win. Afterward, my grandfather wouldn't speak to me. I'm serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of sports bonds.
</P>
<P>
   So the Buckeyes went to Los Angeles as That Other Team, and
Carolina took 'em apart in the semifinal, 80-66.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like the JV game,'' Hosket said. ``The only game
anyone talked about was the rematch between UCLA and Houston.
Houston was unbeaten and had given UCLA its only loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Their versions of that semifinal differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always say if Meadors could have gotten the ball up the
floor, we would have won,'' said Hosket.
</P>
<P>
   ``My memory is that if Hosket could have guarded someone, we
would have won,'' said Meadors.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is serious. Thirty-one years later, they needle each
other like brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, Carolina was a great team,'' Meadors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had Charlie Scott, Larry Miller, Rusty Clark,'' Hosket
said. ``They also had the commissioner of the Big Ten, Jim Delany,
as a reserve guard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got in foul trouble early and got behind and never caught
up,'' Meadors said. ``We always laughed that we were four centers
and a guard. I was the only guy on the floor who could handle the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, early in the season the Buckeyes did start four kids
who played center in high school _ Hosket, Sorenson, Steve Howell
and Mike Swain _ with Meadors. Later, coach Fred Taylor put guard
Jody Finney in place of Swain, but Finney was mostly known for his
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always kidded coach Taylor that we're the team that got him
in the Hall of Fame,'' Hosket said. ``Anybody could have coached
the Lucas-Havlicek team to the Final Four. But only a genius could
have gotten us there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes came back, in those days of consolation games, and
beat Houston in the third-place game. As usual, the Daytonians'
memories diverge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston had Elvin Hayes and he scored like 34,'' Hosket said.
``We were mostly in a zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hosket was assigned to Hayes,'' Meadors said, laughing because
he knew Hosket would eventually read this and fume.
</P>
<P>
   The two men's lives have paralleled each other in many ways
since they graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Hosket is a vice-president at Millcraft Paper and lives in
Columbus with his wife and three sons, two of them named Brett and
Brad.
</P>
<P>
   Meadors is a vice-president at Raymond James and Associates and
lives in Columbus with his wife and three sons, two of them named
Brett and Brad.
</P>
<P>
   The mark of how respected they are came last February in the
ceremonies before the final game in St. John Arena. Fred Taylor's
wife and children chose Hosket and Meadors to push Taylor's
wheelchair to the center circle in the most heart-rending moment of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great honor,'' Meadors said. ``Everybody was crying.
Me and Hoss couldn't look at each other. The ovation lasted five
minutes. It was staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Both will be in St. Pete this weekend and both like OSU's
chances against UConn in Saturday's semifinal. Both like the
matchups and believe this is an OSU team a cut above.
</P>
<P>
   Just as were they, 31 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
