<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVOQ0325-COX     03-24 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVOQ0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO LAUNCHES AIR STRIKES AGAINST SERB FORCES, CLINTON SEEKS
BACKING OF AMERICAN PUBLIC
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim at 1200 words.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MILITARY-0325; KOSOVO-DISSENT-0325;
KOSOVO-NATO-0325.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and its NATO allies slammed
Yugoslavia Wednesday night with scores of cruise missiles and
guided bombs , striking power plants, anti-aircraft sites, army
barracks and other military targets from the country's southern
plains to the outskirts of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   As a massive U.S.-led armada of warplanes -- including a pair of
B-2 long-range stealth bombers -- pressed Operation: Allied Force'
deep into Yugoslavia, President Clinton said the world had lost
patience with Serb military aggression against ethnic Albanians in
Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending this tragedy is a moral imperative,'' Clinton said in
an address to the nation from the Oval Office, hoping to build on
the thin national support for a high-risk mission the White House
has threatened for weeks to launch. ``Our firmness is the only hope
the people of Kosovo have to be able to live in their own country
without having to fear for their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon vowed to continue the air campaign, Clinton
pledged that ``we will deliver a forceful response,'' if Serb
forces counterattack U.S. positions in the region. Several thousand
U.S. troops remain in neighboring Bosnia, helping to police a
fragile peace based on an edgy partition of Serb and non-Serb
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also promised that no U.S. ground troops would go to
Kosovo, except as part of a larger NATO peacekeeping force that, as
of yet, remains part of a contingency plan so far rejected by
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not intend to put our troops in Kosovo to fight a war,''
said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As he has several times in recent days, Clinton braced the
nation for the possibility of U.S. casualties and, for the first
time, warned of the risk of civilian casualties in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are risks in this military action,'' Clinton said,
``risks to our pilots and to people on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But, said Clinton, those threats are outweighed by the dangers
of allowing Serb aggression to continue and risking the spread of
the conflict in the volatile Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a conflict with no natural national boundaries,''
warned Clinton. ``Let a fire burn in this area, and the flames will
spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to the difficulty of explaining the U.S. interests in
what's unfolding in a remote province in the troubled Balkans,
Clinton twice referred to color maps of the region to try to
convince heartland Americans of the dangers of continued violence
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ingredients for a major war are there,'' Clinton said,
pointing out the centuries-old ethnic and religious tensions in a
region that triggered World War I, saw some of the most savage
fighting of World War II and was a crucible of East-West tensions
throughout the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   A year of Serb military attacks on villages and civilians has
left more than 2,000 dead and another quarter of a million homeless
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks of intensive diplomatic efforts to end the fighting
collapsed on Tuesday with the rejection of a U.S.-backed peace plan
by Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic. The plan has been agreed to by
the Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is the president of Yugoslavia, which takes in Serbia
and neighboring Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Explosions ripped the perimeters of Kosovo's provincial capital,
Pristina, and the suburbs of Belgrade beginning just before 8 p.m.,
(2 p.m. EST), as air raid sirens blared through the cities for the
first time since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks near those cities and more than a dozen other sites
continued for roughly four hours, as successive waves of
ship-launched cruise missiles, jet fighters and bombers raked the
small Balkan country in the largest combat attack in the 50-year
history of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missiles were launched from U.S. and British ships and
submarines in the Mediterranean and Adriatic seas and from U.S.
B-52 bombers flying high overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Guided bombs weighing up to 2,000 pounds each were dropped from
U.S. F-16 and F-15 warplanes, and a pair of the B-2 Spirit stealth
bombers. It was the first mission ever for the 11-year-old Spirits,
which cost $2.1 billion each and were designed in the waning years
of the Cold War for deep penetration into Soviet airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials wouldn't publicly confirm speculation that
the Spirits formed the spearhead of attacks near a heavily-defended
military air base outside of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the strikes began, Milosevic went on state-run
television in Belgrade to assail the long-advertised attack,
portraying it as a criminal assault on a sovereign nation and
urging his countrymen to employ ''all means,'' to defend their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at stake here is the freedom of the entire country,''
Milosevic said. ``Kosovo was only the door intended to allow
foreign troops to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   The peace plan Milosevic rejected called for 28,000 NATO
peacekeepers, including 4,000 Americans, to occupy Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon would say little about the attacks, citing security
concerns. News reports from Yugoslavia, however, suggested that
more than 20 targets were hit in the initial phase of what could be
a long-term assault aimed at ''seriously diminishing,'' in
Clinton's words, Serb military capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The target list is extensive,'' Defense Secretary William
Cohen told reporters at a Pentagon briefing, insisting that the
duration of the campaign would be determined by the extent of
damage air strikes do to Serb military capability, not by any
predetermined schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen confirmed that NATO pilots had engaged in air-to-air
combat, amid reports of the downing of at least one Soviet made
Serb MiG fighter.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday's operations nearly complete, Cohen said he knew
of no NATO losses, saying ``our aircraft have safely returned,'' to
their bases in Italy, Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the joint chiefs, said NATO would
press its attacks on Serb air defenses -- in hopes of reducing the
risk to NATO pilots -- as well as power plants and other support
systems, Serb troops, and the hundreds of tanks backing those
troops in and around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton laid out three objectives for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The first, Clinton said, is to demonstrate to Milosevic that
NATO will no tolerate further Serb military attacks on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, where a year of repression has left more than
2,000 dead and another quarter of a million homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second,'' Clinton said, is ``to deter President Milosevic from
continuing and escalating his attacks on helpless civilians, by
imposing a price for those attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   And third, Clinton said, ``if necessary, to damage Serbia's
capacity to wage war against Kosovo in the future, by seriously
diminishing its military capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as NATO moved ahead with air strikes, the Clinton
administration insisted the diplomatic option remains open to
Milosevic, should he agree to the international peace plan and the
NATO implementation force it would mandate.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke, who spent two fruitless
days in Belgrade earlier this week trying to persuade Milosevic to
sign onto the agreement, remained in the region, in nearby
Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to get in touch with each other,'' said State
Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to fill a diplomatic breach, Clinton had a 45-minute
telephone conversation Wednesday with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, who went on television in Moscow to decry the NATO attacks
on Russia's traditional Serb allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue as an area where we and the Russians must agree to
disagree,'' said Rubin. ``Russia should not let our relationship be
stymied by the activities of a petty dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by China, which also opposes the strikes, Russia called
an emergency meeting of the United Nations Security Council to
discuss the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan criticized NATO for not
consulting with the Security Council before launching the strikes,
a move NATO avoided due to the certainty of a veto by Russia and
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Security Council has primary responsibility for
maintaining international peace and security,'' Annan told
reporters at U.N. headquarters in New York. ``Therefore, the
Council should be involved in any decision to resort to force.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's rebuke was a mild one, however, and he laid the blame
for the strikes clearly at the feet of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret that in spite of all the efforts made by the
international community, the
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav authorities have persisted in their rejection of a
political settlement which would have halted the bloodshed in
Kosovo and secured an equitable peace for the population,'' said
Annan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indeed tragic that diplomacy has failed,'' said Annan.
``But there are times when the use of force may be legitimate in
the pursuit of peace.''
</P>
