<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3083 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS &LR;      03-24 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA BREAKS TIES TO NATO AS PROTEST OF BOMBING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In an outburst reminiscent of the Cold War, Russia
broke ties with NATO Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and threatened further action
to protest the US-led alliance's bombing in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris N. Yeltsin, saying he was ``deeply shocked''
after his last-minute phone call with President Clinton failed to
avert the airstrikes, said in a statement that Russia was ``ready
to take adequate steps, including of a military nature, to ensure
its own security and that of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Promptly after the bombing began, Russia demanded an emergency
session of the UN Security Council. Russian officials said Moscow
at such a session might call for lifting the UN arms embargo
against Yugoslavia. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Russia was
considering withdrawing from the embargo unilaterally, which could
allow Moscow to begin supplying Serb forces with arms.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting rising tensions between Russia and the West over
Kosovo, Yeltsin recalled Russia's envoy to NATO headquarters in
Brussels and suspended Russia's membership in Partnership for
Peace. The NATO program, which Russia joined in 1994, was designed
to bring former East and West enemies closer by encouraging
military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's response to the bombing also highlighted the
frustration of a snubbed former superpower that found itself foiled
once again in its efforts to stop Washington from bombing an ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US and its European allies . . . have wiped their feet on
us,'' said Vladimir Lukin, Russia's former ambassador to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   NATO launched the raids after Yugoslavia would not agree to a
peace settlement in Kosovo. Serb troops are battling ethnic
Albanian guerrillas in the province, where hundreds have been
killed and 60,000 have been forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which considers its fellow Orthodox Slavs the Serbs
historical allies, has argued against a military solution, much as
it tried to halt US and British airstrikes against Iraq in 1991.
Failing in this effort not only damages ambitions to restore
superpower status to Russia. Wary of their own separatist conflict
with Chechnya, Russian politicians worry about the precedent set by
NATO's decision to bomb without UN approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to the whole world . . . to all politicians, while
there are still a few minutes left, let us convince Clinton not to
take this tragic, dramatic step,'' Yeltsin, who made his first trip
to the Kremlin after a month recovering from a bleeding ulcer, said
in a televised address. ``This is a war in Europe, and maybe even
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's comments also showed signs of Moscow's growing
frustration with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, (Milosevic) is a difficult negotiator. Sometimes you have
to speak to him two, three, five, 10, or 20 times,'' growled the
Russian leader. ``But we shouldn't regret talking to him those 10,
20 times for the sake of the hundreds and hundreds of people who
will die in a few hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who returned home Wednesday
after canceling his planned trip to Washington in midflight on
Tuesday, said he had admonished Vice President Al Gore to ``think
it over once more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think that the strikes will help stabilize the
situation in Kosovo,'' Primakov said on arrival in Moscow. ``On the
contrary, they will be destabilizing, and our relations with the
United States as well as stability in Europe will suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov had been hoping to secure billions of dollars in new
loans for Russia's sagging economy, which has been sapped by
corruption, poor tax collection, and the low price of oil, the
country's main export.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's decision to cancel his trip was applauded by
Communists and nationalists in parliament, but others criticized
the move as evidence of the fundamental flaw in Russia's policy of
tacitly supporting Milosevic while asking the West for loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A weakened Russia should not bet its fate on the moods of
President Slobodan Milosevic,'' said Sergei Karaganov, head of a
Moscow think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Others were more emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of friends of Russia are these, who make us look
like complete idiots to the rest of the world?'' asked centrist
legislator Nikolai Goncharov.
</P>
<P>
   With talks with the International Monetary Fund temporarily on
hold, the Russian currency tumbled nearly 2 points to 26 to the
dollar, a new lowpoint for the ruble since it was devalued in
August. Some analysts predicted a further drop. Others said
Primakov's cancellation would not hurt Russia's chances for IMF
money.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Communist and ultranationalist leaders, who often
play up Russia's kinship with Serbs to express their anti-Western
sentiments, called on Russians to volunteer to fight alongside
Yugoslav forces. The extremist Russian Party said it had already
gathered 150 men; the party also warned American citizens to leave
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov compared the NATO attack to
Hitler's expansionist moves that started World War II, and called
for massive military aide to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Another Communist legislator, Viktor Ilyukhin, notorious in the
West for his anti-Semitic comments, advocated moving nuclear
weapons back into Belarus. The former Soviet republic, wedged
between Russia and new NATO member Poland, had dismantled its
strategic arsenal after the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the West think about it,'' said Ilyukhin. ``Should they
become targets for our heavy rockets, including the new countries
of NATO?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
