<HEADER>
A3084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-NOTES25     03-24 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offensive load lifted, Langdon thriving
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ During his four seasons at Duke, guard
Trajan Langdon has been considered a money player, a guy who always
comes through when a clutch shot is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Always, that is, until the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 and 1998 NCAA Tournaments, the senior from
Anchorage, Alaska, was less than clutch, hitting only 19 of 68
shots from the field, 28 percent, including 11-for-38 on
3-pointers. Duke was eliminated in the second round by Providence
in 1997 and lost to Kentucky in the South Regional Final in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon's postseason woes have ended this season. In Sunday's
85-64 victory against Temple in the East Regional championship
game, Langdon hit 5 of 6 from 3-point range and needed only seven
shots from the field to score 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out Duke's first NCAA Tournament game against
Florida A&AMP;M, Langdon has hit 19 of 30 from the field and 11 of 18
from 3-point range. He is the hottest shooter in the country coming
into Saturday's Final Four game with Michigan State at Tropicana
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trajan is not one who would ever succumb to pressure, but he
is a human being, and he can get worn down,'' coach Mike Krzyzewski
said. ``He got worn down because he carried us _ further probably
than we should have advanced a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon said his improved shooting in this tournament has come
from playing on a team with a lot of offensive options, including
Elton Brand, Duke's All-American center and leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different mindset,'' Langdon said. ``I put too much
pressure on myself in the postseason these last couple of years. We
have such a talented team, they really don't need my shot, or if I
don't shoot well, we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly family and friends
</P>
<P>
   When teams make it to the Final Four, the players suddenly hear
from friends and relatives they didn't know they had. Just ask
UConn's Kevin Freeman, who had dozens of messages awaiting him when
the Huskies returned home from the West Regional in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of people who really don't know you or were
your friend in the past,'' Freeman said. ``Then you've got
relatives that want to fly in from everywhere. They can make it to
Florida, but they couldn't make it to Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Freeman said, is simple: Turn off the phone and let
your parents distribute the six tickets each player is allotted.
</P>
<P>
   Naismith awards
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski and Brand were chosen the winners of the Naismith
Coach and Player of the Year awards presented by the Atlanta Tipoff
Club. The women's award winners were Purdue coach Carolyn Peck,
whose team will face Louisiana Tech in the Friday's national
semifinal, and Tennessee senior Chamique Holdsclaw. The awards will
be presented at the Naismith banquet April 3 at the Cobb Galleria
Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
