<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LAWMAKERS CRITICAL OF U.S. ROLE IN AIRSTRIKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-RATIONALE and
KOSOVO-POLITICS.) 
 
By JENNIFER DAY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the U.S. House of Representatives voted
overwhelmingly to lend moral support for armed forces fighting in
Kosovo, some members of Congress continued to rail against American
involvement in NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 424-1 for a resolution supporting armed forces
sent to Kosovo, with Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Calif., opposing the
measure. Unlike the Senate's 58-41 vote Tuesday authorizing the
president to go ahead with the airstrikes, the House's resolution
was not a referendum on the decision to take military action.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who voted against the airstrikes, is
continuing to wage one of the most vocal protests, saying he cannot
support military action where there is no vital national interest
at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that President Clinton views American pilots,
soldiers and sailors as world social workers,'' said Gramm, who
voted Tuesday with 40 other senators to oppose the airstrikes. ``He
scours the globe for opportunities to do good in hostile lands, and
when he finds a problem, his inclination is to dispatch our troops
to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm criticized the president's plan in Kosovo and warned about
sending in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, agreed the strikes are a mistake,
stressing that ``a mission like this should not be initiated
without a clear exit strategy in place.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Illinois, and Sen. Olympia
Snowe, R-Maine, also questioned Clinton's long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, attempted to pin the
president to a timetable by blocking funding for the airstrikes
unless a detailed mission plan was submitted to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Her amendments were shelved, however, after fellow Republicans,
including Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., opposed them.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain, a Vietnam veteran who was a prisoner of war for
six years, acknowledged the risk of casualties inherent in military
involvement, he voted Tuesday with 16 other Republicans and 42
Democrats to support the airstrikes. He continued to be a backer of
the initiative Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support the president. We support our men and women, and
(Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic) has made a very big mistake,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, also agrees with the decision to take
military action, stating that Milosevic's ``ethnic cleansing''
policies are destabilizing the region and setting up circumstances
similar to those that sparked World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not act now, the slaughter would intensify, the
violence could spread, and the credibility of the United States and
its NATO allies would be shattered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen's words echoed those of the Democratic leadership,
including Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and Sen. Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., who both said NATO had ``no choice'' but to act.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, expressed caution, stating he was
worried about NATO taking the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said, ``Whatever our
reservations about the president's actions in the Balkans, let no
one doubt that the Congress and the American people stand united
behind our men and women who are bravely heeding the call of duty
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
