<HEADLINE>
DISASTER RELIEF APPROVED IN FACE OF CLINTON VETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Against the backdrop of a veto threat by President
Clinton, the House on Wednesday night approved a $1.3 billion
emergency spending bill that included nearly $1 billion in relief
to Central American countries ravaged by hurricanes and scaled back
an array of government programs to pay for the expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The final minutes of the vote, during which several Republicans
who had voted against the bill changed their positions to ensure
its passage by a narrow margin, underscored the slightness of the
Republican advantage in the House and the difficulty that party
leaders may face in passing legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally was 220-211. Only 10 Democrats joined
Republicans to support the bill, while only 11 Republicans joined
Democrats to oppose it. On Tuesday, the Senate also approved a
disaster bill that has drawn White House opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The hours of debate over the bill, the first spending measure
taken up by the House this year, foreshadowed what are certain to
be even more bitter disputes when the House turns its full
attention toward the budget for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assailed the cuts in the bill as unnecessary and
dangerous _ particularly a $648 million reduction in ``callable
capital,'' money set aside to guarantee loans by international
development banks, and a $150 million decrease in money for the
disposal of weapons-grade uranium and plutonium in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said that finding trims was the only way to pay
for the emergency spending while both keeping lawmakers' fingers
out of the federal surplus and staying within budget caps mandated
by Congress in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone thinks they have heartburn over this small number of
offsets, just wait until we bring the fiscal year 2000 budget to
the floor,'' said Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., chairman of the
House Appropriations Committee, toward the start of what turned
into a six-hour debate over the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in callable capital in particular drew protest
from the Clinton administration. In a letter to Young made public
Wednesday, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said that the measure
``could have negative consequences beyond the current budgetary
horizon for the developing world and our economy'' and would
probably ensure a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Senate overwhelmingly passed a similar
emergency spending bill that authorized $500 million more than the
House bill called for. The two bills, which concern supplemental
spending for the current fiscal year, will now proceed to
conference, where lawmakers will try to iron out differences
between the measures.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration has said that the president may
veto the result. Administration officials object to a number of
provisions in the bills, including cuts in money to beef up
security around U.S. embassies and to dispose of uranium and
plutonium in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats expressed particular alarm about the latter
proposal, saying that it jeopardized the security of the United
States. Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the senior Democrat on the
House Appropriations Committee, called it ``the most egregious and
reckless of the recommendations,'' but an amendment he offered that
nullified this and three other cuts in the Republican bill was
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $956 million in hurricane relief, the House bill
includes $100 million in economic and military assistance to Jordan
and nearly $106 million to support loan guarantees to farmers.
Several Democrats, including Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
complained that the aid to farmers was too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill did not include one item that senators added to
their version, a provision that would allocate $40 million to
families of the victims of last year's accident in which a Marine
jet sliced the cable of a ski gondola in Aviano, Italy, and killed
20.
</P>
<P>
   When the time for voting on the House bill had initially
expired, it did not have enough votes to pass. But the time was
then extended, and in the next few hectic minutes, enough lawmakers
voted or changed their votes to tilt the tally.
</P>
</TEXT>
