<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AOL Plans To Slash Workforce
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
America Online Inc. said yesterday it will lay off up to 1,000
people in the wake of its $10 billion acquisition of Netscape
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The online giant announced yesterday it is cutting between 350
to 500 jobs from Netscape's workforce of 2,500 employees and a
similar number from its own 9,500-person staff. In addition, AOL is
reorganizing its operations and will take an undisclosed
third-quarter charge to cover restructuring costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at this as a companywide reorganization _ not about
grafting Netscape on and then gutting it,'' said Barry Schuler, AOL
executive in charge of the Netscape transition. ``It was important
to streamline all of our operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Netscape layoffs will come from its Mountain View
headquarters. Overlapping administrative and marketing positions
will be hit hardest, leaving largely unscathed Netscape's coveted
core of 550 software developers and managers. Details of severance
packages were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus (in cuts) was on administration,'' Schuler said.
``We wanted to keep our engineering talent.''
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to employees, AOL CEO Steve Case and AOL Chief
Operating Officer Bob Pittman said, ``We are creating a new
organization that will bring together the best of our cultures and
maximize the strengths of each company.''
</P>
<P>
   While briefly acknowledging the ``painful'' process of layoffs,
the message concludes: ``Together, we can make history building a
new medium we can all be proud of and a company that we hope will
become the most valuable and respected anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   However, AOL officials privately expressed concerns that job
cuts will damage employee morale and spur defections of more
Netscape software designers. In fact, a number of former employees,
dubbed Net-escapees, are already leading Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs, which take place over the next few weeks, were
announced yesterday morning during a 90-minute ``all-hands''
meeting in a huge tent erected in the Netscape parking lot. More
than 2,000 people packed into the tent, eager to learn their fate
after reports surfaced last Thursday that up to 700 people would
lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   On hand to address the crowd under overcast skies were former
Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale, Sun Microsystems Chief Operating
Officer Ed Zander, Pittman and Schuler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The reaction was very upbeat considering it was not-so-good
news,'' said Schuler, who will run Netscape out of Mountain View
the next few months before commuting from AOL's headquarters in
Dulles, Va. ``Clearly, employees wanted us to be direct.''
</P>
<P>
   The only hint of tension came when one employee asked if
Netscape's signs would be replaced by AOL's triangular logo. AOL
officials said no.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  One Netscape employee who attended the meeting said he
``appreciated the fact that management was straight up'' about the
cuts. ``Two large companies merged; layoffs are a consequence of
that action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape employees have been bracing for layoffs since AOL
announced its intention to buy Netscape last November.
</P>
<P>
   The two Internet behemoths completed their merger last week. AOL
is the world's largest online service. Netscape created the first
widely used Web browser for retrieving information off the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; AOL's acquisition of Netscape is steeped in irony.
</P>
<P>
   Derided for years by the digital elite as the ``McDonalds'' of
cyberspace, AOL has survived self-inflicted wounds and stiff
competition to establish itself as the leading brand.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, conversely, was a darling of the digerati because of
its freewheeling personality and leading-edge technology. But it
was badly damaged by Microsoft in a brutal marketing war and was
forced to find a buyer to bail it out of financial straits.
</P>
<P>
   However, AOL intends to continue highlighting Microsoft's
Internet Explorer browser as part of its online service. In
exchange, Microsoft has agreed to give AOL a prominent link on the
Windows operating system, which runs 90 percent of the world's
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's telling that the company perceived to be the Internet
brand has been consumed and digested by a company that many at one
time had written off,'' said analyst Ron Rappaport, of Zona
Research Inc. in Redwood City. ``In the future, many will look at
Netscape as a history lesson rather than as a browser company.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its restructuring, AOL will break into four product
groups:
</P>
<P>
   _Interactive Services, a division overseeing AOL, Netscape and
CompuServe, will be headed by Schuler.
</P>
<P>
   _Netscape Enterprise, an e-commerce and software development
venture with Sun, will be led by former Netscape executives Barry
Ariko and Steve Savignano.
</P>
<P>
   _International operations will continue to be run by veteran AOL
executive Jack Davies.
</P>
<P>
   _Interactive Properties, the division in charge of
instant-messaging and online content, will be headed by &UR;  &LR; another
AOL executive, Ted Leonsis.
</P>
<P>
   Many laid-off Netscape employees should be able to quickly find
new jobs. Some are expected to end up at Sun, which announced a new
e-commerce and corporate software division yesterday that will be
staffed in part by Netscape and Sun employees.
</P>
<P>
   The division is part of a complex three-way deal signed as part
of the AOL-Netscape merger. Sun is paying AOL $1.25 billion over
three years for rights to co-develop and sell software for the
online giant.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tolliver, currently president of the consumer and embedded
unit at Sun Microsystems, will be president and general manager of
strategic alliances between AOL and Sun.
</P>
<P>
   AOL stock fell $3.88 to $117.13 yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
