<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA Reveals Post-Merger Layoff Figures
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
BankAmerica Corp. laid off 1,800 employees in the final three
months of last year following the September 30 merger of San
Francisco's Bank of America and NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The information, contained in the annual financial report filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission this week, shows that
the combined bank is well on its way to meeting its target of
cutting 5,000 to 8,000 positions over two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, now headquartered in Charlotte, said the 1,800 cut
jobs were throughout the coast-to-coast franchise. It declined to
disclose whether employees of the old BofA got hit the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, bank sources say BankAmerica has added
more than 600 positions in North Carolina while shedding ``a few
hundred'' jobs in California. However, BankAmerica employees in
California outnumber those in North Carolina by more than a 3-to-1
ratio, or about 50,000 to 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bank reported that by the end of last year, it had spent
$483 million of the $1.325 billion reserve it set aside to cover
merger-related expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest chunk _ $740 million _ went to severance and other
employee-related costs. Of this amount, $253 million was used in
the fourth quarter to pay severance to the 1,800 laid-off employees
and to the more than 200 BofA executives who had employment
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The NationsBank-BofA deal triggered change-in-control provisions
of the employment contracts of 1,134 executives of the old BofA.
The combined bank offered jobs to 918, or 81 percent, of these
managers, and the vast majority agreed to stay. But some, including
many of BofA's top executives, joined the 216 who were not offered
jobs and cashed in their ``golden parachute'' severance packages.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,800 lost jobs represent about 1 percent of the bank's
total of 171,000. In addition to the anticipated 3,200 to 6,200
additional layoffs this year and next, BankAmerica expects to
eliminate another 10,000 positions over three to four years through
attrition and employees taking new jobs within the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The task of merging the two banks is far from complete. For
example, by the end of 1998, BankAmerica had spent only $7 million
of the $150 million it allocated to convert computer and other
systems, and spent only $106 million of the $300 it budgeted to get
out of certain businesses and contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the major conversions are not going to happen until
later this year and next year, in part to avoid Y2K problems,''
said Joseph Morford, a bank analyst with First Security Van Kasper.
However, he believes that ``the integration is proceeding on track,
and some cost savings should begin to emerge in the first-quarter
results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
