</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLORER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Microsoft Browser Laden With Features
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The latest version of the Internet Explorer Web browsing package is
quintessentially Microsoft. It's a huge program laden with features
and designed to beat its competition senseless.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Bill Gates and Co. are taking the same approach
with their browser that they've used to dominate the market for
word processors, spreadsheets, databases, presentation programs,
online encyclopedias _ basically the entire software industry.
</P>
<P>
   And it's working. Microsoft browsers _ including an earlier
version that comes with America Online, now control more than 40
percent of the market. Meanwhile, Netscape Communications, which
once owned 80 percent of the market, has fallen below 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With Internet Explorer 5, Microsoft continues its policy of
giving the software away over the Internet (something Netscape also
does). You can get IE 5 at &LR;  www.microsoft.com/ie. &LR;  It's available
for Windows computers but not yet for the Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   If the browser battle were a prize fight, the referee would stop
it and award Microsoft a victory by technical knockout. IE 5 has
just too many features that Netscape can't match with the current
version of Communicator _ especially when it comes to customizing
the program for individual tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Netscape, which is now owned by America Online, has
given up on the notion of beating Microsoft by competing
feature-for-feature and is now concentrating on developing
slimmed-down browsers that can be used in small computing devices
as well as PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy new stuff that gives Microsoft IE 5 an advantage over
Netscape Communicator 4.5 includes:
</P>
<P>
   _A customizable toolbar that lets you add and remove buttons for
various functions such as copy, paste and font size.
</P>
<P>
   _A Search Assistant that gives you the option of using multiple
search engines when looking for Web pages, mail and e-mail
addresses and maps.
</P>
<P>
   _Autosearch, a feature that lets you conduct a Web search simply
by typing a phrase or question in the Internet address bar and
hitting Enter.
</P>
<P>
   _An improved History bar that provides quick access to sites
you've previously visited and lets you arrange them in a number of
ways, including by date or by how often you visit them.
</P>
<P>
   _Error messages in plain English. Instead of an HTTP 404, you'll
get an explanation of reasons why a page can't be accessed and
suggestions for getting around the problem.
</P>
<P>
   _A Radio toolbar that lets you listen to and change
Internet-based radio programs while you browse.
</P>
<P>
   To Microsoft's credit, IE 5 doesn't commandeer your desktop like
the previous version did by modifying the look of Windows and
imposing an Internet channel bar on the screen. Those incursions
were not well received by those who have an ingrained suspicion of
Microsoft's motives.
</P>
<P>
   IE 5 isn't superior in every way. Netscape's browser has a few
unique talents of its own, including excellent one-on-one chat
software and the ability to display the current price of any stock
by simply typing ``quote'' and the stock symbol in the address
space and hitting Enter.
</P>
<P>
   Both Microsoft and Netscape claim their browsers are the
fastest, but real-life tests are inconclusive, and besides, a lot
of the performance of a browser depends on the speed of the
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Although IE 5 boasts more features than Communicator, it does
have one big drawback. Like most Microsoft programs and operating
systems, it's the biggest bully on the block. A standard install of
the package, which includes Outlook Express e-mail, takes up 55
megabytes on your hard disk.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Netscape's Communicator uses less than half that
much, and the company is developing a new browser-only program
called Gecko which  &LR; that will be less than 2 megs.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape wants to promote Gecko as an ideal browser for
Internet-only devices and other small computers that can't
accommodate a leviathan-like IE 5. The company also is
collaborating with Sun Microsystems, which bought Netscape's
software business, to develop a new kind of browser. Based on Sun's
Java programming language, it would work nicely with Java-enabled
appliances such as smart phones.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a very small browser on the market. Called
Opera, this software out of Norway takes up less than 2 megabytes
and works well on pre-Pentium computers. It does have a few
drawbacks, however. It doesn't support some of the latest Internet
technology, which means multimedia pages may lose some of their
zing. It doesn't have a complete e-mail system like you get with IE
and Communicator.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike its bigger rivals, it's sold, not given away. You
can download it at &LR;  www.operasoftware.com  &LR; and give it a try, but
if you decide to keep it, you'll have to pay $35.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Microsoft still rules the roost. The new IE 5 is a
worthy successor to IE 4 and a solid addition to any desktop. And,
hey, it's free. You can't beat that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
