<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Eyeing an All-In-One Printer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I've been thinking of getting an all-in-one machine that
serves as a printer, scanner, copier and fax. But two intelligent
friends of mine advise against it. They claim multifunction
machines don't perform as well as those dedicated to a single
function. What's your opinion?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  In most ways, your friends are right. All-in-one
office machines generally are pretty good printers, but in other
ways they fall short. Copies, for instance, are generated using the
printer, a process that can take a long time and may not give
results comparable to a stand-alone copy machine. Scanning also can
be a problem because the machines use a sheet-feed mechanism that
precludes scanning irregularly shaped pages and doesn't give the
precision control of a flat-bed scanner. And the fax component of a
multifunction machine usually is slower than a regular fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   The other issue with all-in-ones is reliability. With so much
going on inside the machine, the chances of a breakdown are greater
than for single-function devices. And a malfunction could reduce
your multifunction to a no-function.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of an all-in-one is that it takes up a lot less space
than four separate machines, and it also costs a lot less. In fact,
prices of multifunctions have never been lower. The Canon MultiPass
C5500, capable of printing, copying and scanning in color, has a
street price of under $400. And the Hewlett-Packard OfficeJet 710
color-everything is $499.
</P>
<P>
   Contact List Conversion
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am running Windows 98 and am unable to convert my ACT 4.0
contact list to Microsoft Outlook 98. When I try to import the ACT
contacts into Outlook I receive a fatal error message. What's the
problem, and is there a solution?
</P>
<P>
   A: A fatal error? Maybe one of your contacts dropped dead (just
kidding). It's hard to say what's causing the message, but Outlook
98 doesn't list ACT 4.0 as a program from which it can import data
directly. Don't despair, however, because there is a way around
this nasty little problem. You should be able to export your
contacts from ACT in a text-only file, which you can then import
into Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   To export from ACT, go to that program's File menu and choose
Data Exchange, then Export. An Export Wizard will appear that will
guide you through the process of creating a text file for
exporting. After you finish, open Outlook, go to the File menu and
choose Import and Export. This will display Outlook's Import and
Export Wizard, which will show how to import the contacts. By the
way, text files can be imported into most personal information
managers as well as spreadsheets and databases.
</P>
<P>
   Lasting Memory
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an HP Pavilion PC that came with a 16-megabyte SDRAM
memory chip. I want to replace that with a chip that holds 64 MB.
My question is, if you replace a memory chip, do you lose
everything in the memory? If so, is there any way to transfer it
from the old chip to the new one?
</P>
<P>
   A: Relax. You don't lose anything because there's nothing to
lose. The main memory chips in a PC only hold information when the
computer is turned on. When it's turned off, they're empty.
Incidentally, if your PC has more than one SDRAM slot, you can add
the new chip without removing the old one. That way, you'll have a
total of 80 megs of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia Notebooks
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am planning to buy a notebook computer to use in producing
multimedia presentations for real estate listings. I'd like to get
the fastest possible computer, but I'm finding that even though one
can buy a desktop PC with a 500 MHz Pentium III chip, the fastest
notebooks only come with 366 MHz Pentium IIs. When will notebooks
with Pentium IIIs be introduced, and do you think it's worth
waiting for them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Intel tells me that Pentium III-based notebooks should start
appearing in the second half of this year. But why wait? A 366 MHz
processor is plenty fast for your presentations. The real key to
your success will be the video system in your new notebook. It's
got to be fast enough to display multimedia images and full-motion
video smoothly. If I were buying a 366 Pentium II notebook I'd look
for one with a 3D-capable system from ATI or NeoMagic.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Don't settle for the frightfully small text that Windows by
default uses for icons, menus and other system elements. You can
change fonts and sizes easily in the Appearance section of the
Display Properties dialog box. To access it, right-click any empty
area of the desktop and choose Properties from the menu that
appears.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
