<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TELEVISION, A WAR WITH NO PICTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Critic's Notebook) 
(wg) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first images of the destruction done by NATO missiles did
not arrive until late afternoon, and they came prefaced with the
warning that they were from Serbian State Television. The American
commentators on cable who picked up these scenes could not verify
or identify the dramatic scenes of fiery buildings and rubbled
streets. But everyone seemed greatly relieved to have any images at
all.
</P>
<P>
   For much of Wednesday, after the Yugoslav authorities shut down
the facility that Western news organizations had used to transmit
their stories, viewers were tossed back to a pre-satellite era of
television. It was immensely frustrating for both reporters and
viewers: a televised war with no pictures.
</P>
<P>
   What the networks and cable channels called, with slight
variations, ``Crisis in Kosovo,'' had always been a story so
complicated it demanded primer-style features on the order of:
Where is Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing worse for television was a complicated foreign
story with no live action.
</P>
<P>
   When the networks broke into their regular programs just before
2 p.m. to announce that the attacks had begun, they were forced
into the same approach the cable channels had been using for hours.
Reporters in Belgrade and Pristina (the more dangerous of the two
cities, where journalists had been threatened the day before),
talked on the phone while the television screen showed a still
photograph of that correspondent alongside a map marked with his or
her location. The reporters made it clear they were inside
buildings, looking out and using their ears as much as their eyes
to gauge what was happening. ``From our vantage point,'' and ``as
far as we can tell'' became their cautious catchphrases.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Sadler, speaking on CNN from Pristina, reported hearing
``at least three heavy explosions in the last few minutes.'' He
explained that gathering information would be difficult because,
``We have limited access to going out on the streets.'' From
Belgrade, his colleague Christiane Amanpour reported ``two orange
flashes'' outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Though this was disorienting to viewers, so accustomed to
instant images, the reports were also harrowing because the
situation was obviously precarious. On CBS, Allen Pizzey was
reporting by phone from Pristina and saying, ``The lights have just
_ '' when he was cut off mid-sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden silence may have been more heart-stopping than
watching missiles land. ``Allen Pizzey, are you there?'' Dan Rather
asked. He wasn't. The problem turned out to be nothing worse than a
power failure, but it provided a jumpy moment that was
characteristic of the day's tone.
</P>
<P>
   CNN managed to send a brief live nightscope photo of missiles
landing, a shaky video image sent by satellite phone. The
pixillated image turned up on screen looking like a cubist
painting, of geometric shapes in various shades of green with round
balls of light dropping through it.
</P>
<P>
   Then two hours after the attacks had begun, an eternity in
television time, the Serbian images arrived. They were used
immediately, with various degrees of warning.
</P>
<P>
   The network evening news broadcasts used the images, too. The
CBS Evening News was most direct about the limitations on
reporters. Mark Phillips' phone report from Belgrade noted that one
target ``seemed to be the special state security headquarters.''
When Rather led into Pizzey's report he noted it was ``by phone and
with the limited pictures available from Yugoslav government
television.''
</P>
<P>
   On ABC's ``World News Tonight,'' James Wooten reported from
Belgrade by phone (though that wasn't mentioned). He then appeared
on camera and said the television transmission facility was shut
down, and the only way to get pictures out was by using the
official government facility. He didn't explain how his pictures
were being sent. (An ABC spokesperson explained Wooten had been
sending a story just when the facility was shut earlier in the day;
his was the last American report sent.)
</P>
<P>
   When the networks returned to carry President Clinton's address
in the evening, he was surrounded by symbols associating him with
the image of a fatherly leader: conspicuous behind him were flags,
a bust of Abraham Lincoln, a photo of his daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   But the president explained the Kosovo crisis in more lucid and
human terms than the military analysts had. Like them, he had maps.
Unlike them, he did not merely say that the Serbs had attacked the
ethnic Albanians; he said the Serbs had been ``shelling civilians
and torching their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, he took control of the language and the iconography of
the Kosovo crisis, using television more effectively than it had
been used all day.
</P>
</TEXT>
