<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MICHST25-COX     03-24 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHST25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spartans' fire getting its spark from Flint
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apparently, as soon as a child is born in Flint,
Mich., the obstetrician is replaced y the tattooist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Mayor Woodrow Stanley confirmed, newborns ``All get the
tattoo and a basketball along with the name tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint's good mayor, of course, was joking. Many of his
constituents wait all the way until puberty before getting their
address inked into their bodies. On Saturday, four of Flint's
finest will lead Michigan State to its first Final Four appearance
in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   They are recognizable in a couple of ways. They will be the ones
making or breaking the Spartans _ Mateen Cleaves, the point man;
Antonio Smith, the leading rebounder; Morris Peterson, the leading
scorer; and Charlie Bell, the starting off-guard. And they all bear
a ``Flint'' tattoo, having turned their biceps into a
chamber-of-commerce billboard.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from that hard-edged town 60 miles north of Detroit, it
is not enough to wear your allegiance on your sleeve. You must wear
it beneath your sleeve as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just our way of representing them,'' said Smith, the
senior forward most responsible for opening the pipeline from Flint
to East Lansing. When he committed to Michigan State, the others
fell in line and followed him. ``A lot of people helped us there,
and it's a way of being thankful for what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tattoo is letting people know we're from Flint and we're
proud of it,'' Cleaves said. ``A lot of people, all they know about
Flint is violence or the plants closing. We want people to know
that there are some positive things about Flint.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of other cities, Flint has its blights. It has ridden
the crests and troughs of the U.S. auto industry, starring in
Michael Moore's biting movie ``Roger &AMP; Me.'' Its streets are
dangerous, its gangs pervasive. As much as anyone among the Flint
Four, Cleaves has experienced the dark side of the place. He used
to wear the initials of a slain friend, a minor drug dealer killed
by police, on the back of his basketball shoes. He has been
confronted by a gun-waving group seeking someone to kill. A stray
bullet is still lodged in the wall of his mother's house, hidden by
a little spackle and paint.
</P>
<P>
   Lest their story gets bogged down in a recital of America's
urban ills, the mayor is quick to remind any audience, ``This is a
feel-good'' story for Flint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any city would be proud of the positive kind of attention we
are experiencing because of the `Flintstones,''' Stanley said. So
proud is this one that it is planning a city-wide celebration for
the fellas sometime in May.
</P>
<P>
   Folks have taken to the remarkable story of this many young men
coming from the same city of 140,000 who have lifted the Spartans
to their first Final Four since Magic Johnson was a sophomore.
Sparty, the overstuffed Michigan State mascot, has taken to wearing
a faux ``Flint'' tattoo on his terrycloth arm. The pep band
regularly plays ``The Flintstones'' theme song, with new lyrics
applied by students: ``Flintstones. We're the Flintstones. We're
the best ballplayers in his-tor-ee.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint has produced more than its share of notable athletes. The
city brought you Andre Rison. And Roy Marble, ever so briefly a
Hawk. When Bell set the city high school scoring record, he bumped
Glen Rice into second. Antonio Smith's brother, Fernando, is a
defensive lineman with the Jacksonville Jaguars, and cousin Tawana
McDonald is the starting center for the Georgia women's team, which
plays Duke on Friday in the women's Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Its athletic tradition is well known and heavily mined. ``I'm
trying to get (Spartans basketball coach) Tom Izzo voting
privileges.'' Stanley said. ``And to get him to start paying taxes.
He's here enough, looking at players.'' Mayor Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes a group of athletes that grew up together, competed
against each other and arose as one on a resurgent college program.
It has fostered pride in a place where that feeling is heavily
rationed. And bred a closeness that otherwise would be impossible.
The theme of unity runs all through this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a family within a family,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``See this woman _ she's my sister,'' Peterson's mother,
Valerie, shrieked in the aftermath of Michigan State's regional
final victory against Kentucky. She was embracing Frances Cleaves
at the time. The four mothers travel and room together on the road.
And, for the record, none of the Flintstones' moms are named Betty
or Wilma.
</P>
<P>
   Their children are to basketball what Flint is to the urban
landscape. They are not flashy; even the talented Cleaves is best
at getting others involved. They do the dirty work of defense and
rebounding without complaint. They persevere.
</P>
<P>
   Haughty, powerful Duke might well end the Michigan State run
come Saturday's semis. But the Blue Devils are on notice that Flint
is not impressed. ``The guys at Michigan State have a level of
resiliency similar to that of the people in the community,'' the
mayor said. ``We've been counted out before, and we're still
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke beats a lot of people before the game even starts,'' he
said. ``People give in to the Duke mystique. But if (the Blue
Devils) are waiting on a concession, they're not going to get it
here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Upon further review, coming from Flint might have some
advantages. Certainly, when it was time to burn birthplaces into
skin, four guys from a five-letter Michigan town were grateful they
didn't come from Bloomfield Hills or Sault Ste. Marie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
