r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOON-REVIEW-LADN     03-24 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SHINE IN `WALK ON THE MOON'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use  Friday, March 26 by  NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 STARS 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ Though slight, ``A Walk on the Moon'' is a nicely
detailed family drama disguised as an overheated sexual fling. It's
erotic enough, especially in that female-self-discovery way that
movies like to give meaning to sex with. But the film is much
better whenever people who are stuck with each other are forced to
exhibit mutual respect and understanding.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Directed by actor Tony Goldwyn, inspired by some of writer
Pamela Gray's childhood memories and produced by Dustin Hoffman's
company, this observant, straightforward film is also blessed with
excellent performances and a strong sense of setting.
</P>
<P>
   It's the summer of '69. Men _ as the title indicates _ are on
the moon for the first time. Woodstock's about to erupt a couple of
valleys over. But at Dr. Fogler's Bungalows in the Catskills,
working-class Jewish families from New York City are enjoying
summer vacations in the same way they have for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Kantrowitzes have set up house in one of the semi-rustic
cabins. Youthful Pearl (Diane Lane), her insistently pubescent
daughter Alison (Anna Paquin), her younger son Daniel (Bobby
Boriello) and her slightly psychic mother-in-law Lilian (Tovah
Feldshuh) stay in the woodsy encampment for weeks on end; Pearl's
husband Marty (Liev Schreiber), a TV repairman, tries to make it up
from the city on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl and Marty married in their teens when she got pregnant.
Both gave up pursuing dreams in order to raise their family. Now
Pearl feels like she's really missed out on something, especially
with this space exploration/sex/drugs/rock 'n' roll stuff going on
all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Blouse Man shows up. Dr. Fogler's isolated
lakeside resort is serviced by an assortment of traveling salesmen,
and the guy with the step van full of women's clothing just happens
to be a cute, soft-spoken, hippie-haired free spirit who looks like
Viggo Mortensen. He gently but insistently expresses his interest
in Pearl. With lots of time and not much Marty on her hands, she
lets her imagination wander into territory she's never dared think
about before.
</P>
<P>
   Full moon, rock festival ... you know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   From our sadder-but-wised-up vantage point of the '90s, Pearl's
fling is easy to judge as selfish and irresponsible. Indeed, she
has very little to say in her defense whenever somebody busts her
on it, which reinforces the perception that she just didn't think
things through very well. Yet Lane is such an empathetically
sensuous actress that she invests Pearl with an undeniable
emotional wisdom. This was something she needed to do, no simpler
or more complicated than that.
</P>
<P>
   And let's face it, it was the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the plot's main concern is with what the affair is
going to do to Pearl and the squarely upstanding (emphasis on the
square) Marty. And while some of the couple's encounters are
compelling, the really memorable moments are intergenerational,
between mothers, daughters and granddaughters. Feldshuh, Lane and
Paquin play three cussedly determined women, all defined very
differently by their ages and the times they lived through, yet all
equipped with marvelous depths of compassion and forgiveness for
one another.
</P>
<P>
   All you need is love, indeed. ``A Walk on the Moon''
acknowledges that the '60s mantra was a lot easier to chant than it
was to live. But without at least trying to, what's the point of
living?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
