<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS CRACK DOWN ON FOREIGN JOURNALISTS COVERING AIR ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV,
KOSOVO-STEALTH, KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(bl) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Serbian military authorities on Wednesday cracked down on
foreign journalists who were reporting news of the NATO air strikes
from Yugoslavia, shutting down all television transmission
complexes, threatening a CNN correspondent and his crew in Pristina
and detaining 20 reporters and technicians, including at least six
Americans, in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Milligan of The Boston Globe and William Glauber of The
Baltimore Sun were among those detained by the police on the roof
of a hotel in Belgrade, but were released Wednesday night,
according to their editors. Four CNN crew members were also rounded
up, some television equipment was confiscated, and at least one
local television employee was beaten by police.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, capital of Kosovo province, two American television
correspondents remained Wednesday, Allen Pizzey of CBS News and
Brent Sadler of CNN. Sadler said armed Serbian officials had
slashed the tires of his vehicle and had threatened him and his
crew by holding out two bullets and saying, ``These are for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Among American newspapers, The New York Times has a reporter in
Kosovo. The Washington Post, The Boston Globe, Knight-Ridder
newspapers and The Baltimore Sun do not. The Associated Press moved
some reporters out of Pristina, but continued to have a half-dozen
there, according to a spokeswoman, Tori Smith.
</P>
<P>
   After the satellite transmission complexes that belong to the
European Broadcasting Union and are used by all six major American
commercial networks were shut down in Belgrade, American television
reports were restricted to footage from the Serbian state network
and correspondents' telephoned reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs shut off all the satellites,'' said the vice
president for news at the Fox News Channel, John Moody. ``Why they
would want do that today is beyond me, because it's the only way
they'd get their side of the story out. But the Serbs are not known
for their PR skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after the bombing began, CNN managed to transmit what it
called ``nightscope'' pictures from Kosovo, using a technology that
allows video to be transmitted over a satellite telephone, but the
greenish, blurred pictures showed little.
</P>
<P>
   The three American broadcast networks and three cable news
networks all had correspondents in Belgrade and in Sokpje,
Macedonia, where refugees were fleeing. NBC News said it had moved
a correspondent, Ron Allen, from Pristina to Belgrade for safety
reasons. Earlier this week, Jim Wooten and Mike Lee of ABC News
also left Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Burns of CNN left Yugoslavia altogether, moving to
Skopje, after Serbian authorities had broadcast a photograph of him
on Yugoslav television with a report that called CNN ``a factory of
lies.'' CNN, unlike most other foreign networks, can be seen in
Yugoslavia on its international service.
</P>
<P>
   With no access to independent information about the air strikes,
many Serbian university students flocked to the most reliable news
source available, the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As bombs were exploding near the Belgrade airport, younger Serbs
spent hours on line Wednesday scrolling through Internet-based news
groups and the Web sites of American news media. Late into the
night, many Belgrade University students spent hours holed up in
their homes connecting to friends abroad through e-mail, as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
