<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GROWING IMPORTANCE OF INTERACTIVE OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sign of the growing importance of operations
outside the realm of traditional advertising, three giant agency
companies are expanding in interactive marketing and media
services.
</P>
<P>
   Two, Interpublic Group of Cos. in New York and Grey Advertising
in New York, are adding to their interactive operations with an
alliance and an acquisition. The third, Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago,
is proceeding with the uniting of virtually all its global media
operations at a stand-alone agency, Starcom Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic, the world's No. 3 agency company with estimated
billings of $30 billion, is hooking up with Icon Medialab
International AB in Stockholm, Sweden, the largest independent
Internet services and consulting company in Europe. The alliance,
subject to approval by Icon shareholders at a meeting on April 27,
includes a $20 million investment by Interpublic in exchange for an
initial equity stake in Icon of just under 20 percent. That would
be one of the biggest single investments ever made in cyberspace by
an agency company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for ways to bring more resources to bear on
behalf of clients to craft broad business strategies,'' said Barry
Linsky, senior vice president for planning and development at
Interpublic. ``This is an alignment with the hope of benefits both
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal also ``reflects our continued commitment in and
optimism about the importance of this Internet and e-business area
going forward,'' he added. ``We've been active in this going back
to our initial investment in CKS.'' He was referring to a stake
that Interpublic took in 1995 in the company now known as USWeb/CKS
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic has ``become increasingly enamored of alliances of
this sort,'' said Linsky, citing other investments in Internet
specialty agencies like Nicholson New York and Zentropy in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic's investment in Icon, the world's No. 18 interactive
agency according to the trade weekly Adweek's IQ Interactive
Report, would make Interpublic the largest shareholder in Icon, and
Interpublic has a right to increase its stake. Icon was the only
overseas-based agency on the IQ list of the top 50 interactive
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Icon has more than 400 employees at offices in Sweden and nine
other countries, including the United States. It handles accounts
with estimated revenue of $16 million from clients including
Amnesty International, Compaq Computer, Netscape Communications,
Charles Schwab, the Swedish Post Office and Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance will make Icon a so-called preferred provider of
interactive services to Interpublic agencies. The first tangible
results of the agreement will come in Norway, where the Icon
operations, recently bolstered by acquisitions, will be merged with
Thunder House, the interactive division of Interpublic's JBR-McCann
unit in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   News of the alliance sent Icon shares climbing almost 5 percent
Wednesday in Stockholm, where they closed at $22.96. Interpublic
shares rose $2.3125 on the New York Stock Exchange to close at
$72.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The Interpublic interactive alliances are in addition to
Internet operations at the worldwide agencies owned by Interpublic,
including Ammirati Puris Lintas and McCann-Erickson World Group.
One, however, is being rocked by defections of top personnel.
</P>
<P>
   APL Digital, the interactive division of Ammirati Puris in New
York, has lost six senior employees just days after the departure
of Brian Cauley, who had been president since the division was
formed in July. Cauley, 39, attributed his resignation to what he
described as differences with top agency managers over the
direction APL Digital should take.
</P>
<P>
   The other executives handed in their resignations on Monday, 10
days after Cauley's departure. They included Mark Avnet, 43,
production and technology director, and Lynn Bolger, 45, media
director, who had been named to head APL Digital on an interim
basis while a successor to Cauley was sought. Also resigning were:
Grant Collier and Evan Lewis, creative directors; Vicky Evans,
executive producer, and Dawn Winchester, vice president and
management supervisor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday if they were joining him in a new interactive
agency venture, Cauley replied that it was ``a good bet.'' Mike
Cargill, a spokesman for Ammirati Puris, said that the agency was
``committed to the digital business,'' adding that ``searches are
under way'' for replacement personnel. APL Digital's clients
include Iridium, Lego Systems and the United Parcel Service of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the other Internet expansion, the Grey Interactive
unit of Grey, the world's No. 9 agency company with estimated
billings of $7.9 billion, acquired majority ownership of Module
Communications Ltd. in London, which specializes in
business-to-business new-media accounts. Financial terms were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Orin Wechsberg, managing director at Grey Interactive, the
fourth-largest Internet agency on the IQ list, said that Grey
Interactive planned to acquire the rest of Module in the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive advertising is a combination of ``global strategy
and local execution,'' Wechsberg said. ``You want to plant a stake
in the ground in countries where you have your clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Module will become the third division of Grey Interactive
Services Ltd. in London. The others are Grey Interactive UK and
Grey Interactive TV. Grey Interactive Services will have combined
billings estimated at more than $12 million, out of the Grey
Interactive total of more than $50 million. Clients include
Autobytel.com, Guinness, Procter &AMP; Gamble, Reebok and Shell.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Marks, 33, chairman at Module, will be chairman at Grey
Interactive Services, and Brian Lee, 33, managing director at Grey
Interactive UK, will be chief executive at Grey Interactive
Services.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on the media services front, Burnett, the world's No.
13 agency company with estimated billings of $6.6 billion, is
joining competitors like Grey, Interpublic and Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.
by consolidating planning and buying operations for television,
radio, print, outdoor, Internet and other media at an autonomous
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of Starcom, expected to be completed by July 31,
comes after Burnett has operated stand-alone media agencies under
the Starcom banner in Australia, Mexico, Thailand and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll admit we're not the first at this,'' said Jack Klues,
44, executive vice president and worldwide media director at
Burnett, who becomes chief executive at Starcom. ``But we're very
confident we'll be highly competitive and ultimately be the best at
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of Starcom as a separate entity was something we
started talking about in fall 1997,'' he added, but it was put
aside to pursue talks with MacManus Group in New York about
combining media operations. When those negotiations ended abruptly
in November, Burnett resumed plans for forming Starcom.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 8,500 Burnett employees worldwide, 1,500 in about 75
countries will become Starcom staff members, said Bob Brennan, 40,
U.S. media director at Burnett, who becomes chief operating officer
at Starcom.
</P>
<P>
   Starcom will handle media services for accounts with billings
estimated at $7.3 billion; the goal is to reach $10 billion in two
years, Brennan said. Current clients include Canon, Coca-Cola,
Kellogg, McDonald's, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Procter &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Starcom will operate alongside _ and sometimes
compete against _ Motive, the media services unit of Bartle Bogle
Hegarty in London, the creative shop in which Burnett holds a 49
percent stake. Motive will operate as an independent brand; Mark
Cramner, chief executive, will be one of eight members of the
Starcom board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
