</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, ALBANIANS REJOICE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV, KOSOVO-STEALTH, KOSOVO-MEDIA,
KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(wg) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All Wednesday morning, Albanian men crowded into
their Bronx clubhouse, chain-smoking and grimly focusing on CNN.
When President Clinton appeared on television to announce that the
NATO bombing of Serbia had begun, they were utterly silent,
seemingly too tense to allow themselves to exhale.
</P>
<P>
   ``They listened to every word,'' said Isuf Hajrizi, editor of
Illyria, the Albanian-American newspaper. ``When he finished, there
was an outburst. They were shaking each other's hands. They were
throwing cigarettes to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Perlleshi, in nearby Pelham Parkway, had been watching the
president with five or six friends in his real-estate office. When
the bombing was announced, he ran onto the street and began
joyously buttonholing Albanian passersby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `We start bombing!''' he said. ``This makes all
Albanians very very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the New York metropolitan area, Albanians _ recent
immigrants and longtime U.S. residents, mostly from Kosovo _
rejoiced. But their joy and relief is mixed with fear for their
relatives and American servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to explain to the rest of the world,'' said Dervish
Ukehaxhaj, a manager of a Belmont bakery, who had a brother and
cousins killed. Referring to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
he added: ``Negotiations is a big joke to him. He massacres women
and children. Now it is time to punish him.''
</P>
<P>
   Subduing Milosevic and his army is crucial to prevent
hostilities from spreading throughout Europe, said Joseph
DioGuardia, a former congressman who now lobbies in Washinghton for
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. ``We are right in the nick of time _ I
hope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Milosevic revoked the autonomy of Kosovo in 1989,
expatriates in Europe and America have supported their countrymen.
but in the last year, as the violence flared, donations have
skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian immigrants in New York have been behaving like people
in mourning. The parties and big weddings with traditional music
and dancing have been canceled. There were traditional wakes to
mourn slain relatives every weekend throughout the summer and fall
at various Albanian clubhouses _ so many that finally even they
were stopped.
</P>
<P>
   When there is peace, there is time to grieve for the dead
properly, said Ismer Mjeku, 38, who started a small business in the
Bronx. But in war there are too many deaths to mourn individually.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, Mjeku was among the men in the Belmont
clubhouse focused on the television. ``I hoped,'' he said. ``But
actually it was only hope. I did not believe it. There has been so
much talk but no action. We needed to see action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he continued, ``it is a reality. We can breathe now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hajrizi, the editor, said he had steeled himself for
disappointment. ``There has been so much suffering and complaining
and horror and pain in this community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now in a way, it's wonderful,'' he said. On Wednesday
afternoon, he warned a freelance journalist in Kosovo to be
careful. ``Let them hit us,'' he said, repeating the words of the
journalist. ```If we're killed by friendly NATO fire, at least
we'll die happy.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
