<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS BLOWS PAST SCHETT TO MAKE SEMIFINALS OF LIPTON
CHAMPIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Alternately buffeted and bolstered by a
capricious summer breeze on the stadium court Wednesday, top-seeded
Martina Hingis hit her way into the semifinals of the Lipton
Championships with a brisk 6-1, 6-1 dissection of Barbara Schett of
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   While the 20th-ranked Schett, who reached the quarterfinals by
ousting last year's runner-up, Anna Kournikova, did more missing
than hitting in the shifting conditions, Hingis coped like a
chameleon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel from one side like a weight lifter, and from the
other, so easy and loose,'' Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, a Swiss teen-ager, used a canny combination of sharply
angled ground strokes and intermittent net rushes to make short
work of Schett. The Lipton's champion in 1997, Hingis was doubly
ambushed here last year by the Williams sisters.
</P>
<P>
   After being worn to a frazzle and needing to save match points
against Serena Williams in the quarterfinals, she was pummeled by
Venus Williams in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Hingis said she would relish the opportunity to test
herself in the semifinals against Serena Williams, who rode a
tour-best 14-match unbeaten streak into her quarterfinal Wednesday
night against Amanda Coetzer of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has won both previous matches against Serena, the younger
Williams sister. But both confrontations happened before Williams
commenced the current tear that has brought her back-to-back
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't fear anyone; I fear God only,'' Serena Williams
said of the prospect of a semifinal against the top-ranked Hingis
and a final against her own sister.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Schett said she didn't fear Hingis either. And she
lived to regret her impertinence. Schett's misplaced confidence
came from a match in Sydney, Australia, in January when she nearly
upended Hingis. But Wednesday afternoon, Hingis allowed her only
two games in 43 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the problem: I really stepped out on the court and
thought I'm going to beat her,'' Schett said. ``I'll never do that
again, I think, to go out on the court and be sure that I'll beat
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 6-0 against Schett, Hingis took a more respectful approach.
``I took her much more serious than I did in Sydney,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The decidedly one-sided quarterfinal was hustled along by
Schett's six double faults and six dropped service games. ``She
didn't have to do too much today; I think I missed a lot of
shots,'' said Schett, reflecting on 30 unforced errors.
``Especially my serve was really bad, and without a serve, you
can't beat the No. 1, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's draw, 74th-ranked Sebastien Grosjean of France not
only beat the top-seeded player, Carlos Moya of Spain, in the
fourth round, but also cost Moya his new No. 1 ranking. Wednesday,
Grosjean, at 20 the youngest and lowest-ranked player left in the
star-deprived men's field, advanced to his first Lipton semifinal
and first semifinal of 1999 with another, though milder, upset.
</P>
<P>
   After blowing two match points in the 10th game of the second
set, Grosjean dismissed 40th-ranked Dominik Hrbaty, 6-3, 5-7, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Frenchman faces the winner of Wednesday night's quarterfinal
between 22nd-ranked Francisco Clavet of Spain and 30th-ranked
Nicolas Kiefer of Germany. In Thursday's other semifinal,
seventh-seeded Richard Krajicek, who drilled Pete Sampras into a
premature exit, will face 14th-seeded Thomas Enqvist of Sweden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2143EST &QL; 
