<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MICROSOFT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MAKES PROPOSAL TO SETTLE ANTITRUST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  (This is now a New York Times A1 story.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. made an opening step toward trying to settle its
antitrust battle with the government in a four-page proposal sent
to the Justice Department on Monday, lawyers close to the case said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, described as a ``framework'' by one person close
to the case, suggests easing Microsoft contract restrictions on
personal computer makers, Internet service providers and others in
the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   These restrictions _ some of which Microsoft has already
loosened under pressure from the industry and the government _
limit manufacturers somewhat in what appears on the first desktop
screen when users turn on their machines or restrict Internet
service providers in the distribution of competing browser
software.
</P>
<P>
   But the Microsoft proposal, according to people who have seen
the document, does not mention any of the broader remedies to
curbing the big software maker's market power that the company's
critics insist are necessary to restore competition in the
industry. Those suggested remedies have included breaking up
Microsoft into separate companies or forcing it to license the
programming code for its industry-standard Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Microsoft nor the Justice Department would comment on
the Microsoft proposal. But Microsoft is likely to contend that it
represents a serious overture that could fundamentally alter its
relationship with personal computer makers, who are the key
distributors of Microsoft software.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal apparently falls well short of the expectations of
both the Justice Department and the 19 states suing Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The California attorney general, Bill Lockyer, called the
Microsoft proposal ``a minimalist opening offer that is far from
what anyone in our group would expect to be adequate,'' adding,
``It was a very small offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust suit accuses Microsoft of repeatedly
using its monopoly in the operating system market to stifle
competition and innovation. During the trial, which began last
October and recessed for a lengthy break in February, the
government alleged that Microsoft thwarted competition by, among
other things, restrictive contracts, giving favored pricing deals
to manufacturers who favor Microsoft software and rewarding them
with marketing funds.
</P>
<P>
   The remedies in any settlement, the government says, must insure
greater openness, or ``transparency,'' and be enforceable. That is
why Microsoft pricing pacts with personal computer makers and its
marketing development agreements have been a focus of the trial,
and why forcing Microsoft to publish its price lists and open up
its marketing contracts to scrutiny have been among the remedies
they have sought.
</P>
<P>
   In its document, Microsoft has not offered to publish price
lists or open its marketing agreements to third-party monitoring,
said a person who has seen the Microsoft proposal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Wednesday, Bill Gates, the chairman of Microsoft,
said he was eager to settle his company's antitrust case, but he
also heaped scorn on the government's suit.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comments on the prospect of a settlement,
Gates said, ``We'd like nothing more than to have this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gates then quickly reiterated Microsoft's long-held position
that the government suit seeks to hobble his company's freedom to
innovate _ signaling that he is enthusiastic about a settlement,
only if it can be done on Microsoft's terms.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is engaged in ``ongoing discussions'' with the Justice
Department and the 19 states suing the big software maker, Gates
said. Yet despite the Microsoft proposal, lawyers involved in the
case say, the two sides have not begun negotiations, though they
are expected to talk soon.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are expected to be briefed on Microsoft's offer
in Washington Thursday by the Iowa attorney general, Thomas Miller,
who received the proposal along with the Justice Department. Miller
held a conference call on Tuesday to read the Microsoft proposal to
the 18 other attorneys general involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   When the antitrust trial broke for a lengthy recess on Feb. 26,
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson called both sides into his quarters
and urged them to see if they could find some common ground. Since
then, the issue of whether Microsoft and the government would talk
about settling the case has not been in doubt. To ignore the
judge's advice, legal experts say, would risk antagonizing the
court.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is whether Microsoft and the government will
pursue substantive settlement negotiations, given how far apart the
two sides seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general in charge of the
Justice Department's antitrust division, suggested on Monday that
Microsoft would have to make significant concessions for him to
approve a settlement. ``The Justice Department,'' he said, ``has
always been and remains open to a settlement that fully protects
consumers and assures that similar antitrust violations do not
occur in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates made his comments about settlement talks during an
interview conducted by Sir David Frost before an audience at an
investor conference. Gates said the key principles for Microsoft
were its ``right to innovate'' by adding anything it wants to into
its Windows operating system. ``As long as we can keep those
intact, we'd like to settle this thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials remain skeptical of Gates and his
company's opening salvo in the settlement process. The Microsoft
proposal, they say, contains scant sign of genuine movement on the
company's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what they've given us,'' one official said,
``Microsoft still seems to have a very different sense of this case
than we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
