<SLUG> BC-COACH-GUN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man who pointed pistol at coach given high bail
 &HT;    By A. Scharnhorst
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A North Palm Beach attorney accused of
pointing a gun at a Little League coach remained in jail after a
court hearing Wednesday to establish his bail.
</P>
<P>
   John Skrandel was arrested Sunday on charges that he attacked
the coach in an argument over the use of a batting cage at Osborne
Park. The coach, Mike Adams, told police he asked Skrandel to move
to another batting cage so his Little League team could use a
larger one. Skrandel refused, court records say, and attacked Adams
with a baseball bat. Adams fended off the blow and stripped the bat
from Skrandel's hands, so Skrandel grabbed a Glock 40 handgun from
a duffel bag and held the gun to Adams' face for about five
minutes, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A county judge Monday ordered Skrandel held without bail until
he could undergo psychiatric evaluation. Wednesday, Judge Paul O.
Moyle reviewed and sealed the evaluation and heard arguments from
attorneys before setting Skrandel's bail at $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The aggravated assault charge Skrandel faces generally carries a
bail of $3,000, Moyle said. Assistant State Attorney Rick Penalta
successfully argued for a higher bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts themselves warrant that he's a danger to the
community,'' Penalta said.
</P>
<P>
   Skrandel is represented by the public defender's office because
he proved that he could not afford his own lawyer, Moyle said.
Skrandel, 28, has been a lawyer for about two years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
