<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bahamian officials dismiss rumors of another sunken ship of
refugees
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Radio waves crackled again Wednesday
with gruesome news from Haiti: A sailboat loaded with hundreds of
refugees had sunk last week, casting its human cargo into Bahamian
waters.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, relief followed as Bahamian officials denied the
initial report.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahamians confirmed they rescued 119 people from a sailboat
Saturday, but said none was injured and no passengers were missing.
The boat was discovered beached on Castle Island on the southern
tip of the Acklins, not drifting in open seas, they said.
</P>
<P>
   If another boat had gone down, carrying 300 as reported by a
radio station on Haiti's north coast, surely some evidence _
debris, clothes, a body _ would have washed ashore, Bahamian
officials speculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have it mixed up,'' said Samuel Moss, head of
enforcement for the Bahamas Department of Immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Etincelle reported Wednesday that a 40-foot boat set sail
from Port-de-Paix and went down Saturday when it began taking on
water. The station said a survivor claimed that panicked passengers
jumped overboard and eventually two passing Bahamian boats rescued
100 off Cat Island, just south of Eleuthera, and returned them to
Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   But Haitian and Bahamian officials doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Island, fenced on the east by a chain of small cays and
Exuma Sound, is far from the usual refugee route, Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   The 119 refugees discovered Saturday were also aboard a 40-foot
wooden sloop. Defense forces discovered it after receiving a tip
from the U.S. Coast Guard office in Nassau, and turned its
passengers over to immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, as was reported to us, there were no
casualties,'' said Sub-Lt. Darrin Hensfield. ``We have no knowledge
of the other incident.''
</P>
<P>
   When word reached the United States, Daniella Henry, director of
the Haitian Community Center in Delray Beach, called the Haitian
Consul in Miami to verify the report. Lesly Jacques, station
manager for Radio Haiti Amerique Internationale, tried contacting
sources in Port-Au-Prince. Neither was able to confirm the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus far, it's rumors,'' said Jean-Gabriel Augustin, Haiti's
consul in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the report _ coupled with a March 6 rescue of three men
30 miles off Palm Beach that remains clouded by contradictions _
shows the difficulty in pinning down information about people
fleeing in secrecy, on uncharted courses across hundreds of miles
of open water. While U.S. Border Patrol and Bahamian immigration
officials can estimate the number they catch, no one is able to say
how many slip through or perish trying. The Associated Press
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
