<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3123 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NTSB-CRASH-SPI &LR;      03-24 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NTSB-CRASH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NTSB: RUDDER SYSTEM, NOT PILOT ERROR, CAUSED 737 CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON AND ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Va. _ Rejecting Boeing's claims of pilot error, the
National Transportation Safety Board Wednesday blamed the rudder
system of the Boeing 737 for the Sept. 8, 1994, crash near
Pittsburgh that killed 132 people.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted 4-0 that the probable cause of the crash was a
stuck valve that caused the rudder of the Renton, Wash.-built plane
to turn in a direction opposite that commanded by the pilot,
rolling the jetliner over and slamming it into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the board also pointed to a rudder reversal as the
probable cause of the crash of United Flight Flight 585 in 1991.
That Boeing 737 rolled over and dived into the ground while on its
final approach to the Colorado Springs airport. All 25 people on
board the jet were killed. The safety board had ruled in 1992 that
there was insufficient evidence to determine if a rudder
malfunction caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Though it blamed the Boeing jet for both crashes, the safety
board accepted Boeing's contention that improvements already under
way on most of the older 737s still flying, or the new design in
the latest generation of the world's most popular commercial jet,
would prevent a repeat of the ``rudder reversal'' problem that
caused the Pittsburgh crash.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the board asked the company and the Federal Aviation
Administration for further design review of the rudder system,
saying it could malfunction in other ways that might jeopardize the
flying public.
</P>
<P>
   The board recommended that the FAA order 10 safety changes, and
study more modifications than those that have already begun on the
737 rudder system, as well as immediate improvements to pilot
training and flight data recorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of improvements that have been made to the
rudder system that are in the process now of being installed on the
737 fleet, both in this country and worldwide, and I think those
are obviously important improvements and will provide a safer
system,'' said NTSB Chairman Jim Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, (because of) the long history of the type of flight
control problems with the rudder ... the government, and Boeing as
well, owe it to the flying public to take a comprehensive look
again to satisfy themselves that this system is entirely safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials until Wednesday had tried to blame the USAir
crash on pilot error. But after the close of the hearing, a Boeing
vice president said the company accepted the NTSB's finding that
the crash was likely caused by a mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-year history of the Boeing 737, there are five
recorded cases in which planes have experienced rudder reversal,
according to the NTSB. Board investigators blamed rudder reversal
for the United and USAir crashes, as well as a non-fatal incident
involving Eastwind Flight 517 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The rudder reversal phenomenon also is suspected in two other
incidents, the board said. In 1992, a United Airlines pilot
performing a preflight control check on a 737 in Chicago found the
rudder pedal jammed and returned the plane to the gate. And the
NTSB suspects rudder reversal may have caused the 1994 crash of a
Sahara India 737 in New Delhi, in which eight people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the safety agencies believe further rudder reversals
will be prevented by a change in the hydraulic valve system that
controls the rudder. As of March 1, that change had been made in
484 of the 1,025 older-model 737s flying in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have completely eliminated any possibility of a reversal,''
said Charles Higgins, Boeing vice president of airplane safety and
airworthiness. ``There is no mode that we're aware of today that
could possibly lead the rudder to reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said Boeing would now ``do everything we can to look at
the 737 rudder system and see if there's any additional improvement
that can be made.'' He said Boeing would cooperate with a new
government investigation of the rudder, and he said Boeing accepts
the safety board's recommendations and findings.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board did not call for specific changes to the design
of the trouble-plagued rudder system, instead opting to call for
the creation of a new board to study potential failures of the
rudder.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board urged the FAA to ``require that all existing
and future 737s have a reliably redundant rudder actuation
system,'' and noted pointedly that it believes, contrary to the
position of Boeing and the FAA, that the current rudder system ``is
not reliably redundant.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the NTSB wants Boeing's 737 fleet to contain a
backup method for pilots to control the rudder should the power
control unit fail. Boeing and the FAA have insisted that the
current system includes backups and have resisted a costly redesign
of the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   A top FAA official was noncommittal about whether the agency
will follow the NTSB's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   FAA Associate Administrator Thomas McSweeny said ``reliably
redundant'' needs further definition. Backup systems already are
included in Boeing's redesigned rudder control system, he said, and
pilots have the option of switching to a standby rudder should the
primary control fail.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, McSweeny said, the FAA needs more data on the
rudder problem before ordering a fix. The agency recently
established a review board to take another look at the Boeing 737.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA now has to sit down with the National Transportation
Safety Board and determine ``what data, what evidence do they have
that says more changes have to be made,'' McSweeny said. ``Without
the data telling you where you're going, you won't know if you ever
got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rudder concerns, the safety board, the FAA and
Boeing all insisted that they believe the 737 is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This airplane has a long and enviable and admirable record,
both of reliability and safety,'' said safety board member George
Black Jr. ``I fly on them, my family flies on them, and I don't
have any hesitancy in that. ... We've been focusing on failures
here, (but) there's an awful lot of successful flights out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other key recommendations by the NTSB to the FAA:
</P>
<P>
   _ Improve training to ensure that pilots practice how to regain
control of an airplane if the rudder jams.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require that certain plane maneuvers be conducted at higher
speeds to prevent a rare situation in which, at low speeds, pilots
can't use the wheel to control the plane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Install better flight data recorder systems on all 737s to
provide more kinds of information and more frequent information
that would help investigators understand not only what goes wrong
during crashes, but how airplanes respond to normal conditions.
Among the data recorded by the new devices would be information
about how pilots use rudder pedals.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the crash victims praised both the NTSB findings
and its recommendations. They broke into applause when the board
called for more sophisticated flight data recorders that would make
it easier for investigators to determine crash causes, and spare
others years of emotional turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hanley, 35, of Chesapeake, Va., wept after the board
announced its finding. Hanley, whose wife, Sarah, was a USAir
flight attendant, embraced Ernest Germano, brother of the pilot of
USAir Flight 427.
</P>
<P>
   Germano said the findings, which rejected pilot error as a
cause, vindicated his brother, Peter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to us,'' said Germano, 47, of Elmira, N.Y. ``We
knew all along how he trained himself, how he prepared himself. We
knew he ... was doing the job that needed to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanley said the safety board and its investigators had done
their job, too, although he expressed skepticism at whether the FAA
would follow the safety board's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley also spoke bitterly of Boeing and its refusal to accept
blame for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope their stock goes down,'' he said. ``I hope it drops as
fast as (USAir) 427.'' (It closed up 3/16 at 34 5/16 Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   The pilots' union also praised the safety board's actions. Capt.
John Cox, president of the Air Line Pilots Association, said the
investigation was an example ``of the system as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the board's right on track,'' he said. ``We're able
to fly the plane safely today, and in the future there's design
improvements that can be made, and should be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox stressed that pilots believe in the underlying safety of the
737, the most widely used commercial plane in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew (737s) for 15 years,'' Cox said. ``I flew in here on a
737 and I'm going to fly out of here on a 737. I have absolute
confidence in the safety of the airplane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
