<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH25-COX     03-24 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush hopes brisk campaign fund-raising will be enough to skip
taxpayer funds
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush, charting a White House course
nobody has successfully navigated, is trying to amass a campaign
war chest large enough to let him forgo taxpayer funds _ and
spending limits _ in his bid for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Since the public financing system began in 1976, standard
operating procedure for major presidential candidates has been to
take the matching money and run.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's strategy, dependent on being able to raise money at a
brisk pace, is sparked largely by Steve Forbes, the only major
contender in recent years to eschew the government matching funds
while seeking nomination. But Forbes, a billionaire businessman,
did it by digging into his own deep pockets in 1996, not by raising
the money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush _ wealthy, but not in Forbes' league _ will try to raise
the more than $45 million in campaign contributions it would take
to be able to skip the federal funds. Forbes again will skip the
government money next year and not have to abide by the spending
limits.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of facing an aggressive, well-funded opponent
unrestrained by spending limits concerns the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and his team, for fear of setting goals that could
prove tough to hit, do not talk publicly about a fund-raising
target. But it is discussed in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a goal that we are all actively working toward,''
Connecticut GOP Chairman Chris DePino, who met with Bush last month
and is now raising money for the presidential campaign, said of the
effort to avoid federal funds. ``He talked about the restraints of
taking federal money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to sit back like Bob Dole unfortunately had
to do and watch Al Gore and the spinmasters decimate our
candidate,'' DePino said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, philosophically opposed to public financing of political
campaigns and rich enough to put his money where his philosophy is,
ran on his own dimes, $37 million worth of them in 1996. By doing
so, he avoided the strings that come with the federal money,
including state-by-state and overall spending limits that can
hamstring a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who raised $31.2 million for the 1996 primaries, ran into
a fiscal brick wall in the months after he clinched the GOP
presidential nomination. He was tapped out after being forced to
reply to Forbes' high-dollar, aggressive ad campaigns in Iowa and
New Hampshire. In Iowa, Forbes spent nearly $10 million.
Republicans in the field who took federal money were limited to
about 10 percent of that.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Forbes spent over $5 million. His opponents
were capped at $600,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bush has left open the possibility of skipping the
federal funds, but dismissed the question by saying ``it's too
early to make any of those tactical decisions.'' The decision
probably has to be made by mid-October so the federal money could
flow shortly after New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, spokeswoman for Bush's presidential exploratory
committee, said Wednesday that avoiding spending limits is the best
reason to pass on the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee has discussed the possibility of not taking
matching funds,'' she said. ``It will be some time before we see
how the fund-raising numbers look so we can begin to seriously
consider that option.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to escaping spending limits, a candidate who does
not take the government funds is free from federal audits that
scrutinize spending, and a $50,000 limit on contributions to his or
her own campaign. Bush has given no hint of planning to pump a
sizeable sum of personal money into the race.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether to take the matching money is limited to
the primaries. Once nominated, all candidates take the money for
the general election, though Forbes might not if he gets the nod.
</P>
<P>
   The federal money, estimated at up to $16 million for qualified
primary candidates next year, matches up to 25 percent of
individual donations, which are limited to $1,000. There is no
match for contributions from political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   The money comes from taxpayers who sign the $3 checkoff box on
their income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown University government Professor Clyde Wilcox, a
campaign finance expert, said Bush should be eager to avoid
repeating the Dole scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he buys is avoiding the spending limit,'' Wilcox said of
forgoing federal funds. ``Dole got pounded by Forbes in October and
November before the campaign started and he had to spend a lot of
money answering those ads. By the time he clinched the nomination
in April, he had pretty much spent all the money he was allowed to
spend.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wilcox said there could be a political cost to not taking
the money if an opponent tries to make the case that Bush ``has
chosen to disregard the normal procedure and wants to raise
unlimited money from wealthy donors.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Tony Fabrizio, Dole's 1996 pollster, said
it's an easy call, assuming a candidate can do without the
taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would absolutely forgo the matching money,'' Fabrizio told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   That means aggressive fund raising, a task Bush has proven equal
to. Two gubernatorial campaigns (he raised almost $18 million for
last year's re-election victory) and well-heeled family ties
combine to make him a fund-raiser of impressive proportion.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is temporarily handicapped by his promise not to stage
fund-raising events until after the legislative session ends May
31. Though fund raising is underway, there is nothing quite like a
big event, featuring the candidate, to bring in big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Bush is expected to immediately go on the road
after the legislative session to begin appearing at fund-raisers
across the country. The personal appearances are so important that
Bush is likely to schedule some events even in the crucial 20 days
after the session in which bills reach his desk to be signed or
vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   In California, a treasure trove of political money, the
anticipation is palpable, according to Rep. Rod Pacheco, the state
Assembly's GOP leader and a Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks that have been supportive of me ask me, `When is
Governor Bush coming to California? ...We want to attend his
fund-raisers,'' Pacheco said after meeting with Bush on Wednesday
at the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is working toward skipping the federal money, other
candidates _ namely Republican Gary Bauer and Democrat Bill Bradley
_ use qualifying for it as a landmark moment. Though it's a
relatively low hurdle to clear _ at least $5,000 raised (with no
more than $250 from any single donor) from each of at least 20
states _ candidates try to use it as a measure of viability.
Bradley and Bauer trumpeted the news when they passed the
qualification standard this month.
</P>
<P>
   Two previous Texas presidential candidates skipped the federal
matching money. In 1980, convinced the spending limits would make
it difficult for him to derail Ronald Reagan, former Texas Gov.
John Connally didn't take federal funds. He wound up spending $12
million and garnering a single delegate to the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Ross Perot poured $60 million of his own money into his
third-party presidential race and skipped the federal funds. In
1996, Perot took $29 million in federal funds and, like in 1992,
failed to get a single electoral vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
