<SLUG> BC-TEXLEGIS-BARADS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Results of referendum on campaign advertising questioned
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Henrietta lawyer Frank Douthitt never alleged
ballot-box stuffing in his complaints against a Texas State Bar
referendum. But what he alleged in a hearing Wednesday before a
special judge appointed by the Texas Supreme Court was that the
State Bar didn't count all the voters it should have in a
referendum last fall and, in the process, counted more votes than
it should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to make the rules,'' Douthitt said during a
break, ``then we ought to follow them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the devil played Hades with the details.
</P>
<P>
   State Bar President Richard Pena of Austin said Douthitt opposed
referendum proposals that the state's lawyers approved handily.
</P>
<P>
   In the referendum, lawyers approved changes in disciplinary
rules and voted to do away with the ``Not Board Certified''
disclaimer in advertising for attorneys practicing in certain areas
subject to specialty examination and certification.
</P>
<P>
   The issue in the contest over the referendum was whether enough
votes were cast to make the election proper. State law requires at
least 51 percent of the bar's active membership to vote in a
referendum to make it valid. By the state bar's calculation, the
vote drew only a few more than 51 percent of eligible Texas
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Douthitt questioned whether ballots that came in a day after the
declared voting cutoff should have been counted and the integrity
of replacement ballots faxed to lawyers in mass just before the
deadline. The bar's executive director, Tony Alvarado, said a
one-day delay in mailing the ballots triggered the day-later vote
count and that a New York company hired to conduct the voting had
procedures that assured its reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
