<HEADER>
A3127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXLEGIS-POLLUTION25-     03-24 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXLEGIS-POLLUTION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin representative targets aging industrial plants
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A coalition of lawmakers, environmentalists and
consumer advocates expressed support Wednesday for proposed state
legislation that would require so-called grandfathered industrial
plants to comply with current limitations on air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would crack down on hundreds of power plants,
chemical factories, refineries and other industrial plants that
have been exempted from anti-pollution laws for nearly 30 years.
The state Legislature exempted existing plants from new pollution
rules when the Texas Clean Air Act became law in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``These facilities could have great-grandchildren by now,'' Rep.
Glen Maxey (D-Austin), the sponsor of the proposal, said at a
Capitol news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The grandfathered plants collectively emit 900,000 tons of air
pollutants, 36 percent of all industrial air pollution in the
state, according to a review of state records by the Environmental
Defense Fund, a nonprofit group. About 1,000 of the state's 2,500
industrial plants are grandfathered. The environmental group found
that a voluntary emissions-reduction program launched by Gov.
George W. Bush had achieved little improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Maxey's bill and a Senate version sponsored by Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos, D-Austin, face an uphill battle. Competing legislation
has been filed by Rep. Ray Allen, R-Grand Prairie, and Sen. J.E.
``Buster'' Brown, R-Lake Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Allen and Brown measures build on Bush's voluntary approach
and are supported by the governor. Allen's bill, for example, would
encourage cleanup but it stops short of mandating new permits. The
measure would allow companies to establish wildlife preserves or
environmental-education programs instead of trimming emissions, and
it would restrict the public's opportunity to participate in
regulatory proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush, said the governor's
approach is already working. More than 50 companies have agreed to
obtain permits for 120 grandfathered plants, for an expected
pollution reduction of 100,000 tons a year, McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   An electric-utility deregulation bill also includes incentives
to reduce power plant emissions. The measure, sponsored by Sen.
David Sibley, R-Waco, would allow utilities to recover their
anti-pollution expenses from ratepayers. The bill has been passed
by the Senate and is awaiting action in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Maxey-Barrientos legislation is far more comprehensive than
the Allen-Brown or Sibley measures. It would require all
grandfathered plants to obtain new permits under current rules. The
plants would have to install what pollution laws refer to as the
``best available control technology'' to reduce emissions, and the
public would retain full rights to participate in quasi-judicial
proceedings known as contested-case hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Maxey and several co-sponsors said emissions from grandfathered
plants are a particular concern for children, and especially for
minority children. Minority students make up 49 percent of the
school-age population, according to a study by the Sustainable
Energy and Economic Development Coalition and other environmental
groups. But in seven Texas counties violating federal air-quality
standards, 225,000 students attend schools within two miles of
grandfathered plants, and 69 percent of those students are members
of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The grandfathered plants include four in Travis County: the City
of Austin's Decker and Holly power plants; the University of Texas'
power plant; and the Austin White Lime Co.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
