<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXLEGIS-VOUCHERS25-C     03-24 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXLEGIS-VOUCHERS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas conservatives oppose to voucher bill, passed
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Peggy Borchert, a Fort Worth mother, paid little
attention two years ago when lawmakers were debating a pilot
voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Borchert made her third trip to the Capitol in as
many months to tell lawmakers why using public money to send
children to private schools _ even as part of a small program _
would be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the government funds, it must regulate,'' said
Borchert, whose daughter attends a private school in Fort Worth.
``This is the first step in government regulation of private
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the voices in the debate over vouchers have
not changed in the four legislative sessions that the issue has
come up. They are the voices of special interests groups. School
groups and teachers organizations have adamantly opposed vouchers,
which they say would drain public schools of money and bright
students. Conservative think tanks and other groups vigorously have
pushed for a voucher pilot, which they say would provide parents
more choices in their children's education and generate competition
for public schools.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, when the Senate Education Committee passed a bill
to create Texas' first voucher pilot, new voices joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Like Borchert, many newcomers were conservative and Republican.
They were mothers with children in private or home schools. And
like Borchert, they were there to oppose the voucher bill sponsored
by Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, chairman of the Senate Education
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is full of regulation,'' said Michele Quinones, a
Halton City homemaker who accompanied Borchert. ``There will be a
tremendous cost to private schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of two whom she homeschools added: ``They will have
to teach the (public school curriculum), pay for transportation,
offer bilingual and special education. Public schools will lose
money. Private schools will lose their freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bivins' Senate Bill 10 low-income, low-performing students
enrolled in schools in the state's six largest districts would be
eligible for a voucher. Not all students who meet that criteria
would get a voucher, however. Bivins amended the bill so that no
more than 5 percent of a district's enrollment could participate.
Before the cap, about 148,000 students would have been eligible.
Bivins did not know how many would qualify with the 5 percent cap.
</P>
<P>
   The voucher would be worth 80 percent of the state and local
money a school district spends per pupil, or about $4,257 in
Austin. That could be higher or lower, depending on how much a
district spends per student. The remaining 20 percent of tax
dollars would remain behind in the student's public school.
</P>
<P>
   Schools participating in the state-voucher pilot would be
required to enroll all-comers. If a school had more applicants than
spaces, it would conduct a lottery to determine admission.
</P>
<P>
   Private schools _ called ``free schools'' in the bill _ would be
required to test voucher students, using the state achievement
exam, the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, and provide free
transportation to some students. The schools would have to accept
the voucher as full payment, even if it did not cover the total
tuition and fees.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bill cleared its first hurdle Wednesday, it faces an
uphill battle in the House, where Democrats opposed to vouchers
control the House Public Education Committee. Its chances also are
uncertain in the full Senate, where Democrats in 1997 blocked a
similar measure from coming to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Other new voices at the hearing came from advocates for students
with disabilities, the Arc of Texas, which for the first time are
opposing vouchers. And some parents and educators of children with
special needs, who were there to support vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son spent six years in the public school system. As of
September of this year, he could not read,'' said Jenni Contreras,
choking back tears.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras, of Hurst, told the Senate committee that her son has
a learning disability school officials were not prepared to deal
with. She now pays $4,500 a year to send him to the Phoenix Special
Needs Education school. ``I drove for three hours from Hurst to
tell them about my son. '' I believe in choice,'' Contreras said.
``If the Hurst-Euless-Bedford district did not want to educate my
son, then I should be able to take that money and use it to give my
son the education he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
