<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-PICK-ART-94     03-24 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-PICK-ART-940&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKILI SMITH SCALES THE DRAFT DAY MOUNTAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last December, NFL scouts believed that Akili Smith of Oregon
would be selected near the bottom of the second round, perhaps
60th, in the April 17 draft.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of January, he was projected near the 40th spot.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of February, the projection was near the 15th spot in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing, climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Today? Smith is in Cleveland. The Browns are talking with him,
testing him, peering into his mind and into his eyes, wondering if
they will find a champion. The Browns own the No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this: Tim Couch of Kentucky and Smith. One of
these two quarterbacks will be the first pick in the draft. Couch
is no surprise. He has been poked and prodded and monitored
throughout his illustrious career. First, in a high school and then
at the state's biggest university in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   But Akili Smith? Oregon? Who?
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the mold. On the rise. Out of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been breaking the mold for a while. He was a minor
league first baseman and outfielder in the Pittsburgh Pirates chain
before he was a college quarterback, a guy who found trouble in
college before peace, who had a hard head before a wise one, who
stammered before becoming loquacious and who tripped over his feet
at quarterback before displaying artistic footwork and a
dart-throwing arm, a 23-year-old who is climbing a personal
mountain in a magical way.
</P>
<P>
   What else from a guy who grew up on Peter Pan Street?
</P>
<P>
   There is a touch about him, an unmistakable charisma, and
something that speaks strength and winner. He grew up in San Diego
and played football in San Diego at the same Lincoln High School as
Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Smith started at quarterback for Oregon for only a season and a
half, including last season, a record-shattering year in which he
threw for 456 yards, and threw two touchdowns and ran for another
against Colorado in the Aloha Bowl. By the time he left Oregon,
whispers abounded _ Akili Smith might be a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing to me those scouts who look at a guy play
and then look at film and then see the competition and still do not
recognize his talent,'' Smith said. ``I got a late start in
college, but, really, and I don't mean it as bragging, but how
could you not look at me and believe that I can't play football?
That my best years are ahead of me?''
</P>
<P>
   That at 6 foot 3 and 225 pounds, he shows moxie at the position
and the nifty footwork, the great arm strength, the touch when he
needs it, the quick release, the long ball and the short ball, the
mobility? The package.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some quarterbacks in this draft who I think can play
a lot of football for a very long time,'' said Tony Dungy, the
Tampa Bay Buccaneers' head coach. ``I see five quarterbacks that
look like first-round picks and five more that are second round and
maybe high third round. The positioning of these quarterbacks could
go up, and so could the dollar figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I had the first pick in this draft, I'd lean toward
Akili Smith,'' Dungy said. ``I like his ball. He throws the ball
like Warren Moon. It's a beautiful ball with more revolution on his
passes than any quarterback I've ever seen. He's a little older
than the regular college quarterback, and I like that experience in
his life, if not at his position. He throws a tight, accurate ball.
He's done a lot of the things against big-time competition in the
Pac-10 that you like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Norv Turner, the Washington Redskins' head coach, said: ``He had
a very good combine and more people paid attention to him after
that. They got in there and did the film work and study and saw
that the film did not lie. You could easily pick him No. 1. It all
comes down to personal preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   For Akili Smith, it all came down to personal choices. And then
rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   Low test scores out of high school in 1993 helped him choose pro
baseball over college football. The Pirates signed him and he spent
a year in the minors in Bradenton, Fla., and then another year in
Erie, Pa. ``I struggled with hitting the off-speed pitch and in the
outfield,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he missed football. So, in 1995, he played football for one
season at Grossmont Junior College near San Diego. ``I was the
No.-1 rated player coming out of junior college,'' Smith said. And
Oregon swiped him.
</P>
<P>
   But in his first few months at Oregon he was arrested in an
assault case _ ``a group of guys followed me and a friend outside
and started a confrontation,'' he said _ and on a DWI. charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was hanging out too much in a new environment,
trying to fit in and learn, and what I needed to do was stay in and
study and concentrate on my football,'' Smith said. ``Those
incidents, those things woke me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that his father, Ray Sr., is one of his best friends.
His father spent 2{ years in a penitentiary for attempted armed
robbery. Now, his father works as a counselor in San Diego, dealing
with troubled youth and gangs. His father also is a minister who
has long shared his life with his son and has long challenged him
to make wiser decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me about things, but some things I had to see for
myself,'' Smith said. ``I had to grow. And I have. The scouts now
and the teams, they ask me about these incidents and I tell them
truthfully about them. I talk openly about them, because I'm not
ashamed about having learned some lessons the hard way. I'm more
proud that I learned them completely and that they changed me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed helpful coaching at Oregon, made good friends,
settled in and then blossomed. In 1997, he played 11 games and made
seven starts. Last season, he started all 12 games, leading the
Ducks to an 8-3 record overall and a third-place tie with Southern
California in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   His game grew and grew. Out of the woods. From near complete
obscurity. Smith finished with 3,763 passing yards. He threw 32
touchdown passes and only eight interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkable: 19 starts at Oregon and he could be pro football's
No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm the one-year wonder,'' Smith said, chuckling. ``I
want to go to the NFL and take care of my family and win Super
Bowls and Pro Bowls and then retire and spend time with my family.
Just come and then go.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of obscurity. And then one day, he hopes, after a bright
career, right back into it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
