</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BACK TO BUDGET ROOT CANAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, March 25:
</P>
<P>
   The new era of federal surpluses was supposed to change the
tired dynamics of budget battles in Washington. That was because
there really is enough money to enact some tax cuts, some new
spending and some help for Social Security and Medicare. For now,
however, the Republican congressional leadership appears to prefer
radical tax and spending cuts to reasoned accommodation on the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate budget committees are pushing similar plans
that call for excessive tax cuts and spending reductions while
leaving Medicare's problems unaddressed. Even many Republicans fear
that the party's budget schemes are unwise and unrealistic. They
and like-minded Democrats should reject the budget plans when they
come to a vote on the House and Senate floors this week.
</P>
<P>
   The most positive feature of the Republican proposal is that the
surplus revenue generated by the Social Security payroll tax,
estimated at $1.8 billion in the next 10 years, would be used to
strengthen the retirement system itself. Ideally, this money should
be used to shore up the solvency of the program rather than to
create new individual retirement accounts. In general, however, the
Republican proposal shows a willingness to follow President
Clinton's lead and ``save Social Security first.''
</P>
<P>
   The major problem with the GOP budget is that it takes nearly
all the remaining $800 billion projected budget surplus in the next
decade to finance a whopping tax cut. There would be little if any
money left over for Medicare or for saving myriad other federal
programs from being chopped severely. Moreover, if those budget
forecasts prove optimistic, tax cuts passed this year could lock
the government into more deficits down the line.
</P>
<P>
   It is of course customary for the White House and the Democrats
to cry foul and come up with a list of budget ``horribles'' at this
time of year. But projections presented by Sen. Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, a Republican and chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, show that so-called discretionary spending would have to
be cut by tens of billions of dollars in order to pay for the tax
cuts and targeted spending increases that Republicans favor for the
military, some school aid and veterans' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are not required to specify where the cuts might
come from at this early stage in the budget process. But if the
last few years are any guide, it is clear what some of these cuts
will have to be. The budget cannot be cut by the amounts that the
Republicans want without Congress going after child and maternal
nutrition programs, aid to farmers and environmental and job safety
enforcement. Administration budget experts say that even the number
of drug enforcement, border patrol and FBI agents will have to be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The job of actually making these cuts will fall to various
appropriations committees later in the year. Right now, these
lawmakers are saying privately that there is no way they will be
able to get such cuts through the Senate, or a House only barely
controlled by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to see what is being gained by the Republican
approach. Maybe the leaders figure that an eventual confrontation
with Clinton will lead to a budget accommodation at the end of the
year, saving Republicans from the root-canal instincts of their
budget hawks. Maybe the lawmakers are listening to Republican
presidential candidates like Gov. George Bush of Texas proclaiming
their belief in less government, and they just want to show the
public what that might mean.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion here, however, is that if it means less help for
the poor, the sick and the disabled and less enforcement of labor
and environmental laws, Republicans might find that the public is
less interested than they suppose. The Republican strategy might
end up looking like what it seems to be, a triumph of ideology over
common sense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
