<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      03-24 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO FORCES HAMMER MILITARY TARGETS IN YUGOSLAVIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See also: KOSOVO-POLITICS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-RATIONALE and
KOSOVO-CONGRESS.) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S.-led forces pummeled Yugoslav military targets
from the air Wednesday as NATO, launching the first attack in its
50-year history against a sovereign nation, attempted to halt the
fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the initial wave of cruise missiles slammed into
the Balkan nation, including sites near the capital Belgrade,
President Clinton said the raids were required to stop a brutal
assault by the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
against Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo's crisis now is full blown,'' Clinton said in a
statement he read in the White House briefing room. ``And if we do
not act, clearly it will get even worse. Only firmness now can
prevent greater catastrophe later. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the aim of NATO's attack, which was condemned by
Russia as a violation of international law, was to ``seriously
diminish'' Milosevic's military capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In a longer address to the nation Wednesday night from the White
House, Clinton sought anew to convince Americans of the need for
the military operation, including use of a map to illustrate his
view that Kosovo is central to European security.
</P>
<P>
   The military operation was one of the most unorthodox ever
undertaken by NATO, which was established in 1949 as a military
shield for western Europe against the Soviet Union and has been
struggling to demonstrate its relevance in the post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
   The assault came after the Clinton administration and its major
European allies had failed for weeks to get Milosevic to agree to a
cease-fire in Kosovo and the stationing of NATO troops in the
southern Yugoslav province to police the deal. Kosovar Albanians
accepted the proposal during recent talks in France, but Milosevic
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised address before the airstrikes began,
Milosevic said ``the only right decision was to reject foreign
troops on our territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The strikes by dozens of cruise missiles were followed quickly
by bombing raids, including the first use in combat of the $2
billion B-2 stealth bomber. U.S. military sources refused to offer
an initial damage assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav military officials said a NATO plane was downed, but
the alliance headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, denied the report.
Western sources said at least one Yugoslav jet, almost certainly a
Soviet-built MiG, was fired on and hit after engaging NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
   The assault included targets in both halves of Yugoslavia _
Serbia and Montenegro _ as well as in Kosovo, the scene of bitter
ethnic fighting for more than a year. Ninety percent of Kosovars
are ethnic Albanians and many seek independence from Yugoslavia, a
move opposed by Milosevic, most of his Serb opposition and even the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin condemned the attacks on fellow
Slavs as ``outright aggression'' and called for an emergency
meeting of the U.N. Security Council, which began late Wednesday
afternoon. Russia withdrew the leader of its mission to NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Russian television shortly before the airstrikes
began, Yeltsin said the attacks will lead to ``a war in Europe, if
not worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and Russian presidents spoke by telephone earlier
Wednesday, and National Security Spokesman David Leavy said Clinton
``reviewed ... the situation on the ground (in Yugoslavia), how
fighting has intensified, how the Serbs are burning villages and
driving people up into the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   China also voiced its objection.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faced heated domestic opposition to the assault, with
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, saying the president ``views American
pilots, soldiers and sailors as world social workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 58-41 Tuesday to back the airstrikes. On
Wednesday, after raids began, the House voted 424-1 on the narrower
issue of supporting U.S. forces in the military operation.
</P>
<P>
   As the raids continued through the night, officials at Yugoslav
army headquarters said ``more than 20 sites'' had been hit in the
first hour of bombardment. The official Tanjug news agency said the
targets included military housing where the victims included wives
and children of former Yugoslav soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said the forces of 11 of the
19 NATO member nations took part in the initial assault. The
alliance earlier this month admitted Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic, the first additions from the old Soviet bloc. NATO plans
a 50th anniversary summit next month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our NATO allies unanimously support this action,''Clinton
said. ``The United States must stand with them, and stand against
ethnic violence and atrocity.''
</P>
<P>
   European Union leaders, meeting in Berlin, adopted a statement
that said, ``President Milosevic is fully responsible for what is
going on now.'' The EU leaders said Milosevic could ``stop the
military action by immediately halting his violent action in
Kosovo'' and by accepting the cease-fire and NATO enforcement
troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO mounted airstrikes in 1995 against Serb positions in
Bosnia-Herzegovina that forced Milosevic to the bargaining table
and resulted in the peace deal known as the Dayton accords. U.S.
troops make up part of a NATO force policing the agreement in
Bosnia, another former piece of the old Yugoslavia that began
breaking up on the death of Marshal Tito and the dissolution of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the afternoon statement he read in the White House
press briefing room, acknowledged the risks faced by NATO
personnel, but ``I have concluded that the dangers of acting now
are clearly outweighed by the risks of failing to act _ the risks
that many more innocent people will die or be driven from their
homes by the tens of thousands. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The president outlined U.S. aims:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strikes have three objectives. First, to demonstrate the
seriousness of NATO's opposition to aggression and its support for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, to deter President Milosevic from continuing and
escalating his attacks on helpless civilians by imposing a price
for those attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And third, if necessary, to damage Serbia's capacity to wage
war against Kosovo in the future by seriously diminishing its
military capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said the alliance had a
``moral duty'' to seek an end to the violence and ``humanitarian
catastrophe'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, the former Yugoslav republic to the south of Kosovo,
reopened its border to thousand of fleeing refugees Wednesday after
a one-day closure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
