<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KEVORKIAN-NYT &LR;      03-24 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KEVORKIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DR. KEVORKIAN'S CLIENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, March 25:
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Kevorkian is learning the hard way that a court of law
is not always a congenial forum for airing a political or moral
position. His blundering attempts to present his own case at his
murder trial are looking more pathetic than crusading. The doctor
is charged with deliberately killing a man by lethal injection in a
macabre case where the key piece of evidence is his own videotape
of the death, broadcast on CBS's ``60 Minutes'' last November.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian has wanted to use his trial to move the public debate
from doctor-assisted suicide, where doctors supply desperately ill
patients with the means to kill themselves, to euthanasia, where
the doctors do the ``mercy killing.'' He taped the death to goad
prosecutors into charging him with it. Now that the case is in
court, allowing his lawyers to speak for him would deprive him of
center stage. But Kevorkian is probably beginning to realize that
the courtroom, bound by the law and rules of evidence, is not very
hospitable to attempts to initiate a moral debate.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, who says he has helped more than 130 people commit
suicide, is charged with first-degree murder for injecting Thomas
Youk, a man suffering from Lou Gehrig's disease, with a fatal dose
of drugs. The doctor has been tried four times before on
assisted-suicide charges, with three acquittals and one mistrial.
In the earlier cases he rigged up a ``suicide machine'' that
allowed the individuals to administer the drugs themselves, whereas
this time it was he who did the injection.
</P>
<P>
   The outcomes were the same. The people all died through means
provided by the doctor. Yet the legal difference between
Kevorkian's injecting the drugs and an individual's pulling a
string on a Kevorkian-created device is great. In an
assisted-suicide case, for example, Michigan law allows evidence
concerning the patient's suffering to be presented in court,
exerting a powerful impact on jurors reluctant to convict a doctor
for relieving suffering. That is why prosecutors dropped the lesser
charge of assisted suicide this time and stuck with murder alone.
The trial judge has ruled that evidence of suffering is irrelevant
in a murder case and that consent to be killed is not a defense to
murder. That position seems to shut down much of Kevorkian's legal
argument.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor has never appeared particularly concerned about his
lack of legal skills. He seems to yearn for martyrdom. He says he
simply wants to do his duty as a physician. As he argued on ``60
Minutes,'' ``This could never be a crime in any society that deems
itself enlightened.''
</P>
<P>
   He may never be allowed to make that argument directly to the
jury. Faced with this odd case, the jury members could decide that
what Kevorkian did to Youk, however reckless and misguided it was,
still does not feel like murder. Or, given the doctor's bumbling
presentation and the letter of the law, they could convict him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
