<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' DECISIONS MAY WAIT UNTIL L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ One lefty or two in the bullpen? Dave Hansen
or Scott Livingstone? Trenidad Hubbard or Jacob Brumfield as the
fifth outfielder?
</P>
<P>
   Up to this point the cuts the Los Angeles Dodgers made in spring
training could have been predicted two months ago _ with the
exception of 21-year-old left-hander Onan Masaoka. Now it's
nitty-gritty time.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation process intensifies. The veterans vying for
backup jobs have little leeway. They must perform well to win jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, don't expect much to get resolved before the Dodgers
break camp next Wednesday and head to Los Angeles. Manager Davey
Johnson said the aforementioned questions may not get answered
until late Easter Sunday, after the Dodgers and New York Yankees
conclude the exhibition schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably be a lot of decisions that we take to the
last day,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question is in the bullpen. If the Dodgers remain
status quo with their starting pitchers, lefties Greg Cadaret (0-1,
4.66 ERA), Chris Haney (1-0, 4.09), Pedro Borbon (0-0, 3.00) and
Masaoka (0-0, 1.00) will spend the next 11 days battling for one or
two spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be guessing if I told you who I thought it would be,''
pitching coach Charlie Hough said. ``Generally, this club has taken
three or four extra pitchers west for the Angels series, and this
year it's very important to have guys ready because there is no
off-day between (the last exhibition game) and the start of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson said he favors Tripp Cromer and Jose Vizcaino as
middle infielders, Hansen (.216, 1 HR, 4 RBI) and Livingstone
(.414, 2 HR, 7 RBI) are fighting for the backup corner position.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hubbard (.111) returned Wednesday after missing 15
days with a shoulder and thumb injury, the result of an outfield
collision with Hiram Bocachica. During that absence the Dodgers
brought Brumfield up from minor-league camp to play with the
big-league club.
</P>
<P>
   Brumfield, who played for Johnson in Cincinnati, has hit .276
with two homers and three RBI. He also offers speed and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about that,'' Hubbard said. ``You have to be a
surgeon of the situation. All I can control is my playing time. All
I'm doing is planning on getting ready so when (Johnson) calls on
me, I'm ready to hit the lefties.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy does it, big fella: Raul Mondesi got his foot caught under
the fence chasing down a double in the right-field corner in the
fifth inning Wednesday. Mondesi, who saw the ball frequently during
the afternoon, wanted to continue. But Johnson saw enough, getting
his right fielder out of the game before anything else could go
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were running him ragged,'' Johnson said. ``I wanted to
get him out of there before they killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster cuts: Four more players were cut from the major-league
roster, including catcher Tim Laker (Simi Valley High). He and
pitcher Jamie Arnold were reassigned to the Dodgers' minor-league
camp. Infielder Adam Riggs and outfielder Kevin Gibbs were optioned
to Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Johnson said Todd Hundley is expected to
catch his first Grapefruit League game Friday against Baltimore....
Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek, bothered by shin splints, played for
the first time in six days.... Jack Zduriencik, the Dodgers'
special assistant to the general manager/director of international
relations, will be the Dodgers' representative who travels to Cuba
for Sunday's exhibition game with the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
