<SLUG> BC-RETURN-SHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME RETURN TO FAMILIES IN HOMELAND UNDER ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE MS ALBA, in the Adriatic Sea _ As NATO fighter jets
streaked overhead on their way to drop the first bombs on
Yugoslavia, a rusted cargo ship slowly slipped anchor in the
Italian port of Bari Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and headed home.
</P>
<P>
   The Alba's few passengers and much of its crew, most of them
from the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, gathered in a tiny
captain's galley as the ship creaked and swayed in the swells of
the Adriatic. Listening to shortwave radio, they sat stunned at the
news and consumed with worry over family and friends at home, where
bombs and cruise missiles were falling. They were desperate to get
home, and the Alba, a 30-year old freighter, was the only way to
get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us know what we're going home to,'' said the ship's
cook, Borjedar Antonovic, 39. ``All of us are afraid. I just can't
believe this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the galley was a cross-section of Yugoslavia. There
were three high-ranking government officials rushing home to a
homeland under attack, a married couple nervous about the fate of
their three children, a playwright, and a businessman. There was
the ship's mechanic and its first mate.
</P>
<P>
   There were long silences, and some shook their heads in
disbelief that for the first time in 50 years, US and allied forces
had actually attacked another country within Europe. The long
diplomatic game of brinksmanship between the United States and NATO
on one side, and the defiant Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
on the other, had finally come to war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe it. I can't believe they bombed us,''
echoed Voin Dukonovic, Yugoslavia's former vice president and now a
trade minister in the Republic of Montenegro who had left a
conference to rush home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people will suffer and Milosevic will get stronger for the
short term,'' he said. ``The Serbs will rally around him, but then
we can only hope people will see the destruction and the
devastation and turn on him. We can only hope this will be the end
of his days.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reports of the bombing crackling over the radio were grim.
The heard that their native Montenegro had been hit hard. The
airport had been bombed. While Slovenia, Bosnia, Macedonia, and
Croatia have deserted the Yugoslav Federation, Montenegro remains
with Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   They heard that military installations near the port of Bar, the
ship's destination, had been slammed by cruise missiles fired from
the US Navy's 6th Fleet, which cruised unseen in the same waters as
the slowly chugging freighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can they do that? They promised that Montenegro would be
spared,'' said Marian Sekulic, who was traveling with her husband
and had been trying without success all night with a mobile phone
to reach her three children and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has no understanding of this situation,'' she went on.
``They have no understanding of how the Montenegrins have tried to
preserve democracy to improve the economy despite Milosevic. And
still they bomb us as if we are no different than him.''
</P>
<P>
   They were the people lucky enough to get on the ship. With
airports closed and roads the long way around to the north blocked
by troops, dozens of Yugoslavs in the Italian port of Bari had
begged the captain of the ship, which sails under the flag of
Montenegro, to give them passage. But he couldn't take them all.
</P>
<P>
   Marko Taylor, a 38-year old construction worker from Texas, was
one of those who was turned down. He is married to a Yugoslav
woman, and he said he feared for his wife and son. Their home is on
the coast near a Yugoslav army military installation that was
believed to have been hit by NATO. ``I have a wife and kid. They
won't let me on. I have no idea what I'm going to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bozo Machailovic, a professor of economics at Montenegro
University, said he had two sons, and he feared they would be
called up for military service in the escalating conflict. He also
feared for a homeland that was in a state of ``economic collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Budimir Dubak, a playwright who is also Yugoslavia's minister of
culture, lit another cigarette and sighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad, very sad to see what has happened,'' he said.
``Yugoslavia was a proud, confident place. In the 1970s and 1980s
we held a very important place in European culture. We were
Socialist, but open and free.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As artists we have lost so much through the isolation under
Milosevic . . . Now we will go home to the ruins of the bombings,''
he said. ``You have no way of knowing how that makes us feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
