<HEADLINE>
HIGHER EARNINGS FORSEEN ON COUNTRYWIDE SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. -- Countrywide Credit Industries is expected
to report higher earnings for the fourth quarter and year-end than
last year, thanks to 1998's record real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among 16 analysts polled by First Call is that the
earnings report, expected today, will show 85 cents for the quarter
and $3.28 for the year. In the prior year, the nation's largest
independent mortgage lender reported a 74 cents-a-share profit for
the fourth quarter and $2.78 for the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   While expectations are optimistic, it's anyone's guess what the
stock will do after the report comes out.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the company reported an 84 cents-per-share profit
for the third quarter, up 22 percent from the year before. It beat
analysts' estimates of 82 cents a share. In the following 12 days,
the stock rose by about $2 to hover in the $50 range. But it has
dropped back to the mid-$30s since then. For the year, Countrywide
is down 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All of which irks Angelo Mozilo, Countrywide's chairman and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he told analysts that the stock is ``horribly
undervalued by any measure'' and should be trading in the $70s.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
