<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AIR CAMPAIGN AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, March 25:
</P>
<P>
   With the start of NATO air and missile attacks on Yugoslavia
Wednesday, the long-running crisis over Kosovo has entered a new,
uncertain and decidedly more dangerous phase. More broadly, the
attacks mark an important watershed for the Atlantic alliance.
While NATO planes attacked Serbian militias in Bosnia a few years
ago, the alliance had never before unleashed its military power
against a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
   The air attacks are warranted. Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan
Milosevic, has rejected all efforts at meaningful diplomacy and, in
violation of his own previous commitments, has ratcheted up his
military campaign against the innocent civilians of Kosovo. NATO's
aim is to protect those civilians by hobbling the Yugoslav
military, and beyond that, to force Milosevic to accept the
compromise peace plan that already has been accepted by
representatives of Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some countries, notably Russia, are uncomfortable with the
idea of NATO action in support of these goals. Washington must
manage the diplomatic side of the conflict carefully, seeking to
minimize strains with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who addressed the American people twice on
Kosovo Wednesday, framed the issues well. While acknowledging the
risks of acting, he pointed to the dangers of not acting, noting
the region's history as a ``powderkeg at the heart of Europe''
whose conflicts previously have exploded into wider war. He rightly
stressed the moral imperative of protecting innocent people against
killings and the destruction of their homes and cited NATO's need
for resolve in halting these atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   In making its stand against Milosevic and his armed forces, NATO
brought formidable air power into play. The alliance has nearly 400
warplanes, half of them American, based within easy flying distance
of Yugoslavia. Destroyers, cruisers and submarines armed with
cruise missiles patrol nearby Mediterranean waters. Many additional
planes and missiles could be made available should a prolonged
bombing campaign prove necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there can be no guarantee that air strikes alone will force
Milosevic to compromise, and no clear consensus on what military or
diplomatic steps to take if air power proves insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the use of cruise missiles and stealth aircraft, there
is a significant risk of NATO planes being shot down by Yugoslav
defenders. Yugoslavia's army is one the largest and toughest in
Europe, equipped with mobile anti-aircraft guns that can be
silenced only by low-flying planes.
</P>
<P>
   These factors point up the need for a steadiness, persistence
and unity from the NATO allies now that the attack has been made.
In theory, the complex ethnic and religious conflicts of Yugoslavia
could have put the unity of the 19-member NATO alliance to a severe
test. In reality, faced with Milosevic's intransigence and
brutality, NATO has found it relatively easy to reach a united
stand. That is encouraging, since it is a reasonable bet that NATO
may again be called on to act against ethnic conflict in Europe in
the years ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
