<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CUBA-BALTIMORE-NY     03-24 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-BALTIMORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA TRIP IS OPPOSED BY CUBANS IN MAJOR LEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major League Baseball's presence in Castro's Cuba could have
become a regular event had world political and military events not
intervened nearly a quarter of a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Baltimore Orioles' game Sunday against the Cuban
national team will be the first for a major league team in Cuba
since 1959, Bowie Kuhn, then the baseball commissioner, was
prepared to send an all-star team to Havana in 1976. The game could
conceivably have led to a regular series.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Gomez, a Cuban native and former major league manager,
recently recalled the planning for the game, including a meeting
with Cuban officials in Mexico City in 1975 after the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was arranged,'' he said. ``We were going to go
there and play in March of '76. Henry Kissinger approved it. Bowie
Kuhn was going to take a player from each team. Some owners and
general managers were going on the trip. We were going to fly out
of Orlando. There was going to be a big dinner with Castro. Then in
January they found out there were Cuban soldiers in Angola.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years later, the State Department again has
sanctioned a game that could lead to expanded relations between the
two countries, at least in sports. But the Orioles' trip is by no
means popular among Cubans who play or coach in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it; I don't think it's right,'' said Cookie
Rojas, the New York Mets' third-base coach, who was born in Havana
in 1939. ``He's never given anything back. It's just take, take,
take. Where are the human rights, the freedom of the Cuban people?
I haven't been back since 1961. Now I'm 60 years old and I haven't
been able to go to my land. I'd rather die without seeing it and
remember it the way it was when it was free.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Mets players who defected from Cuba, Rey Ordonez and Jorge
Toca, agreed with Rojas. Livan Hernandez of the Florida Marlins
also has spoken out against the game. His half-brother, Orlando, of
the New York Yankees, declined to comment, as did Jose Canseco and
Rolando Arrojo of Tampa Bay and Jose Cardenal, the Yankees'
first-base coach.
</P>
<P>
   The game has disrupted the Orioles' pitching rotation. Juan
Guzman, whose turn it would have been to start Sunday, has opted
not to go to Cuba. He is Dominican, but he lives in Miami among
Cuban Americans and said he did not wan to offend his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban Americans have staged protests at Fort Lauderdale Stadium,
where the Orioles play their spring training games. Some members of
Congress have also urged the Orioles not to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, however, eagerly awaited the game. Speaking of the
opposition to it, he said, ``I understand their feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   The game has not aroused any opposition in Cuba. ``If they had
200,000 seats, they would fill the stadium,'' said Gomez, a special
assistant to the Anaheim Angels' general manager, who in 1959
managed the Havana Sugar Kings of the International League. If the
Cuban team should win, he added, ``Cuba will be in an uproar.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban national team has long been the best team in
international tournaments, but it has played amateur teams from
other countries and has never played a team that is considered the
caliber of a U.S. major league team. The Cuban government, whose
leader is the country's No. 1 baseball fan, takes the sport so
seriously that a rare loss, either of a tournament game or a game
to the United States, has triggered a change of managers and sports
officials.
</P>
<P>
   For this game, the Cubans could be at a disadvantage because
they will be using wood bats instead of the aluminum bats they use
during their season. They have used wood bats in their playoffs,
which have reached the championship series, and one U.S. baseball
official said he heard the games have been littered with broken
bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
