<HEADER>
A3149 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWEST-AZR &LR;      03-24 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST FLIGHT ATTENDANTS' DEAL FIRST CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five-year, $80 million contract negotiated by America West
Airlines flight attendants is first class compared with the coach
contract of $53.5 million offered by the carrier nearly 18 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an upgrade from the $68.7 million the company offered
before an impasse was declared by federal mediators in February.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Flight Attendants released details Wednesday
of the tentative contract, which was settled early Saturday, about
90 minutes after the union was free to strike. Now the rank and
file will vote on whether the latest contract is an improvement
over the deal reached on Halloween 1997 that was rejected by 88
percent of the union members.
</P>
<P>
   AFA Council 66 negotiators have been meeting with America West
in Washington D.C. since Saturday to finalize contract language and
implementation schedules for sections of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming home with an agreement in hand,'' said Scott
Ramsey, AFA Council 66 vice president. ``It's a contract our
members will be proud of because we took on the company, got the
best deal possible and didn't have to risk a single flight
attendant job in a CHAOS strike action.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempe-based America West will not comment on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to give an opportunity to the union to review
the contract with its membership,'' company spokeswoman Patty
Nowack said.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 2,300 flight attendants. The AFA has lowered its
official membership figure from 2,400.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the new annual wage scale will range from $14,400 to
$32,200. Currently, pay ranges from about $12,000 to $22,000. After
42 months, pay will range from $15,200 to $33,800.
</P>
<P>
   The union said it got close to achieving a pay scale that is 90
percent of what Southwest Airlines pays its flight attendants.
Southwest's pay scale ranges from $14,500 to $41,200, according to
the AFA.
</P>
<P>
   The union had initially sought a deal worth $129 million, but
reduced its demands to $85.3 million. It got close to that, but
made concessions on travel expenses or per diem. Flight attendants
wanted $1.80 per hour in per diem, on par with pilots, but settled
for $1.30 per hour. That will increase to $1.50 after 2{ years and
to $1.75 on the final day of the contract, April 30, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants had been earning the equivalent of 89 cents
per hour in per diem under a different system of pay for travel
expenses that will be scrapped if the contract is ratified.
</P>
<P>
   Pay will increase initially from $14.18 per hour to start, to
$16.13, and to $16.93 at the end of the contract. Upon
ratification, top pay will jump from $24.41 per hour to $35.80, and
$37.59 in the fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants are paid only for their flight time, which
they say makes their hourly wages misleading when compared with
most 9-to-5 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to achieve bigger gains on the pay scale, the union
made concessions on the scheduled vs. actual pay. Currently, flight
attendants are paid for the scheduled flight time and aren't
compensated if a flight is late unless it's more than 30 minutes
late. Under the new contract, America West will pay them for the
extra time if the delay exceeds 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a flight is due in at 10 a.m. but arrives at
10:13 a.m., the flight attendants won't get any extra pay. But if
it arrives at 10:18 a.m., they would be paid for 18 extra minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After two years, America West will pay for the extra time on
delays starting at the first minute beyond the scheduled time.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative contract also settles a bonus-pay lawsuit filed by
the union that goes back to 1994 when flight attendants voted to
unionize.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, flight attendants will receive a
signing bonus of $3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Further details of the contract will be explained to flight
attendants at road shows in Phoenix, Las Vegas and Columbus, Ohio,
starting the week of April 5. America West has agreed to print
copies of the contract for each flight attendant and those should
be delivered by April 2, according to the AFA.
</P>
<P>
   It's anybody's guess whether flight attendants will get on board
to support this contract. Initial reactions were favorable, but
union members haven't seen contract details. Still, some Wall
Street analysts predict that flight attendants will ratify the
deal, which has improved the outlook for America West.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs analyst Glenn Engel raised his estimate of the
carrier's first quarter earnings per share from 40 cents to 60
cents and the full year from $1.80 per share to $2.10.
</P>
<P>
   The strike threat will cost America West 5 to 10 cents per
share, but increased business from a sickout by American Airlines
pilots boosted earnings an estimated 15 to 20 cents per share,
Engel said in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he warned that America West could be hurt ``by the
growing industry oversupply and any slowdown in consumer
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratification of the contract will be voted on in a secret mail
ballot. Ballots will be counted April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McGlashen, AFA Council 66 president, said the contract
improves salary and per diem, and gives flight attendants greater
flexibility in their work schedules.
</P>
<P>
   That echoes statements made in 1997 by then-AFA President
Deborah Volpe about the previous tentative contract.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen and his team of negotiators were scheduled to return
to Phoenix at 9 p.m. Wednesday. AFA members were encouraged to meet
the flight wearing their full uniforms, not the bright green CHAOS
strike T-shirts. &QL; 
 &UR; Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
