<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVLON SHARES SOARING ON TAKEOVER SPECULATION
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Revlon surged $5.1875, or 30.4 percent, to $22.25, on
speculation that a buyer may soon step in and rescue the cosmetics
giant from its huge debt and weak performance lately in the powder
and perfume business.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon stock has risen 54 percent over the last two days on
heavy volume. Investors are reacting to growing speculation that
Revlon and the billionaire Ronald O. Perelman, who controls 83
percent of its shares, may be near a deal to sell the struggling
company, which makes Revlon, Colorstay and Almay cosmetics, to a
larger consumer-products concern. The two names mentioned most
often by bankers and analysts as potential buyers are Unilever of
the Netherlands and Procter &AMP; Gamble in Cincinnati. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT PROPOSES A SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft made its opening step toward trying to settle its
antitrust battle with the Government in a four-page proposal
delivered to the Justice Department on Monday, according to lawyers
close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   IN YUGOSLAVIA, A SHATTERED ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   With the Yugoslav economy in tatters and trade limited since
international economic sanctions were imposed in 1992, little more
economic harm is expected from air strikes by the United States and
its NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   ORDERS FOR DURABLE GOODS DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders for big-ticket goods posted the largest decline
in more than seven years in February, a sign that an expected
recovery in manufacturing could be a few months away, the Commerce
Department said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE IMF AID SEEN FOR INDONESIA
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund is likely to approve more
financial aid to Indonesia at a board meeting in Washington today,
a senior official said in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH PHONE VENTURE MAY BE SOLD
</P>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless and the Mediaone Group want to sell One 2
One, a British mobile-phone venture worth $13.1 billion, an
investment banker advising on the sale said. Options could also
include an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   BARON FIRM PAYS FUND FOR LOSS
</P>
<P>
   The investment firm headed by Ronald Baron has paid $1.6 million
to the Baron Asset Fund because of unrealized losses on 650,000
shares of AMF Bowling the fund bought from a private client in
October. Mr. Baron said no shareholders had threatened to sue.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY RALLY LIFTS NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks caught fire in the last 90 minutes of trading,
lifting the Nasdaq composite index 42.44 points, or 1.83 percent,
to 2,365.28. The late rally did little, however, for blue-chip
stocks as the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 4.99 points, to
9,666.84, receding further from the 10,000 mark it flirted with
last week. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 6.45
points, or five-tenths of a percent, to 1,268.59. In the bond
market, the yield on the 30-year Treasury fell to 5.53 percent,
from 5.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AMERITECH BUYS 20 PERCENT OF BELL CANADA
</P>
<P>
   Ameritech, the phone company set to be acquired by SBC
Communications, said that it would buy a 20 percent stake in
Canada's leading carrier, Bell Canada, for $3.4 billion to take
advantage of deregulation. Bell Canada plans to use the proceeds to
invest in electronic commerce, satellite services and other
fast-growing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   EXPANSION IN INTERACTIVE MARKETING
</P>
<P>
   Three giant advertising agency companies _ the Interpublic
Group, Grey Advertising and Leo Burnett _ are expanding operations
in interactive marketing and media services. Stuart Elliott:
Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   RARE PRAISE FOR A STATE REGULATOR
</P>
<P>
   Procedures used by the New York State Public Service Commission
to open the local phone market to competition have won praise and
could become a model for other states.
</P>
</TEXT>
