<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN ARMY IS SOPHISTICATED FIGHTING FORCE WITH HIGH MORALE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In Iraq, the bombing in December lasted four days.
In Bosnia in 1994, airstrikes took a little more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   But this is neither Iraq nor Bosnia. And in the coming days of
Operation Allied Force, military officials said Wednesday, NATO
should not expect a hasty retreat by the Yugoslav Army, which is
fiercely determined to win and better equipped to shoot down planes
than any force the United States has faced in years.
</P>
<P>
   Intense midair sparring took place almost immediately after the
airstrikes began Wednesday, as NATO jets shot down three Serb
planes, according to a US defense official. Two US planes and a
Dutch F-16 fighter jet were responsible for the scores, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that success, military officials noted the unique
dangers of the Balkan terrain and sought to prepare the public for
the worst. Defense Secretary William S. Cohen stressed at a
briefing that the Serb military has an ``extensive air defense
system.'' Army General Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, reiterated, ``There is no such thing as a
risk-free military operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although at this point we have no casualties to US or NATO
forces, we continue to take all measures to reduce the risk to our
pilots and air crews,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the term ``airstrike'' has come to imply
relatively low potential for loss of life, particularly after
repeated successful air raids in Iraq. But in Yugoslavia, where the
defenses against air attacks include more than 150 surface-to-air
missiles and a frequent shield of clouds and fog, air attacks might
face challenges never seen in the deserts around Baghdad. Even
without sending in ground troops, which NATO has insisted it will
not do, this mission could be the most dangerous the organization
has faced, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian ``air defense system is both more mobile and more
practiced than anything the Iraqis have been able to mount,'' said
retired Army Colonel Dan Smith, now an analyst in Washington. ``For
low-flying aircraft, there is a much greater possibility of being
brought down. So it's a very difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, NATO forces are devoting the first part of the
mission to destroying Serbian antiaircraft equipment, clearing the
way for lower-flying planes to follow up in the days to come. Their
targets are formidable, say military officials: at least two dozen
SA-6 surface-to-air missile systems scattered over Yugoslavia, as
well as another three dozen less sophisticated SA-2 and SA-3
antiaircraft batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The antiaircraft batteries, produced in the former Soviet Union
and East Germany, are more capable than anything Air Force fighters
faced in Iraq, analysts said. Each can hold between 15 and 30
missiles, and many of them are mobile, creating a sea of movable
targets that NATO planes could have a difficult time dodging or
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Serb soldiers are also equipped with hundreds of
shoulder-launched air defense missiles. In the air, analysts said,
the Yugoslav military has about 15,000 troops prepared to fly about
780 planes, although analysts say only a dozen of those jets are as
sophisticated as the US jets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Yugoslav troops, despite a steady state of war in
the Balkans, have not seen their equipment decimated as Saddam
Hussein has in Iraq. Any comparison to Operation Desert Fox in 1998
is ``completely erroneous,'' said one military analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pfaltzgraff, a professor of international security at the
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, agreed
and said this is ``different in a number of ways from Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Desert Fox, we were mounting attacks against fixed
facilities, military bases, headquarters for Republican guards.
They were targets you could find,'' he said. ``The Serbs have far
more advanced systems. They are more capable of shooting down
aircraft. They have a capability _ in terms of interception, radar,
target identification _ far superior to anything Saddam had. This
will be a more difficult task.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
