<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATIONS-NYT &LR;      03-24 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN ENDORSES NATO AIRSTRIKES, WITH ONE RESERVATION
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV,
KOSOVO-STEALTH, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(wg) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With an important reservation, Secretary
General Kofi Annan effectively endorsed the NATO airstrikes against
Yugoslavia on Wednesday, blaming Yugoslavia's persistent rejection
of a political settlement for the resort to force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret that, in spite of all the efforts made by the
international community, the Yugoslav authorities have persisted in
their rejection of a political settlement, which would have halted
the bloodshed in Kosovo and secured an equitable peace for the
population there,'' Annan said two hours after NATO began striking
targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indeed tragic that diplomacy has failed, but there are
times when the use of force may be legitimate in the pursuit of
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Annan implicitly reprimanded NATO for having
acted without Security Council authorization, reiterating his view
that while the United Nations charter gives ``an important role to
regional organizations,'' such as NATO, the council ``should be
involved in any decision to resort to the use of force.''
</P>
<P>
   But Annan's reiteration of this principle of international world
governance came only after his criticism of Yugoslavia and his
resigned conclusion that force is sometimes necessary in restoring
or preserving peace. The order of his statements alone was
interpreted both by his aides and fellow diplomats here as a
cautious blessing of NATO's decision to use force and Washington's
insistence that the force was legal and legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Security Council debate, which lasted more than two
hours, reflected what has become an increasingly persistent
division among the five permanent members of the 15-member council
_ with the United States, Britain, and France, all NATO members,
defending military action as essential to prevent an even broader
catastrophe, and Russia and China condemning it as illegal and
destabilizing to world security.
</P>
<P>
   Given the division within the council, no resolution was
expected to be adopted, and none was.
</P>
<P>
   In demanding an immediate halt to the military strikes, Sergey
Lavrov, Russia's representative to the United Nations, said that
Russia would recall its military representative to NATO, suspend
its participation in the Partnership for Peace, the program linking
NATO and Russia, and postpone talks on the opening of a NATO
military liaison office in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Lavrov called the military strikes ``an attempt by NATO to enter
the 21st century in a uniform of global policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burleigh, the American representative, argued that force
was needed to prevent ``a humanitarian catastrophe of immense
proportions,'' and that NATO had been forced to act, ``with the
greatest reluctance,'' by the failure of months of peaceful
mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat and seasoned veteran of U.N. debates said that
Russia's attack on the United States and NATO on Wednesday marked
the effective end of an era on the Security Council _ the 11 years
in which the five permanent council members managed to resolve some
pressing threats to international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
   David Malone, the president of the International Peace Academy,
a private, independent group that studies the United Nations,
called Annan's statement ``sober and responsible,'' but also a
``justified departure'' from tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant that he signaled that the use of force can
sometimes be necessary with, or, by implication, in extreme
circumstances, without the authorization of the Security Council,''
Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   But Vladislav Jovanovic, Yugoslavia's envoy to the United
Nations, was obviously displeased. Speaking to reporters before the
council debate, he lashed out at both the Security Council and
Annan for failing to criticize NATO's ``aggressive'' attack on his
country.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at NATO headquarters last January, Annan signaled
his growing frustration with Serbia's violations of human rights in
Kosovo and its staunch rejection of mediation efforts. Warning that
human rights in Kosovo were being callously violated, Annan warned
that ``we may be reaching the limit, once again, in the former
Yugoslavia'' of diplomacy and political mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's delegate, called the debate on
Wednesday ``predictable'' given the council's division, but added
that a majority of member states appeared to support the NATO
action. Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would be able to take
``little comfort'' from Wednesday's session, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
