<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3162 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      03-24 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US-led NATO forces Wednesday unleashed a battery of
cruise missiles and bombs aimed at Serbian military targets in
Yugoslavia, plunging America into a military conflict that
President Clinton said was necessary to stop ethnic cleansing and
bring stability to Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have acted with resolve,'' Clinton said Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night in
a 13-minute televised address. ``By acting, we are upholding our
values, protecting our interests, and advancing the cause of
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the Oval Office and using a map of the region to
make his point, Clinton asked, ``Do our interests in Kosovo justify
the dangers to our armed forces? I thought long and hard about that
question. I am convinced that the dangers of acting are far
outweighed by the dangers of not acting.''
</P>
<P>
   Using dozens of cruise missiles, an array of fighter-bombers and
for the first time ever, two Air Force B-2 Stealth bombers, the
strikes were aimed at Yugoslavia's air defense network. They were
designed to force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt a
Serb offensive in Kosovo and to accept a peace deal for the
southern Yugoslav province, where ethnic Albanians are fighting for
their independence.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO attack followed months of diplomacy that failed to end
a year of fighting between Yugoslav forces and the separatists.
More than 2,000 people have been killed and over 400,000 left
homeless in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are resisting Kosovar Albanian demands for
independence because they consider Kosovo part of their religious
and historical homeland.
</P>
<P>
   At a late afternoon briefing Wednesday, Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen said all NATO planes returned safely to their
bases after the intitial wave of strikes. Other Pentagon sources
said two Yugoslav planes were hit, including a MIG-29 jet.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman in Naples denied a Yugoslav media report that a
NATO plane had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the attacks had three objectives: to demonstrate
the seriousness of NATO's opposition to Serb aggression; to deter
``an even bloodier offensive against innocent'' ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo; and ``seriously damage'' Serbia's military capacity. The
Yugoslavia government issued a declaration of war after NATO
attacked targets from Belgrade to Pristina. The declaration from
the official Yugoslav news agency Tanjug did not specify who had
made it or what its consequences would be.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which opposes the airstrikes, responded by pulling out
of the NATO Partnership for Peace, an informal alliance between
Russia and the West, and recalled its representative at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The successive waves of strikes pummeled army barracks, power
plants, and air defense batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Army General Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said NATO'S objectives were clear: ``Our actions are
designed to reduce the ability of the Serbian military forces to
continue their offensive operations against the people of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Clinton said that the Serbian leader's
hard-line stance violated his commitment last fall to stop the
repression of the Kosovars, and that Milosevic also had spurned
repeated efforts to resolve the crisis diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   He said Milosevic was a ``dictator'' continuing his aggression
against the Kosovars, ``moving from village to village, shelling
civilians and torching their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``In short, if President Milosevic will not make peace,
we will limit his ability to make war.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, explosions rocked Pristina, Kosovo's capital,
as well as a big Serb military base and airport at Batajnica, the
largest military installation near the Yugoslav capital of
Belgrade. Air raid sirens filled the air in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon dismissed rumors that American troops in Bosnia had
received threats from Serbian authorities in Belgrade. ``I haven't
heard anything about that,'' said Lieutenant Colonel Steven
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   US officials promised that the bombing campaign would be heavy
and severe. ``This is not a pinprick,'' one top Clinton
administration official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Once strikes were launched, support from congressional leaders
came quickly, even if there were some reservations. A few hours
later, the House voted 424-1 to voice its support for US troops
without expressly embracing Clinton's decision to send them.
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott said, ``Whatever reservations
about the president's actions in the Balkans, let no one doubt that
the Congress and the American people stand united behind our men
and women who are bravely heeding the call of duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Charles Bass, Republican of New Hampshire, said,
``I remain concerned about the Clinton administration's policy in
Kosovo, especially if the president still intends to deploy US
ground troops in any future peacekeeping mission.'' Bass also
faulted the president for failing to explain how to successfully
conclude the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   House minority leader Richard Gephardt, however, was
unequivocal. ``In the face of a Serbian military offensive against
the people of Kosovo, NATO had no choice but to deter this
aggression and prevent the slaughter of innocent civilians,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton spent 35 minutes in a ``frank and
honest exchange of views'' with Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin,
according to a White House official. Clinton once again laid out
the case for NATO strikes in the face of Milosevic's refusal to
sign the peace accords, while Yeltsin expressed Russia's long-held
opposition to any use of force against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton also made
clear to Yeltsin that the United States and Russia should not allow
Milosevic ``to drive a wedge'' between them.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to shore up faltering US-Russian relations, however,
failed. After the strikes were launched, Yeltsin said he was
``deeply shocked,'' and he rejected the military action as
``outright aggression against Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia reserves the right to take adequate measures including
those of a military character to ensure Russia's safety,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, in a dramatic show of disapproval, Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov turned his plane around in midair over
the Atlantic, postponing his Washington visit indefinitely. Russia
severed links with NATO Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the United Nations Security Council met behind closed
doors for an emergency meeting called by Russia, Secretary General
Kofi Annan stated his support for NATO's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indeed tragic that diplomacy has failed. But there are
times when the use of force may be legitimate in the pursuit of
peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright spent the day calling
her international counterparts, making the case that ``a
humanitarian crisis of staggering dimensions'' was unfolding, said
James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said NATO forces were preparing for the possiblity that
Milosevic would retaliate beyond the borders or Kosovo _ or
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, he said, was ``formulating detailed plans for reacting''
to possible scenarios for Serbian aggression in the face of
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns that the war could spill over Kosovo's
borders and that NATO troops in Macedonia were vulnerable, Rubin
said, ``The authorities in Belgrade should be aware that we will
not tolerate attacks on Americans in Serbia, Yugoslavia, or
neighboring countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton canceled a three-day swing to Ohio, Nevada and
California that was to begin Thursday to raise money for the
Democrats. Instead, he will remain in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After the first wave of bombing started, Clinton made a hastily
arranged appearance in the White House briefing room to make the
announcement. The president said he had consulted with world
leaders and key members of Congress about the military action and
acknowledged it ``is not risk free.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, with the map as a backdrop, he warned, ``Let a
fire burn in this area and the flame will spread.''
</P>
<P>
   He compared the Kosovo situation to the two world wars, saying,
``Europe was slow to recognize the dangers, and the United States
waited even longer'' to enter. In Bosnia, Clinton said, ``The world
did not act early enough to stop that war, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
