</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI RESERVES JUDGMENT ON POLICE COMMISSIONER'S TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday that he
expected Police Commissioner Howard Safir to keep his job, but that
he would await the outcome of an ethics investigation into Safir's
trip last weekend to the Academy Awards ceremony, as a guest of a
Revlon executive, before passing judgment on it.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor said the commissioner ``is doing an excellent
job,'' he would not comment on whether the trip was appropriate,
and skipped the opportunity to offer detailed or enthusiastic
praise of Safir's leadership, as he did just days ago in response
to a call for the commissioner's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, people who have been informed of the plans for the
commissioner's trip said that he originally planned to return on
Revlon's corporate jet on Monday, which would have made him miss a
City Council hearing spawned by last month's fatal police shooting
of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir returned instead on Sunday night, paying his own fare
for a red-eye flight and turning up at the City Hall hearing on
Monday. Safir's spokeswoman said he came back sooner because of
progress in negotiations with the City Council over the scope of
his testimony, and not _ as his critics had speculated _ because
Channel 2 news in New York ran footage of him at the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the free flight, $700-a-night hotel suite and tickets
to the Oscars does not appear to violate the city's ethics rules
because Revlon does not have pending business with the city. But
the trip, coming amid the biggest crisis of Safir's tenure, has
raised questions about his political judgment. A similar
controversy over gifts of expensive travel was part of what ended
the reign of his predecessor, William Bratton.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Edward Koch, who has criticized the
administration's response to the shooting, called the
commissioner's trip ``just plain stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's looking at them because of the Diallo case,'' said
Koch. ``It's certainly one of the most foolish things I've seen a
commissioner do, because it's so obviously wrong, it's so obviously
public, and it's so obviously going to come back to haunt him.''
</P>
<P>
   The stickiest point for Safir may turn out to be not who paid
for his weekend out west, but how it affected his appearance Monday
at the City Council hearing, and whether his aides were honest in
discussing it.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 12 letter to the mayor indicating he would be out of
town, Safir said he would not return until 6 p.m. Monday, long
after the 10 a.m. hearing. Marilyn Mode, Safir's spokeswoman, said
Wednesday that the commissioner did not plan, at that point, to
testify because he and the Council could not agree on ground rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mode said Wednesday that Safir decided on Saturday that
``there was hope that an agreement would be reached,'' and bought
an airline ticket to get him back in time to attend the hearing.
But that conflicts with a statement made on Sunday by First Deputy
Commissioner Patrick Kelleher that Safir would not attend the
hearing because of ``several important, long-scheduled meetings,''
as well as with accounts by both people involved in the trip and
the City Council hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Several City Council aides involved in the negotiations over the
commissioner's attendance said they did not hear of his change of
heart until 8 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would go to the Oscars, with parties after the Oscars, and
still plan to be in New York City at 9 o'clock?'' said Councilman
Sheldon Leffler, who presided over the hearing. ``It defied logic
to believe he really tried to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leffler noted that Safir declared in 1997 that members of the
Police Department would be dismissed for making false official
statements. ``This is inappropriate leadership,'' he said. ``Other
officers who are going to be in tight spots are going to say to
themselves, `You can make false statements, Safir himself did
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Davies, executive director of the city's Conflicts of
Interest Board, would not comment directly on Safir's trip, but he
said there were three broad prohibitions on public officials'
accepting gifts. City employees cannot take anything worth more
than $50 from a person or firm doing business with the city, even
routine matters like applying for building permits or zoning
variances. Employees are also barred from using their jobs for
public gain, and thus should not accept gifts that are only offered
because of their job, Davies said. Finally, there is a ``catchall
prohibition'' outlawing ``any action that's in conflict with your
official duties,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would also apply to accepting something when it looks
bad,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir maintained that there was nothing improper about his
cross-country jaunt with his wife, Carol, because it was paid for
by George Fellows, Revlon's chief executive, whom he described as a
friend who ``doesn't have any dealings with the city.'' Safir did
not ask the ethics board to approve the trip before he went, but
requested the investigation by the corporation counsel after
criticism was raised in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hess, the corporation counsel, said he would conduct a
broad review of all ethical issues raised by the trip, and was
unsure how long it would take. While officials said Revlon had no
pending city business, the company has a close relationship with
the Police Department; its security chief is Safir's former top
deputy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
