<HEADLINE>
QUOTATION OF THE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This quotation refers to BC-KOSOVO-RDP-NYT, which moved in
``i'' news file.) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Inaction in the face of brutality simply invites more
brutality, but firmness can stop armies and save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   -PRESIDENT CLINTON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-24 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FROM PALMER TO TORRE, BE PATIENT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the New York Yankees' dugout last season, Joe Torre was
talking about his daughter, Andrea Rae, then 2{ years old, who
earlier that day had been acting like, well, a 2{-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali,'' the Yankee manager said, referring to his wife, ``kept
telling her: `Andrea, I've lost my patience with you. I've lost my
patience with you.' About five minutes later, Andrea walked over to
her and said, `Mommy, I've found your patience.'''
</P>
<P>
   From the mouths of babes. Because now, a week after Torre's
prostate cancer surgery, even if the 58-year-old Yankee manager
should lose his patience during his estimated 6 to 12 weeks of
recuperation, he knows Andrea Rae will find it.
</P>
<P>
   And according to someone who would know, Arnold Palmer, the
golfer who is perhaps the world's most famous prostate cancer
patient, Torre needs to be a patient patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's different,'' Palmer said Wednesday from his office
at the Bay Hill Club and Lodge in Orlando, Fla., ``but I think the
major advice anybody who's had this would give Joe is, just take it
easy and do what the doctors prescribe. That's all I tried to do.
Keep up with what they tell you to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer learned he had prostate cancer in January 1997. Within
days, he had surgery at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctors told me to rest, to not do anything,'' he recalled.
``Give your body a chance to heal. When you feel like you're strong
enough, start walking as much as you can. We have a three-mile
track around the golf course here that I walked. I was out walking
and putting golf balls in about two weeks, but nothing strenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing as strenuous as swinging his driver, as only he can
swing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do that for eight weeks,'' Palmer said, laughing.
``For me, everything was based on eight weeks because I wanted to
play in my tournament here at Bay Hill that March, eight weeks
after my surgery, and I was able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, then 67, also played in that year's Masters and in 13
events on the Senior PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could say anyone is going to recover in any
specific period of time,'' he said, ``but for me everything was
based on eight weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Did that mean Joe Torre could be back in the Yankee dugout in
eight weeks?
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be able to do it prior to that actually,'' Palmer
said. ``As long as he doesn't have to strain or get himself in a
dither.''
</P>
<P>
   Working for George Steinbrenner, it was suggested, every Yankee
manager has often been in a dither. Palmer laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Yankees are playing good, Joe would probably have no
problems,'' he said. ``If the Yankees are having problems, he might
have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre is recuperating at his spring training home near the
Yankee complex in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me there was still some pain a week later,'' Palmer said,
``but you're given medication to take care of that. The thing you
notice most is the inconvenience of the operation. Getting the
stitches out, the other things involved.''
</P>
<P>
   More than two years after his surgery, Palmer shot 78-74 last
week in the Bay Hill Invitational and will tee off in the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very fortunate; I feel very good,'' he said. ``About a
year and a half after the surgery, my doctor decided I should have
radiation, which I have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, whose wife, Winnie, is dealing with breast cancer,
completed his radiation treatments in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in radiation, you stay away from too many fruits
and vegetables, but I'm past that,'' Palmer said. ``The radiation
sets you back a little, but its effect is mostly inconvenience,
that's all. I'm not on any medication. I'm exercising every day. I
stretch. I do leg work and arm-and-shoulder work with weights. I
feel very close to back to normal, or at least I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   And at Bay Hill he is playing golf virtually every day, as he
always has except for those weeks after his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing the doctors tell you was give yourself a
chance to get your strength back,'' Palmer said. ``Don't try to
overdo it. Don't try to go too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Joe Torre needs to be a patient patient.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankee manager knows that if he does happen to lose his
patience, little Andrea Rae will know where to find it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
