u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-HAMILTON-86     03-24 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-HAMILTON-860&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COMPLETE RICHARD HAMILTON: FAST FEET, DEEP THOUGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward Hamilton was a steel worker who knew how to handle a pool
stick. His grandson Richard knew how to handle a basketball.
Neither would talk about his gifts much, especially last summer
when the two would sit together in front of the television
wondering what the fall would bring.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton was worried about the foot he had broken in
July at the USA Basketball tryouts for the World Championships. The
broken foot, in which a screw was implanted, kept him from
traveling on a tour with his Connecticut teammates. It put him in
the TV room of his grandfather's house on the hill in Coatesville,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Edward was worried, too. He was battling lung cancer _ and
losing, as a series of scars from surgery attested.
</P>
<P>
   Neither wanted to talk basketball. Both ignored the clippings
and the photographs taped to the walls that chronicled Richard's
climb from skinny, junior high school player to Big East Player of
the Year, an honor he had earned a few months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   They just talked. About their surgeries. About what they wanted
for lunch. About how nothing they did before or would do in the
future mattered, unless they had fun doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't about what was said,'' Hamilton said recently. ``It
was just being together. It taught me to not always take things for
granted. It was a messed-up time, and being with him is the best
thing that could have happened for both of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned was when I got back to school I wanted to make
the year an experience of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an experience of a lifetime for Hamilton, one that
has been emotional and far from storybook. Edward Hamilton died in
October. And Richard cried.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday in Phoenix, he scored 21 points to lead
Connecticut over Gonzaga in the West Regional final and to the
school's first Final Four appearance. He cried there, too.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he tentatively came back from the foot injury and
pushed UConn to the No. 1 ranking, which it held for 10 weeks. He
then sustained a thigh injury that his coach, Jim Calhoun,
challenged him to fight through.
</P>
<P>
   He did _ well enough to be named an all-American and conference
co-player of the year and to carry the Huskies to their fifth Big
East title in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people mistake how laid back he is for a lack of
strength,'' said his father, also named Richard. ``My father _ his
grandfather _ was like that. He was a great pool player, but even
my mother didn't know it because he never talked about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run and lift weights with him in the summer,'' the older
Hamilton said about his son. ``I see how dedicated and tough he is.
He just doesn't need to talk about it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the NCAA tournament, the son has averaged 23.5 points a game
and has demonstrated a willingness to play defense that few knew he
had. He has also renewed a two-part debate: Will he enter the NBA
draft after this, his junior year? And, at 6 feet 6 inches and 185
pounds, can his greyhoundlike frame and sensitive soul make an
impact in the wide-bodied, cold-hearted NBA.?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rip has shown me something that I knew but needed to have
reaffirmed,'' Calhoun said, referring to Hamilton by his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a greater appreciation for him being one of the best
players in college basketball. You think he can't go by you because
he's not that quick. You think he can't get nine rebounds, but he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   During Hamilton's three years at Connecticut, Calhoun has
alternately boasted about him and browbeaten him. He has been
dazzled and, a few times, discouraged by him. Before the season,
Calhoun told Hamilton that the Huskies were the forward's team,
that he was special in a way only a few of his former players have
been _ players like Connecticut's Ray Allen and the late Reggie
Lewis, whom he coached at Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   But when Hamilton suffered a thigh contusion in late January
against St. John's and missed the next two games, Calhoun directed
his blunt talk at his star. Without Hamilton, the Huskies lost
their first game, to Syracuse. The coach sounded exasperated when
he repeatedly had to announce that Hamilton's condition was day to
day.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun now says that ``coddling and loving'' Hamilton was as
much a part as pushing him to return. But Calhoun challenged his
star's toughness because the Huskies needed him back if they wanted
to reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun admits to having an easier rapport with Khalid El-Amin,
the brassy, bowling-ball shaped point guard who, like the coach
himself, leads with his lip. El-Amin has felt Calhoun's wrath on
the floor, exchanged good-natured barbs off it and has sat in
Calhoun's office to talk about subjects far afield from basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khalid is like talking to a 30-year-old,'' Calhoun said,
explaining how he has related differently to Hamilton. ``Rip is
different. He's 100 percent in tune with the world but at the same
time has this ability to be insulated from it, and that, I believe,
comes from his parents. He comes from a very strong family that has
put all its effort into raising a good kid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Rip was born, his father claims, he was 31 inches long _
about a foot longer than most babies. His father put tiny
basketballs in his crib. When he saw his son go through three
defenders in a seventh-grade game, he bought a video camera the
next day. He has since amassed a tape collection of the more than
400 games his son has played.
</P>
<P>
   But both parents have also taken an intense interest in
Hamilton's education. There were plenty of books around, and Pam
Long, Rip's mother, currently lives in Hartford and is pursuing a
master's degree at Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Both parents counseled him to stay in school last year when he
was projected as a top 15 NBA pick. Richard Hamilton the father
says they probably will vote the same way when it's time to make a
decision about the draft in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always wanted to put him in the right situations, to
make sure that he is a student of all things,'' said the older
Hamilton, who is in the trucking business in Coatesville.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Freeman, Hamilton's roommate, said the toughest part of
the game is the mental part, and Rip works hardest at that. Freeman
said Hamilton watches film of his own performances, trying to
maximize his strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 24-hour thing with him,'' Freeman said of Hamilton.
``He has a game like he did against Gonzaga, where he shut down
their best shooter and still got 21, and he can still find plays
where he missed an open man or something. If he doesn't shoot well,
he'll have trouble sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he cried after the Gonzaga game because he was
overjoyed that after months of working so hard he had earned an
opportunity to play in a Final Four tournament that he had dreamed
about as a little boy. He was sure Edward Hamilton would have
appreciated that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows I'm having fun,'' he said, smiling. ``Like we talked
about.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
