u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RATIONALE-HNS &LR;      03-24 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RATIONALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APPEALS FOR SUPPORT IN EXPLAINING REASONS FOR ATTACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POLITICS and
KOSOVO-CONGRESS.) 
 
(Eds.: the Continent is cq in third graf) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton appealed to the American people
Wednesday for support of NATO airstrikes against Serbian military
forces, insisting that the ethnic killing in Kosovo could erupt
into a wider European war if the United States and its allies fail
to act.
</P>
<P>
   Casting the Kosovo conflict as a repeat of the brutal aggression
that preceded the first two world wars, Clinton said NATO's
post-Cold War defensive role in the world must evolve into an
offensive one to ensure that Europe remains stable and undivided.
</P>
<P>
   If it were unwilling to stop massacres of innocent people ``on
NATO's doorstep,'' he said the Western alliance would be of little
use in combating future threats to the stability of the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both wars Europe was slow to recognize the dangers and the
United States waited even longer to enter the conflict,'' the
president said in an address to the nation in which he sought to
lay out his rationale for NATO's first attack on a sovereign
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Taking military action now in the face of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's mounting offensive against Kosovo's
predominantly Albanian population would ``defuse a powder keg at
the heart of Europe that has exploded twice before in this century
with catastrophic results,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By acting now, we are upholding our values, protecting our
interests and advancing the cause of peace,'' the president added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took pains to help Americans understand the strategic
significance of Kosovo, noting that it lies just 160 miles east of
Italy and only 70 miles north of Greece. Using maps to pinpoint the
Serbian province, Clinton stressed that the Serbian offensive in
Kosovo threatens to engulf NATO allies such as Macedonia and other
smaller countries on its border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually,'' he said, ``key U.S. allies could be drawn into a
wider conflict _ a war we would be forced to confront later, only
at a far greater risk and greater cost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let a fire burn in this area and the flame will spread,''
Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
   The president also made the case for NATO airstrikes by painting
in graphic terms the human tragedy of Kosovo. Clinton said
Milosevic's forces had shelled villages and torched homes as
thousands of ethnic Albanians were forced to flee into the
mountains or leave the country entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen innocent people taken from their home, forced to
kneel in the dirt and sprayed with bullets,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a war in the traditional sense. It is an attack by
tanks and artillery on a largely defenseless people, whose leaders
have already agreed to peace. Ending this tragedy is a moral
imperative,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also drew similarities to the war in Bosnia. NATO
intervened there too, but not until after an estimated 250,000
people died at the hands of Milosevic-backed Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world did not act early enough to stop that war either,''
Clinton said, recalling the Serb concentration camps where Bosnian
Muslims and Croats were imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A quarter-of-a-million people killed, not because of anything
they had done but because of who they were. ... This was genocide
in the heart of Europe, not in 1945 but in 1995,'' he said, adding
that Milosevic must be stopped in Kosovo ``before what happened in
Bosnia happens there too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia was an independent nation when NATO intervened to stop
Serb rebels there from trying to reunite the country with
Milosevic's government in Belgrade. The NATO airstrikes were
directed against Serb rebel targets and drew little criticism.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO's assault Wednesday on Yugoslavian forces was roundly
criticized by many in Congress as ``an act of war'' against a
sovereign power that would inevitably lead to protracted U.S.
involvement in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech six hours after the air attacks began, Clinton did
not mention that the NATO operation was the first time in the
alliance's 50-year history that it had attacked a sovereign
country. Instead, he focused on portraying Milosevic as
cold-blooded dictator interested only in expanding his territorial
hold in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic will not make peace, we will limit his
ability to make war,'' Clinton said. Administration officials
conceded that is the primary goal of the NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, Mr. Milosevic will realize that his present course
is self-destructive and unsustainable,'' Clinton said, adding that
if Milosevic accepts the Washington-brokered peace agreement signed
by the Albanians, NATO would help implement it with a peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   But while noting that U.S. troops would take part in a
peacekeeping effort, Clinton stressed that American military
personnel would not become involved in a conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not intend to put our troops in Kosovo to fight a war,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the NATO strikes would likely
continue for several weeks unless Milosevic agrees to return to the
negotiating table. In order to deal with the crisis, Clinton
canceled a scheduled three-day domestic trip, including several
Democratic fund-raisers, to remain in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, Clinton said he was hopeful that by acting now NATO
would bring some measure of stability to the Balkans, and Europe as
a whole, so that Americans do not in the future have to ``cross the
Atlantic to fight another terrible war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we've learned anything from the century drawing to a close,
it is that if America is going to be prosperous and secure, we need
a Europe that is prosperous, secure, undivided and free,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
