u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-PROTESTS-NY     03-24 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-PROTESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS IN POLICE SHOOTING GROW LARGER, AND MORE DIVERSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Sidney Socolar, 75, a retired
biophysics professor, got himself arrested was in the mid-1980s,
when he sat outside Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato's office to protest
America's involvement in El Salvador's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, he stood with his 82-year-old wife in a crush of
demonstrators outside One Police Plaza, awaiting the handcuffs. ``I
am enraged about our mayor's attitude toward civil liberties,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking the door was a group of 17 elderly white women,
including Carolyn Goodman, 83, whose son's murder in Mississippi
was a touchstone for the civil rights movement of the 1960s. Ms.
Goodman was escorted into Police Headquarters to be handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   She was part of the largest and most diverse group to be
arrested in the 12 days of protests against the police shooting of
Amadou Diallo. Among the 212 people taken into custody Wednesday
were 126 members of Jews for Racial and Economic Justice, including
several rabbis, and representatives of three labor unions.
Wednesday's arrests brought the total to 574 for the daily rallies.
</P>
<P>
   So many people were arrested that the police had to book the
protesters in station houses in three different precincts in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters had to wait behind police barricades and be
shepherded inside, 30 at a time. Police officers told them through
megaphones that they would be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd chanted, sang psalms in Hebrew and held up signs that
read ``Stop the Death Squads'' and ``Arrest Giuliani.'' Before
being led inside, Socolar described the day as a ``welcome
resumption'' of the unity between blacks and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, whose political advocacy group National
Action Network has been organizing the daily protests since March
9, proudly noted the diversity of the rally as he stood in the
midst of supporters. ``It robs the mayor of his argument that we're
being divisive,'' he said. ``We've got a lot more diversity here
than the Police Department has.''
</P>
<P>
   He renewed his call for the arrest of the four police officers
from the Street Crime Unit who killed Diallo, an immigrant from
Guinea, on Feb. 4. Diallo was unarmed. A grand jury in the Bronx
finished hearing testimony in the case Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another demonstrator, Dennis Rivera, the president of Local
1199, the National Health and Human Service Employees Union, which
has 150,000 members, said that he came to protest the fact that the
Police Department does not reflect the city's racial mix.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he agreed with the city's public advocate,
Mark Green, that Police Commissioner Howard Safir should resign,
Rivera said, ``I think he demonstrated an awesome lack of
sensitivity, and most likely we need a change of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   He was led inside and arrested along with several other labor
leaders, including Lee Saunders, the trustee in charge of District
Council 37, an umbrella group representing 120,000 city workers;
James H. Butler, the president of Local 420 of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, and Charles
Ensley, the president of Local 371, which represents 15,000 social
workers.
</P>
<P>
   During the protest, Safir was in the auditorium at One Police
Plaza conducting a ceremony to announce the promotion of 64 police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the need to communicate effectively and be
courteous, even when making arrests, he said: ``There's also
nothing wrong occasionally saying, `I am sorry for inconveniencing
you.' That's a decent thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Police Department are planning to hold their
own rally Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a flier posted around police headquarters, James Higgins, a
police union official who is to lead the rally, said that it was
necessary because ``a number of political opportunists have
surfaced to prejudge and crucify cops, all cops.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
