</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STRAWBERRY SHOULD TAKE LONGER VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees were so catatonic they could barely
muster enough energy to toss a ball. Rarely will you ever witness a
more demoralized group of athletes, as well as a very ashen young
general manager named Brian Cashman.
</P>
<P>
   This was the muggy afternoon in Texas last fall when the Yankees
officially learned that their pal Darryl Strawberry had colon
cancer. The tears and the raspy voices were a tribute to the man _
the flawed, comic, multi-journeyed Straw Dog.
</P>
<P>
   Who is to say that the Yankees' prayers, and their intense
get-well greeting in front of every camera, did not help Strawberry
get through his fears, the surgery and the wrenching chemotherapy?
</P>
<P>
   Once Strawberry was revealed to have a somewhat advanced case of
cancer, it is a safe bet that he and every member of the Yankees
would have settled to see him back in uniform, rock-solid, able to
swing a bat, full of Straw-Dog bluster once again.
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, George Steinbrenner committed $2.5 million to
Strawberry for this season. It is reasonable to ask if George would
have been so generous if Darryl were not threatened by cancer, and
if Darryl did not need the money.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is time for Darryl Strawberry to give back a little bit
of the love he was tendered last fall. From his sessions in
battling his addictions, Strawberry knows all about the concept of
gratefulness _ there is a point where you give thanks just for
being here. It's time for Darryl to spread a little of that
gratefulness around.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a distraction this spring, grumbling about minor
details of batting practice, grumbling about his status on opening
day, grumbling about the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Darryl to cut it out. He has come too far from
being the man who had major problems with alcohol and drugs and
taxes and money and family. He has been a mensch ever since George
Steinbrenner took a huge chance on him three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   George warned him that he would be Darryl's worst nightmare if
Strawberry should slip, the right threat to the right man at the
right time. Strawberry has been a mature bench player, an example
to young people until this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl showed signs of straightening out Tuesday night when he
approached Cashman and said he would not act out again. On
Wednesday he hit a home run and had three runs batted in. Thursday
night he is expected to play left field, to show if he can get
around on his 37-year-old legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to prove he can do everything to make the club, and
obviously speaking for him it's a frustrating situation, not
knowing what's going on and competing for a job,'' Cashman said
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He questioned me on what the possibilities are, and I said,
`Right now, I don't know,''' Cashman reported. ``He also asked the
possibilities if he didn't make the club, and I said, `I don't know
that, either.' I said, `You've got to answer one question before
you answer the other.' I said, we need time to basically look and
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   That is reasonable. The Yankees are not paying Strawberry $2.5
million to fail. There may be one frugal corner of George
Steinbrenner's heart that notes it will save him $833,000 in luxury
tax if Strawberry does not play for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But all of us have watched George over the years. He talks
cheap, he bullies, he wheedles _ and then he spends the money for
what he wants, or needs (not always the same, but so what?). If
Darryl can help the Yankees at all, he'll be on the roster, and it
will not be charity.
</P>
<P>
   The nasty incursion of cancer was a cruel blow to Strawberry,
but he could not miss the outpouring of love when he was able to
make an appearance in the World Series celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Straw is also picking the wrong time to act out, while Joe Torre
is recovering from his own surgery for prostate cancer. Torre has
not turned his back on Strawberry, the way some managers do when a
player is not able to perform at his peak. Torre has his own
problems. Strawberry needs to recognize that and not take it out on
Don Zimmer, an older man who is nowhere near the tolerant father
figure and innate psychologist that Torre is.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite possible that Strawberry _ who has his morbid side
and probably always will _ has been suffering through some form of
depression after the latest turn in his life. He's entitled.
</P>
<P>
   It seems rather clear that George Steinbrenner, with all his
flaws, is fairly aching to make Darryl a Yankee for life, in some
capacity or other. Darryl need not grovel, but he needs to remember
the Yankees are not his enemy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
