u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-PURDUE-TEAM-570&AMP;A     03-24 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PURDUE-TEAM-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS AT PURDUE AS FOCUSED AS THEIR COACH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ZACK BURGESS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Off the court, the Purdue players and coaches had been guarded
and almost bland whenever they spoke during the Midwest Regional
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, with Tennessee and Connecticut no longer around,
someone had to live up to the expectations of a No. 1 seeded team,
and Purdue finally had, rallying to defeat Rutgers Monday night to
reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Purdue players had finished cutting down the nets,
and during coach Carolyn Peck's post-game interview, it became
clear that a change _ however subtle _ had occurred. Their
collective sigh of relief was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Peck raised her voice a little and her eyes became larger as she
spoke. She was talking with an emotion in her voice rarely heard.
</P>
<P>
   But her animation just added to the mystery of Purdue and
especially its 33-year-old coach. Who is the person inside the
coach? Is she the woman who always answered with a smile, the one
who gave away no secrets, the one who knew exactly what to say?
</P>
<P>
   Her closed-mouth approach is a reflection of her corporate
background, when she worked as a pharmaceutical sales
representative. She was an assistant under Tennessee's Pat Summitt
for two years before going to Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   She became the Boilermakers' head coach last season when she was
promoted to replace Neil Fortner, who had been named coach of the
USA Basketball women's national team.
</P>
<P>
   Peck will gladly talk about Purdue basketball. She will not
answer questions about her migration this summer to the WNBA, where
she will be the general manager of the expansion Orlando Miracle.
The praise has always gone to her players. For now, Purdue
basketball is her personality.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the personality of her players. When any of Purdue's
outstanding guard combination of Ukari Figgs, Stephanie
White-McCarty and Katie Douglas talks, they also follow the company
line. They will only talk about ``the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing unusual,'' Stephanie White-McCarty said. ``It's
what she has instilled in us as a coach. We know that we wouldn't
be in this position if it didn't take a team effort. It took
everyone to get here. It would be unfair for one or two people to
take the credit. That's what we've learned from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Peck was asked about how she felt about making it to
the Final Four, she responded: ``I want to play our last ball game
the very best that we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers this weekend will take on Louisiana Tech, a
quick and extremely athletic team that has the ability to shoot the
jump shot as well as score in the low post. With forward Monica
Maxwell and junior college transfer Betty Lennox leading the way
for Louisiana Tech , they will be looking to avenge a 71-65 loss to
Purdue in late December. It was the last time the Lady Techsters
(30-2) lost this season.
</P>
<P>
   While Louisiana Tech (30-2) has been a staple in the women's
Final Four, this is only Purdue's second visit, with its first
coming in 1994. This time, it is ranked No. 1 and riding a 30-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Making this trip even more special is that Peck, Figgs and
White-McCarty will be moving on once their quest for the title is
finished. ``I think the whole season has been special,''
White-McCarty said. ``It's not that just coach Peck is not going to
be here. Were not going to have this team ever again. We realize
that. We want to make the most of the opportunities we have with
this team.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For most of the year, Figgs and White-McCarty have been the two
players who have led this well-balanced Purdue team. White-McCarty
has averaged 18 points a game in the tournament while Figgs has
contributed 16.5.
</P>
<P>
   But Purdue's role players _ 6-foot-4 center Camille Cooper, who
scored 20 points against Rutgers, guard Katie Douglas and forward
Michelle Duhart _ are major contributors to a Purdue team that has
won its tournament games by an average score of 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at Stephanie White-McCarty _ she breathes life
into death,'' Rutgers coach C.Vivian Stringer said. ``By that I
mean that a shot could be dead and you think she has stopped.
Everything seems to be stuck. And somehow she's able to pull the
ball through and see light. The offense is not done until the ball
actually is out of her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then it's on to the next person. It doesn't matter whether
you're in a zone or man defense, this team is complete. They can do
a lot of damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
