<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATING-CHAMPIONSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS WIN GOLD IN PAIRS, AILING KWAN LEADS QUALIFYING AT WORLD
CHAMPIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ If the crowd in Hartwell arena had been
scoring the pairs competition at the world figure skating
championships Wednesday night, there is no doubt who would have had
the highest marks: Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo of China.
</P>
<P>
   The nine judges in Hartwell took a different view, awarding the
gold to the defending world champions, Yelena Berezhnaya and Anton
Sikharulidze of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the final results flashed on the scoreboard, there
were whistles and boos from spectators who had watched Berezhnaya
tumble after misjudging a double axel and had seen the Chinese
skate a clean and technically superior program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, we tried to skate easy and beautiful and patient, and
I think we did it,'' Sikharulidze said
</P>
<P>
   The judges agreed, and though eight of the nine gave the Chinese
higher marks for technical merit, eight of the nine gave the
Russians higher marks for presentation. (They received 5.9s across
the board.) Because the presentation mark is the tie breaker,
China's first world championship medal in pairs turned out to be a
silver, not a gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to win the championship, but also wanted to
perform our best,'' Zhao said through a translator. ``We think we
succeeded in the second case.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland also won its first medal in pairs at a world
championships when Dorota Zagorska and Mariusz Siudek took the
bronze.
</P>
<P>
   The new American team of Kyoko Ina and John Zimmerman finished
ninth. The brother and sister team of Danielle and Steve Hartsell
placed 10th. Laura Handy and Paul Binnebose, the third American
team, withdrew because Binnebose has been unable to shake the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Kwan, the favorite in the women's event, has also been
ill this week and is being treated with antibiotics for a severe
head cold. Asked to rate her level of fitness, Kwan said ``85
percent.'' But the reigning world champion won her group easily in
Wednesday's qualifying round, which for the first time counts for
20 percent of the final score.
</P>
<P>
   She was not at her sharpest or most confident, downgrading a
triple lutz to a double, but she landed six other triples. Though
she received one 5.5 for technical merit from the Slovak judge and
a 5.6 for presentation from the Finnish judge, she was still a
great deal more impressive than her rival Maria Butyrskaya of
Russia, who won the other qualifying group despite a painful fall
on a triple salchow and several other errors.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Hughes, the 13-year-old from Great Neck, New York, in her
first world championships, placed fourth in Kwan's group despite
falling on a triple flip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different than what I thought it would be,'' said Hughes,
who will now skate in the second-to-last group in Friday's short
program. ``I just went out there and when I was taking my position,
I said to myself that this might be my only chance to be at worlds.
I definitely had my four minutes of enjoyment.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3185 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-HNS &LR;      03-24 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO-CONGRESS.) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
B-2s MAKE COMBAT DEBUT DURING YUGOSLAV ATTACK 
 
(See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-POLITICS, KOSOVO-RATIONALE andBy JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The B-2 stealth bomber made its combat debut
Wednesday as part of an 11-nation armada of air and missile power
that lit up the night skies over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bombs from two B-2s and cruise missiles from a half-dozen B-52
bombers and several U.S. and British warships began hitting
Yugoslav military barracks, air defense units and power plants
shortly after sunset in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials reported no U.S. casualties and no loss of
aircraft by any of the NATO-member nations. Officials denied a
Yugoslav media report that a NATO aircraft had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   A Defense Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said two Yugoslav MiG-29 fighters had been knocked from
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said NATO planes had
encountered aircraft from the Yugoslav Air Force, but he gave no
details. ``There was some air-to-air engagement that has taken
place. But I think we need more information before we can confirm
what the result of that was,'' he said. ``Our aircraft have safely
returned _ those that were in the region to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cohen and other U.S. officials said it was too early to
provide an accurate assessment of damage from the satellite-guided
bombs and missiles, a Yugoslav military leader told reporters that
more than 40 targets were hit in the first wave of attacks. Lt.
Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic, commander of Yugoslav troops in Kosovo,
claimed that damage was ``minimal.'' Televised reports from Serbia
showed buildings engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to say how many of the 400 NATO aircraft in
the region participated in the attack. At the same time, U.S.
officials stressed that no ground troops were being deployed except
to rescue downed NATO fliers if their aircraft crash in enemy
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of explosions were heard near the Kosovo capital of
Pristina, which was plunged into darkness when a power plant was
hit, and near Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital. The official Tanjug
news agency reported Pristina's airport had been hit by bombs or
missiles and an army barracks in Danilovgrad had been set ablaze
during the initial attack. The agency reported that civilians,
including the families of military personnel, had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Except to say the B-2s had acquitted themselves well on their
first combat sorties, Pentagon officials provided few details of
their flights from Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri, across
parts of two continents and an ocean to drop a total of 32
satellite-guided bombs, each 2,000 pounds, before returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft performed according to its capabilities,'' said
Cohen, who as a Republican senator from Maine in the 1980s likened
using the $2 billion, bat-winged B-2 in battle to sending a
Rolls-Royce on a grocery-run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stealthy aircraft that can fly in all weather with
considerable ordnance aboard,'' Cohen told reporters Wednesday at a
Pentagon briefing. ``So we are satisfied it was able to conduct
itself and carry out its mission accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   First seen by the public in November 1988, the B-2 has been
plagued by a radar system that has trouble distinguishing mountain
ranges from clouds, radar-absorbent paint that wears off too
quickly, wing skins that developed holes, and ejection seats that
did not work properly. The aircraft did not become operational
until 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A senior defense official said the B-2 was picked for
Wednesday's mission, which involved several midair refuelings,
because it carries 16 bombs, each weighing a ton, and can attack
several targets.
</P>
<P>
   The two B-2s were only a fraction of the firepower thrown
against Serbian military targets.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials said about 100 Tomahawk cruise missiles were
launched from U.S. ships based in the Mediterranean and Adriatic
seas. Six U.S. warships, a cruiser, three destroyers and two
submarines, all armed with Tomahawks, are cruising within range of
Yugoslavia. Also in the fleet is a British submarine equipped with
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate count of the missiles launched from the
six B-52 bombers flying from an air base in England. Each B-52 can
carry 20 cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   As the air campaign progresses, 12 of the Air Force's F-117
fighters, armed with two laser-guided bombs each, are likely to be
used when skies are clear over Yugoslavia. The accuracy of the
F-117's weapons are hampered in cloudy weather.
</P>
<P>
   Once satisfied that Yugoslav air defenses have been sufficiently
damaged, NATO is expected to dispatch a variety of aircraft,
including U.S. and allied F-16s and American F-15s, to attack
weapons depots and Serb troop concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   Army Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the military Joint Chiefs
of Staff, cautioned that NATO casualties are likely as the attacks
continue.
</P>
<P>
   A cornerstone of the Serbian military, Europe's ninth-largest,
is the air defense system, which Shelton described as well-equipped
and well-coordinated. He said that once low-level attacks begin,
the air defenses pose their greatest threat. Allied pilots must fly
low when late winter clouds obscure targets, many of them in
mountainous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although at this point we have no casualties to U.S. or NATO
forces, we continue to take all measures to reduce the risk to our
pilots and air crews,'' Shelton said. ``But there is no such thing
as a risk-free military operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs most effective air defense weapon, which officials say
was not used extensively Wednesday, is the Soviet-made SA-6
anti-aircraft missiles. They are highly mobile. Less mobile
components include the Soviet-made SA-2s and SA-3 anti-aircraft
missiles. The Serbs also have dozens of shoulder-fired missiles
similar to U.S. Stingers, a weapon most useful against low-flying
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Air Force, consisting mainly of old Soviet planes
and about 15 newer MiG-29s, is not considered a major concern.
</P>
<P>
   Administrations officials took great pains Wednesday to say that
no troops would be put on the ground in Serbia except as a
peacekeeping force accepted by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking about ground forces in anything but a
permissive environment,'' said Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. ``We have no plans to have American ground forces in a
non-permissive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen gave a similar answer when pressed about the possible use
of soldiers from the United States or other NATO countries. ``What
we have indicted to the Congress and to the country is that this
is an air operation campaign,'' Cohen told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cohen acknowledged, elite Air Force teams have
been assigned to the region to rescue any U.S. fliers downed in the
combat zone. However, he stressed, no U.S. ground troops would be
used in offensive action against the Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   The teams will be drawn from 150 air commandos, parachutists and
other personnel from the 16th Special Operations Group in Florida
assembled at a military base in southern Italy, about 200 miles
from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue teams reach their targets aboard all-weather MH-53J
Pave Low III helicopters and MH-60K Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
