<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-WATER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SPEEDWAY GM DENIES WATER PROBLEMS AT TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Eddie Gossage says there are no problems
with water ``weeping'' through the pavement anywhere at Texas Motor
Speedway, a rumor that surfaced in the garage area at Darlington
(S.C.) Raceway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no weeping in Turn 3. There's no real exciting story
here,'' said Gossage, executive vice president and general manager
of TMS. ``All I've got to say is: `Ask me Sunday evening.' It's
frustrating, but we'll go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage was referring to a published report in which NASCAR
Winston Cup driver Ken Schrader and Winston Cup crew chief Jeff
Hammond cited possible drainage problems at TMS. The track had a
new drainage system installed last April and May as part of a $3
million reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said he spoke with longtime friend Hammond yesterday,
the eve of qualifying for the NASCAR Busch Grand National Coca-Cola
300 on Saturday. Qualifying for Sunday's NASCAR Winston Cup
Primestar 500 is scheduled for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Jeff and said, `Where did this come from?''' Gossage
said. ``He told me he was repeating a rumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, crew chief for Chad Little at Roush Racing, said the
rumor was circulating through the garage area at Darlington Raceway
during the TranSouth Financial 400. The rumor apparently picked up
momentum during a 2-hour, 47-minute rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it was somebody trying to get something started,''
Hammond said from Charlotte, N.C. ``But it had gotten to three or
four different people. I didn't say it was a fact. I said, `Rumor
has it.' From what I understand now, there is no rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie told me, `We've got no problem with anything. There is
no weeping or crying.' I'm glad I got set straight. I like the
track, and I want it to turn out to be something the people of
Texas, and especially Fort Worth, can be proud of. I hope
everything goes well this weekend. I wouldn't want to do anything
to create any more controversy at that place \RTMS\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage confirmed that additional drainage has been installed in
Turn 3 to accommodate the placement of 7,500 temporary grandstand
seats. Another 2,500 temporary seats have been set up in Turn 4 and
2,199 in Turn 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We graded some of the berm up there \Rin Turn 3\S, so it has
positive drainage away from the racetrack. Nothing special there,''
Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   TMS was subject to similar rumors last year in the week leading
up to the NASCAR races. Cup qualifying subsequently was postponed
on Friday evening and moved to Saturday morning after water seeped
through Turn 1 as the sun began to set.
</P>
<P>
   A NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series race and two Pep Boys Indy
Racing League events have been run at the reconfigured track
without incident since last spring's water problems. And several
Cup teams have tested at the 1.5-mile quadoval, also without
incident, since December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating to have held two races without any
issues and to have testing all winter long _ with the media in
attendance _ without any issues,'' Gossage said. ``And a week
before \Rthe racing\S, people start spreading rumors.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
