<HEADER>
A3281 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BULLPEN-HN     03-24 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BULLPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ To fully appreciate the Astros' dilemma regarding
righthanded reliever Dean Crow, it is necessary to understand the
complicated options process.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The short version: Once a player is placed on the 40-man roster,
he receives three options. That player can be optioned to the minor
leagues any number of times in a given year, but it counts as just
one option. Once all three options have been used, the player must
clear waivers before he can be assigned to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Crow. He's out of options, and his poor
spring showing has the Astros exploring other possibilities for the
bullpen job that has been his to lose. Crow, a Houstonian whom the
Astros acquired in an offseason trade with Detroit, has been
perhaps the biggest disappointment of the spring for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   He has allowed 15 runs on 17 hits and eight walks in just 8
innings. There are instances when players perform better than their
statistics might indicate, but this isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may actually be pitching worse than my numbers reflect,''
said Crow, a product of Stratford High School. ``I've pitched
poorly, and I have no one to blame but myself. Maybe pressure could
be part of it. It's a new organization for me, plus I'm from
Houston. Maybe I'm putting a little too much pressure on myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what to say about it. I've just pitched
poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   The easy solution would be to remove Crow from consideration and
focus on another reliever _ perhaps Brian Williams, who ran his
scoreless-innings streak to 10 Wednesday with two perfect frames
against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But because Crow is out of options, the Astros run the risk of
losing him to another team _ a scary thought considering he was one
of the key players the club received in exchange for Brad Ausmus
and C.J. Nitkowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he ends up being the 11th pitcher (on an 11-man staff)
because he's out of options, so be it,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said. ``He could win by default. But I certainly don't
think that's the way he wants it or the way we want it. But it
could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Astros commit themselves to breaking camp with the
six relievers who appear to be the best at present. In that
scenario, it would be almost impossible to overlook Williams, whom
the club signed to a minor-league contract and invited to camp as a
non-roster player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen is unsettled, and it's time for someone to step up
and take a job,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``We're not
just going to carry someone because they're out of options. If
anyone has stepped up and caused us to notice him, it's Brian
Williams. He's thrown the ball really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Dierker and Hunsicker are cautious about reading too much
into spring performances. As Hunsicker said: ``If you just went by
spring training, (Craig) Biggio might be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But the brass has seen a change in Williams, who struggled with
his control during his first stint with the Astros but has thrown
strikes consistently this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know the people making the decisions are saying
good things about me, but that doesn't mean I'll make the team,''
Williams said. ``That's why I can't worry about that. I feel like
I've shown that I still have good enough stuff to pitch in the big
leagues and help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner, Jay Powell and Doug Henry are the only sure things
in the Astros' bullpen. If Xavier Hernandez remains healthy, he'll
join them. Trever Miller also is a good bet, but his spot could be
in jeopardy if Williams makes the team and Scott Elarton is placed
in the bullpen _ a possibility that seems to be gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Working in Miller's favor is the fact he's one of two
lefthanders in the bullpen, the other being Wagner. Nevertheless,
nothing seems as certain as it did when camp opened, and a lot of
it has to do with Crow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a terrible spring,'' Hunsicker said of Crow, who
posted a 3.94 ERA in 45 innings with the Tigers last season.
``There's no way to sugarcoat that. He's a better pitcher than what
he's shown us. The bullpen is just very much up in the air right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   And it likely will stay that way until the final cuts are
announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
