<HEADLINE>
NEWELL'S SPIN ON OLOWOKANDI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While several media sharpies were eager to slap
the ``buster'' tag on center Michael Olowokandi before the middle
of his rookie season, Pete Newell, the Yoda of low-post play, is
keeping the faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only seen him on TV a few times,'' Newell, who coached
the Cal Bears to a national championship in 1959 and now runs his
Big Man Camp in Hawaii, said when contacted at his home north of
San Diego. ``But, given the circumstances, he seems to be adjusting
well.''
</P>
<P>
   In 19 games this season, the 7-footer from Pacific is averaging
8 points and 7 rebounds per game, but shooting only 41 percent from
the field. His adjustment has included figuring out which low-post
moves many of those picked up while attending Newell's camp will
pass muster with NBA refs. In particular, the baseline spin move
has been a favorite target of NBA traffic cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfectly legal move,'' Newell said. ``I taught
Shaquille O'Neal the same move and they allow it; I guess Michael
hasn't been in the league long enough or something. It's pretty sad
that some 5-6 guy who never played the game can take away moves
some of these kids have worked many hours to perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   After missing five games with an injured ankle and returning in
less-than-spectacular fashion, Olowokandi had a solid road trip. In
addition to reaching double digits for points in three of the five
games, he grabbed a career-high 16 rebounds in Sunday's victory at
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's going to be a very good player,'' Newell said of his
former pupil. ``It takes time, though. But he doesn't have any ego
that gets in the way of his progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Final Four-cast: Forward Maurice Taylor, a three-year starter at
Michigan, is rooting for Big Ten rival Ohio State to do well in
this weekend's Final Four. Ken Johnson, the Buckeyes' center, was
Taylor's teammate at Detroit's Henry Ford High.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor has no warm feelings for the hated Michigan State
Spartans, who meet top-ranked Duke on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Duke to kick their butts,'' Taylor said of Michigan's
bitter in-state rival.
</P>
<P>
   Point wants to click: Backup point guard Troy Hudson, signed
Tuesday to a 10-day contract, decided to exhaust out any pre-game
jitters with a 45 minutes of shooting drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just gotta be ready,'' said the former Southern Illinois
University star, who played eight games for the Utah Jazz at the
start of last season. ``I have a couple of the plays down now, but
after a bit more practice, I know I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson was summoned back to the big (OK, medium) time because
two Clipper point guards _ Sherman Douglas and Pooh Richardson _
are on the injured list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
