<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOMO-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SEND NOMO TO MINORS, MAY LOOK TOWARD HERSHISER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ After clearing waivers, the
once-celebrated Japanese right-hander Hideo Nomo was sent outright
by the Mets to Triple-A Norfolk Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As a player with three-plus years in the major leagues, Nomo can
decline to accept the demotion and become a free agent. The Mets
expect his decision by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to delete Nomo from the Mets' 40-man roster was a
matter of control _ or lack of it. Last season, he walked 56 in 89
2/3 innings after being traded from the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had not shown the improvement and command of his fastball
that we would have liked to see,'' said general manager Steve
Phillips, who made the announcement Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Occurring less than two weeks to go before the season opener,
Nomo's departure leaves a gap in the Mets' starting pitching
rotation. He filled the No. 4 slot last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several possibilities,'' Phillips said. ``I'm not sure
we can point to any one guy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility may be Orel Hershiser, which would be exchanging
one former Dodger for another. The Mets have made inquiries with
the agent of the 40-year-old right-hander, to gauge what it would
take to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   As a sinkerball pitcher who works rapidly, Hershiser could be a
perfect fit with the Mets' infield, which in the off-season added
the slick-fielding third baseman Robin Ventura to the double-play
combination in shortstop Rey Ordonez and second baseman Edgardo
Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo's pitching style is just the opposite of Hershiser's. It
does not take advantage of the Mets' infield.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo walked 186 and struck out 300 over the last two seasons _ a
style that often left his infielders standing around waiting for
something to happen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mets seem to be ignoring any financial incentive they have
to dump Nomo outright. If they waive him by next Wednesday, they
can save more than $2 million of his one-year, $2.975 million
nonguaranteed contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the typical approach, but if you want to win,
sometimes you do what you need to do,'' said Phillips, who noted
that the Mets' owners were aware of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hershiser appeared a viable option. He signed a minor
league contract this spring with Cleveland but is a free agent now.
He exercised an option that if the Indians did not put him in their
starting rotation by last Sunday, and they did not, he would be
eligible to sign with whatever team he chooses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hershiser, who has averaged 14 victories over the last four
seasons (although he was 11-10 with a 4.41 earned run average in
San Francisco last season), says he wants to sign with a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage of my career, my priority is winning,'' he said
from his home in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' main competition for Hershiser's services appears to
be the Atlanta Braves. Manager Bobby Cox recently expressed concern
about his No. 5 starter, Bruce Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, a former Los Angeles Dodgers standout, is intent on
winning at least 10 more major league games, which would give him
200 career victories and a shot at induction into the Baseball Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marlins have also been pursuing Hershiser. They are
believed to have raised their one-year offer to about $2.5 million
from $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ends up that I'm a player-coach for a younger team, so
be it,'' Hershiser said. ``But that's not my priority right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he had no comment about Hershiser, after he exited
a closed-door session this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was a no-comment by Phillips on Tuesday that foreshadowed
Nomo's exit. Asked if he had the same sentiment about the pitcher
as the week before, when he said it was highly unlikely he would be
put on waivers, Phillips went through a pained pause before passing
up the chance to give his pitcher some sign of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones and Yoshii, Valentine said spring results can be
deceiving. He is comfortable entering the season with them as
starters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pretty consistent last year,'' Valentine said.
``They gave us a chance to win pretty much every time they went out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, knocked around early in the spring, looked better on
Tuesday, allowing three hits and two runs in five innings in the
Mets' 10-inning, 3-2 victory over Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitched in this league a long time and has done a very
good job every year that he's pitched,'' Valentine said. ``Last
year he didn't have as many wins as he usually does, but he
finished stronger. He was stronger in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who was 6-8 last season with a 3.93 ERA pitched
Wednesday night against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine likened Hershiser's pitching style to that of
Yoshii's, ``as far as pitch selection and competitiveness.'' The
main difference is that Hershiser's asking price has gone up. Way
up.
</P>
<P>
   That is because he has pitched well in spring training, and
injury and uncertainty have had an impact on numerous teams, the
Mets included.
</P>
<P>
   If something happens to improve the Mets' pennant chances,
Valentine will gladly accept it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Mets had passed on Hershiser last winter, and
also let such candidates as Willie Blair and Armando Reynoso
depart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
