A3332 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      03-24 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POVERTY WAS GIRL'S FATAL ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death of 13-year-old Gricelda Zamora was unspeakably
gruesome and painful, but it was not complicated.
</P>
<P>
   We're about to make it ``appear'' complicated, but it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   We can't stop ourselves, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   Well-meaning people have demanded an investigation into the
needless suffering of the sixth-grade cheerleader, and soon the
newspapers and television stations and radio programs will be
filled with idiot attempts by lawyers and doctors and PR
specialists to ``clarify,'' ``elucidate,'' ``account for,''
``justify'' or otherwise explain the many possible reasons a girl
like Gricelda could enter a hospital with a stomach ache and wind
up dead.
</P>
<P>
   No investigation is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   We know exactly why it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Gricelda Zamora died because she was poor.
</P>
<P>
   We'll try to come up with some other excuse, to provide some
other kind of explanation, because even though most of us are happy
with a health care system that leaves the working poor with little
or no coverage, we don't like to believe the system could kill a
pretty young girl in otherwise good health. &QL; 
A series of tests
</P>
<P>
   So, we play a little game of ``let's pretend.''
</P>
<P>
   We investigate the possibility of mistakes being made at Mesa
Lutheran Hospital, where Gricelda's parents brought their daughter
last week, doubled over in pain and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   The girl was run through a series of tests and X-rays, and kept
overnight. But she was sent home in the morning, her parents told
it was a case of stomach inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   Gricelda's mother and father don't speak English. Her father
told ``The Republic,'' ``When we left the hospital, she was crying.
She was still in pain and she wouldn't stop vomiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Would this happen to you?
</P>
<P>
   Could you imagine going along with doctors who want to discharge
a girl who's that sick?
</P>
<P>
   Could you imagine your doctor allowing it to happen?
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe, we decide to pin blame on Dr. Stewart Agren, the Mesa
physician to whom the Zamoras were referred. &QL; 
The doctor's office &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few days after going to the emergency room, the family went to
Agren's office. They had to bring a 14-year-old friend of
Gricelda's with them to serve as interpreter. Antonia Zamora is a
legal resident and has a job, but, still, a man who can't speak
English is looked upon, and treated, differently than the rest of
us.
</P>
<P>
   The family says they were kept waiting and waiting at the
doctor's office, with receptionists seemingly more concerned about
the proper insurance information than the symptoms displayed by the
girl. The doctor's attorney denies this, saying the doctor's staff
offered to treat the girl but the family chose to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gricelda was taken again to the emergency room. This
time, she was airlifted to Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center,
where doctors discovered her burst appendix.
</P>
<P>
   It was too late to save her.
</P>
<P>
   In the days and weeks to come there most likely will be comments
from medical professionals about a ``system breakdown'' and
``errors in judgment,'' when the sad fact is that Gricelda Zamora
got exactly the kind of medical treatment most poor people receive.
</P>
<P>
   The majority are lucky enough to survive it. Some are not.
</P>
<P>
   No investigation by the police or the medical community is going
to change that. And all the hand-wringing and soul-searching in the
world isn't going to alter the fact that those of us lucky enough
to have good health insurance have no interest in setting up a
system that would provide the same care for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   It would bankrupt us, we say.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``socialized medicine,'' we say.
</P>
<P>
   We extend our sympathies. We say it's too bad. But that's the
way it is, and if that costs a family a girl now and again, so be
it.
</P>
<P>
   As long as she's not one of ours. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
