<SLUG> BC-KIWI-AIRLINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ABRUPT REVERSAL, FAA GROUNDS KIWI AIRLINES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J. P.R.)  (rk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A day after Kiwi International Airlines thought it had won a
reprieve from a government-imposed death sentence, the Federal
Aviation Administration Wednesday grounded the struggling carrier,
saying that it was unsafe to fly.
</P>
<P>
   The agency ordered Kiwi to suspend its entire six-city schedule
immediately, forcing the airline to cancel its daily flights,
beginning Wednesday afternoon and continuing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Three flights from Newark International Airport in New Jersey ,
where Kiwi is based, to San Juan, P.R., Orlando, Fla., and Miami
had already taken off Wednesday morning when the order was issued.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the government had shut down a scheduled
carrier since Valujet was grounded in 1996 after one of its DC-9s
crashed in the Everglades, killing 110 people.
</P>
<P>
   The action forced hundreds of Kiwi passengers with return
tickets to make alternate plans and left 80,000 others who paid for
advance reservations on the airline over the next 11 months holding
potentially worthless tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Kulat, a Kiwi spokesman, said that the airline planned
to meet with the FAA Wednesday and was not sure how long it would
be grounded. ``We don't know what's going to happen,'' he said.
``We stand by our safety record. We have flown over 8 million
people without incident.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Kiwi filed for bankruptcy for the second time since
its founding in 1992 and simultaneously announced that it was
receiving a $3 million bailout from Pan American Airlines, the once
world-renowned carrier that itself has risen from the dead twice
since first going under in 1991 and is now a charter carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Kiwi hastily concluded the deal with Pan Am after the Department
of Transportation in Washington threatened to revoke its operating
license because it said that Kiwi did not have competent management
and was not adequately financed. Kiwi lost $20.6 million last year
and owes various airports $750,000 in fees.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the government gave Kiwi 14 days to respond but did
not prevent the carrier from continuing to fly. Indeed, it
specifically stated in a news release issued on Tuesday that the
FAA, which is part of the Transportation Department, had determined
that Kiwi was operating safely.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's complete reversal of that position created confusion
that added to the inconvenience suffered by many Kiwi passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The airline had no representatives at its check-in counter at
Newark Airport in the afternoon, even though scores of passengers
had arrived to find that their evening flights had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Kulat said the Kiwi employees had been sent home. A handful of
airport employees, who work for the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey, tried in vain to help the stranded passengers make
other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just chaos all over the place,'' said Jinine Richiusa,
one of the Port Authority workers. ``Most airlines are not honoring
any Kiwi tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what had changed overnight that caused the government to
reverse itself, Eliot Brenner, the FAA's spokesman in Washington,
said that the agency had been examining Kiwi for months and only
reached its final decision to ground the carrier Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said that that the apparent flip-flop was the result of
miscommunication and the Transportation Department's attempt to
draw a distinction between its job of determining an airline's
financial and managerial fitness and the FAA's role of overseeing
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's order cited a series of maintenance and safety
violations that it said resulted in Kiwi flying airplanes that were
``in an unairworthy condition.'' In one case, Kiwi flew one of its
four jets for two days in late February without fixing an oil leak
in one of its two engines, the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
