A3336 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-MARK-MARTIN-TEX     03-24 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARK-MARTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK MARTIN IS HUMBLE ABOUT HIS TEXAS SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Martin was the first driver to turn a hot lap at Texas
Motor Speedway, when he conducted a Goodyear tire test in
September, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first driver to win a race at TMS, taking the
checkered flag at the Busch Grand National Coca-Cola 300 two years
ago in the No. 60 Winn-Dixie Ford.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the second driver to win a Winston Cup race at TMS,
finishing first at the Texas 500 last year in the No. 6 Valvoline
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin owns TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect him to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a special track,'' Martin said of the facility that
plays host to the BGN Coca-Cola 300 and the Winston Cup Primestar
500 this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Martin doesn't like coming to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tremendous facility,'' Martin said. ``You watch
futuristic movies when you're younger and you see all this stuff
that's beyond reality. Well, that's sort of what it's like to me to
walk into that place. I never thought I'd see the day that there
would be facilities like that and that I'd be racing them. I'm
still that same guy who raced dirt tracks in Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it would be out of character for Martin to crow about
his accomplishments at TMS, or anywhere. The 40-year-old driver
from Batesville, Ark., is a walking definition of humble.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had one of the greatest seasons in NASCAR history last
year, winning a career-best seven races. He had 22 top-five and 26
top-10 finishes in 33 starts and finished with 4,964 points, the
most since Cale Yarborough earned 5,000 in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an accomplishment,'' he said. ``We were proud of what
we did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he did not win the Winston Cup championship. That went to
some guy named Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won 13 races, tying the modern-era record. He had 26
top-five finishes and 28 top-10s in 33 races. He earned 5,328
points, the most since NASCAR began using the current system in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was Sammy Sosa, whose 66 homers were the most in the
majors since 1961. Gordon was Mark McGwire, whose 70 homers were a
record.
</P>
<P>
   But just as he isn't the type to boast about things that go
right, Martin also isn't the type to bemoan his luck when they
don't. He doesn't dwell on the fact that a 4,964-point season would
have been good enough to win a championship ever year except for
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not where my focus is,'' he said. ``My focus is
performance. There's a lot of things that you can't control that
have a bearing on that. I'm not going to lose any sleep over the
stuff I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has won 30 Cup races in his career, including the North
Carolina 400 at Rockingham on Feb. 21. He's won a series-best 33
BGN races, including the Sam's Town 300 at Las Vegas on March 6. He
has won four International Race of Champions titles, including the
past three, beating the best drivers in the world in identically
prepared cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the best driver in Winston Cup racing because he
understands cars and he goes fast,'' said Roush Racing teammate
Jeff Burton. ``Whatever he sits in goes fast. There's no denying
that.''
</P>
<P>
   His resume lacks a Winston Cup championship, but he has finished
second three times. He is the only driver to finish in the top six
in points every year since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   His fellow drivers know Martin is a threat to win when the green
flag drops every week. They know he will race hard, but clean. It's
hard to find anyone in the garage area with anything bad to say
about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a lot of respect, and that's very important to me,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin earns that respect not only with his performance on the
track but his demeanor off it. The past two years he refused to
join the chorus of voices criticizing TMS for its litany of
problems from the tight, one-groove layout to the seepage problems
that plagued last year's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I shut it down was because there was a
sensationalized bandwagon slamming the track,'' he said. ``There
was nothing you could do about it that day. You had to race. So
whether they wanted to fix it or not, cared or not, it didn't
matter. We had to race. I've raced on race tracks where the asphalt
has gone up, where chunks have come out of it, where the lights
didn't work right. Everything under the sun in my career. The
circumstances weren't nearly as tough as some I've been caught in.
They've done our racing series a great service by building that
facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Only now, after the reconfiguration that has drivers who have
tested at TMS calling it a much improved track, is Martin willing
to express his displeasure with the way it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed,'' he said. ``I was very disappointed. But
you know what? They fixed it. In the meantime, I got a couple of
wins there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
