<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-GIULIANI-NY     03-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR, IN REVERSAL, AGREES TO MEETINGS WITH BLACK LEADERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Also see NY-POLICE-SAFIR, NY-POLICE-PROTEST)   By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After an hourlong meeting with C. Virginia Fields,
the Manhattan borough president, whom he had shunned for more than
a year, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said on Wednesday night that he
would meet again with her and with other leading black officials at
a time when the aftershocks of the Amadou Diallo shooting continue
to rumble through the city.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office also announced that he finally would meet
with the state's highest-ranking black elected official, State
Comptroller H. Carl McCall. The two men last met in November 1994;
since then, the mayor has refused several requests from McCall for
another meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden decision to open his door marked a stark turnaround
for the mayor, who had previously dismissed Ms. Fields and McCall
as being more interested in publicity than in substantive
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor has come under increasing pressure to appear more
conciliatory, as the outcry continues over the death of Diallo, an
unarmed black man killed in a hail of 41 bullets fired by four
white officers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said Wednesday that he expected Police
Commissioner Howard Safir to keep his job, though he declined to
comment on whether it was appropriate for Safir to have accepted a
free trip to Los Angeles for the Academy Awards ceremony from a
cosmetics executive. Safir has been under fire for the trip and for
the conduct of his officers in the Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Police Headquarters in lower Manhattan drew the
largest and most diverse crowd of protesters there since Diallo's
killing on Feb. 4. More than 200 people were arrested and charged
with disorderly conduct, including rabbis, labor leaders and the
elderly, as they gathered for the 12th day of civil disobedience to
protest the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The stubbornness for which he is so well known seemed to melt a
bit in the mist that fell outside Gracie Mansion, where the mayor
met with Ms. Fields Wednesday night. Giuliani stood alongside his
former nemesis as Ms. Fields told an assembly of reporters that
during their meeting she had pointed out ``ways in which I felt
that he has not shown the level of sensitivity and understanding
andit has not served to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the mayor offered a defense: ``And I think what I
did is try to explain why I have, as best as I can, tried to
express my sensitivity, my concern, my regret over this situation _
and at the same time not allow a Police Department to be defamed in
the way in which it was being defamed, which could be enormously
destructive to the effort to save lives in African-American and
other communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Peter F. Vallone, the City Council speaker, who had
brokered the detente, stepped forward. ``This is a beginning,'' he
said, ``a beginning of dialogue, and it's an important, a major
step, in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In another context, a meeting between the mayor and the
Manhattan Borough president would not be newsworthy enough to
persuade reporters to stand in an evening drizzle. But the Diallo
shooting has brought to light the deep fissure that divides
Giuliani and most of the city's top elected black officials.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has dismissed many of the city's black leaders as
``highly partisan'' Democrats who resent his Republican
administration. He and his aides have maintained that they have
been meeting with other black officials, including ministers and
representatives of an African group from Brooklyn. But critics have
argued that the mayor has been selective in choosing those he
deigns to meet; by and large, they say, his meeting are with people
who have city contracts, or are not elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mayor's office has determined that it is time for
``building bridges,'' as Cristyne F. Lategano, the mayor's
communications director, put it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the mayor held a press conference that was free of
the dismissive tone that he has sometimes used when discussing the
reaction to the Diallo shooting, particularly the protests.
Although he continued to defend the Police Department, which he
described as one of the best in the country, the mayor also said
that ``there is a reality'' to the feeling ``in the minority
community that police officers are unfair to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
