<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-1STLD     03-24 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ADDRESS TO THE NATION, CLINTON EXPLAINS NEED TO TAKE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite and inserts new 17th and 18th grafs.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV,
KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Wednesday night that his
decision to authorize military strikes against Yugoslavia was
derived from moral revulsion at the killing in Kosovo and a
calculated assessment of American interests in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   He said that despite the risks to American and allied forces, he
was compelled to act now because the costs would only increase if
he failed to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the dangers of acting are far outweighed
by the dangers of not acting, dangers to defenseless people and to
our national interests,'' Clinton said in his televised address
from the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had been reluctant to commit U.S. forces to the
Balkan conflict and that he had acted only when he was certain that
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia would respond to nothing
less than a forceful military action that struck at the heart of
his machinery of oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a didactic 13-minute address, said the NATO attacks
on Yugoslav targets were intended to avert a humanitarian disaster
and to serve American geopolitical interests. He conjured images of
Balkan concentration camps and ``genocide in the heart of Europe''
that offend American moral sensibilities and threaten American
values and interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we and our allies were to allow this war to continue with
no response, President Milosevic would read our hesitation as a
license to kill,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that American and NATO credibility were at stake and
even alluded to an American economic interest in a stable and
prosperous Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave the American people a selective lesson in history
and geography, using colorful maps to locate Kosovo and to
dramatize its historical role as the powder keg of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, will not be contained
in its borders, Clinton warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let a fire burn here in this area,'' the president said, ``and
the flames will spread. Eventually key U.S. allies could be drawn
into a wider conflict, or we would be forced to confront later,
only at far greater risk and greater cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reviewed the tragic history of the former Yugoslavia
after the country spun apart in 1989. He said the West should not
repeat the mistakes that it made in Bosnia from 1992 to 1995,
allowing a bloodthirsty campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' to rage
for almost three years without outside intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, as a presidential candidate in 1992, criticized
President Bush for failing to act in Bosnia. But once in office,
Clinton did not approve a military response to Serbian slaughter of
Bosnian Muslims until 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic only sat down at the peace table after American-led
NATO forces had delivered punishing attacks on his forces in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must apply the same lessons in Kosovo before what happens
in Bosnia happens there, too,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ingredients for a major war are there, ancient
grievances, struggling democracies and, in the center of it all, a
dictator in Serbia who has done nothing since the Cold War ended
but start new wars and pour gasoline on the flames of ethnic and
religious division,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   The president glossed over important differences between Bosnia
and Kosovo. Bosnia was an independent republic with a mixed Muslim
and Serbian population that invited Western intervention to halt
Milosevic's effort to drive out the Muslims. Kosovo, with a large
ethnic Albanian majority, was stripped of its autonomy but has
remained a part of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The administration supports autonomy, but not independence, for
Kosovo. But Clinton sowed confusion when he said, ``Right now our
firmness is the only hope the people of Kosovo have to be able to
live in their own country without having to fear for their own
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House official explained that Clinton was referring not
to an independent Kosovo, but to the right of Kosovars of Albanian
descent to live without fear as citizens of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic _ and President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, who angrily
denounced the air strikes _ contend that the United States and its
allies are intervening in a civil war against the wishes of a
sovereign state, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, said Wednesday
evening that Clinton had been presented with a group of unpalatable
choices like doing nothing and introducing American ground troops
into Kosovo. The alternative that he chose, a limited air campaign,
carries significant risks and only modest prospects of success, but
is better than all the other choices, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has been very clear that this is the only choice
among a series of imperfect choices,'' he added. ``We came to an
end-state that is not perfect. But compare it to an end-state of
not acting. There would be chaos and catastrophe of both a human
and a strategic kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Berger nor the president directly addressed the question
of what guideposts they had set for measuring the success of the
operation or what NATO and the United States would do if the air
raids did not halt Milosevic's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said Clinton had been compelled
to act because American and NATO threats had begun to ring hollow
after months of inaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you threaten,'' Lieberman said in an interview, ``and the
person you're threatening repeatedly does exactly what you've told
him not to do, then you'd better act on your threat or you will
have dissipated your own strength. Nobody, not just in the Balkans,
but around the world, will take you seriously. That's the situation
we were in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spoken at length on Kosovo several times in the last
five days. In addition to the strategic and humanitarian arguments
that he made Wednesday night, he suggested that America had a
number of other interests in peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said Wednesday night in an interview
that he supported Clinton's decision for the air assault. But he
tempered his support with harsh criticism of the president's record
on the Balkans and said Clinton's failure to back up previous
threats with action had undermined the credibility of the United
States and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard a president do what he did a couple weeks
ago,'' McCain said. ``He allowed two deadlines to pass when he said
there would be action, unless deadlines were met. There is a
problem with credibility there.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that it was difficult to predict Milosevic's
behavior, but that he did not believe that Milosevic would
capitulate after the initial barrage of air and missile strikes.
McCain complained that the administration had yet spelled out how
it would respond if Milosevic dug in his heels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
