<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houston man wanted in million dollar insurance scam
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Arrest warrants were issued for six people
Wednesday in an insurance scam that netted millions of dollars in
settlements for staged car accidents and phony injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The scam involved law offices and chiropractor clinics in
Austin, El Paso and Houston and was uncovered by a yearlong
investigation by the Travis County district attorney's office and
other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   According to a search warrant affidavit, the scheme was
organized by a Houston man named Alex Ferdman, 40, who used
businesses across Texas, including the Uptown Austin Rehabilitation
Center in Austin off North Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests warrants were issued for Ferdman and five other people,
four of whom are from Austin. Tuesday, officials also searched the
office of Austin attorney Donna McCarty and law offices in Houston
and El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Ferdman paid others to gather car accident
reports from the police and then call accident victims who would be
referred to a law office involved in the scam. The lawyers in turn
would refer the accident victims to chiropractors who would
prescribe lengthy treatments, regardless of whether the accident
victims needed them, according to court records. The lawyers would
then press the insurance companies for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Ferdman would have ``runners,'' or people he paid
to contact accident victims, stage fake accidents or cause real
accidents in order to generate business, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdman and the five people named in the arrests warrants face
charges of insurance fraud and money laundering. According to the
affidavit, the group laundered millions of dollars through a small
furniture store in Houston. Investigators estimate that about
$200,000 from insurance scams went through the store every month
since early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, Ferdman carried a briefcase full of
cash that he would use to pay runners at the Uptown Austin
Rehabilitation Center. In some cases, he would ask his contacts to
pose as lawyers to press insurance companies for legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Fraud schemes like this are common and cost insurance companies
$14 billion annually, said Dennis Pompa, chief fraud investigator
at the Texas Department of Insurance, which also helped in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies may ask for investigations when the same
attorneys show up on claim forms or when the same accident victims
show up again and again.
</P>
<P>
   This particular scheme allegedly involved more than 30 people
across the state. It was thwarted by a yearlong investigation by
the Public Integrity Unit of the Travis County district attorney's
office and 16 other agencies, authorities said. The Public
Integrity Unit receives state money to police ethics in state
government. Its investigations involve a wide range of violations,
including crimes committed by private citizens who deal with the
state or offenses committed by state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Five people wanted by authorities include two employees of
Uptown Austin Rehabilitation Center: manager Victor Hugo Cuevas,
31, and clinic driver Juan Del Toro, 32. The others are Eric
Arriola and Raul Cucvas of Austin, and Armando Casillas of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the district attorney's office searched McCarty's
offices in Austin and Houston, and the offices of attorneys Mickey
Altman and Lloyd Dunn in Houston and El Paso. They also searched
Interstate Rehab, a chiropractic clinic in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
