<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redd staying, Penn unsure
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Like with any great player whose team
makes it into the glaring spotlight of the Final Four, Scoonie Penn
and teammate Michael Redd already have been asked about their
intentions for next season. Will they stay at Ohio State or turn
pro?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely staying regardless of if we win,'' Redd said.
</P>
<P>
   In a teleconference call on Tuesday afternoon, Penn skirted the
question, saying ``right now my main focus is UConn.'' However, he
was quoted in an Associated Press story later in the day saying,
``I'm thinking next year about coming back here and playing at Ohio
State. The NBA has been a dream of mine. But right now, I have no
thoughts about leaving college basketball at all.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Still escaping: Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien has worried all
season about his team's poor foul shooting (61 percent). Each time
he was asked about it, he warned that if it didn't improve soon, it
would cost the Buckeyes a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Well, somehow, OSU has managed to keep winning despite shooting
60 percent from the foul line in NCAA tournament play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we've needed to make free throws at the end, we've done
that,'' O'Brien said. ``But I've been telling kids one of these
games our free throw shooting is going to do us in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
