<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE SENATE AGAIN PASSES BAN ON TYPE OF ABORTION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For the third time, the state Senate Wednesday
passed a bill outlawing a form of abortion, continuing a national
debate over the procedure, which opponents call partial-birth
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Assembly is deeply divided over the issue, people
close to Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, said it was
likely that he would prevent the bill from coming to a vote in that
house, as he has in years past. Advocates of the ban believe it
would win passage in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, has said he would sign the
bill if it came to his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight states have enacted some version of the measure.
The law has been challenged in court in 20 of the 28 states, and in
18 it has been struck down completely or in part. Alabama's ban is
partly in force as it awaits a court ruling. Only in Virginia has
the law been upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has passed bans, but two times has narrowly failed to
override President Clinton's vetoes. In referendums in Washington
and Colorado last year, voters rejected the ban.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Republican-controlled Senate voted 41-19 Wednesday
for the ban, which it passed in different form in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is akin to infanticide,'' said Sen. Serphin
Maltese, the Queens Republican who sponsored the bill. ``I think
this is a reprehensible, absolutely barbaric practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Dollinger, D-Rochester, his voice rising to a
shout, replied to Maltese, ``Don't you dare be in the maternity
room with me, my daughter, my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In the procedure at issue, a fetus is extracted from the uterus,
all except the head, and a doctor then punctures the skull to
remove the brain, before pulling the head out. Anti-abortion groups
call that partial-birth abortion; doctors use the term intact
dilation and extraction.
</P>
<P>
   Most versions of the ban are written so vaguely, opponents say,
that they could apply to any abortion procedure. Courts have
generally agreed, finding the laws unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents often describe the procedure as a form of
late-term abortion, but medical groups say it is used any time
after 16 weeks of pregnancy, less than halfway through a normal
40-week pregnancy. Abortion in the final trimester of pregnancy is
already illegal around the country, except when the life and health
of the mother are in jeopardy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
