<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED A REASON TO BOO GORDON? HE'S GOING TO WIN SUNDAY 
COMMENTARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beyond driver introductions, the boo-birds who typically
serenade Jeff Gordon at racetrack after racetrack during the NASCAR
Winston Cup season have had little chance to exercise their vocal
cords at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Gordon has won three of the past four Cup championships, a
record-tying 13 races in 1998 and two of five events this season.
</P>
<P>
   At TMS, however, the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet
has been just another banged-up hunk of sheet metal. Swept up in
wrecks during the inaugural Interstate Batteries 500 and the Texas
500 last year, Gordon has posted respective finishes of 30th and
31st.
</P>
<P>
   Even among Gordon's most ardent detractors _ and TMS security
has you on videotape _ who could work up a good ``boo'' about
results like that?
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Gordon finished 87 laps behind winner Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gordon finished 82 laps behind winner Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 668 total Cup laps run in Fort Worth, Gordon has led 69,
all in the early stages of the first race.
</P>
<P>
   That said, remember we are talking about racing on the ``old''
TMS. Which is why it makes perfect sense to me that Gordon is going
to win the Primestar 500 on the ``new'' TMS this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and crew chief Ray Evernham did not have a lot of holes
in their race-day resumes entering the 1999 season, but three
venues historically and admittedly have given them fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Las Vegas, Atlanta and Texas _ those are the tracks that we
have at the top of our list to have better finishes at,'' Gordon
said last weekend at Darlington, S.C. ``We've done pretty well at
the other two \Rthis month\S, and hopefully we can keep it going in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   All three tracks on Gordon's short list are 1.5-mile triovals,
although AMS and TMS have been reclassified as ``quadovals'' since
their recent reconfigurations and repavings.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon finished third at Vegas behind the Burton brothers, Jeff
and Ward, on a track that is banked at 12 degrees. AMS and TMS, of
course, are banked at 24 degrees, so without a sneak peek into
Evernham's notebook we have to assume that whatever chassis setups,
etc., clicked at Vegas would not get it done around AMS or TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, however, what worked at AMS should
transfer to the ``new'' TMS. And in case you have been too busy
booing to take note, Gordon has won the past two races at Atlanta
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   More so, Gordon said after the Cracker Barrel 500 on March 14
that he finally has a combination with which he feels comfortable
at NASCAR's fastest non-restrictor-plate racetrack. Very timely,
because open testing at TMS has indicated the track _ with its
wider, driver-friendly entrance into Turn 1 and exit out of Turn 4
and new pavement _ should be a couple of miles per hour faster than
last year.
</P>
<P>
   And forget about one lap of qualifying for a moment and think
about the 334-lap race _ and what Gordon and Evernham and the
Rainbow Warriors are capable of orchestrating once they get
dialed-in with a setup. Think about how they plot strategy, down to
their patented two-tires only (and fuel) pit stops in the waning
laps. It all worked to perfection at Hampton, Ga., and there is no
reason to believe it will not fall into place again in Fort Worth
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a lot of comments about how the Texas track now is
very similar to, and it drives very similar to, Atlanta,'' Gordon
said. ``So, that's certainly promising.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreboding, actually, might be a better description. And let us
not forget that unlike the previous two years at TMS, Gordon will
be running in the Coca-Cola 300 NASCAR Busch Grand National race on
Saturday. Gordon debuted his No. 24 Pepsi Monte Carlo, the car he
is driving in a limited five-race schedule, at Vegas with a nice
fourth-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he racked up laps at one of NASCAR's newest
venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I have not had many laps at Texas, so I definitely want
to get more,'' Gordon said. ``Doing it in the Busch car is one of
the reasons why we picked that track. And from what I learned in
Vegas on Saturday, I think it will definitely help me out in Texas
on Saturday for Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   At least I'm buying it. So boo-birds, better get your vocal
cords ready.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
Martin the team owner?
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kenseth was a protege of NASCAR Winston Cup star Mark
Martin longbefore Kenseth pulled off a 10th-place finish Sunday in
relief of the injured Bobby Labonte at Darlington Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   And Martin is interested in establishing a formal owner/driver
relationship with Kenseth, the NASCAR Busch Grand National points
leader heading into the Coca-Cola 300 at Texas Motor Speedway on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jack Roush, who owns Martin's No. 6 Valvoline Ford
Taurus, said he is willing to get involved with Kenseth, the
27-year-old Wisconsin native who is planning to run five Cup races
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's come forward and said he would like to be an owner in
the team and would enjoy seeing the team operating under Mark
Martin Racing, or something like that,'' Roush said. ``It's in the
developmental stages.''
D.W. must crank it up
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Cup champion Darrell Waltrip heads into the Primestar
500 at TMS without the safety net of a provisional start for the
first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, who is in his initial season of driving the No. 66 Big
Kmart Ford Taurus owned by Carl Haas and Travis Carter, has used
his allotment of four provisionals in the first four races. The
team slid to 30th in car-owner points _ 25th is the cutoff _ after
last weekend's uncompetitive 41st-place finish at Darlington
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip is ineligible for a non-chargeable points provisional
under NASCAR's complicated system.
</P>
<P>
   That means he must qualify among the top 36 on speed at TMS, or
sit out.
</P>
<P>
   D.W. now has gone 200 consecutive races since his last victory,
at Darlington, on Sept. 6, 1992.
Last laps
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one NASCAR Winston Cup regulars will attempt to qualify
for the Busch Grand National Coca-Cola 300 at Texas Motor Speedway
today. In all, 62 drivers are entered for 43 starting spots.
</P>
<P>
   Only four drivers have finished in the top 10 in both Winston
Cup races at TMS _ native Texans Terry and Bobby Labonte, Steve
Grissom and Michael Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Waltrip, driver of the No. 7 Philips Ford Taurus, will
attempt to qualify for his 400th career Cup race at TMS. He never
has won a Cup race. Last words ``Anybody that puts a whupping on me
gets my respect.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jack Roush, Winston Cup team owner, on why he hired Chad
Little
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
