r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     03-24 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISMAIL'S AGENT HAS RUN OUT OF TOMORROWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Mula is my new agent.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to read an immediate quote from Mula that tomorrow I will
announce a peace settlement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Also tomorrow, according to my man Mula, I will reveal how
traffic congestion has been eliminated for Sunday in north Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned tomorrow, when I solve the mystery of the Rangers'
rotation. By tomorrow, I will have also filed a missing persons
report on Dirk Nowitzki.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss tomorrow, Mula will tell you, when Mayor Barr and
myself officially declare Love Field closed to air traffic. Then be
sure to catch tomorrow's political bombshell when I break the story
on George W. Bush's tabbing Molly Ivins as his presidential running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger yet, however, will be Mula's announcement that receiver
Rocket Ismail has signed with the Cowboys. That will be tomorrow,
of course. And if not then, by the weekend, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Jack Mula? And why doesn't he simply keep his mouth shut
until there is something to say?
</P>
<P>
   Based on what's been observed over the past three weeks, it
would be a decade of tomorrows before I'd consider hiring Mula for
anything, including yard work. But he's Ismail's agent, along with
Doug Flutie's, so if they are happy, I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past three weeks, Mula has appeared in local print
four times saying Ismail is ready to reveal where he will make a
free- agent landing. Tomorrow is the day, so sayeth Mula.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday, Ismail was still a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be this hard. Only two teams _ the Cowboys and the
Carolina Panthers _ are in the running for Ismail's services.
Ismail has played for Carolina the past three seasons. He is
building a new home in Charlotte, N.C. But all indications are he
will sign with the Cowboys. Tomorrow. Which means it will probably
be Carolina. Tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   If Ismail is this indecisive running his routes, who would want
him anyway? But is it Ismail, who has never uttered a public word
throughout the process, or is it an agent making his client look
goofy? Mula keeps setting deadlines that are never met.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys don't seem particularly concerned one way or the
other, but the $5 million signing bonus they've offered Ismail
suggests they are dead serious. The way to bet is that Dallas will
be Rocket's new home. The fact the Panthers want him back at a much
higher salary also speaks to perceived value.
</P>
<P>
   But the lines of communication between Mula and Ismail are
apparently flawed. Why don't you try to fix that, Jack. Like,
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   There are those in the NFL who wonder if Ismail is worth this
wait. And basically, his career performance chart backs up that
theory.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rocket is just that, and The Cowboys are desperate for a
speed receiver after the offensive shutdown in the second half of
last season. Ismail can provide fast feet. Until 1998, however, he
had never provided any reason to be considered a free-agent plum.
</P>
<P>
   For three seasons with the Raiders, and two in Carolina, Ismail
carried a ``bust'' label. But 69 catches and 1,024 yards in 1998
almost doubled his best from any previous year. He had 11 career TD
catches in five seasons, then eight last year.
</P>
<P>
   To begin '98, the Panthers had no plans to start Rocket. But an
injury to Rae Carruth provided an opening, and ...
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys suddenly became very interested in Ismail's
free-agent status. A career year in a free-agency season is
normally tagged with red warning flags, but Valley Ranch has a
different view.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail has spent his NFL career catching passes from Kerry
Collins, Steve Beuerlein, Jeff Hostetler and Vince Evans. When a
heady quarterback like Beuerlein took over last season for Collins,
the Rocket took off.
</P>
<P>
   So what would he do with Troy Aikman whistling balls his way?
</P>
<P>
   Everything considered, Ismail is in the right place at the right
time to provide exactly what the Cowboys need. In other words, he
runs fast and at least for one season _ last season _ he showed the
stuff of a first-class receiver.
</P>
<P>
   That the Cowboys are after Ismail makes sense. That their
financial offer to Ismail is said to be larger than Carolina's also
makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   But what no one can decipher is why Jack Mula keeps babbling.
When the decision is made, tell us then. And not tomorrow.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
