<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKS SITS IN JUDGMENT OF RANGERS' STAFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ In the circus-like atmosphere that
followed the Yankees to Charlotte County Stadium yesterday, Rangers
owner Tom Hicks, standing to chat with visitors just before game
time, found fans pushing their way between him and his seat
adjacent to the home team dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' Hicks said with an easy smile, ``I'll get it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good. Rangers fans should feel very comfortable with the
fiercely competitive and well-heeled Hicks in the organization's
prime seat.
</P>
<P>
   How comfortable everyone else should be remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the one small problem I have with the Rangers' new
owner.
</P>
<P>
   The question that lingers, as the Rangers prepare to launch
their first full season under Hicks' ownership, is whether jobs are
on the line. So let's get that one out of the way immediately.
</P>
<P>
   You bet they are.
</P>
<P>
   If jobs were hanging in the balance in late September last
season _ and they were _ while Hicks waited to see whether the
Rangers were going to win the AL West, why wouldn't the same
scenario hold this year?
</P>
<P>
   No, Hicks didn't say that. There are too many unanswered
variables at this point for him to hazard a guess as to whether
Doug Melvin, or Johnny Oates, or his coaching staff might find
themselves in trouble at some point this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an unfair question,'' Hicks said, ``and it's an
impossible question to answer in a vacuum. How bad are we? What
injuries did we have? What were the extenuating circumstances?''
</P>
<P>
   Without being able to fill in those blanks and overflowing with
the usual optimism of spring, the furthest thing from Hicks' mind
is a scenario in which somebody's job could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, it is an unfair question. Yet, it has lingered through
the winter like the smell of mildew on an old gym towel, a leftover
from those frantic last weeks of September, when the Rangers were
fighting to pull away from the Angels and the future of Oates and
his coaching staff was hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it clear how I felt last year,'' Hicks said. ``I wanted
to wait to see if we won the West before extending contracts. That
was just good business.''
</P>
<P>
   Good business in the corporate world, maybe, but it was highly
unusual in baseball for a contending team's coaches to be left
hanging that late in the season. At the same time that they were
trying to win a pennant, Oates and his coaches were forced to
discreetly make calls to their friends in baseball to see what jobs
might be available, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has proven himself as an excellent manager. He has won
division titles in Texas two of the past three seasons. He has
beaten a 25-year history of losing and of teams that were deemed
better by most baseball experts. No one can say he should have done
more with the talent at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   His players respect him and play for him. He is not only a good
baseball man, but a good man, period.
</P>
<P>
   He and his coaches should not be approaching a season wondering
whether their jobs will be forfeited if, heaven forbid, John
Wetteland can't pitch, or Rafael Palmeiro's knee doesn't come
around, or Juan Gonzalez's back starts to act up.
</P>
<P>
   Or what if it's not injuries? What if it's simply that the
pitching staff stinks, a distinct possibility? Or three or four key
hitters have off-years?
</P>
<P>
   Those, presumably, are the variables and extenuating
circumstances that Hicks was talking about. All indications are
that he is a just and fair man and will take all those things into
account.
</P>
<P>
   Last September's hesitation, however, continues to nag.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal right now is just to win the AL West,'' Hicks said.
``I don't think that's going to be easy, because the Angels are
improved and they're going to be tough, and I think Seattle will
probably be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also think that if we can get into the playoffs, we'll
do better than we did last year \Rwhen the Rangers were swept in
three games by the Yankees\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Rangers are stronger with Hicks as the owner.
He's straightforward, accessible to his people, quick to understand
problems and creative at getting them resolved. When Melvin
suggested the Rangers should try to sign Randy Johnson this
off-season, Hicks was ready with his checkbook. Ditto for Melvin's
efforts to trade for Roger Clemens, who wanted his contract
rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is also a quick study. His seat comes with built-in heat
and tough decisions, but he's earned it.
</P>
<P>
   He's smart enough to know that Oates has earned his, too.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
