<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-GOLDWYN-FILM-ART     03-24 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-GOLDWYN-FILM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLDWYN ON THE WAY UP IN THE FAMILY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 Sylviane Gold, who reviews dance for Newsday, has been a theater
critic for The Wall Street Journal and writes frequently about the
arts.  
 By SYLVIANE GOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About five years ago, the actor Tony Goldwyn started getting
restless. ``I'd gotten to the point in my career where I knew I
would get work _ I knew the mortgage would get paid,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His performance in the 1990 off-Broadway play ``The Sum of Us''
had put him on the New York theater map. The same year, his
portrayal of the yuppie villain in ``Ghost'' had done the same in
Hollywood. But he wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor,'' he says, ``your involvement in the filmmaking
process is limited: you show up, you make your contribution and you
leave. I felt, `Is this what I want from my life, just to be
providing services?'''
</P>
<P>
   His response was perhaps inevitable for the son of the movie
producer Samuel Goldwyn Jr. and the grandson of the Hollywood
legend Sam Goldwyn. He would find a script he wanted to act in and
produce himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, if I'm in a big hit movie, and become financeable,'' he
recalls thinking, ``I'll say, `Here's a script I've always wanted
to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   He saw it as something that might happen 10 years down the road.
But it didn't turn out the way he expected because of a script
called ``The Blouse Man,'' by a poet and playwright named Pamela
Gray. Seizing on the screenplay, Goldwyn filmed it as ``A Walk on
the Moon,'' which opened on Friday. And although Goldwyn does not
act in it, he is indeed one of the producers and, more important,
its director.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray, who grew up in Brooklyn, based ``The Blouse Man'' on
her memories of the Catskills, where she spent summer vacations
with her family. A California boy, Goldwyn knew nothing of the
annual summer exodus that brought working-class Jewish families
from New York City to ``the mountains'' during the 1940s, 50s and
60s. And he was only 9 years old during the summer of 1969, when
Neil Armstrong planted his boots on the lunar surface and some
400,000 hippies turned a concert in upstate New York into a
cultural watershed.
</P>
<P>
   But he fell in love with Ms. Gray's story of Pearl Kantrowitz, a
young Brooklyn mother, who is drawn into an affair when the spirit
of Woodstock invades her Catskills bungalow colony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really identified with that moment that usually happens to
people in their early 30s,'' says Goldwyn, now 38. ``You suddenly
see your life laid out in front of you. And you say, `Is this the
life I dreamed of having? Am I the person I wanted to become?' If
the answer's no, that's a very scary moment. And sometimes what it
takes to deal with that is very risky: it requires shattering the
status quo. And I thought the setting for Pearl's love affair, in
1969, was the perfect metaphor, because that's exactly what was
happening to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Walk on the Moon,'' recreates the summer ritual of cars
overflowing with bedding, suitcases and kitchenware heading north
toward the low-rent cousins of fancy resorts like Kutsher's and the
Nevele; loudspeakers announcing the arrival on the premises of the
ice cream truck or the knish truck or the blouse truck; al fresco
mahjong games during the day, third-rate comedians or old movies in
the ``casino'' at night.
</P>
<P>
   It's the man who sells the blouses, played by Viggo Mortensen,
who disturbs the equilibrium of the Kantrowitz family: Diane Lane
as Pearl, dimly aware that she's missed something; Liev Schreiber
as her decent but dullish husband; Anna Paquin as their pubescent
daughter, and Tovah Feldshuh as Pearl's shrewd mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always watched directors on all the films I've worked on
and thought, `I'm so glad that's not me,''' Goldwyn says, sitting
barefoot in the airy living room of the rambling Connecticut house
he shares with his wife, Jane Musky, who is a movie production
designer, their two daughters and their two dogs and two cats. ``I
had tremendous admiration for directors, and I didn't know if I
possessed the skills required. But it didn't seem like a lot of
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   His plan was to produce the film and let someone else take on
the ``anxieties'' of directing. He'd been helping Ms. Gray refine
the script. It was ``never black and white'' she says, ``but he
helped me put in more shades of gray.'' And he was wondering how on
earth he would find a director who shared his passion for the
story.
</P>
<P>
   Then one spring day _ he remembers the moment vividly _ while
getting a massage in the Hoboken, N.J., neighborhood where he and
his wife had renovated three brownstones before moving to
Connecticut, it hit him: if he wanted ``A Walk on the Moon'' to
reflect his vision, he would have to direct it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him order around the household pets _ ``Sit!'' he says
sternly to the dogs, who blithely ignore him _ is perhaps not the
best introduction to his directing abilities. But when the
4-year-old, Tess, who's been in bed with a nasty reaction to a
vaccine, awakens flushed and feverish, Goldwyn coolly takes charge,
quiets the wailing child and brushes off the suggestion of a call
to the doctor. You get the idea that his unflappable assurance
could come in handy on a movie set.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray confirms the impression. ``He was a calm, steady center
in the midst of chaos,'' recalls Ms. Gray, who was around for the
entire 36-day shoot last summer in the Laurentian Mountains of
eastern Canada. ``He was doing damage control every minute, but he
was always the most focused person there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I decided to direct it,'' Goldwyn says, ``I thought, `OK,
this is going to be a war, and I'm just going to tough my way
through it.''' One of its producers, Dustin Hoffman, also resorts
to military imagery: making a movie, he says by telephone, is like
being in a foxhole. ``And you want a director who makes you feel
it's OK to get up and charge, but who helps you stay relaxed _
`don't worry, you won't get killed.'''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Goldwyn ended up directing a film he had wanted to
produce, Hoffman ended up producing a film he had wanted to direct.
He had read the screenplay and thought he might like to try his
hand at directing it. When he found that Goldwyn had got there
first, Hoffman and his production company joined the project as
producers. ``It was the next-best thing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The two actors had never met. But, Hoffman says: ``We hit it off
right away. After a couple of conversations, we knew we were
responding to the same things in the script. It's like a first
date: you know pretty quickly if there's going to be a second.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Hoffman's Punch Productions involved, the movie could
actually be made. Ms. Lane gives Goldwyn high marks for his
``tenacity and follow-through.'' Speaking by phone from California,
she says: ``They ought to give Oscars to the people who get to the
green light. That's a pure labor of love, because you never know if
it's actually going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's participation did more than just insure that ``A Walk
on the Moon'' would happen, Goldwyn says. ``What's so brilliant
about Dustin,'' he says, ``is that he's always looking for the
possibilities, never saying, `It's done.' And having a creative
voice telling me that made us a really good combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn also got advice from his father, who had been
encouraging him to direct. `` `You can do more than act,' he would
tell me,'' Goldwyn says. ``And I'd go, `Yeah, Pop, leave me alone.'
But I think one of the things that led me to say, `Yes, I should do
this,' was that I'd heard it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn's father admired Ms. Gray's script, but though he was
encouraging, he couldn't quite understand why his son was so driven
to make the film.
</P>
<P>
   When the elder Goldwyn saw a rough cut of ``A Walk on the
Moon,'' ``He got it,'' his son recalls; ``He said, `I understand.
You made a movie about love.' And then he gave me lots of notes. I
involved him a fair bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a new element in their relationship, he says. ``We've
kept our careers separate _ deliberately. When I was starting out
as an actor, we sort of had a rule: it was my thing. I didn't want
his help, nor did he want to give it; nor (italics)could(end
italics) he have, really.''
</P>
<P>
   While that may be a little hard to swallow for struggling actors
without two generations of movie contacts in the family, Goldwyn
makes a plausible case, recalling how his brother John, now
president of Paramount Motion Picture Group, would sometimes
suggest to a director that Tony read for a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get the appointment,'' Goldwyn says, ``but the directors
were just doing it as a favor to my brother. They would glaze
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn, whose parents divorced when he was 5, is descended from
show business royalty on both sides of his family. His maternal
grandfather was the playwright Sidney Howard, and his mother,
Jennifer Howard, and her mother, Claire Eames, were both stage
actresses.
</P>
<P>
   His lineage, Goldwyn says, ``is a tremendously important thing
to me; it's the fabric of who I am, and I'm very grateful and proud
to be part of that.'' On the other hand, he continues, ``starting a
career in show business with a famous last name is a total drag.
Because when you have a legacy of success of that caliber, it's a
pretty high standard to hold yourself to. You can't just do OK It
took a while to develop the confidence to say: `I think I'm doing
the right thing. This is what I was meant to do.' Then, on the
other side, there is the perception of you as this Hollywood kid,
and people assume you're a dilettante trading on the family name.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn says his interest in acting came from his mother's
introducing him to the theater. ``The movie business held no
romance for me,'' he says. ``But the theater did. And theater
actors did. There was something magical about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he began acting in plays at his Colorado prep school. There
was no doubt that he would go east for college (he attended
Hamilton College in upstate New York and Brandeis University in
Massachusetts): from the age of 10, when his father took him along
on a trip to New York, he had been mad for the city. ``Somehow the
East Coast always felt like home to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He won his Equity card working as an apprentice at the
Williamstown Theater Festival for three summers. It was there that,
at 21, he met his future wife, then a 27-year-old assistant set
designer. ``She's a very decisive person, and it was like, `You're
it; I know.''' He went on: ``We didn't get married for six years.
But I knew early on that I'd gotten it right. It ties into why I
was interested in this movie: like Pearl, I was in a marriage that
I had entered into very young. I understood the impulse to want to
break out.''
</P>
<P>
   His marriage, he says, has withstood that impulse. But he
(italics)has(end italics) broken out of the acting career that was
giving him pause five years ago. He had to drop out of two movies
during the two years it took him to bring ``A Walk on the Moon'' to
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   There are two more screenplays he has fallen in love with, and
he and Hoffman are planning to work together again, with Goldwyn
directing Hoffman as a Las Vegas chiropractor. Directing doesn't
scare him any more. ``It was fun,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
