<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORZA-OPERA-2TAKES-$A     03-24 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORZA-OPERA-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING INVOKED THE POWER OF FATE, AN OPERA FEELS IT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal, The Atlantic Monthly and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Last month, after an absence of 20 years, ``La
Forza del Destino'' returned to La Scala, where in 1869 Verdi
introduced the opera in its significantly revised, definitive form.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this century _ from the late 20s to the mid-60s _
audiences in Milan could count on two revivals per decade; in the
40s alone, there were four. But even as the consensus of informed
opinion has been advancing the reputation of the composer's lesser
as well as his greatest works, the challenge of realizing some of
them in performance has grown all but insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Riccardo Muti, the music director of La Scala, is not one to
capitulate. Several seasons back, he lifted the curse on ``La
Traviata,'' unfazed by memories of Maria Callas, whose specter was
thought to condemn all future Violettas in Milan to public
disgrace. With ``Forza'' _ a title more clearly and less lazily
Englished as ``The Power of Fate'' than as the more familiar
``Force of Destiny'' _ the malignancy is harder to name.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Macbeth'' in the playhouse, the opera exists in its own
microclimate of unease. The blood chills at the chronicle of
Leonard Warren, a stalwart of the Metropolitan Opera, who launched
Don Carlo's scena with the words ``Morir! Tremenda cosa!'' (``To
die! A dreadful thing!''), collapsed and expired, his aria unsung.
</P>
<P>
   One night in late February, the premiere of the new ``Forza''
safely past, warning bells began sounding virtually with the rise
of the curtain. The overture, a Muti specialty, had set the house
ablaze with the tempestuous passion and soul-sick melancholy that
toss and churn at the opera's core.
</P>
<P>
   But with Leonora's opening aria, all that was lost. Of the
Spanish noblewoman's anxiety on the threshold of elopement, the
soprano Ines Salazar conveyed little, and what mainly registered
was an incapacity to project any but her high notes past the
footlights.
</P>
<P>
   Then Alvaro, the half-breed Inca royal, came bounding in, in the
person of Jose Cura, looking like a million bucks, and choked on
some airborne foreign particle. Instead of conjuring up the dazzle
of the rising sun (``god of the Indies''), he covered a coughing
fit as best he could, with his back to the house. The trilling
flute, at least, dazzled right on cue.
</P>
<P>
   In the next scene the vivacious mezzo-soprano Luciana d'Intino,
telling fortunes as the Gypsy wench Preziosilla, added a memory
lapse to the blotter, but this was minor, and she never looked
back. As for the prima donna, her later and more demanding scenes
failed to improve on the initial impression.
</P>
<P>
   Cura, on the other hand, returned after a cryptic announcement
to give a shattering portrayal of his strange character, so
honor-bound, so prone to self-abasement, so fierce of temper.
</P>
<P>
   He probed especially deep in the haunting battlefield duet
``Solenne in quest' ora.'' Here, the wounded Alvaro, expecting to
die, exacts his only friend's promise to consign to oblivion the
secret that gnaws at his heart. Neither brother officer suspects
that under their noms de guerre they are hunter and quarry:
Leonora's brother, Don Carlo, is out to avenge the death of his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Cura gave the gloomy opening phrases an unearthly lightness, as
if his soul were already hovering at the mystic threshold, but in
the serene melody that follows, he let the light go out, steeping
in solemnity a moment more conventionally played for the false
comforts of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The tapestry of ``La Forza del Destino'' is woven from precisely
such tangled threads, which to some minds condemns it as an absurd
mass of confusions. The action, drawn with liberties from a messy
Spanish original, stretches credulity, certainly, but only for
those whose experience of life is so narrow that they suppose
coincidence to be the invention of the likes of Shakespeare and
Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   Alvaro's gun fires accidentally in Act I, and Leonora's father
takes the bullet. How far-fetched is this? More questionably, the
lovers _ separated in flight, tragically mistaken about each
other's fortunes _ meet again years later. Unsuspecting, they have
retreated to the same monastery, she as a hermit in disguise, he
having taken vows and a new alias.
</P>
<P>
   A likely story, some sniff. But again, how far-fetched is this?
The ``coincidence'' reflects the properties of character that have
brought them to this pass, and character is destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The literal-minded balk, too, at the way unrelated characters
major and minor keep bumping into one another across the maps of
Spain and Italy. Those who prize consistency of tone object to the
all but plotless Shakespearean episodes of camp and tavern life,
which interrupt the arc of high romantic tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   It all seems so lumbering and ``Russian,'' in the manner of
``Boris Godunov.'' In point of fact, Mussorgsky's procedures mimic
those of Verdi, who wrote ``La Forza del Destino'' for St.
Petersburg and unveiled it there in 1862, six years ahead of that
most Russian opera of them all.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the flaws of ``Forza'' are more apparent than real.
Emotional states create their own geography, as the split focus on
two nonintersecting planes of action defines its own genre: an
opera ``a intenzioni,'' Verdi called it, an opera of ideas. (``Bad
ideas if you like,'' he added parenthetically.)
</P>
<P>
   As the title suggests, the work carries a framework of
philosophical speculation that most operas do without; it promises
to reveal not only what happens to the actors but also the story's
hidden causes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the common run of humanity _ Preziosilla, the
soldiers, even the irascible lay brother Melitone, who answers
Leonora's knock at the monastery gates and works the soup kitchen
with an ill grace _ is the unconsidered life, a constant rushing
hither and yon to little consequence.
</P>
<P>
   For exceptional, tragic souls _ Leonora, Alvaro, Don Carlo, the
Padre Guardiano who hears Leonora's confession and admits her to
the hermitage _ fate is manifest at a flash point or two or three.
Only then, and suddenly, does life take on meaning. The drama of
such people as this consists of moments of passage. In between,
empty years of contemplation stretch like the desert.
</P>
<P>
   One great moment of passage occurs when Leonora arrives at the
monastery. The slate is empty. The high tremolo of violins sheds a
single ray of hope, undercut by an enigmatic pulse of plucked
cellos and double basses. In this void, with the soprano line
discreetly doubled by flute, oboe and clarinet, the outcast senses
that her father's cursing shade has ceased its pursuit. She is on
hallowed ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pace, pace,'' her aria in the final scene, captures the
intensity of the still intervals, and the panic as a new crisis
approaches like a whirlwind. For an act and a half (a fictional
span of many years), since closing the door of her cell behind her,
Leonora has been lost to view. This was as it had to be. In the
meantime, her life has been consumed in private thought.
</P>
<P>
   Divas capable of sustaining the theatrical illusion while doing
justice to the music do not come along every day, as Verdi knew.
``I can't imagine without laughing the idea of la Lotti with her
crinoline and her fichu dressed as a man and as a monk,'' Verdi
wrote his publisher when that lady's name was floated for Naples.
``Anyway, you need different blood in your veins to do that part.''
</P>
<P>
   In living memory (as documented in available recordings),
Callas, Renata Tebaldi and Leontyne Price all mustered the proper
cell count. So did Galina Gorchakova in a concert performance of
the St. Petersburg version at the Kirov Opera under the baton of
Valery Gergiev in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As an added bonus, Gergiev fielded a bewitching Preziosilla in
Olga Borodina, a casting choice that in itself went far to
vindicate the opera's unconventional balance. (The presence at the
work's Italian premiere, in Rome, of the glamorous Marchisio
sisters, Carlotta and Barbara, may have achieved the same effect.)
</P>
<P>
   Gergiev's Alvaro was the robust Armenian tenor Gegam Grigorian,
who strove manfully with a far more daunting challenge than that of
the standard score. Here, too, Verdi knew how much he was asking
for. He accepted the commission from St. Petersburg largely at the
urging of the renowned tenor Enrico Tamberlik and tailored Alvaro
to his exceptional prowess.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Il Trovatore,'' Tamberlik had Verdi's blessing for an
unwritten high C from the chest to cap ``Di quella pira''; with
``La Forza del Destino,'' the concession worked the other way.
Contrary to his usual practice, Verdi instantly transposed from the
key of C to the key of B flat a bravura cabaletta for the tenor
aria that in the Milan score disappeared altogether. ``No one,''
Verdi wrote his publisher, ``will be able to perform what was
written for Tamberlik.'' ( Grigorian did sing the cabaletta, in C.)
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Gergiev recorded the St. Petersburg ``Forza'' for
Philips and took the work back to the stage in the original decor
(``very opulent,'' according to the composer). It argues artistic
conscience in Gergiev to have revived ``Forza'' for his home
company in its native form.
</P>
<P>
   For all other stages, the right choice is the Milan revision,
which boasts a superior overture, irons out some wrinkles in
continuity, gives tenors less feisty than Grigorian a fighting
chance and substitutes for an abrupt ending of blasphemy and
violence a more mature finale of conditional acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Outside St. Petersburg, even the most important houses come to
grief casting the opera these days. To Muti's credit, the recent
travails did not invalidate the epic breadth and vivid novelistic
detail he achieved through La Scala's chorus and orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   His predicament resembled James Levine's when the Met took its
last shot at ``La Forza del Destino,'' in 1996. On that occasion,
Placido Domingo revisited Alvaro after 20 seasons, to noble effect.
For the rest, the conductor, orchestra, chorus and maybe a
secondary singer or two valiantly set the stage for principals who
were not there.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of a revival the next season, starring Luciano
Pavarotti in what would have been a preposterously late debut as
Alvaro, went unkept. (In a Met first, all scheduled performances of
one opera were replaced by another, ``Un Ballo in Maschera,'' an
assignment Pavarotti could still manage.) This from the company
that first presented ``Forza'' with a cast led by Enrico Caruso,
Giuseppe de Luca, Jose Mardones, and the 22-year-old phenomenon
Rosa Ponselle, fresh from vaudeville.
</P>
<P>
   Like St. Petersburg and Milan, New York has bragging rights
where this singular masterpiece is concerned. But staking a new
claim is proving tough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
