<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE MISSILES, FIGHTER JETS AND BOMBERS LEAD ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite.)  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.,
KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV,
KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Waves of NATO strikes Wednesday opened what
officials said would be a protracted assault on the Yugoslav
military, but one that would do little immediately to end the
deadly crackdown in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The first barrage of several dozen cruise missiles started
falling on air defenses across Yugoslavia, Pentagon and NATO
officials said. They were fired from six B-52 bombers and four
American ships, two American submarines and a British submarine.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief lull, American warships fired another burst of
cruise missiles at a target, not long before dawn in Yugoslavia.
That strike _ involving only a handful of missiles _ was not part
of the original plan but rather came after NATO commanders saw an
opportunity to hit Yugoslav aircraft that had returned to one of
their bases, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes also pressed new attacks, the officials said,
describing rolling waves of strikes. ``It's a fairly continuous
attack,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive entailed scores of fighter jets and bombers from
the United States and seven other NATO members, including Britain,
Germany and the Netherlands, the officials said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's strikes were not aimed at the Serbian troops and
tanks that have been systematically destroying village after
village in Kosovo with renewed fury since peace talks collapsed
last week. The battering focused largely, though not entirely, on
the air defenses and command network that pose the greatest threat
to allied pilots crisscrossing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a few days of this,'' a NATO official said, ``before
you can put in a larger number of the aircraft you need to go after
the forces involved in the repression.''
</P>
<P>
   The attacks Wednesday included strikes by F-117 ``stealth''
fighters, as well as the combat debut of the B-2 ``stealth''
bomber, which at $2.1 billion apiece is the the most expensive
warplane ever built. Two of the B-2 bombers, flying from Whiteman
Air Force Base in Missouri, each dropped 16 one-ton bombs.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Yugoslavia mounted a fierce defense, though not
precisely the one expected, American and NATO officials said. The
Yugoslav air force, which is made up largely of Soviet-era MiG
fighters, joined the battle against NATO's warplanes, in what
officials said was the most serious air-to-air combat since the
Persian Gulf war of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The MiG's provided the bulk of the Yugoslav resistance
Wednesday, the officials said. The Yugoslav ground forces evidently
did not fire their surface-to-air missiles, perhaps because their
own planes were in the skies, making it harder to distinguish enemy
jets.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said all American and allied
aircraft had returned safely to their bases after their raids,
despite assertions by Yugoslav officials to have downed a NATO
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon reported Wednesday night that NATO pilots were
confident that they had shot down at least three MiGs. Two of the
pilots reporting shootings were Americans, the other Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, declined to discuss the operation in detail. But they
vowed to press the attack until the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, agreed to end his repression of Kosovo's ethnic
Albanians or until his armed forces posed little threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are striking a range of military targets, including
Yugoslavia's extensive air defense system, its command and control
system and the military forces that Yugoslavia is using to suppress
the Albanians in the province of Kosovo,'' Cohen said at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Yugoslavia, including television images showing
buildings in flames, said the sites hit included an air base near
Batajnica, an aircraft plant near Zarkovo and targets around
Pristina, the capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports of strikes in other Yugoslav cities,
including Krusumlija, Pancevo, Novi Sad, Golubovac, Danilovgrad and
the air base near Podgorica, the capital of Montenegro, a city that
during Communist rule was called Titograd.
</P>
<P>
   One NATO official said Wednesday's assault was the first of at
least three nights of strikes. Such attacks enable American and
NATO forces to build on their technological advantage, the official
said. Each night of strikes will be followed by a day of work to
assess damage and prepare for new raids.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said the campaign could last much longer,
depending on factors including weather and the success of
Yugoslavia's defenses. The officials said they had a clear idea of
how much damage NATO hoped to inflict, though they would not say
how it would be measured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we want to accomplish,'' a senior Pentagon
official said.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton and the Pentagon have described the
military objective as the degrading of the Yugoslav military's
ability to wage war against insurgents in Kosovo, officials said
they still hoped that the severity of the opening shots would
encourage Milosevic to relent. By day's end, there was no sign of
that, with Yugoslavia declaring a state of war.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military poses a far more formidable threat to
pilots overhead than Iraq's battered air defenses ever could during
four nights of American and British raids in December or during the
skirmishes that have continued since then.
</P>
<P>
   In particular the Pentagon fears that Yugoslav's air defenses
could pose a serious threat. They include 60 sets of Soviet-era
SA-2, SA-3 and SA-6 surface-to-air missiles, as well as hundreds of
antiaircraft batteries and even shoulder-fired missiles that could
down a low-flying jet.
</P>
<P>
   In planning the raids, the Pentagon has predicted that at least
a dozen American and NATO aircraft may be lost if the fighting
continues, a senior Air Force official said. ``Given time, we can
take it all down,'' the official said. ``But that comes with a high
degree of risk, a risk that we as a country have not been used to
in some time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days ahead, the strikes are expected to include new waves
of cruise missiles, including those fired from the British
nuclear-powered submarine Splendid, which last October became the
first non-American ship equipped with American cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen took pains to say that the strikes were aimed at
Milosevic's ``military infrastructure'' alone and that NATO forces
were avoiding civilian casualties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
