<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILLY-ARTS-CENTER-3T     03-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-ARTS-CENTER-3TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING PHILADELPHIA MORE FRIENDLY FOR ITS ORCHESTRA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Anne Midgette writes frequently on international art, music and
theater.  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Ask a Philadelphian to name the most beloved
building in the city, and chances are, the answer will be the
Academy of Music. An elegant brick edifice on Broad Street, the
academy opened in 1857 and is the oldest continuously operating
music hall in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It has a passionate following among music lovers, many of whom
regard it as virtually synonymous with its oldest resident company
and landlord, the Philadelphia Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Yet love can be blind, or in this case, deaf. The hall's
acoustics are poor, at least for orchestral music. Built as an
opera house, the academy has a proscenium arch that traps the
sound, which comes across in the auditorium as dry. As a result,
said Peter Dobrin, a music critic for The Philadelphia Inquirer,
``Philadelphians have never really heard the Philadelphia
Orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not the first to notice. An emphatic article in a
newspaper here stated that the Philadelphia Orchestra, the only
major American ensemble to play on a proscenium stage, should have
a proper hall of its own. That was in 1908. Successive generations
have taken up the cry. Plans for a new hall were drawn up during
the music directorships of Leopold Stokowski, Eugene Ormandy,
Riccardo Muti and now Wolfgang Sawallisch.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a plan may be realized. Ground was broken last November
for a new Regional Performing Arts Center, with a 2,500-seat
symphony hall and a 650-seat recital theater, scheduled to open in
2001. The current project has also served to spotlight some of the
orchestra's difficulties as it approaches its centenary season and
tries to keep pace with the modern world.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the center, in its final form, is not an orchestra
project at all. The Philadelphia Orchestra will move into its new
home as a tenant, not a landlord. And the orchestra was ultimately
glad to be rid of the responsibility. The question remains whether
the center's new administration, will be able to repeat the success
of other performing arts centers, from Lincoln Center in the 1960s
to the New Jersey Performing Arts Center more recently, in
revitalizing the community.
</P>
<P>
   None of this was quite what the orchestra had in mind when it
announced plans for a new hall in 1986. It purchased a site on
Broad Street, a block south of the academy, and commissioned the
Philadelphia-based architect Robert Venturi to design the building,
assuming that Philadelphians would flock to donate the $140 million
needed to realize the project. But fund-raising efforts, marred by
a degree of hubris, soon slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised $25 million and hit a plateau,'' said Joseph H.
Kluger, who has since become the orchestra's president. ``There was
a latent emotional resistance from those attached to the idea of
the academy and the orchestra in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them were the leading philanthropists Walter H. Annenberg
and R. Anderson Pew, who also sat on the orchestra's board. The
Annenberg Foundation refused to give any money to the new hall
project, and the Pew Charitable Trusts offered $1.5 million, which
the orchestra undiplomatically rejected as being too low.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pew and Annenberg did have funds for another project,
proposed in 1994: a thorough overhaul of the academy, at a
projected cost of $44 million. Renovation was certainly overdue.
The building's technical facilities were outdated, and its very
structure proved increasingly unsound. Yet the renovation initially
planned was so high-tech that it would have compromised the
building's architectural integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken goal was to turn the academy into such a modern
hall that the orchestra would have no reason to leave. The Pew
trust chipped in $7.5 million and the Annenberg Foundation $10
million for the project. The renovation is still in progress,
although the plan was ultimately scaled down to focus on restoring,
rather than transforming, the academy, to the tune of $31 million.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a new hall, meanwhile, seemed to have ground to a
halt. The orchestra was having problems of its own, culminating in
a debilitating 64-day strike in 1996. The strike ended with both
sides working on constructive changes, like instituting a range of
players' committees to give musicians a more active role in the
orchestra's business life.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Philadelphia's colorful, charismatic mayor,
Edward G. Rendell, assumed a major role. Since taking office in
1991, Rendell has overseen the transformation of a sleepy
Philadelphia, a conservative city that abhorred change, into a more
active place. Center City, as the downtown area is called, is
dotted with construction sites, including 15 new hotels to
accommodate visitors to the five-year-old convention center.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has bolstered the city's morale, and both Rendell
and Willard G. Rouse, the developer responsible for the convention
center and other major buildings, enjoy widespread popularity.
</P>
<P>
   One of Rendell's pet projects is the Avenue of the Arts, which
has basically redefined South Broad Street by developing its
theaters and other arts facilities. Rendell is motivated less by a
great love of the arts _ he prefers sports _ than by his idea of
the changing definition of a city in today's world: no longer a
necessary hub of commerce and industry, in an age of
telecommunications, which have effectively decentralized business
activity, but a ``destination,'' a place for tourism and
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to office, we were desperate to get out of
economic crisis'' Rendell said. ``One way to do that was to build
up Philadelphia's status as a destination. We need to make
Philadelphia attractive for companies.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his motivation, Rendell became an energetic champion of
the new hall, and he marshaled a group of community leaders,
including Rouse, to find solutions that would enable it to be
built. It was this group that developed the idea of acquiring both
the Broad Street site and the academy from the orchestra and
managing both facilities for a number of resident companies,
including the opera and the ballet.
</P>
<P>
   And it was this group that ultimately became the board of the
Regional Performing Arts Center in 1997, with Rouse as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Adding other arts companies to the mix afforded further
justification for civic involvement, demonstrating that the new
hall project was about more than just the orchestra's wish for
better acoustics. Philadelphia suffers from a chronic lack of
performance space.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 study analyzing the number of seats in performing-arts
facilities in 15 major American cities, Philadelphia, the
fifth-largest city in the United States, came in last. San
Francisco has about 8,400 seats per million residents; New York,
6,000; Philadelphia, between 600 and 800.
</P>
<P>
   The academy is desperately overcrowded. It has two resident
companies besides the orchestra _ the Pennsylvania Ballet and the
Opera Company of Philadelphia _ both straining to get more time.
The thriving opera company, restricted to 30 evenings a year, has
had to turn away would-be subscribers. The ballet performs ``The
Nutcracker'' as many as three times a day to make the most of its
window of opportunity; when it can't get into the academy, it
wanders from hall to hall, like other arts institutions in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, larger touring ensembles, from orchestras to
Broadway shows, pass Philadelphia by. ``When you think about the
Vienna Philharmonic coming to this country and not coming to
Philadelphia,'' said Stephanie Naidoff, the new center's president,
``it leaves you salivating.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Naidoff, a corporate lawyer, and the center's other
administrators have little experience in the arts, but thanks to
Rouse, they knew about building. They threw out the Venturi plans
and commissioned the architect Rafael Vinoly to design the new
center. His plans, with two individual halls inside a glass barrel
vault, were unveiled last April and became one of those rare things
that Philadelphians agree upon. The enthusiasm generated $50
million in donations by the time of the groundbreaking, six months
later.
</P>
<P>
   But the price tag has gone up considerably over the years, and
the center, despite having received $73 million of state and city
funds, is still $50 million short of its $255 million goal. And the
Annenberg and Pew foundations are still withholding support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain large trusts have yet to recognize their
responsibilities,'' said Sidney Kimmel, the chairman and director
of Jones Apparel Group and, with a pledge of $15 million, the
largest private donor to the center. ``I see it as that, a
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Annenberg, 91, a publishing magnate and former ambassador to
Great Britain, who declines comment to the press, is evidently
simply opposed to the idea of a new hall. In 1992, according to an
article in The Philadelphia Inquirer, he specified that none of his
$20 million donation to the Avenue of the Arts should go toward the
new hall project.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pew trust, the issue is different. Conscious of its
leading role as a patron of the arts in the United States, the
foundation in 1997 introduced new guidelines for the distribution
of funds to Philadelphia organizations.
</P>
<P>
   This Cultural Leadership Program has made waves by cutting off
longtime recipients that fail to meet new criteria, like ``fiscal
stability.'' The orchestra briefly lost its financing in 1997, and
the ballet was turned down in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, they cannot be running a significant deficit,''
said Rebecca W. Rimel, the president of the Pew trust. ``There is
no ambiguity about the rules, and while a lot of people might not
agree with them, I don't think anyone would say we are exercising
our stewardship in an arbitrary or capricious way.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, Ms. Rimel added, has yet to make it over Pew's bar.
``We are supportive of having a new facility in Philadelphia. And
we think it's a beautiful building. Our concerns boil down to,
after it's built, what will it cost to run it? And what is going to
be the impact on these already fragile arts organizations when
their rents go up? If those two questions can be answered, our
board would be very willing to consider the grant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pew trust's questions about finances seem not altogether
unreasonable. The center's administration has so far been long on
rhetoric and short on concrete figures. It is still not clear, for
example, how much companies will have to pay to use the spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting for answers,'' said Robert B. Driver, the director
of the opera company, which would like to increase its presence in
the academy to 50 evenings a year. ``They say I'll be paying
approximately what I'm paying now. That's not enough. I'm paying
too much as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But most people believe that prices not only for the academy but
also for the two new halls will have to be considerably higher than
the current norm to keep the center running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know the specifics of scheduling policies and
booking policies, and how we were going to run the box office, and
things like that,'' Ms. Naidoff said. ``We had to get everyone to
recognize that the definite agreements will come somewhere down the
line. I learned early on, don't promise things you're not sure you
can deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although it no longer officially controls the center, the
orchestra is still intimately involved with the project. A players'
committee meets regularly with the center's design team _ Vinoly,
the acoustician Russell Johnson and the theater consultant Richard
Pillbrow _ to outline the orchestra's needs in its new hall, from
rehearsal rooms to door sizes. And the chairman of the orchestra's
board, Peter A. Benoliel, sits on the center's board, as does the
donor Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   One thing still to be negotiated, evidently, is where the
center's responsibility begins and the orchestra's ends. It is not
even clear when and how the center will take over the academy from
the orchestra, though it is to happen by next year.
</P>
<P>
   The public's identification of the center with the orchestra can
only be strengthened by moments like the intermission of a concert
conducted by Sir Simon Rattle last month. Sir Simon has been cited
as a desirable replacement for the departing music director,
Sawallisch, but was reported in January to have given a clear no to
the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Rouse, the center's chairman, offered a toast to the ``best
conductor in the world,'' informing Sir Simon that ``Philadelphia
is not a town that takes no for an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically speaking, any offer to Sir Simon should be the
responsibility of the orchestra rather than the center, though like
any ardent suitor, Kluger, the orchestra's president, is happy for
all the help he can get.
</P>
<P>
   The center needs the orchestra as much as the orchestra needs
it. For the orchestra remains the principal guarantor that once the
new center is built, there will be something to put in it. Resident
chamber and dance companies may occupy the recital theater, but
they will hardly fill the larger auditorium. And while the center's
administration dreams of presenting a range of touring ensembles,
it lacks the experience necessary to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly,'' Ms. Naidoff said, ``if this thing is going to
work up to the world-class standards that we want for it, we're
going to have to bring in professionals who have worked in these
areas before.''
</P>
<P>
   With right of first refusal for dates in the new center, the
orchestra is effectively getting its long-desired new hall without
taking a significant financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   '`There is a difference between renting as tenants and having
your own space, after 40 years of autonomy, even if it makes sense
intellectually,'' Kluger said. ``On the other hand, if there's a
deficit, it's their problem, not our problem.''
</P>
<P>
   For the orchestra musicians, construction of the center, now
that it has started, is not a topic of burning relevance. ``This
orchestra has been hearing for 10 years that it's going to get a
new hall,'' said David Cramer. a flutist. ``O.K., so now they've
dug a hole, but it's down the street. People don't see it every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate concern are the search for a new music
director and the renegotiation of the players' contract, which
comes up for renewal this year. Management would presumably like to
follow the New York Philharmonic and other orchestras in extending
the traditional three-year contract to five years or more.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Orchestra could then negotiate the transition
to the new hall and a new music director without the threat of
labor disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Regional Performing Arts Center highlights
America's increasing recognition of the arts as an essential part
of a city's makeup. From Los Angeles to Newark to Miami, the arts
are touted for their potential economic benefit, so that community
leaders without a specific interest in the arts, like Rouse and
Rendell, are stepping forward like Renaissance dukes to support
them.
</P>
<P>
   But in order for a center to live up to this economic potential,
there has to be creative excitement as well. And while Philadelphia
administrators focus on fund-raising in their efforts to complete
the new center, it will take quality performances as well as
attractive architecture to insure that Vinoly's cello-shaped hall
and airy atrium join the academy on the list of Philadelphia's
most-beloved buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
