<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIDDEN-MUSIC-TRACKS-$     03-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIDDEN-MUSIC-TRACKS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDDEN TRACK: ALREADY A WORN TRICK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Scott Sutherland writes about music and culture and lives in
Portland, Me.  
 By SCOTT SUTHERLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The music of Whitney Houston, the Offspring, Robert Earl Keen,
Sheryl Crow, Korn, Beck and Jewel has little in common, but the
musicians do share one thing: they all included hidden tracks on
their most recent CDs.
</P>
<P>
   From hip-hoppers to singer-songwriters to rockers, more pop
artists than ever are adding hidden tracks _ bonus tracks that are
not listed on the song lineup _ in an effort to surprise, delight,
mock or annoy fans. Hidden tracks can last a matter of seconds or
30 minutes or more and range from original songs to uncategorizable
noise.
</P>
<P>
   They can be the best thing on an album, or they can be so
juvenile and gratuitous that they prompt listeners to reconsider
the artist's entire oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually hidden tracks are just the artist trying to be cute,''
said Bob Ludwig, owner of Gateway Mastering in Portland, Maine, who
has mastered thousands of pop albums over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden track is merely the latest entry in a long list of
pop-music gimmicks, the digital equivalent of the LP track designed
to be played backward. Today's listeners have been inundated with
hidden tracks and other ruses (like albums with successive blank
tracks) for so long that they have come to expect a surprise on
every new CD, just as kids expect a plastic trinket in a box of
Cracker Jack.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread use of hidden tracks has indeed inspired
musicians to devise new tricks: CD-ROM drives enable musicians to
add still images and video clips to their albums, and the new DVD
disks, with their enhanced video and sound capabilities, will no
doubt prompt artists to invent yet more needless surprises.
</P>
<P>
   But enough already. It's time for musicians and labels to
rethink why they hide what they hide. If most artists have a hard
enough time filling even half the space on a 74-minute CD with
compelling material, why bother hiding something equally
uncompelling? And if a song is good enough to be the best thing on
the disk, why hide it at all?
</P>
<P>
   Call me a killjoy, but I'm not alone. ``I don't see the point of
hidden tracks,'' says Paul Chesik, manager of the pop-music
department at Tower Records in Greenwich Village. ``The whole
shtick is well past the point of being interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidden tracks are largely the product of digital technology;
antecedents from the days of LPs, like the Clash's hit ``Train in
Vain (Stand by Me)'' on the band's 1979 album ``London Calling,''
are rare. Unlike LPs, on which each song was marked by plainly
etched grooves, the smooth surfaces of CDs give nothing away about
the contents. Almost as soon as CDs were introduced in the early
80s, musicians began adding hidden tracks to their albums.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenters like Doug Mayo-Wells, who runs a Washington-based Web
site (www.pathetic-caverns.com) that includes a segment called
``The official pathetic scoop on hidden tracks,'' trace the current
rash of hidden tracks to the unlisted song on Nirvana's 1991 album
``Nevermind.'' ``The song is called `Endless Nameless,' and it's
basically just Kurt Cobain screaming at the top of his lungs,''
Mayo-Wells says. ``You'd see hidden tracks once in a while before
`Nevermind,' but after that it seemed like everybody had to have a
hidden track.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those tracks were excellent, like the instrumental at
the end of Pearl Jam's 1992 album ``Ten,'' the Ramones' remake of
the ``Spider-Man'' theme on their 1995 album ``Adios Amigos'' or
the slow-dance number at the end of John Hiatt's 1996 album ``Walk
On.''
</P>
<P>
   Most, however, had few if any redeeming qualities, like the 15
minutes of gibberish at the end of the Lemonheads' 1993 album
``Come on Feel the Lemonheads.'' Others simply mocked the
convention: Beck's 1996 album ``Odelay'' ended with a minute of
noise that sounded like a harshly industrial cuckoo clock, while
Ash, a chart-topping power-pop group from Ireland, capped off its
fine 1996 album ``1977'' with 30 minutes of muddled conversations,
punctuated with the sound of a person vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the final word in hidden-track mockery appeared at the
end of the 1997 Ben Folds Five album ``Whatever and Ever Amen,''
when an obnoxious, unidentified male voice said, ``Look, man, I got
your hidden track right here, pal _ right here, listen'' and
proceeded to malign the character of Folds.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Verna, reviews editor for Billboard magazine, defines an
ideal hidden track as a song that offers a contrast _ an alternate
take of a song, different instrumentation, a different point of
view in the lyrics _ to the prevailing mood of an album. But he has
a hard time coming up with a good example. When pressed, he names
one that's close: ``Subway,'' the hidden track on Ms. Crow's
Grammy-winning album, ``The Globe Sessions,'' a song in which Ms.
Crow vents her disgust over the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subway'' is just one of a host of recent songs that suggest
musicians may have had enough of nonsensical hidden tracks. Whitney
Houston's latest album, ``My Love Is Your Love,'' includes an
earthy, soulful remake of ``I Was Made to Love Him,'' produced by
Lauryn Hill; Ms. Hill, meanwhile, includes two fine hidden tracks
on ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' which won five Grammys last
month: a cover of ``Can't Take My Eyes Off of You,'' and ``Tell
Him,'' a Hill original that sounds like an homage to Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Offspring include a brief Tex-Mex version of
their hit ``Pretty Fly (for a White Guy)'' on their new album
``Americana.'' Beck makes up for the dreadful hidden track on
``Odelay'' with a nice instrumental on his latest album,
``Mutations,'' and Korn kicks in an amusing version of Cheech and
Chong's ``Earache My Eye'' on its latest, ``Follow the Leader.''
</P>
<P>
   But if musicians have begun to realize how self-indulgent the
practice is, record labels, as evidenced by their packaging and
marketing of albums with hidden tracks, still seem perplexed. ``My
Gift to You,'' the final song on Korn's album, clocks in at about
seven minutes, but the liner notes list it at 15 minutes 40 seconds
_ a pretty good indication that there's more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Houston's album bears a sticker on the CD case, helpfully
informing listeners that the album includes a hidden track, a
strategy that seems to be catching on among the major labels. Such
inconsistencies suggest that record companies want it both ways:
they embrace hidden tracks as proof of the musician's boundless
creativity only to trumpet them to the music-buying public in an
attempt to sell more albums in a highly competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, gimmicks always succumb to the bottom line, which is
why it's time to retire this threadbare convention and move on. As
Verna puts it: ``A lot of the mystery has gone out of the hidden
tracks thing. To tell you the truth, I always got a much bigger
kick out of spinning records backwards than finding hidden tracks
on CDs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
