<DOCNO> NYT19990324.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-INFLUENCE-2TAKES-$     03-24 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-INFLUENCE-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO TO HOLLYWOOD, RE TV: IT'S NOT THAT BAD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM MCDONALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)You people sit there day after day, night after night,
all ages, colors, creeds. We're all you know. You're beginning to
believe the illusions we're spinning here. You're beginning to
think that the tube is reality and that your own lives are unreal.
You do whatever the tube tells you. You dress like the tube, you
eat like the tube, you raise your children like the tube, you even
think like the tube. This is mass madness, you maniacs!(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard Beale (played by Peter Finch), addressing his
television audience in the 1976 film ``Network.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O.K., O.K., television is evil. It corrupts the young. It turns
our brains to mush. Americans got the message in 1961, when the
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission looked out upon
the television landscape and saw that it was bad. ``A vast
wasteland,'' he thundered. Everybody nodded in agreement, then
flipped through the TV Guide to see what was on that night.
</P>
<P>
   But the phrase stuck _ became lodged, in fact, in the national
corpus of received wisdom and stock phrases. For a time it was
gravely invoked by critics, scholars and politicians. Finally, worn
out, it was tossed onto the ash heap of cliches, to be retrieved
and reused thereafter only with ironic intent. Television, it
seems, had stopped being the worst thing ever.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say we had learned to stop worrying and love the
tube. People, with good reason, have never stopped beefing about
television: there's too much sex, there's too much violence, there
are too many commercials, there's too much Howard Stern. Tasteless,
mindless television has afforded generations of critics a decent
living, and no one has argued that families don't watch enough TV
together.
</P>
<P>
   But what you seldom hear nowadays is the kind of
monster-in-a-box jeremiad that Paddy Chayevsky delivered in his
bracingly barbed ``Network'' screenplay _ the kind of rant heard
even more regularly in television's early years, when the TV set
was becoming as common as a coffee table in the American home,
giving rise in mandarin circles to dark portrayals of the medium as
an insidious influence that would surely sap the minds of Americans
if not their precious bodily fluids.
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't hear much of that anymore, unless you happen to be
at the movies. Curiously, at a time when the viewing public shows
signs of having withstood television's lobotomizing effects and has
even begun exerting a kind of power of its own over the medium
through remote control, VCRs, CD-Roms, home video, computer
link-ups and all kinds of niche cable choices, the movies have
their dials stuck on a quaint, flickering, black-and-white vision
of the tube.
</P>
<P>
   The settings may differ, so may the plots, but there's a thread
running through them that might be traced back to George Orwell and
the postwar fears of water-tainting, mind-policing totalitarianism.
In this portrayal, television is a nightmarish force _ soulless,
invasive _ even if its theater of operations is something of a
dreamscape.
</P>
<P>
   That's a reference to ``The Truman Show'' and ``Pleasantville,''
both of them television movies, if you will, set in surreal
environments. ``Pleasantville'' is about two 90s teen-agers who
magically wind up in a 50s sitcom; ``Truman'' is about a manchild
who has, unawares, lived his life in Pleasantville _ actually a
fantastic variation on it called Seahaven _ where his every
breathing moment has been televised and turned into a hit show.
</P>
<P>
   Both movies were in theaters last year, meaning that if you
watch them now you watch them _ appropriately somehow _ on
television, as videos. And both think the worst of the medium, one
finding hypocrisy aplenty in the amiable sitcoms of the past
(``Pleasantville''), the other intimating a callous and
manipulative televised future (``The Truman Show'').
</P>
<P>
   As for the here and now, there is ``EdTV,'' another film with a
bad feeling about television, only this one has a more
good-natured, comical way of showing it, with little of the
sardonic edge of the others. It's another sure-to-please offering
from Ron Howard (it opened on Friday), and it's sure to remind you
of ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   In this movie, though, the protagonist, Ed Pekurny, an affable
but aimless video clerk played by Matthew McConaughey, lives not in
an eternally chirpy custom-made utopia but in the downbeat real
world, and he not only knows his life is being televised, he wants
it that way: round-the-clock coverage is the prize he won in a
contest run by a struggling cable channel, and it's his ticket out
of his rut.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a deal struck with the Devil. A Faust in blue jeans,
Ed soon discovers that becoming a media darling has a harrowing
price: the cameras trailing his every move, turning the days of his
life into soap opera, rob him of privacy, sour his relationships
and actually make him rather glum. In short, on the supposition
that it takes one to make one, television has created a monster.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, let this be a lesson to us all about the emptiness and
destructiveness of our voyeuristic fascination with celebrity and
our misdirected hunger for fame. We're so in thrall to television
that we can no longer tell the difference between real life and
what's on the screen. Howard Beale had it right, you'd have to
conclude.
</P>
<P>
   Ed, however, is too nice a guy, or too dumb, to be pilloried for
a larger social failing. Blame must fall on those evil electronic
eyes stalking him and the cold, calculating, ratings-driven
executives who run the channel and eventually hold Ed hostage to
it. Television is ruthless, television is intrusive, but worst of
all television poisons family life, ruins emotional health and
deadens the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty scary. No wonder Howard has the cast clowning it up or,
when Elizabeth Hurley is on the screen playing a temptress,
practically screaming sex.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing so bald intrudes on Peter Weir's ``Truman Show,'' one of
the blackest sun-drenched movies ever made. Yet in many ways ``The
Truman Show,'' even though it was released first, is a logical
extension of ``EdTV.'' Both films blur the lines between
make-believe and reality, and both portray television as a sort of
ominous surveillance operation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``Truman,'' 5,000 cameras in the placid suburban soundstage
that is Seahaven watch the unsuspecting Truman Burbank (Jim Carrey)
day and night, as they have since he was plucked from an
abandoned-baby ward and given his own show without his ever being
let in on it. In Truman's world, all is treachery and deceit behind
a pastel veneer of amity: everyone in ``The Truman Burbank Show''
is a hired performer but the star.
</P>
<P>
   His cookie-baking wife is for all intents and purposes the call
girl next door, her services paid for in this case by the studio.
His best friend not only looks as if he came out of a beer
commercial, he is one, carrying a six-pack product placement
wherever he goes. Truman's world is the inverse of a paranoid's, a
place where a man of sound mind has no idea that everyone around
him really is part of a grand conspiracy against him.
</P>
<P>
   But the people Truman sees are bit players beside the one he
can't, Christof, the Dr. Moreau who created the show and directs
Truman's life from a sunless command center. If the one-word name
doesn't give him away as the bad guy (a whiff of religious cult, an
echo of the Evil Empire), the beret and black suit will.
</P>
<P>
   Christof, played by Ed Harris, is the television creative type
from hell: arrogant, cynical, power-mad. And the show he produces
is heartless and even sadistic at the core: Christof may watch over
this child of his imagination with a kind of almighty tenderness,
but he has reared him in captivity and seems ready to let him die
that way if it will boost ratings. If this is where television
could lead, what are we supposed to think of the people producing
it now?
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, what should we think of their
forerunners, the television producers of 30 or 40 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' has an answer for that, and it's damning. Its
measuring rod is a fictitious 1950s sitcom by the same name, a
black-and-white fantasy of suburban tranquillity that betrays no
inkling of life's grays. But just as in ``The Truman Show,''
unpleasantries lurk behind the Ozzie-and-Harriet facade. The young
hero of ``Pleasantville'' (Tobey Maguire) would like to think
otherwise, of course.
</P>
<P>
   A child of divorce and 90s ennui, he watches the sitcom
fanatically, seeing in its endless reruns everything his
dysfunctional world is not. But after he's swept into the
television screen itself, dragging his oversexed sister (Reese
Witherspoon) with him _ the two of them introducing passion, and
living color, to the town _ he begins to discover the truth.
</P>
<P>
   For the world of ``Pleasantville'' is soon exposed to be
emotionally sterile, hypocritically prudish, conformist,
patriarchal, racist (the town comes to discriminate against
``coloreds''), anti-intellectual, intolerant of creativity and
easily egged on into mob rule.
</P>
<P>
   An indictment of 1950s America? It seems so, although the movie
comes wrapped in entertainment values for box-office appeal, and
the Pleasantvillians do eventually reform themselves. But certainly
``Pleasantville'' finds television of the 50s guilty of fostering a
repugnant set of values inside the white picket fences, and of
lying.
</P>
<P>
   The message is clear: rather than show Americans their country
as it really was, the network men told them only that father knew
best. No wonder the subsequent years brought civil unrest, a
drugged counterculture and political disillusionment, the movie
seems to say; look to television for blame.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the viewing public is entirely let off the hook in
these films. Both ``The Truman Show'' and ``EdTV'' portray the
television audience as willing dupes of the industry. These are
Americans who can't get enough of Truman's and Ed's unremarkable
adventures, who gobble up the spinoff merchandise, who elevate the
ordinary to the plane of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about getting a life: television gives them Ed's and
Truman's. Maybe it's a kind of mass narcissism being depicted here:
everyday people crazy about people like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, the audiences here appear incapable of making
ethical or moral judgments on their own. People are truly fond of
Truman and Ed, but no one seems to regard their captivity _
particularly Truman's involuntary one _ as, you know, kind of,
well, wrong. At least not until Truman and Ed try to escape; then,
like muddled sports fans rooting for both teams, the audience that
has cheered on these guys in their fish-bowl existence now pulls
for them when they try to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Such blockheads, such sheep. And what steers them this way and
that? Correct. They're not far removed from the automatons
populating the state-run terrorscape of Orwell's ``1984'';
ubiquitous television screens control them, too. (It may be telling
that two movies, in 1955 and 1984, have been based on the novel.)
</P>
<P>
   Orwell wrote his cautionary tale in 1949, as the world, having
rid itself of one totalitarian state (Germany's), was nervously
witnessing the flowering of another (the Soviet Union). It was also
a time when the world was embracing television, and becoming
worried in some quarters about its potential brainwashing power. So
perhaps it's no coincidence that fears of one sort of population
control (electronic) were rising in tandem with fears of another
(political).
</P>
<P>
   But judging by the movies of late, habits of mind die hard.
Though Orwell's novel proved less than prophetic, though the Soviet
walls came tumbling down, the movies haven't given up their
suspicions about television. It's still out there, they warn, and
it may get us yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
