s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIDE-THEATER-$ADV28-N     03-24 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDE-THEATER-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
70 MINUTES ON AN EMOTIONAL ROLLER-COASTER: A SOLO JOURNEY FROM OHIO
TO AUSCHWITZ  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bizarre Murder!!! A Lesbian Forces Blind Holocaust Victim on
Roller Coaster!''
</P>
<P>
   This phony headline is trumpeted by Lisa Kron about herself
halfway through her one-woman show ``2.5 Minute Ride,'' directed by
Mark Brokaw and opening Sunday night at the Joseph Papp Public
Theater &UR;  &LR; in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But the performer is a clown, not a killer: with auburn hair and
hazel button eyes, she bounces across the stage like a Claymation
figure. (New York audiences last saw her as a wisecracking,
wheelchair-bound rabbi in Paul Rudnick's current comic play, ``The
Most Fabulous Story Ever Told.'')
</P>
<P>
   The headline refers to an amusement-park ride that Ms. Kron
takes with her retired father, who lives in Lansing, Mich. The ride
proves to be a breeze compared with a trip to a concentration camp
_ the other major story in ``2.5 Minute Ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kron knows that her newest solo effort evokes laughs, but
she hopes that this account of a visit to Auschwitz with her father
goes deeper. ``It's the next natural step for my work,'' she said
recently. ``It's always been so easy for me to just be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The fake headline speaks volumes about the mix of humor and
horror in ``2.5 Minute Ride.'' In true tabloid fashion, Ms. Kron
does not fret about exaggeration in her titles. Her last solo
effort, the 1994 ``101 Humiliating Stories,'' offered far fewer
embarrassing scenarios from contemporary urban life than that.
Writing in The New York Times, Ben Brantley called the show ``a
blissful piece of theater of abashment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``2.5 Minute Ride'' is, in fact, a 70- minute play that had its
premiere at the La Jolla Playhouse in California in 1996 and then
went through various transformations at the Mark Taper Forum in Los
Angeles, the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass., and
the Barbican Center in London, among other stops.
</P>
<P>
   The roller-coaster ride occurs during the annual pilgrimage of
the author's family to an Ohio amusement park. It is an apt
metaphor for a piece that swerves sharply between comic family
anecdotes and the journey Ms. Kron made in 1990 with her ailing but
implacable 77-year-old father to the concentration camp where his
parents perished.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kron, a member of the Five Lesbian Brothers performance
troupe, got the idea to juxtapose the quotidian and the unthinkable
after reading Anne Frank's diary a few years ago. ``Today, we can
talk about the Holocaust as a historical event with 20-20
hindsight,'' Ms. Kron said. ``We (italics)know(end italics) what
happened. But I was struck by the fact that these people were
dealing with their day-to-day mundane experience.''
</P>
<P>
   To join the two narratives, Ms. Kron uses a series of projected
blank slides, a device suggested by the woman she lives with, Peg
Healey, who is also a member of the Lesbian Brothers. ``Blank
slides are the perfect metaphorical container,'' Ms. Kron said.
``The blankness speaks not only to the difficulty in representing
the Holocaust, but in telling a story about someone else's life. It
also allows the audience to envision their own stories and project
them into my particular story.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kron, who would say only that she is in her mid-30s, noted
that she had learned to view the tragic and the comic ``as really
just quick turns of the screen.'' It is an ancient theme given
contemporary life by, for example, Roberto Benigni's current
Oscar-winning movie ``Life Is Beautiful,'' which employs humor as a
foil for dealing with the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many oddly funny stories I didn't use,'' Ms. Kron
said. ``For example, when my father, who was in New Haven, heard
that his parents had been sent to Auschwitz, he immediately tried
to order a ham sandwich, to distance himself from Judaism. But he
couldn't. He'd say to the waitress, `Um ... tuna fish.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
