<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-24 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3368 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIKE-KRZYZEWSKI-T     03-24 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIKE-KRZYZEWSKI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S COACH K ALMOST LETTER PERFECT IN RETURN TO SPLENDOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duke. Final Four. Coach K.
</P>
<P>
   College basketball's holy trinity, its modern-day mantra, is
complete again. The Blue Devils and coach Mike Krzyzewski are back
where they seemingly belong, playing in another Final Four, their
sights set on another national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went there in 1980, Duke was a good job,'' said
Delaware coach Mike Brey, a Duke assistant from 1988 to '95. ``In
the early '90s, he made it a great job. And what you have now,
bottom line, is the best coach at the best job. Nobody else is even
close.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1986 to 1994, Duke was in seven Final Fours and won two out
of five championship games. That's the best championship run for
any coach not named John Wooden or Pat Summitt. The Blue Devils
(36-1), who face Michigan State in an NCAA Tournament semifinal
Saturday, have been dominating while dealing with the seasonlong
pressure of being the championship favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's amazing NCAA success _ a record winning percentage of
.761 _ is fueled and driven by Krzyzewski, whose competitive fire
burns white hot.
</P>
<P>
   But four years ago the man who ``is'' Duke basketball was nearly
consumed by that fire. Krzyzewski doesn't coach by rote, but by
feel. Four years ago, Krzyzewski was numb.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was an unprecedented 16-0 in the Atlantic Coast Conference
this season, has an average winning margin of nearly 26 points and
a 31-game winning streak. But this remarkable season is also as
much about the 52-year-old Krzyzewski's personal renewal project.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't say it, but I think it means a lot to him,'' junior
Chris Carrawell said of Duke's place in this weekend's Final Four.
``It's kinda like, `We're back.' The problems he went through a few
years ago ... now we're back where he's wanted to be.''
Life-and-death matters
</P>
<P>
   The death of a friend. Infirmity that confirms one's mortality.
The death of a beloved parent. The marriage of the oldest child
that confirms the future.
</P>
<P>
   These are the life passages that have led Mike Krzyzewski on his
journey.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1992, former North Carolina State coach Jim
Valvano was found to have cancer. He spent much of his time trying
to beat the disease at Duke Medical Center. Krzyzewski was a
frequent visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't BS a BSer,'' Krzyzewski said of Valvano. ``When we
were talking, it was just straight. We laughed and cried so much.
... Those were great times for the two of us. We'd kick everyone
else out of the room, so it could just be the two of us. We could
be coaches. We could be just friends, honest with one another.
Those were ... very special times.''
</P>
<P>
   Valvano died in April 1993. That summer, a ``Sports
Illustrated'' article recounted Valvano's valiant battle. Valvano,
in what amounted to a deathbed confessional, explained how he
believed he had allowed coaching and fame to consume his life after
winning the 1983 national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Mickie Krzyzewski underlined the passages she thought pertained
to her husband. ``She said, `This is you,' '' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew Jimmy's message was speaking to him,'' Mrs. K said.
``He just had no idea what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The next season, all seemed well _ another Final Four, nearly
another national championship. But Krzyzewski entered the
off-season questioning if coaching was a worthwhile profession.
</P>
<P>
   And he was caught in a time-guzzling whirlwind. Whether it was
filming an NCAA promotional spot for CBS or helping select USA
Basketball teams or leading the fight on a coaching issue or
speaking at the local Catholic Youth Organization, Krzyzewski
couldn't or wouldn't say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was always reminding himself where he came from,''
Brey said. ``He's a Chicago guy, a blue-collar guy. he didn't want
anybody to say, `Well, Mike's too big for us now.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the 1994-95 Blue Devils lost three starters. And the program
was suffering from recruiting mistakes. Duke was still signing
All-Americans, but Krzyzewski wasn't taking the time to get to know
them like before. Krzyzewski, a West Point graduate and five-year
Army veteran, compensated by working harder.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski, then 47, had been suffering chronic back pain. In
October 1994, he underwent surgery for a herniated disk. Preseason
practice had started. Doctors told him he needed six weeks to
recover; Krzyzewski returned to work 10 days after the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he was Superman,'' his wife said. ``That recovery
time was for average people. If his rehab called for 10
repetitions, he'd do 20. He thought it was like anything else, that
it could be solved by hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The whirlwind became a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, just after the start of the ACC portion of the
season, Krzyzewski made what for him was a terrible admission of
weakness. Exhausted in body, mind and spirit, he told his staff
that he didn't ``think he could make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Mickie Krzyzewski made a doctor's appointment
for her husband. Husband told wife the appointment conflicted with
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never issued demands,'' Mrs. K said, ``but I told him if
he wasn't at the doctor's office I will know you have chosen
basketball over me and I will have to act on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slammed out of the house. Driving to the doctor's office, I
was praying he would be there because I had no idea how I was going
to act if he wasn't there. I was so relieved when I got there and
saw his car. From that point on, we were on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Under orders from then athletic director Tom Butters, Krzyzewski
took the remainder of that season off. This good Catholic boy, who
still covertly crosses himself before every tipoff, self-confessed
his own sins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got sick, the way my mind works, I thought, `It can't
just be my back. It's gotta be cancer,''' Krzyzewski said.
``Because I had done the same things that Jimmy had done. `I
deserve it, but please don't let it be cancer.' When it wasn't
cancer, I realized that I was so lucky that I had something I was
going to recover from; he had something he could not get better
from.''
Soon to be Grandpa K
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski is the son of Billy and Emily, first generation
Polish immigrants who raised two sons on the North Side of Chicago
by working hard, harder, hardest. Billy Krzyzewski died when Mike
was a senior at West Point. Emily Krzyzewski died in September 1996
after a yearlong battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after his mother's death, Krzyzewski hasn't broken
the habit of calling her after every game; he still moves toward
the phone, ready to make the call to someone who's not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``For almost 50 years of my life, I had someone who was always
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not over that yet,'' Mickie Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, the Krzyzewskis' oldest daughter, Debbie, married
Peter Savarino. Dad gave daughter a fairy-princess wedding on the
Duke campus. ``He never let go of my hand that day,'' Debbie says.
Earlier this month, Debbie found out she was pregnant. Coach K will
become Grandpa K.
</P>
<P>
   On April 5, one week after Monday's national championship game,
Krzyzewski is scheduled for surgery to replace his degenerative
left hip. This time, there is no exhaustion, no late-night guilt
trips about the pain being caused by cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always tried to be a rock,'' said Jay Bilas, an ESPN
announcer who played on Duke's first Final Four team under
Krzyzewski in 1986. ``He wanted his players to be tough, so he had
to be a tough guy. Now, he can be tough when he needs to be but
also enjoy the other things about his life without guilt or
regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the Krzyzewskis moved to a secluded new house just
minutes from the Duke basketball offices. Now, Coach K can run home
for an hour or so, listen to music, sit on his deck, or take his
Labradors, Defense and Cameron, for a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski, a private man in a public profession, is taking time
to stop and plant the flowers. He planned all the landscaping
around the new house, and he relaxes by planting flowers.
</P>
<P>
   And the ``Sports Illustrated'' article moved with them. It's
there on Coach K's bedside table.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski has learned how to work smarter, not harder. The
oft-replayed message of his friend Jim Valvano was ``Don't give up,
don't ever give up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if Mike had not gone through those health problems, by
now he would have given up coaching,'' Mickie Krzyzewski said.
``Mike was humbled; he knows he's been given a second chance. Jimmy
didn't have that. I think Jimmy's message to Mike was,`Don't give
up coaching, but find another way to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski has learned to say no. The Duke basketball office is
computerized and reorganized. His time is more his and his energies
are more focused. This season's team is the new and improved
product stocked with stunning talent recruited by Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 recruiting class of Elton Brand, Shane Battier, Chris
Burgess and William Avery was the best in school history and forms
the backbone of this Final Four team.
</P>
<P>
   This season's top recruit, freshman Corey Maggette, is the sixth
man, and he would probably start for any other team in the country.
Next season's freshman class could be just as talented.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Duke is back. And his family and friends have a single word
to describe Krzyzewski: Happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting back to the Final Four for me is incredibly
fulfilling,'' Krzyzewski said after his team's East Regional
victory Sunday over Temple. ``In 1994-95, there was part of me that
wasn't sure we could do this again. For a while, it seemed like it
was promised to us; we went seven out of nine years. But it's not
promised to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a good group. I'm really lucky to be coaching
these guys. NCAA games are won because of really gritty players.
I've had a lot of gritty players.''
</P>
<P>
   Coached by a gritty coach who is now a man fulfilled.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
