<HEADLINE>
FORMER TOP AIDE AT NEW YORK CITY UNION ADMITS HE HELPED ALTER
CONTRACT VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former top official in New York City's largest
union of municipal workers Wednesday became the first person to
plead guilty to fixing a 1996 contract ratification vote and
implicated three other union leaders in the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Mark Shaplo, who was a top aide to Stanley Hill,
the former executive director of the union, District Council 37,
said Wednesday that two other top Hill aides and Albert A. Diop,
the longtime president of one of the biggest union locals in the
council, took part in the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   While making his plea in state Supreme Court in Manhattan,
Shaplo stopped short of implicating Hill, who is under
investigation by the Manhattan district attorney, Robert M.
Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   Diop and Hill, who retired last month after being forced to take
a leave, have repeatedly denied either approving or participating
in the vote fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Shaplo also pleaded guilty Wednesday to receiving more than
$50,000 in kickbacks from the sale of hundreds of holiday turkeys
each year at inflated prices to a union local representing clerical
workers at the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Shaplo described a vote-rigging scheme in which leaders of
District Council 37 of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees printed thousands of extra blank ballots and
then marked them to show approval of the contract. Next, they mixed
these ballots with piles of authentic ones, helping to insure
approval of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   This spared Hill and his ally, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, an
embarrassing repudiation of the five-year agreement they
negotiated. The contract was deeply unpopular with the district
council's 120,000 members and its 56 locals because it contained a
two-year pay freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the district attorney's office hinted Wednesday
that there could be more indictments or guilty pleas over the next
week. In a news conference about the Shaplo case, Morgenthau
announced the unsealing of a guilty plea made in December by Bessie
Jamison, the president of Local 1251, which represents nearly 1,800
clerical workers at the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Joseph DeCanio, president of a local representing
1,000 city highway repair workers, pleaded guilty to taking more
than $50,000 in kickbacks from his work as the chief middleman in
providing more than 10,000 turkeys a year to various locals.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's plea, Shaplo, who was long one of Hill's
right-hand men, admitted that he also got a piece of the action,
acknowledging that he ``received a portion of the stolen amount in
cash from DeCanio after the checks were cashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaplo, who was forced to resign in October following newspaper
reports that several top council officials knew about the vote
fraud, said Wednesday that Martin Lubin, the council's associate
director who was essentially Hill's deputy, and John McCabe, the
director of the union's white-collar division, also participated in
the vote-rigging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
