<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY HEROES SAVE PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ A nervous freshman comes in and saves the game
like a proven veteran. A light-hitting second baseman hits a
tie-breaking three-run home run. This is what happens when a team
is having a special season.
</P>
<P>
   So far, not much can go wrong for the Pepperdine baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-ranked Waves beat USC 6-4 on Wednesday afternoon in a
non-conference game at Eddy D. Field Stadium. Pepperdine (23-3)
scored five runs in the sixth inning against the No. 22 Trojans,
who had won seven of their past eight games.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely pair cooled USC. Left-hander Stephen Correa, who
flopped as a starter earlier in the season, got the final out with
the potential tying run at first base. Junior second baseman Damon
Katz, who had just three career homers, broke a 3-3 tie in the
sixth with a three-run homer over the left-field fence. He went 3
for 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Katz has been swinging the bat better lately,'' Pepperdine
head coach Frank Sanchez said. ``The progress and the strides he
has made ... he just typifies what this team is.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz's homer wouldn't have meant much if it wasn't for Correa
staying calm in an awkward situation. Closer Jay Gehrke, who hasn't
given up an earned run in 18 appearances this season, started the
ninth and threw five consecutive balls.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez went out to talk to Gehrke. It was Sanchez's fourth trip
to the mound, and according to college rules he was forced to
remove his pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Correa, who at one point this season had an ERA of a little over
81 and who hadn't gotten out of the first inning in two consecutive
starts, was called in from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves held their collective breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew as long as I threw strikes my defense could do the
job,'' Correa said. ``I threw two innings at Gonzaga this past
weekend and I threw pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Correa struck out Beau Craig and got Justin Lehr to fly out.
Then he walked ninth-place batter Jason Gemoll before inducing a
flyout from Seth Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust Correa,'' Katz said. ``He threw great in the fall. He
shuts down our hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine starter Steve Schenewerk didn't allow a hit until
Greg Hanoian's leadoff single in the sixth. But Schenewerk walked
five and gave up a two-run single to Brad Ticehurst later in the
sixth that gave USC a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves' Dane Sardinha hit a two-run homer, his seventh of the
season, in the sixth off Trojans starter Rik Currier (2-4) to tie
the game 3-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-99 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
