<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REPORTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS HOLD FOREIGN REPORTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS,
KOSOVO-U.S.-ALBANIANS, KOSOVO-U.S.-SERBS, KOSOVO-TV,
KOSOVO-STEALTH, KOSOVO-MEDIA, KOSOVO-ECONOMY, SAFIRE-KOSOVO) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yugoslav military authorities have begun to crack down on
foreign journalists who were reporting news of the NATO air strikes
from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   They detained a Washington Post correspondent early Thursday,
and on Wednesday shut down all television transmission complexes
and threatened a CNN correspondent and his crew in Pristina, the
capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At about 4:30 Thursday morning, Belgrade time, Yugoslav
plain-clothes agents who identified themselves as border guards
entered the Hyatt Hotel in Belgrade and asked for Peter Finn, one
of two Washington Post correspondents working in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The agents took Finn out of the hotel, saying he would be
deported.
</P>
<P>
   They also acted to deport a Belgian journalist, Philippe Debroz.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Milligan of The Boston Globe and William Glauber of The
Baltimore Sun and four CNN employees were also detained by police
on the roof of a hotel in Belgrade, but were released Wednesday
night, according to their editors.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, two American television correspondents remained
Wednesday, Allen Pizzey of CBS News and Brent Sadler of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said armed Yugoslav officials had slashed the tires of
his vehicle and had threatened him and his crew by holding out two
bullets and saying, ``These are for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Among American newspapers, The New York Times and The Los
Angeles Times each has a reporter based in Kosovo. The Associated
Press moved some reporters out of Pristina, but still has a
half-dozen there, according to a spokeswoman, Tori Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
