<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FRIDGE-DUMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SUES NEW YORK CITY OVER DISPOSAL OF FREON APPLIANCES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lawsuit filed Wednesday by the federal government
seeks to impose heavy fines on New York City for disposing
refrigerators and other appliances in ways that cause
ozone-depleting refrigerants to be released into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In documents filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency said the city had intentionally
ignored federal rules on proper disposal of the appliances and
asked for a fine of more than $48 million, or $27,500 for each day
since March 25, 1994, when the order took effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the city's failure to properly address this important
issue in the past,'' said Jeanne M. Fox, the regional administrator
of the EPA, ``the federal government felt it necessary to pursue
this legal action, and expects that it will result in increased
environmental awareness on the part of city administrators.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Allan, a Sanitation Department deputy commissioner and
the agency's chief lawyer, said she had not seen the legal papers
and had no comment on the lawsuit. But she said the agency believed
that a new policy enacted on March 15 puts it in compliance with
the federal order.
</P>
<P>
   Under that policy, the Sanitation Department has posted new
guidelines in various buildings for the removal of the refrigerant
Freon or Freon substitutes from appliances. The guidelines suggest
that people wishing to dispose of appliances that contain Freon
should call the Sanitation Department's Action Center at (212)
219-8090 before placing the item on the curb. Sanitation workers
will then remove the refrigerant and tag the appliances before
taking them away.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Mears, an EPA spokeswoman, said that ``just putting out
notices is not enough'' and that the Sanitation Department needed
to provide greater documentation. The city, despite the new policy,
remains liable for the complete fine for the five years that it did
not comply with the administrative order, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the sooner they come into compliance, the less the
penalties they will face,'' Ms. Mears said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA charged that the Sanitation Department had failed since
the order was implemented to remove Freon or its substitutes from
compacting trucks in which refrigerators, air-conditioners and
other appliances containing Freon are crushed. Freon had thus
escaped into the atmosphere, it said. The gas also might have
escaped at the city's landfill at Fresh Kills on Staten Island,
where the appliances were further crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Freon belongs to a class of chemicals called chlorofluorocarbons
that can damage the ozone layer, which shields the earth from
ultraviolet radiation that can cause skin cancers, cataracts and
other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   The gas has been banned in the United States since 1995 because
of its effects on the environment, but is still found in many older
appliances and automobiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
